<HEADLINE>
DRIVEN BY DISTRACTION  
 2 OF OPEN LEADERS HAVE THOUGHTS ELSEWHERE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Sometimes distractions can be a very good
thing. Especially when a golfer of considerable reputation is
competing in the U.S. Open with the onus of having never won a
major championship weighing him down.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson and David Duval, who own 24 victories between
them, have rehashed their failures in the majors more than enough
times. Both grimace slightly when the question is asked.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps it was refreshing to both young men that the hordes
of reporters covering the 99th national championship at Pinehurst
No. 2 were preoccupied with other things on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For Mickelson, whose wife is expecting the couple's first child
this month, the baby questions offer a pleasant alternative. For
Duval, who suffered second-degrees burns on his right hand in a
teapot accident last week, his blistered thumb and forefinger have
been the perfect remedy.
</P>
<P>
   Both are tied for the first-round lead at 3-under 67, as are
Paul Goydos and Billy Mayfair, who, like Mickelson, hails from
Scottsdale and played at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   The typical pressure that comes at a major championship _ at
least so far _ has been minimal for Mickelson and Duval, thanks to
everything else that's going on in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be the case, in that I have something to take my
mind off a major championship,'' admitted Mickelson, whose caddie
is carrying a beeper just in case his wife, Amy, goes into labor.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, a licensed pilot, said that should he hear the beep,
he is ``outta here,'' in the air headed for Scottsdale. He might
even fly the plane, provided he is as steady in the cockpit as he
was on this day, when he holed five birdies to offset two bogeys
and rescued himself with four big saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably fly (the plane). But I've also got a co-pilot
who can fly,'' said Mickelson, who promised that no matter what his
position is on the leader board, the birth of his daughter ``is not
something I'm going to miss.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval said his life has been focused because he has stayed away
from the course for the most part until the real deal finally got
under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I just unpacked, worked out, played with the cat,
watched TV,'' he said of his preparation. ``That's what I did.
Pretty boring, I guess, but I rather enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some tenderness in his index finger, Duval never bogeyed
on a day that began in a pouring rain and ended under sunny skies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rain really softened it up,'' Duval said of Pinehurst No.
2, which managed to show its teeth around the greens as the opening
round wore on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to get more difficult as the week
progresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair, who made four birdies and a lone bogey, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to death to shoot 3 under on this course,''
Mayfair said. ``Once it dries up, those shots around the green are
really going to become complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they were tough enough the first time around, as
players seemed to pull out every club in their bag. More than one
chip was chunked, and numerous putts rolled up the false fronts
only to return at the feet of their senders.
</P>
<P>
   Of the pre-tournament favorites, Tiger Woods was right there
after rolling in birdies on the last two holes for a 68.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling very happy, because if you saw me play today, you
would say there's no way he could have shot that number,'' said
Woods, who almost holed out a 9-iron at the 11th hole.
</P>
<P>
   John Daly also made a surprise appearance at 2 under. Daly, who
blew out of the gate with three straight birdies, nearly had a
share of the lead except for a misfire on the last hole, where his
drive ricocheted all the way from the pines on the right into the
rough on the left, leading to a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in about as much shock as everybody else right now,'' said
the often-ridiculed bad boy of golf, who still commands a
considerable fan base.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few bad drives, but I was really pleased. Coming in here, I
felt like the whole game was just gone. I had no confidence or
expectations. But knowing I could pretty much hit driver on most of
the holes helped an awful lot.''
</P>
<P>
   On a day of distractions, Daly admitted that he might have been
the biggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the greatest feeling in the world,'' he said as he
got a rousing ovation coming to the 18th green. ``The fans have
stuck with me through thick and thin, and it was so nice to give
them a good round. I haven't figured out quite why they do it, but
I love them for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
