<HEADLINE>
MICKELSON READY FOR CHILD RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. - Some couples starting a family share the good
news by announcing, ``We're pregnant!''
</P>
<P>
   Medically speaking, this is highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Being pregnant isn't a shared activity, like playing mixed
doubles tennis or bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson isn't carrying a child on alternate months, or
even one day a week. ``He's'' not going to give birth soon.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Amy, is.
</P>
<P>
   Phil is golfing this week. He hopes to win the U.S. Open before
his beeper goes off. In the event it does between now and Sunday's
final round _ the beeper in his caddy's pocket will signal Amy is
in labor _ Mickelson vows he will drop his driver or putter or
whatever club is in his hand and take immediate paternity leave,
sprinting off the course and withdrawing from the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   A private plane is waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, a licensed pilot, has the emergency getaway planned.
He figures he can fly home and be at his wife's bedside at a
Scottsdale hospital in five hours, 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I don't want to miss,'' Mickelson said of the
arrival of the couple's first child.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open co-leader confirmed his plans to a predominantly
male audience of sports writers. Many are married, with children.
Reaction ranged from admiring nods to looks that said, ``Are you
NUTS?!''
</P>
<P>
   A guy from Cleveland wondered what Shawn Kemp would do.
</P>
<P>
   Hands in the interview room went up.
</P>
<P>
   Phil, say you're tied for the lead after the third round. What
if the beeper goes off?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to be there,''
Mickelson replied, unwaveringly. ``The U.S. Open takes place every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But what if if you're leading Sunday going to the 15th hole? You
mean you still would walk away? The winner's check is $625,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dunno,'' Mickelson said, hedging. The former ASU
All-American lifted a hand and rubbed his forehead, as if he felt a
migraine coming on.
</P>
<P>
   How about this scenario. It's the 72nd hole. All you've got to
do to win the Open is finish No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's the last green and there's five minutes left?''
Mickelson asked. He paused, mulling the hypothetical. He said he
would putt out. ``I think five minutes wouldn't make a bit of
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   One hopes for Lefty's sake that daughter Amanda arrives on
schedule (June 30) and he stays to play all four rounds. The Open
course is one of his favorites, calling it ``the best test of golf
I've played in a major championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinehurst No. 2 puts a premium on the short game, and
Mickelson's mastery around the greens is his strength, as he
demonstrated in shooting 3-under 67. In the opening round, he holed
a 25-foot chip for one birdie. He made a 30-foot putt for another.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson's accomplishments and shortcomings are well
documented. He won three NCAA titles. He won his first pro
tournament in Tucson as an amateur. Two years ago, he became the
youngest player since Jack Nicklaus to win 11 PGA Tour titles.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson is a multimillionaire. His Web site touts his
``integrity, intelligence, charisma and good looks'' and describes
him as ``one of the most respected under-30 athletes in the world.
. . .''
</P>
<P>
   But the game's best left-handed player still hasn't won a major.
He has come tantalizingly close several times.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is off to a fast start on a course he likes, and his
confidence level is high.
</P>
<P>
   Can he win? Sure. But winning the U.S. Open or any major
championship is is some ways like being in labor. You sweat. You
strain. Supporters keep telling you, ``C'mon, you can do it.'' When
you deliver, words can't describe the relief and pure joy. What a
story it would be if Phil Mickelson wins the Open.
</P>
<P>
   On Father's Day. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
