<HEADLINE>
STARS SHUT OUT SABRES, 2-0, TO TAKE LEAD IN STANLEY CUP FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The struggle for the Stanley Cup could end as soon as
Saturday, when the Dallas Stars could win their first championship
in the team's 32-year history. They scored a 2-0 victory on
Thursday night over the Buffalo Sabres to take a 3-2 lead in the
National Hockey League finals.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano, playing with a damaged left wrist, assisted on both
Dallas goals and performed with elan. The Stars carried a 1-0 lead
until late in the third period, when Pat Verbeek, after taking a
pass from Richard Matvichuk, scored the second goal with a fake and
a backhanded shot past the Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek. Modano's
work with the puck sprang the two-on-one rush from the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modano was our X-factor,'' said Dallas Coach Ken Hitchcock.
The coach said he called his star center at home on Wednesday night
to give him a pep tralk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pretty good relationship,'' Hitchcock said. ``I'm
able to say some things candidly and openly to him. It was a phone
call of support. He took it to heart. He went about his business
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Darryl Sydor scored for Dallas early in the second
period. Hasek stopped 19 shots, while the Stars' Ed Belfour had 23
saves in recording the shutout.
</P>
<P>
   If the Stars win the title, it will be the first time since the
New York Rangers won the cup in 1994 that the regular-season
champion won the post-season tournament. This is the sixth season
in Texas for the team, which was formed as the Minnesota North
Stars in the expansion of 1967. But the series is shifting back to
Buffalo for Game 6, and the Sabres have lost only one of nine home
games in this two-month tournament. Game 7, if necessary, will be
in Dallas on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Although close and tense, Thursday night's game was the least
entertaining of what has been a well-contested series. Each team
was stifled by tight checking. Because of mediocre ice conditions,
passing and playmaking were difficult. Whistles and face-offs were
frequent in a game that took more than three hours to complete.
``It is really bad ice,'' said James Patrick, Buffalo's veteran
defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   In the final 31 seconds, the Sabres were on the power play and
had another extra attacker because they pulled Hasek and replaced
him with one more skater. Although the Sabres kept the puck in the
Dallas zone, they never came close to scoring. In a scrap with
Dallas defenseman Derian Hatcher at the final buzzer, Buffalo
defenseman Rhett Warrener appeared to injure his right leg and was
helped off the ice by his teammates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
