<SLUG> BC-BBN-SPRING-DODGERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SAY TALKS WITH TRIBE PROGRESSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Fort McDowell Mohave-Apache Indian Community and
the Los Angeles Dodgers are moving closer to serious negotiations
on a deal that would lure the team from Florida to Arizona for
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials and representatives of the Fort McDowell
community east of Scottsdale met Wednesday on the reservation in
their continuing informal talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a step forward,'' said Fred Coons, business development
director for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the tribal proposal does not include
housing, which the Dodgers would like because they have it at
Dodgertown in Vero Beach, their spring home for 51 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Coons said again that housing alone will not make or break a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that the Dodgers will leave Dodgertown this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe and the Dodgers outlined their positions on various
issues Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good discussion,'' Coons said.
</P>
<P>
   He described the ongoing talks as a ``collaborative effort'' and
not negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Fort McDowell is offering a spring training complex with a
12,500-seat stadium, a cloverleaf practice facility, locker rooms,
batting cages and other amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also are talking with Vero Beach area officials who
want to keep the team. Their effort suffered a serious setback when
Florida Gov. Jeb Bush vetoed $7.5 million in state aid to the
project last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers no longer want to be the only major league team to
own their complex, preferring a more financially beneficial lease
setup. And Dodgertown is in need of major renovations and expansion
to bring it up to speed with state-of-the-art complexes such as
those in Peoria and Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Coons said talks with the tribe will continue on a regular basis
and that the team still has no timetable for resolving the issue. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
