<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-PLESAC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ATMOSPHERE PLEASES PLESAC  
 TRADE FROM TORONTO REJUVENATES RELIEVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Three games, five batters, five outs.
</P>
<P>
   Life on the mound couldn't be any sweeter for Dan Plesac, who
walks around Bank One Ballpark as if on air.
</P>
<P>
   Since being traded last weekend from the Toronto Blue Jays,
where he struggled, to the Diamondbacks, where he's flourished, the
veteran left-hander has been in baseball heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Retiring to a horse ranch in Indiana can wait.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old's youthful enthusiasm is back _ relishing the
role of zeroing in on left-handed hitters, looking forward to the
possibility of pitching in the postseason for the first time in his
14-year career, anticipating the next pressure-packed moment he's
handed the ball.
</P>
<P>
   He calls the Diamondbacks' experience, so far, ``overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how his head is come Saturday,'' Manager Buck
Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Plesac may have gotten to face an Atlanta Brave or two.
It's not quite the same as a diet of Florida Marlins left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   But Plesac, acquired in a deal that sent shortstop Tony Batista
and right-handed reliever John Frascatore to Toronto, has seen his
share of difficult situations, with runners on base in three tight
games.
</P>
<P>
   His first chance was Sunday in Anaheim, when he came on in the
10th inning to face Garrett Anderson with runners on first and
second. Plesac struck him out on four consecutive sliders, and the
Diamondbacks ended up winning, 3-1, in 13 innings.
</P>
<P>
   That after flying all day across the country to get to Anaheim
for his first game with the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was time to tighten the belt up and get after it,''
he said. ``It seems like when I got here, it was a perfect fit for
me. It was like a wake-up call of, `Forget about the last two
months. The only thing that matters is right now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter realizes Plesac no longer possesses the 98 mph
fastball he had when compiling 95 saves for the Milwaukee Brewers
from 1986 to '89.
</P>
<P>
   Plesac's primary role here will be facing left-handers in tight
situations. There will be games when he may pitch to one batter.
</P>
<P>
   Plesac, 6 feet 5, still can get up to 91-92 mph with his
fastball, and he can still tie up a left-hander with a nasty
slider.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was 0-3 with an 8.34 ERA in 22 innings to start
the season, left-handers were hitting 9 for 47 (.191) against him,
struck out 15 times and didn't have an extra-base hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was a different mind-set, as opposed to worrying long
term, thinking, `How long am I going to keep on struggling? When is
it going to end?' '' Plesac said. ``I was like, `I can't worry
about that now. I'm at a new place. They expect me to get a job
done. Let's get it done.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On the flight to Anaheim, Plesac simply recalled the line from
his first big-league pitching coach, Don Rowe: ``Sometimes you get
paralysis from analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   For Plesac, it meant less reliance on video.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at so much tape that you don't even know what you're
looking at after a while,'' Plesac said. ``Sometimes you get so
much information that you forget the most important thing, and that
is to keep the game simple, take the ball in your hand and put it
in that glove where that catcher is holding it. If it's a fastball
in, get it to that glove.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   He's feeling so at home that he's spent the week searching for a
house.
</P>
<P>
   His in-laws live in Glendale, so his wife, Leslie, is pretty
happy about the trade, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely a perfect fit,'' Plesac said. ``I feel like I
can bring something to the table, a small piece of the puzzle to
help this team.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade was criticized by some who looked at Plesac's overall
numbers in the season's first two months, but Arizona reliever
Darren Holmes knew better. He had teamed with Plesac for two years
in Milwaukee in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said he had heard four days before that the trade for
Plesac was in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy don't need no money,'' Holmes said. ``He's playing
because he wants to win. He wants to go to the World Series. You
get him in the environment where he's got that shot, I think this
is the type of person who is going to pitch. He's pitching in
situations where he's supposed to be pitching in now.''
</P>
<P>
   Plesac came to spring training with thoughts that this would
probably be his last year. He said he went to camp in the best
shape of his life _ down 15 pounds to 217. His shoulder felt great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard reasons I was throwing poorly was because I lost too
much weight and I pitched better when I was heavier,'' Plesac said.
``After a while, I was just so glad that I didn't listen to that
nonsense. I said, `I'm going to keep grinding, something good is
going to happen to me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's thinking maybe he's got a few more years left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't put into words what a shot in the arm this has been
for me,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
