<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMBINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBINE DEBATE TEAMS COPES WITH LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By M. BRADFORD GRABOWSKI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Brooks Brown would rather be identified as the
best debater in Phoenix Friday than as the controversial friend of
the two Littleton, Colo., gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   But even at the National Forensic League's Desert Sun National
Speech and Debate Tournament in Tempe, Ariz., this week, the recent
Columbine High School graduate couldn't escape the day in April
when he lost four of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is one of 2,300 high school students from around the
nation participating in the tournament, which ends Friday. Past
competitors include Richard Nixon, James Dean and Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Brown is the tournament's best-known competitor _ for
reasons he and his teammates would rather forget.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was casual friends with the two gunmen. Two of his
teammates were killed.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he amazed his fellow competitors by taking on the
issue of whether parents should be held responsible for their
children's actions. Currently, the Littleton attackers' parents are
facing a multimillion-dollar lawsuit for their teenage sons'
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stood up and said, `I know the parents of the two kids who
committed the attack,' '' Chris Hajduk of Loyola Academy in Chicago
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more of an emotional appeal than anything that parents
shouldn't be held responsible. It was a very powerful speech. He
was on the verge of crying. It was the best speech I've ever heard
in debate. People didn't want to argue against it. How could you
respond to it?''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said other competitors were nervous about talking to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people here have misconceptions,'' Brown said,
explaining that he and the two attackers weren't as close as
reported by news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was worried about offending him,'' said Daniel Hansen
of Washburn Rural High School in Topeka, Kan. ``You kind of had to
guard yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who was questioned about his relationship with attackers
Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold after the incident, declined comment
about that. But he couldn't stop talking about one of the victims,
slain teammate Daniel Mauser, 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that I'm here for Dan,'' Brown said on competing at
nationals. ``He was my most favorite little kid in debate. I love
that little kid. He kept telling me how much he loved watching me
debate. I want to do the best that I can (for him).''
</P>
<P>
   He and other Columbine speech and debate team members competing
at this week's tournament said losing teammates Mauser and
18-year-old Rachel Scott was like losing family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very hard, we miss them,'' said Columbine coach
Paula Reed. ``There's an empty spot. We lost two family members.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said that speech and debate teammates tend to form strong
friendships, so losing team members is very painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of any other activity where kids are together
for 14 hours straight on a weekend,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And between competing there are hourlong breaks and there's
nothing to do except talk about things like philosophy and life
with each other. It forces the students to become close.''
</P>
<P>
   Another team member, Sara Martin, said the competition has been
a welcome break from the emotional stress all Columbine students
have endured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to have fun this week,'' she said. ``We
haven't been distracted by what happened, but it is a part of who
we are and will continue to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said that everyone has been supportive of her team. Private
donations helped fund the three students and two coaches trip to
nationals and a moment of silence was held in memory of the two
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people come up to me and tell me, `I just don't know
what to say to you,' '' Reed said. ``And I tell them, 'Anything you
say tells me that you're concerned.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Three members of the team said they were in the building when
the shootings began. They declined to go into details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just ready to move on,'' said coach Martha Benham.
``What happened is past us. Now, we need to address `What can we do
from here to prevent this from happening again?' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   M. Bradford Grabowski can be reached at (602) 444-8222. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
