<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0182 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-OPEN-DALY-HNS &LR;      06-18 1443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-DALY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PINEHURST, N.C. _ Consistency has never threatened to inflict
itself on John Daly's life.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether it was his war with alcohol addiction, serious gambling
problems, a troubled personal life or his erratic golf game, Daly
always has found ways to keep people guessing, often to his
detriment.
</P>
<P>
   So when Daly was merrily stringing together par after par on the
back nine Thursday at the U.S. Open, you just knew he couldn't keep
the Nick Faldo impersonation going.
</P>
<P>
   Daly finally cracked with a regrettable swing on the 18th tee
that led to a walk-away bogey. But even that mistake couldn't take
the sheen off of perhaps Daly's finest moment since his
much-publicized battle with the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Daly shot a 2-under-par 68 at Pinehurst No. 2, and only his
18th-hole miscue cost him a share of the lead in the 99th Open. But
on a day when a softened-up Pinehurst teased and tempted but never
let anyone get in a clean cut at Donald Ross' venerable course,
Daly put himself in the middle of the spotlight with three birdies
to start his round and an uncharacteristic string of pars near the
end.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who was a combined 24 over par in his previous
five rounds at three tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm about as much in shock as everybody else is,'' Daly said.
``The thing with me is I don't know who's going to show up in the
next round. That's the way it's been all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But right now, I just want to soak this day up and pat myself
on the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodness knows, he has earned it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the weekend is done, David Duval might be the toast of
the tournament. He is part of a four-way tie for the lead at
3-under-par 67. Phil Mickelson, Billy Mayfair and Paul Goydos also
shot 67 to lead a parade of 23 players who broke par-70 in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   But you get the feeling a lot of people are rooting for Daly to
hold it together this week.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, he has been the soap opera we love to
watch on the PGA Tour. Two of his four victories have been at
majors. But since the '95 British Open, Daly's misfortune has
merited more headlines than his golf game.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knew exactly the depths to which Daly sank at times. But
Thursday, he made it clear he has seen more bad days than good, and
certainly more bad ones than anybody should have to handle.
</P>
<P>
   To deal with the stoppage of alcohol intake, Daly has gone
through a series of other addictions. First, it was gambling.
</P>
<P>
   From 1993 to November 1996, Daly's gambling losses mounted
faster than his list of missed cuts on tour. And that's fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be specific, I lost $51 million and I won $42 million,''
Daly said. ``So I was down $9 million. The most I owed at any one
time was about $3 million $2.8 million, I think. One of my favorite
things was to go to a casino and see how much money the dealer at
the $10,000 table had. If they had $340,000 at the table, I wanted
to see if I could get all of it. That's the ultimate feeling when
they have to call for more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they took a lot more from me than I took from them.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Daly was, and is, on the verge of financial
ruin. To pay his bills, Daly needs to earn about $40,000 per month.
That includes alimony and child support, in addition to house
payments and other expenses. He already has sold his Mercedes and a
home in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've still got houses in Arkansas and Memphis,'' he said.
``But I'm probably going to have to sell the one in Memphis.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was in financial trouble at the moment, Daly said:
``A little.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get completely out of debt with the many casinos he
frequented until he went through his second alcohol-rehabilitation
stint, after which he signed an endorsement contract with Callaway.
As part of the contract Daly signed, the golf-equipment company
took care of $1.8 million in debts Daly owed to casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinking is a lot more of a temptation now,'' Daly said,
``because I don't have any money to gamble with now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I'm playing good, the cravings are there. So you can
imagine what they're like when I'm playing bad. The cravings are as
bad now as when I first quit. It scares the living hell out of me
and scares the people around me, which it should. I don't know why
it's harder for me. But it is. And I know there are a lot of people
out there who know what I'm going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Without drinking and gambling, Daly has resorted to other binges
to satisfy some of his urges. The main thing is food _ chocolate,
to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started with M&AMP;Ms, and now it's Oreos,'' he said.
``Basically, if it's chocolate, I don't care what it is, I'll eat
it.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the problem, Daly revealed how he planned to
celebrate Thursday's grand play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six cheeseburgers from McDonald's, a bag of Oreos and a carton
of milk,'' he said. ``I'm going to watch SportsCenter and hopefully
see myself on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Without drinking and gambling, Daly said his closest friends
have convinced him he has to use golf as his outlet. Wrap himself
up in the game and try to get some gratification from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you're playing bad, it's hard to do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Thursday will be a springboard to better times. But even
Daly admits that the round qualifies as a bolt from the blue. He
withdrew from two of his previous four tournaments and missed the
cut in the other two. He admitted the past couple of months haven't
been any fun for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect to win the U.S. Open,'' Daly said. ``I can't
sit here and say that. My game's not in that fine of a rhythm right
now, and I don't quite have the confidence. But if I could keep
doing what I'm doing, hopefully I can find the confidence to pull
it off through the week. But I don't expect to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew what held me back. I've worked harder this year
than I have any other year. I think I've been putting too much
pressure on myself trying to force things to happen instead of
letting them happen.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Daly just let it happen. He made 12- and 20-foot
putts on the first two holes and then hit a lob-wedge to within
five feet on the third for his quick start. He closed out the front
nine with a bogey-birdie parlay and then strung together the eight
pars before confronting the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how to describe the drive on the 18th,'' he said.
``I don't know if my hand slipped or if I came down a little quick
and opened the face. But it was actually more of a good break than
a bad one. If it hadn't hit the tree, it could have gone
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the ball smacked a tree on the right of the fairway
and kicked into the left woods, barely 100 yards off the tee. Daly
punched into the fairway, then hit a wedge to 20 feet and
two-putted for his bogey.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the round for Daly was that he got to hit his driver
on every par-4 and par-5 except for one. Last year at The Olympic
Club in the first round, he didn't use the driver once.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very frustrating,'' Daly said. ``Last year wasn't a
course where I needed the driver. And I believe that a major
championship should be where you have to play golf and not hit 2-,
3- or 4-irons off the tees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just really good to be able to hit the driver. I felt
like my whole game was gone coming into this week. I didn't have
any confidence or any expectations coming here. But knowing that I
could hit driver on most of the holes helped an awful lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Daly wasn't sure how he did it Thursday, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at my stats, and to hell with them,'' he said. ``If you
look at them, they're awful. And I'm 2-under somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same player who had a six-putt from eight feet two
weeks ago at the Memorial tournament. That was the lowest point in
the stretch of four tournaments where he either missed the cut or
withdrew. And he is not sure why he has played so poorly of late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said. ``Maybe it's a test. That's how I'm
looking at it. I don't feel like my swing is that bad. But I just
find that I'm doubting myself a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawals were easily explained. At Colonial, too much
pollen made him miserable, and at Memorial, he was so far back
after the dreadful six-putt that Daly packed up and headed home to
his home in Memphis to prepare for the following week's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no chance to make the cut anyway,'' he said. ``The sad
part about the six-putt is that I was actually trying on four of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   And Daly has a new putter this week, having ditched the six-putt
traitor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
