<HEADER>
A0183 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-3RDLD-W     06-18 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE NARROWLY APPROVES WEAK GUN CONTROL MEASURE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a jolt to President Clinton and gun-control
advocates in the Democratic Party, the House late Thursday night
narrowly approved a provision to regulate sales at gun shows that
is substantially weaker than legislation passed by the Senate last
month.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, sponsored by Rep. John Dingell, a Michigan Democrat
working in conjunction with Republicans, eked through by a vote of
218 to 211. It drew the support of 173 Republicans and 45Democrats,
though most Democrats stuck with the president.
</P>
<P>
   The House then began debate early Friday morning on a stricter
gun-show measure, which was intended to supersede the Dingell
measure. The National Rifle Association has been working for weeks
to see that the House does not back the same gun regulations that
Democrats unexpectedly pushed through the Senate after the school
shootings in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   In emotional debate on Thursday night, Rep. Dick Gephardt, the
House minority leader, pleaded for the House to take a strong stand
on gun shows. He ticked off the places where deadly gunfire had
erupted in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have Littleton and you have Georgia and you have
Arkansas and you have Oregon and you have Kentucky,'' he said,
``and you have kids killing kids in high schools, not just in
inner-cities but in suburbs all across this country, you have a
national crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Saxby Chambliss, R-Ga.,, spoke out uncompromisingly in
favor of the constitutional right to bear arms. ``The majority of
the amendments we're debating aren't about saving lives,'' he said.
``They're about taking rights away from law-abiding citizens. What
we're talking about is gun control, and that is the wrong issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Several more gun-control measures were to be considered by the
House on Friday, but the success of the Dingell gun-show measure
threw the entire fate of the final bill in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal Democrats were threatening to bolt from the final bill
because its gun-show provision is too weak, while conservatives
were saying they could oppose it if additional amendments, such as
one to raise the minimum age for the purchase of all handguns or
another to ban the import of high-capacity ammunition clips, should
pass and make the bill too strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The less gun control, the more apt it is to pass,'' said Rep.
Tom DeLay, the House minority whip. He had worked unwaveringly to
persuade conservatives to rally around Dingell's bill in order to
trump the stronger version sponsored by Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, a
New York Democrat whose husband was killed by a gunman on the Long
Island Rail Road in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Another gun-show provision sponsored by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
was contained in the base bill under consideration and represented
a mid-point between the other versions.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the complicated politics on the issue, Dingell
refused to say whether he would vote for the final measure if his
amendment prevailed. ``I might or I might not,'' he told reporters
at midday, sphinx-like.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in favor of gun control accused their opponents of
orchestrating a charade by first weakening the bill and then
preparing to vote against it. ``If Republicans cynically vote for
Dingell and against the bill then their strategy is no gun
safety,'' said Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md. He said Democrats were going
to have to weigh ``whether or not a small step is better than no
step.''
</P>
<P>
   The late-night showdown over the gun-show measures came
centerstage after two long days of sometimes impassioned clashes
over God, values, the entertainment industry and the Constitution.
That debate culminated early on Thursday night in passage by a vote
of 287-139 of a wide-ranging bill that would provide $1.5 billion
for fighting juvenile crime and enact tough mandatory minimum
sentences for young people in gun crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In a victory for social conservatives, the House voted 248-180
to include in the crime bill an amendment sponsored by Rep. Robert
Aderholt, R-Ala., giving states the right to allow the display of
the Ten Commandments in public places, including schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that simply posting the Ten Commandments will not
instantly change the moral charcter of our nation,'' Aderholt, the
measure's sponsor, said just before it passed. ``However, it is an
important step to promote morality and an end of children killing
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., and other critics countered that
the amendment raised constitutional questions, including whether it
would pass muster on the separation of church and state. ``Whose
Ten Commandments?'' Nadler asked. ``Which version? The Catholic
version? The Protestant version? Or the Jewish version?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday evening, long after prime time, the House turned to
the gun-control debate, which is the preferred political ground of
the Democrats. A dozen separate gun amendments were under
consideration, ranging from a measure requiring child-safety
devices to be sold with handguns to a proposal to repeal the
District of Columbia's ban on the posession of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   But the most significant showdown was over the rival measures of
varying strictness to regulate sales of weapons at gun shows, at
which collectors and hobbyists selling firearms are not now
required to conduct the kinds of background checks on buyers that
licensed dealers are.
</P>
<P>
   In a fierce lobbying blitz, Clinton arose early in Paris to
telephone four wavering Democrats: Gary Condit and Mike Thompson of
California, Marion Berry of Arkansas and Ron Kind of Wisconsin, to
urge them to vote for the gun-show amendment sponsored by Mrs.
McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy for the United States to be the only advanced
country in the world that doesn't take comorehensive, sensible,
thorough steps to keep handguns out of the hands of criminals,''
Clinton told reporters in Paris, where he was attending a summit of
industrialized nations. ``It's just _ it doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   To hammer home the point the White House sent Attorney General
Janet Reno to the Capitol late on Thursday afternoon. As the debate
neared a late evening vote, Republicans said that Clinton and the
attorney general were still calling a handful of wavering
Republicans from mostly suburban districts who could turn the
outcome either way.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association and DeLay shored up support among
conservatives for the weaker version sponsored by Dingell of
Michigan, who is a former member of the NRA board.
</P>
<P>
   All day long Dingell insisted that he was going to win. He said
that Clinton would not make headway with conservative Democrats
because ``he cost us control of the House and a lot of people
remember that.'' The Republicans won the majority in 1994, months
after Congress enacted a ban on assault weapons avidly sought by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the NRA has largely held sway on Capitol Hill. But
after the school shootings in Littleton, the Senate last month _
with Vice President Al Gore casting the tie-breaking vote _
approved a proposal that would compel all vendors at gun shows,
licensed or unlicensed to run such checks. Law enforcment officials
are given three business days to complete the checks.
</P>
<P>
   And in debate on Thursday night, Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash.,
recalled that he had lost his seat in 1994 for favoring gun contol
and then been re-elected. ``It was bitter and it was painful,'' he
said of his election defeat. ``But I have not regreted that vote
for one minute. No congressman's seat is more important than any
child's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dingell's amendment on gun shows differs significantly from the
Senate's. Its definition of what constitutes a gun show is narrow,
and only 24 hours would be allotted for background checks. Mrs.
McCarthy's version largely mirrors the Senate legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In other votes late Wednesday and early today the House approved
a veriety of measures signaling support, sometimes symbolic and
sometimes more concrete, for public expressions of religion. The
debate over the Ten Commandments was the most spirited.
</P>
<P>
   But the House also overwhelmingly approved measures allowing the
use of religious language in memorials on school grounds and
prohibiting discrimination against religious organizations in the
awarding of contracts to provide social services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
