<HEADER>
A0187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT &LR;      06-18 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH LEITER AS POINT MAN, METS TOP CARDINALS, 4-3 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Twelve days ago at Yankee Stadium, Al Leiter helped
turn the New York Mets' fortunes around. Thursday night, after his
third successive strong pitching outing, it looks as if Leiter
might also have turned his season around.
</P>
<P>
   With help from Dennis Cook, who rescued John Franco in relief,
Leiter evened his record at 5-5 in the Mets' 4-3 victory over the
St. Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, the Mets' 38-year-old closer, came on in the ninth with
a 4-1 lead, faced four batters, and _ with no help from a
questionable safe call at third base _ did not get anyone out.
</P>
<P>
   Franco had converted 16 of 17 save opportunities this year. But
he did not blow this one because Cook bailed him out. After Franco
allowed a 2-run single to Fernando Tatis, Cook came on and struck
out Ray Lankford, retired Willie McGee on a fly out and then
induced Eli Marrero to a foul popout to leave the tying run on
third and the winning run at first.
</P>
<P>
   Cook's first save of the season came in Bruce Benedict's second
game _ and second victory _ as substitute manager for Bobby
Valentine, who sat out the second part of his two-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter allowed 1 run and 3 singles in 7 innings before 37,601
fans at Busch Stadium, and appeared to be on his way to victory as
Mark McGwire went hitless in 4 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when the Mets got three hits apiece from Robin
Ventura, including a two-run homer, and Rey Ordonez, and Mike
Piazza had two hits to extend his hitting streak to a career-high
20 games, Leiter struck out 8 and walked just 1. He lowered his
earned run average to 5.20. Three starts ago, it was 6.39.
</P>
<P>
   Since Leiter defeated the Yankees, 7-2, on June 6 to snap the
Mets' eight-game losing streak, the Mets (36-30) have won 9 of 11
games. During that stretch, their starters, so woeful that they
cost pitching coach Bob Apodaca his job, are 8-0 with a 3.01 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter has unquestionably led the way. His last three starts
have been brilliant: 4 runs in 21 innings, 3 wins, a 1.71 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the Cardinals' second, when Leiter allowed all three
singles, the 33-year-old left-hander was near perfect. The only
other base-runner Leiter permitted was Joe McEwing, who walked
leading off the sixth. He was quickly erased when Edgar Renteria
bounced into a double play on which he broke his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter finished his night's work with a flourish, striking out
the side in the seventh on 11 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets still had to sweat this one out. Just before Franco
allowed the two-run single to Tatis in the ninth, McGwire hit a
comebacker with runners on second and third to Franco, who threw
the ball to third base - only to have umpire Ed Rapuano rule that
McEwing had dived back safely.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Mets hung on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to at least somewhere in the last few years of my
career be on a winner,'' McGwire said before the game. He went to
three World Series in a row with Oakland from 1988-90, but has not
been to the postseason since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least get the taste of it again,'' McGwire said. ``It's
been quite a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals again have an injury-depleted pitching staff,
they have dropped 6 of their last 9 games, are 12-17 at home, and
they might even see manager Tony LaRussa walk away from the
organization after this year.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, who has 19 home runs, said he is happy this season that
the media has pretty much left him alone. The man who shattered one
of baseball's cherished records by hitting 70 last season said
whoever broke his mark would be under worse pressure than he was.
</P>
<P>
   I'd feel for the person in that position,'' he said. ``It would
be a thousand times worse than what I went through. The media
pressure would be a thousand times greater.''
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire was asked if he thought he could ever top himself,
he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, what happened last year, you can't expect it
again. If people expect that, you don't live in the real world.
Nobody ever talks about how there have only been 18 people who have
ever hit 50 or 60 in history. A lot of people don't live in the
real world, I guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
