<HEADER>
A0189 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-T     06-18 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ, SELE LEAD RANGERS PAST YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sixth-inning, game-tying home run by Texas
Rangers right fielder Juan Gonzalez traveled 370 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh-inning single by left fielder Roberto Kelly barely
escaped the dirt in front of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the long and short of the Rangers' 4-2 victory
Thursday night against the New York Yankees and five-time Cy Young
Award winner Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's two-out, swinging-bunt single off Clemens (6-2) scored
catcher Gregg Zaun from third base with what proved to be the
winning run. It also made a winner of right-hander Aaron Sele, who
beat Clemens despite the latter's season-high 13 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Sele (7-5) surrendered two runs on six hits despite five walks,
and the Rangers escaped Yankee Stadium with a split of this
four-game series and a two-game winning streak without seven-time
All-Star catcher Ivan Rodriguez and left fielder Rusty Greer in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, the two wins are exciting,'' manager Johnny Oates
said after the Rangers beat the Yankees for the sixth time in their
past 20 regular-season encounters. ``But the thing that's exciting
to me is the way those two guys pitched the past two nights.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitching performances by Sele and Rick Helling _ who started
and won Wednesday night _ gave the Rangers the opportunity to win,
and the Rangers took advantage of breaks that always seem to go
against them when playing the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers turned a second-inning triple play and an
eighth-inning double play on line drives by Yankees designated
hitter Chili Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the two balls Chili hit,'' Oates said. ``We got five
outs on those two balls. Then look at Roberto's single. Now, we're
not going to throw it back. There have been some things here that
have went against us. Things went our way tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens appeared annoyed at plate umpire Eric Cooper on the
pitch before Kelly's game-winning single. Clemens attempted to sell
the two-strike pitch as the third strike by walking toward the
Yankees' first-base dugout, but it did not pass through Cooper's
strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens muttered while pacing around the mound after the pitch,
and Kelly chopped the next delivery into the dirt surrounding the
plate. Catcher Jorge Posada went to field the ball, but a momentary
slip on the grass _ wet from a steady rain _ gave him no chance to
retire Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Zaun, who led off the inning with one of four infield singles
against Clemens, scored after being advanced with a sacrifice bunt
and a ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared early to be a hopeless night against Clemens, who
retired 11 of the first 17 batters on swinging strikes before
shortstop Royce Clayton lined a one-out, fifth-inning double into
right field and scored on a game-tying single by second baseman
Mark McLemore.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, though, battled and refused to give in despite issuing
consecutive third-inning walks to shortstop Derek Jeter and center
fielder Bernie Williams. The latter scored Posada with the Yankees'
first run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Roger was on,'' Sele said. ``He looked sharp, and I
knew it was going to be a battle. One base hit could have meant two
or three runs, and we couldn't afford that.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
