<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATE SENATE APPROVES BILL PROTECTING ABORTION CLINIC
ACCESS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, New York _ The state Senate approved a bill Thursday
night making it a crime to block access to abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   And another law long sought by liberals, punishing hate crimes,
including crimes against homosexuals, moved closer to reality after
Roman Catholic Church leaders indicated Thursday that they would
consider supporting such a measure.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of either measure's passage remain unclear, despite
the passage of the abortion clinic bill by a 56-4 vote. The
versions of the bills in the Republican-controlled Senate face
uncertain futures in the Democrat-controlled Assembly, which has
passed stronger versions of both.
</P>
<P>
   And even if church leaders come out in favor of a hate crimes
bill, that would not guarantee Senate passage, because many
Republican senators genuinely oppose the idea, but it would improve
the bill's chances.
</P>
<P>
   But the apparent movement was hailed by supporters of both
changes as a sign that the Senate Republicans, especially their
majority leader, Joseph Bruno, were loosening their longstanding
conservatism on many social issues. Sen. Roy Goodman, a Manhattan
Republican who has long favored laws on clinic access and hate
crimes, said, ``I think there's really been a sea change on these
matters on which the Senate has tended to be to the right of public
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Both houses of the Legislature met Thursday _ a day after the
scheduled end of their 1999 session _ in a harried bid to close
most of their business for the year. But at day's end, negotiations
were still under way on dozens of issues, and there were no talks
on a state budget because Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver spent
most of the day in New York City at political events with Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent Republican officials said that Cardinal John
O'Connor, the archbishop of New York, appeared to be laying the
groundwork for the Church hierarchy to support a hate crimes law
that would provide harsher penalties for certain crimes, like
assault or graffiti, when they are motivated by hatred of a
particular group, like blacks, Jews, Catholics or homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal's office referred calls to John M. Kerry, executive
director of the New York State Catholic Conference, who insisted
that the cardinal remained neutral on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry confirmed that the cardinal planned to raise the hate
crimes bill at the September meeting of the Catholic Conference,
the group of New York's 26 Catholic bishops, and ask them whether
they wanted to take a position on it. The group last considered the
issue eight years ago, when it decided to take no position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cardinal has indicated that he would be open to
consideration of legislation,'' Kerry said. ``The Catholic bishops
are very concerned about bias and violence in any form.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican officials, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
said that while the cardinal has been careful not to say that he
favors the measure, they understood him to be giving it his tacit
support, or at least to be giving the bishops the green light to
back it.
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 federal law provides criminal penalties for people who
block access to abortion clinics, but federal law enforcement
officials say they do not have the resources to enforce it
aggressively. A state law could be enforced by local police and
sheriffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly has passed a clinic access law several times, but
Bruno, until Thursday, had refused to allow one to come to a vote
in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The bill the Senate approved Thursday differs from the Assembly
bill in two important ways: it adds penalties the Senate
Republicans have sought for the crime of stalking, and it does not
contain the Assembly version's provision to allow individuals to
sue anti-abortion protesters for damages for blocking clinics.
Assembly Democrats say they would probably accept the stalking
penalties, but they want to keep the lawsuit provisions.
</P>
</TEXT>
