<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0194 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-TEX     06-18 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS ONE WIN AWAY AFTER GAME 5 TRIUMPH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Call it a manicurist's nightmare _ and the NHL's dream.
</P>
<P>
   Fingernails have been an endangered species in the Stanley Cup
Finals, and last night's Game 5 proved that cuticles could be next.
After four consecutive sweeps in the Finals the previous four
seasons, high-tension hockey is finally at its most intense in the
battle for sport's oldest trophy.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars survived a beautifully physical, stunningly
suspenseful 2-0 victory against the Buffalo Sabres before a
win-thirsty crowd of 17,001 at Reunion Arena to grab a 3-2 lead in
the best-of-seven series and are now one victory from winning the
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the first period was the best anybody played against
us all year in our building. The second period was the best that we
have played in a long time in the playoffs,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``And then the third period was just war.''
</P>
<P>
   The game had everything. Great defense, great goaltending,
high-skilled scoring plays and plenty of pushing, shoving and
hitting. With both sides exchanging punches and verbal barbs
walking off the ice, it showed just how close these two teams are
heading into Game 6 tomorrow in Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a feel for anything right now,'' Hitchcock said.
``The emotional swings in these games are so dramatic. I just think
this thing is up for grabs until the end.''
</P>
<P>
   With last night's victory, the Stars now have a cushion, a
margin of error that has been critical in this series. They lost it
in a crucial Game 4 defeat, but they gained it back last night by
being nearly flawless.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever mistakes they made, Stars goalie Ed Belfour cleaned up
as he picked up his seventh career playoff shutout, the third of
this playoff campaign. What's more, he tied the NHL record for
allowing opponents one or fewer goals in nine playoff games in the
same season.
</P>
<P>
   Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek was almost as good as Belfour, but
he simply was beat by fantastic shots. Hasek was tagged by Darryl
Sydor on a second period power play and by Pat Verbeek on a
breakaway with 4:39 remaining in the game. Otherwise, he held up
well.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Stars showed in this game that they were the ones
who were going to make the big plays and each goal contained three
outstanding points for each player.
</P>
<P>
   Goal 1 started with Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov moving the
puck out of his own end on the power play. Zubov drew Sabres
captain Michael Peca deep into the corner and then found Stars
center Mike Modano skating out of the defensive zone and gathering
speed. With Zubov's pass on his stick, Modano was able to fly into
the offensive zone and disorient the Sabres' penalty killer,
particularly Peca, who trailed far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Modano drew all the attention to the right side of the offensive
zone and then found Sydor sneaking in from his left point. Sydor
lifted a perfect wrist shot over Hasek and the Stars had the lead
they needed at 2:23 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the norm, we're used to one-goal hockey,'' Hitchcock
said before the game. ``If there was a two-goal lead, we won't
probably know what to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars worked hard to find out as they limited the Sabres'
scoring chances, got strong play from all four lines and all six
defensemen and carried their one-goal lead into the third period.
There, the Sabres cheated up their defensemen one time too many.
</P>
<P>
   Modano made the key play on Goal No. 2 as he outworked Sabres
defenseman Alexei Zhitnik deep in the defensive zone and kicked
free a puck into the neutral zone. There, Stars defenseman Richard
Matvichuk swooped in to pick it up, carried it into the offensive
zone and fed a cross-ice pass to Verbeek.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed Verbeek then faked Hasek with a forehand shot
and went to the backhand to tuck in his third goal of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Stars have an appointment to win the Stanley Cup. They
can take it tomorrow night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
