<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK DIALS MODANO'S NUMBER AND THE STAR ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For the entire game I was convinced that Mike Modano,
the whirling dervish wearing No. 9 for your Dallas Stars at Reunion
arena Thursday night, must be a faithful ``Star-Telegram''
subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe he is.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, however, quickly put to rest any notion that he spent
much time reading the newspapers yesterday. Instead, he spent the
day replaying the call that came from his head coach Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock's message could be boiled down to this:
</P>
<P>
   Don't be afraid to reach out and touch someone yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The bruised and battered Buffalo Sabres can attest to how well
Modano listens.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, the man Hitchcock said Wednesday had to play better for
the Stars to have a chance to win this series, was easily the best
player on the ice Thursday night, leading the Stars to a 2-0
victory and a 3-games-to-2 lead in the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and did we mention that he did all this with an injured
wrist?
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night Hitchcock ``actually called me at home and we
talked on the phone for a while,'' Modano said on national TV as
soon as the game ended. ``I know I hadn't done much in the last
couple of games, just hanging around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight the wrist felt better, and I seemed to have better
range of motion. Give some credit to my trainers; they came up with
a new concept and it worked tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Modano didn't snap his goalless streak, which has reached 10
games, but the only thing he didn't do right Thursday night was put
the puck in the net.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Modano the Stars so desperately needed, playing
with a purpose and a fire that simply was missing in Dallas' 2-1
loss in Game 4 in Buffalo. That flame was fed by Hitchcock, once
again pushing the right button at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought when we came into the game that we had an X-factor
and tonight he was the X-factor,'' Hitchcock said of the Stars'
superstar center. ``I thought for us to win, whether he scored a
point or not, Mike had to be a player of significance. He made a
big step in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to throw a 1-2 punch out there with Modano and
(Joe) Nieuwendyk that was effective and he had a big impact in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   That _ surprise, surprise _ was exactly what Hitch and his star
player chatted about Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have a good relationship,'' said Hitchcock, who
joked that he really just phoned Modano, ``to say hello to his mom
and dad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm able to say some things candidly to him that maybe I can't
say to other players. It was a phone call of support and I asked
him to think in some other directions. He took it to heart and
played great tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Those directions obviously included asking Modano to decapitate
any Sabres player that crossed his path Thursday night. Modano, the
guy with the Hollywood smile, playing tough guy? You better believe
it.
</P>
<P>
   He was, as Dave Reid likes to call it, ``hacking and whacking''
with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd wanted to talk to me earlier that day at the rink but I
wasn't in a very approachable mood that morning,'' Modano said,
``So he called me at home in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of chats during the time he's been here and
we've been together.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical of Hitchcock, he was blunt and to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just plain and simple asked me what kind of player I was
going to be tonight. I told him I was going to be involved in every
aspect of the game. I felt I'd gotten away from that in Game 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano used his speed to punish the Sabres. He hit and took
hits, slashed and was slashed, even got into a scrum or two in the
heat of the moment. Check out Buffalo center Curtis Brown's jersey.
I'd swear Modano slashed a giant ``M'' right in the center of it,
ala Zorro.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly it was Modano who set up both Stars' goals.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second period, he took an inspired cross-ice pass
from Sergei Zubov and broke across the Buffalo blue line along the
right boards. Skidding to a stop, he lasered a pass to Darryl
Sydor, alone in the left circle. Sydor's shot appeared to catch
Dominik Hasek in the forearm, above the glove, and caromed high
into the upper right corner of the net for a 1-0 Stars' lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started in our zone with a breakout and Mike has a lot of
speed and he always attracts a lot of people,'' Sydor said.
``That's what happened this time and he gave me a great pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano's help in the Stars' second goal, which put the Sabres
away l6:29 into the final period, wasn't as obvious but just as
essential.
</P>
<P>
   He won a faceoff in the Stars' end, battled for the puck, the
slid it out to Richard Matvichuk along the boards on the left.
Matvichuk and Pat Verbeek were off on a two-on-one break .
Matvichuk slipped a pass between Vaclav Varada's legs and Verbeek
did the rest, faking right to get Hasek spread-eagled, then cutting
left to scoop the backhand into the net.
</P>
<P>
   It all started with a phone call from Hitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always has my number,'' Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night you could say the same about Modano and the
Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   One more victory and I say it's free subscriptions all around.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
