<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES DON'T EXPECT OFFENSIVE CHANGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Buffalo Sabres generated little offense, and they
weren't shy about the reasons after last night's 2-0 loss against
the Stars in Game 5 of the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a few chances, but their teams played great defense and
their guy made some great saves,'' Sabres defenseman James Patrick
said. ``It's no different than the rest of the series.''
</P>
<P>
   To remedy that in Game 6 and keep the series alive, Buffalo
doesn't plan on changing anything.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo center Erik Rasmussen said last night's loss in Dallas
was typical of the previous five games, and just because the Stars
scored twice doesn't mean Buffalo played poorly.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres fell behind, 1-0, on a power-play goal.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' final goal came with less than five minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play the same way,'' Rasmussen said. ``Change?
Change what? It's a one-goal game, and they got one at the end.
We're going to keep doing the same things, and maybe get one in the
goal. A lot of times, it comes down to breaks, and you have to be
on the other end of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Several players from Buffalo said after last night's game that
luck is always a factor in close games like every one in this
series. A lucky deflection of somebody's leg or strange rebound off
the goaltender, or even a wacky bound off the boards can lead to
victory, Sabres winger Dixon Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward also said you need pinpoint shooting like Dallas had in its
first goal. Mike Modano passed to Darryl Sydor, who lifted a shot
in for the second-period lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes the perfect shot sometimes, especially with the way
these teams play defense,'' he said. ``On their goal, Modano made a
great pass and Sydor made an unbelievable shot. He put it the only
place he could have. We can do the same thing, and we have in this
series. We're going to continue working hard and bring the series
back to Dallas. Maybe we'll get a break.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo went quietly through the first two periods last night,
despite throwing 23 shots on goal.
</P>
<P>
   But Belfour offered no place for the puck, and he offered no
rebounds. In the third period, when Buffalo scrambled in front of
the net, Belfour was equally tough.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's added pressure in the final minutes led to a Dallas
breakaway, and the Stars made it 2-0 on a goal by Richard
Matvichuk.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
