r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     06-18 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSON LEARNED, KNOWLEDGE APPLIED LEAVES STARS SO CLOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Fifteen down. One silvery dream of a victory to go.
</P>
<P>
   After 82 regular-season games, after 114 regular-season points,
after 58 days of Stanley Cup playoffs ... the dream is so close,
they can almost skate with it.
</P>
<P>
   After beating the Buffalo Sabres on Thursday night, 2-0, the
Stars are at the doorstep. They are poised at the gate. Hockey
heaven could be as near as Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   You live and learn, the Stars have insisted. They lived through
the opening-round loss to Edmonton two years ago, and they learned.
They lived through the spanking at the hands of Detroit last
season, and they said they learned.
</P>
<P>
   And they played Game 5 of a series just 19 days ago. They
learned.
</P>
<P>
   On that Sunday afternoon against Colorado, the Stars locked with
the Avalanche in a foolish snowball fight. Twelve goals were
scored, seven by the winning Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars swallowed that decision. They survived. They learned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game had so many swings of momentum, I don't think
anybody ever had control,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Hitch was listening to his heart, which was probably still
pounding.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, his team had begun to dictate the tone of this Game 5
as early as the second period. It was destined to be a defensive
effort on the order of what the Stars had performed in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   After what had happened in the Colorado series and in the first
four games of the Finals, the Stars had announced that any kind of
victory, even a 1-0 one, would surely do.
</P>
<P>
   They nearly had one. The Sabres managed to squeeze out only five
shots in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first period, we didn't really do anything we set out
to do,'' defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``But we regrouped during
the first intermission, and we came out and played our game a
little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   Their game. Stars hockey. The hockey literati might label it
with stronger adjectives.
</P>
<P>
   But the last thing that the Stars wanted was another 7-5 game,
not that the Sabres would ever try to instigate one.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock took exception, however, to the suggestion Thursday
night that his team grabbed a 1-0 lead and then nested over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we had control was the score,'' Hitch argued. ``But
we spent some time in our end because of the way Buffalo plays. We
had to just hang in there and hope the cracks were there.''
</P>
<P>
   The cracks were few, but they did come. Mike Modano's effort
along the boards, kicking the puck out of his own zone, keyed the
two-on-one break that led to Pat Verbeek's goal, making it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   And on this night, there didn't seem to be any way that the
Stars were going to surrender a two-goal lead, especially in the
final five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the first period was the best that any team has
played in our building all year,'' Hitchcock said, acknowledging
the Sabres' effort. ``And I thought the second period was the best
we've played in the playoffs in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then the third period was just an absolute war.''
</P>
<P>
   In hockey parlance, it was a night for grinders. In the stands,
it was a night for fingernail chewers.
</P>
<P>
   It was shift-by-shift hockey. And when Verbeek, Darryl Sydor,
Derian Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk are at the frequent center of
the action, the Stars are usually playing their game. Even with a
furious Buffalo push at the end, shots for the visitors were
difficult to come by.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, what did slip through the defense, goaltender Ed
Belfour was there to halt.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pretty, but the Stars learned. The past has taught
them that an opportunity in Game 5 should never be squandered _ not
in this series, especially. The two foes are simply too close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a feel for anything right now,'' Hitchcock said,
``because the swings of momentum happen so quickly with these two
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, except for us being up three games to two, that
any team can feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, after eight months of hockey, after 58 days of playoffs,
the end is so close, the Stars can feel it.
</P>
<P>
   It is shiny and silver. It is the stuff of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   And there's just one more memorable night to go.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
