<HEADER>
A0207 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RANGERS-CANSECO-TEX     06-18 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-CANSECO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OTHER GOALIE' BELFOUR TAKES BOWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dominik Hasek is the goalie with the Olympic gold
medal, the two Hart Trophies for being the league MVP, the four
Vezina Trophies for being the NHL's best between the pipes, the
well-earned reputation as the best on the planet and, if the
commercial is to be believed, the slinky for a spine.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Belfour is the goalie with the only shutout in the Stanley
Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour's team is the one with the 3-2 lead in the series, and
the one that's one victory away from winning hockey's big prize.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars beat the Sabres, 2-0, Thursday night at Reunion Arena
because their goalie, with a huge assist from his defense, pitched
a shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played great,'' Stars defenseman and captain Derian Hatcher
said. ``He kept us in the game. You could say he won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but he wouldn't have done it without a defense that
atoned for two huge gaffes in Game 4 in Buffalo. The Stars lost
that one because mistakes by Shawn Chambers and Craig Ludwig handed
the Sabres two gift-wrapped goals.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the defense made sure Belfour faced a minimum of
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk, his defensive partner, combined
to dish out 11 hits and block eight shots.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, the goat on the first goal on Tuesday, played 25
shifts and blocked a team-high five shots. Ludwig, Darryl Sydor and
Sergei Zubov were solid.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also provided most of the offense. Sydor scored the
first goal on a power play early in the second period, and
Matvichuk started a rush and passed to Pat Verbeek for the clincher
late in the third.
</P>
<P>
   But to repeat Hatcher, you could say Belfour won this one.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, who posted his third shutout this postseason and
allowed less than two goals for the ninth time, faced 23 shots.
Nine of them came in the final period, but that's not indicative of
the pressure he faced. The Sabres were pressing hard to get the
equalizer, and constantly had players flying at the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both goaltenders are really under siege,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``The shot totals are not indicative of the
tenacity in front of the net.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, Belfour stopped a changeup of a shot by
Alexi Zhitnik by squeezing it between his pads. He snapped out the
glove to snag a Zhitnik shot. He used his stick, his blocker and
his body to stop the puck.
</P>
<P>
   He made tough saves that brought gasps, then cheers, then chants
of ``Eddie, Eddie'' from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   He made saves that weren't so obvious, but difficult
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie made two good saves in the third period, one on a
deflection and one on a cross-ice pass,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The goalie with the reputation for being a hothead remained cool
in the third period when a desperate Sabres team, knowing they
might be playing for their Stanley Cup lives, buzzed all around
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie played very well again,'' Stars forward Mike Keane said.
``We needed great goal-tending, and Eddie supplied us with that.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive series, Belfour is the ``other
goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Conference semifinals, the glamour net-minder was
Patrick Roy. In this one, it was Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care,'' Belfour said. ``That's the way it goes
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his teammates can see the determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie's been playing unbelievably for us,'' Sydor said. ``He's
been in the shadow of a lot of goaltenders, and I think he's taken
that as motivation.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
