<HEADER>
A0208 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CUP-BICKLEY-AZR &LR;      06-18 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CUP-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET READY FOR A NEW HOCKEYTOWN - DALLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS - Here in the land of strip malls and strip clubs, where
a sign outside Reunion Arena warns customers to leave their
firearms at home, lies a terrible truth:
</P>
<P>
   Texas is poised to become king of hockey.
</P>
<P>
   It is a little-known fact, but when you count minor-league
organizations, Texas has more professional hockey teams (13) than
Canada (12).
</P>
<P>
   And the dreaded Dallas Stars are 60 minutes away from its first
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done anything yet,'' the Stars' Darryl Sydor said.
</P>
<P>
   True, and wouldn't it be nice to pull the plug on Buffalo's
misery, to end the longest running gag in professional sports? To
solidify the self-esteem of a locale famous only for chicken wings
and Super Bowl futility? Yes, the Sabres are resilient, and if
anyone is capable of winning two games by himself, it's Dominik
Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   But it's starting to smell like armadillos and quesadillas.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that the Stars fit the villain's cloak with ease,
and whattayaknow, Derian Hatcher may have seriously injured yet
another player in a post-game scrum with Buffalo's Rhett Warrener.
Right after Stars Coach Ken Hitchcock initiated a shouting match
with Sabres Coach Lindy Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as it hurts, it's time to give credit where it's
due.
</P>
<P>
   In a frenzy to pass the pace horse, the Red Wings and the
Avalanche both executed blockbuster deals at the deadline, but it's
the Stars who are still skating. And still winning, even without a
healthy room.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, with Brett Hull and Benoit Hogue
questionable for Game 5, Hitchcock called Mike Modano at home.
Modano has an injured wrist, can barely shoot a puck, and was
slipping into the realm of non-factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just asked me, plain and simple, what kind of hockey player
I was going to be tonight,'' Modano said. ``I told him I was going
to be a player involved in every aspect of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He kept his word, flying all over the ice, winning face-offs,
setting up Darryl Sydor on a gorgeous goal, the only one the Stars
would need.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor also has close ties to Hitchcock. When Sydor was 13,
Hitchcock recruited him for his junior team. When Sydor was 16 and
homesick, Hitchcock occasionally found Sydor at the Greyhound
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, at age 14, he weighed 20 or 30 pounds more
than he does now,'' said Hitchcock, who has shed much blubber
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Yet no one is primed for redemption quite like the goalie, Eddie
Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   It is a little-known fact, but Belfour once received a speeding
ticket in Chicago and drove away while the officer was in his
patrol car filling out the citation. Belfour pled ignorance,
claiming he didn't know he had to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   It is common knowledge, however, that Belfour was once a
hot-head prone to volcanic eruptions. These days, he's the picture
of calm and focus, ready to claim the big prize.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a fascinating series, the puck equivalent of a
pitcher's duel, and the competitive balance has been striking. In
this decade, only two Stanley Cup Finals have reached six games.
But this more than just duration.
</P>
<P>
   Until Pat Verbeek's clinching backhand on Thursday, Buffalo and
Dallas had played 310 minutes and 51 seconds of hockey with a
one-goal differential or less. The only blip amounted to 26
seconds, an empty-net goal in Game 2 that gave the Stars a 4-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just no read on momentum,'' Hitchcock said. ``It's an
absolute shift-by-shift battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey in a pressure chamber, which has led to an amazing amount
of animosity between two teams with very little history and two
states wrestling in a rare spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Dallas Morning News'' contacted a mathematician,
requesting the odds of two teams from Texas battling two teams from
New York for both the NBA and NHL title.
</P>
<P>
   Try 1-in-4,250.
</P>
<P>
   After a tenacious victory on Thursday, the odds of Texas
prevailing in both have improved dramatically. And the bragging
rights will only continue.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Nolan Ryan - the great icon of Texas, the man who
epitomized the Don't-Mess-With-Us mentality - will enter the Hall
of Fame. In New York.
</P>
<P>
   Brace yourselves. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 0052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
