</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TOCCHET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURKE: TOCCHET SHOULD SHUT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Coyotes owner Richard Burke issued a stinging rebuke
Thursday to veteran forward Rick Tocchet's published comments
questioning his future in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of two things. It's either agent B.S., or it's Rick
being part of the problem and not part of the solution,'' Burke
said from Denver, where he was studying the construction of the
Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   Burke criticized Tocchet for the timing and tone of remarks in
Dan Bickley's column on Saturday in ``The Arizona Republic''.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of the time, Rick's part of the solution. But
10 percent of the time, he's part of the problem,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good timing. It's the right time to keep his mouth
shut. Sit on your hands and your mouth, Rick.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes hold the option to bring back the 400-goal scorer
for one more season at the same $2.15 million he earned last year,
but they have shown no interest in signing him beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   Burke added, however, that he fully appreciates the ``90 percent
of the solution'' part of Tocchet and isn't trying to sound overly
negative because ``We've got some guys who are 50-50, and Rick's a
90-10. I didn't have good sense when I was his age either, and
sometimes, I still don't.''
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Bobby Smith is expected to exercise the options
on Tocchet and veteran left wing Greg Adams, but the team wasn't
happy with the 35-year-old Tocchet's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't understand what they're doing,'' Tocchet told
Bickley. ``They have to go one direction or another. If they're
struggling, why don't they just let me go, not bring back Greg
Adams, and trade (Jeremy Roenick) for a bunch of prospects? I don't
want to hear that they're losing $5 million to 6 million a year.
You know what? Then gut the team, call it a business decision and
wait until you get your stadium to go after the Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocchet declined comment Thursday, but his agent, Steve Mountain
of Philadelphia, responded to Burke's comments and questions about
his client's future in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why someone would say that. We're not trying to
manipulate anything here,'' Mountain said. ``Rick's entitled to his
opinion, though, when a writer calls and asks what the team is
going to do about his option year and he says, `I don't know what
they're going to do, go ask them.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, we understand the rules, and neither Rick nor I has made
any or had any conversations with the Coyotes organization since
last year. And I have specifically shut down writers' requests to
discuss Rick's contractual relationship publicly. The bottom line
is Rick loves Phoenix and he wants to keep playing there.''
</P>
<P>
   Without an extension, Tocchet could be moved at the March
trading deadline. If the strained relationship with the club
continues, it's also possible he will be traded this summer, to
which Mountain said, ``That would be disappointing because Rick
doesn't want to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tocchet situation isn't the only immediate matter Smith must
face. He also is preparing for next week's NHL expansion draft and
entry draft, searching with new Coach Bobby Francis for two new
assistant coaches, and trying to plan a budget to fit the team's
payroll. In addition, Smith needs to address at least a dozen
player contract issues by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Coyotes may be faced with possible holdouts by two of
their top-echelon players. Goalie Nikolai Khabibulin and
second-line center Robert Reichel are seeking lucrative new deals,
and negotiations regarding both likely could last the entire summer
and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel and Khabibulin are set to become Group II restricted
free agents on July 1 and could be headed to lengthy stalemates
with Smith over salary.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel's agent, Paul Kraus, already has rejected the club's
initial offer, believed to be about $2.2 million a season. Reichel
wants a salary of about $3.5 million and is threatening to leave
the NHL altogether to play in his native Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes hold exclusive rights over restricted free agents
but must tender offers that include a minimum 10 percent increase
in pay. Other NHL teams can sign the players to offer sheets, but
then face forfeiting a series of draft picks as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Burke have indicated that star players Keith Tkachuk
and Jeremy Roenick will be back next season and won't be dealt in
cost-cutting maneuvers. The team likely will try to add a few
players for depth through free agency or trades, but will not make
a pitch for a ``core-type'' player, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The team has several potential free agents, including defensemen
Oleg Tverdovsky, Stan Necker, Gerald Diduck and Jamie Huscroft, and
forwards Shane Doan, Tavis Hansen, Jim Cummins, Mike Sullivan and
Bob Corkum. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
