<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-ELIMINATION-TEX </SLUG>
 
Sabres face new problem 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Buffalo Sabres players have defeated a No. 2 seed,
played without game-stealing goalie Dominik Hasek and survived when
40-goal scorer Miroslav Satan suffered an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Sabres players have encountered and overcome just about
every possible adversity in this Stanley Cup journey, except one.
</P>
<P>
   They have yet to stare down the face of elimination. Until now.
</P>
<P>
   A 2-0 Stars victory in Game 5 last night at Reunion Arena has
brought the Sabres face-to-face with that challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres find themselves trailing 3-2 in this Stanley Cup
Finals series and in need of a victory in Game 6 to keep alive
their chance to bring a Stanley Cup championship to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know what your psyche will be until you get in that
situation,'' Sabres defenseman James Patrick said. ``The game will
be won or lost on the ice. ... Obviously, there is no tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Big games call for big cliches, and Sabres players used just
about all of them in the postgame locker room when the subject
turned to Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   They will play desperate hockey, forward Curtis Brown assured.
</P>
<P>
   They were a couple of breaks away from winning Game 5, Patrick
said.
</P>
<P>
   They're a confident team, winger Dixon Ward insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, we expect to win,'' Ward said. ``I'm not going to
guarantee anything, but we're going out there with the idea to win
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sabres coach Lindy Ruff: ``We're a confident team in our
own building, and we believe we'll be back here for Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo has a 8-1 mark at Marine Midland Arena so far this
playoffs. Their only loss? The Stars stunned the Sabres with a 2-1
victory in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Sabres players say while Game 4 didn't officially count as an
elimination game, it was close enough for them to say they have
experience in that type of situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres were trailing 2-1 in the series at that point. They
had just been soundly defeated in Game 3 at home. They looked
tired. They looked beaten. They looked done.
</P>
<P>
   They, instead, responded by playing maybe their best game of the
series and came away with a 2-1, series-tying victory over the
Stars as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any room for error last time we headed home,
either,'' Ward said. ``... No we haven't faced elimination before,
but really we have.''
</P>
<P>
   To a man, Sabres players insisted that adversity is all the same
whether its winning without Hasek or facing an elimination game.
Patrick's words had a certain resonance, though, because saying and
doing are two totally different things.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres know they have to win, say they can, but don't
actually have any experience in winning games like these.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the situation we're in. You guys don't have to tell
us,'' Ward said. ``We're smart enough to count to seven. The first
team there wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The math is simple. The Sabres are only a single loss away from
the end of their season. The psychology is a little bit harder.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, not even the Sabres, knows how they are going to
respond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
