<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0224 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALK-AZR &LR;      06-18 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDANT IN SLEEPWALKING TRIAL CAN'T ACCOUNT FOR GLOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 and RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The man who says he was sleepwalking when he killed
his wife couldn't explain the gloves he put on before dragging her
into the backyard pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't honestly know where those gloves were on that
particular night before all this happened,'' Scott Falater told
Maricopa County prosecutor Juan Martinez, who says Falater
committed premeditated murder.
</P>
<P>
   Falater took the stand Thursday in Maricopa County Superior
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The gloves are a gap in the defense case, which has featured
testimony by sleepwalking experts that most of Falater's actions on
the night of his wife's death were routine or habitual.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by Martinez, Falater, 43, said the gloves may have been
in a pile in the garage of his north Phoenix home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That meant that you had to go and sort of match them up,''
said Martinez. His point was clear: Falater's actions were so
purposeful and complex that they prove he committed premeditated
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez claims Falater stabbed his wife 44 times, then put on
the gloves to drag Yarmila into the pool where he snuffed out her
remaining breath. But defense attorneys claim that if the attack
had been premeditated, he would have put the gloves on beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, defense attorney Michael Kimerer guided
Falater through the events leading up to what the defense says was
a fatal episode of sleepwalking for which Falater has complete
amnesia.
</P>
<P>
   Falater said Yarmila fell asleep watching ``ER'' as he made an
abortive attempt to fix the defective pump for the backyard pool.
He said he gently shook her awake and kissed her good night before
going upstairs to sleep, apologizing that he hadn't been able to
fix the broken pool pump in the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Falater said the next memory he has is of waking up to people
shouting and dogs barking in the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   He went downstairs, he said, where a cop pointed a gun at him
and ordered him down on the carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as he sat handcuffed in a patrol car, he figured it out _
he was the prime suspect in the murder of his wife, Yarmila,
Falater testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's slowly dawning on me,'' Falater said of those hours in
the back of a squad car, ``that `Yarm' is hurt, really hurt, and
I'm the guy they think did it because I'm the guy sitting in the
car with handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see anyone else in handcuffs.''
</P>
<P>
   During cross-examination, Martinez pressed Falater about
removing his Mormon undergarments, which were found streaked with
blood in Falater's car. The prosecutor is challenging the defense
claim that Falater was following a familiar pattern when he changed
into and out of work clothes in his sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez drove his point home after Falater acknowledged that
Mormons customarily don't remove the garments _ which symbolize
commitment to the church _ unless they are about to bathe or the
garments are soiled.
</P>
<P>
   Falater must have been consciously aware that the garments were
bloody, Martinez said, or he would not have removed them and
stashed them in the wheel well of his Volvo station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez asked Falater, who claims that he always stored work
clothes in the car, how often he removed his Mormon undergarments
in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   `'It's not a thing that would come to mind, that habitually you
would do it?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that is unusual,'' said Falater.
</P>
<P>
   Falater, 43, could also not explain the mouth guard that police
found with the bloody clothes. Martinez said the mouthpiece, which
DNA evidence has tied to Falater, is evidence that he planned the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez fired away with questions about other troublesome
details, whose cumulative weight he says demands a guilty verdict.
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecutor also fired several apparent duds _ with his
accusation that Falater didn't know his wife's birthday, his claim
that Falater had no reason to be troubled by problems at Motorola,
and his suggestion that the motive for murder may lie in a cryptic
Falater comment about an ``unforgivable sin.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez launched his 90-minute cross-examination with the
sarcasm that has become a trademark of his interrogation of defense
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   If Falater loved Yarmila as devoutly as he claims, ``How is it
that you don't even know her birthday?''
</P>
<P>
   Falater responded coolly that Yarmila's birthday was Feb. 5. But
Martinez, relying on erroneous police records, announced that her
birthday was in September. He backed off when Falater held his
ground, pointing out that the police records were in error.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also belittled the defense claim that stress at
Motorola, where Falater oversaw a new computer chip that flopped in
the marketplace, helped trigger his tragic sleepwalking episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would not have been the first manager who had a project
fail,'' he said, claiming that Motorola seldom fired engineers as
talented as Falater.
</P>
<P>
   Falater, under questioning from Kimerer, laid out a compelling
scenario of stress at his high-tech workplace. While he felt
compelled to recommend that Motorola cut its losses on a failing
project, he knew that some colleagues would brand him a quitter.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez asked Falater why he had mentioned an ``unforgivable
sin'' in an interview with a psychologist after the killing. The
prosecutor suggested darkly that Falater murdered his wife because
he believed she had done something horrific.
</P>
<P>
   Falater offered a benign explanation. In his torment after
Yarmila's death, he said, he thought constantly about ``the
teaching in the church that someone who kills will not have
forgiveness in this world or the world to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater said he had gotten little sleep in the nights before the
attack. Workplace stress compounded his tense exhaustion as he went
to sleep that bloody night, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he talked about frustrations he had over trying to fix a
backyard pool pump. A rubber O-ring in the pump had broken into
pieces, and Falater testified he couldn't dig all of it out with a
screwdriver.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came back inside, Yarm was asleep on the couch,''
Falater told the jury, using his wife's nickname as he often has in
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer asked him if he had any thoughts about killing his wife
before he retired for the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' Falater said. ``That was the furthest thing from my
mind. It's kind of ridiculous to even think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Falater said he fell into bed without taking his contact lenses
out of his eyes. ``When I'm really tired, I don't want to spend
five minutes fiddling around with (contact lens) solutions,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Falater said it didn't dawn on him that he was the suspect in
his wife's murder until he was actually at the homicide division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the one going in in the cuffs,'' he said, ``and homicide
means someone's dead.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't believe he actually stabbed his wife until a
friend told him details the police were releasing to reporters.
Another neighbor told police he watched Falater dunk his wife's
head underwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction was that I guess my brain had broken somehow,'' he
said, beginning to cry for the first time on the witness stand
Thursday. ``Maybe there's a tumor in my head or something really
happened in my head.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to describe his emotions about killing his wife,
Falater told of a dream he had about Yarmila about two weeks into
his jail stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yarm was a very tall, white statue with a long flowing gown.
Sort of like an angel, except she wasn't moving,'' he said, sobbing
hard between breaths. ``And I crawled up to her and hugged her feet
and begged her forgiveness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
