<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0228 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLA-FUGITIVE-LADN     06-18 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLA-FUGITIVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER RECOUNTS SOLIAH'S PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE AND CHARLES BOSTWICK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As legal experts cast doubt on the 24-year-old
case against former Symbionese Liberation Army member Kathleen Ann
Soliah, her mother said the radical group sought out Soliah, not
the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   She and her brother, Steven, first encountered the SLA after
Soliah spoke at a 1974 memorial rally in Berkeley for six group
members killed in a shootout with police, said Soliah's mother,
Elsie Soliah.
</P>
<P>
   That speech led fugitive SLA members and newspaper heiress
Patricia Hearst _ whom the group had abducted _ to ask Soliah for
help in hiding, she said. Steven Soliah joined them on the run, but
was caught and acquitted of charges that he helped in an SLA bank
robbery. Kathleen Soliah began a life on the lam from charges that
she tried to blow up two police cruisers in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Soliah called his parents shortly after his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing he said was, `We weren't part of that group.
We were helping those people, and I'm sorry we got involved. We
made a mistake,''' his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the woman believed to be Soliah appeared before a
judge to begin identity and extradition hearings. Captured by the
FBI Wednesday in Minnesota, she did not acknowledge in court that
she is indeed Kathleen Soliah, as authorities insist. The doctor's
wife and mother of three identifies herself as Sara Jane Olson.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney, Howard Bass, did not confirm that Olson and Soliah
were the same person. But he argued that the crimes Soliah are
charged with in California are not punishable by death or life in
prison, and that bail should be set for his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``And those are only regarding the allegations against Kathleen
Soliah. I haven't even addressed the issues with Sara Olson,'' Bass
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey County District Judge Kathleen Gearin said she would
decide on bail after studying the California statutes. The next
court date is set for July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Olson is Soliah, the 52-year-old Palmdale High School
graduate is expected to be returned to Los Angeles within six weeks
to face a five-count grand jury indictment issued in Los Angeles in
February 1976.
</P>
<P>
   She is charged with one count of conspiracy to commit murder,
two counts of being in possession of a destructive device and two
counts of attempted murder of police officers. Police and the FBI
believe Soliah tried to blow up two Los Angeles Police Department
squad cars in August 1975 as possible revenge for the May 1974
shootout with police that left six SLA members dead.
</P>
<P>
   But Elsie Soliah said her daughter and son, Steven, were never
SLA members, Elsie Soliah said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Soliah was outraged when her actress friend Angela
Atwood was killed with five other SLA members in the 1974 shootout,
she said. That nationally televised incident spurred her comments
at a memorial rally in Berkeley's Ho Chi Minh Park, where she
wished ``good luck'' to Hearst and her associates William and Emily
Harris, who were all on the run from police.
</P>
<P>
   The complicated relationships and the amount of time that has
passed since the Soliahs are expected to be obstacles in the Los
Angeles County District Attorney's efforts to prosecute Soliah.
</P>
<P>
   According to former District Attorney Ira Reiner, the chances of
gaining a conviction in a case so old ranges between poor and
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can forget about any credible testimony,'' Reiner said,
adding that memories fade and jurors may not trust witness
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legally, she should stand trial for the crimes she may have
committed, but that can break down with a jury because there was no
physical harm done and it appears she has led a law-abiding life
since then,'' Reiner said.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney spokeswoman Sandi Gibbons declined to say what
evidence remains against Soliah, but prosecutors are confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've prosecuted cases as old or nearly as old and were
successful,'' Gibbons said, citing three convictions for murders
between 16 and 20 years old. ``But it's true cases do not get
better with age.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Levenson, associate dean at Loyola University Law School,
agreed, adding that many jurors may never have heard of the SLA,
which would work against any outrage prosecutors would need to
generate to win the case.
</P>
<P>
   And Soliah could easily point the finger at her alleged
accomplice Jim Kilgore, who remains a fugitive, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jurors are going to ask: With all this crime out there, why
are we spending time prosecution a 25-year-old case against a house
mother who has led a good life, especially since no one was hurt?''
Levenson said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
