A0230 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-18 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: UNDERSIZED KNICKS FACE A TALL ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ After the New York Knicks practiced on Thursday,
Larry Johnson was caught off guard _ a bit like trying to keep a
pair of 7-footers away from the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you have a gimpy knee, and then I see you out there
with Tim Duncan and David Robinson, and I thought, `Poor fella,'''
a reporter said. ``I mean, what's it like, guarding those giant
sequoias?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson smiled and swallowed hard. ``That's cold-blooded,'' he
said. ``What's it like guarding me?''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed and rubbed his beard with his left hand, pondering
how to respond. ``I had a rough night; I've got to do things
different,'' he said. ``I've been in this game eight years now and
I got some tricks. But those cats got tricks, too. You can't teach
height. I think the majority of the time those cats just shot over
me and there's not a lot I can do about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is listed at 6 feet 7 inches, but even the small forward
admits he is closer to 6-5. Officially, he gives up between five
and seven inches to the 7-2 Robinson and the 7-foot Tim Duncan, the
two men who combined for 46 points and 25 rebounds in San Antonio's
Game 1 victory Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Johnson got help from his teammates. Other times, he
did not. Either way, his valiant but futile attempt to stop the
Spurs' monstrous frontline was emblematic of the larger picture:
adversity may build character, but it can also beat you down. The
Little Team That Could may not be able to scale Mount
Duncan/Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson, their only true low-post scoring threat, barely
able to push off his creaky right knee, the Knicks have to find
another answer. Johnson played 21 minutes on a sprained right knee
ligament and shot 1 of 3 from the floor. He had 5 points over all
and seemed to pass up open 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Size did not pose a problem for the Knicks in the first three
rounds of the playoffs. Now it does.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid falling into an 0-2 rut on Friday night, it would not
be surprising to see Coach Jeff Van Gundy alter his rotations in
the paint. Yet even then, how much the Knicks can compete falls
largely on Johnson. How much he can contribute on offense?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some certain things I can't do,'' Johnson said. ``You
know what? I worry about my offense more than my defense. Because I
know we have to have some low-post threat in this series. We can't
win this series from the perimeter. We've got to be able to go in
there and tackle them big guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's film session told a disturbing tale about the Knicks'
chances. First, there was the sight of Johnson playing defense,
trying to establish a low center of gravity by spreading his legs
and bending his knees so he could keep the big guys out of the key.
That sight was followed by Robinson drawing fouls on him in the
first quarter, and Duncan calling for the ball behind a fronting
Johnson in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, the frustration continued. Johnson had one beautiful
move in the first half, spinning by Jaren Jackson and getting
Duncan up in the air with a strong pump fake before putting in a
layup off the glass that circled around the rim and fell through
the net.
</P>
<P>
   But the most enduring images came later. Johnson plowed into
Jerome Kersey on the baseline for an offensive foul and failed to
make himself a legitimate threat from beyond the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Knicks' surprising run through the playoffs
has been about Johnson squaring up from behind the arc and letting
fly those devastating 3-pointers. They hurt Miami and Atlanta, and
shellshocked Indiana. In Game 1 of the NBA finals, he barely looked
at the rim when he was on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't looking for it,'' he said, playing down the notion
that he can't push off his right knee from that far away. ``I may
have passed up one or two. But I think I can shoot it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is hurting, probably more than he will admit, after
spraining the ligament in his right knee against Indiana last
Friday. That he came back for Game 1 is admirable, but more than
anything he has become a symbol for an undermanned, beat-up team
that simply may not have the answers this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to be a burden, just lingering on the floor and
not helping,'' Johnson said. ``I don't think I hampered the team,
which I feel good about. But I definitely didn't do my job well.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy wanted to spread the fouls around in Game 1, but
Robinson was as surprised as anyone to have Johnson guarding him
and Duncan. After facing a barrage of Duncan questions on Thursday,
Johnson finally got fed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was part of the game plan to go one-on-one with Tim?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson replied curtly, ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you stop him one-on-one?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, looking away, annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on that thought a few moments later, he caught
himself giving in to the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, you guys sure like Duncan around here, don't you?'' he
said. ``You know that guy who asked if I could take him one-on-one?
He knew I was just playing around, right?''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
