<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-POPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE POPE GOES HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 18:
</P>
<P>
   The flu that intruded on Pope John Paul II's 13-day trip to
Poland was a reminder of the frailty of the 79-year-old pontiff,
adding special poignancy to a visit already full of emotion. Poles,
while rejecting many of the pope's doctrinal orthodoxies,
nevertheless revere the Roman Catholic Church, which for centuries
has been viewed as the guardian of sovereignty in an
often-subjugated land. Many Poles believe that no one did more than
John Paul II to save Poland from Moscow's rule.
</P>
<P>
   Communist control of Poland was already slackening in 1979 when
Karol Wojtyla, who became John Paul II, made his first papal visit
to Poland and exposed the weaknesses of the system. He drew crowds
approaching two million people, and for the nine days he was there,
the Communist state receded into the background. The pope did not
overtly attack the government, but urged his compatriots to think
for themselves. The next year, Solidarity was born.
</P>
<P>
   Most Poles had never been conforming Communists, in large part
because of the church _ one of the few social organizations
anywhere in the Soviet bloc that the authorities did not control.
By the late 1960s, Cardinal Wojtyla and Poland's primate, Cardinal
Stefan Wyszynski, charged the Communist regime with violating
Poles' basic human rights. They gave shelter to the opposition.
Cardinal Wojtyla even played host at a banned lecture on George
Orwell's ``1984.''
</P>
<P>
   The church's defiance softened the harshness of Moscow's rule.
Collectivization of agriculture and political purges were
relatively mild. Poles could speak more freely than their
neighbors. Poland's military even had priests as chaplains.
</P>
<P>
   But Poles have proved as creative in their practice of
Catholicism as they were with Communism, angering the pope. In
surveys, most Poles have disagreed with church teaching on divorce,
birth control and abortion. The church's open attempts to influence
politics have often backfired. Today, young people in a rapidly
growing Poland scoff at the pope's rejection of consumerism. But
none of this makes John Paul II less beloved, as the large and
passionate crowds he has attracted on this trip, which concluded on
Thursday, show. Poles may not follow his teachings. But to them,
John Paul II is a powerful symbol and moral force.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
