<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS SHOW ALL-AROUND GAME IN BEATING TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Home runs? Yes, one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Working the count? Got it. Strong defense? Check. Clutch
hitting? Solid starting pitching? A save from the closer?
</P>
<P>
   A successful squeeze bunt?
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to find any component of the game that the Mariners
did not execute when they had to Thursday night. They needed every
bit of it to beat Jeff Weaver and the Detroit Tigers, 4-3, in the
last game Seattle ever will play at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a couple of years since we've won a game like
that,'' said Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez, who homered in the
seventh. ``We've done it a little bit more consistently this year,
and it feels good. Our team is a much better defensive ballclub,
and Freddy Garcia is really emerging as our ace. We had a little
bit of everything tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The game matched the two best 22-year-old starters in baseball,
and both right-handers threw eight strong innings. Weaver used a
hard slider to hold the M's to one run, and Garcia used his
fastball-curve-change assortment to limit the Tigers to two.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia (8-3) allowed six hits and had seven strikeouts, each
coming with men on base. Weaver allowed five hits and had five
strikeouts, and turned over a 2-1 lead to the bullpen in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. fell behind left-hander C.J. Nitkowski, 0-and-2,
but recovered to foul off a few pitches and draw a leadoff walk.
Butch Huskey singled off Todd Jones, and a triple by David Segui
brought in two runs. Huskey raised his fist as he crossed home
plate, which drew belly laughs in the M's clubhouse as the
highlight was shown on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The rally came with two big bats out of the lineup _ Jay Buhner,
who has a strained hamstring, and Edgar Martinez, who has a sore
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``From top to bottom, we have a good team,'' said Huskey. ``It
doesn't happen all the time, but the longer the game goes on, the
better our hitters get. It's just that much more potent if Jay and
Edgar are in there.''
</P>
<P>
   After a one-out intentional walk, David Bell came to the plate
and looked for the sign from third-base coach Steve Smith. It was
something he hadn't seen all year, and a play the M's haven't
called since spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Sqeeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just relieved that I got the sign (right),'' Bell said.
``It's not something you look for every day. Once I got it, really
all you have to do is get it in fair territory. It doesn't matter
how hard you bunt it, as long as you get it down. It was a pretty
good pitch to bunt, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell tapped the high fastball _ the first bunt of any kind for
him all year _ back to Jones, who had no play on the streaking
Segui and had to throw Bell out at first.
</P>
<P>
   That run would matter, because closer Jose Mesa allowed a
one-out, solo homer to Gabe Kapler in the ninth. But Mesa got Gregg
Jefferies to bounce out and Karim Garcia to fly out, ending the
game and earning his 14th save in 15 chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners may not have been in position to win had they not
gotten two fine defensive plays to halt a Tiger rally in the
eighth. Bobby Higginson led off with a single, and Palmer was hit
by Garcia, who leaped in despair after the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Wilson threw out Higginson trying to steal third, Tony
Clark struck out and Bell snared a wicked liner by Damion Easley to
keep the Tigers' lead at 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Higginson got a fairly good jump, and Wilson made just an
absolutely perfect throw,'' said Mariners manager Lou Piniella.
``It had to be perfect. And (John) Mabry made a good, quick tag at
third.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Tigers, it was the fifth time in the past 16 games
they've lost despite leading in the seventh or later. The Mariners'
winning rally spoiled the effort of Weaver, the former Texas A&AMP;M
star who was the 14th player picked in last year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited about leaving Tiger Stadium with a bang, and
then we got the reward of having Mr. Weaver on the mound, which is
no day at the picnic against righties,'' said Rodriguez, who became
the first right-handed hitter to homer off Weaver. ``He had good
stuff. This was the first time I've faced him, and today we were
feeling each other out a little bit. It's going to be fun facing
him over the years, because he's going to be around a while.''
</P>
<P>
   So will Garcia, if he pitches more games like Thursday night's
and fewer like his prior start, when he lasted two innings and
allowed five runs in a loss to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I felt good in my mechanics,'' Garcia said. ``The last
time I pitched, at home, I felt pretty good in the bullpen, but I
got to the game, and everything changed. Tonight, I had a good
bullpen and took it into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella was happy about all of it, saying he enjoyed the
pitchers' duel and the way his club came back. More all-around
efforts like this, and the Mariners should turn out just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team's been playing hard all year,'' Piniella said.
``We've been trying to put together the best combination of
pitching we can, and if that settles down for us, we could have a
little fun with this team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
