<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0236 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-18 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPOVICH AND VAN GUNDY: TWO FORGETTABLE COACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The most useful information that will emerge from
the 1999 NBA Finals is not new, but regularly forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   In the NBA, coaching is overrated.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence: Gregg Popovich and Jeff Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Pro hoops would be hard-pressed to find two more colorless,
resume-light coaches than the men leading the San Antonio Spurs and
New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   No NBA playing background, either as star or thoughtful reserve.
No extensive tutelege under wizened masters. No high-profile
college-coaching deeds. Until the last month, no dazzling
achievements in their short NBA head-coaching tenures.
</P>
<P>
   Just a couple of career hoop hacks who are bloody lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that either man is a bad coach, nor that
coaching does not have some value. But to those Sonics fans who
agonize over the departure of George Karl and worry about the
future under Paul Westphal, and who also fear the arrival in the
Pacific Division of Chief Running Triangle, Phil Jackson, the
presence of Popovich and Jeff Van Gundy at the summit offers
reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   Never forget that most coaches are too old, short and fat to
make the outlet pass and fill the lane on the break. The club
employees who are capable of such feats are where the differences
reside in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   No less a figure than Popovich admitted same in the run-up to
the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of coaches who could take this team to the NBA
Finals,'' he said, offering an observation that makes him the '99
leader in the clubhouse for the Full Reverse Nethercutt Award for
honesty in public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The presence in the Spurs lineup of David Robinson and Tim
Duncan, highly skilled big men taken, improbably, 10 years apart as
the No. 1 player in their respective drafts, is why Popovich has
entered the national semi-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy, on the other hand, is here virtually despite himself.
For much of the stumpy regular season, he resisted giving time to
Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby, two players whose acquisitions
Van Gundy fought. Now, of course, Sprewell and Camby, thanks to
injuries that forced Van Gundy into playing them, are the main
reasons the Knicks are the first No. 8 seed to make a Finals
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   But a few years from now, nearly all that will be recalled of
the Knicks' great adventure was that Van Gundy must have been some
kind of coach to out-smart Miami's Pat Riley, Atlanta's Lenny
Wilkens and Indiana's Larry Bird to reach the championship.
</P>
<P>
   While he's done well in keeping the team together despite the
tumultuous events in New York, Van Gundy, in his fourth season as
head coach, isn't quite as secure as Popovich in admitting that
anyone could have done it. For good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Popovich, he's not the franchise's general manager, too.
Van Gundy's GM and chief backer, Ernie Grunfeld, was fired in
mid-April as the Knicks teetered on the edge of the playoffs. Club
president Dave Checketts then made an ill-advised overture to
Jackson about coaching the Knicks if Van Gundy were also ousted.
Word leaked, Checketts denied, then admitted his denial was a lie.
</P>
<P>
   The mess has made Van Gundy appear the victim, and so he has
been embraced and exalted by Knick fans and the tabloid media that
plays to them. He is now cast as many New Yorkers see themselves: A
gritty, proud survivor of a harsh life.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good story line but has little to do with whether he's a
capable coach. That description may well fall to him if he manages
to coax at least one win out of a series in which his team is
almost entirely overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   Popovich, on the other hand, is still trying to erase a mess of
his own doing that will take every bit of a championship aura to
obscure. On the same day in late 1996 when Robinson was returning
from the injured list, Popovich fired coach Bob Hill and replaced
him with _ Popovich.
</P>
<P>
   Completely free of previous pro head-coaching experience, the
former boss at Air Force Academy nevertheless felt he was
well-suited to do both jobs, a conclusion endorsed by club
ownership but condemned by most fans, who made the nondescript Hill
into a martyr.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as February, when the Spurs were 6-8, fans and media
were recalling Popovich's dubious ascension and undistinguished
stint as reasons to off him. Four months later, he's the architect
and engineer of the biggest event in South Texas sports history.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I read a book and got smart,'' he said Thursday, amused at
his sudden anointment. Actually what Popovich understood a little
better than some of his more obsessive contemporaries was that when
all the X's and O's fail, be sure that your best players are 7 feet
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking for myself, I would say the biggest thing that I've
learned over the years is that these players are pretty smart,'' he
said. ``And their participation is really important in trying to
put something on the court that they can really believe in and want
to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get into the league, you might think you've got some
answers and you're going to do it a certain way. It's good to have
a foundation, but I think you really need to listen, because the
players know what the hell's going on out there.''
</P>
<P>
   That conviction is a little easier to adopt when the stars are
Robinson and Duncan, two of the NBA's brightest, most even-tempered
and cooperative players. When it's Gary Payton, Allen Iverson,
Alonzo Mourning, Sprewell and a number of others, the chore is more
onerous.
</P>
<P>
   But the point is still the same in the NBA: Players remain the
name of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The other names, be they Popovich and Van Gundy, or Jackson or
Riley or Karl or Westphal, are highly interchangeable, albeit
objects who often appear larger in the rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
