<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AKERS LEADS BY EXAMPLE, STILL FUELS U.S. WOMEN'S TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, N.J. _ On a perfectly manicured field at the
private school where the U.S. Women's World Cup team practiced
Thursday, a soccer ball was driven over a fence with a thunderous
boom.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt about it. That was a Michelle Akers shot, though this
one was just a hair over the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   Akers quickly corrected herself. Her next five shots blazed
through the goalmouth, curling at wild angles past the hands of the
stand-in goalkeeper before scorching the back of the poor net.
</P>
<P>
   At age 33 and now called the grand dame of women's soccer after
her roughneck start in boys' leagues back in Seattle, some things
about Akers have not changed. Her hair is still a curled mane. Her
will to work, compete and win is still undeniable. Her Christian
faith and ministry is her bedrock.
</P>
<P>
   And that massive shot is still as potent and percussive as ever.
</P>
<P>
   It was Akers' booming foot that kicked the game-tying goal
during the semifinals of the 1996 Olympics. The U.S. was trailing
1-0 when Norway was whistled for a handball, and it was Akers who
demanded to take the penalty shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew it would go in,'' Akers said.
</P>
<P>
   After tying the score, the U.S. went on to win the game, the
gold medal and, in the process, lift recognition of women's soccer
to a new level. This World Cup is being billed as the largest
women's sporting event in the world, ever.
</P>
<P>
   What has changed, though, since Akers led the U.S. women to the
first World Cup championship in 1991 are her perspective and sense
of self-preservation.
</P>
<P>
   You learn that after years of injuries and chronic fatigue
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   What also has changed since Akers became the first lady of
soccer is her position. Where once she was a forward who ran
through every defense in the world, now Akers is the midfielder
through whom the plays must go.
</P>
<P>
   The move by U.S. coach Tony DiCicco was orchestrated a few years
back, although the only way DiCicco could convince Akers to accept
the change was to promise it would extend her stellar career.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the heavily favored U.S. women set to open the 1999
World Cup Saturday against Denmark in front of 76,000 at Giants
Stadium, everyone with an interest in seeing the U.S. women do what
they do best should be thrilled Akers is still such an integral
part of this U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates like co-captain Julie Foudy are.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all her knee injuries and concussions and Epstein-Barr
(chronic fatigue syndrome) and all that goes on, playing up top is
a lot different position. You're always getting whacked from behind
and you're taking a lot of physical contact,'' Foudy said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``With her up there as a target, she was an easy prey and
obviously taking a lot of abuse physically. So when Tony placed her
in the midfield, you're playing facing your own goal then with your
back to the goal, so she's not having to take as many hits.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what was supposed to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now instead of getting hit in the legs and from behind,
I'm just crashing into people head-on,'' Akers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Something about Akers attracts collisions and busted bones.She
has had so many knee surgeries, she can't remember how many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eleven or 12,'' she said. ``I lost track.''
</P>
<P>
   Akers was knocked out of a World Cup All-Star game last February
when she broke an orbital bone in her face, requiring more stitches
than a soccer ball and surgery, too.
</P>
<P>
   She had collided in mid-air with Norway star Linda Medalen,
another 33-year old veteran who knows that Akers is as much the key
to the U.S.'s attack as Mia Hamm, Kristine Lilly and Tiffeny
Milbrett.
</P>
<P>
   If the engine is shut down, there's a good chance the car won't
be running.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many players could go from being a great
forward to a great playmaker with a lot of touch and skill and
play-making ability and the technical ability to set play for us in
the middle,'' Foudy said about Akers.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. lost in the semifinals during the 1995 Women's World
Cup and many of the players are highly motivated to avenge this
defeat. Akers, however, is not quite so driven by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is in the forefront of a lot of their minds. In
some ways, it's their fuel. A lot of them don't want to experience
that again and I don't either, but that's not what drives me,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lessons I have learned in the World Cup, I have put them
into action for my preparation. I think what was difficult (in '95)
were all the distractions. There was a lot more attention. I
thought we overtrained. I think our legs were burnt. I think our
performance was flat. Our spring wasn't there, so our staff and our
team have made note of that and made sure not to make the same
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she has been told time and again that her chronic
fatigue symptoms would ease if she quit playing, Akers has refused.
She wants to see this thing through. What she helped start in '91
by winning the first Cup has set off a chain reaction in the sport
she loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Michelle's strength is definitely by example,'' Foudy
said. ``She's definitely vocal, but when you watch her play, she's
running over people. That's always been her strength. She's even
had to restrain herself. You can't go on and win every tackle. You
can't go and win every ball when it's 90 percent not on your favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the great thing about playing beside Michelle. You
know that any game she's going to leave everything on the field,
even a few bones and teeth. That's what you love about her and why
you love having her on your team.''
</P>
<P>
   The big engine is still running. She's the one in the middle
now, the turnstile everything must pass through.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
