<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PARKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A MEDAL FOR ROSA PARKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 18:
</P>
<P>
   With President Clinton, the congressional leadership and a
half-dozen aging warriors of the civil rights movement looking on,
Congress on Tuesday awarded its highest civilian honor, the
Congressional Gold Medal, to Rosa Parks, the heroine of the
Montgomery bus boycott.
</P>
<P>
   The medal was a long time in coming. Congress and the nation
have owed Mrs. Parks, now 86, a large debt ever since Dec. 1, 1955,
the fateful day when she refused to yield her seat to a white man
on the Cleveland Avenue bus in Montgomery, Ala., and was promptly
arrested under a city ordinance requiring segregated buses. The
arrest touched off a 381-day bus boycott organized by the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr., gave King national stature and pumped new
life into a fragile and fitful civil rights movement that, after
another decade of struggle, eventually forced Congress to approve
the watershed civil rights legislation of the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case with heroes, a few myths have attached
themselves to Mrs. Parks' story, chiefly the notion that she was
only a tired seamstress with sore feet who just wouldn't move when
the bus driver told her to. She was a seamstress all right, but she
was also a seasoned activist and an official in the Montgomery
chapter of the NAACP, which turned her case into a formal and
ultimately successful challenge to the city's bus laws. She was
indeed tired, but what had tired her was not her work but
injustice, and what anchored her to her seat _ in King's words _
were ``the accumulated indignities of days gone by and the
countless aspirations of generations yet unborn.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Parks knew that her brave act would change her life, and it
did. After a series of threats, she and her husband moved in 1957
to Detroit, where she has lived ever since. Many honors have come
her way, many streets have been named after her, but the
Congressional Gold Medal is especially fitting. For it was in
Congress that Mrs. Parks' aspirations for equal treatment were
codified, at long last, into law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
