<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN M'S SEARCH FOR SOUVENIRS OF TIGER STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ There's a general consensus that Detroit's Tiger
Stadium, which has stood at the corner of Michigan and Trumbull
since the day the Titanic sunk in 1912, has served its purpose. The
Tigers will move into new Comerica Park next season, one of five
facilities to open by the start of the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   But several Mariners were on the look out for souvenirs of their
last trip to the park, where the M's have gone 46-82.
</P>
<P>
   Video coordinator Carl Hamilton, from Benton Harbor, Mich., saw
his first baseball game from the left field upper deck at Tiger
Stadium. He had Hall of Fame Tigers broadcaster Ernie Harwell sign
a photo of the ballpark before last night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Rafael Bournigal said he wants to buy some Tiger
Stadium seats to put by the pool at his home, though he's
interested only in the green, wooden seats that used to ring the
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, I had a chance to buy some seats from the old
Comiskey Park in Chicago, for $100 each,'' Bournigal said. ``I've
always wished I'd bought them.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said he might keep the final lineup card he fills out
at Tiger Stadium, and reliever Aaron Scheffer said some players
wanted to scoop up some dirt off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Matt Mieske, a native of Midland, Mich., attended
about five Tigers games a year as a kid, and was there when Detroit
clinched the 1984 American League pennant. The first photos of
Mieske in a big league uniform were taken at Tiger Stadium, and he
also has a video of himself hitting there.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't looking for more souvenirs Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's enough,'' Mieske said. ``And just the memories _ you
can't take those away. I'll always remember the special times
coming down here with my dad. You don't need pictures to remind you
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are the first American League team to make its last
visit to Tiger Stadium this summer.
</P>
<P>
   BREAK TIME: Ever since spring training, left-hander Jeff Fassero
has maintained that the minor surgery on his throwing elbow last
winter had no affect on him. He reiterated that Thursday, and the
M's also say he is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one of the reasons Fassero is moving to the bullpen
is to give his arm a rest. The Mariners want to see Fassero work
through his problems and return to the rotation, and a lighter
workload should mean he'll be fresh for the second half of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think probably his arm is not as strong as it could be,''
Piniella said. ``Myself, I think that's a good part of it. I don't
think he's gotten back to his total arm strength. I think pitching
out of the bullpen will help him with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said pitching coach Stan Williams: ``His stuff seems to go
backwards after four or five innings. This is just speculation, but
maybe it's because he was cut on. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff is a much better pitcher than that, and he's healthy. So
there's no reason Jeff Fassero can't get back to being Jeff
Fassero.''
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: Piniella had a note waiting for him on his desk
in the visitors clubhouse Thursday. The message: ``I'm going to
play center field.'' And so Ken Griffey Jr., who had played
designated hitter the past two nights, got one more chance to play
center at Tiger Stadium. . . . The Mariners announced that the
final game at the Kingdome, on July 27 against Texas, is sold out.
Former Mariners Diego Segui, Ruppert Jones, Gaylord Perry and Alvin
Davis will be on hand for a post-game celebration. . . .
Right-hander Paul Abbott will need at least one more start for
Class AAA Tacoma before joining the M's. Abbott pitched well
Tuesday, but the Mariners would like his pitches to be a little
sharper. . . . Designated hitter Edgar Martinez, who did not start
in the four-game Detroit series, could be ready Friday. He has a
sore left elbow. . . . The Mariners had discussions about signing
former Oakland knuckleballer Tom Candiotti, who was released
Wednesday and can be signed for the minimum salary. But with Abbott
coming back and Frankie Rodriguez pitching well, the M's are
unlikely to pursue Candiotti. . . . The Mariners are the only team
in baseball without a complete game thrown for or against them this
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
