<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0241 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-STARZZ-COMETS-HNS     06-18 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-STARZZ-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Often, said Comets coach Van Chancellor, the first analytical
utterings to come from a coach's mouth after a game can be a bit
confusing and even misleading.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Such was the case Thursday night after the Comets razed the Utah
Starzz 93-73 at Compaq Center to run their record to 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening horn almost until the very end, the Comets,
spurred by the efforts of cat-quick Sheryl Swoopes, put the Starzz
in a defensive vise and by halftime already had the game well in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Chancellor began his postgame analysis, he talked
more about an offense that fed off 30 points from Cynthia Cooper
(23 in the first half) and 25 from Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   He downplayed the facet of the game Utah coach Frank Layden
pointed to as the linchpin to his team's second straight loss after
a season-opening win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense wasn't what I wanted it to be,'' Chancellor said.
``When (the lead grows) to the 20-point range, it's hard to keep
that defensive intensity. But I was pretty pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor was then informed that Layden called the Comets'
defense the key to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that got us the lead,'' Chancellor said. ``We forced
a lot of turnovers (11 in the first half, 20 for the game). They
only got two more rebounds than we did, and we had only 11
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the more I think about it, I would have to say we were
better defensively than I (originally) thought we were. I just
didn't want to give up 73 points to nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting the tone early, Swoopes had 12 points and three of her
four steals in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Utah was looking up from a 53-34 deficit by
intermission and Layden was looking for solutions to a confounding
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to our team at halftime, they (the Comets) do a
terrific job defensively,'' he said. ``They don't let you get
started; they don't let you run what you want. And they take
control of the game through a great defensive effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad for Layden and the Starzz, the Comets' defense never
rested.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper took charge of the other side of the ball, starting
slowly and then showing once more why she has been the league's
leading scorer each of the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to get some open looks because of the picks I was
getting from Tina Thompson and Polina Tzekova,'' Cooper said.
``They were really working hard to get me open, and because of that
I got a lot of open looks. When you get those type of looks, the
only thing you have to do is put them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Simply stated. And Cooper made it look easy while shooting
9-of-17 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we did well, especially on the fast break,''
Cooper said. ``We got some easy buckets because of our defense.
Once our defense got going, there's no way you could stop us.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a night when the Comets, usually prolific from 3-point
range, were only 5-of-23 from behind the arc. Yet Swoopes was
12-for-18 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson contributed 13 points and Tzekova 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets scored 17 points off the break while slowing the
Starzz, who have turned to an up-tempo game this season, to a mere
two fast-break points.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the Starzz (1-2) has usually been a huge problem for
the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   But the razor-sharp anticipation of Swoopes on defense and the
fireworks of Cooper and Swoopes negated the Comets' height
disadvantage and gave Layden some big problems of his own with
which to contend.
</P>
<P>
   Like a cat lying in the bushes ready to pounce on its prey,
Swoopes time and again in the opening period disrupted the
offensive flow of the Starzz.
</P>
<P>
   Her second steal and fast-break layup staked the Comets to a
14-8 lead. She later would tip a Utah pass into the hands of point
guard Sonja Henning.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end, Henning assisted on a layup by Cooper that
resulted in a three-point play.
</P>
<P>
   The lead was up to 19-9. But when Adrienne Goodson, one of
Utah's three American Basketball League refugees, fired in a
3-pointer three minutes later, the Starzz had cut the lead to
24-18.
</P>
<P>
   It was with Utah close at 26-20 that Cooper began to kick it
into high gear. She scored 10 of the Comets' 12 points during a
2:21 span, and Utah was suddenly looking up at a 38-26 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Down by 19 points at halftime, Utah never got closer than 15 in
the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played hard,'' said Layden, ``but we made a lot of unforced
errors. I have to give the Comets a lot of credit. They're a
terrific team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
