<HEADER>
A0243 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-DINGELL     06-18 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-DINGELL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINGELL, SEEN AS UNDERCUTTING HIS OWN PARTY, IS UNAPOLOGETIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 5th graf for updating)  (Eds: With CONGRESS-GUNS, CONGRESS-GUNS-SKETCH. Story will be
updated if necessitated by congressional voting tonight.) 
(ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo/graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1994, Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., faced the
toughest vote in his long congressional career: whether to ban
assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   A proud board member of the National Rifle Association at the
time, Dingell hated the measure. But President Clinton was urging
him to support it and his party leaders were demanding loyalty. So
Dingell, an avid hunter who adorns his Capitol Hill office with the
stuffed heads of wild boar and other game he has bagged, quit the
NRA board and voted yes, infuriating friends and even one of his
sons. He has regretted it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Months after the assault weapons ban passed, the Republicans
swept into control of Congress, stripping Dingell of his powerful
position as chairman of the Energy and Commerce Committee. He was
convinced that a major factor was his party's fervent support for
tough gun control.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Dingell has championed a measure that has
angered gun-control advocates, confounded his party leaders, given
heart to conservative Democrats squeamish about gun restrictions,
and won support from Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, the majority whip and
a fierce opponent of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell's amendment, which the House narrowly approved late
Thursday night, is a weaker alternative to a bill supported by the
House Democratic leadership that requires criminal background
checks of gun buyers at gun shows. Dingell's amendment, which has
been endorsed by the NRA, would require the checks in 24 hours, as
opposed to three days in the Democrats' bill, or let the sale
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   To the many advocates of gun control in his party, Dingell's
bill undercut the Democrats' efforts to portray Republicans as
unreasonable opponents of reasonable gun restrictions, trapped in
the pocket of the NRA. Moreover, Dingell's amendment may have
demonstrated that the Democrats are far from united on gun control,
and that the issue may not be as potent in the 2000 elections as
many Democrats had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``His bill hurts our message,'' said Rep. Louise Slaughter, a
Democrat from Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   But in Dingell's mind, he has been acting like a loyal Democrat,
trying to save his party from itself, and from a replay of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows if Democrats don't do the right thing, they are not
going to retake the House in 2000,'' said his wife, Deborah,
president of General Motors Foundation, whose advocacy of gun
control puts her in conflict with her husband's views. ``He
absolutely believes he is helping the party.''
</P>
<P>
   A barrel-chested, gruff-voiced 72-year-old whose 44 years in the
House makes him its longest-serving member, Dingell scoffs at the
suggestion that he has hurt his party, saying he has simply given
voice to the desires of his blue-collar district, which runs from
Dearborn south along Lake Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``My people love the out of doors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possibility that some felons might be more
easily able to buy guns at gun shows under his bill, Dingell leaned
his 6-foot frame into a questioner and wrapped his mittlike hands
around his shoulder. ``When do you think you will get a perfect
world?'' he asked with a wry smile. ``I'm just trying here to get a
better bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats assert that Dingell used the possibility of a
Democratic victory in 2000 to cajole his party mates to vote for
his bill. If the Democrats retake the House, Dingell would regain
his chairmanship of the powerful Commerce Committee, which controls
legislation on a wide range of matters, from telecommunications to
energy to defense contracting. As chairman in the 1980s, Dingell
was widely known as a procedural genius, a zealous investigator of
government waste, and a bit of a bully.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very powerful man,'' said Rep. Carolyn McCarthy,
D-N.Y., who is author of the other Democratic gun show bill. ``A
lot of things go through his committee. And he might be chairman
again.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Dingell replied, his voice dripping with innocence,
``Why should anyone be afraid of me?''
</P>
<P>
   Dingell, a former county prosecutor, was first elected to
Congress in 1955 to replace his father, who had held the seat for
23 years. He describes himself as an ``old-fashioned, New Deal
Democrat,'' but his record has been hard to categorize.
</P>
<P>
   With Ford Motor Co. in his district, he has frequently fought
environmentalists over air pollution regulations. But he was also a
major proponent of the Clean Water Act and Endangered Species Act.
While he has battled his party on gun control, he has carried its
banner on health care reform, currently pushing bills intended to
protect managed care consumers.
</P>
<P>
   And while he likes hunting, fishing and other traditionally
masculine sports, he is also an avid fan of the ballet and opera,
who raised his four children after divorcing his first wife.
</P>
<P>
   As an NRA board member in the 1970s, Dingell helped create the
rifle association's Institute for Legislative Affairs, which has
evolved into one of the most powerful lobbying and political action
committees in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He is also famous for calling Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms agents ``a jackbooted group of fascists'' in a 1981 NRA
promotional film. He says he has no regrets about coining the
phrase, saying, ``If it's true, what is wrong with it?''
</P>
<P>
   Dingell says he is planning on running for re-election next
year. And he says he fully expects his party to retake the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be working for it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
