<HEADER>
A0248 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPARE-RACE-KAN &LR;      06-18 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPARE-RACE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYMENTS TO DESCENDANTS WOULD HEAL WOUNDS OF SLAVERY, ADVOCATE
SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Eugene Frison sees something missing in his mostly
black neighborhood north of downtown. Few economic opportunities,
scant political power, not enough harmony with white residents.
</P>
<P>
   He has a solution.
</P>
<P>
   Frison, 74, says reparations for the descendants of slaves would
allow black Americans to catch up to the economic head start of
whites. Reparations also would bury resentment and guilt left over
from slavery, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most important issue the world has ever faced. We're
still feeling the effects,'' Frison said.
</P>
<P>
   Frison and his group, the National Coalition of Blacks for
Reparations in America, want the government to pay trillions of
dollars. The group expects about 300 people at its national
convention this weekend in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Frison has spoken at city meetings, churches and businesses. One
wall at the group's local headquarters is covered by letters to
legislators. Another wall is papered with pictures of Martin Luther
King Jr., Malcolm X and other icons.
</P>
<P>
   Many of all races are not sure the idea would work. How would
black Americans prove they descended from slaves? Where would the
money come from?
</P>
<P>
   The notion isn't new.
</P>
<P>
   After the Civil War, the government promised former slaves a
settlement of 40 acres of land and a mule. Congress passed a
reparations bill, but President Andrew Johnson vetoed it.
</P>
<P>
   Frison's rationale is this: Slaves themselves were part of the
wealth whites amassed _ some estimate they pumped $8 billion into
the economy. When they were freed, they got none of it. They found
it hard to buy land or start businesses.
</P>
<P>
   That lack of capital, coupled by Jim Crow laws, made it tougher
for black Americans to buy homes and create housing equity to pass
on.
</P>
<P>
   ``White people are living pretty good in America, and it came
through the slavery system,'' said Frison, the conference
organizer.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of reparations regained momentum in 1988 when the
government paid settlements to the families of Japanese-Americans
interned in concentration camps during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But recent reparation bills have gone nowhere in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 poll found that two-thirds of blacks support a national
apology for slavery and reparations. On the flip side, two-thirds
of whites oppose an apology and 88 percent oppose reparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of white people say black people don't need this.
They've been out of slavery for 150 years. Why should we give them
money?'' said Ray Winbush, director of the Race Relations Institute
at Fisk University in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've been using bubble gum to patch up what this country
has been doing to black Americans for centuries. This could be a
way to fix it in one fell swoop,'' Winbush said.
</P>
<P>
   Winbush said he thinks reparations will happen. Others, such as
sociologist Thomas Shapiro of Northeastern University, warn that
reparations could spur a backlash from white Americans who don't
feel responsible.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents note that most white Americans of the 1800s weren't
slaveholders. Some fought for abolition. Others point to post-Civil
War immigrants who had nothing to do with slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Frison said his group's plan demands money for education,
economic development and individual settlements. Frison said the
resources would allow black Americans to gain more power in banks,
police departments and schools.
</P>
<P>
   Frison also says black Americans need political power. He
suggests that states donate land so blacks can establish a
political base.
</P>
<P>
   If reparations happen, Frison says, affirmative action should
end.
</P>
<P>
   Frison, who worked with the Nation of Islam and as a deputy
sheriff, said his biggest challenge has been opening people's
minds. He said blacks and whites are equally skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people don't know. They just live with it because they
figure that's the way it's supposed to be. White people are going
to have to start taking it more seriously, too,'' Frison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to start by at least talking about it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
