<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0253 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAVE-FRIENDS-KAN &LR;      06-18 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVE-FRIENDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTLING DISCOVERY, PAIN UNITE DESCENDANTS OF SLAVE, SLAVEOWNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hard core. This is hard core.
</P>
<P>
   We're trying to crack the bonehard core
</P>
<P>
   Of an obscene, abominable past
</P>
<P>
   And it's worse than surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The only anesthetic is denial
</P>
<P>
   Which totally foils the operation!
</P>
<P>
   Can I do this?
</P>
<P>
   -- from ``Hard Core,'' by Ann Neel
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. -- Ann Neel and Pam Smith had come too far
to turn back. They had already discovered that their research into
family history in central Missouri would be no pleasant trip down
memory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Their families had been on opposite sides of a huge racial
divide.
</P>
<P>
   Neel had found the inventory of her
great-great-great-grandfather's belongings. Spinning wheels.
Heifers. And several black men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Smith had found records that showed her great-great-grandfather
was sold on the courthouse steps in Howard County in 1854.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, starting in 1991, they talked three times
a week on the phone, sharing their latest discoveries of Missouri
history.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their different histories, they became friends. They
shared a passion for exploring their pasts -- and how it shaped
them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Smith finally tracked down the owner of Baltimore
Robinson, her great-great-grandfather. She showed the document to
Cecy Rice, president of the Randolph County Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Rice recognized the slave owner's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that's one of Ann's,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith didn't know what she meant. Then it became clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you saying Ann's family owned my family?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Smith could barely talk. She raced back to her hotel in Moberly
and called Neel in Seattle. Smith didn't even say hello.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your family owned my family,'' she blurted.
</P>
<P>
   Neel was equally dismayed. They exchanged regrets. They hung up.
</P>
<P>
   Smith called another friend. She barely remembers the call now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never going to speak to her again,'' Smith told her.
</P>
<P>
   I am not amused by pain
</P>
<P>
   I want to ball you up
</P>
<P>
   like a messed up piece of paper
</P>
<P>
   and throw you out of my life.
</P>
<P>
   Can you believe that?
</P>
<P>
   And can you be that --
</P>
<P>
   a piece of garbage
</P>
<P>
   like your ancestors might have treated mine?
</P>
<P>
   -- from ``Wasteland,'' by Pam Smith
Genealogical sleuthing
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of slavery didn't leave Missouri untouched.
</P>
<P>
   The Dred Scott decision, which determined that slaves were not
citizens, started from a case in St. Louis. Abolitionist John Brown
launched bloody raids into the Show-Me state. Some of the Civil
War's most significant battles took place in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Neel, a professor at the University of Puget Sound near Seattle,
knew this when she returned to Missouri in 1981 to research her
genealogy.
</P>
<P>
   She often assigned family research to her students, but she also
wanted to learn about her own roots. Her most startling discovery
was that her great-great-great-grandfather, Thomas Jackson, was a
slave owner.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a communications consultant from Chicago, became
interested in genealogy in 1990 after seeing the television series
``Queen,'' a follow-up to Alex Haley's ``Roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Area researchers pointed Smith to Neel, who eagerly shared
advice.
</P>
<P>
   Sifting through documents in Moberly, Smith found the paper
trail to Baltimore Robinson, her great-great-grandfather. She began
connecting the dots to his owner.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1870 census -- the first after the Civil War -- Smith
learned Baltimore Robinson's age. That was important, because slave
owners' inventories only listed the ages and genders of slaves, not
their names.
</P>
<P>
   She found his owner by correctly guessing that, like many
slaves, he took his owner's last name. In Philip Robinson's slave
schedule, she found a black man who matched Baltimore's age.
</P>
<P>
   It all was going smoothly until she learned of Neel's
connection. Philip Robinson was Thomas Jackson's brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Now what?
</P>
<P>
   Neel was mortified. Smith was hurt. But the deepest emotions
wouldn't come until later. Both decided to ignore the initial pain
and push forward.
</P>
<P>
   Smith didn't follow through with her vow not to talk to Neel.
They began speaking on the phone, but their friendship had cooled.
</P>
<P>
   Neel finally invited Smith to visit her in Washington. Their
first meeting was awkward, but they began talking. They bared their
feelings for three hours, a conversation Neel recorded and
transcribed.
</P>
<P>
   Their frankest exchanges have always come through poetry they
exchange. The dialogue started with Smith's ``Wasteland,'' which
spawned Neel's ``Hard Core.'' In the written word, they have shared
anger, guilt and fear.
</P>
<P>
   But they agreed on one important point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that we really needed to do something about the
connection. It seemed almost cosmic that this happened,'' Neel
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask me if I apologized to Pam,'' she added. ``I
didn't apologize to her because I didn't personally do it. But I
took responsibility for it. I can't change what they did. But I can
try to do something to make amends or give something back to making
it better.''
</P>
<P>
   If I had to answer for all my father's sins
</P>
<P>
   I would be in hell --
</P>
<P>
   Precisely where this tunnel seems to lead.
</P>
<P>
   Am I willing to stay this righteous path?
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
<P>
   -- from ``Hard Core'' by Neel
Anger into action
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Neel and Smith will present 10 talks throughout
Missouri, part of a series called ``Entangled Lives: Facing Our
Slaveholding Past.''
</P>
<P>
   They will speak in St. Joseph on July 24 and at the University
of Missouri-Kansas City on July 25. Springfield is using their July
15 presentation to launch a citywide project on race relations.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites are Macon, St. Louis, Fayette and Sedalia.
</P>
<P>
   At their first presentation, last week in Jefferson City, Neel
and Smith showed slides of their families' journey through slavery,
segregation and racial understanding.
</P>
<P>
   They don't gloss over their own struggles to stay friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people relate to us because we've had our own share of
struggles and conflict. We're no different than a lot of the people
we're talking to,'' Smith said. ``The difference is we are
committed to barreling through.''
</P>
<P>
   And they do.
</P>
<P>
   Both women have faced resistance from their own loved ones.
Smith said her friends don't understand why she wants anything to
do with Neel. Neel said her family is upset that she is making
their history so public.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the resistance is part of their own blood. Both say
their fathers had little love for people of other races.
</P>
<P>
   But they hope to see the fruits of their discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Before each presentation, they ask city residents about what
specific issues are relevant. In nearby Moberly, for example, many
black and white residents are upset about a recent Ku Klux Klan
recruiting drive.
</P>
<P>
   In another presentation outside Missouri, a white audience
member confided to Smith that he used to fear black people. She was
glad he told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happens when people are not afraid to penetrate
the surface, to understand the differences,'' Smith said. ``Once
that dialogue starts, it allows healing to take place.''
</P>
<P>
   Neel added: ``On the deepest level, it's letting people see that
it's possible to have honest communication. It doesn't mean that
it's going to be happily ever after.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith compares their experience to climbing a mountain. She had
climbed Mount Kilimanjaro on a trip to research slave history in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The women know it would be much safer to stay at base camp and
not strive for more. By aiming higher, they risk it all. But the
reward might be greater than they can imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Smith writes about their quest in the final passage of
``Wasteland.''
</P>
<P>
   To every person, their conscience
</P>
<P>
   For every moment,
</P>
<P>
   an opportunity lush with hope.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kilimanjaro on a rainy day
</P>
<P>
   through the mud, over the danger zones,
</P>
<P>
   on toward the summit...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 0126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
