<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0256 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDGE-TEENS-SPI &LR;      06-18 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-TEENS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CARD, A CALL AND TEENS CAN GET SAFE RIDE HOME AFTER PARTYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TRACY JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISSAQUAH, Wash. _ Issaquah District Court Judge Mary Ann
Ottinger sees a parade of grim-faced teenagers in court trying to
explain the drunken-driving charges against them.
</P>
<P>
   Many face stiff fines, or loss of their license, or the wrath of
their parents. Some are lucky to be alive, Ottinger says, after
spinning off the road in a beer-clouded haze or barreling into a
tree.
</P>
<P>
   And far too many claim they drove because they ``had to get
home.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a poor excuse, and it has even less weight now that the
judge and some of her friends are offering to do the driving.
</P>
<P>
   Her Safe Rides program has put cards in the hands of roughly
1,000 Skyline High School students in Issaquah, a suburb of Seattle
across Lake Washington. The cards list telephone numbers for adults
promising to be on-call, confidential chauffeurs.
</P>
<P>
   Ottinger said she doesn't want students to feel they must decide
between weaving their way home or calling their parents, because
many are much more afraid to do the latter. And taxis aren't easy
to find in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to provide them with another option,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ottinger and the eight volunteers _ one a Skyline secretary, the
rest parents of students _ want the kids to know they won't rat
them out to their parents. Nor will they lecture young passengers
about alcohol or drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The cards themselves read ``no questions asked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point is just to get these kids home if they made a
mis-take,'' said volunteer Jane Stoeklin.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers say they haven't yet received any calls, but they're
ready for this weekend's keg-party potential. Skyline seniors
graduate Friday. Everyone else will be sprung for the summer next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Knight, an 18-year-old graduating Friday, keeps the
card tucked in her backpack. She says her parents would happily
pick her up from a party if she needed them, but she's seen plenty
of other kids stagger to their cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens every weekend. Everybody drinks and drives _ it's
pretty scary,'' she said. Teens ``are going to drink no matter
what, but if you can prevent them from driving, you might save a
life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good idea,'' agreed Chris Jenkins, a junior.
``I hope a lot of people will use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others didn't think they needed help _ they would just spend the
night or hop in a car anyway because, as one boy put it, ``I trust
my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But recent tragedies east of Lake Sammamish have made parents
particularly wary. On the Sammamish Plateau last month, 19-year-old
Ryan Scott Wilson died in a wreck in which, police say, the driver
had been drinking. About 18 months earlier, 17-year-old Guy Kelly
was killed when his car slammed into a tree after a party.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have so little experience in driving by itself, that when
you add alcohol to it, it's frightening,'' said Mary Weeks, who
eagerly volunteered to join Safe Rides.
</P>
<P>
   Before starting the program, Ottinger talked over the idea with
her sons, both teens at Skyline, and their friends.
</P>
<P>
   They told her they might use it, and that they'd be more likely
to call if they were assured their parents wouldn't find out.
</P>
<P>
   And if their friends' parents were listed on the card, well,
they'd definitely call someone else. The confidentiality of
strangers seemed to be the key, Ottinger said.
</P>
<P>
   She wasn't sure if they'd be leery about calling a judge, though
she pledges the same secrecy she asks from volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea hit Ottinger last year, when she visited a high school
and overheard hallway chatter about the previous weekend's drunken
bash. She heard one boy telling his buddies he was sloshed when he
climbed into his car, and she cringed to hear why he decided to
drive anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no choice. I had to get home. I had to drive,'' Ottinger
heard him explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to reach out and say, `Why didn't you call
me?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And now he can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
