<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS AT KANSAS CITY SCHOOLS IS UNEVEN, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR and TANIKA WHITE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- The Kansas City School District is making
uneven progress in improving classroom instruction, according to a
new report.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Gouwens, an assistant professor of education at Roosevelt
University in Chicago, also found problems with the district's
efforts to train teachers in the 12 schools she visited this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur A. Benson II, attorney for the plaintiff children in the
district's desegregation case, has commissioned Gouwens for several
years to tour schools and issue the report.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Chase, the district's interim chief administrator for
curriculum and instruction, said Thursday she had not seen the
report but wasn't surprised by the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like everyone to make a quantum leap, but it's unrealistic
to believe everyone is going to progress at the same time and on
the same level,'' Chase said. ``It's our job as administrators to
continue delivering the information and training until everyone is
functioning at a high level.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the report focused on efforts to improve instruction,
raise academic performance and implement a core curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Gouwens found that some schools and teachers were making great
strides and others were doing little or nothing to change.
</P>
<P>
   Benson noted that this year's evaluation is less critical than
previous ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed teachers in many cases are working a lot harder, in
many instances finding ways to overcome the academic inertia of the
district and make improvements on their own,'' Benson said. ``It
raises the question of how much faster and further we could go if
we had strong administrative support.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems remain, the report shows.
</P>
<P>
   During one visit, for example, an English teacher at Middle
School of the Arts did nothing to engage students who dozed, kept
their books closed or otherwise did not participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When students asked if their answers were correct, the teacher
made no attempt to teach...leading the observer to wonder if the
point of the lesson was to complete the exercise or to know
something about adverb phrases,'' Gouwens wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, a science teacher at the same school took a rubber
band from a student and then used it to demonstrate kinetic and
potential energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't know you were doing something scientific, did
you?'' the teacher said.
</P>
<P>
   Benson said he was disturbed that the core curriculum, which
explains what a student should know and be able to do in each
subject at each grade level, is not in full use three years after
being approved by the school board.
</P>
<P>
   At Lincoln College Prep, for example, Gouwens reported seeing
copies of the curriculum on teachers' desks but little or no
evidence of it in their instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Some principals and teachers said large turnovers in student
population caused problems this year.
</P>
<P>
   At Southeast High School, for example, only 75 of this year's
1,275 students attended the school the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   At Rogers Middle School, Principal Sally Newell said the change
from a magnet to a neighborhood school brought many challenges,
including lower attendance, less parent involvement, more problems
with drugs, larger class sizes and more staff turnover.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Newell said ``Without the drawing card of our
magnet theme, it's going to be real important to continue to find
ways to build community with our students and parents.... It may
involve us getting a lot more active in the life of the
neighborhood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
