<SLUG> BC-CHIMP-BABE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD CHIMP BORN AT L.A. ZOO AS KEEPERS PUZZLE OVER PATERNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The chimpanzees at the Los Angeles Zoo made
monkeys out of the keepers again, as a third surprise pregnancy
yielded another baby Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, zoo keepers don't know the identity of the father,
but they insist the Casanova isn't going to remain anonymous for
long.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day the new 4-pound male arrived, officials shipped
off blood and tissue samples from all male chimpanzees in the
exhibit for paternity testing. They expect to know within 30 to 60
days which male or males, all of whom they thought were unable to
reproduce, impregnated three female chimpanzees within the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a couple of months before we know who the father
is,'' said Manuel Mollinedo, director of the zoo. ``Obviously chimp
parentage isn't a high priority at these DNA labs.''
</P>
<P>
   All six of the exhibit's male chimpanzees in breeding age have
had vasectomies.
</P>
<P>
   The latest addition to the zoo was born to 15-year-old Regina at
the Chimpanzees of Mahale Mountains exhibit. The healthy infant was
placed in a nursery, where it will be hand-raised by zoo keepers,
along with another 6-week-old chimp named Jean.
</P>
<P>
   The new baby is being fed infant formula and was given a plush
toy chimpanzee that was rubbed on its mother for her scent to help
him adjust to the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newborn is doing very well considering that he is only a
couple of days old,'' said Jenny McNary, curator of mammals. ``His
presence in the nursery will be wonderful for Jean who now has a
companion.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials have not named the baby, but plan on announcing a
name contest within the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to remove the babies from the 13-member troop was
made because of the death of another infant and a threat to baby
Jean. Last month a 4-month-old baby chimpanzee, Toshi, died in the
exhibit after young male chimps fatally injured her while
roughhousing.
</P>
<P>
   Jean was removed after young male chimpanzees snatched the baby
from its mother, Gracie, and Jerrard, a 9-year-old chimp, grabbed
the baby from the other juvenile males in an apparent power play.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo keepers considered segregating Gracie and her baby from the
other chimps but decided that would both cause a rift in the
chimpanzee troop and cause Gracie great distress.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the baby chimps will make daily visits to the main
exhibit. After 18 months, zoo staff will evaluate whether the
chimps should move into the exhibit permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Mollinedo said the troop was in the midst of a power play of
sorts. The upstart Jerrard has been maneuvering to take control of
the group from Judeo, 22. Prior to the chaos of the last year, the
zoo's chimp family had raised seven infant chimps since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The paternity debacle started with the birth of Toshi.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
