<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WALKING THE PLANK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just wait. Sometimes it'll take an inning, maybe
two, and other times it happens late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But, inevitably, something will go wrong, almost as if the
Dodgers are waiting for it.
</P>
<P>
   For Chan Ho Park and the Dodgers, that time arrived in a
decisive five-run seventh inning in which mental errors combined
with the physical. It enabled the Pittsburgh Pirates to win the
finale of the three-game series 8-3 Thursday night at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It dropped the Dodgers (30-34) to 4-10 in June. They haven't won
back-to-back games since June 4-5 and have lost five of six to the
Pirates this season. The Dodgers have also lost eight of 10 and 11
of 15. And Kevin Brown remains the only Dodgers starter to win this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates outfielder Brant Brown hit a pair of solo homers off
Park. It was his first multi-homer game of the season; three of
those five homers came during this three-game series. Brown was
also walked intentionally, hit by a pitch with the bases loaded and
popped to third in the ninth in his bid for his third homer.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates leadoff hitter Al Martin had three hits, walked twice
and was a homer shy of hitting for the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was that good for the Dodgers. Park (4-4) allowed seven
runs on 11 hits in 61/3 innings. He struck out seven but walked
four in throwing 112 pitches. By contrast, Pirates starter Kris
Benson (4-6) allowed three runs _ one earned _ in 61/3 innings and
didn't walk a batter.
</P>
<P>
   The five-run seventh also turned a solid Park outing into
another abysmal one. Park returned from a seven-game suspension
(punishment for punching and kicking the Angels' Tim Belcher during
a fight) to pitch six strong innings, only to have the effort
evaporate in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's homers in the third and fifth gave the Pirates a 2-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game Park said he felt refreshed and strong after the
layoff, then had his troubles in the seventh. And a poor decision
by rookie catcher Angel Pena didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates starter Kris Benson began the inning with a single to
right. Martin walked and Ed Sprague sacrificed the runners over.
But Pena threw to third to try and get Benson, who slid in safe.
Brian Giles then doubled in a pair of runs to give the Pirates a
4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Park struck out Kevin Young, but another run scored on Jason
Kendall's infield single to third. Park walked Warren Morris to
load the bases before being replaced by Doug Bochtler.
</P>
<P>
   But for the third time in four games a Dodgers pitcher hit a
batter to force in a run. Jamie Arnold did it twice Wednesday, and
Bochtler joined the club when he hit Brown as the Pirates went
ahead 6-1. Abraham Nunez's fielder's choice made it 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers cut the lead to 7-3 in the bottom of the inning with
RBI doubles from Eric Karros and Devon White.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates, a ballclub built on doing the little things, added
a run in the eighth by doing just that. Martin led off with a
double, moved to third on a short fly ball in foul territory and
scored on a perfect squeeze bunt by Adrian Brown to go ahead 8-3.
It was wonderful execution of what the Dodgers tried to do earlier
in the game, only to have Park bunt the ball foul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 0132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
