<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AGENCY ORDERS PART OF PIPELINE INVOLVED IN ACCIDENT
CLOSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLINGHAM, Wash. _ Federal regulators worried about the safety
of the Olympic pipeline are ordering the company that operates it
to keep the northern end of the 400-mile line closed and run some
other segments with less fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't reopen it until we're satisfied of the safety of
reopening it,'' said Kelley Coyner, administrator of the U.S.
Transportation Department's Research and Special Programs
Administration. That branch of the DOT is responsible for
regulating pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   The order will compel Olympic Pipe Line Co., whose pipeline
ruptured and then caused a deadly fire in Bellingham last week, to
make safety improvements on the line, including installing new
valves; to double check the computer that operates it; and to
inspect the pipe. Officials emphasized that the safety improvements
are needed but are not necessarily an indication of what caused the
rupture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is totally expected, and these are areas that we are
looking at,'' said Joann Hamick, a spokeswoman for Renton-based
Olympic Pipe Line. ``We planned to test everything and do
everything that needs to be done to make sure it's safe before we
are operating. We would do that regardless (of federal orders).''
</P>
<P>
   The rupture and fire cut off two refineries from the pipeline,
leaving it with only two other supplying refineries in Anacortes.
</P>
<P>
   That has left the pipeline operating at 45 percent of its daily
14 million-gallon capacity. Already, refineries are using more
barges to ship fuel to customers and may increase such shipments,
depending on how much regulators order pressure in the pipeline to
be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic had no record of violations with federal regulators
until its 16-inch pipeline ruptured into Bellingham's Whatcom Creek
last week, spilling about 277,000 gallons of fuel into the creek.
Gasoline vapor ignited, creating a fireball that killed two boys. A
teenager also died after being overcome by fumes and drowning.
Bellingham officials said Thursday that they believe the two boys
ignited the fire as they played with a butane fireplace lighter.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers were working late into the night in Washington, D.C.,
Thursday putting the final touches on the Transportation
Department's order. It was expected to be sent by overnight mail to
Olympic Pipe Line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making sure we are confident of the integrity of the
line,'' Coyner said. ``We're making sure it's safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department's order will keep closed the upper
37 miles of the pipeline. That section carries gasoline, diesel
fuel and jet fuel from refineries at Cherry Point and Ferndale,
through Bellingham, and on south to Allen in Skagit County.
</P>
<P>
   At Allen, a pipeline from the west brings petroleum products
from the two refineries in Anacortes to the main line. The pipeline
will continue to operate with fuel from those two refineries, but
at reduced pressure in at least some sections, Transportation
Department spokeswoman Patricia Klinger said.
</P>
<P>
   That will likely reduce the amount of fuel heading south to
Seattle and Portland. About 60 percent is gasoline, but the line
also supplies Sea-Tac Airport, which uses about 1.5 million gallons
of jet fuel every day. The pipeline also supplies Portland's
airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're worried about the integrity of the line, but Seattle
also has a need for the product,'' Klinger said.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department's action against Olympic has not
been used often. It took similar action earlier this decade against
the Colonial Pipeline Co., which operates more than 5,000 miles of
pipeline from Texas to New York. Colonial had major spills in 1991
in South Carolina and 1993 in Virginia, prompting the National
Transportation Safety Board to issue a special report on pipeline
safety and federal oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty serious order,'' Coyner said of the action
against Olympic. ``I would say we do a fairly small number of
these.''
</P>
<P>
   Klinger said the Transportation Department took the action
because regulators worried that Olympic would soon return to normal
operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to put replacement pipe back in and start up,,'
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-mile section has been closed since the June 10explosion
and would have likely remained closed perhaps into July. The
damaged section of pipe hasn't been removed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Thursday that job may take two weeks. Among other
things, a water line nearby must be moved before the damaged
pipeline can be dug up.
</P>
<P>
   Klinger said the order that will be delivered Friday will impose
several requirements on Olympic for the first section of the
pipeline:
</P>
<P>
   _Make sure the computer system that controls, monitors and
detects leaks on the pipeline is operating properly. The company
will have to perform an in-depth analysis of the system, known as
SCADA for supervisory control and data acquisition. Olympic's
computer system crashed about an hour, then a backup system crashed
before the first reports of a leak in Bellingham.
</P>
<P>
   _Test all block valves, which can stop the flow of fuel, in
populated and environmentally sensitive areas and correct any
problems.
</P>
<P>
   _Determine whether more block valves _ which stop the flow of
fuel in the pipeline _ are needed and produce a schedule for their
installation.
</P>
<P>
   _Install an additional check valve near the water treatment
plant in Bellingham; the rupture occurred near the treatment plant.
A check valve operates something like a pet door. It is open as
fuel passes through the pipeline, but closes without any fuel. It
closes automatically, keeping fuel from backwashing.
</P>
<P>
   _Make sure any plan for corrective action on the 34-year-old
pipeline includes a way to deal with corrosion.
</P>
<P>
   _Internally inspect the line for corrosion and pressure-test the
line.
</P>
<P>
   Coyner said she couldn't estimate how long it would take to make
the safety improvements. But she said her agency could order more
actions by Olympic, especially after the ruptured section of pipe
is removed, then analyzed for corrosion and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to federal regulators, the state of Washington will
take a close look at pipeline safety.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke, who toured the site of the blast in Bellingham
Thursday, said he will set up a team to look at ways to prevent
accidents like the Olympic spill and to improve response to such
emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   The team will look to see whether gaps exist between federal and
state regulation of pipelines, whether local police and fire
departments need to update response plans and whether regional
command teams should be set up to respond to pipeline spills.
</P>
<P>
   The team will include the state fire marshal, representatives
from local jurisdictions and officials from the state's Emergency
Management Division, Transportation and Utilities Commission and
the Ecology Department.
</P>
<P>
   Locke himself also has a major role in regulating pipelines. He
will have the final say on whether Olympic will be allowed to build
a 231-mile pipeline across the Cascades from near Woodinville to
Pasco.
</P>
<P>
   Locke would not discuss Thursday how he is likely to decide on
the cross-Cascades pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed pipeline would go through Snoqualmie, North Bend,
Kittitas and Pasco.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Post-Intelligencer reporters Lisa Stiffler and Ellis E.
Conklin contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
