<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0264 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURVEY-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-18 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURVEY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ore., Wash.) 
ADVERTISING: MICROSOFT DROPS WIEDEN &AMP; KENNEDY FOR McCANN-ERICKSON 
 (rk) 
 By   STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A five-year relationship between the Microsoft Corp. and Wieden
&AMP; Kennedy in Portland, Ore., ended abruptly Thursday, as Microsoft
dismissed the agency and shifted its corporate brand account, with
billings estimated at $100 million, to McCann-Erickson Worldwide
Advertising, a newcomer to the company's roster.
</P>
<P>
   Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, best known for its clever campaigns for Nike
Inc., had once been Microsoft's principal American agency. It
created Microsoft's first brand campaigns, image-polishing ads that
appeared on television, in print and on the Internet carrying the
theme ``Where do you want to go to today?''
</P>
<P>
   But after a partnership with Wieden &AMP; Kennedy that at times
turned turbulent, Microsoft clearly concluded that it was time to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision,'' Robert J. Herbold, executive vice
president and chief operating officer at Microsoft in Redmond,
Wash., said in a telephone interview. ``We've had to make a very
difficult choice between two world-class agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift, effective immediately, was described as a mutual
parting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is a unique company,'' Dan Wieden, president and
chief creative officer at Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, said in a statement.
``Our relationship has been intense, filled with highs and lows,
but it has run its course.''
</P>
<P>
   The change is emblematic of the spate of rapid account changes
that has rocked Madison Avenue recently. One week last month, for
instance, accounts with billings estimated at $600 million left
their old agencies for new ones.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft move, which consolidates Microsoft's corporate and
product advertising at offices of McCann-Erickson, deprives Wieden
&AMP; Kennedy of one of its largest clients. The agency's worldwide
billings last year were estimated at $790 million; besides Nike,
other big clients include Coca-Cola Co. and the Miller Brewing Co.
unit of Philip Morris Cos.
</P>
<P>
   But the loss has wider implications for Wieden &AMP; Kennedy because
Microsoft _ even with all its antitrust and other problems _ is a
prestigious client in a red-hot marketing category, technology.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the trade publication Adweek reported that Wieden had
told agency colleagues during one of their perpetual struggles on
the Nike account that Microsoft represented the agency's future.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Microsoft loss was foreshadowed when in April the
company withdrew the assignment as agency of record for the Windows
operating system in the United States from Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, which
helped introduce the two previous versions, Windows 95 and Windows
98.
</P>
<P>
   The next shoe dropped May 27, when Microsoft named
McCann-Erickson to handle American duties for Windows after a
review. Spending has not been determined pending plans to introduce
Windows 2000, but trade publications estimated the budget at $50
million to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be at a disadvantage to have two agencies trying to
do two different things,'' Herbold said, referring to Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy's handling of brand campaigns and McCann-Erickson's
handling of product campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if it was not common practice among many advertisers
to divide image and product accounts between two agencies, Herbold
replied: ``You don't want to confuse consumers as to what Microsoft
is. If one campaign is more in depth about our trademark and one
campaign is more in depth about specific business solutions and
products, that's hard to do with two agencies. That was the dilemma
we faced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had no dissatisfaction with the work on the corporate
image effort'' by Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, Herbold said. ``The work
running now is probably the best we've ever produced.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``in recent weeks, as we've been evaluating our plans for
television advertising for fiscal year '00, which begins in July
1999,'' he added, ``it became clear that moving to a unified
advertising strategy with a single agency would best address our
overall marketing needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Herbold said that he had discussed the decision with Wieden
``over the course of this week.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Wieden said Wieden &AMP; Kennedy would not dismiss the
employees who have worked on the Microsoft account. ``Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy has built a uniquely talented technology team,'' he said.
``Due to the growth in this category and the success in creating
such an experienced group, the agency will keep the team intact for
new business opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   To land the Windows assignment last month, McCann-Erickson
teamed up with a sibling agency under the Interpublic Group of
Cos.' umbrella, Anderson &AMP; Lembke in San Francisco, which had
handled other tasks for Microsoft. McCann-Erickson merged its San
Francisco office with Anderson &AMP; Lembke last week to form an agency
named McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L.
</P>
<P>
   The New York and Seattle offices of McCann-Erickson, which are
collaborating with McCann-Erickson/A&AMP;L on the Windows work, will
also pitch in on the new Microsoft corporate brand assignment, said
John J. Dooner Jr., chairman and chief executive at McCann-Erickson
in New York, a unit of McCann-Erickson World Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't anticipate this,'' Dooner said in a telephone
interview, referring to the consolidation. ``We're excited and
thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what changes McCann-Erickson might make to Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy's ads, Dooner said: ``We'll be making an assessment of what
needs to be revised or modified. We will respect what exists that's
working.''
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft corporate account is the most recent in a lengthy
list of gains by McCann-Erickson; others include DuPont, Gateway, a
company to be spun off from Hewlett-Packard, Lowe's and Sprint.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
