<HEADLINE>
AVRE GROWS UP FAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CULVER CITY -- Patience Avre is a mere 23 years old, but by
Sunday evening she will be a veteran of her second World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerian forward is making a name for herself on a team
whose most recognizable figure is veteran forward Mercy Akide,
nicknamed ``Marvelous'' Mercy for her on-field exploits.
</P>
<P>
   Avre, who has played with Akide since 1995 on the national team,
has learned plenty from her, but it doesn't stop there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learn a lot from her,'' said Avre, who sports streaks of
magenta in her hair, ``but she learns a lot from me. We all learn a
lot from each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Nigeria is out to prove it is more than a one-woman
team, although that portrayal has more to do with certain media
perceptions than an actual feeling within the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what I saw in the practice this morning, there are so
many weapons on this team, from the goalkeeper to the (11th player
on the field),'' said Julius Ujeh, one of the team's media liasons.
``If any team is going to just concentrate on Mercy Akide, they got
another thing coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy scrimmaged a local under-17 Olympic Development Team on
Thursday at Loyola Marymount with the Italians coming out on top,
4-0, after a scoreless first half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
