<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CRITICAL VIEW _ EVERYTHING'S FINE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The easiest thing you could do Friday morning is rip
the Red Sox for what they did Thursday night. In fact, I think it
would be the perfect antidote to road rage. Instead of releasing
your frustrations on fellow drivers in gridlocked traffic, you
should first vent about the Sox. It can be done in less than 30
seconds. And you'll feel better, too.
</P>
<P>
   You could start with Pat Rapp. He gave up four runs in the first
inning and seven in three-plus innings of work. Afterward, he
explained his eventual 8-7 loss to the Twins by saying, ``They just
hit the holes.'' He also added, ``They just put the bat on the
ball.'' Also: ``Four quick ones is hard to rebound from. We did and
I just kept letting them get more.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, Pat.
</P>
<P>
   Or you could talk about the way Jose Offerman dunked the ball.
Second basemen aren't supposed to dunk. But that's what Offerman
did in the fourth inning. He tried to make a relay throw and wound
up throwing the ball into the grass. It traveled about 7 feet.
Offerman said the ball simply slipped out of his hand. It was such
a horrific play that Pedro Martinez must have been hiding from the
official scorer rather than flashing him with the choke sign.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman's basketball play was far less glamorous than that of
Twins left fielder Jacque Jones, who tried to avoid the tag by
leaping over Jason Varitek and grazing the plate. Jones missed, so
he then tried to juke Varitek and touch the plate. He missed again.
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, shredding the Sox is easy. But I won't do that.
Actually, I'm here to tell you how good they look. I'm here to tell
you that, in the next couple weeks, they could easily distance
themselves from their wild-card competitors. And, yes, I'm even
here to say that I'm not so sure that everyone should be conceding
the American League East to the Yankees; the Sox just might win it.
</P>
<P>
   Before I get to that, may I request 30 more seconds of road rage
prevention? The Sox had Trot Nixon on third base with no one out in
the eighth. They trailed by a run. They had Offerman, John
Valentin, and Nomar Garciaparra coming up. Offerman lined out.
Valentin and Garciaparra struck out. No runs. Jimy Williams would
say later that he saw ``cows jumping over the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   But you know why I like the Sox? They know how to slump. Less
than two weeks ago, they began a stretch in which they lost 7 of 8.
Their closer, Tom Gordon, had a saves streak snapped at 54. One of
their starting pitchers, Bret Saberhagen, went on the disabled list
because he cut his foot with glass at a party (imagine if he had
decided to walk over burning coals). They released a local
reliever, Jim Corsi, and asked him to join the front office. And
they recalled a local infielder, Lou Merloni, after he had asked
the team to trade him because he didn't foresee the team recalling
him.
</P>
<P>
   After all of that chaos and turnover, take a look at the
standings. The Sox trail the Yankees by a half game. That's it. A
half game. They started Rapp, one of their least reliable pitchers,
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night and still could have swept the Twins if someone had
stepped up in the eighth. And just in case you are concerned about
Rapp, Ramon Martinez (a 123-game winner who has never had an ERA
above 4) is gradually making his way toward the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of you still want to vent, right? But before you get too
engaged in that, there is also the issue of the schedule. Of the
Sox' next 20 games, 16 are against the Orioles, White Sox and Devil
Rays. The only interesting thing about Tampa Bay is watching Jose
Canseco hit home runs. But the Sox can easily squash the hopes of
Baltimore and Chicago by doing what they did to the Twins: taking
three out of four.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they won't win much if they continue to play like
they did Thursday night. You can usually look at the Sox and say,
``Now there's a team that reflects its manager.'' Solid. Measured.
Not much flash. But they looked a little ragged Thursday &UR;  &LR; night.
Williams was asked if that was atypical of his team. ``Not sure
what that means,'' he said. Later, someone asked him if it was
ironic that his team, usually desperate for runs, scored more than
five runs and lost. ``I don't know about irony,'' he said. ``Is
that atypical?''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone got a laugh out of that one and eventually moved out of
Williams's office. The manager won't look ahead, but he knows there
isn't too much to fear in the AL. His team has already played well
against the Indians and Yankees, two division leaders. This
weekend, it gets the Rangers. What exactly is there to fear? We are
heading toward the All-Star break and the New Yorkers still haven't
soared away as most people expected.
</P>
<P>
   The easiest thing to do this morning? Praise the Sox. But let's
get back to that rage thing. Hey, Dan Duquette. What's up, man?
When are you going to trade for a power hitter?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
