</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICKS-GORE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL GORE, REP. NORM DICKS HAVE FORGED LASTING FRIENDSHIP OVER THE
YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON AND JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Norm Dicks, the gruff linebacker from Bremerton,
Wash., and Al Gore, the smooth-talking newsman from Carthage,
Tenn., were rivals when they first met because they had something
in common: they were the two best-connected members of Congress'
1976 freshman class.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore and Dicks quickly became personal friends and political
allies. They will be together in Seattle on Friday as Gore touches
down on the last stop of a tour launching his campaign for the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign Chairman Tony Coelho describes Washington as a
``critical'' state on Gore's path to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In a business where friendships get strained in the quest for
power, and sometimes are broken by disagreements of principle, Gore
and Dicks have forged a lasting relationship important to both men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norm is one of my very closest friends in the Congress, and he
and (wife) Suzie have been close friends to Tipper and me for
almost a quarter century,'' Gore said in a telephone interview
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It began with a competition between two House rookies eager to
win a seat on the money-dispensing House Appropriations Committee.
Gore could be seen walking the corridors of the Capitol with his
biggest asset in tow _ his father, former three-term Sen. Albert
Gore Sr., D-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   But Dicks was no novice to Capitol infighting and had his own
patrons _ former boss, Sen. Warren Magnuson, and two powerful
colleagues, Rules Committee member Lloyd Meeds and House
Agriculture Committee Chairman Tom Foley, all Washington Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks recognized that the affable Gore was more popular among
the freshman class, but he successfully persuaded his fellow
freshmen not to choose among themselves but to let the committee
assignment be made by the old bulls of the House leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than two decades later, Dicks still sits in that seat
on his beloved Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks says jokingly that he deserves credit for the vice
president's subsequent success: Gore wound up on the Commerce
Committee, where he managed to garner tremendous publicity from a
series of hearings and launched himself into the Senate. Gore
agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a few days of that competition, we were competing
against each other on the basketball court, and competing on the
same team (in Congress) and we became close friends,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a similar sense of humor, we both laugh a lot together
and we both married above ourselves,'' he added. ``We also both
remember the old days ... and we share a common set of historical
memories from that era. We can talk in a kind of a shorthand that
some others don't understand right away, because we're referring to
debates that took place 30 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has appointed Dicks as one of two congressmen trying to
rally support for the vice president in the House, and he is
looking to Dicks to help him raise money and win support around the
country, not least in Seattle, where Mayor Paul Schell has endorsed
Gore's primary rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington state is critical to our election in November of
2000, and we're also very conscious of the primary,'' Coelho said.
``Norm is very engaged in giving us the state of the state,
politically and otherwise. When I decided to do this job, Al and I
talked about his friends that we trusted, and Norm was on that list
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dicks, who counts himself both a fan and friend of the vice
president, also has much to gain.
</P>
<P>
   In a Gore administration, Dicks could be a contender for
director of Central Intelligence or secretary of Defense. Even if
Dicks remains in Congress, which he believes is likely, he could be
chairman of the Interior Appropriations Subcommittee in a
Democrat-run House. Together, he and the environmentally conscious
Gore would be in a unique position to tackle the ticklish natural
resources problems of the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Congress, I enjoy my job on the Appropriations
Committee, I am not seeking anything else and, frankly, Gore is
going to need allies in the Congress,'' Dicks said. ``I'd love to
be chairman of the Interior Appropriations Subcommittee with Al
Gore as president of the United States. We could take care of the
parks in this country, the Everglades, and do the right things in
Washington state for salmon, restoring those species up and down
the West Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said it is too early to talk about what role Dicks might
play in a Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year friendship between Dicks and Gore, forged in those
first weeks as freshmen, was nurtured in the 1980s by two shared
passions: arms control and basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are similarities in personality, albeit camouflaged,''
said former Rep. Al Swift, D-Wash. ``Al Gore is a very aggressive,
very bright, on-the-move guy who has never been publicity shy. And
so is Norm. (And ) they were not your standard, knee-jerk
conservative Democrats. Al and Norm reflected a Henry Jackson-type
position, strong on defense but quite liberal on domestic policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dicks and Gore were at the center of a group of Democrats in
Congress who supported the controversial MX missile as a lever to
get President Reagan to back away from confrontation with the
Soviet Union and to support some degree of nuclear arms control.
</P>
<P>
   The two also were among a group of competitors who bonded in the
House gym.
</P>
<P>
   Gore tells the story of how Dicks, a one-time University of
Washington linebacker, would shout ``Huskies'' each time he made a
long shot. And Dicks still marvels at a trick shot Gore had
perfected in the shooting contest called horse, in which Gore would
bounce the ball off the wall and into the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were both hard-chargers; they're a lot alike,'' said
former Gov. Mike Lowry, who served in the House with them.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship was cemented in 1988. Dicks was one of a
handful of House members to endorse Gore in his ill-fated first
campaign for president. After it was over, Dicks helped Gore raise
money to retire his debt.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Dicks again is helping Gore in the House and in
Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norm has just one gear, and that's full speed ahead,'' said
Rep. Bart Gordon, D-Tenn., who is co-chairing the Gore effort in
the House with Dicks. So far, the two have lined up 180 of the 211
House Democrats to support Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been the Clinton administration's point man on such
Northwest issues as helping forest communities hurt by logging
cuts. Gore is central to the administration's efforts to help the
Northwest pay for salmon conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks credits Gore with helping to force a renegotiation of the
U.S.-Canada salmon treaty, and with helping to steer the coveted
November meeting of the World Trade Organization to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship hasn't meant that Dicks, who is never bashful
about demanding federal largesse for his individual and corporate
constituents, gets everything he wants.
</P>
<P>
   The administration was not particularly helpful to Dicks in his
battles to fund the B-2 bomber _ a plane Clinton now celebrates
because of its usefulness in Kosovo _ and Dicks was openly
disappointed that Gore didn't do more to help Washington cities win
empowerment zone grants, although Tacoma did get a consolation
prize of $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my 31st year as part of this delegation _ eight with
Maggie, and 23 in the House _ and we've never had an administration
that's given us the help that this administration has given us,''
Dicks said. ``Al's been there for us in everything we've asked him
to do, and he deeply cares, as we all know, about the environment,
which I think is a good issue in Washington state.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
