<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0270 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS     06-18 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
One of Jose Lima's many pet phrases is ``Believe it!''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves didn't. In fact, they went out of their way
to disprove it in a high-spirited game that included a brushback
pitch, trash-talking and plenty of elements sure to make future
meetings worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   But that is for another day and time. Thursday belonged to the
Braves, who had their way with Lima and the Astros in an 8-5
victory before a Lima-inspired crowd of 39,477 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone who turned out for their usual dose of Lima Time
could have left after six innings, along with Lima, who battled
through what might have been his worst outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was terrible,'' said Lima, who allowed a season-high seven
runs (five earned). ``I (stunk). But I'm human; I'm allowed to make
a mistake. I tip my hat to them; they got me.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss ended a three-game winning streak for Lima, who lost
for only the third time in 14 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the first game of the series, the Braves rallied to
take the next three, pushing the Astros from their perch atop the
National League in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Three days ago, the Astros had the best record in the NL. But
for now, they will have to look up to see the Braves, who tied
Arizona for the NL's best record. The Braves appear to have
regained their form after being swept at home by the lowly Orioles
before their trip to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Baltimore series was not a typical Braves performance,''
Atlanta manager Bobby Cox said. ``We knew that. We took three out
of four from a pretty good team, and we're pleased to get out of
here with three wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are just as happy to see them go. Believe it.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros struck out a season-high 14 times Thursday, and they
whiffed 48 times in the four-game series. After avoiding
back-to-back double-digit strikeout performances in their first 61
games, the Astros struck out at least 10 times in each of their
four games against the Braves and hit .220 in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Lima has been the NL's best pitcher this season, but he was no
match for Atlanta's Kevin Millwood, who threatened to treat
Thursday's crowd to a historic night.
</P>
<P>
   The second-year righthander struck out seven of the first nine
batters he faced and took a perfect game into the seventh inning.
Craig Biggio broke it up with a line-drive single to center on
Millwood's first pitch of the seventh. Millwood allowed only two
hits and struck out a season-high 11 batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched a great game,'' Astros interim manager Matt Galante
said. ``He had a great fastball and a pretty good slider. We're one
of the best-hitting teams in the league, so when you do that to us
you're doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   The intensity that characterized Wednesday's game spilled into
Thursday's third inning when Millwood buzzed a pitch high and tight
on Lima, who hit the ground and gazed into the Braves' dugout as he
dusted himself off and got back into the batter's box. Lima struck
out to end the inning, and he barked at Millwood all the way to the
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were trying to get to (Lima),'' Galante said.
``Any time you have an emotional player, you want to try to get
them out of their game.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared to work. Lima gave up three runs in the fourth _ a
rare occurrence considering he had allowed five runs in his
previous 29 innings. The Braves batted around in the inning, which
was started by Bret Boone's sharp double to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Boone scored on a hit by Javy Lopez, who tied a career high with
four hits. Ryan Klesko had an RBI double, and after an intentional
walk to eighth-place hitter Randall Simon loaded the bases, Lima
walked Millwood on a 3-2 pitch to force in the Braves' third run of
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't walk the pitcher,'' Lima said. ``That's a guy you
should be able to get out. That's what got to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But he clearly wasn't happy with the decision to give Simon a
free pass. It was only the fifth intentional walk the Astros have
issued this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment about that,'' Lima said. ``I'm not (11-3)
because I'm lucky. But I'm not the manager; that's not my decision
to make. They're (the coaches) the bosses.''
</P>
<P>
   Galante, managing his fourth game in Larry Dierker's absence,
understood Lima's frustration but defended his decision to walk
Simon with two out in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either facing a pitcher or a regular hitter,'' Galante
said. ``We only needed one out to get out of the inning. I felt
more confident with the pitcher at the plate. With Jose's control
(1.7 walks per nine innings), the last thing I expected was a
walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima settled down for a perfect fifth inning but was anything
but perfect in the sixth when the Braves erupted for four more
runs. Lopez hit a solo home run, Millwood added insult to injury
with an RBI single, and Ozzie Guillen's two-run double pushed the
Braves' lead to 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   Simply making contact was a victory in itself against Millwood,
and the Astros finally won a small battle when they scored a pair
of runs in the seventh. Carl Everett drove Biggio home from third
with a fielder's-choice grounder, and Spiers scored on a wild
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Everett's RBI double and a two-run double by Ricky Gutierrez
made things interesting in the final inning, but the Braves already
had laid claim to the victory in a game that wasn't as close as the
score indicated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
