<HEADLINE>
FENWAY FOLLIES: RED SOX FALL GUYS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-TWINS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Maybe this is what John Harrington really meant when he
coined the term ``silly season.''
</P>
<P>
   In a game that should have left both dugouts bathed in blushes,
the Red Sox came up a run short in their attempt to sweep a
four-game set from the Minnesota Twins, losing, 8-7, before a
Yawkey Way gathering of 31,446 that was exposed to plenty of
tomfoolery from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times do you see a guy jump over a catcher?'' said
Sox manager Jimy Williams, referring to the flying leap Twins
leadoff man Jacque Jones made over Sox catcher Jason Varitek in the
fourth inning, only to miss the plate upon landing. ``I've heard of
cows jumping over the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some wacky things happened out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, with a chance to tie in the eighth, failed to score
Trot Nixon from third with none out, but were given one last
pratfall to exploit in the ninth, when Twins left fielder Chad
Allen broke back, then fell on what should have been a game-ending
fly ball by Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that was weird,'' said Varitek, who was credited with a
single but was stranded when Darren Lewis fouled out to first base
to end the game. ``But there was a lot of stuff out there, from the
first inning on.''
</P>
<P>
   Twins closer Mike Trombley, the Wilbraham native, already has
had more than his fill of Fenway strangeness _ Monday night, he was
beaten by back-to-back home runs by Lewis and Jeff Frye. It was
almost too much for him to take when Varitek's ball fell safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking of that curse of the Bambino,'' Trombley said
as he pondered if yet another night would go the Sox' way. ``I was
wondering if it really existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Trombley had entered in the eighth, after Nixon singled, stole
second and took third on a throwing error by catcher Javier
Valentin. Bob Wells, who gave up the hit to Nixon, retired Jose
Offerman on a liner to second with the infield drawn in, before
Trombley was summoned. John Valentin, who earlier hit a three-run
home run, fanned on a full count, and after Brian Daubach walked on
a full count, Nomar Garciaparra struck out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made some great pitches,'' Garciaparra said. ``He did his
job. Yeah, (the game) was long and weird, but there's nothing for
us to hang our heads about. We came back from the road trip and won
three, and we made tonight interesting. We can't complain.''
</P>
<P>
   The nutty stuff came early and often.
</P>
<P>
   Sox starting pitcher Pat Rapp retired only one of the first
seven Twins he faced, and four of them scored.
</P>
<P>
   On Marty Cordova's single to center, Lewis wanted to throw to
second, but no one was there. Garciaparra had ended up in short
right field trying to flag down Cordova's grounder, and Offerman
had scooted over to cover first, with first baseman Daubach at the
mound to handle a throw to the plate. ``I don't really know what
happened there,'' Lewis said. ``I just threw in the direction of
the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Daubach had a throw from Garciaparra clank off his
glove for a two-base error that led to the Twins' fifth run.
</P>
<P>
   But not to worry. Twins starter LaTroy Hawkins, winner of just
18 of 78 career starts and possessor of an 8.30 earned run average
entering Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's game, allowed four of the first Sox
batters he faced to reach base, two of them scoring. An inning
later, Hawkins surrendered a three-run home run to Valentin that
cleared the TV camera well in left-center field, 421 feet away. Sox
5, Twins 4.
</P>
<P>
   Through two innings, 25 batters already had paraded to the
plate. Amazingly, Hawkins settled down, holding the Sox scoreless
until the sixth when he gave way to Joe Mays.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, reliever Bob Wolcott's first pitch as a member of the
Red Sox was lined into the right-field corner for a two-run double
by Jones, breaking a 5-all tie in the fourth. Jones took an extra
base when second baseman Offerman inadvertently spiked his relay
throw a few feet in front of him. ``I tried to stop my throw, and I
couldn't,'' said Offerman, who was charged with an error, a
decision that didn't provoke a peep from Pedro L. Martinez. ``No
big deal. Nobody scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though there were no outs and the infield was playing in,
Jones set sail for the plate on Cristian Guzman's roller to
Offerman and actually vaulted over Varitek. That won him huge style
points, but failed to result in a run, as he missed home plate upon
landing and was tagged out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, first time anyone's ever done that,'' Varitek said. ``I
was surprised, because I was still reaching for the ball. If I'd
had the ball, I probably would have launched him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolcott gave up another run in the fifth when Cordova singled
and scored on Ron Coomer's drive high off the Monster, which Troy
O'Leary played into a double, the carom bouncing over his head.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox climbed back with the help of another spring
training play, when shortstop Guzman overran Valentin's popup near
the third-base box seats, the ball bouncing into the stands for a
180-foot ground-rule double. One out later, Garciaparra singled
Valentin home and after a walk and hit batsman (pinch hitter Mike
Stanley) loaded the bases, Varitek hit a sacrifice fly to make it
8-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept waiting for that little guy in the TV show to walk out
to the middle of the field and make that announcement, `You're in
the Twilight Zone,' '' Coomer said.
</P>
<P>
   Sox manager Williams was asked if the game was atypical of the
Sox season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's atypical,'' he said. ``I don't know what
atypical is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironic, then, that the Sox scored seven runs and didn't win?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know about irony,'' Williams said. ``Is that
atypical?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
