<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO ANSWERS CALL FOR STARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ On Wednesday after practice, Dallas Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock tried to talk to one of his star centers about his
performance in the Stanley Cup finals, particularly in Game 4, in
which the Buffalo Sabres had tied the series at two games each.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano said he wasn't in the mood for a chat with the
coach, so he headed home.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Hitchcock called him that night to insist on a talk on
the eve of Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's pivotal Game 5, Modano wasn't
surprised but he was more willing to listen.
</P>
<P>
   The result of Hitchcock's challenge resulted in Modano assisting
on both Dallas goals Thursday &UR;  &LR; night as the Stars shut out the
Sabres, 2-0, to move within one win of capturing the franchise's
first Stanley Cup. They can close out the Sabres Saturday night in
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am able to say some things candidly and only to him that
maybe I can't say to other players,'' summed up Hitchcock of his
discussion with Modano. ``It was just a phone call of support and
getting him to think in some other direction and if he listened,
great. I mean, I think he took it to heart and he went about his
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano smiled when asked about the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a lot of chats throughout the time he's been here
and we've been together,'' said Modano. ``He just plain and simple
asked me what type of player I was going to be tonight, and I told
him I was going to be a player who was very involved in every
aspect of the game. I felt I got away a little bit from that in
Game 4 and really wanted mentally to be a little stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano, who has turned his game from all offense to a mixture of
opportunistic scoring and responsible defense under Hitchcock,
definitely answered the bell in this one.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars and Sabres were scoreless after 20 minutes for the
third time in five games. In the second, the Stars turned up the
old Texas heat.
</P>
<P>
   Just 1:42 into it, Buffalo center Curtis Brown took an
interference penalty, setting up the Stars' power-play goal and the
only offense they would need.
</P>
<P>
   Modano, who has been playing the last three games with an
injured left wrist, skated down the right side and pulled up in the
far side of the right circle. After drawing Buffalo forward Dixon
Ward, Modano patiently fed the puck across to the left circle for
defenseman Darryl Sydor. Sydor made a perfect shot into the right
top corner of the net and over the shoulder of Dominik Hasek. The
Stars were up, 1-0, at the 2:23 mark, and they proceeded to get
stronger and stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Modano was one half of a potent Stars punch with fellow center
Joe Nieuwendyk. Nieuwendyk's best scoring chance came at the 12:20
mark during a two-on-one when he blasted a shot at Hasek from the
left circle. Hasek made the save, but the Sabres were having a hard
time containing the Stars' surging offense.
</P>
<P>
   It was the antithesis of Game 4 in which the Sabres completely
bottled up the Stars and didn't allow them to get anything going.
Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, it was the Sabres who had a hard time generating
any offense. Buffalo's power play, which was so stunning against
the Senators, Bruins, and Maple Leafs, started off very effectively
in this series. In the first two games, Buffalo converted 3 of 8
opportunities. However, in the next two games and through two
periods Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, the Sabres had gone 0 for 16 on the man
advantage, including 0 for 3 Thursday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   At 15:21 of the third, the Stars added an insurance goal on a
nice move by veteran forward Pat Verbeek. Modano picked up the puck
from defenseman Alexei Zhitnik and kicked it up to defenseman
Richard Matvichuk, who skated it up the left side. He dished a pass
from the left circle into the slot for Verbeek, who slalomed down
and beat Hasek with a backhander inside the left post. It was
Verbeek's third goal of the postseason and first of the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Modano said he wouldn't shy away from more talks with Hitchcock,
only because he won't be able to avoid them. When asked if he
thought about changing his phone number, Modano laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always has my number,'' he said. ``He has got every number
I think I have, so he tracks me down wherever I'm at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
