<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-4THLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE DEALS A STINGING DEFEAT TO GUN CONTROLS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a stunning victory for the National Rifle
Association, the House early on Friday morning narrowly approved a
provision to regulate sales at gun shows that is substantially
weaker than legislation passed by the Senate last month.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, sponsored by Rep. John Dingell, a Michigan Democrat
working in conjunction with Republicans, eked through a tense House
by a vote of 218 to 211 just after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   It drew the support of 173 Republicans and 45 Democrats. Most of
the Democrats _ or 163 of them _ stuck with President Clinton and
their party in opposition to the amendment. They drew 47 moderate
Republicans and one independent to their side.
</P>
<P>
   As the narrowness of the vote became clear, Democrats sought to
punctuate how things might be different if they had control of the
House. Led by Rep. Patrick Kennedy of Rhode Island, who is their
campaign chairman, they chanted ``Six seats, six seats,'' the
increase in seats they need to win in 2000 to regain the majority.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Rep. Tom DeLay, the House minority whip who had
worked tirelessly for passage of the Dingell measure, clapped his
hands once as his victory became clear. He walked over to hug
Dingell, who was on the Republican side of the aisle. Speaker
Dennis Hastert also cast his vote with Dingell.
</P>
<P>
   Later on Friday morning, a competing gun-show amendment favored
by most Democrats failed by a vote of 193 to 235. It was sponsored
by Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., who was elected to Congress after
her husband was killed by a gunman on the Long Island Rail Road in
1993, and it mirrored the Senate legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Near tears, Mrs. McCarthy chided the House for playing politics.
She said she had come to Congress only to prevent others from
suffering the fate of her husband and her son, who was also
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me go home,'' she said. ``Let me go home. I love working
with all of you people. I think all of you are great. But somehow
we sometimes lose sight of why we are all here. And I'm trying to
remind you of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, and many Republicans, gave her a standing
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The moment capped a long two days and nights of clashes over gun
control and social issues.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Rep. Saxby Chambliss, R-Ga., spoke out
uncompromisingly in favor of the constitutional right to bear arms.
``The majority of the amendments we're debating aren't about saving
lives,'' he said. ``They're about taking rights away from
law-abiding citizens. What we're talking about is gun control and
that is the wrong issue.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort by each side to draw support from across the aisle,
Republican pro-gun forces gave some of their speaking time to a
parade of conservative Democrats, while Democrats showcased
Republican allies on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Several more gun-control measures are to be considered by the
House later on Friday, but the success of the Dingell gun-show
measure threw the entire fate of the final bill in doubt. John P.
Feehery, a spokeman for Hastert, said: ``There's a lot of risk left
in this bill. There are a lot of dynamics.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, liberal Democrats were threatening to bolt from the
final bill because its gun-show provision is too weak, while
conservatives were saying they could oppose it if additional
amendments, such as one to raise the minimum age for the purchase
of all handguns or another to ban the import of high-capacity
ammunition clips, should pass and make the bill too strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The less gun control, the more apt it is to pass,'' said DeLay
who had worked hard to persuade conservatives to rally around
Dingell's bill in order to trump stronger versions. Another
gun-show provision sponsored by Rep. Henry Hyde, Republican of
Illinois, had been contained in the base bill under consideration
and represented a midpoint between the other versions.
</P>
<P>
   If the final bill is passed in its current form, it would be
different enough from the Senate version to force it into a
conference committee. And it is not clear how President Clinton
will react to a measure with a weaker gun-control provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The late-night showdown over the gun-show measures came
centerstage after two days of sometimes impassioned clashes over
God, values, the entertainment industry and the Constitution. That
debate culminated early Thursday night in passage by a vote of
287-139 of a wide-ranging bill that would provide $1.5 billion for
fighting juvenile crime and enact tough mandatory minimum sentences
for young people in gun crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In a victory for social conservatives, the House voted 248-180
to include in the crime bill an amendment sponsored by Rep. Robert
Aderholt, R-Ala., giving states the right to allow the display of
the Ten Commandments in public places, including schools.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that simply posting the Ten Commandments will not
instantly change the moral character of our nation,'' Aderholt, the
measure's sponsor, said just before it passed. ``However, it is an
important step to promote morality and an end of children killing
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., and other critics countered that
the amendment raised constitutional questions, including whether it
would pass muster on the separation of church and state. ``Whose
Ten Commandments?'' Nadler asked. ``Which version? The Catholic
version? The Protestant version? Or the Jewish version?''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday evening, long after prime time, the House turned to
the gun-control debate, which is the preferred political ground of
the Democrats. A dozen separate gun amendments were under
consideration, ranging from a measure requiring child-safety
devices to be sold with handguns to a proposal to repeal the
District of Columbia's ban on the possession of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   But the most significant showdown was over the rival measures of
varying strictness to regulate sales of weapons at gun shows, at
which collectors and hobbyists selling firearms are not now
required to conduct the kinds of background checks on buyers that
licensed dealers are.
</P>
<P>
   In a fierce lobbying blitz, Clinton arose early Thursday in
Paris to telephone four wavering Democrats: Gary Condit and Mike
Thompson of California, Marion Berry of Arkansas and Ron Kind of
Wisconsin, to urge them to vote for the gun-show amendment
sponsored by Mrs. McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is crazy for the United States to be the only advanced
country in the world that doesn't take comprehensive, sensible,
thorough steps to keep handguns out of the hands of criminals,''
Clinton told reporters in Paris, where he was attending a summit of
industrialized nations. ``It's just _ it doesn't make any sense.''
</P>
<P>
   To hammer home the point the White House sent Attorney General
Janet Reno to the Capitol late Thursday afternoon. As the debate
neared a vote, Republicans said that Clinton and the attorney
general were still calling a handful of wavering Republicans from
mostly suburban districts who could turn the outcome either way.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association and DeLay shored up support among
conservatives for the weaker version sponsored by Dingell, who is a
former member of the NRA board.
</P>
<P>
   All day long Dingell had insisted that he was going to win. He
said that Clinton would not make headway with conservative
Democrats because ``he cost us control of the House and a lot of
people remember that.'' The Republicans won the majority in 1994,
months after Congress enacted a ban on assault weapons avidly
sought by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the NRA has largely held sway on Capitol Hill. But
after the school shootings in Littleton, the Senate last month _
with Vice President Al Gore casting the tie-breaking vote _
approved a proposal that would compel all vendors at gun shows,
licensed or unlicensed to run such checks. Law enforcement
officials are given three business days to complete the checks.
</P>
<P>
   And in debate Thursday night, Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., recalled
that he lost his seat in 1994 for favoring gun control and then
been re-elected. ``It was bitter and it was painful,'' he said of
his defeat. ``But I have not regretted that vote for one minute. No
congressman's seat is more important than any child's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dingell's amendment on gun shows differs significantly from the
Senate's. Its definition of what constitutes a gun show is narrow,
and only 24 hours would be allotted for background checks. Mrs.
McCarthy's version is similar to the Senate legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In other votes on Wednesday and Thursday, the House approved a
variety of measures signaling support, sometimes symbolic and
sometimes more concrete, for public expressions of religion. The
debate over the Ten Commandments was the most spirited.
</P>
<P>
   But the House also overwhelmingly approved measures allowing the
use of religious language in memorials on school grounds and
prohibiting discrimination against religious organizations in the
awarding of contracts to provide social services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
