u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-HNS &LR;      06-18 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ They have butted heads, each trying to impose his will and
style on the other, with neither ever quite getting it his way.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask about the relationship, and Mike Modano smiles and shakes
his head. Ask Ken Hitchcock, and the slight grin hints at battles
won and lost.
</P>
<P>
   Strange bedfellows, to be sure, these two. But with a Stanley
Cup hanging in the balance Thursday night at Reunion Arena, Modano
the star and Hitchcock the coach got together on the essentials of
a 2-0 Dallas Stars win over the Buffalo Sabres, an outcome that
gives Dallas a three games to two lead in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pretty close relationship,'' Hitchcock said after
watching Modano assist on both goals. ``I've spent a lot of time
with him, and I'm able to say some things candidly that maybe I'm
not able to say to other players.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of this pivotal Game 5, Hitchcock phoned with a
simple question: Could the Stars expect to see a full effort from
their best player, or would it be more of the timid play Modano _
who has been playing with a fractured left wrist _ offered in Game
4?
</P>
<P>
   ``He plain and simple asked me what kind of player I was going
to be tonight,'' Modano said. ``I told him I was going to be
involved in every aspect of the game. I got away from that a little
bit in Game 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 is Saturday night in Buffalo, where the Sabres will try
to avoid elimination and force a seventh game here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Modano had much to do with pushing Buffalo to the brink. He
didn't score in this one, but his impact was felt everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   He found Darryl Sydor with a perfect setup for the first goal of
the game at 2 minutes, 23 seconds of the second period. Modano then
helped close the deal when he dug the puck out of the corner and
got it out to Richard Matvichuk, who fed Pat Verbeek for an
insurance score at 15:21 of the third.
</P>
<P>
   Modano was on the ice for nearly 21{ minutes, the most of any
Dallas forward. He won 15 faceoffs, had three takeaways and blocked
a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike made great plays,'' Sydor said. ``A lot of people have
been on him through the series and through the playoffs. He's just
sticking with it and doing his thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano's thing has changed in the eight years since he helped
the Minnesota North Stars get to the Stanley Cup Finals. In Dallas'
defense-first system, checking and defense have taken priority over
fancy skating and piling up goals.
</P>
<P>
   Those alterations were the source of heated discussions between
coach and player, but they have the Stars a game away from claiming
hockey's greatest prize.
</P>
<P>
   This time, when Hitchcock called, the star of the Stars knew
what needed to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took it to his heart and went about his business today,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano was not alone in that regard. Goalie Ed Belfour stopped
all 23 Buffalo shots for his seventh career playoff shutout,
getting the best of Dominik Hasek, who could handle only 19 of 21.
Dallas also blocked 20 shots and dished out 39 hits to the Sabres'
36.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought both teams emotionally gave it everything they
had,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said. ``It was tight as tight could
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, this one seemed destined to be a different story. If
the Stars felt any sense of urgency to avoid heading back to
Buffalo facing elimination, it wasn't readily apparent in a
lethargic first period. The Sabres outshot Dallas 9-8 and were
credited with one more hit (12-11). Even more telling were the
Stars' eight giveways and a paltry two blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first period was the best anyone has played against us in
our building all year,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Belfour kept the game scoreless after 20 minutes, and
Dallas showed signs of life at the start of the second period. With
the Sabres' Curtis Brown off for interference, the Stars cashed in
on the power play. Modano found Sydor with a nifty cross-ice pass,
and Sydor beat Hasek high and to the goalie's left to make it 1-0
at 2:23 of the period.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor had a golden opportunity to give his team a virtually
unheard-of two-goal lead just a few minutes later when he
accompanied Modano on a break but could not get his stick on a nice
pass through the crease.
</P>
<P>
   But the one-goal lead held up through two periods as Belfour
came up with a big glove save on a blast off the stick of Jay McKee
in the final minute. Dallas held a 15-14 edge in shots at the
second intermission and was beginning to get the better end of the
flow. Still, the Sabres were just a shot away from tying the game,
and they stayed right there until the final five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Modano dug the puck out of the corner and got it ahead
to Matvichuk, who was off on a two-on-one with Verbeek. Matvichuk
fed Verbeek in the middle, and Verbeek faked the shot, then slipped
by Hasek for a backhand that gave the Stars a 2-0 lead and
breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there were smiles all around the Dallas locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike doesn't have to score to get the job done for us,'' Sydor
said. ``He does a lot of other things, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, when it mattered most, Modano did them. The art of
compromise leaves the Stars on the lip of the Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
