<HEADER>
A0283 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-18 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PINEHURST, N.C. _ There is no place Phil Mickelson should rather be
than right here, right now. He has waited all his life for
something like this _ a U.S. Open with his name written all over
it.
</P>
<P>
   But Mickelson's plane is parked at the airport. It's fueled and
ready to fly. Back home, there's a baby about to be born that also
will have Mickelson's name written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's not even a question of should I stay or go,''
Mickelson said Thursday. ``I'm out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   But suppose that Sunday afternoon Mickelson is making the turn
with a two-shot lead in the Open, when the call comes from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaving,'' he said. ``A tournament doesn't even stack
up.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a matter of a young father's priceless moment against maybe
a $625,000 U.S. Open moment. It's a matter of walking away from the
best chance yet to etch his name in golfing lore, all because back
home in Scottsdale, Ariz., there's a Mickelson _ or Mickel-daughter
_ on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be U.S. Opens,'' Mickelson said. ``You
only have your firstborn once.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, this Open's only water hazard might be 2,000 miles away
and about to break.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there might not be a player better-equipped to handle the
Pinehurst challenges Donald Ross laid out nearly a century ago. But
Mickelson's bags are packed, and a driver _ the kind behind a
steering wheel _ is on 24-hour call.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any doubt this one-time boy wonder has grown up,
wonder no more.
</P>
<P>
   Here is this 29-year-old talent, whose most recent reputation
has been the ever-cruel ``Best Player Never To Have Won A Major,''
not caring a bit that this week might belong to him.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the ironic twist: Mickelson finally has a lush stage
on which to show off all the tricks in his golf bag, and it all
might be sidetracked by the arrival of the latest Mickelson boy
wonder. Or girl wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win a major, of course,'' Mickelson said. ``And I've
never been more excited about a U.S. Open. In past years in the
Open, the short game has been rendered practically obsolete. It was
a little frustrating. If you didn't get it on the green, you just
tried to knock it out of the high grass and put it in. But this is
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Never has it looked more like a tournament Mickelson could own,
as his opening-round 67 on Thursday showed. Playing alongside
Esteban Toledo and David Duval, Mickelson moved the ball here and
there off the tee masterfully.
</P>
<P>
   Around the perilous crowned greens, he pulled all sorts of clubs
out of his bag _ everything from a 3-wood to a 4-iron to a putter.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if he was a kid with a set of new toys, eagerly
playing with each one, then tossing it aside for the next one. He
hopped the ball onto the green on near-perfect lines all day.
</P>
<P>
   He putted like magic, holing a 30-footer on the 383-yard par-4
13th for birdie, following with a 10-foot birdie on the testy
436-yard 14th and ending the round with a spiraling 14-footer to
save par.
</P>
<P>
   He was just like a kid again, the boy wonder. But of course, we
know he's all grown up because he'll drop it all at the buzz of a
beeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been this excited about a golf course in a long
time,'' Mickelson said. ``It brings out every shot in the bag. If
you're off the green, it's going to be tough, but you're still
going to have a shot. You'll have a lie. You just have to create a
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He chipped in for birdie on the monstrous, mean 482-yard par-4
No. 5, which played as the toughest hole of the day. He knocked
smart shots to the green on so many holes, playing partner Carlos
Franco called him ``someone who knows what this game is about.''
</P>
<P>
   But more. Only moments after he finished the 3-under 67, which
shared the first-round lead with David Duval, Billy Mayfair and
Paul Goydos, he talked about knowing what life is all about.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have told Mickelson the baby is not due for two more
weeks, but it could come early. And if it does, he says he'll walk
off the course no matter what the leader board says.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 20 years old, I used to think winning a major was
everything,'' Mickelson said. ``But what would I tell my kid years
from now I wasn't there because I was playing golf?''
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the boy wonder now. He's all grown up, doing the
responsible thing, slaying a course that seems to be made for him
and calling it all just a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go by what I saw today,'' Franco said, ``you have to
believe Mickelson will be there on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you have to believe it. But he'll be there only if the
cellular phone in his caddie's bag doesn't ring or the pager
clipped to his pants pocket doesn't buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure it's going to be five hours and 15 minutes from the
time I get the beep to the time I arrive at the hospital,''
Mickelson said. ``I'll get out of here real fast, then it's about
20 minutes to get in the air, four hours and 45 minutes to fly
back, then 10 minutes to the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   And then it will be a lifetime of memories that he calls
priceless. And even for those who wouldn't consider Mickelson's
possible decision priceless, at least we know where the bidding
could start _ $625,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
