<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0288 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-18 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ By 4:45 a.m. Thursday, Don Chaney, blurry-eyed and
groggy, finally turned off the VCR. He put down his legal pad and
put in for a wake-up call for roughly four hours later.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is not an unusual practice for an NBA assistant coach,
particularly one facing a 1-0 deficit in the NBA Finals and a
riddle, as do Chaney and the other New York Knicks coaches.
</P>
<P>
   But after hours of examining the tapes for secrets, studying the
San Antonio Spurs' defense and considering its strengths and
oddities, Chaney was forced to ask himself how to exploit a
weakness he could not find.
</P>
<P>
   ``They take away,'' Chaney said, ``what you want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in those tapes there must be a clue to the weakness in
the Spurs' defense.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of finding things to exploit, Chaney, the former
Rockets player and coach, found offensive tactics the Spurs would
not allow. They remove penetration to the basket, stubbornly stay
with outside shooters and refuse to try the gambles that could
create openings.
</P>
<P>
   The more he looked, the less he found.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do things a little different defensively than a lot of
teams, and it's paid off for us big-time,'' Spurs forward Sean
Elliott said. ``There's a lot of times, when a man penetrates, he
wants us to do things a lot differently than we've ever done.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams want to penetrate to dish the ball to open
shooters. We don't leave the shooters. We let the big men handle
the penetration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more cohesive as a unit. We have each other's back more.
If a guy gets beat, guys are there to help him out. We don't settle
for, `Well, I just got beat.' Guys try to play great individual
defense out on the floor. And then we have two big guys to help
clean up the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs led the NBA in field-goal defense each of the past two
seasons. They allowed opponents to make just 40.2 percent of their
shots in the regular season and in the playoffs heading into
Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a sluggish start defensively against the Knicks, the
Spurs allowed New York to make just 31 of 81 shots (38.3 percent)
on Wednesday, just five of 22 in the decisive fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And like the Portland Trail Blazers and Los Angeles Lakers
before them, the Knicks' offense quickly degenerated to, Knicks
coach Jeff Van Gundy said, ``frenetic'' one-on-one play and outside
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have two big guys clogging up the paint, you resort
to shooting long jumpers,'' Knicks forward Marcus Camby said. ``We
have to drive the ball a lot more. We can't just settle for jump
shots. We have to bring it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   But that has proved next to impossible. Though there are
mysteries about the Spurs' defense, there are none about where its
dominance begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They clog the middle up,'' Chaney said. ``Most teams thrive on
getting to the paint area, sucking the defense in and kicking the
ball out or driving all the way to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so big inside, they take away the initial drive.
They're great shot-blockers and very good athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Spurs) do a very good job of covering the perimeter.
They don't worry about helping out inside, because they have two
guys who are very good at covering the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not stiffs. They're two 7-footers who are very
athletic and can really move. That's their advantage. Most
7-footers take awhile to get from one side of the lane to the
other. These guys get there as fast as guards get there. They don't
need help in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, one of Spurs coach Gregg Popovich's first moves
was to break the Spurs of some basic defensive fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   With David Robinson and Tim Duncan to patrol the lane and erase
defensive mistakes outside, when opposing players penetrate, which
is the Knicks' greatest strength, the Spurs' weak-side defenders do
not help. They remain on their assignments.
</P>
<P>
   A player beaten off the dribble does not rush to catch his man.
Instead, he finds a passing lane his man might try.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically believe in some things a little different from
the norm,'' Popovich said. ``Having those two 7-footers out there
makes it easy to believe in those things. You might not have that
commitment to it if you didn't have Tim and David back there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parts of it are good; parts of it are very weird that I
wouldn't recommend to anybody unless they had those kinds of
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Because some of the tenets of Popovich's defense are so unusual,
they took time to work. His schemes rely on players working well
together consistently, and that, they said, took time to develop,
particularly after a lifetime spent learning different defensive
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Because those schemes must be executed in sync, Popovich said
faith in the ``weird'' is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   But there comes a time the players also must believe in the
strength of their own defense. As unusual as some of the Spurs'
rotations off penetration might be, they are conservative outside,
rarely gambling or going for steals.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Spurs play basic man-to-man outside, making
opponents work to get to the next, tougher line of defense and
allowing little shot-clock time left for the three or four passes
Chaney said are needed to find an open shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have five people who trust each other defensively
and really believe in their guts, not just talk but in their guts,
that they can make stops whenever they need to make a stop,''
Popovich said. ``If you have five guys that believe that, that's
the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Spurs' offense seems designed to help defensively,
especially against the fast-break-minded Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   With Duncan usually on the low post and Robinson often at a high
post, the Spurs generally have three players back, at least two at
the 3-point line. When teams try to break, they often find the
Spurs back because their perimeter players were in good defensive
position even when their team had the ball.
</P>
<P>
   But as with every defense, the Spurs leave an opening. Van
Gundy, Chaney and the Knicks coaches found it, too.
</P>
<P>
   If their tough-to-cover perimeter players penetrate, Duncan or
Robinson will come to meet them, and Spurs defenders will remain
close to the Knicks' shooters and jump into the passing lanes.
</P>
<P>
   But when Duncan and Robinson leave their men open, the Knicks
can pass for open midrange jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you really need against them is big guys who can make
perimeter shots, so as you suck them in you find your bigs guys
along the baseline on the perimeter,'' Van Gundy said. ``But right
now (with Patrick Ewing out and Larry Johnson playing hurt), that's
not us.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. Back to the tapes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
