<P>
   RUSSIA-PLANE (Le Bourget, France) _ On June 2, the big,
four-engine Russian Ilyushin IL-96T became the first wide-body jet,
other than ones made by Airbus Industrie and Boeing Co., to meet
FAA safety standards. It was not easy. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   3COM-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Eric Benhamou, the chief executive
of 3Com, may feel as if he has aged a few years in recent months.
The once ballyhooed company stunned investors with a weak earnings
report in March, and many analysts say it simply has too many
diverse businesses to regain its old momentum, management focus and
reputation as a high-growth company. By Matt Richtel with Seth
Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   SURVEY-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The next phase of a major multiyear
communications effort to promote the importance of advertising is
getting under way _ and not a moment too soon, judging by the
results of a national survey of top corporate executives. By Stuart
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   BONUS-BMW (Holmdel, N.J.) _ Arcnet, an engineering and
architectural firm that builds and installs wireless communciations
factilites, is giving away 28 BMW's to employees in a publicity
stunt that says something about the lengths companies will go to to
retain employees with skills in high demand. By Ronald Smothers.
