<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-SPURS (San Antonio) _ The Knicks won the first game
of the first three rounds of the NBA playoffs, each time winning on
the road. But they were unable to pull off that same feat against
the San Antonio Spurs, who were the best team in the NBA this
season and looked like the better team in Game 1 of the NBA finals
on Wednesday night. Now the somewhat undermanned and undersized
Knicks have to come up with a plan for Game 2. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Pinehurst, N.C.) _ Sports of The Times
column on David Duval, playing the U.S. Open despite two blisters
on his right hand. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' code)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PARRISH-EXHIBIT (Philadelphia) _ In 1925, a New York printing
company called the House of Art estimated that one of its
best-selling products, a lithograph of Maxfield Parrish's painting
``Daybreak,'' could be found in one of every four American homes.
Even allowing for a titanic dose of hype, the statistic rings true.
Like apple pie, the flag and indoor plumbing, ``Daybreak'' was,
indeed, an American fixture. So was Parrish himself. He was an art
machine. He turned out countless paintings, many of them intended
for print reproduction. Together, they made him one of the
country's first brand-name artists, and they helped define the mood
and style of an era. ``Maxfield Parrish, 1870-1966,'' which opens
tomorrow at the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts in
Philadelphia, is a first-time look at the full range of a career
that, almost preposterously, stretched from the post-Victorian
Gilded Age of the 1880s to the Pop world of the 1960s. By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ-FESTIVAL (New York) _ Take it as coincidence or take it as
synchronicity or take it as one more affirmation of the ways
musicians tune in ideas across boundaries and decades. The JVC Jazz
Festival, which starts its major concerts tonight and runs through
June 27, has two threads that connect its most promising events,
two pervasive influences that should intersect at many different
angles for 10 days. One is the ever-expanding recognition of
Brazilian music, past and present, as more American listeners break
the language barrier and more Brazilian musicians travel
internationally. The second is the lasting influence of Miles
Davis, who spawned entire schools of jazz with each phase of his
music from the 1940s well into the 1970s. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo (NYT6) is being sent to NYT photo clients)
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-WINE (Undated) _ A treasury of priceless glass in a land
of free-flowing wine: how good an idea is this? Good enough, it
turns out, if the combination pairs the strikingly expanded Corning
Museum of Glass in Corning, N.Y., and the vineyard-ringed Finger
Lakes. You can taste your way through dozens of wineries hugging
the hillsides along the sky-blue waters and tour the world's most
comprehensive collection of art glass and high-tech exhibits in a
new section, opening Saturday, of a $62 million glass-sheathed
addition to the museum. (Or more prudently, perhaps, you can do it
the other way around.) By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
