<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-GOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN EMERGING AS CHOICE OF GOP ELITE  
   
   
  
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLA MARINUCCI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
If George W. Bush, the front-runner for the GOP presidential
nomination, has momentum that political insiders call the ``big
mo,'' then Arizona Senator John McCain has the next best thing: the
buzz.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as the Texas governor grabs the spotlight, McCain is moving
up in the polls, increasingly viewed as the candidate who may step
out from the GOP pack _ and right into the top spot if Bush fails
to meet expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's every Republican intellectual's choice for the
presidency,'' said Alfred Balitzer, professor of politics at
Claremont-McKenna College and a former Republican pollster. And
more and more of them, he said, are making book on McCain's dark
horse candidacy: ``They're saying he's taken Elizabeth Dole's place
as No. 2, and if Bush falters, he will be the odds-on favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain begins a two-day swing through California Friday, hitting
Silicon Valley for a breakfast with the Technology Network, the
bipartisan high-tech lobbying group, then a roundtable discussion
with reporters. Tomorrow, he'll launch a nationwide youth
leadership campaign at Fort Mason in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe California is the critical state in my campaign,''
McCain said in an interview this week as he prepared for his trip.
When it comes to technology issues, the Arizona Republican argued,
he is the most qualified candidate because of his ``day-to-day,
hands-on involvement'' in issues that matter most in Silicon Valley
_ such as telecommunications reform, Y2K liability, the expansion
of temporary visas for skilled workers, education and charter
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Al) Gore does have an advantage over me _ I did not invent
the Internet,'' quipped McCain, chairman of the Senate Commerce,
Science and Transportation Committee, referring to a statement the
vice president made during a recent TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who said he plans to return to California ``for a couple
of weeks'' in August, has already established some serious
credentials in the state. Thursday, he named Dan Schnur, a
respected GOP analyst and former Governor Pete Wilson's spokesman,
as his national campaign spokesman, calling him ``one of the best
strategists in California.''
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Herald poll this week gave McCain a boost; it showed
him drawing even with Elizabeth Dole at 11 points, compared to
Bush's 45.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's head start in the polls and in fund-raising doesn't
bother McCain, who said that ``ultimately, this election is going
to be about who can articulate the vision'' in key issues that
matter to voters.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been helped by a near-constant media presence on the
Kosovo crisis that gave his campaign valuable free exposure,
increased his name recognition and established him as a foreign
policy expert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's terrific. He had a clear idea of what America's policy
should be in Kosovo, and he stuck with it,'' said Dudley Buffa, who
heads the Lafayette-based Institute for the New California, an
independent think tank that studies political and technology
issues. ``He's demonstrated his complete ability to be
independent.''
</P>
<P>
   That means, Buffa said, that McCain has begun to shape his image
as a reform ``anti-establishment'' candidate _ a role assumed by
challenger Bill Bradley on the Democratic side.
</P>
<P>
   The former Navy pilot and prisoner of war, who was shot down
during the Vietnam War, also has a life story that clearly
distinguishes him from the pack of Republican hopefuls. ``If you
read about what this guy went through, it's hard not to be
impressed,'' said Buffa.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, even the most aggressive Democratic attack dogs
have so far tended to blunt their assaults on McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like McCain, as a Vietnam vet,'' said Bob Mulholland, the
California Democratic campaign adviser who earned a Purple Heart in
Vietnam. ``He went through a very tough time and paid a heavy
personal price. Of all the Republicans, he has the most impressive
resume, having served almost at the cost of his life. But the GOP
will be very tough on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland is not alone in suggesting that McCain's success may
depend on the failure of others _ notably Bush, who has so far
grabbed the lion's share of endorsements, money and media
attention. ``If one of the front-runners goes down on the side of
the highway as a corpse, (McCain) will be viable,'' Mulholland
said.
</P>
<P>
   That thinking simply isn't part of the McCain plan, his campaign
insists. ``Everyone's talking about us waiting for George W. Bush
to stumble, but that's not what this campaign's about,'' said
Howard Opinsky, a McCain spokesman, this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous market for reform in California ... and
John McCain has challenged the status quo,'' Opinsky said. ``It has
cemented his credibility to fight for the change Americans yearn
for.''  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COL. 2 of MCCAIN () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
