<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0521 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALINGER-LETTERS-NYT &LR;      06-18 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALINGER-LETTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NYC COLUMN: A RECLUSE MEETS HIS MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you really want to hear about it, the first thing you'll
probably want to know is what, word for word, is in those seductive
letters that the middle-aged J.D. Salinger sent in 1972 and '73 to
the young Joyce Maynard.
</P>
<P>
   Can't help you there, kiddo, even after reading them. Copyright
laws make direct quotations impossible.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have followed this messy business at all, you already
have an idea about the contents of the 14 handwritten and typed
letters, which officially went on display at Sotheby's Thursday in
advance of a public auction on Tuesday. You also may have chosen
sides in the debate over who has exploited whom in this affair.
</P>
<P>
   There seem to be two basic schools of thought.
</P>
<P>
   Camp A includes those who see Ms. Maynard, 45, as nothing more
than a literary Linda Tripp. She has spent her life trading on this
great writer's celebrity, they say, and is now betraying his fierce
desire to remain a recluse by plundering their distant romance and
peddling his thoughts to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maynard's standing with them is hardly helped by her
notorious exhibitionism. She has written about everything from her
sexual dysfunctions to her breast implants, and maintains a Web
site so that her fans can keep up with the latest tidbits of her
life. It matters little to the type A's that, whether or not they
like Ms. Maynard, the letters are her property, to do with as she
pleases.
</P>
<P>
   In Camp B are those who say Salinger, 80, had it coming.
</P>
<P>
   With his letters, he lured an impressionable young woman. In
1972, she was a mere 18 to his 53, and had just made a splash with
an article in The New York Times Magazine reflecting on her life.
She fell understandably victim, the type B's say, to what Ms.
Maynard now calls ``psychological manipulation'' by a powerful
older man. In this camp are those who accept as an article of faith
that whenever anything goes wrong between a man and woman, it is
his fault.
</P>
<P>
   (A version of this emerged during President Clinton's
impeachment when some Clinton haters insisted on referring to
Monica Lewinsky as a ``girl,'' as though she were not past the age
of consent. This so irritated Gloria Steinem that she observed at
an anti-impeachment rally in New York that Dwight D. Eisenhower was
president when she was Ms. Lewinsky's age _ and under no
circumstances, she said, could she imagine herself climbing into
bed with Ike.)
</P>
<P>
   Getting back to the Salinger-Maynard letters, no one can just
wander into Sotheby's and peruse them. You have to make an
appointment, and first you must persuade the auctioneers that you
are a serious buyer. ``Serious'' means you do not blanch at a
pre-auction estimate of $60,000 to $80,000 for the lot, cash that
Ms. Maynard says she will use for her children's college education
(not that that buys much more these days than two years' worth for
a single child).
</P>
<P>
   If you can pass muster at Sotheby's _ and people there say the
appointment book is filling up nicely, thank you _ you will be
treated to a rare glimpse of a cult figure. This hermitic writer,
unpublished since 1965, reveals himself as one who embraces
homeopathy, takes his son to Dartmouth football games, adores old
Hitchcock movies, quotes Seneca and turns on his television to
watch ``The Andy Griffith Show.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of it is charming. But not everything, not by a long shot.
Salinger's views on celebrity are often funny and trenchant. There
are unmistakable echoes of Holden Caulfield. Yet a mannered
pessimism that may be endearing in a fictional teen-ager comes
across as dyspeptic in his middle-aged voice. Grown up, Holden can
be one heck of a grouch.
</P>
<P>
   And you have to wonder what a 53-year-old could possibly see in
an 18-year-old to sustain a relationship for even the nine months
that this one lasted. May-December is one thing. This was more like
February-September. Bewilderment turns to concern with Ms.
Maynard's claim to have discovered in recent years that she was but
one of several very young women who were romanced with letters from
Salinger.
</P>
<P>
   If that is true, you also have to wonder if God played a grand
joke: teaming a fanatical recluse with a woman incapable of keeping
anything to herself, punishing both in the process. J.D. Salinger's
mistake may have been to ignore his own admonition at the end of
``The Catcher in the Rye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ever tell anybody anything,'' Holden Caulfield says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
