<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0603 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKGAME-PROBE19-COX     06-18 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKGAME-PROBE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Struggling board game company linked to agent, UF investigation
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch and Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ A small company set up to sell
black-achievement board games _ and losing about $1 million a year
_ has assumed a curious place in a probe of a sports agent's
alleged gifts to University of Florida players of cash and cars.
</P>
<P>
   BAOA Inc.'s stockholders include Rev. Jesse Jackson, who said
Thursday that as far as he knew, sports agent and BAOA director
William ``Tank'' Black never used the company as a slush fund to
buy gifts for clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is he is innocent until proven guilty,'' Jackson
said. ``I have tremendous respect for Tank. He has done tremendous
things for young people.''
</P>
<P>
   But officers at BAOA said Black is no longer a director there _
contrary to the firm's last annual report posted at the Securities
and Exchange Commission Web site _ and declined to say when or why
the relationship ended.
</P>
<P>
   BAOA, a San Diego firm set up to sell a board game called Black
Americans of Achievement, has reported annual losses ranging from
$1.2 million in 1995 to $882,000 in 1997, records show.
</P>
<P>
   As of Dec. 31, 1997, some 128 investors included active and
former football players Sterling Sharpe, Deion Figures and Ike
Hilliard, as well as Black himself. The NFL Players Association
says players bought the stock for up to $1 per share, but it's
worth about 5 cents now.
</P>
<P>
   Black is under investigation by the NFLPA and Florida campus
police for allegedly giving cash or cars to several Florida
football players before their college eligibility expired so they
would hire him as an agent. He has also reportedly been questioned
by the Securities and Exchange Commission, though an SEC spokesman
said he could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Steven R. Wright, BAOA's secretary and treasurer reached by
telephone in San Diego, said he was surprised to learn of
allegations that Black had, on more than once occasion, arranged
for players to pay for BAOA stock by way of checks made out to
another firm, P.E. Communications.
</P>
<P>
   P.E. Communications' funds are under Black's personal control,
the NFLPA alleged in a five-page complaint reported by at least two
news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a cause of concern,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   There are no corporate records for P.E. Communications in South
Carolina, where Black is based, or in Florida, where he represents
pro players including ex-Gators Fred Taylor and Reidel Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   Black's attorney, Leonard Mungo, did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Belle Glade native Taylor, meanwhile, said reports linking him
to the Black investigation are untrue. The NFLPA alleges in its
complaint against Black that an LSU assistant coach said Black told
him that he used Taylor's money to purchase a car for a Unversity
of Florida football player before his eligibility had expired.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who was a star tailback at UF, denied that any of his
money was used to purchase a $133,500 Mercedez-Benz for former
Florida linebacker Jevon Kearse. Taylor signed with Black and was a
first-round pick by the Jacksonville Jaguars last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that's bull, It's not true,' Taylor told The Times-Union
in Jacksonville. ``I'm sure if (Black) wanted to buy Jevon the car,
he wouldn't need my money. Why would he use my money?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just trying to make Black out to be a bad person. I'm
not going to buy a $135,000 car. That's stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Also listed among BAOA shareholders is Nathaniel Moore _ but
former Gator receiver turned broadcaster Moore says if he is an
investor, he is not aware of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can write down my name,'' Moore said Thursday. ``I
don't own any of that stock. I never have owned any. I've never
received any dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said he has known Black for 15 or 20 years, and they had
dinner at the last Florida-South Carolina game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I haven't had any business dealings with him and I hope I
never do,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   After losing money on the board game, BAOA reported in its last
annual report that it has shifted its focus to planned
telemarketing operations in ``enterprise zones'' _ typically,
inner-city areas with tax breaks _ in cities including Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   BAOA's last annual report, for the year ended Dec. 31, 1997, was
filed in April 1998. Quarterly reports have been filed since, but
they reveal few details about management and shareholders. No
annual report for 1998 is mentioned at the SEC's website, and
company officials declined to say why a more recent report is
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Treasurer/secretary Wright said he had seen no evidence of
wrongdoing in the company's books, nor was he aware of any SEC
investigation involving BAOA. Wright has signed company reports
sent to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had about no dealings with Mr. Black'' in recent months,
Wright said. ``He's spent all of his time in South Carolina, not
here.''
</P>
<P>
   BAOA attorney Charles Smith said he did not wish to comment on
when or why Black left as a director.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jackson, he signed a two-year deal in February 1997 to
receive 100,000 BAOA shares annually in exchange for consulting
services to BAOA Inc. Company records say he was given 100,000
shares at the end of 1997, then valued at 10 cents apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said Thursday if he still owns the shares, he is not
aware of it.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC, according to Street &AMP; Smith's Sports Business Journal,
has been conducting a year-long investigation into sports agents
and their involvement in clients' finances.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Mungo acknowledged that Black met with SEC officials on
May 25 to answer questions about his role in his clients'
investments, the SBJ reported. The federal agency reportedly
questioned Black, but didn't take any documentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know any details,'' Jackson said in response to
questions from The Palm Beach Post during a conference call
Thursday. ``I do know that unfortunately the tendency is to try
convict people in newsrooms, not the courtroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
