<HEADER>
A0615 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-GUN19-COX     06-18 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gun legislation puts Bush in a tough spot
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Guns rival boots, barbecue and pickup trucks as
emblems of the Lone Star State. But as Republican George W. Bush
attempts to move from the Governor's Mansion to the White House,
Democrats are poised to make gun laws that are popular in Texas a
liability for Bush in a national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few days, Bush will sign a bill barring Texas cities
from suing gun makers to recover damages resulting from gun
violence. Signing the legislation, which was overwhelmingly
approved by state lawmakers, is a no-brainer in pro-gun Texas. But
it could be politically problematic for Bush in other areas of the
country, especially in pro-gun control, electoral vote-rich states
like New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   Gun violence is heating up as a prominent campaign issue in the
wake of the Littleton school massacre, and gun control advocates
view court action as a way around the National Rifle Association's
considerable legislative clout. Democratic presidential
front-runner Al Gore and gun control groups have already begun to
portray Bush, who also supported Texas's concealed handgun law, as
a candidate who is cozy with the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``While some want to pass new protections for gun manufacturers
to shield them from lawsuits, I will work to get guns off the
street, out of the schools and away from children and criminals,''
Gore said this week in a not-so-veiled reference to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the governor ``does not
believe lawsuits should replace legislation as a method of
accomplishing things in a democracy.'' Hughes said Bush views gun
lawsuits as a tort reform issue, not a gun control issue. She noted
that the bill allows the Texas attorney general to approve a city's
lawsuit or file one on behalf of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Vice President Gore wants to take the side of frivolous
lawsuits, which cost jobs and clog the courts and delay justice for
people who need it, we'll fight that fight,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1998, about 20 cities and counties in 11 states have sued
gun makers, arguing that gun violence adds millions of dollars to
their expenses for medical care, emergency services, police,
courts, prisons, and school security. In most cases, plaintiffs
argue that gun manufacturers could do more to make guns safer, such
as installing safety locks and devices that indicate that there is
a bullet in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   In most of the lawsuits, the cities and counties also accuse gun
makers of negligent marketing, contending that they intentionally
oversupply cities and states with weak gun laws, knowing that
excess guns will be sold illegally in markets with stricter laws.
Some also argue that manufacturers employ false advertising when
they claim that having a gun makes a household safer. Gun control
advocates cite studies showing that a gun is more likely to kill or
injury a family member than an intruder.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush ``believes that the best gun control is to
enforce tough laws against people who commit crimes with guns.''
She noted that the Legislature this session approved a Bush-backed
bill mandating detention for juveniles who illegally possess a gun,
and that the governor previously signed a law penalizing parents
when their children are injured or killed because the parents
didn't store their guns safely.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the governor supports instant
background checks at gun shows, which are currently being debated
on Capitol Hill. She said he opposed a background check bill that
died in the Legislature this session because it would have forced
unlicensed gun dealers, who don't currently have access to a
federal database, to perform the checks. Bush opposes laws that
would force gun makers to install safety locks, but supports
``voluntary'' efforts by manufacturers to do so, Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has never been a member of the NRA or its Texas affiliate,
which gave him a total of $6,000 during his most recent
gubernatorial race, a fraction of the$17.7 millionhe collected.
</P>
<P>
   But former Colorado Gov. Roy Romer, the chairman of the
Democratic National Commitee, said there's only one reason Bush
would sign the lawsuit bill: ``a knee jerk reaction to the NRA.''
``George Bush ducked the issue of background checks, and this is
another failure. I think it raises a real question of his
leadership ability, because it's clearly a response to a special
interest group,'' Romer said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Beard, who heads the Coalition to Stop Gun Violence,
said gun control advocates will make sure that voters hear about
Bush's decision to sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Particularly in places like California and New York and Ohio,
we're going to do everything we can to publicize the fact that he
wants to take away home rule,'' Beard said. ``Apparently he's more
interested in the NRA and protecting gun dealers than protecting
the rights of gun victims.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, gun control advocates have won one victory in a lawsuit
against manufacturers, but it wasn't in a lawsuit by a city or
county. Last February, a group of shooting victims in New York won
a $4 million verdict in a case based on the negligent marketing
argument.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates liken the lawsuits to the popular and
largely successful lawsuits against tobacco companies, in which
states have won billions of dollars as compensation for their share
of Medicare and Medicaid costs. Texas' lawsuit netted $17.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to drive them out of business _ that's not
the point. Mayors will drop these lawsuits in a minute if the gun
manufacturers agree to change their manufacturing and distribution
practices,'' said Nancy Hwa of the Washington-based Center to
Prevent Handgun Violence. ``The goal is to reform the industry, and
to stabilize and reduce the amount of gun violence in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Hwa's contention, the National Rifle Association, which
has been pressuring state legislatures to pass laws banning the
lawsuits, argues that the goal is to put gun makers out of
business. Chief lobbyist Jim Baker said the court action is an end
run around the legislative process, and that it is being pushed by
lawyers looking to get rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to blame the firearms manufacturers, who are
highly regulated at the state and federal level, for the criminal
misuse of their product. It would be like suing the Ford Motor Co.
because someone driving drunk in one of their cars killed someone.
Who knows where it will stop?'' said Baker. He added that gun
lawsuits are different from those against the tobacco companies
because tobacco can't be used safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody, whether you're a firearms owner or you support
ownership or not, ought to be concerned about the lawyers who hope
to bring this type of suit against industries across the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
