<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-NATGUARD-BOSNIA19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas Guard soldiers train for Bosnia mission
 &HT;    By Mike Kelley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Army National Guard soldiers, including
several units based in Austin, have begun training for deployment
early next year to the NATO peacekeeping mission in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   When troops of the 49th ``Lonestar'' Armored Division, based at
Camp Mabry in Austin, arrive in Bosnia in February, it will mark
the first time National Guard units will be in command of
active-duty U.S. military, as well as international peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of that, Camp Mabry spokesman Aaron Reed said,
is threefold: closer integration of National Guard with active-duty
troops; expanded opportunity of missions the Guard may be called on
to fill; and ``a sign of relief on the horizon for some of these
active-duty units who keep getting tapped for contingency
operations one after another.''
</P>
<P>
   The Guard troops began their training at Fort Hood last weekend
and will continue through June 26. Reed, who has served with the
Guard in Bosnia, said that while at Hood, the soldiers will train
in things ``specific to Bosnia.'' Those, he said, include dealing
with civilians on a battlefield, detecting land mines and
conducting vehicle searches.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,100 Texas Guard troops are involved in the current
training for deployment. They will serve no more than nine months
on active duty and probably about seven months in Bosnia, Reed
said.
</P>
<P>
   There will be further training before the troops leave, he said,
including a mission-rehearsal exercise in November at Fort Polk,
La.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the five units based at Camp Mabry, headquarters of the
Texas National Guard, units training at Fort Hood are from Dallas,
Abilene and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Guard, civilians for most of the year, train one
weekend a month and two weeks every year in their military
specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
