<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Find your father now and tell him that you love him
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ I am going to tell you of a horrible mistake I
made. I tell you in the hope that you may avoid making it yourself.
Indeed, on certain days I believe that if I can save just one
person from making this mistake, my life will have been worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   And I will tell you, to the extent humanly possible, without
emotion, dry-eyed and clear of voice. At least that is what I
intend to do.
</P>
<P>
   But first things first. Right now, before another minute passes,
stop whatever you are doing, get up, find your father, in person or
by telephone, it doesn't matter, and say these words:
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Do not wait to do this or it may be too late. Put this newspaper
down. Do not finish this column. You can finish it when you are
done with the task or never at all, I do not care so long as you do
what I ask of you.
</P>
<P>
   Say the words or risk that, like me, your father will be gone
with those words never having passed between the two of you, in
either direction. Say the words or risk having them haunt you for
the rest of your life.
</P>
<P>
   For they haunt me and I know they always will.
</P>
<P>
   Say the words even if your father is bedridden in a nursing home
in a coma with his mind on hold. No one understands how the human
mind works in its unconscious state. Who knows for sure that your
father wouldn't hear the words and feel some unspeakable joy?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, those words do as much good for the one who speaks them
as the one who hears them. Verbalizing your love, respect and
commitment to honor your father will forever remain in your memory.
Trust me, neglecting to do so will also be with you forever.
</P>
<P>
   The wonderful thing is that, upon saying ``I love you, Dad,''
there is the greatest of possibilities that you will hear it back.
Nothing but hearing that from your mother could be so special.
</P>
<P>
   I had my chances, dozens _ more likely, thousands _ of chances
to tell my father I loved him. Unfortunately, I was too much like
him to act.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that my father was cold but he had difficulty
expressing his emotion with words. Yes, I know he loved me. I did
not need to hear to words to validate his love but, nonetheless, I
would have liked to hear them. Probably he would have liked to hear
them from me, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Did he know I loved him? I can only hope that he did because I
will never know for sure.
</P>
<P>
   I know there must be many fathers and sons who, like my father
and me, can't quite say ``I love you'' to another man. Is this
stupid? Certainly. I feel stupid every day.
</P>
<P>
   I had a final chance just a few days before he died, as he lay
wasting away in a nursing home, the victim of a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could rationalize it all away, that I could say I did
not know he was going to die so soon.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is different. I stood beside his bed knowing that,
when I left the room, I would never again see him alive. The words
rolled up from my gut and stuck on my tongue. I wanted to rub his
shoulder and tell him: ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I turned and walked away. My prediction proved correct.
He died less than 48 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Like all decisions one makes, I live with the consequences. I
have tried to make up for it by making sure the words are spoken _
and received _ often from my two sons.
</P>
<P>
   It is not enough. It will never be enough.
</P>
<P>
   So my mission in life is to make sure you do not make the same
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Say the words. Say them now. Say them for me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
