</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A lesson learned from Rosa Parks
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The first time Patricia Ellis headed to the
nation's capital on behalf of Rosa Parks, she didn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   At 7:30 a.m. July 29, 1997, near Petersburg, Va., a tour bus
plunged off Interstate 95 into the Nottoway River. The bus carried
29 students and five chaperones, including Ellis. They were taking
part in a tour, sponsored by Rosa Parks' foundation, of historic
sites in the civil rights struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an out-of-body experience,'' Ellis said. She saw the bus
fly into the air and plummet into the river. Submerged under water,
she heard a voice calling her name. ``I was getting ready to turn
around and to see who it was when the water became water lilies.
Even now when I close my eyes, I can see it, and it is one of the
most beautiful things I've ever seen in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The water lilies symbolized the presence of God, Ellis said,
calling her from death to life, from surrender to the water to the
struggle to save the lives of the children.
</P>
<P>
   This week marked the second time Ellis headed to Washington,
D.C., on behalf of Rosa Parks. This time, the Oxford woman made it
there safely, spending much of two days with Parks and watching
proudly Tuesday as President Clinton awarded the civil rights
heroine the Congressional Gold Medal.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone stood up and gave an ovation to this small, frail woman
who had the courage, nearly 44 years ago, to sit down and be
counted.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very courageous woman, and she was an instrument of
God,'' Ellis said. ``She was not standing up for herself; she was
sitting down on racism across the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And the world listened _ not only in 1955, but in the decades of
unflagging civil rights activism that followed. ``Mrs. Parks passes
on the courage to be and to do what's right,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in a tight-knit black community in Hamilton, Ellis
shared her neighbors' anxiety when she first heard about the
soft-spoken seamstress who refused to move to the back of the bus.
Ellis was only 14, but she understood the implications:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most frightening thing,'' she recalled. ``We knew
when anybody goes against the system, when anyone dares to go
against that way of life, especially in the South, there is a good
chance they would be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis grew up to become a history teacher at Hamilton High
School, a civil rights historian, and an adviser for the National
Underground Railroad Freedom Center in Cincinnati. She has won
numerous awards for her work as a teacher and civil rights
historian, including the Governor's award from the Martin Luther
King Jr. Holiday Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she was taken by surprise the morning in June 1997 when she
received a call from someone claiming to represent Rosa Parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right,'' she thought to herself. Next thing you know, Oprah
will be calling.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the real thing. She was being asked to come along on
a monthlong Pathways to Freedom bus tour, designed to bring the
history of the civil rights movement to life for young people. She
would serve as chaperone in addition to her role in evaluating the
program.
</P>
<P>
   During five days of training in Canada, Ellis spent a
considerable amount of time with Parks. ``She doesn't talk very
much,'' she said, but Ellis felt she had come to know the woman:
her quiet strength and spirituality, her graciousness and humility.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three days into the trip, tragedy struck.
</P>
<P>
   In the first moments after the crash, Ellis said, she felt
herself lying ``peacefully in the water,'' feeling no sense of
struggle. It was only when she prayed, ``Oh my God, are all the
children going to die this way?'' that she shook off her stupor.
</P>
<P>
   The bus had landed on a sandbank in deep water, with everything
under water except the top of the bus. Ellis helped the students
clamber on top of the bus through narrow openings in the windows.
Only one person remained unaccounted for _ Adisa Foluke of Detroit,
a 25-year-old chaperone and Rosa Parks' godson.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis led the students in the Lord's Prayer as they waited atop
the bus. Then she prayed aloud, ``God, I'm afraid.'' She prayed for
guidance and then told the children to form a human chain across
the river of all those who could swim and were not afraid
</P>
<P>
   Adisa Foluke had drowned. All of the 29 students, ages 11 to 18,
survived, although one teen's leg was so mangled it required
amputation.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it was believed that Ellis had sustained a serious eye
injury, but the cut above her eye required only 15 stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis had not set foot on a bus since the tragedy _ until this
week.
</P>
<P>
   She hadn't planned it that way. She had purchased a round-trip
plane ticket to D.C.
</P>
<P>
   For two days, she went to lunch and dinner with Parks and her
group. She met Ruby Dee, Cicely Tyson, Colin Powell, Dick Gregory.
``There were actors, senators, movers and shakers, a who's who of
the civil rights movement _ and me,'' she said, laughing at the
improbability of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of those people at the White House could not have been
there if it were not for Rosa Parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Something stirred in Ellis when she saw Parks accept her award,
when she heard her praised as ``the mother of the nation.'' All at
once, she knew she would have to take the Greyhound home, that she
would have to set foot in a bus, despite her terror. It was a
12-hour ordeal _ ``very traumatic,'' she said, ``but it was
something I needed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only in stepping outside herself, overcoming her fear,
after all, that she was able to help save the students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only when you deny yourself and come out of the self
that God can use you,'' Ellis reflected.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lesson she learned from Rosa Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
