r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN19-COX     06-18 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Readers, lend me your ears
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ Working for a newspaper has many hazards.
Reporters and editors get into trouble without trying. Thousands of
readers are out there every day, anxious to catch mistakes.
Newspapers, by definition, offer innumerable ways to make them.
</P>
<P>
   Editors and reporters go to a factory every day to manufacture a
product. They never know exactly how the product will be packaged,
or what size it will be. The parts that go into the product come
from all over the world, numbering in the hundreds, even in tens of
thousands if you count words. Nobody knows in advance where these
parts will come from.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few hours these parts must be trimmed or expanded, and
reshaped to fit into the day's newspaper, which is then printed,
and within a few hours, delivered to hundreds of thousands of
doorsteps at the cost of a candy bar. It can be used to learn about
current events, for entertainment, and sometimes for thoughtful
discussion, not to mention lining bird cages, wrapping fish and
starting fires.
</P>
<P>
   When some English teacher spots a misspelled word (perhaps a
typographical error) or a wrong tense, the newspaper gets a letter
asking why illiterate idiots are allowed to work there. Considering
time constraints, newspapers do a pretty good job of limiting
mistakes. Lawyers can take days and weeks at several hundred
dollars an hour to write a single document, whereas newspaper
reporters write stories in minutes, for considerably less.
</P>
<P>
   When I was gainfully employed at the Atlanta newspapers, I put a
lot of effort into making sure we didn't bury anybody alive on the
obituary pages. This can be embarrassing as well as slightly
libelous. It happened on my watch.
</P>
<P>
   A man who was feuding with a neighbor called the newspaper to
report the neighbor had died. He gave all the details, up to
survivors and pallbearers. Unfortunately, a beginning reporter who
didn't know the rules about checking with funeral homes took the
call. The neighbor was somewhat upset to find himself deceased in
the morning paper.
</P>
<P>
   When I signed on as a semi-columnist for the Southside editions
of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, I made a few rules I felt
appropriate for an elderly journalist out to pasture. I would do no
research; would not deal with subjects requiring tedious facts;
would conduct no interviews; would not travel north of Harp's
Crossing or south of Woolsey unless my wife made me. Basically, my
semi-column wouldn't involve real work.
</P>
<P>
   This philosophy was stolen from the late Lewis Grizzard. Lewis
was not only a great writer, he was a great teacher. While visiting
him at the hospital during his last illness, he pointed out that
I'd told him when he began writing a column he should plan on doing
something else after about 10 years, when he was likely to burn
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you to know,'' he said, ``that I've been doing it for
over 11 years and I'm still going strong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's remarkable,'' I replied. ``How do you do it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret to writing a newspaper column,'' Lewis said with a
sly grin and a twinkle in his eye, ``is remembering a lot of things
that never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   All I can say is it's a lot more fun than trying to resolve
Kosovo and getting tangled up in abortion issues. However, my best
efforts haven't kept me entirely out of trouble. A couple of weeks
ago I managed to marry off a young lady who isn't married, although
I'd guess that won't be true for long.
</P>
<P>
   Relating a guided tour of the new Azalea Estates retirement
complex in Fayetteville, conducted by a charming young lady named
Elaine Odom, I described her as ``the former Elaine Massengale of
the Starr's Mill Massengales.''
</P>
<P>
   I got a nice note from her mother. ``You were right about
everything else, but she is not married _ yet! Elaine Odom is the
daughter of Mary Alice Massengale Odom and Don Odom. She is the
granddaughter of Kendrick Massengale, the last person to operate
Starr's Mill.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought Elaine said ``I was a Massengale from Starr's Mill.''
What she said was, ``My mother was a Massengale from Starr's
Mill.''
</P>
<P>
   All I can do is offer the standard apology and correction and
promise to revisit the hearing aid issue I thought I had cleared up
by returning the two earplugs my wife thoughtfully gave me last
Christmas, and which made the simple act of turning on a water
faucet sound like Niagara Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Not one to give up easily, she has suggested after the
Odom-Massengale mistake that I either get my hearing aids back or
quit writing a newspaper column. At least I'm not alone. According
to Newsweek, one out of 10 Americans suffer some hearing loss, and
they're not all elderly.
</P>
<P>
   I flunked the test on how to tell if you're going deaf. I
sometimes do ask people to repeat themselves; I turn up the TV
louder than my spouse prefers, and she often tells me I don't hear
well. According to Newsweek, I can barely hear it thunder.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of nights ago, the usual dinner-interrupting telephone
solicitation was a young lady trying to sell me an amplified
receiver. I don't know who told her I needed one, but after I kept
asking her to repeat she soon hung up on her own accord. Being deaf
ain't all that bad.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
