r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBA-ON-TV19-COX     06-18 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-ON-TV19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drama of long series could raise TV ratings
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Spurs, who boast the well-liked, clean-cut
David Robinson, don't have the superstar power of Shaq and the
Lakers or the Bulls of the Michael Jordan era, but NBC doesn't seem
to care.
</P>
<P>
   Given the sluggish ratings for Wednesday's opening game of the
NBA Finals, maybe it should.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Nielsen national ratings for game one, the
figures were down 36 percent from last year's first game _ about
11.5 million television households this year vs. about 18 million
last year. But NBC is quick to point out that last year's game was
the highest-rated first game in NBA Finals history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is having a long series,'' said Ed Markey, vice
president of sports press for NBC. ``That's all a network ever
pulls for. Longer series build drama and gather viewer interest as
it goes along.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does NBC worry that San Antonio is a relatively small TV
market (37th-largest in the nation). It helps that New York is the
biggest TV market, and you'd think it would help even more if the
other team were from a top 10 market, too. But as long as the NBA
Finals between the Spurs and the New York Knicks goes at least six
_ and preferably seven _ games, NBC is certain viewers will come.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were a one-game, winner-take-all championship, we
might be worried,'' Markey said. ``But over the course of a series,
these events have a way of building interest. If the series goes
six or seven games, market size may have no impact at all.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, last year's World Series, featuring the New York
Yankees against the San Diego Padres, was the lowest-rated World
Series ever. The Yankees are popular across the country, and New
York is the No. 1 TV market, but analysts say the ratings were low
because the Yankees won in a four-game sweep with little suspense.
</P>
<P>
   NBC expects its overall ratings for the Finals this year to be
lower than last year, possibly by as much as 20 percent. That's
because last year's Finals between the Bulls _ in what would be
Jordan's grand finale _ and the Utah Jazz went six games and set a
record with almost 20 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be down 20 percent this year and still have an
average that's in the top 10 of all time,'' Markey said.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 percent of NBA television viewers are men, and most are
18 to 49 years old, according to Nielsen Media Research. And the
audience for postseason play is different than the crowd that tunes
in for the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you move into the playoffs and Finals in prime time, you
attract more casual fans, people who might not know all the details
of the NBA but like the big story and big-event nature of it,''
Markey said. ``The regular season attracts primarily hard-core NBA
fans, `hoop-heads.' They watch no matter who is playing.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably why the regular-season ratings for the NBA on
NBC did not sink catastrophically with the retirement of Jordan, as
some expected they would. Nielsen said the regular ratings dipped
only 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Casual fans are more likely to be attracted by pop-culture stars
like Charles Barkley and Dennis Rodman. And certain teams with a
special cachet also draw more casual viewers. Those attractive
stars and star teams can spring up overnight, and next year's Spurs
could very well turn out to be the new red-hot team, especially if
they win the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to '94, we didn't have the Rockets on too much, but they
made the playoffs, won the championships and something happened,''
Markey said. ``People started to discover how good Hakeem Olajuwon
and the Rockets are. Since then, they've become a staple of our
schedule. The Spurs' success will pay off down the line as we go
forward, and their story will start to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
