r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN19-COX     06-18 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't hit the road
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The urgency coming out of the two-way radio
grabbed the attention of the leather-clad riders standing near the
water coolers in the pit-lane shed.
</P>
<P>
   These radios are usually pressed to the heads of turn watchers
and track bosses when
</P>
<P>
   motorcycles scream past.
</P>
<P>
   Someone on the unattended pit wrangler's radio was shouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did he say?'' asked one of the sweating riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rider down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Riders,'' came the correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riders?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many are down?'' demanded a calm radio voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three,'' said the excited radio voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we need an ambulance?'' asked the calm voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two are up and walking,'' said the excited voice. ``All three
are up. Instructors are there
</P>
<P>
   now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we need an ambulance?'' repeated the voice in authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said the now calm observer. ``They're OK.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What turn?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he said six,'' said another rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be that sealer in six,'' said a rider. ``I nearly lost
it there when it started to rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah. Yeah. It must have been the track sealer that is used by
sadists to patch torn-up portions of the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   When sealer patches get wet, they get slick. This is a bigger
deal to people who ride
</P>
<P>
   motorcycles at amusing speeds than it is for race car drivers.
</P>
<P>
   We were in the second day of the California Superbike School at
Texas World Speedway outside of College Station when the run-offs,
get-offs, high-sides, low-sides and plain old crashes started to
mount.
</P>
<P>
   Motorcycle riders like to know what type of dismount occurred
and where it happened in the hope that they can avoid the same
fate.
</P>
<P>
   If they could talk, I imagine that African gazelles would have
the same conversations after
</P>
<P>
   a leopard reduced their numbers by one.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was he doing? Where did it happen? What did he do
wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   Gazelles get better at avoiding leopards by the constant
thinning of their gene pool by hungry leopards, who get better at
killing gazelles by the constant thinning of their gene pool by
weaker leopards that starve to death.
</P>
<P>
   Motorcyclists prefer less drastic methods to get better at what
they do, which is why nearly 100 of us paid up to $600 a day to
enroll in Keith Code's renowned superbike school.
</P>
<P>
   Code is a legend. He's a former champion racer. He is best known
now as the god of motorcycle racing instruction. He has trained
more world champion racers and street riders than anyone on earth.
Three of the current national No. 1 plate holders have been his
students.
</P>
<P>
   The science of motorcycle racing instruction was developed by
Code, who will personally share his discoveries with anyone who
wants to become a better rider and has a credit card that can take
a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Code teaches all the classroom stuff. He has a stable of
professional riding coaches who guide students on the track where
they practice the drills that go with the latest technique taught
by Code in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   It's classroom-track, classroom-track over and over from 7 a.m.
until 5 p.m., rain or shine
</P>
<P>
   Students can go as fast as they want. They can pass inside,
outside, high or low. But if they crash, they're out. No more
riding.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the rain or the sealer, in my opinion, that caused so
many riders to go down that afternoon. I think frisky riders were
pushing their newly acquired limits before time ran out, which is
probably a lesson even gazelles should learn.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway's columns appear on Wednesdays and Fridays.
E-mail: rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
