<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, June 19,
1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive and personal finance
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books, fashion, and
home &AMP; garden
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ This column will not move today. (Warner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-BAPTISTS _ The Southern Baptist Convention, just
finishing its annual meet in Atlanta this week, has undergone
dramatic changes over the last two decades. Once a voice of
moderation, the SBC today is known for its conservative political
and biblical positions, beliefs that at once make it popular along
America's Bible Belt and heartland and feared by those more liberal
forces in the country. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIENCE-MEDICINE PAGE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH 0615 -- Research on premature babies who share
a bed with their siblings suggests it's more than just comforting
to stay close with their buddies from the womb as soon as practical
after birth. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) Art includes 3-column color
photo of babies in crib.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAUMA RESPONSE -- Paramedics arriving to the scene of
accidents in well-equipped vehicles and trained in up-to-date
techniques have improved the chances a victim of a traumatic
accident will survive. (Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
