<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 11:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0643 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     06-18 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, June 18, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHRONICLE-SALE (San Francisco) _ After 134 years of secrecy, the
San Francisco Chronicle may be opening its books to some of its
closest and fiercest competitors. The veil will be lifted, a
Chronicle spokesman said, to accommodate would-be suitors lining up
to buy the family-owned enterprise. By JULIAN GUTHRIE and SCOTT
WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   SLA-FUGITIVE (St. Paul, Minn.) _ After more than 23 years of
hiding in plain sight, the woman alleged to be Kathleen Ann Soliah,
alias Sarah Jane Olson, found herself standing before the world
Thursday in a bright orange prisoner's jumpsuit. Her shocked
friends say she was a typical ``soccer mom.'' By LARRY D. HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-CAMERAS (Laredo, Texas) _ The federal government is
installing high-tech cameras along the border that would track
fugitives and stolen cars by scanning the license plates of all
vehicles entering or leaving the United States, officials said. By
DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   REPORTER-MURDERED (Undated) _ FBI agents believe two Huichol
Indians jailed in Mexico are responsible for the brutal death of
San Antonio Express-News journalist Philip True, according to a
U.S. Justice Department official following the case. By GARY
MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGE (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco Chamber of
Commerce has become one of the first major business groups to
oppose a statewide ballot measure that would ban recognition of gay
marriages. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-SILICON (Undated) _ Steve Jobs and Bill Gates were the
originals, trailblazers who laid down the first cobblestone of what
would become the Information Superhighway. ``Pirates of Silicon
Valley'' (Sunday at 8 p.m., TNT), covering the years 1971-97,
chronicles their rise to master innovators, thinkers, maneuverers
and _ especially important _ thieves. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-BEGGARS (Undated) _ There are a lot of searing jokes
and satiric insights in ``Beggars and Choosers,'' a tremendously
good new series on Showtime that spoofs all the truths of the TV
industry. But there's one thing left out: Network television is so
littered with average shows that if you want something truly great,
you have to pay for it. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-BESIEGED (Undated) _ There is indeed dialogue in
``Besieged.'' Characters swap hellos, conduct business, hobnob with
drunken pals, even engage occasionally in the odd moment of searing
emotional truth. But while Bernardo Bertolucci's enthralling and
poetically simple work includes a bit of conversation, it is at
heart a silent film. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-DESERT (Undated) _ It's a dry, dry state of affairs
in the Southwest town of Baxter when even Fred Schneider of the
B-52s sounds comatose as the town DJ. It's also a disembodied
reminder that ``Desert Blue'' isn't just the name of Morgan J.
Freeman's somnambulant cemetery of a movie, it's a state of mind.
By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-VIOLIN (Undated) _ The best word to describe the new
film from director Francois Girard, ``The Red Violin,'' is
``beautiful.'' Simply, beautiful. The film tells the story of a
violin created by an Italian master in the 17th century and the way
it affects a long parade of lives. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-GENERAL'S (UNdated) _ The general's daughter was a
freak. That's what the boys around Fort MacCallum military base
called her. But Capt. Elisabeth Campbell (Leslie Stephanson) was
supposedly a freak on a mission, one that gets her ``raped . . .
tortured . . . and murdered'' late-'80s-early-'90s action-thriller
style: her raw, naked body splayed in the base courtyard. By WESLEY
MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SEXUAL (Undated) _ With the philosophical ambition
of a man who's decided that the first few chapters of Genesis
needed an autobiographical make-over, Mike Figgis presents ``The
Loss of Sexual Innocence,'' an allegory configured as a ``personal
journey'' toward some kind of enlightenment about the contemporary
deflowering of our carnal selves. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ If an employee believes he has been
discriminated against at work, he typically lodges a complaint with
the human resource department or affirmative action office. But
what does the employee do when the top officer in charge of
investigating complaints is accused of the very same wrongdoing and
remains in office? Whom does he turn to? By L.M. SIXEL
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ If there are remaining doubts about
whether Microsoft ``gets'' the Internet, they are dashed by the
latest version of the software giant's cash cow, Office 2000. It's
the first application suite that treats the Net as a given. By
DWIGHT SILVERMAN
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``We have a single
computer in our house that I share with my wife and two small
children. I have noticed that, when the children are using the
computer, their CD-ROM software doesn't work as well as it used to.
... What could be wrong?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS-DUNCAN (San Antonio) _ He is the anti-MTV,
anti-slacker, anti-showboating, anti-smack-talking antidote to the
next generation of wannabe stars.In a world that worships style,
Tim Duncan insists on offering substance. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-PEBBLE-SALE (San Francisco) _ A celebrity-studded group that
includes Peter Ueberroth, Arnold Palmer and Clint Eastwood grabbed
one of the most coveted chunks of real estate in California,
agreeing to buy Pebble Beach golf course for $820 million. By PETER
HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-WOMEN'S-CUP (Undated) _ The favorites are the United States,
China, Norway and Germany, but don't be surprised if the Women's
World Cup, which begins a three-week run Saturday with
doubleheaders in East Rutherford, N.J., and San Jose, turns wild
and woolly. By DWIGHT CHAPIN.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-SOSA (Undated) _ Sammy Sosa's gift for diplomacy borders,
well, on the frightening. Thursday, for example, he performed the
heretofore unattempted ``I Like It Here AND There'' double Salchow
from the visitors dugout at Candlestick Park. To nobody's surprise,
he executed it flawlessly. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
</TEXT>
