<HEADLINE>
FILM TAKES A HARD LOOK AT THE GEEKS OF SILICON VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The celluloid Steve Jobs is seen as the dreamer, the spiritual
druggie with a new-age vision for a technical utopia. Bill Gates is
the porn-loving daredevil who drag-raced a bulldozer one midnight
and won virtually every poker hand he played.
</P>
<P>
   Including his biggest hand of all.
</P>
<P>
   These college kids grew into two very young men who changed the
late 20th century, and certainly all of the next. The computer
mavens _ Jobs of Apple, Gates of Microsoft _ were the originals,
trailblazers who laid down the first cobblestone of what would
become the Information Superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' (Sunday at 8 p.m., TNT), covering
the years 1971-97, chronicles their rise at opposite ends of the
country (Jobs at Berkeley, Gates at Harvard) to master innovators,
thinkers, maneuverers and _ especially important _ thieves.
</P>
<P>
   This is really a chase movie _ Jobs chasing a vision, Gates
chasing, well, the thrill of the chase. This is a movie about
geeks, but not necessarily just for geeks. They are the
late-millennium superheroes, without the personal ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Tinged with Shakespearean themes of loyalty and treachery and
the heights of power and megalomania, this film is above all
engrossing fun, one that will leave you with an observation and a
question:
</P>
<P>
   The observation: Man, they were lucky. Sleazy, but lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The question: Why didn't I think of that?
</P>
<P>
   Above all this is a story about two men, one who became rich,
the other the richest, who saw what others (IBM, Hewlett-Packard,
Xerox) didn't. They knew, just knew, that the computer _ and, in
the case of Gates, software _ would have applications and appeal to
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how you survive?'' Gates says in the movie. ``You
make people need you. You survive because you make them need what
you have. Then they have nowhere else to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates wanted to dominate, Jobs wanted to shape. Both dominated,
both shaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to make a dent in the universe,'' Jobs reportedly
tells director Ridley Scott as he is making the legendary 1984
Apple Macintosh commercial for the Super Bowl, an Orwellian ``Big
Brother'' slap at IBM. ``Otherwise, why even be here? We are
rewriting the history of human thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Noah Wyle, as Jobs, and Anthony Michael Hall, as Gates, may have
also rewritten their careers. The typecasts of Dr. Carter (Wyle)
and the '80s movie geek (Hall) fade early into the movie as both
actors _ each of whom bears startling physical resemblances to the
very real people they portray _ quickly and effectively slip into
their characters.
</P>
<P>
   And Jobs and Gates are portrayed in lights that are respectful
of their brilliance, but far from flattering.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs is seen abandoning his daughter (they reunite at the end)
and eviscerating employees, while Gates is shown to be lying and
manipulative, stealing ideas from those who do not realize their
ideas' import.
</P>
<P>
   The other legendary sidemen _ Steve Wozniak (Joey Slotnik) of
Apple and Steve Ballmer (John DiMaggio) and Paul Allen (Josh
Hopkins) of Microsoft _ are all present, with Wozniak and Ballmer
acting as alternating narrators.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the book ``Fire in the Valley,'' by Paul Freiberger and
Michael Swaine, ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' was done without the
input of Jobs (who was pushed out by Apple in 1985, but returned in
1997) or Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Writer/director Martyn Burke said extensive research went into
the $7 million project, but this is not a documentary or even a
docu-drama (the movie opens with Jobs and Wozniak getting
tear-gassed at a 1971 demonstration at Berkeley, even though they
did not meet until 1973 at Hewlett-Packard). What it is is very
good drama, abetted by sharp editing and a great soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Gates emerges as dominant, seen on a giant screen
via satellite above a much smaller Jobs at a podium at a 1997
meeting announcing Microsoft had invested in Apple.
</P>
<P>
   The message can't be missed: Bill Gates, Big Brother. In a poker
game with 10-figure stakes, Gates won again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His e-mail address
is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
