<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
June 19. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News
Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLE: Americans strongly support legal gambling despite
concerns about the integrity of sporting events and the threat of
addiction, a new poll shows. Nearly two-thirds of American adults
approve of legal gambling, according to a Gallup poll released this
week. Three-quarters of those surveyed said they approve of state
lotteries, while 67 percent said that opening a casino helps a
community's economy.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POP: A Father's Day tale about a widowed dad in Greenwood, Mo.,
with five kids, including a set of twins. It's not as easy as it
sounds. This guy is super-organized, and really enjoys being with
his kids. Russ Pulley. 35. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   JAKE: We meet Jake, owner of Jake's BBQ on Main, a Kansas City
establishment that has fallen on hard times. Seems that Jake's
pitman has had a stroke and while he rehabilitates, the boss tries
to substitute. He's not doing very well, and Jake's, a longtime
Main street restaurant, is in trouble. Popper. 30 inches. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   RILEY: Missouri Rep. Terry Riley, who led a protest against
Kansas City Mayor Kay Barnes two weeks ago at City Hall over the
Pat Gray-Water Department controversy, was interviewed by Kansas
City police Thursday in connection with the break-in at Gray's
office. Police asked Riley if he stole the document and asked him
to take a polygraph. Riley is outraged, accusing the police of
being politically manipulated to intimidiate him. Gromer Jeffers.
20.
</P>
<P>
   TRUMAN: The Harry Truman Good Neighbor Foundation, criticized
for its lack of diversity, has named its first African-American
board member. He's Wyandotte County (Kansas) District Court Judge
Cordell Meeks. In addition, Charles W. Battey has replaced Phil
Pistilli as board president. Brian Burnes. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ROAD. Travelers hitting the road this summer will find the going
slow, as highway repair work, combined with a record number of
drivers expected to take advantage of still-low gas prices,
threaten to make long-distance treks more like rush-hour commuting;
the added construction has increased the risk of traffic accidents
at construction sites, as well. Ruth Igoe, Robert Cronkleton, Anne
Lamoy and others.
</P>
<P>
   SARA: A Kansas City girl, no older than 12, Sara Rimmerman, has
written a book about Fay Gillis Wells, co-founder of the
International 99s, a group of women aviators whose champion was
Amelia Earhart. The book came out Wednesday. Mark Wiebe. 15. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   AUTO _ Western Auto job cuts. By Steve Everly
</P>
<P>
   PAY _ Payless moving its headquarters to Lee's Summit. Jennifer
Mann
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ Column by David Hayes//Finn Bullars
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
