<HEADLINE>
NO LOSERS IN `BEGGARS AND CHOOSERS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are a lot of searing jokes and satiric insights in
``Beggars and Choosers,'' a tremendously good new series on
Showtime that spoofs all the truths of the television industry.
</P>
<P>
   But there's one thing left out: Network television is so
littered with average shows that if you want something truly great,
you have to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   So if you want to watch ``Beggars and Choosers'' (Saturday, 10
p.m.) _ a series that could become the kind of breakout hit that
``The Sopranos'' was for HBO _ get Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   It's the unintentional bull's-eye laugh of the 90-minute pilot,
a kind of painful home truth that indicts the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But this is reality, which the late Brandon Tartikoff, who
developed the series, was getting at while skewering the industry
so precisely. Although it's nice to have an ``ER'' or ``NYPD Blue''
or ``Ally McBeal'' to get hooked on, simple math suggests the
broadcast networks and cable are not creating as many hits as they
once did and the overall quality isn't there.
</P>
<P>
   But HBO has used high quality to virtually force viewers to pay
for something better. After years of strong programming, it hit on
a water-cooler show when ``The Sopranos'' motivated people to spend
the extra money for pay cable. ``Beggars and Choosers'' is the
series that Showtime hopes will be its ticket into your
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beggars and Choosers'' revolves around Rob Malone (wonderfully
portrayed by Brian Kerwin), a man who used to want to be a
playwright but now runs the Luddin Global Television Network, a
floundering, ratings-deprived bottom-dweller. The series is set in
the present, so LGT shows are going up against all the favorites _
``Ally McBeal'' and the rest. Mostly, LGT is dead last, a fact
reinforced every morning when, still half-asleep in the bathroom,
Malone dials in on speakerphone and gets the overnight ratings.
</P>
<P>
   His suffering is helped by an understanding wife (Isabella
Hoffman), but hampered by his 21-year-old daughter, Audrey (Keegan
Tracy), who is moving in with Parker Meridian (Paul Provenza), star
of the only LGT show that has much of a pulse, and a guy not only
the same age as Malone, but an egotistic star seeking a major
restructuring of his deal, which could cripple the network.
</P>
<P>
   Other elements in Malone's stressed life include Lori (Charlotte
Ross), the network's conniving vice president of development who is
out to get his job. And the owner of the network, E.L. Luddin (Bill
Morey), a 76-year-old curmudgeon who has a thing for S&AMP;M. He's not
impressed with how Malone is running the network, even though
Malone just got the job several months ago. (This is eerily similar
to three current real-life entertainment presidents.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Beggars and Choosers'' was written by Peter Lefcourt, who is
executive producer along with Tartikoff's widow, Lilly. What
they've managed to do is tap into Tartikoff's uncanny knowledge of
how screwed up Hollywood and television really are (Tartikoff ran
NBC and was one of the most respected and risk-taking entertainment
presidents ever). Much like ``The Larry Sanders Show'' on the small
screen and ``The Player'' on the big one, there are bountiful,
jaunty elements of satire that go beyond cliche and unmask the
industry for what it is: Mostly shallow (diet fads, gossip, copied
trends), peopled by characters you couldn't make up, and utterly,
dangerously cut-throat.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to say this is a critical-darling type of show,
given that all the in jokes and characterizations hit home in a way
that's all too familiar to people who cover the medium, but
``Beggars and Choosers'' works on many levels. It's an intelligent,
adult drama-comedy that avoids the heavy-handed punch lines and
spruced-up laugh track of network television.
</P>
<P>
   The shark-infested waters at Malone's network and his struggles
to keep some self-respect and stay employed are ripe for comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Tartikoff knew what he was talking about, and much of
Hollywood and the industry will see themselves in ``Beggars and
Choosers.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger question is, will you? Is a great TV show worth
paying for? Perhaps that quandary will come up in episode two, if
you order in time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
