<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-BESIEGED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENCE IS GOLDEN IN `BESIEGED' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lest there be any misunderstanding, there is indeed dialogue in
``Besieged.'' Characters swap hellos, conduct business, hobnob with
drunken pals, even engage occasionally in the odd moment of searing
emotional truth.
</P>
<P>
   But while Bernardo Bertolucci's enthralling and poetically
simple work includes a bit of conversation, it is at heart a silent
film. So many turns in plot and character development are revealed
through gesture, glance or a plain streak of light that long after
the final credits roll, it's the images that linger, not the
scattered dialogue. Few movies use so few words so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besieged'' features Thandie Newton in her first role since
last year's complex, underrated ``Beloved.'' As in ``Beloved,'' her
character in Bertolucci's film is a raw personality, bewildered and
slightly wild; she eats an ear of corn as though it might sprout
legs and run away.
</P>
<P>
   But in ``Beloved'' Newton played the intruder, and here she's
the intruded upon: Shandurai, a young African woman whose husband
is abducted and imprisoned by the military. The film begins with
his arrest and her terror, a nightmare from which she awakens in a
spare Italian apartment. Shandurai is now studying medicine in Rome
and cleaning house for her landlord, an eccentric English pianist
(David Thewlis) whose rooms are filled with art and antiques. As
she Hoovers and dusts, she draws Mr. Kinsky's gaze and attracts his
love, which he expresses in small, mute gestures and enigmatic
gifts sent via dumbwaiter to her flat. Then, one day, he spills his
guts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you! I absolutely I'm in love with you! ... Marry me!''
he pleads, all immature desire, as he fumblingly tries to embrace
her. ``What do I have to do to make you love me? I'd do anything.
Anything!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You get my husband out of jail!'' startles Mr. Kinsky, who had
assumed she was single, and transforms ``Besieged'' into a
mesmerizing romantic mystery. How Mr. Kinsky responds to
Shandurai's charge will not be revealed here. But respond he does.
And as the plot unfolds, Bertolucci's film becomes less a
conventional sex triangle than an elegant narrative about love and
the nature of promises.
</P>
<P>
   Fluid, economical, luminous and sensual, ``Besieged'' succeeds
because the eye behind it _ Bertolucci's and the camera's _ is so
perceptive. Fabio Cianchetti's cinematography is both understated
and daring, using natural light, broad angles and judicious slow
motion to emphasize the radiant simplicity of the tale.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Last Tango in Paris'' (less so the director's more recent
``Stealing Beauty''), ``Besieged'' is almost as much about a place
a space is about the characters who inhabit it. Thewlis and Newton
are transparently sympathetic in their roles, but it's Mr. Kinsky's
ornate Roman home that's truly transformed by love.
</P>
<P>
   Aurally as well as visually, the movie works. As in any silent
picture, the score tells part of the story; Mr. Kinsky's stretches
at the piano (practicing Mozart and Bach; ``composing'' a rattling
syncopated piece by Stefano Arnaldi, who also plays on the
soundtrack) are as packed with revelation as those rare scraps of
dialogue. In a film built on wordless epiphanies, music and silence
speak the loudest of all.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. E-mail:
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
