<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-DESERT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD-BE STUDY IN ECCENTRICITY FALLS FLAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a dry, dry state of affairs in the Southwest town of Baxter
when even Fred Schneider of the B-52s sounds comatose as the town
DJ. It's also a disembodied reminder that ``Desert Blue'' isn't
just the name of Morgan J. Freeman's somnambulant cemetery of a
movie, it's a state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman has the dubious honor of having written and directed
``200 Cigarettes'' pulseless twin. That film was Risa
Bramon-Garcia's attempt to wrangle a menagerie of edgy youngsters
into a John Hughes rodeo. This one infects some of those same
actors with contagious doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desert Blue'' has eccentricity on its mind, but it can't think
of anything nuttier to do than ask Christina Ricci to play a punky
pyro-nut in a town of deadpan wastrels punking and pouting when a
cola truck overturns on the highway and possibly releases the
soda's secret formula into the environment, thus holding the
citizens of Baxter on lockdown until they find what's in that cola.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman is after some evocation of those atomic B-movie
thrillers in which towns are shut down by an ecology under siege.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Desert Blue'' is more a study of what happens in a
post-apocalyptic ``indie'' land after a group of firecracker actors
is given carte blanche to be gruesome mannequins of self-parody.
Ricci is at her obnoxious, nihilistic worst, while Casey Affleck
races around this Thunderdome environment in spoiled-brat
rebellion. And the usually hotheaded Brendan Sexton III discovers a
before-unseen grace in his scenes with Kate Hudson (the reluctant
mint in this get-fresh-soon crew), but this is the one movie that
could've used him to start a real fire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
