<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SEXUAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEXUAL INNOCENCE' BEWILDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the philosophical ambition of a man who's decided that the
first few chapters of Genesis needed an autobiographical make-over,
Mike Figgis presents ``The Loss of Sexual Innocence,'' an allegory
configured as a ``personal journey'' toward some kind of
enlightenment about the contemporary deflowering of our carnal
selves.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis has been consistently attracted to the force with which
sex, both as an act and idea, defines behavior, but turning his
usual anthropological-erotic gig into a loosely intertwined series
of metaphors is a fruit best left on the vine.
</P>
<P>
   Figgis overlays his story of the evolution of a male named Nic
with Adam and Eve's stint in Eden. Nic's life is divulged in
non-chronological chapters of development _ as a 5-year-old (John
Cowley) in Kenya, a 12-year-old (George Maktar) in gym, a
16-year-old (Jonathan Rhys-Meyers) in warm lust and as an adult
(Julian Sands) seemingly in a trance.
</P>
<P>
   The structure is intended to illuminate the complexities of Nic,
who's a chopped-up literary stand-in for the Kenyan-born,
England-reared writer-director. He's rendered an enigma instead.
</P>
<P>
   With Figgis at his most self-indulgent, the film is narratively
bewildering. He shows us a pair of newborn babies, blood-red and
shrieking in their bassinet. They're separated and the film flirts
with their reunion as adults (at which point they're embodied by a
striking Saffron Burrows).
</P>
<P>
   One's prim and English, the other a sexy Italian sound-recordist
working with adult (and adulterous) Nic, who now makes
documentaries. Figgis tries to milk irony from coincidence,
resulting in conceits lacking in resonance, drunk on atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Cinematographer Benoit Delhomme is the dynamo-magician who gives
``Innocence'' its impressionistic opulence, fusing painterly cues
with hypnotic invention to forge a visual fantasia that Figgis'
story can't match.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of substance, or its banishment, and the director's
reliance on allure (in the film's casting and in its look and
sound, which features haunting music by Beethoven and Chopin),
leave ``Innocence'' with the quasi-profound, giggly overreach of a
magazine layout come to shameless, shallow life.
</P>
<P>
   A black Adam (Femi Ogumbanjo) rises from a lake. A few scenes
later, a Nordic Eve (Hanne Klintoe) follows suit. Starman-like,
they wander around The Garden shivering, shyly discovering each
other's privates, having that first pee in the lake that spawned
them. Their eviction from Eden into a media-polluted metropolis
should echo with something more thunderous than the supercilious
aggrandizement of a Benetton ad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris is a film critic for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
