<HEADLINE>
CARPENTERS UNION CHIEF HAMMERS HOME REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON -- His supporters say he's a liberal reformer who's
turned their union around. His detractors call him a misguided
micromanager. But they all agree: David Bergeron doesn't waste any
time.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years since he was elected secretary-treasurer of the
22,000-member New England Regional Council of Carpenters, Bergeron
has slashed some business agents' annual pay by as much as $25,000,
fired seven business agents and organizers, brought in 1,700 new
members, hired 36 new organizers and business representatives and
negotiated the first regional agreement with New England general
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the 45-year-old labor leader's whirlwind pace has
breathed new life into a moribund union. But the ongoing
reorganization of the sprawling organization has led to an internal
revolt by a group of employees called Carpenters for a Democratic
Union, who say the reforms have stripped them _ and members _ of
their rights.
</P>
<P>
   Under the restructuring, the international union will spend
about $25 million of its 1999 budget on organizing. And it plans to
build a $12 million training center in Las Vegas. The goal? To
control at least 70 percent of the US construction market.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth of 11 children born to the wife of a diesel plant
worker in Springfield, Bergeron worked his way up the union
hierarchy, climbing from carpenter to a business manager.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in his South Boston office, he now has the look and
bearing of a chief executive of a Fortune 500 company. Dressed in
navy blue suit and tie, he's come a long way from canvassing
door-to-door to recruit members.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is at the center of a debate over union democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Reactions to a nationwide restructuring of local carpenters'
unions by the United Brotherhood of Carpenters and Joiners in
Washington, D.C., have ranged from protests in New York and
Michigan to wildcat strikes in northern California.
</P>
<P>
   One key change, implemented by Doug McCarron, president of the
international union, angered some local officials, even though it
went into effect a year before Bergeron took office in 1997. It
involved the creation of regional councils to oversee 1,100
carpenters locals.
</P>
<P>
   Another change: The adoption of a policy that calls for the
appointment, rather than election, of business agents at union
locals.
</P>
<P>
   A third reform gives members the right to an advisory vote on
tentative contracts, with elected delegates making the final
decision to ratify or reject agreements. The system works much like
the popular vote for the US presidency and the vote of the
electoral college.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, CDU members aren't happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still want local autonomy,'' said Thomas Harrington, a
business representative who was business manager of Carpenters
Local 33 in Boston before the reforms. ``People are proud of their
local no matter which one it is. They want their identity, and they
want to be able to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Louvier, a former business agent at Local 43 in
Connecticut, said Bergeron fired him because he did not vote the
way Bergeron wanted. ``There are no checks and balances on the
council. David micromanages everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 13 positions on the council's executive board. The
highest position is Dave Bergeron. The trouble is, 11 of the 13 all
work for him,'' he said. ``Some of them are afraid of voting
against what he wants. Who is going to argue with the boss? One man
should not be dictating what goes on in the union.''
</P>
<P>
   Council spokesman Bert Durand said Louvier was fired for not
doing his job. ``Members of the executive board have open and
lively debates; they don't roll over because (Bergeron) says so.''
</P>
<P>
   A tall, lanky man known throughout New England as a hard-driving
reformer who turned a bankrupt local in Springfield into a
powerhouse, Bergeron acknowledges that there is a potential for
abuse under the new system. He argues, however, that there was
plenty of abuse under the old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have I ruffled feathers?'' he asked. ``Yes, I've terminated
some business agents, and there is now progressive discipline. . .
I've also brought in more organizers, and we have, for the first
time, a new regional agreement with contractors. There is also more
accountability now than there was in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is no longer local,'' he added. ``It's regional
and national in scope.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979, membership in the national union has dropped from
880,000 to approximately 500,000 today, while the number of
nonunion carpenters has grown. In Massachusetts, union membership
dropped to about 11,000 in 1996 from 15,000 in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Documents from the US Department of Labor's office of labor
management show Bergeron has made an impact: In 1997, the newly
formed New England council took in $7.4 million in dues. Last year,
with an additional 817 new members and 267 nonunion contractors
added to the union fold, $10.4 million in dues were collected. That
number may have been affected by a plan to equalize the dues
structure, which was high in some areas and low in others, said
council spokesman Bert Durand. The council, which brought in 912
members between 1998 and 1999, hopes to organize 150 nonunion
contractors this year.
</P>
<P>
   The council plans to use the extra money it has collected to
build financial reserves to help locals in need. ``If the industry
goes bust, we can support the structure,'' said Bergeron. ``The
last thing we want to do is to lay off people.''
</P>
<P>
   If asked to describe Bergeron in one word, his supporters would
say ``persistent.'' Labor organizer Curtis Stubbs, a former
colleague, recalled that while serving as business manager of
Carpenters Local 108 in Springfield, Bergeron doggedly pursued an
East Hartford contractor who was hiring undocumented, nonunion
workers at cheap wages.
</P>
<P>
   After a five-year war, Bergeron got the contractor to sign an
agreement, by luring away his best drywallers and promising them
union jobs that paid $3 to $5 more per hour plus benefits. Then, he
sent organizers to apply for their jobs, and hauled the company
into court for refusing to hire them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to have a slogan on his desk that said, `Never give
up,' '' said Stubbs. ``He was very, very persistent.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to address claims that union democracy is being
threatened, Bergeron and his second-in-command, Mark Erlich,
bridled at the notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now more activism and involvement than ever before,''
stressed Erlich. ``In July, members will determine whether
increases in the final two years of a four-year agreement should be
split between wages, pension, or health benefits. That has never
happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, labor specialists say Bergeron and his peers in other
regions have a tough fight ahead. Dwindling membership and a
longstanding reluctance to organize have not only helped fuel the
growth of nonunion labor, but have also created an entrenched
organization loathe to change.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, private developers have shifted away from having
general contractors coordinate the work. Instead, many rely on
construction managers with business degrees who, in looking at the
bottom line, may not choose to hire union labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the trades excluded other people,'' including
minorities, women, and other skilled workers without union cards,
said David Weil, associate professor of economics at Boston
University's School of Management. ``Now, they are attempting to
change a system that has been in place for at least 100 years. ''
</P>
<P>
   But as the union takes a more businesslike approach, can it
succeed?
</P>
<P>
   Weil isn't sure. ``Unions are democratic institutions that are
set up to maximize the interest of their members. That usually
means two things: being good at collective bargaining and being
whatever the members feel the union should be. That can be at odds
with an attempt to reshape a union _ even if the union's survival
may depend on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
