<HEADER>
A0747 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WWC-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      06-18 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WWC-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROWDS AND SPORT GROWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody dreamed it would be this big. When FIFA, which runs
global soccer, awarded the third Women's World Cup to the
Americans, it was thinking of something modest in a handful of
small East Coast stadia. But the Rose Bowl? Soldier Field? The
Meadowlands? Nearly half a million seats sold before a ball was
kicked?
</P>
<P>
   Only in America, perhaps, where the public is always eager to
snap up tickets to the Big Show, whether it's the Olympics or
Picasso or King Tut. And yet the global magnitude of this
tournament, which begins Saturday with the United States meeting
Denmark before a sellout crowd of 79,000 at Giants Stadium, is
undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   The advance ticket sales _ more than 460,000 and counting _ has
already made the Cup the largest women's sporting event in history.
The average attendance will be over 27,000, more than five times
what it was in Sweden four years ago. An aggregate of a billion
people in 74 countries across the planet is expected to watch on
television and 2,000 journalists from 30 nations will be covering.
``This is a breakthrough event for women's sport,'' says Marla
Messing, the Los Angeles attorney who directs the organizing
committee.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the definitive coming-out party for women's soccer,
which until the 1996 Olympics was an unappreciated (and decidedly
underfunded) attraction in most countries. Though many nations,
particularly in Africa and the Middle East, still view soccer as a
man's game, the women are gradually gaining ground _ and
acceptance. ``It's not a global game yet,'' says US men's coach
Bruce Arena. ``It's not played in 190 countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, 63 nations of an eligible 115 entered the qualifying
competition that produced the 16 finalists. Brazil, which once
consigned its females to playing pickup games on the beach, has
poured attention and resources into its national team. The
Australians, who finished last four years ago, have cranked up
their program dramatically since they'll be hosting both next
summer's Olympics and the 2003 Cup. And other nations, from Russia
to Ghana to North Korea, are following suit. The future of the
game, FIFA president Sepp Blatter says, is ``feminine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, who were a Third World team until the 1990s, have
been showing the way both on the field and at the box office thanks
to Title IX and an explosion of spectator interest in women's
sports.
</P>
<P>
   The United States didn't even have a national team until 1985.
``We were a bunch of all-stars in red, white, and blue,'' recalls
Michelle Akers, who scored the first US goal and still starts in
the midfield. Six years later, the Americans won the inaugural
World Cup in China and came back to find that nobody but their
families knew they'd been away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of reporters at the airport,'' says Akers.
``Now, we can't step off the field without a camera and a
microphone getting stuck in your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, NBC wouldn't even broadcast the Olympic final
between the US and China. For the Cup, all 32 matches _ even North
Korea-Nigeria _ will be shown coast-to-coast.
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup will be both a breakthrough and a showcase for the
`feminine future' of the world's most popular sport. ``This is my
game,'' the tournament slogan proclaims. ``This is my future. Watch
me play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1324EDT &QL; 
