<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GENERALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVOLTA TAKES CHARGE IN `GENERAL'S DAUGHTER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE GENERAL'S DAUGHTER 
Directed by: Simon West 
Screenplay by: Christopher Bertolini, William Goldman 
Starring: John Travolta, Madeleine Stowe, James Cromwell, Timothy
Hutton, Clarence Williams III, James Woods, Leslie Stefanson 
Running time: 118 minutes 
Rated: R (graphic images relating to sexual violence including a
strong rape scene, some perverse sexuality, nudity and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raw tabloid vigor and high-octane performances carry ``The
General's Daughter,'' a military murder mystery that's steamy and
kinky, if also more than a little generic. It's given the dramatic
spine it needs by the bold, strongly arched performance of John
Travolta as a military cop called in to investigate the brutal and
lurid killing. Before her mutilated body is found staked, nude, to
a training site in a swampy Army base in Georgia, we see just
enough of Leslie Stefanson's victim in action as an Army
psychiatrist to realize that she's a formidable person who insists
on exercising every sexual prerogative her male colleagues do.
</P>
<P>
   Her relationship with her commanding-officer father predictably
is not a simple one. But when James Cromwell's general, on the
verge of retiring from the military to embark upon a political
career, calls in Travolta's investigator, he's more than just a
vengeful father. He points out that the Army has 36 hours to solve
the murder before the FBI enters the picture and the case goes
public and, in his words, turns into a circus. With jutting jaw and
icy blue eyes narrowed in meaningful focus, Travolta's cop assures
the general that he's a good soldier loyal to the Army. What he
doesn't say is that he isn't going to allow that to compromise his
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Things immediately grow more complicated and more interesting
when he finds he's sharing the case with Madeleine Stowe's rape
counselor and Criminal Investigation Division colleague. There's
talk about an affair they once had in Brussels. At one point,
Travolta slyly goofs on ``Casablanca'' when he says, ``We'll always
have Brussels.'' But while Stowe's poise and savvy make even her
interrogations seem sexy, there are no sexual sparks between the
two leads. ``The General's Daughter'' is not a film that's going to
make it on resonant dialogue or on anything but a relentless
selling of punched-up violence. Some of that violence is frankly
gratuitous, especially in a prologue that shows Travolta
undercover, nailing gunrunners.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about that intro is Travolta broadly unspooling a
corn-pone Southern accent that's soon revealed to be another
self-spoof. In fact, Travolta's use of humor to relieve a grim and
brutal story is the film's most pleasantly surprising element.
Stowe can more than hold up her end of the film's sultry tone. The
other supporting performances are strong, too, especially James
Woods's turn as the dead woman's commanding officer, a character
who is not unacquainted with mind games. It will occur to many that
the general seems a bit too inhumanly blameless, but then everybody
with lines is a suspect. These include Clarence Williams III's
fiercely loyal aide, Timothy Hutton's nosy provost marshal, and
Daniel von Bargen's nasty local police chief, whose son dated the
murdered woman.
</P>
<P>
   The selling of the violence and kinkiness is rather more
apparent than any devotion the film may have to feminist principle,
despite the strength with which its two women act (before one is
viciously murdered). In the end, it's the investigative square-offs
that provide the best scenes, Travolta's with Woods's cagy colonel,
Stowe's with a cocky West Point grad. TV series have been built on
characters less compelling than Stowe's, and Travolta once again
makes virtuosity look deceptively easy. Watching him square his
shoulders and stride purposefully into the challenge of carrying
yet another film has become one of the satisfying filmgoing
experiences of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   It's what's being carried in the case of ``The General's
Daughter'' that will give pause to some. Me, for one. Although I
don't subscribe to the currently fashionable and morally convenient
Hollywood-bashing (what ever happened to the idea of making it
harder to get guns?), I felt in the end that this film is just a
little too mechanical and hokey and cynical to divert us from the
way it's cashing in on some pretty meretricious stuff. ``The
General's Daughter'' doesn't seem to bring any point of view to
what it's depicting except a skilled, efficient crudity in
depicting it. It's that bulldozing imperative that I find too
off-putting to allow ``The General's Daughter'' to be thought of as
entertainment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
