<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0750 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-HNS &LR;      06-18 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPENDING SALE SPELLS END TO SECRECY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIAN GUTHRIE and SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After 134 years of secrecy, the San Francisco
Chronicle may be opening its books to some of its closest and
fiercest competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The veil will be lifted, a Chronicle spokesman said Thursday, to
accommodate would-be suitors lining up to buy the family-owned
enterprise after Wednesday's announcement that the Chronicle
Publishing Co. intends to sell all or parts of its holdings, which
include the Chronicle newspaper and KRON-TV.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen or more media companies _ including the San Francisco
Examiner and the San Jose Mercury News _ may get a look into the
inner workings of the morning San Francisco newspaper and the nine
other properties that make up Chronicle Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   The entry of the Mercury News into the Chronicle Publishing
sweepstakes came as a surprise when it was reported Wednesday and
confirmed Thursday by Tony Ridder, chairman and chief executive
officer of Knight Ridder, which owns the Mercury News, the Contra
Costa (Calif.) Times and newspapers in Miami, Philadelphia and
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   In early May, Ridder said he had no interest in acquiring the
Chronicle. ``(W)e would have tough Justice Department objections to
overcome,'' Ridder was quoted as saying in the Mercury News.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to likely objections by the department to the
acquisition by Knight Ridder of any other newspapers in the San
Francisco Bay area, in light of federal antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Ridder reversed himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to our lawyers and I think we are in a position to
buy it _ probably all of their newspapers,'' Ridder told the
Examiner. ``We have not actually made a decision to buy. We're
going to be looking at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridder, whose company competes with the Chronicle and Examiner,
denied that he would attempt to see proprietary data without having
a genuine interest in purchasing the Chronicle and smaller dailies
in Illinois and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not look at the book of a company unless there is a
real interest there,'' he said. ``I don't do it just to learn
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in the book will be historical business data, financial
data, long- and short-term performance projections and analyses of
various company holdings, said William Sherman, a senior partner in
the Palo Alto office of the Morrison &AMP; Foerster law firm.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette (DLJ), the New York investment
banking firm authorized to sell the company, on Wednesday provided
Chronicle Publishing's board of directors with a list of
prospective buyers, including the Hearst Corp., which owns the
Examiner and 11 other daily newspapers; General Electric (owner of
NBC TV); Fox; Gannett; the New York Times; NBC; News Corp. and
Knight Ridder.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a joint operating agreement between the Examiner and
the Chronicle, the Hearst Corp. has the right of first refusal in
any sale of the Chronicle. Estimates of the value of the Chronicle
Publishing Co. have ranged from $1.5 billion to $3.2 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
