<SLUG> BC-BOX-GRANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT BEARING A HEAVY WEIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He's not selling tickets and he's trying to sell
himself. Such is the life of ``The Next Great Heavyweight,'' as
Michael Grant has been dubbed by people praying that is true.
</P>
<P>
   Grant may or may not actually be The Next Great Heavyweight, but
for the moment, at least, he has been handed that designation in
the boxing world, and he's finding it not as easy a place to
function in as one might hope. More than half of the 5,700 tickets
available for Saturday's fight against Bronx-native Lou Savarese at
the Garden remained unsold Thursday, and the Knicks' run to the NBA
Finals has knocked him to the edges of New York's many sports
pages.
</P>
<P>
   It has also left the undefeated Grant in an odd position. He may
be The Next Great Heavyweight, but on the day he came to New York
to discuss the point, there was more talk about whether stablemate
Evander Holyfield would fight Lennox Lewis in a rematch in November
than there was of his bout with Savarese, even though the winner
has been designated as Lewis's likely next opponent if
Lewis-Holyfield II cannot be made.
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way for The Next Great Heavyweight to be treated?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sometimes like I'm fighting God,'' Savarese said, the
sarcasm dripping from his lips. ``Michael Grant is the greatest
fighter of all time, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   That seems unlikley, and if Grant doesn't find a way to beat
Savarese, who is his greatest challenge to date but not a great
fighter, he won't any longer be considered The Next Great
Heavyweight, either. Instead, he'll just be another 6-foot-7-inch
guy who wasn't what we thought he was.
</P>
<P>
   Grant (29-0, 21 KOs) fully understands this, just as he
understands he doesn't yet fully understand his craft. He did not
even begin to fight until seven years ago, after runs as a college
basketball player, football player, and baseball pitcher of note in
Chicago and then around Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he played basketball briefly for Fullerton State
before being discovered in a Las Vegas casino by part-time referee
and full-time pit boss Richard Steele, who took one look at Grant's
massive frame and suggested he move on to other athletic pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   Grant did, for a time under the direction of Steele's wife,
before hooking up first with Bill Cayton and now with Craig
Hamilton and Jim Thomas, Holyfield's attorney. Through most of that
time he's been ably trained by Don Turner, a longtime New York
fight fixture who claims, ``Michael will be better than all them
before he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyperbole is not usually Turner's stock and trade, but he
believes in Grant's punching power, his character, his ability to
take a shot on the beak and his willingness to fight when the real
fighting begins. All of those traits may or may not be tested by
Savarese (39-2, 32 KOs) because although he is a veteran who went
12 rounds with George Foreman, he also got knocked out in five
rounds in his next fight by journeyman David Izon, the same Izon
Grant KO'd in five rounds.
</P>
<P>
   This makes Savarese as much of an unknown as Grant, although the
fact is the fight wasn't made by HBO and Grant's promoters with the
intention of showcasing Lou Savarese. So what this all means is as
difficult to fathom at the moment as whether or not Grant is as
advertised or proves to be merely the latest guy handed the title
of Crown Prince of Pugilism before he earned it.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Michael Grant at least seems to understand the
position he's in is tenuous, until he proves otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patience is on my side,'' Grant said. ``I'm just sitting back
and waiting and if I have to wait a little longer for my chance,
I'll wait longer. Until then I just have to show people something
in fights like this. I don't even think about the title. I think
about my next fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the ring, I'm starting to feel more comfortable but there
were many times I wondered if this was right for me. It's not
natural yet (hand-to-hand combat), but it's starting to get
comfortable. You have to develop a different mentality in this
sport than in other sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally went over that hill last year. I finally began to
let go of those other sports after I beat Al Cole and Jorge Luis
Gonzalez. Until then I watched Keyshawn (Johnson, a boyhood friend
who is the New York Jets' top receiver and a former No. 1 draft
choice) and my friends playing college basketball or in the NBA and
it kept ringing in my head a lot what else I might have done. But
after those wins in 1997, I started thinking about what I could do
next in this sport.''
</P>
<P>
   What his people may have him do next _ if he beats Savarese and
HBO can't beat back promoter Don King's refusal to sign a morals
clause that would eliminate him as promoter of Lewis-Holyfield II
if he's indicted for trying to fix any fights _ is fight for the
Lewis's World Boxing Council title held by Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   There is no telling if Grant is ready for that challenge because
he still often looks like a kid with a lot to learn when he's in
the ring. In fact, there'll be no telling for sure if he's ready
for Savarese until late Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   These days that's what being The Next Great Heavyweight really
means. It means nobody knows if you are or you aren't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great physical speciman,'' Savarese said of Grant this
week. ``He's smart in there and he seems very relaxed but he's
still got a lot to learn and I'll be in there to teach him. That's
the objective, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Not if you're The Next Great Heavyweight, it isn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
