u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-18 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV RATINGS SHOULD BE THE TOUGHEST TO WIN OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As televised sports goes, women's soccer is at the bottom of the
pile. That doesn't mean the sport is boring or without its
superstars. Mia Hamm, for instance, has a soccer shoe designed by
Nike named after her and a new Barbie doll modeled after her.
</P>
<P>
   What the sport lacks, however, is a substantial following, one
that transcends the estimated seven million females playing
competitive soccer in America.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the Women's World Cup then is not only to
attract live audiences at stadiums across the country but also
solid television ratings and favorable media attention.
</P>
<P>
   That will be easier said than done. The target audience of
soccer moms and dads, 12- to 20-year-old girls, and other members
of the Title IX generation may tune in, but success in the world of
television sports means pulling substantial numbers of men ages 18
to 54. And so far, they aren't clicking their remotes from
football, baseball, basketball, or hockey.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Disney have made an investment of about $4 million
to cover production costs to televise all 32 games _ either live or
tape delay _ on ABC, ESPN, or ESPN2. Led by Hamm, the US team has a
good shot to win the championship, and a strong showing should
attract casual fans eager to see an American team do well in an
international competition.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesome, family image of women's soccer has attrcated
corporate sponsorship. Nineteen companies, including Adidas,
Gillette, Coca-Cola, and All-State insurance, have put up $6
million.
</P>
<P>
   But, as ESPN analyst Wendy Gebauer said, ``Television has to
take the sport to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get viewers to tune in, they will be hooked,'' she
said. ``It's a great product that sells itself. These young women
are role models for young girls and young boys. Mia Hamm is one of
the most recognizable athletes in the world and she is good not
just for women's soccer but sports in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Gebauer was a forward on the American team that won the 1991
World Cup. She retired at age 24 because she couldn't make a living
playing a sport she loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sport has changed a lot in eight short years,'' Gebauer
said. ``We were pioneers. We played in front of 65,000 people in
China and it was great. But we had to give up a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN producer Geoff Mason said television ratings will not be
the sole determinant of whether the tournament is a success, or
whether the US will support a professional women's soccer league in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many variables involved with ratings,'' Mason
said, noting that the quality of media coverage coupled with the
level of excitement at the stadiums are just as important.
``Ratings are not the only barometer of the afterlife of women's
soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason said he hopes to attract and satisfy both diehard and
casual fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is an easy sport to televise but a very difficult sport
to televise well,'' Mason said. ``The soccer purists would have us
use one camera to follow the ball. They only want to see the pace
and flow on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mason said good television is not that simple. ``We must try
to bring the viewer into the event,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish that goal, Mason plans to turn up the audio on
field-level microphones. ``I was somewhat surprised at the amount
of communication among the players,'' he said. ``More audio will
give the viewer a new dimension which is more exciting and more
real. Television lenses let viewers see the event. On-the-field
microphones let viewers feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   What matters most, however, is whether the Americans play well
enough to claim the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime soccer announcer John Paul Dellacamera said the US has
to make it to at least the championship game to attract the casual
fans. ``They don't have to win it all,'' he said. ``But in terms of
creating and maintaining interest in the sport, they have to get to
the final. But we're going to cover the tournament from start to
finish, regardless of how the US team does.''
</P>
<P>
   Play-by-play will be handled by Bob Ley, Derek Rae, and Holly
Rowe. Analysts, in addition to Dellacamera, will be Seamus Malin
and former US men's national team player Ty Keough. ESPN's Chris
McKendry will file reports on the US team throughout the three-week
tournament and will serve as a sideline reporter at all US games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a pure game (than men's soccer),'' Dellacamera
said. ``There are fewer stoppages for fouls. There's less of
pulling of jerseys, less acting, less diving, and that sort of
thing. It's a purer game from that standpoint, especially the way
the US plays, with ball possession and stretching the defense. It's
a pretty game to watch as a fan or as an announcer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
