u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEQUILA-CRASH-BOS &LR;      06-18 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEQUILA-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HARVEST OF TROUBLE FOR TEQUILA FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEQUILA, Mexico _ In the nearly two decades that he has nurtured
the spiky blue agave plants that produce his country's most
cherished drink, Juan Mejia Franco has seen just about every kind
of worm, bug, illness, and threat that the arid hills of western
Mexico can muster.
</P>
<P>
   But now, he is stumped over what is killing the precious source
of tequila these days, a disease that during the last six months
has destroyed thousands of plants that were almost ready for
harvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started seeing signs last October, and things quickly got
worse,'' Mejia, 53, said as he stood on a slope of barren soil that
had just been cleared of sick agave plants. ``I've never seen
anything like this before. It just starts at the head and works it
way down very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   After enjoying several consecutive years of record production
and sales, Mexico's tequila farmers are facing a more sober
reality. A lethal combination of bacteria and fungus is eroding a
rapidly growing portion of their agave crop, with more than a
quarter of the country's 203 million tequila-producing plants
showing signs of diseases that no one has a cure for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tequila has always been identified with national pride for us,
but this is a side that's not so pleasant, and not many people are
willing to talk about it,'' said Ana Valenzuela Zapata, an
agronomist at the University of Guadalajara and one of Mexico's
leading agave experts. ``It's hard for us to admit that our
national product is in danger, but this is a problem that is
getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't come at a worse time.
</P>
<P>
   A bumper crop of agave in 1992 and 1995 produced a healthy
supply of the distilled drink for store shelves and bars and pushed
the industry past $200 million in sales for the first time.
Marketing mavens from New York City to Tokyo have bolstered the
drink's image from frat house shot to wing-tip sip, attracting new
bottlers and labels.
</P>
<P>
   And the European Union's decision in 1997 to recognize only
Mexican tequila as the real thing has more than doubled sales
across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   But as America heads into its slushy and margarita-chugging
summer hot season, even industry veterans know that long-term
problems loom _ such as limited supplies of agave and higher prices
for its sweet-tasting core _ unless the diseases can be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could mean the end to many smaller `tequileros' who have
fewer plants and a lower margin of error for their crops,'' said
Luis Yerenas Ruvalcaba, area director for Jose Cuervo, the largest
and oldest tequila producer, which exports about 70 percent of its
liquor to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia's answer for now is to coat his fields with lime to
disinfect and strengthen the soil. Others simply let the plants rot
before trying to plant again. But the truth is no one knows how to
stop these new enemies.
</P>
<P>
   A fungus known as ``fusarium oxisporum'' and a bacteria called
``erwinia caratavora'' are the two most evident diseases that are
being found on the agave plants, which are usually known for their
heartiness through drought and intense heat.
</P>
<P>
   The diseases, known around this tequila-making region as
``plagas,'' are especially dangerous to the plant because they
strike at its core, which is harvested, steamed, and mashed to
extract its sugary sap. The liquid is then mixed with water and
distilled twice before being fermented in barrel casks.
</P>
<P>
   Pure tequila is white. Aging, which can last from 15 days to
several months or even years, produces fuller-tasting,
amber-colored vintages known as reposados or anejos, which are
usually more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Most tequilas sold in the United States are made from 51 percent
agave sugar and 49 percent cane sugar, although production of pure
tequilas _ from 100 percent agave juice _ have more than tripled
during the decade, to more than 375 million liters in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy agave plants mature in eight to 10 years, producing a
round core that is harvested by slicing off the stiff leaves.
Experts say the infected plants begin showing signs of premature
erosion by age three, when leaves begin losing their distinctive
blue-gray color and red lesions start appearing around the base and
a primary stem known as the ``cogollo.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 survey conducted by Mexico's Tequila Regulatory Council,
a government agency created in 1994 to monitor the industry,
estimated that 27 percent of the country's agave crop was infected
with at least one of the diseases. Many farmers and scientists say
that figure is higher today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned about the diseases, but we think we have
things under control,'' Ismael Vicente Ramirez, the council's chief
field director, said during an interview at the agency's
headquarters in Guadalajara. ``There's always a risk of illness in
any crop you grow. There's no recipe for stopping it yet, but we
know who our enemy is.''
</P>
<P>
   The council has deployed teams of scientists to analyze the
fungus and bacteria, which has been found only in the fields of
Jalisco state, where most of Mexico's agave is grown.
</P>
<P>
   One idea they are exploring is the creation of a genetically
stronger version of the plant _ created in a laboratory _ that
would be more resistant to illnesses and produce more juice, but
would not disturb the region's ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, 35, who has published two books on the agave plant,
said the illnesses have reduced the number of mature plants that
will be available for harvests.
</P>
<P>
   The open market price for agave has jumped 30 percent during the
last three months, she said. Fewer plants will force many smaller
farms and distilleries to shut down.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, tequila companies could make up for shortfalls by
buying similar plants grown in other regions of the country. But
stricter rules ensuring the drink's authenticity prevent
distilleries from doing that now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the smaller producers will do,'' Valenzuela
added, while walking through a field of dead agave that was
recently torched, another method used to cleanse infected fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably see many of these farmers plant corn or sorghum
instead of gambling on agave, which takes a much longer time to
grow. Or we'll see many of these properties up for sale, which can
destabilize the local economy.''
</P>
<P>
   A reduced supply of agave could also have a significant effect
on the hundreds of new investors who have entered the market during
the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 brands of tequila are sold today, most of them by
Johnny-come-lately entrepreneurs who jumped in to take advantage of
the booming market and an excess supply of plants, buying them
cheap and using fancy packaging and high-end pricing to get nearly
$40 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The more established tequila-making brands _ the three largest
are Jose Cuervo, Sauza, and Herradura _ have enjoyed double-digit
sales growth annually during the 1990s, and their executives say
they are concerned, but not yet worried, about the diseases. Many
of them have company-funded scientists working on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made it through other threats, diseases, and even a
couple of revolutions,'' said Yerenas of Cuervo, who says they,
too, have seen the diseases in their plants. ``It's possible this
could get worse before it gets better, but we're strong enough that
we'll make it through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
