<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0764 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-MINES-BOS &LR;      06-18 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-MINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSNIA'S ROAD TO RECOVERY POCKED WITH LAND MINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia and Herzegovina _ It gets hot early in central
Bosnia these days, and Suad Garibovic is perspiring freely even
before he dons the heavy helmet and straps shrapnel-resistant pads
over his Helly Hansen designer overalls.
</P>
<P>
   But it's when he gets to work that the real sweating starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge minefield _ we think the biggest in the area,''
he says, gesturing with a sweep of his arm toward a gorgeous
pasture where wildflowers, lavender, and purple loosestrife
struggle up through golden, unmown hay. ``These houses were
Croatian. Those were Serb. And this'' _ he points out weed-clogged
trenches running from house to house _ ``this was the front line.''
</P>
<P>
   The field is in Stup, a semiagricultural section of Sarajevo
canton. It has been made a priority for mine removal because there
are former Croatian residents who are interested in returning and
rebuilding their shattered homes here _ the top goal of the foreign
aid agencies and governments striving to restore some semblance of
prewar Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The task is huge. Bosnia is laced with perhaps a million
landmines and several times that number of unexploded grenades,
rockets, and other explosives that obstruct refugees' return to
their pre-war homes. Conditions are similar in Kosovo, where
refugees trying to return already have run afoul of some of the
hundreds of thousands of mines planted during the 11 weeks Serb
forces were driving out ethnic Albanians and NATO forces were
bombarding the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are killed and injured every day,'' says Ahdin
Orahovac, director of the Mine Action Center of the Federation of
Bosnia and Herzegovina. ``Because of mines, you cannot live like
before the war'' _ the most fervent dream of most Bosnians.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the mines, Orahovac said, an estimated 10 percent
of grenades and other explosives launched during the war in Bosnia
failed to explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can be laying on the roof, or in the high grass behind
your apartment,'' he said, noting that a million such weapons were
launched into Sarajevo alone during the nearly four-year siege of
the city by Serbian forces. ``Returning refugees know nothing of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Garibovic, who fled Republika Srpska, the Serb-run section of
Bosnia, during the war and worked as a part-time manual laborer
before training as a mine remover to make ends meet, knows plenty
about it. When he gets started, he is a study in careful.
</P>
<P>
   First he trims the hay and wildflowers to 20 inches and makes a
visual inspection for tripwires. Then he cuts the growth back
another 8 inches, and looks again. Then, ever so carefully, he cuts
it to about an inch, and begins gently probing the ground with
special tools.
</P>
<P>
   When he finds a land mine, he calls his supervisor, who calls
the group commander, who decides whether the mine can be turned off
with one of the keys he carries in his pocket, or must be
detonated.
</P>
<P>
   This is a particularly dangerous time in the minefields, both in
Bosnia and in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, foreign agencies and governments are giving one last
push to the goal of bringing back refugees. In Kosovo, thousands of
ethnic Albanians are rushing back. In both cases, former residents
are returning to areas that have not been cleared properly.
</P>
<P>
   In late May, one such returnee turned a flock of sheep out into
the field where Garibovic was working, which was not then marked as
a minefield. Twenty animals were killed when they stepped on mines;
28 others were badly maimed.
</P>
<P>
   Four mine clearers were killed in the first 10 days of June,
said Orahovac, who blames the casualties on their loss of
concentration in the hot weather. But some mine removers and
international aid officials say the real cause is the way the
workers are paid by commercial mine-removal companies, 25 of which
are active in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   While projects funded by international agencies such as
Norwegian People's Aid pay by the hour, encouraging mine clearers
to work throughly, commercial firms pay by the square meter,
encouraging them to work quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, as a de-miner, would not want to go into a field cleared
that way,'' Garibovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Thorough work is at best excruciatingly slowly. And when the
flow of money is reduced, or the attention of donors turns
elsewhere, progress is even more halting.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 5.98 million square yards were cleared of explosives
in Bosnia and Herzegovina. The goal for this year was 9.57 million
square yards _ barely 3 square miles. Because of the slow flow of
pledged funds, however, the clearing effort ran at only 69 percent
of the goal through last month, and would have been much worse
except for an injection of funds from the US and Italy to encourage
refugees to return. The new funds allowed for double the planned
amount of land to be cleared in May.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank has ponied up $20 million during the past two
years. The United States has committed $28 million over the next
two. Norway and Canada also are major donors to the mine-removal
effort. But these sums are not huge given the magnitude of the
problem, and they may represent the peak of giving.
</P>
<P>
   British Army Major Roland Cockwell, chief of mines for the
international Stabilization Force in Bosnia, refuses to estimate
how long it will take to clear up the problem. That, he says, is
strictly a function of money and attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``After World War II, Western Europe had a much bigger problem,
and it was cleared up in three, four, five years,'' Cockwell says.
``At the current rate of progress here, it will take a helluva long
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commercial firms and nongovernmental organizations will go
where the funding goes,'' Cockwell said, ``and it is already going
south (to Kosovo) and east (to Serbia).''
</P>
<P>
   As those organizations' attentions are drawn to fresher
battlefields, the burden of mine removal in Bosnia will fall
increasingly on units of the armies of Republika Srpska and the
Muslim-Croat federation. However, as things are currently
operating, these soldiers get no extra pay for their hazardous duty
and even their regular pay is often months in arrears.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little sign of any real commitment to de-mining among
the politicians or the senior military,'' Cockwell says.
</P>
<P>
   Orahovac, the federation's head of mine removal operations, says
the current generation of mine removers can only hope to clear
major urban areas and areas targeted for refugee return, and that
``it will be for the next generation to finish this job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the Olympic committee before the war,'' Orahovac says
mournfully. ``It was very good company. But now we are in very
different company, with Laos, Afghanistan, and Cambodia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
