<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS GROUP URGES DEFEAT OF BAN ON GAY MARRIAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Chamber of Commerce has become
one of the first major business groups to oppose the ballot measure
that would ban recognition of gay marriages in California.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative ``is a mean-spirited attack that is meant to be
divisive, not to help California come together to grow and prosper
and celebrate its diversity,'' said Rhea Serpan, president and
chief executive officer of the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The Definition of Marriage initiative, which would define
marriage as a union between a man and woman only, will appear on
the ballot next March 7.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is also commonly referred to as the Knight
initiative after its chief sponsor, state Sen. Pete Knight, a
Republican from Palmdale. Knight has twice failed to win approval
of similar legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My objective is not to divide anybody in the state of
California,'' Knight said earlier this year. ``My objective is to
maintain the definition of marriage. ... I think the definition
that a marriage is between a man and a woman is one that has been
good for civilization since time immemorial.''
</P>
<P>
   Defeat of the initiative would not legalize gay marriage in
California. A 1977 California law defines marriage as ``a personal
relation ... between a man and a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   But because the U.S. Constitution requires all states to give
``full faith and credit'' to the laws of other states, California
could some day be forced to recognize gay marriages that occur
outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released in January by the Public Policy Institute of
California showed that 54 percent of those surveyed support the
anti-gay marriage initiative. A 1998 Field poll showed 56 percent
of those surveyed opposed gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of rights for gays say they must spend up to $10
million in an effort to defeat the measure. Celebrities such as the
actress Meg Ryan have signed on to support gay marriage, as have
dozens of organizations, including the American Psychoanalytic
Association and the Japanese-American Citizens League.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, chambers of commerce tend to take moderate or
conservative stands on political issues and often avoid potentially
divisive social disputes that do not directly affect businesses.
But in San Francisco, the chamber tends to reflect the more
tolerant, progressive views of the city. In 1996, the chamber was
the first major business organization to oppose Proposition 209,
which outlawed affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The San Francisco Chamber of Commerce has a proud history of
opposing discrimination in any form,'' Serpan said. ``We strongly
urge others to join us in opposing the Knight initiative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
