<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT PERSISTENT PROBLEM: INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 20, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I are ages 39 and 38 and living comfortably on
a $35,000 gross salary. Presently, we have stopped putting aside
money for our retirement and our 30-month-old son's college
education. As of this date we have $120,941 in tax-deferred
retirement funds, with $31,851 in Fidelity Asset Manager Growth,
$18,492 in Fidelity VIP Equity Income, and $4,140 in a life
insurance company's fund. In addition there is $17,730 in Fidelity
Asset Manager and $48,728 in Fidelity Cash Reserves. Where should I
put the cash reserves money so we have a good investment mix? My
financial personality borders on the low end of aggressive; I'm
thinking of putting it in Asset Manager Growth. With what we have
now, could we retire at ages 63 and 62 and live on those dollars as
we have been living on today's dollars, or will we need to continue
saving for retirement? We also have $53,000 cash in a money market
account. I thought I would like to keep $20,000 there for
emergencies and transfer the rest elsewhere, ultimately to be used
for our son's education. What do you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   K.W., Hellertown, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   A. It may look on the surface as if you'll have plenty of
retirement money, but you've overlooked the likely ravages of
inflation. Here's how the numbers work out. Over 24 years, if you
achieved average annual returns of 10 percent, your $120,941 would
grow to $1,191,236. But your living costs will also rise sharply;
if inflation averages 4 percent for those 24 years, you'll need
$89,715 to buy what $35,000 buys today. And to generate such an
income stream you would have to generate a 7.53 percent return from
your nest egg. That, at first seems like a can-do proposition, but
to achieve this safely you would have to put the lion's share of
your nest egg on the fixed-income side, with very little working to
boost your principal.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go back to the growth projection, except this time we'll
assume that both you and your husband managed to put the $2,000
maximum into retirement savings _ optimally in Roth IRAs _ for the
next 24 years. Instead of that $1,191,236 you would have
$1,561,411, and $370,191 of it would be tax-free. You could then
treat the Roth IRAs as your inflation buffer _ continuing to keep
those funds invested in stocks so you will accumulate additional
principal which will protect you from the inflation of the later
years of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Next, with your biggest positions in money markets and with big
holdings in the Fidelity Asset Manager group, you're not taking too
many risks. Remember, Fidelity Asset Manager holds nearly half its
portfolio in bonds and cash, and even for Asset Manager Growth, the
bond-and-cash figure is in excess of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   You have a lot of time to ride out the stock market's inevitable
bumps, so I suggest that instead of buying more Asset Manager, you
look at Fidelity Spartan Market Index as the target investment for
all that cash in the money market fund. I'd also like to see a
small amount _ perhaps $10,000 of it, go into Fidelity Select
Health Care. Without such moves, I don't think the projections of
10 percent average annual growth I've used are realistic.
</P>
<P>
   As for your son's college money, consider Fidelity's Freedom
group of funds. These are funds which alter their portfolio makeups
as they approach a target date. Thus Fidelity Freedom 2030 is
designed for people about 30 years away from retirement, and is now
classified by Lipper Analytical Services as a growth and income
fund. The same classification is given to Fidelity Freedom 2020,
but Freedom 2010 has by now evolved into an equity-income fund, and
Freedom 2000 has become a fixed-income fund. It would seem to me
that Fidelity Freedom 2010 would be appropriate for your son,
evolving into a fixed-income holding by the time it reaches its
target date.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My wife and I are both retired. I'm 63 and she's 57. Our
retirement income more than meets our needs. When I turn 70, an
annuity that now pays us $10,000 a year will cease, reducing our
income by about 8 percent. Our current investment portfolio is just
over $500,000 with 10 percent each in individual small company
stocks, Vanguard's Prime Money Market and Vanguard Growth and
Income. We have 20 percent in Scudder Greater European, a similar
amount split between Vanguard Wellington and Vanguard Asset
Allocation, and 30 percent divided evenly among Vanguard Index
Growth, Vanguard Index Value and Vanguard Total Stock Market funds.
At age 70 I intend to start withdrawing not only the $10,000 a year
which we will lose from the expiring annuity, but also any
additional amount to adjust for inflation. Can you give your
opinion of our portfolio and a projection of the impact our
intended withdrawals will have on it should we both be fortunate
enough to live into our 90s?
</P>
<P>
   P.V., Indian Wells, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think you should be in pretty good shape. By the time that
annuity runs out, your investment accounts should have grown to
$914,019, presuming average annual growth of 9 percent within the
portfolio. Obviously that could support withdrawals of $10,000 a
year like pie, but of course that won't be the problem. The problem
is maintaining your current $125,000-a-year lifestyle after the
effects of inflation. Let's suppose that since your current income
more than covers your expenses, you'll be able to use that extra
money to deal with the effects of inflation during the next seven
years. But if annual inflation averages 4 percent, by the time
you're 70, you'll need to withdraw $49,491 a year to give you the
$164,491 that would be needed to match your current $125,000 buying
power.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, your savings pool will not only support that, but
would also continue to grow, standing at $1,381,002 by the time
you're 80. At that stage, you'd have to withdraw $128,487 annually
to give you the $243,487 that would provide the same buying power
as your current $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for your portfolio, it's certainly fairly bold for the
typical retiree, but given that you won't be drawing on it for
seven years and then only at fairly modest levels, I think the
investment mix is fine. I'd quibble with holding both Vanguard
Index Growth and Index Value (why not just hold Index 500 and get
the same thing?) and I'd rather see a health care fund than the
money market, but by and large it's nicely done.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
