<SLUG> BC-CAMPS-RIFLERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER CAMP RIFLERY CLASSES SURVIVE DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HERMIONE MALONE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many people, Philip Lilienthal became sickeningly familiar
with stories of gun violence in public schools this year. In April,
he watched the news in horror as two students at a Colorado high
school fatally shot 13 people with sawed-off shotguns, a
semiautomatic rifle, and a handgun, then took their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes planted doubt in Lilienthal's mind over whether his
summer camp in Maine should continue to offer riflery to its 150
campers. Some parents expressed concern, too. How could he, in good
conscience, take boys as young as 8 into the woods, hand them a gun
and ammunition, and teach them how to shoot?
</P>
<P>
   How could he not?
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the man with the camp's 80-year reputation on his
shoulders, risked criticism from parents, and said youngsters
deserve the chance to learn how to fire guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If camp were the only place where rifles were found, I would
do away with the activity,'' Lilienthal, director of Camp Winnebago
in Kents Hill, wrote in a letter to parents. ``Judging from the
abundance of toy guns, sticks transformed by the imagination into
guns, and pointed fingers serving as weapons, it is obvious that
our discontinuation of the activity would not affect their use in
fantasy play.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision was not easy. Many other New England camp directors
are struggling with it, too, shadowed by the Columbine killings as
they clean out cabins and repair rowboats to prepare for this
season's young arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   Most have decided that tradition and training are more important
than bending to antigun trends, though some are considering new
precautions in riflery classes.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Cod Sea Camps in Brewster has pledged to keep its program,
even though some parents have called to say they will not enroll
their boys because the camp offers a riflery class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've offered it for 50 years. Parents choosing our program
know clearly that's one of the options,'' said associate director
David Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said the Columbine High School shootings cannot be
solely blamed, because the riflery program turns off a few parents
every year.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Section of the American Camping Association has
been getting some calls from worried parents, too. But the group
says it is not aware of any of the approximately 300 accredited
camps in the region canceling riflery programs this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken some calls from parents who have been concerned
about why target sports are even allowed in camps,'' said Bette
Bussel, executive director of the ACA New England section. ``The
majority of them were probably a little upset as to how that could
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggests to parents that they choose a camp without target
sports like archery and riflery, or, alternatively, tell the camp
director that their child should not participate in such
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still options out there. What children are usually
learning in target sports is proper techniques,'' Bussel said.
</P>
<P>
   Even camps continuing to offer rifle training are emphasizing
caution.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp Winnebago, after discussing the matter with senior staff
and his wife, Lilienthal may consider limiting riflery to older
campers for the first time, rather than offer it to all boys, ages
8 to 18.
</P>
<P>
   Lilienthal said that in 80 years, his camp has never had a
mishap involving guns. He credits that to the way riflery is taught
at the camp. Children learn the dangers of a rifle and how to
safely handle it before they are allowed to touch it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   No targets depicting people or animals are used. Shooting at
anything living, including animals, is strictly forbidden, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not designed in any way to hit something other than a
target,'' Lilienthal said. ``What I hate about guns is that they're
designed to hurt people and we're not encouraging hurting people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aloha Foundation camps in Fairlee, Vt., say they have had no
riflery-related incidents or injuries involving campers. But that
did not stop the 94-year-old camp from examining whether the
program would continue to be offered this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of Columbine and all of the other things that
happened, I asked my directors to be really clear about why we were
doing riflery, in their own heads,'' said Posie Taylor, executive
director of the foundation, which runs two camps that offer
riflery.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Taylor said, the camp decided to continue to teach
riflery, using long-established safety rules. They include storing
rifles separately from ammunicition, allowing only the head
counselor to have a key to both storage units, teaching campers
clear commands before they even touch the rifles, and keeping the
range a good distance away from the rest of the campground.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the concerns of its members, the American Camping
Association has generated safety guidelines and messages on youth
violence for its 2,200 accredited camps.
</P>
<P>
   The ACA website gives information on implementing searches of
campers' belongings and training staff to intervene during
potentially violent altercations between campers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shooting at Columbine has been an opportunity for camp
directors to reeducate themselves about safety at camps,'' said Jen
McCormick, ACA spokeswoman. ``You see school shootings almost every
year. There's never been an incident like that at a camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Though McCormick said the national office has not received calls
from concerned parents, the regional office in the Rocky Mountain
section in Colorado did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right after the shooting at Columbine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in late April or early May, two links were added to the
ACA website: ``Youth Violence &AMP; Camper Safety'' and ``Preventing
Violence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the main concern is not that riflery will contribute
to youth violence, but that isolation will. Being on the fringe
will contribute to that behavior. The camp environment is very
nurturing,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
