<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SCIENTIFIC INSIDERS SAY `BUY' AS THEY SELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Executives from Boston Scientific Corp. were in Houston Thursday
as part of their nationwide tour promoting a planned $500 million
offering of new company stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Natick, Mass. maker of medical devices is selling stock to
pay down part of the debt incurred in its latest acquisition, the
$2.1 billion purchase in September of Schneider Worldwide, a
medical technology unit of Pfizer Inc. Surely, executives are
talking up Boston Scientific's terrific recent quarter and the
addition of new, high-profile chief executive James Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   One detail they probably left off the highlight chart: Insiders
just finished selling about $83 million worth of the same Boston
Scientific shares they are suggesting investors buy.
</P>
<P>
   Five company insiders sold almost 2 million shares from their
personal holdings in the month of May at prices ranging from 39
5/16 to 46, large transactions that have been routinely reported in
company documents.
</P>
<P>
   Chief financial officer Lawrence Best, one of the sellers,
detailed for us the varied reasons why individual insiders decided
to cash in some of their stock last month. Nothing unusual going on
there, he reports.
</P>
<P>
   And that appears to be the case. But Boston Scientific insiders
as a group, though not individually, have demonstrated a keen
ability to buy low and sell high when it comes to their own
historically volatile stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They appear to be very good timers,'' said Robert Gabele, who
tracks insider transactions for First Call/Thomson Financial and
reviewed Boston Scientific activity over the last two years.
``That's pretty good correlation. It's about as good as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston Scientific insiders were buyers just a few months ago,
from Dec. 28 through Feb. 26, when the stock traded in a range from
23 5/16 to 28 1/2. The shares soon traded up above 40 and remained
there this week, finishing Thursday at 42 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Company insiders were also sellers between March and August last
year, shortly before Boston Scientific stock sunk from above 40 to
below 25.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders bought or sold as a group three times in 1997, in each
case getting in before the stock moved up or selling shortly before
a slump. The transactions were sometimes relatively small and
typically involved different company managers or directors on each
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything that has an odor to it,'' said
Best. ``But I can't deny it that when you go through the facts it
leads you to speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's what we wonder about: If insiders have built such a canny
trading record, does the fact that they are selling now mean
anything?
</P>
<P>
   No way, said Best. He insisted the insider trades were a group
of unrelated transactions that didn't amount to a hill of beans.
</P>
<P>
   Take John Abele, cofounder of Boston Scientific and one of New
England's richest people because of his stake in the company. He
sold more than 1 million shares last month, cashing in about $45
million of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Abele, who still owns more than 62 million shares, no longer has
an active role in the company. He sold shares to help fund an
institute he is building in Vermont and to support other
philanthropic interests, according to Best.
</P>
<P>
   Best himself sold 619,472 shares in May, mostly reflecting a
deal he cut with Boston Scientific when he joined the company seven
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Best said he received 500,000 options when he signed on with the
understanding that he could sell them later to diversify and reload
an equal number of new options. He said that was exactly what
happened last month.
</P>
<P>
   The third big seller last month, Joseph Ciffolillo, retired as
Boston Scientific's chief operating officer three years ago. Best
said Ciffolillo was in a use-or-lose option situation because
retirees are required to cash out within 36 months of leaving the
company. ``Joe's options were going to expire in June if he didn't
exercise them,'' said Best.
</P>
<P>
   Put the three big traders together, he said, and they don't
signify anything in particular. Each happened to have their own
reasons to sell during an available ``window,'' a period when all
recent news has been aired and insiders are allowed to conduct
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you should draw any conclusions with regard to
the insider sales and our fundamentals,'' he said. ``Our business
fundamentals have never been stronger in our history.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, which has hammered Boston Scientific stock before,
seems to agree. Of 30 analysts who cover the company, 27 recommend
it with a rating of ``buy'' or better.
</P>
<P>
   But the bumpy ride of Boston Scientific stock can be traced in
part to its rapid-fire acquisition spree, a string of at least a
dozen deals costing $6 billion in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Now the company is swallowing one of the biggest purchases of
all, and the insiders, coincidentally or not, are telling us to pay
attention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
