<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BITTER MEDICINE FOR THE SERBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If not us, who? That is the ultimate question the United States,
as sole surviving superpower, has to ask itself every time
something big goes wrong somewhere and the world demands: Who can
fix it?
</P>
<P>
   Just days after our air power back-bones the NATO war that
forced the murderous Serb regime to capitulate, the White House
dispatches warships to stand by in the naval shoot-up between North
and South Korea. And the United States shoulders its way
diplomatically into the nasty India-Pakistan border brawl over
Kashmir, which has led to shelling by one new nuclear power of
another and what we used to label ``invasion.''
</P>
<P>
   As 50,000 NATO peacekeeping troops enter battered Kosovo, the
British government announces dread evidence of what everyone
suspected: The Serbs massacred at least 10,000 Albanians and
stuffed their bodies in mass graves.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the ailing pope retraces his roots in his
much-warred-over Poland, wringing his hands over the 20th century's
bloodstained course, the United States stands alone as the one
power that can project military force anywhere it wants.
</P>
<P>
   That responsibility cuts both ways. China is angry because some
errant NATO bombs killed three Chinese diplomats in Belgrade.
Russia, smarting under its demotion from the Other Superpower to a
backward kleptocracy unable to wring concessions for its
troublemaking Serb cousins.
</P>
<P>
   We search for the roots of the Balkan conflict, and the search
takes us to the beginning of this century. The Serb government of
the day was linked to the archduke's murder, and we were off to the
races that made ours the worst century for slaughter on record.
</P>
<P>
   It was World War I that triggered the bloodshed still drenching
Europe. ``A tragic and unnecessary conflict,'' begins British
military historian John Keegan's detective-like dissection of the
corpse of 20th century warfare in his new book, ``The First World
War.''
</P>
<P>
   The first great war of the century killed 10 million Europeans,
but it also ``destroyed the benevolent and optimistic culture of
the European continent,'' and the 50 million dead of World War II
``was the direct outcome of the First.''
</P>
<P>
   It began, as this century ends, with murder in the Balkans: the
assassination of the Archduke Ferdinand in Sarajevo. And Keegan
fingers Serbia as ``the worst proportionate sufferer'' Of the 5
million Serbs of the prewar population, 125,000 were killed or died
as soldiers, but another 650,000 civilians succumbed to privation
or disease, making a total of 15 percent of the population lost,
compared with something between 2 and 3 percent of the British,
French, and German populations.''
</P>
<P>
   Loss of life proportionally five to seven times that of the
principal belligerents colors Balkan history and haunts the Serbs
still. But no great cities were destroyed by aerial bombardment in
World War I, which was essentially rural trench warfare, without
the mechanical contrivances _ tanks, bombers, high-powered
artillery, and submarines _ that made World War II so frightful and
industrialized battlefield killing power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First, unlike the Second World War, saw no systemic
displacement of populations, no deliberate starvation, no
expropriation, little massace or atrocity.'' In some ways, ``a
curiously civilized war.''
</P>
<P>
   But the psychological burden on victim and vanquished alike
proved too great to bear. ``It damaged civilization, the rational
and liberal civilization of the European enlightenment, permanently
and for the worse,'' Keegan writes, ``and, through the damage done,
world civilization also.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule of law, and the aspiration for democracy, collapsed and
died, ``in Russia after 1917, in Italy after 1922, in Germany in
1933, in Spain after 1936.'' Liberalism gave way to totaliarianism,
and men of iron will and black soul, the Milosevics of their era:
Lenin, Stalin, Hitler, Mussolini, and Franco.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan's grim formula could be Milosevic's grisly text as the
Serb despot started four Balkan wars this past decade:
``Totalitarianism was the continuation of war by other means. It
uniformed and militarized its mass electoral following, while
depriving voters generally of their electoral rights, exciting
their lowest political instincts and marginalizing and menacing all
internal opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Serbs flee NATO's pursuing soldiers, killing, maiming,
mining, looting, and burning as they go back to Belgrade, doomed to
be denounced anew, dreading the inevitable reprisals of the KLA and
Albanian terrorists, repeating the cycle of centuries of
intolerance. There has to be a lot of self-hate at the root of
causes in which men slaughter livestock, rape and pillage, poison
wells, and mark their retreat with animal-like coarseness.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs leave Kosovo the way they came in: drunk on history,
blinded by blood lust, doomed to swallow again some of their own
bitter medicine, demonized by their own bestial behavior.
</P>
<P>
   They still don't get it. But someone had to stop them. And that
someone, in the current global geopolitical lineup, had to be us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1340EDT &QL; 
