u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-18 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DID BAY STATE GIVE A GRANT TO SMITH &AMP; WESSON? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts is either beating guns into garden mowers or
outrageously helping a company mow us down.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Division of Employment and Training gave $1.6
million in grants to train 1,400 workers. Some grantees were
mom-and-apple-pie institutions such as the YMCA. Others have the
All-America image of Spaulding Sports. Others symbolize uplift,
such as Holyoke Community College. Others symbolize the new
economic drift, such as SpringBoard Technology.
</P>
<P>
   But one firm leapt off the list like a flash fire from bacon
grease. It long ago lost its apple-pie image, so much so that it
has to be asked why the state considers it a source of uplift. One
of the grantees was Smith &AMP; Wesson.
</P>
<P>
   Springfield's Smith &AMP; Wesson is the world's top producer of
handguns. The state awarded the company $35,000. The cash ranked
only 10th among the 14 companies that are training workers for
actual jobs. But Smith &AMP; Wesson will get more bang for its buck
(pun intended) than most of the other firms. The number of workers
to be trained, 110, ranked fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Both the state and Smith &AMP; Wesson insist that this is not a case
of literally getting a bang for the bucks. Both said the 110 new
workers will be trained in a separate nongun division of the
company, a division that takes the technology used to heat, harden,
and protect gun metal and use it for lawn blades, automotive gears,
golf clubs, and medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Jack King, deputy director of the DET, said Smith &AMP; Wesson was a
``sensible'' choice, since the company presented itself
``attempting to diversify into contract machining for nonfirearm
activities.'' While the gun-making side of Smith &AMP; Wesson has
declined from 2,000 in the '70s to about 750 today, Specialty
Services, the division involved in the training grant, has 120
people. Business being brought in by the division is reportedly
growing at 30 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   King said the nongun jobs can pay $14 an hour, no chicken feed
in a depressed urban area where English is often a second language.
The jobs require more skill than gun making involves, since workers
do different things for different companies. At Smith &AMP; Wesson, CEO
Ed Shultz has said he hopes the nongun business will expand from
its current 10 percent of the company's revenues to over 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're doing well, and we're having fun with these
new businesses,'' Shultz said.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Shultz should have such fun at the
taxpayer's expense. Before giving the state a clean bill of sanity
for this grant, there are several things to consider. It would be
one thing if Smith &AMP; Wesson came to the state saying they
desperately wanting to stop making handguns. If that was true, the
state should throw $35 million at them to retool the joint. At $318
per trainee, according to the state, that beats state welfare for
sports stadiums. Studies show that using stadiums to create jobs
costs upwards of $200,000 per job.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith &AMP; Wesson is still shamelessly aggressive about
handguns. It is hard to see how the state can grant public funds to
a company at a time when it is being sued by the state's capital
city for the devastation caused by its products. Smith &AMP; Wesson is
named in most of the 20 city lawsuits filed around the nation for
irresponsible marketing and distribution practices that led to
murder sprees that drain city resources.
</P>
<P>
   It hard to view the grant as ``sensible'' when the firm shows no
sensibility about the carnage. Even though scores of children
killed in gang shootings are innocent bystanders, Shultz said he
has ``no emotion'' on gang shootings. ``As a matter of fact,'' he
has said, ``I just hope they're both good shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith &AMP; Wesson is also coy as to whether there is a permanent
firewall between the gun factory and the nongun metal finishing
factory. All that Jorgensen would say was that on occasion, some
gun workers are used in Specialty Services. He said he was not
aware of any metal finishers being used to make guns, but was also
not aware of any policy against such a use.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocate Tom Diaz said a firewall might be
irrelevant anyway. ``Capital is fungible,'' said the author of
``Making a Killing, The Business of Guns in America,'' and senior
policy analyst at the Violence Policy Center. ``The money the state
gives Smith &AMP; Wesson to train workers in one area is money Smith &AMP;
Wesson can keep for profit or invest in making more guns. . . . I
don't know what metal products they are making, but they should be
making gurneys for trauma centers. Then they have the front end and
the back end of the business covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the state knows for sure that its fronting of training
funds is helping Smith &AMP; Wesson to back out of the gun industry, it
has no business doing business with the company. That will be a
while. Handgun sales are up this year. ``We will be in the gun
business until we are legislated out of it,'' Jorgensen said.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the government issued a study on gun crime by 18- to
20-year-olds. Smith &AMP; Wesson handguns were three of the top 10
weapons most frequently traced to crime. It is naive to think Smith
&AMP; Wesson is beating guns into garden mowers. Its weeds on the
killing fields remain too high and thick to mow down.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
