<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-DUNCAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIM DUNCAN OF SPURS OFFERS SUBSTANCE INSTEAD OF STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ He is the anti-MTV, anti-slacker,
anti-showboating, anti-smack-talking antidote to the next
generation of wannabe stars.
</P>
<P>
   In a world that worships style, Tim Duncan insists on offering
substance. In a country where delayed gratification is going the
route of rotary telephones, Duncan spent four years honing his
skills _ and earning a degree _ at Wake Forest before striking it
rich in the National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   In a league where players craft and cash in on images of
outrageousness and rebelliousness, Duncan dares to harbor bland
ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is the anti-anti-hero. He has so much game, he gets
noticed for all the right reasons. No dying his hair lime green. No
talking enough trash to make the landfills of New Jersey overflow.
No making a fool out of himself in a wrestling ring. No wrapping
his hands around a coach's neck.
</P>
<P>
   If the San Antonio Spurs' 89-77 victory in Game 1 of the NBA
Finals is even the slightest hint of things to come, then it's
going to be a long short series for the New York Knicks. Duncan
poured in 33 points, snagged 16 rebounds, all but swept the Knicks
out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way Duncan's playing now, there's not one man on the
planet who can stop him,'' Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``He's
the best player in the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy admiringly describes Duncan's game as ``a coaching
clinic.'' At 7 feet and 255 pounds, Duncan combines the strength of
a lumberjack with a dancer's footwork. Duncan was the only player
to rank among the NBA's top 10 in scoring (21.7 points per game),
rebounding (11.4), blocked shots (2.52) and field-goal percentage
(.495) during the lockout-shortened regular season.
</P>
<P>
   All-NBA First Team. All-Defensive First Team. And Duncan is only
23. He has so much time for his game _ and reputation _ to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably a little young to be a legend yet,'' Spurs coach
Gregg Popovich said. ``I'm willing to call him that if you want, if
he's going to do this every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates refer to Duncan as ``The Big Easy.'' Anybody who has
seen Duncan play knows that the nickname is self-explanatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough guy to guard one-on-one,'' Knicks forward Marcus
Camby said, ``and he's even tougher to guard when you double-team
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan, in other words, is smart and unselfish enough to pass
the ball to the open man if defenders converge on him. Opponents
might figure out Duncan a little easier if he would occasionally
wear his emotions on sleeve. Maybe that's the method to Duncan's
reluctance to show madness, or gladness, or sadness. Duncan, after
all, did get his degree in psychology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real strange bird in the sense that ... he's mature for
his age,'' Popovich said. ``He has got this natural disposition. I
always say he's on island time, where nothing fazes this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan hails from St. Croix, Virgin Islands. He used to be a
competitive swimmer, until Hurricane Hugo destroyed the local pool
in 1989. He didn't take up organized basketball until the ninth
grade. Then and only then did he began to pay attention to anything
or anybody having to do with the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan didn't score a point in his first college game, playing
10 minutes. Less than four years later, Duncan was the prize of the
1997 draft lottery. Duncan was almost as big a winner as the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of breaking in with the Los Angeles Clippers or some
other NBA ne'er-do-wells, Duncan had the luxury of playing
alongside All-Star and fellow 7-footer David Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to come on this quickly,'' said Duncan, the
ninth rookie in history to make the All-NBA First Team. ``But I'm
in a great situation. The coaches really put me in situations where
I can be effective. It feels good out there right now.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, it feels a lot different than when the Spurs began
this season by losing eight of their first 14 games. Locals were
willing to give Popovich a one-way ticket anywhere, as long as he
went out of town and never came back. Skeptics wondered if there
was enough room on one team for Duncan and Robinson. Spurs guard
Mario Elie questioned the intensity and commitment of the team's
big men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no reaction,'' Duncan said. ``I kept on playing. It
really doesn't bother me what people say about me. I think I play
as hard as anybody out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the Spurs righted themselves, they became as unstoppable as
oat bran. They have won 43 of their past 49 games, including 11 in
a row during the playoffs. Along the way, Duncan and Robinson have
evolved into the most potent combination this side of tequila and
sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love passing it to each other,'' said Robinson, a career
25-points-per-game scorer whose average dropped to 15.8 this
season. ``We love taking care of each other on the floor. There's
such trust. We don't feel like things are ever out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   For reasons best left to mystics to explain, Duncan finished
only third in the league's Most Valuable Player voting. The further
the Spurs go in the playoffs, the closer his reputation comes to
its rightful stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it means,'' Duncan said, ``is there's a bigger bounty on
your head.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the anti-MTV antidote to the next generation of NBA
anti-heroes. If the NBA is truly lucky, he is the future. The
brightest star of all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
