u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-TARZAN-BOS &LR;      06-18 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TARZAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY'S ANIMATED `TARZAN' MAKES THE LEAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TARZAN 
Directed by: Kevin Lima, Chris Buck 
Screenplay by: Tab Murphy, Bob Tzudiker, Noni White (based on Edgar
Rice Burroughs' stories) 
With the voices of: Tony Goldwyn, Minnie Driver, Glenn Close, Brian
Blessed, Lance Henriksen, Nigel Hawthorne, Wayne Knight, Alex D.
Linz, Rosie O'Donnell 
Running time: 88 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been 47 Tarzan movies, but not until the 48th has
there been an animated ``Tarzan.'' Yet Edgar Rice Burroughs
discussed one with Walt Disney in the 1930s, and in some ways
drawing boards and now computer keyboards are the best routes to
the material. For one thing, they allow Tarzan to do the kind of
vine-swinging that not even Johnny Weissmuller in his prime could
have managed. Tarzan's jungle, given that it always has been a
jungle of the mind, looks better than almost all of Hollywood's
scraggly backlot attempts at the real thing. It's a little much
that Tarzan, as drawn, seems as much a mantis as a man, with no
waist to speak of and bulging thigh muscles. But the main thing is
that Disney's new animated ``Tarzan'' works.
</P>
<P>
   It's the strongest Disney animation of the last few years, a
strapping and satisfyingly crafted effort that will do a better job
of leading young audiences into Tarzaniana than yet another
traditional movie could have. The Disney animation canon, which
seems to have lost momentum with its last few offerings, should be
nudged forward again by ``Tarzan.'' It's lively, vividly drawn,
flecked with emotion without being drenched by it, and finally
addresses the question of what to do with the songs, which lately
have become the wrong kind of show-stopper. Instead of stopping the
action for bland generic pseudo-emotions, this new batch by Phil
Collins smartly stays in the background, effectively heightening
the moods and reinforcing the momentum, although sometimes
overdoing the drums.
</P>
<P>
   But there is momentum as ``Tarzan'' largely retains the familiar
story, making only a few departures. We don't see the grown Tarzan
until well into the film. It begins with the infant son of
shipwrecked parents orphaned when mother and father are killed in
their treehouse by a predatory leopard. The baby is rescued and
adopted by a kind gorilla mother who lost her own baby. His boyhood
as something of a freak in the gorilla clan ends when he comes of
age and exhilaratingly goes zooming through the trees. The
traditional Disney comic relief, less memorable than usual on this
occasion, is provided by a cowardly elephant voiced by Wayne Knight
and Tarzan's gorilla playmate, voiced by Rosie O'Donnell. It's a
relief that this ``Tarzan'' eliminates the problematic but
perennial Hollywood characters of Boy and Cheetah.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Close's voice is a plus as Tarzan's nurturing adoptive
mother and Tony Goldwyn's is more than up to the task of voicing
Tarzan's conflicts when humans enter the picture. Minnie Driver
finds an agreeable zone between sappy and forbidding as Jane, and
Nigel Hawthorne is on the money as her dotty Victorian father.
Brian Blessed handles with plummy aplomb the bad-guy slot provided
by the father-daughter team's great white hunter guide, Clayton,
who looks like Basil Rathbone on steroids. Predictably, Tarzan and
the gorillas are far more civilized than the intruders, and the
film can be not only forgiven but applauded for taking a different
path than Burroughs did when it comes to Tarzan's decision on
whether to follow Jane back to England.
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay smartly makes the disruption of the jungle
environment seem a consequence of the colonizing imperative itself
rather than the barbarous acts of a few aberrant individuals. The
animation process takes full advantage of the greater possibilities
for human-animal interaction than any live version could offer. The
drawing style is more traditional than innovative, not a bad thing,
except that it hasn't exactly achieved seamlessness between
differently styled renderings. If this ``Tarzan'' steers itself
away from the primal emotions that would have given it some points
of contact with the very top echelon of Disney animated classics,
it's not far below them. This ``Tarzan'' won't wither on the vine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
