<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TROUBLE WITH JOE MCGINNISS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was supposed to be author Joe McGinniss's comeback book. Now
it's just another messy publishing headache.
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss, who attracts trouble the way trailer parks attract
tornadoes, has just published ``The Miracle of Castel di Sangro,''
the story of a back-country Italian soccer team that achieves
unexpected national prominence. The book has received some very
nice reviews, and has been promoted in conspicuously placed
advertisements in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, McGinniss has declared war on his publisher.
</P>
<P>
   In a five-page-long hysterical e-mail message titled
``Arrivederci, Sarah'' _ distributed to ``friends and associates''
for maximum leaking potential _ McGinniss rails against Little,
Brown's publisher Sarah Crichton, and his editor, Michael Pietsch.
Nominally, the dispute concerns a ``quote ad,'' a full-page
advertisement that publishers award to books that have received
favorable notices. But in reality, the argument plumbs writing's
true heart of darkness _ an author's wounded pride.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that, like all editors, Crichton professed to
love the book; ``It is so original, so human. . . . It is
intoxicating,'' she wrote to McGinniss. In fact, even after
McGinniss's e-mail blitzes, she still likes the book: ``We love
it,'' she told me. ``It's a terrific read.'' But, like many editors
in her situation, she will not commit to further promotional
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   According to Crichton and McGinniss the book had problems during
Little, Brown's standard legal review. Likewise, the cover, which
is still terrible, had to be redone three times. ``Joe didn't like
the first two jackets,'' Crichton says. ``This was the one he
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss complains in his e-mail that Barnes &AMP; Noble and
amazon.com have not honored agreements to properly promote the
book. And what promotion has been done he doesn't like. ``I have
never understood the billing of this as a `Father's Day' book,'' he
writes. ``I think it has about as much to do with Father's Day as
`Fear of Flying' has to do with Mother's Day.''
</P>
<P>
   So he attacks Crichton, a well-regarded New York publishing
personality and the daughter of novelist Robert Crichton, who is
best known for a novel (``The Secret of Santa Vittoria'') that
takes place in an Italian countryside not so different from that of
Castel di Sangro. ``I realize that while your father was an author,
and a fine one, you are a businesswoman, a very different breed,''
McGinniss writes. Astonishingly, he suggests that Teddy Kennedy,
the subject of McGinniss's botched biography ``The Last Brother,''
or someone else ``acting in his behalf,'' may have influenced
Crichton to undercut ``Castel.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he goes after Pietsch, who refused to authorize a modest
travel expense for McGinniss: ``Any Harvard graduate who does not
know the difference between Andover and Amherst, as Michael did not
. . . might be said to be, at the least, unversed in the
practicalities of life.'' Reached at his home in Williamstown,
McGinniss declined to speak with me.
</P>
<P>
   McGinniss is a complicated fellow, a hugely talented former
sportswriter who burst onto the book scene with his superb
``Selling of the President, 1968.'' His more recent outings have
been fraught with controversy. His book about former Green Beret
Jeffrey MacDonald, ``Fatal Vision,'' sold a gazillion copies but
landed him in some serious hot water. McGinniss found himself to be
the subject of perhaps the most famous New Yorker profile of the
last 20 years, Janet Malcolm's ``Reflections: The Journalist and
the Murderer.'' Malcolm reported that McGinniss strung MacDonald
along as an interview source, never sharing his belief that
MacDonald was guilty of murdering his wife and children.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, McGinniss published ``The Last Brother,'' ``an
embarrassingly bad book,'' according to Globe reviewer Gail
Caldwell. Much attention was devoted to a disclaimer attached to
the book: ``Some thoughts and dialogue attributed to figures in
this narrative were created by the author. . . . '' That statement
gave Kennedy spear carriers all the ammunition they needed to
discredit the biography as the product of an overheated
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his anti-Little, Brown screed, McGinniss writes:
``I don't think I'll write another book.'' If ``Castel'' is as
charming as Joe's fans say it is, he should write a dozen more
books. And perhaps less e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
