<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0782 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-VIOLIN-HN     06-18 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-VIOLIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VIOLIN' STRIKES JUST THE RIGHT CHORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best word to describe the new film from director Francois
Girard, ``The Red Violin,'' is ``beautiful.'' Simply, beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   The film tells the story of a violin created by an Italian
master in the 17th century and the way it affects a long parade of
lives. From its inception, when it was created for the anticipated
son of Nicolo Bussotti's pregnant wife, the red violin crosses time
and space, sound and light, as it carries both Anna Bussotti's soul
and the crazed love of her husband across the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back from present-day Montreal, where the violin is
being auctioned, ``The Red Violin'' guides the music in the
instrument through the music in the lives that come to touch it.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in Montreal, Oxford, Vienna, Shanghai and Cremona, Italy,
``The Red Violin'' makes the most of its backgrounds while telling
a broad, romantic story, on the same scale of love and lust and
human frailty as the Academy Award-winning ``The English Patient.''
</P>
<P>
   The photography, by Alain Dostie, is stunning. So is the
production design of Francois Seguin, who creates images in the
brush strokes of Vermeer and David, Constable and Bocklin. And then
there's the music of John Corigliano, whose compositions for the
red violin hit just the right notes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only false note in the film is one the producers
probably thought of as an unqualified plus _ the inclusion of
Samuel L. Jackson in the cast.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who plays a contemporary expert in violins attending
the Montreal auction, is an intrusion into the film. It's not that
he's miscast _ he does his usual outstanding job _ it's just that
``Red Violin'' is the kind of film that works best without
well-known faces.
</P>
<P>
   Before Jackson takes center stage, each actor makes a strong
impression. Carlo Cecchi and Irene Grazioli couldn't be better as
Nicolo and Anna Bussotti, while Anita Laurenzi has both the face
and words to bring alive the family soothsayer, a believer in a
future beyond Cremona. Jean-Luc Bideau is brilliant as Georges
Poussin, teacher of the equally brilliant Christoph Koncz, one of
the most unassuming child actors you'll ever see. Jason Flemyng and
Greta Scacchi do a fine turn as Victorian lovers in the Oxford
segment, which follows on the heels of an oddly affecting
kaleidoscope of gypsy violinists.
</P>
<P>
   The violin moves with a servant from Oxford to China, then
teeters on the brink of extinction as the dehumanizing new order
vows to destroy all Western influences. Standout performances from
Sylvia Chang and Liu Zi Feng melt into the color and sound of China
brought both loudly and softly to the front of the screen. The
Shanghai sequence, lopsided and strident, is riveting.
</P>
<P>
   At times the grandeur of past centuries is spread too thick,
especially in Vienna, where even the poor dress like kings. But
that grandeur serves the film well _ it is only when ``The Red
Violin'' settles into 20th century Montreal and the
all-too-recognizable mannerisms of Jackson that the story starts to
flag.
</P>
<P>
   Girard tries to inject the Montreal scenes with suspense by
replaying the bidding process, adding new insights every time, but
the true suspense of ``The Red Violin'' comes not from what will
happen to the instrument at the auction, but what happened to the
people whose lives became part of it over the years.
</P>
<P>
   The most affecting scenes are those showing how Bussotti created
his violin, how it made its journey from the casket of Kaspar Weiss
to the garden room of Frederick Pope to the guarded loft of a
teacher in Shanghai. By the time Jackson takes over the screen, the
best of ``The Red Violin'' has passed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
