u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV2     06-18 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO TREAT OLD HOMASOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 20, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. In painting the inside of my house, I came across two rooms
whose walls are Homasote. One room is papered, one is painted. In
both rooms I can see the joints between the Homasote panels. Can I
fill them with spackling or joint compound before painting or
papering?
</P>
<P>
   SUE MICHAELS, Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It's interesting; this is the second question this week on
Homasote. First, Homasote needs explaining. It is a papier-mache
material, ground-up newspapers wetted down and compressed into
half-inch-thick sheets. It was popular in the 1930s to 1950s, and
often was used in summer cottages. It has a rough, pebbly surface,
and joints are usually covered with a double-sided molding. While
popular so long ago, it is still being made by the Homasote Co.,
which makes other products such as sound-absorbing board and carpet
underlayment.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its rough surface, it is not practical to fill the
joints with spackling or joint compound, then taping the joints as
one would do with dry wall. The filler is smooth and it is
impossible to match the rough finish.
</P>
<P>
   You could cover the joints with molding, but that's not
attractive unless the joints are lined up nice and square.
</P>
<P>
   But, you could fill the joints of the Homasote you plan to
paper; apply glue size to the wall, let dry, and paper.
</P>
<P>
   And, here is another way: Fill all joints with joint compound,
sand smooth, tape as necessary (it is a good idea anyway), apply
glue size, and apply a heavy-duty wallpaper called Coverall, sold
in wallpaper shops and designed to smooth very rough walls. It can
be painted or papered over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I can't find replacements for old-fashioned hidden, interior
hinges for my kitchen cabinets, which I am redoing, and some which
are missing some hinges. Where can I find some?
</P>
<P>
   OLD HINGE LOVER
</P>
<P>
   A. You could try antiques stores, especially those that
specialize in tools and hardware. Don't expect much success; you
may find one or two, but if you need 10, the quest must continue.
Or, try the Rockler Woodworker's Store catalog (800-279-4441),
which carries many modern but concealed hinges. Or, try the Van
Dyke's Restorers catalog, 800-558-1234. The Van Dyke's catalog
listed a ``Concealed Hinge'' and an ``Invisible Concealed Hinge.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The color of an Oriental rug bled through to the wall-to-wall
carpeting underneath, making a stain. Cleaning faded the stain just
a little. The cleaner does not want to use harsh chemicals on the
stain. What will remove the stain?
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE VADALA, Brighton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If cleaning reduced the stain a little, I think more cleaning
will reduce it further. You can't blame the cleaner for not wanting
to use harsh chemicals, but you could try dabbing a bit of dry
cleaning fluid on the stain to see what will happen. Spot check
first.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, try this one: 1 cup ammonia, 1/2 cup
vinegar, 3 tablespoons baking soda, all in 1/2 bucket of water.
Spot test first.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if nothing else works, consider having the wall-to-wall
carpet dyed. They are in the Yellow Pages, and some will dye the
carpet where it lies.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent the Oriental from further bleeding, put a plastic pad
under the Oriental.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I installed a water heater recently, and not too long
afterwards the pressure-relief valve leaked. I replaced it, and it
was OK for a month, but the new one leaked. What can I do?
</P>
<P>
   MIKE BROOKS, Malborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Put in another, or have a pro put one in, then blame him if
it fails. These valves are sensitive and persnickety, and I think
it is a matter of keeping trying until something works. In fact,
there is an unwritten rule that you should set off the valve once
every six months or so to make sure it continues to work. Trouble
is, when you do that, it is likely to leak. That's life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am putting in pressure-treated deck boards, one-inch-thick
boards 6 inches wide. What is best to install them: nails or
screws? Also, some of the boards that are 12 feet long, and have
crooks and curves, which I think will be impossible to straighten
even secured to the framework. What can I do with them?
</P>
<P>
   MIKE MELANSON, Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Screws are better than nails, and hidden fasteners are better
than screws because there are no screw or nail heads showing.
</P>
<P>
   As for the curved boards, they will curve even more when they
continue drying out. Return them for straighter ones, and
definitely return any warped (cupped) ones, because it is
impossible to straighten a warped board. If that cannot be done,
cut them to shorter lengths, but lengths that will touch joints at
each end. The shorter the boards, the less curved they will be, and
you might be able to straighten them while installing them. You may
have a number of short boards but, but if they butt each other over
a joist and you don't line up the butt joints, no one will know
unless you proudly show them your handywork.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
