<HEADER>
A0787 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-WIDOW-BOS &LR;      06-18 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-WIDOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTIFULLY DRAWN `ARTIST'S WIDOW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE ARTIST'S WIDOW 
By Shena Mackay 
Moyer Bell, 151 pp., $21.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shena Mackay's ``The Artist's Widow'' opens in a Mayfair art
gallery on a rainy summer night, at a private viewing: ``John
Crane, 1918-1996: The Last Paintings.'' Crane's widow, Lyris, an
artist in her own right, is not enjoying herself.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery is hot, noisy, crowded with pseuds and strivers,
``the sort of party John and Lyris Crane hated.'' Lyris's new shoes
are killing her. She'd rather be at home alone, painting, in her
run-down house in south London, but she knows that she must pull
herself together, for John's sake.
</P>
<P>
   Mackay is a British novelist whose work invites and rewards
rereading. In her five previous novels she has shown herself an
intensely wise and humane writer, and very funny too. ``The
Artist's Widow'' is slyly satirical about the contemporary London
art world, but as always, Mackay's wit is tempered with sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   During the opening reception the gallery's on-the-make owner
drapes his arm around Lyris ``in a proprietal yet patronizing way,
trapping her and reminding her of a snake that a man had slung
around her neck once in Tangiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Pursey, Lyris's dreadful great-nephew, a conceptual
artist who works in various media (raw entrails among them),
crashes the party to promote his own career. ``Jacob, my man! Just
the bloke I'm looking for!'' Nathan is heard saying as he corners a
venerable Jewish painter. ``You know that Kristallnacht thingy in
Berlin . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a group of strangers has converged on Lyris and
presented her with a sheaf of bronze lilies _ ``so kindly intended
and such a blasted nuisance,'' thinks Lyris.
</P>
<P>
   Readers of ``The Orchard on Fire,'' Mackay's masterful novel
about child abuse, know her skill at conveying paradox and
ambiguity. Her characters are idiosyncratic and contradictory. Even
the least appealing of them have saving graces. And the best of
them are fallible. Mackay's style is a constant surprise, full of
abrupt changes of tone, suddenly lyrical, abruptly satirical.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the plot centers on Lyris, and various people's plans to
use her. Nathan thinks his elderly aunt has a valuable collection
of art, and conspires with his semi-criminal father, Buster, to
acquire the imaginary hoard. (Buster, a flower dealer, wonders if
Lyris is ``compost mentis.'') Zoe Rifaat, a conniving documentary
filmmaker, has designs on Lyris's life story for her film about
``neglected women artists.'' Nathan's pathetic former girlfriend,
Jackee, thinks Lyris with her ``wise, kind'' face might be the one
person who could love her ``more than anybody else in the world for
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lyris is not the woman any of these scheming younger people
imagine her to be. She's sharper than all of them put together. A
serious painter nearly all her life, Lyris is appalled by the new
generation of conceptual artists personified by her nephew Nathan,
who dreams of the day he can stop ``dicking about with
installations'' and have his own Web site for his tiresome,
opportunistic, and inevitably self-referential projects.
</P>
<P>
   Mackay is a literary artist, and this novel is full of small
masterpieces. The awful Pursey family gathers at an Italian
restaurant: ``It was a warm fleshy evening of Neapolitan love
songs, moist skin and escalopes beaten into the shape of the map of
Italy, the fountain trickling in the grotto behind the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaguely contemplating suicide, Lyris imagines asking the advice
of another great-nephew, a marine biologist who ``would know about
tides and coastal movements and where to find a warm but
treacherous sea where one could avoid officious dolphins who might
insist on snouting one back to shore.''
</P>
<P>
   An obnoxious yuppie couple move in next door to Lyris and make
it plain they're slumming: ``Visible only to themselves and their
friends, a pair of inverted commas hovered above the slate roof . .
. to show that Nancy Carmody and Rod Dyer had set up home there
ironically.''
</P>
<P>
   Mackay economically introduces a large cast of eccentric
characters, some of them benign, a few decidedly not. The low-key
plot unfolds, culminating when Lyris and two friends arrive at a
50th birthday party and are surprised to find the guest of honor, a
woman who works for a hedgehog charity, in tears. ``How can you
stand there and congratulate me?'' she demands. ``Wishing me happy
birthday. . . . Have you no feelings at all?''
</P>
<P>
   They learn that Princess Diana has died. ``Brightness falls from
the air; Queens have died, young and fair,'' says Lyris, moved to
quote Thomas Nashe. But she's soon back in her usual form, bringing
Jackee up short when the young woman's mourning for Diana waxes
maudlin. ``I think we're in danger of genuine grief being whipped
up into something ugly,'' Lyris warns.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Artist's Widow'' Mackay's fans have a treat in store.
Those who have yet to discover her would do well to start with this
novel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
