<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDDY GUY JOINS ERIC CLAPTON SALUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chicago's Buddy Guy once went up to Eric Clapton to express
admiration for the tune ``Strange Brew,'' which Clapton recorded
with the '60s band Cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, that song blows my mind,'' Guy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should,'' answered Clapton. ``Those are your licks.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy tells the story with a laugh, but he just got a chance to
give back respect by recording ``Strange Brew'' for a fine new
Clapton tribute disc, ``Blues Power: Songs of Eric Clapton.'' It
also features Clapton tunes covered by Koko Taylor, Bo Diddley,
Otis Rush, Ann Peebles, and Derek Trucks of the Allman Brothers
Band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric, the Stones, and all those British guys did so much for
us,'' Guy said, referring to fellow Chicago bluesmen Muddy Waters
and Howling Wolf. ``When Eric and Jeff Beck met me in 1965, they
said they had never heard blues played on a Stratocaster before.
And Eric said he slept in a van just to see me play.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy, now 62, had been driving a tow truck in Chicago before he
made that fateful trip to London in 1965. He has remained friends
with Clapton ever since _ and received another career boost when
Clapton invited him to play a series of Royal Albert Hall shows in
1989, which led to Guy being signed with Silvertone Records. The
label later released Guy's Grammy-winning CD, ``Damn Right, I've
Got the Blues,'' and this week issued the compilation, ``Buddy's
Baddest: The Best of Silvertone.'' ``An Innocent Man,'' a song Guy
wrote about Rodney King, a victim of police violence in Los
Angeles, is one of two previously unreleased tracks on the CD.
</P>
<P>
   Guy is backing these latest projects. It's an excellent,
triple-dynamite blues package _ and catches Guy on a high note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having the time of my life,'' he said in a phone interview
this week from his Legends club in Chicago. ``As long as you can
stay in pretty good health and enjoy what you're doing, what else
is there?''
</P>
<P>
   Guy remains a dynamic performer _ a reputation he carved in the
'60s when he played his guitar behind his back and over his head in
clubs. ``I always said, `I want to sound like B.B. King and act
like Guitar Slim on stage,' '' he noted. ``And I was doing a lot of
things back then that Jimi Hendrix picked up on. Hendrix came up to
me once and said, `I've been watching you. I canceled a gig just to
see you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Many people have watched Guy through the years _ and he's
showing no sign of slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Truckin' with the Allmans: Derek Trucks, who turned 20 on June
8, has joined the Allman Brothers Band, which hits the Tweeter
Center in Mansfield June 26. Trucks replaces Jack Pearson, an
underrated player who left because of hearing concerns from
tinnitus.
</P>
<P>
   It means a big opportunity for Trucks _ and he's making the most
of it. ``Every time I take a solo, it's a thrill for me,'' he said
this week from Winston-Salem, N.C., where he was listening to a
Howling Wolf CD and relaxing before his fourth show of the Allmans
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping all the guys get off on a new energy in the band,
because I'm very enthusiastic about being here,'' said Trucks,
whose role is to play a lot of slide guitar and second guitar to
Dickey Betts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Dickey's playing and, over the years, he's been a great
influence. He's written so many great tunes. You hear one note and
you know it's him. He's amazing. When he steps up to take a solo,
he tries to move mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Trucks, the nephew of Allmans drummer Butch Trucks, also was
heavily influenced by early Allmans guitarist Duane Allman. ``He's
probably the reason I started playing and started taking the guitar
seriously,'' said Trucks, who at age 8 and 9 used to go to bed
listening to ``Eat a Peach,'' the classic live album on which Duane
shone. ``It's definitely a trip to try to get up and channel some
of that energy,'' Trucks explained.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1992, when he was only 13, Trucks first sat in with the
Allmans. ``I think it was in Jacksonville and it was probably on
(the song) `Statesboro Blues' or `One Way Out.' You know, I'm not
sure!''
</P>
<P>
   Given his family connections, and his immense ability, it was
only natural for Trucks to get called to join. ``They just called
me . . . and said to be at rehearsals on a certain day. There
wasn't any tryout or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Trucks said the Allmans have been playing a lot of early era
songs on this tour, including ``Les Bres in A Minor,'' ``Leave My
Blues at Home,'' and ``Please Call Home.'' Said Trucks: ``We're
still feeling each other out and I'm trying to find a spot where we
can really lock in. But it's feeling good.''
</P>
<P>
   Trucks also plans to continue sprinkling in gigs with his Derek
Trucks Band this summer (and for the rest of the year when the
Allmans are off the road).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Original Pumpkins: The Smashing Pumpkins are back to their
original lineup with the return of drummer Jimmy Chamberlin. Billy
Corgan, James Iha, D'Arcy, and Chamberlin are currently in a
Chicago studio with producer Flood, who also worked on their
double-CD ``Mellon Collie and the Infinite Sadness.'' Look for an
October release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
