<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BIZKIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIMP BIZKIT UNLEASHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Limp Bizkit's in the house! Limp Bizkit's in the house!''
</P>
<P>
   That's the chant heard on Limp Bizkit's new album, which comes
out Tuesday. But this week, Limp Bizkit's members haven't been in
the house. They've been on the roof. Three rooftops, to be exact _
in Boston, Detroit, and Chicago, where Bizkit fans have flocked
after hearing late-breaking radio announcements for unlicensed,
sneak concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is guerrilla style,'' Bizkit singer Fred Durst said this
week. ``This is set up and play until you get shut down.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of Bizkit's quest to ``keep it real'' and stay
close to the streets, minus any superstar ego. ``We're just fans
who got lucky and sold some records,'' said Durst. ``We've got to
let people know that we're just like them _ we're just fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston was first up on Sunday, as Bizkit appeared on a
parking-garage roof near Fenway Park, drawing 1,500 folks and
playing 25 minutes until police chased them off. Detroit was next
on Tuesday with Bizkit on a record-store roof; the band was able to
do only two songs before police terminated the experience. Chicago
was next on Wednesday with 6,000 people _ the biggest crowd of the
three-city rooftop series. ``The cops were very cool. They came and
saw how many kids were there and they let us play for 30 minutes,''
said Bizkit manager Peter Katsis, reached on his cell phone after
the gig.
</P>
<P>
   Durst then jumped on the cell phone to discuss the Boston date,
which may lead to fines for the band, though no decision has been
made. ``Without a doubt, the Boston show was the coolest thing I
ever experienced,'' said Durst. ``The other shows this week were
amazing, too, but the first one is always the best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pandemonium everywhere, but it's been a lot of
fun,'' added Katsis. (Bizkit will return to play a July 23 date at
the Tsongas Arena in Lowell with Kid Rock and Staind.)
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to nervy rooftop tricks and to momentum from Bizkit's
last album (the 1.5 million-selling ``Three Dollar Bill, Y'all'')
and from bone-crunching sets on the ``Family Values'' tour with
Korn, Ice Cube, Rammstein, and Orgy, Bizkit should make a huge
splash with its new disc, ``Significant Other.'' A VJ on MTV this
week even predicted that it would debut at No. 1 on the charts.
Already, the single ``Nookie'' is blowing up on radio stations
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, it's clear that Bizkit's street-tough brand of heavy
metal/rap is right in sync with listeners who are tired of being
fed corporate hand-me-downs. The music sounds fresh, and the lyrics
are penned by the charismatic Durst, who as a kid in Gastonia,
N.C., loved AC/DC, Kiss, and Ratt, as well as the hip-hop records
he heard at his mostly black high school.
</P>
<P>
   But Durst didn't fit in with either camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the outcast,'' he recalled. ``I was skateboarding all
around school when nobody was ever skateboarding. . . . Until the
Beastie Boys came out, I was a total reject.''
</P>
<P>
   Durst went into the Navy, then opened a skate park in Charlotte,
N.C., then became a tattoo designer _ and first met Korn while
giving the band members tattoos. He moved to Jacksonville, Fla.,
where he formed Bizkit with Wes Borland (guitars), Sam Rivers
(bass), John Otto (drums), and DJ Lethal (turntables and samples).
And the rest has been a fast-moving time bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Durst's residual anger coated Bizkit's debut disc, ``Three
Dollar Bill, Y'all.'' It was a milestone in male rage. ``I just
exploded and you couldn't understand a lot of the words,'' he
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   He also exploded onstage, where Bizkit has truly left its mark
with incendiary performances that ignite mosh pits and devastate
any eardrums that dare get in the way. Imagine John Lennon's primal
screams turned up as high as they'll go, topped by some unearthly
raving.
</P>
<P>
   But although he's a high-wire act onstage, like Iggy Pop, Durst
comes across as mellow offstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's a release for me, for sure,'' Durst said of
performing. ``It's something to see people with a vibe and glow in
their eyes. Everybody is there for different reasons and that
creates one gigantic ball of energy that hits you in different
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain people are singing certain lyrics, and some girls are
screaming, and some other people are crying and feeling other
stuff,'' he added. ``It's so many different emotions. It's the most
powerful thing in the world. I've never experienced anything like
that. It's like an adrenaline rush takes over.''
</P>
<P>
   Durst enjoys the attention, but he's not a macho-style star who
neurotically craves it. In fact, Bizkit's new album has a song,
``No Sex,'' which decries the macho lust of many male rock stars.
In graphic terms, Durst sings, ``I feel disgusted and you should,
too . . . Should have left my pants on, but instead you let me dive
right in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a message I hope people will get,'' said Durst. ``There's
so much meaninglessness out there, so much emptiness . . . Sex is
something that when rushed into can ruin things.''
</P>
<P>
   Sex is also at the heart of the new single ``Nookie,'' about a
former girlfriend he loved and supported, only to find that she was
cheating on him with his friends. The result is an angry
declaration in which Durst finally tells the woman to get lost.
</P>
<P>
   Durst also believes in God _ and believes that God gives him his
lyrics. And, typical of Durst's need to feel a bond with his fans,
he keeps the lyrics on a simple enough plane so that everyone can
understand them _ when he's not shouting himself hoarse, that is.
``I don't want to be eclectic and poetic,'' he said. ``I don't want
to be really artsy, because a lot of people just don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Limp Bizkit has an ability to blister listeners with a
high-volume assault, but also a unique ability to uplift those
listeners, as with the band's hit cover of George Michael's
``Faith'' last year. They pumped up the volume but retained the
song's upbeat message.
</P>
<P>
   The new album, ``Significant Other,'' finds Bizkit offering a
more ``accepting'' view of life, Durst said. ``This record is about
accepting a lot of the pain that you might go through in everyday
relationships, emotions, and friends.'' A case in point is the
moodily psychedelic song ``A Lesson Learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Anger still lurks beneath the surface, but fully explodes on
only one song: ``Break Stuff.'' It's about ``one of those days when
you just don't want to wake up . . . you don't know why, but you
want to justify ripping someone's head off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That song is probably the exception, but every other song
explains what happened to me, then the turnaround of the song is
about accepting it,'' said Durst. ``Or at least understanding it.
And I'd never even thought about trying to understand it in the
past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
