<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0796 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-SOSA-HNS &LR;      06-18 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMMY SOSA, DIPLOMAT, ON THE WAY TO GREATNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service cliens.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sammy Sosa's gift for diplomacy borders, well,
on the frightening.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, for example, he performed the heretofore unattempted
``I Like It Here AND There'' double Salchow from the visitors
dugout at Candlestick Park. To nobody's surprise, he executed it
flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like hitting in this ballpark, I'll miss playing here,'' the
second coming of Mr. Cub said before the Giants' 3-2 victory over
Chicago. ``But I like playing in a new ballpark. Everyone likes to
play where there's a lot of enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did he perform this acrobatic feat on a cold evening
when most athletes would have trouble with muscle pulls, he did it
without any visible strain or exertion, as though it were the
easiest thing in the world to find reasons to like both this joint
and one he hasn't even been in yet.
</P>
<P>
   By now, though, this sort of thing is expected of Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Having set the standard for grace in the face of extraordinary
success a year ago, he is diligent about letting nobody down the
year after. If he wants to like Candlestick AND its successor at
the same time, frankly, he's earned it.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at a time in baseball history when more players are
hitting more home runs than ever before, Sosa seems more and more
like the one who will get the most inner mileage out of it.
</P>
<P>
   He almost surely will become the spokesman for the new power
generation, a group that is larger and more cumbersome than it has
ever been, and includes more players you never thought of in that
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three men hit 30 or more homers last year, a remarkable
figure that is sure to be exceeded this season, even allowing for
those members of the Usual Suspects club who are not currently on a
pace to do so, like Albert Belle, Alex Rodriguez, Tony Clark, Jim
Thome, Frank Thomas, Nomar Garciaparra, Barry Bods, Jeff Kent, Ray
Lankford, Vinny Castilla, Henry Rodriguez and Javy Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, home runs have never been cheaper to obtain than
they are now, for a variety of reasons too numerous to repeat here
for the 350th time. And while it is true that Mark McGwire will
always be the figure against whom all other big-time bombers will
be matched, Sammy Sosa will be the spokesman who explains it all to
the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   That he can manage this while cementing his own place as one of
the dominant figures of the decade is more remarkable than perhaps
it should be. He often says that neither he nor McGwire could have
destroyed Roger Maris' record without the other, but he is also a
leader in the late '90s phalanx of power hitters who have changed
the parameters within which the game is played.
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Baker, Giant manager and part-time baseball historian, was
asked before the game if he thought Sosa was on the verge of
achieving the kind of stature that Frank Robinson, Henry Aaron and
Roberto Clemente did in the '60s. Baker, not surprisingly,
acknowledged that Sosa was almost, but not quite, there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting close,'' Baker said in admiration. ``He's
definitely getting in that echelon. But it took those guys 10, 15
years. You don't get in that echelon overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   One can argue, though, that Robinson, Aaron and Clemente got to
be Robinson, Aaron and Clemente in a lot fewer than 10 years, in
which case Sosa is already there. He would have six consecutive
years of 30 or more homers if his figure in the strike-shortened
1994 season were pro-rated, and his newfound selectivity at the
plate has now made him a consistent .300 hitter. Plus, he is only
30, which allows him plenty of time to convince Baker beyond all
shadow of doubt.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, Sosa's ability to see the half-filled glass and
know that the waiter is on his way to fill it to the top any second
now that will separate him from the dozens of other sluggers of his
generation. Those who remember 1998 (``I try not to remember it,''
Sosa says with a smile) will remember the way Sosa not only helped
raise the bar mathematically, but emotionally as well. He made the
world safe for fun through achievement, and for the most cheerful
kind of diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   He says he likes Candlestick Park, after all, and if he weren't
Sammy Sosa, you'd be sure he was lying through his teeth.
</P>
</TEXT>
