<HEADLINE>
PEBBLE BEACH SOLD TO ARNOLD PALMER, CLINT EASTWOOD AND OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A celebrity-studded group that includes Peter
Ueberroth, Arnold Palmer and Clint Eastwood grabbed one of the most
coveted chunks of real estate in California, agreeing to buy Pebble
Beach golf course for $820 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ueberroth called the course the best in the world, and pledged
to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a transparent change from one owner to the other,''
Ueberroth said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ueberroth, the former baseball commissioner, put together the
group _ golf legend Palmer, actor Eastwood, former United Airlines
CEO Richard Ferris and General Electric Pensions _ that succeeded
in purchasing the Pebble Beach Co. and its impressive list of
property holdings from current owner, The Lone Cypress Co.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement ends several months of negotiations between the
two groups over the sale of Pebble Beach, the legendary birthplace
of the Bing Crosby Pro-Am Golf Tournament _ the ``Crosby
Clambake,'' as some called it.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the deal will close on July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it is a fair price,'' Ferris said. ``It is a good
investment or we wouldn't be investing.''
</P>
<P>
   The new ownership group brings together four men who have
climbed to the pinnacles of success in four vastly different
professions. All four love golf, especially the challenge of
playing Pebble Beach. Ueberroth, Ferris and Eastwood all have long
ties to Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is possibly the most famous golfer of the last half of
this century. At 69, he is winding down his memorable career on the
PGA Senior Tour. Palmer has for many years been involved with his
Arnold Palmer Co., which has managed the Presidio Golf Club in San
Francisco since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood, whose acting or directing credits include such
classics as ``Dirty Harry'' and ``High Plains Drifter,'' said the
group is ``sensitive to the values'' of the Monterey peninsula and
the surrounding environment.
</P>
<P>
   The 68-year-old Eastwood, formerly the mayor of nearby Carmel
and still a resident of that town, is a longtime golfer who plays
every year in the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am.
</P>
<P>
   Ueberroth, 61, who was baseball commissioner from 1984-89 and
president of the Los Angeles Olympic Organizing Committee in 1984,
also is a regular in the AT&AMP;T Pro- Am and a member of the
tournament's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very special place; people come from all over the world
to play here,'' Ueberroth said.
</P>
<P>
   Pebble Beach officials said the deal would not have succeeded if
the new group didn't have close ties to the community. All of the
new principal owners have played the course in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes four golf courses _ the Pebble Beach Golf
Links, Spyglass Hill Golf Course, The Links at Spanish Bay and Del
Monte Golf Course _ and two resorts, The Lodge at Pebble Beach and
The Inn at Spanish Bay along with tourist-friendly 17-Mile Drive
that winds through Pebble Beach and nearby Del Monte Forest. In
addition, the new owners take over several hundred acres of
undeveloped land, where they plan to build another golf course and
more than 300 homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Pebble Beach area has long been a tourist attraction. In
1919 it was developed when the grandnephew and namesake of
telegraph inventor Samuel Morse, Samuel F.B. Morse, purchased the
Del Monte Forest on the Monterey peninsula for a then-whopping $1.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Ueberroth's group becomes the fourth owner of the Pebble Beach
Co. this decade. Bank of America is providing financing. Ueberroth
said the price was ``exactly $820 million'' _ less than the same
property sold for nine years ago. The price tag means it is one of
the few pieces of real estate that has not skyrocketed in value
this decade.
</P>
</TEXT>
