<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-RUSSIA (Cologne, Germany) _ Two days before a scheduled
summit between President Clinton and Russian President Boris
Yeltsin, senior U.S. officials express deep wariness of Russia and
Yeltsin in the wake of Russian troops' surprise seizure of the
airfield in Pristina and protracted negotiations that continue over
Russia's role in a peace-keeping force in Kosovo. By STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-STUDY (Washington) _ Adolescents are more likely than
adults to become addicted to gambling, says a new federally-funded
study. The National Gambling Impact Study Commission estimates that
about 85 percent of youngsters 12 to 18 have gambled at least once
in their lives. The commission recommends raising the minimum
gambling age to 21 and banning Internet gambling. By JENNIFER
CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-AMBASSADOR (Washington) _ Luxembourg's ambassador to the
United States, Arlette Conzemius, will host a dinner at her
country's embassy here to welcome gay rights advocate James C.
Hormel to his new post as U.S. envoy to Luxembourg. Hormel received
a recess appointment earlier this month from President Clinton
after conservative Republicans blocked a Senate vote on his
nomination. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEARST-COSMOPOLITAN (New York) _ Hearst Magazines, publisher of
37 international editions of Cosmopolitan, the world's best-selling
title for young women, announces that the company will introduce a
new teen title under the Cosmopolitan name. The magazine, titled
CosmoGIRL!, and its related Web site (www.cosmogirl.com), are
designed for girls 12 to 17 and will debut on June 29. By The
Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ If he were still alive, President
Harry Truman would recognize the political games played by today's
naysayers, who refuse to admit they were wrong about the air
campaign that forced Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to
capitulate and who decline to commend Bill Clinton for his
steadfast support of that campaign. Truman faced similar myopic
politicians 50 years ago. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
