<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOMEN'S-CUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN GOLFERS GEAR UP FOR WORLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DWIGHT CHAPIN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The favorites are the United States, China, Norway and Germany,
but don't be surprised if the Women's World Cup, which begins a
three-week run Saturday with doubleheaders in East Rutherford,
N.J., and San Jose, turns wild and woolly.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of that, you need look no further back than last
weekend, when 500-1 tournament longshot Nigeria knocked off China,
4-3, in a tuneup match in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can say the match didn't mean anything. But Chinese
coach Ma Yuanan, questioned about the defeat earlier this week, was
scurrying to find excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Although saying, ``I think the Nigerian team is very good and
will play very good in this competition,'' Ma noted that the
playing field ``was not very good,'' that the goals were two
different sizes, that a couple of his players were feeling the
effects of jet lag and one key performer was injured.
</P>
<P>
   All of which leads to the conclusion that the loss was at least
unsettling to a quick and tenacious Chinese team that has been seen
as a tournament co-favorite, with the United States, after beating
the Americans twice in three matches this year.
</P>
<P>
   And the China-Nigeria result just may portend what's ahead in
the 16-team Women's World Cup, which with 475,000 tickets already
sold will be the biggest women-only sports event ever.
</P>
<P>
   The action on the West Coast starts Saturday at Spartan Stadium,
with Sweden against China, followed by Canada facing Japan. A
quarterfinal double-header is set at Spartan Stadium on July 30,
with a semifinal at Stanford Stadium on July 4. The tournament will
conclude July 10 with the final at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there is one favorite in the World Cup,'' said
coach Wilson De Olivera Rica of Brazil, which is in the second tier
of contenders along with Denmark, Sweden, Canada, Brazil, and _ off
the China upset _ perhaps Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is seen by so many countries as the top
nation, primarily because they train together year-round and play
so many games together. They certainly will be the team to shoot
for. But there is a host of nations who, when they put 11 players
on the field, can compete with the U.S. or anyone else. Including
Brazil.''
</P>
<P>
   The two top finishers in each of four groups will advance to the
quarterfinals. And, as a bonus, at least seven of the eight
quarterfinalists automatically qualify for the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   (Australia, as host of the Games, is guaranteed a spot in 2000).
</P>
<P>
   This is the third Women's World Cup. The United States took the
first one, in 1991, with Norway winning the second, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Those two countries have had an ongoing rivalry for years. The
Americans defeated the Norwegians for the '91 championship, but
Norway returned the favor in the '95 semifinals. In the 1996
Olympics, the United States downed Norway in the semifinals. But
Norway came back to hand the American women their worst loss ever _
4-1 _ in a tournament in Portugal last year.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the tournament will be the biggest showcase ever for
the U.S. team, which opens play Saturday at Giants Stadium against
Denmark, followed by a Brazil-Mexico match.
</P>
<P>
   Tony DiCicco, who has coached the U.S. squad since 1994,
believes his veteran-laden team is ready to play _ and play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel pretty good,'' DiCicco said. ``There's a great
mentality on this team. It's a very close team, as close as any
I've ever been associated with as a coach. We've been training a
long time. Now it's time to test what we've done on the playing
field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
