<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-COSMOPOLITAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARST ANNOUNCES NEW VERSION OF COSMOPOLITAN FOR TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hearst Magazines, publisher of 37 international
editions of Cosmopolitan, the world's best-selling title for young
women, announced Friday that the company will introduce a new teen
title under the Cosmopolitan name.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, titled CosmoGIRL!, and its related Web site
(www.cosmogirl.com), are geared for girls ages 12-17 and will debut
on June 29.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Magazines will test three issues during 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teenagers in the United States either spent, or encouraged
their parents to spend nearly $125 billion last year,'' said
Cathleen P. Black, president of Hearst Magazines. ``This is a
growing market, and the time is right for us to introduce this
title.''
</P>
<P>
   Atoosa Rubenstein, 27, project editor of the new magazine and
former senior fashion editor at Cosmopolitan, said the
publication's message is that ``through advice, inspiration, and
scoop... our reader can be all that she desires to be. This is what
distinguishes CosmoGIRL! from other teenage titles.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein said she wants CosmoGIRL! to be the teenage girl's
best friend _ the one whose going to help her get through junior
high school and high school. She's the one girls go to when no one
else understands... the one who inspires her to `Go Girl!'''
</P>
<P>
   The new magazine also will have its own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our initial response is very encouraging and we believe
CosmoGIRL! will be a hit with readers and advertisers alike,'' said
Donna Kalajian Lagani, senior vice president and publisher of
Cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Barnard College in 1993, Rubenstein began
working at Cosmopolitan as a fashion assistant under Helen Gurley
Brown, the creator of Cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   She also worked at Sassy magazine in the beauty and fashion
departments and at American Health magazine (Reader's Digest
Corporation) throughout her college years.
</P>
<P>
   CosmoGIRL! will have a newsstand distribution of 850,000 and a
cover price of $2.99.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0828 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-BAPTIST2NDTA     06-18 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-BAPTIST2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Baptists in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Land, head of the Southern Baptist Convention's Ethics
and Religious Liberty Commission, agrees. If conservatives had not
won, he said, there would have been a ``significant hemorrhaging''
of conservatives from the Southern Baptist Convention and it might
now be dealing with issues that trouble mainline Protestant groups
such as the United Methodist Church, Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)
and Episcopal Church. ``Our convention might now be debating
whether to ordain homosexuals to the ministry, and our convention
might be debating whether to bless same-sex unions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Cooperative Baptist Fellowship does resemble
so-called mainline Protestantism. Whereas the platform of the
Southern Baptist Convention is filled with male clergy, four of
eight moderators of the Cooperative Baptist Fellowship have been
women, and several, including the current moderator, are laity. And
the Fellowship is much more inclined than the SBC to participate in
ecumenical efforts with Methodists, Presbyterians and
Episcopalians.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Southern Baptist Convention often joins hands with
the country's evangelicals, aligning with leaders such as James
Dobson and Chuck Colson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at Washington and what's going on legislatively,
you see a lot of cooperation between Southern Baptists and
evangelicals,'' said Timothy Morgan, an editor for Christianity
Today magazine, founded by evangelist Billy Graham to cover the
evangelical movement.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fellowship has not affiliated with the National Council
of Churches, the meeting ground for the country's historic
Protestant bodies. And the Southern Baptist Convention is not an
official member of the National Association of Evangelicals, a
network of conservative denominations and ministries.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of both the Southern Baptist Convention and the
Cooperative Baptist Fellowship predict bright futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am firmly convinced that we have been tested and found true
to God's word, and he is going to use us to lead a great revival in
the United States,'' said Land of the SBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're healthy and we're growing,'' said Vestal, who directs
the Fellowship. ``And we're young and still emerging to shape our
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is confident that both or either will prosper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be concerned about the future of both groups,'' said
Greg Warner, editor of Associated Baptist Press, a Baptist news
service developed as an alternative to the official denominational
news agency. Warner, a graduate of Southwestern Baptist Theological
Seminary, has been covering Southern Baptists since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Warner sees the Southern Baptist Convention ``drawing the circle
smaller and smaller and drawing itself in opposition to culture and
to the rest of Christendom, whether or not that's intentional. ...
The whole tone and mode create a negative impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Fellowship's mission is clearly ``geared for a
future faith,'' Warner said, ``they haven't lived out their mission
statement yet.'' Although many sociologists of religion believe the
traditional denominational model of Christianity is outmoded, the
Fellowship, he said, ``is still populated by Baptists who function
primarily in the denominational mode. They're still thinking
institutionally and in some ways trying to create a new
denominational structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of both groups acknowledge they will not prosper with
business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   At the Southern Baptist Convention this week in Atlanta,
Patterson used his presidential platform to push evangelism,
ministry and missions in the nation's cities. The denomination that
grew out of the agrarian South is now largely suburban. But
Patterson told his fellow Baptists that many of the nation's
problems are in its cities, and they should be playing a
constructive role in solving them.
</P>
<P>
   And Vestal says the Fellowship will begin strategic planning
with its annual assembly in Birmingham next week. The Fellowship,
he said, ``sees itself primarily as a network that has multiple
partners'' and functions with ``more freedom, more flexibility and
much more diversity than denominations with firm hierarchies and
huge bureaucracies.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few thousand of the country's Southern Baptists will
attend either the Fellowship or the SBC meeting this year. Most
remain in their churches and communities, far from national
policy-making or politics.
</P>
<P>
   At the state and local level, Baptist leaders are still
attempting to hold together the two sides to toil together in the
fields of the Lord. ``The way to avoid splits is to recognize that
diversity exists and, where it is possible, to be gracious and
extend opportunities for service to those who disagree,'' said the
Rev. Robert White, executive director of the Georgia Baptist
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, the ties appear to continue to bind, albeit to
various degrees. Membership and giving in the state's Southern
Baptist churches are at record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of the controversy, God's work continues to be
done,'' said White, ``which, I think, says a lot about the power of
God and his message.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
