<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0829 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-BAPTISTS1STT     06-18 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-BAPTISTS1STTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two decades ago, conservatives captured the leadership of the
Southern Baptist Convention; now they're firmly in control
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Rev. Jerry Falwell looked right at home on the
podium of the Georgia Dome, facing the Southern Baptists sitting in
the blue-green seats of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Paige Patterson, convention president, welcomed him as
a brother and a ``new Southern Baptist.'' Then Falwell prayed,
thanking God for ``this invincible church,'' for Patterson, and for
all the agency heads and seminary leaders of the Southern Baptist
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 20 brief years,'' he reminded God, ``men of God in every
position! We thank you for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The reference was obviously directed at the 1979 Southern
Baptist Convention, when the conservative resurgence _ known by
opponents as the fundamentalist takeover _ surfaced. It began with
the election of the Rev. Adrian Rogers of Memphis as president of
the convention, and has continued, gaining steam, every year
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   But even without Falwell's spoken reminder, his presence on the
platform beside Patterson as president was ample evidence of how
much the country's largest Protestant denomination has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Before that historic Houston meeting, Patterson was an outsider
to convention leadership, but from his distant outpost, he was
plotting a strategy that would radically alter the course of the
convention. Falwell was an independent Baptist, well to the right
of Southern Baptist leaders. His Thomas Road Baptist Church in
Lynchburg, Va., now contributes to Southern Baptist Conservatives
of Virginia, a new state convention formed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As Falwell suggested in his prayer, the extent of conservative
change reaches far beyond the convention platform, extending up and
down the ladder of leadership, from directors of mission agencies
to reporters for the denominational news service.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the so-called moderates, whose decline in
denominational influence began with Rogers' election, retreated and
regrouped after 12 consecutive years of being on the losing side of
the political bloodshed. In 1991, 6,000 of them held their own
rally in Atlanta with rousing speeches that compared their group _
the Cooperative Baptist Fellowship _ to great liberation movements
from the Israelites to civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The two Baptist entities are neither separate nor equal.
</P>
<P>
   Although many congregations contribute to both, not daring to
risk a church split by taking a straight up-or-down vote on either,
the two groups differ drastically in size, shape and the company
they keep.
</P>
<P>
   The SBC today claims 15.7 million members _ more than before
some moderates began to drift away. That number declined in 1998
for the first time since 1926, according to official records. But
those figures include a large number of ``nonresident'' members who
have moved away or whose whereabouts are unknown. The convention's
resident membership is 10.7 million _ and actually peaked at 11
million in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The SBC claims 40,870 churches and adopted a 2000 denominational
budget of $159.6 million for its institutions and missions.
</P>
<P>
   The Cooperative Baptist Fellowship, based in Atlanta, gets
support from 1,790 churches, has an annual budget of $14.5 million,
sends out its own missionary force, and is associated with 11
theological educational programs, including two in Atlanta, at
Mercer and Emory universities.
</P>
<P>
   While speakers to the Southern Baptist Convention have included
Falwell, then-President George Bush and then-Vice President Dan
Quayle, the most famous person to address the Cooperative Baptist
Fellowship is former President Jimmy Carter, who declared himself
to be one of their number.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee and concern
</P>
<P>
   It all began over beignets in 1967 when Patterson, a student at
New Orleans Baptist Theological Seminary, met Judge Paul Pressler,
a justice on the Texas Court of Appeals. Both were worried about
what they saw as the liberal leanings of Baptistdom, especially in
the classrooms of the denomination's seminaries.
</P>
<P>
   Over coffee at Cafe du Monde, the two shared their concerns.
``Basically the conservative movement was born right there,''
Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   The two determined that if they could get enough people to the
annual Southern Baptist Convention, conservatives could win the
presidency. And the president could appoint committees that would
eventually turn around the entire denomination.
</P>
<P>
   After a decade of planting and nourishing, they were ready to
harvest in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In the ensuing years, both the intensity of convention politics
and attendance at annual meetings skyrocketed. Only 12,000 souls
had voted in that 1979 election, but by the late 1980s,
``messengers'' _ official attendees _ numbered more than 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Daniel Vestal of Dunwoody was nominated for president
of the convention in 1990. With 37,856 people voting, he lost to
the Rev. Morris Chapman, a Wichita Falls, Texas, pastor.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``A Messenger's Memoirs: Sixty-one Southern Baptist
Convention Meetings,'' Robert Naylor, president emeritus of
Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary in Fort Worth, Texas,
wrote of the meeting, held in New Orleans, ``There was a difference
about this convention. It could have been the gathering of the
Republicans and the Democrats. The controversy that had plagued
this convention for a dozen years seemed to be reaching its apex.''
</P>
<P>
   With Vestal's defeat, the moderates defected in spirit if not in
membership. In 1991, convention attendance was less than half that
of the previous year, and Chapman was re-elected without
opposition. A corner had been turned.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's convention, Pressler promoted his new book, ``A
Hill on Which to Die,'' which details ``how conservatives wrested
control from the moderates'' (Broadman &AMP; Holman, $29.99). It was a
sellout at the convention bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Mainline or evangelical?
</P>
<P>
   The doctrinal party that became known as conservatives or
fundamentalists had built its platform on the ``inerrancy'' of
Scripture, the claim that the Bible is literally true. The party
that became known as the moderates focused on the priesthood of all
believers, or the right of all Christians to interpret Scripture
for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Mohler, president of the Southern Baptist Theological
Seminary in Louisville, casts the battle as a struggle over whether
the Southern Baptist Convention would become a mainline Protestant
denomination or an evangelical group. Mohler, one of the young
leaders of the conservative movement, clearly prefers the
evangelical side.
</P>
<P>
   Many other Protestant groups underwent fundamentalist-modernist
struggles in the 1920s, and in those cases, the modernists won,
Mohler says. The evangelical movement was founded largely by
conservatives who pulled out of those groups.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the Southern Baptist Convention half a century
later is that the conservatives won. Now, Mohler says, ``there is
an evangelical denomination of Baptists in the South and a mainline
Protestant denomination of Baptists in the South.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
