<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLA-FUGITIVE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUGITIVE IN 1975 CALIFORNIA TERRORISM CASE APPEARS IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. _ After more than two decades of hiding in plain
sight, the woman alleged to be Kathleen Ann Soliah, alias Sarah
Jane Olson, found herself standing before the world in a bright
orange prisoner's jumpsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Her backers proclaimed that the church-going, casserole-baking,
play-acting soccer mom they had known as Olson for two decades
could not possibly be Soliah, the bomb-laying, rich-hating
terrorist and fugitive that the FBI and Los Angeles Police
Department said she was.
</P>
<P>
   ``No evidence was introduced in court (today) indicating Ms.
Olson is in fact Kathleen Soliah,'' her attorney, Howard Bass, said
Thursday, hours after she appeared in Ramsey County (Minn.)
District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Her appearance was to answer charges that she was, indeed, the
former associate of the terrorist Symbionese Liberation Army who
planted bombs under police squad cars in Los Angeles in 1975 in
order to kill cops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult for everyone who knows Sarah Olson to believe
that she could be Kathleen Soliah,'' Bass said. ``Ms. Olson is
described by those who know her as a pacifist who is involved in
numerous peace and justice issues, a liberal Democrat, a gun
control advocate and a perfect neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   With two dozen church women from her neighborhood Methodist
church cheering her on, Olson/Soliah was further extolled by Bass
for assisting the blind and ghetto kids and feeding the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``By all accounts, Ms. Olson is the typical soccer mom _ not the
revolutionary terrorist Kathleen Soliah is alleged to have been a
quarter-century ago,'' Bass said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI scoffed at claims that Olson was not Soliah. FBI
spokeswoman Coleen Rowley said a fingerprint analysis removed any
doubt.
</P>
<P>
   In the front row of the small, crowded courtroom, her Olson's
daughters _ Emily, 18, Sophia, 17, and Layla, 12 _ wept. Her
husband, emergency room physician Gerald F. Peterson, remained
stoic.
</P>
<P>
   His 51-year-old wife, who alternately looked somber and smirked
as she stood in the dock, is accused in Los Angeles of attempted
murder and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The government charges Soliah was part of the terrorist SLA, or
its offshoot, the New World Liberation Front. The SLA, a ragtag
collection of ex-convicts and young student radicals, assassinated
Oakland Schools Supt. Marcus Foster, kidnapped newspaper heiress
Patricia Hearst and committed bank robberies in its brief, violent
existence in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Soliah, according to official and other sources, joined the NWLF
after six SLA ``soldiers'' perished in a shootout with Los Angeles
cops in Compton in May 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, who had converted to the terrorist group, and surviving
members Bill and Emily Harris, were captured in their San Francisco
hideouts the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Soliah, who went underground when Hearst and the Harrises were
arrested, was seized by FBI and local police Wednesday near her
vine-covered home in an upscale St. Paul neighborhood. She was on
her way to teach a class in English as a second language, which she
did regularly, neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan B. Jordan, an Oakland lawyer hired to represent her, did
not concede that Soliah and Olson were the same person, but said in
a statement that charges filed in 1976 might have been politically
motivated and without basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are allegations which arose at a time in our history of
intense scrutiny of all political activists,'' Jordan said. At the
time, ``overreaction on the part of law enforcement . . . was not
unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   California Gov. Gray Davis is expected to file an extradition
request soon and Minnesota's Gov. Jesse Ventura is expected to
approve it.
</P>
<P>
   Soliah refused in court to waive extradition proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   During the brief hearing, District Judge Kathleen Gearin ordered
that Soliah be held without bail pending resolution of whether the
alleged crimes in California were bailable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   She continued the case until July 15, although action on Davis'
expected extradition request could come sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The potential sentence is life imprisonment with possibility of
parole, but legal experts say faded memories of witnesses and the
easing of any public outrage could lead to a plea bargain.
</P>
</TEXT>
