<P>
   In a TIMELY commentary titled ``THE POWER OF LETTERS,'' writer
Joyce Maynard responds to the controversy surrounding her decision
to sell 14 letters written to her by J.D. Salinger when she was 18
years old. The letters are scheduled to be auctioned off at
Sotheby's on Tue., June 22.
</P>
<P>
   This special commentary is available for purchase exclusively
from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... My choice to break a quarter-century-long silence
concerning my relationship with Salinger has unleashed accusations
of exploitation and betrayal made all the more outrageous, in the
eyes of my critics, because the one whose privacy I am charged with
violating is a man whose reclusiveness has become an American
legend,'' Maynard writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the sale of Salinger's letters, I mean to lay to rest an
event that has haunted me all my adult life. Before I close this
chapter, though, I want to explain my actions ...''
</P>
