<SLUG> BC-BORDER-CAMERAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DEPLOYS NEW EYES ALONG BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ The U.S. government is installing cameras at
border points in Texas to track fugitives and stolen cars by
scanning the license plates of all vehicles entering or leaving the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras, which are being set up from Brownsville to El Paso,
will automatically scan the front and rear license plates and feed
the information into a national law enforcement database in
Newington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras, which cost approximately $60,000 each, could boost
the ability of the U.S. Customs Service and Immigration and
Naturalization Service to track when and where travelers have
entered or left the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it will better give us an opportunity to identify
people coming through who are not doing the right thing,'' Joe
O'Gorman, chief of land border passenger processing for Customs,
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras are mounted on six-foot poles and can read license
plates of cars traveling as fast as 50 mph, according to Customs.
</P>
<P>
   Images of the license plate numbers would be digitalized and
bounced to the Virginia database where they would be checked
against information on suspected fugitives, smugglers and other
criminals, as well as stolen vehicles, O'Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
   At present, border guards in Texas manually punch into computers
the license plate numbers of people entering the country, but no
information is gathered on traffic headed south, O'Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras could speed up border crossings, but that is not the
principal purpose of the equipment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Border guards are already using the cameras in Southern
California and the devices are expected to be operational as soon
as next week in El Paso, O'Gorman said.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, officials expect the cameras to be
operational at nearly all of the U.S.-Mexico border ports of entry.
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol, which is part of the INS, already has cameras
and sensors installed along the Rio Grande that detect footsteps
and vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   There is not universal acceptance of the technology.
</P>
<P>
   In Laredo, City Councilman Louis Bruni said he supports efforts
to improve security, but is concerned about the increasing law
enforcement presence along the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I fear is that we are turning into a police state _
it is extremely scary,'' Bruni said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see why the federal government wants these things for
national security, but it is frightening we have arrived at this
point,'' Bruni said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1431EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
