r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     06-18 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT GRAMPS OR A 14-YEAR-OLD?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I'm a 77-year-old computer neophyte. (My kids
gave me this PC to drive me out of my mind. I keep a 2-pound sledge
beside me, and one day _ kapow! _ out of my misery!!) I've started
getting a screen from the ``content adviser'' on America Online
blocking Web sites because the sites were not rated and a
supervisor's password was needed. I've talked to AOL three times.
</P>
<P>
   _ Access Denied
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DENIED: You know, you'd think AOL would have known the
answer since it is its program that's giving you fits. Or maybe AOL
thinks you really enjoy listening to Muzak while you're on infinity
hold.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it sounds as though you're running up against the filter
that was intended for horndog teen-agers looking for naked pictures
of Star Trek: Voyager's Seven of Nine _ at least those teen-agers
with parents responsible enough to enable the filter.
</P>
<P>
   An AOL account can have multiple users with different screen
names, but only the big honcho who first set up the account _ and,
since a credit card was required, is presumably at least 18 _ can
adjust the parental controls. I'm guessing your kids set you up as
a peon on their account.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that what you've been trying to look at is dirty. At
least that's what we'll tell the kids. The sites probably don't
carry any of the embedded information AOL is looking for in order
to rate them. If it doesn't know for sure, stuff gets blocked.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell right away if you're the boss. Just go to the
parental controls part of the member setup and try to change your
login to 18-plus. Or have those rotten kids do it.
</P>
<P>
   If you're the only user of the account, and you're already set
to 18-plus, then something is goobered up elsewhere. I'd uninstall
AOL to wipe out any bogus settings, then reinstall the latest
version. And if that doesn't work, I'd guilt the kids into getting
you an account with a real Internet service provider instead of
depending on AOL's gateway to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: My 56K modem connects to AOL at around 28K.
Only rarely do I get anything above 30K. My neighbors have no
trouble connecting at 56K.
</P>
<P>
   _ Slow Burn
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BURN: Almost nobody connects at 56K. There are too many
things out there conspiring to slow you down. I feel lucky to get
on at 31.2 from home, and I'm using the finest equipment I could
hide in my briefcase on the way home from the office. Maybe you
should ignore that last part.
</P>
<P>
   You might have cruddy wiring in your house. Maybe you have a
cheap modem with out-of-date brains. Maybe you're dialing into a
lousy connection. Maybe the modem you're connecting with is limited
to 28.8. Maybe you have bad karma.
</P>
<P>
   Haul your rig next door where they supposedly get 56K
connections and see what happens. That should narrow things down.
Or try dialing other 56K modems, like the one on 3Com's bulletin
board ( (847) 262-6000). You may just have to live with 28.8. It
isn't really that horrendous. You kids today are just spoiled. In
my day, we downloaded barefoot all day at 300 baud, and we never
complained. We made our own electricity with hand cranks and
coconut shells filled with salt water, and when that didn't work,
we'd hook up our telegraph keys, which in those days were called
hyperambulatators, to the streetcar combine's secret Tesla coil
flux generators. ...
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay has obviously gone off
on another rant. His editors have thoughtfully cut him off. He'll
just think he ran long again. Reach him at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101 in case you've
forgotten Morse code, or fax: (817) 390-7257. In real life, he is
Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
