<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0878 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT19-COX     06-18 2230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, June 19,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   G8-KOSOVO _ COLOGNE, Germany _ At the opening of the Group of
Eight summit meeting here on Friday, National Security Advisor
Samuel E. Berger said the White House still is uncertain, a week
after the fact, why Russian troops deployed to Kosovo and what it
says about the state of Russian President Boris Yeltsin's control
there. The Clinton administration feels the troop decision was made
amid a fog of uncertainty inside Moscow and, as a result, the
United States is no longer sure quite what it's dealing with. Will
fold in the day's other developments out of Helsinki and Cologne,
including details on a massive (approaching $50 billion) debt
relief program. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-G8 _ COLOGNE, Germany _ Bouyed by his leadership of a
NATO win in Kosovo, the strongest American economy in a generation
and the fading echoes of his House impeachment six months ago
Saturday, President Clinton is projecting an air of fresh authority
at the annual summit of seven of the world's most powerful heads of
state. Walking tall among his counterparts, Clinton appeared
comfortably in control of the agenda Friday, as the G-7 leaders
opened a weekend of talks on issues ranging from Balkans
reconstruction to debt
</P>
<P>
   relief for developing countries. And he drew one accolade after
another from his fellow heads of state for his role in leading his
NATO partners in the coalition air war against Yugoslavia's bloody
repression in Kosovo. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-G8 _ MOSCOW _ If the Group of Eight industrialized
nations were a country club, Russia would be like the annoying
member who cannot afford to pay the dues, but dominates the debate
during the club meeting. Turbulent relations between Russia and the
world's seven richest nations threaten to overshadow the three-day
summit of the G-8, which opened Friday in Cologne, Germany. Russian
President Boris Yeltsin is not scheduled to arrive at the summit
until Sunday. (Holmes, Cox News Service) 30.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-QUAKE _ PUEBLA, Mexico _ Many of the buildings damaged
here in Tuesday's earthquake are colonial architectural jewels that
date back hundreds of years. The temblar raises questions about the
future of structures in Puebla and other cities. Loosened by the
earthquake, chunks of brick and plaster were thrown from the
baroque cupolas' graceful arches, landing on a cracked floor at the
state university of Puebla. Stunned by the death of 17 people in
the region _ a toll that was expected to rise _ residents of this
city of 1.2 million also mourned the damage to buildings whose
baroque, renaissance and Arabic-influenced architecture have been a
source of pride and a draw for tourists from around the world.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL-WEDDING _ How Sophie's wedding, which is today, compares
with Di's, Fergie's, Anne's and Liz's. The frock, the ring, the
this, the that. Fun stuff! (Grantham, Palm Beach Post). WITH
6-COLUMN CHART.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA _ VERDAN, Yugoslavia _ German soldiers detained 25
ethnic Albanian rebels today after finding one elderly man dead and
more than 15 others hurt in a police station that had been under
control of the Kosovo Liberation Army since early this week. Most
of the victims seemed to be ethnic Albanians or Gypsies between the
ages of 50 and 60, said Lt. Col. Dietmar Jeserich, a spokesman for
the German army serving in the Kosovo peace force in the region.
The Kosovo Liberation Army moved Friday to repair its ties with
U.S. peacekeepers by promising to release five kidnapped hostages
who it described as Serb war criminals. A KLA brigade commander
said in an interview that he had told the top U.S. commander of the
82nd Airborne Division that from now on he was going to leave it up
to NATO investigate war crimes. Even with this development, NATO
faces problems trying to keep peace between the KLA and the Serbs.
In one region with 43 villages and 56,000 people, Americans are
making do with only 200 peacekeepers. (Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RAPE _ PEC, Yugoslavia _ At the Hotel Karagac here,
mentioned prominently in the U.S. State Department's report on Serb
atrocities in Kosovo as the site of a ``rape camp,'' there are
small signs of the horrors that are believed to have taken place.
But NATO peacekeepers have yet to investigate the hotel because
it's ``low on their priority list'' the Kosovo Liberation Army and
Serb troops are still fighting on the roads around it. Developing.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SOLAR _ WASHINGTON _ The Smithsonian Institution kicks off a
traveling exhibition, ``Under the Sun: An Outdoor Exhibition of
Light,'' which features ``sunlight-powered high-tech devices on the
cutting edge of consumer-friendly, environmentally sensitive
design.'' (Hill, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: To move Wednesday, June 16.
</P>
<P>
   GUNS _ WASHINGTON _ Coverage of House debate on gun control: The
House is ready to pass a gun bill that President Clinton calls a
``great victory for the NRA.'' Then will come negotiations between
House members and senators who voted for tougher controls.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WICCANS _ The witches of Fort Hood, under fire from the
religious right, hold a nighttime ceremony in support of religious
tolerance. The witches are going beyond Fort Hood: A national pagan
prayer circle for religious tolerance sponored by the Military
Pagan Network is scheduled for June 28 at the Jefferson Memorial in
Washington, D.C. (Perkes, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The ritual begins at 9 p.m. EDT. Austin expects to file
shortly thereafter with news and color top on background material
written earlier in the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE _ They couldn't stop the poop from getting in the water,
so now federal regulators are considering weakening the rules on
Florida utilities' widespread practice of pumping treated sewage
deep underground - waste that the feds acknowledge is seeping into
potential drinking water supplies. The U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency says the rules may be unreasonably strict, since
Florida's geology makes it impossible to guarantee that the waste
won't escape upward from the depths of the Floridan Aquifier. The
EPA insists it would make sure none of the waste is dangerous by
the time it reaches drinking water. But the idea horrifies
environmentalists. ``EPA's proposed solution is to legalize the
contamination rather than prevent it,'' says Suzi Ruhl of the Legal
Environmental Assistance Foundation, which has been fighting for
years to rein in the underground injections. Waste has shown up in
shallower monitor wells of Seacoast Utilities in northern Palm
Beach County and other areas around Flroida. (King, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM-RIDERS _ ATLANTA _ In 1964, civil rights freedom rider
James Earl Chaney and two others were killed in Meridian, Miss.,
while advocating for black suffrage in the South. This week, the
freedom riders are riding again, in the form of the Unity
Coalition, to introduce a new generation to Chaney's struggle for
civil rights. We'll accompany them as they pass through Atlanta and
find out what their goals are and how they are working to achieve
them. (Rodriguez, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY-GEORGIA _ Georgia political react to national gambling
study report due out Friday. Report may call for some form of
federal oversight of lotteries, some state officials fear. They
don't want that. (Mantius, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BULLOCK-OBIT _ AUSTIN _ Two unavoidable cliches: Former Lt. Gov.
Bob Bullock really was larger than life. And his death really does
mark the end of an era. Bullock died Friday morning at home,
surrounded by family. A first-generation Texan, Bullock fiercely
embraced the state's colorful history and did more than his part to
preserve and contribute to it. His temper could melt a brass
doorknob, but he was considerate of his friends. He could be
courtly and combative, gentlemanly and lewd, magnanimous and
unforgiving, humble and intimidating, persuasive and threatening _
all within seconds. He also pushed through monumental programs _
changing everything from the way Texas collects taxes to how it
funds its schools _ and never shied from a little political
bloodletting for what he believed to be in the best interest of
Texans. (Beach, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BULLOCK-HIGHLIGHTS _ Time line of Bullock's life. (McCarthy,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BULLOCK-ACHIEVE _ Bullock's accomplishments. (Reynolds, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BULLOCK-REACT _ Reaction quotes, with mugs. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BULLOCK-MCNEELY _ Column for op-ed page. (McNeely, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   NOTE TO TEXAS EDITORS: Austin expects to move this package by 5
p.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   FAULDER-SCENE _ HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Described by prison
officials as being peaceful and calm, Joseph Stanley Faulder, 61,
became the first Canadian executed in the United States in 47 years
on Thursday. ``He said he was at peace with his maker and ready to
go, and one way or another, he would be set free tonight,'' Texas
Department of Criminal Justice Public Information Officer Larry
Todd said. Faulder was sentenced to die by lethal injection for the
beating and stabbing death of 75-year-old Inez Phillips during a
1975 robbery of her home in Gladewater. (Longview News-Journal).
</P>
<P>
   BKN-FINALS-WAGERS _ U.S. Sen. Phil Gramm fired the first salvo
from his Washington office.''Eat our dust, city boy,'' he said to
his New York counterpart, Sen. Charles Schumer. ``And hey, what the
heck is a Knick anyhow?'' Schumer, fired back as quickly as a Texas
outlaw: ``Ask Larry Bird what a Knick is, senator. I'm sure they
have a clear idea.'' He then went on to call the San Antonio Spurs,
who are currently tangling with the New York Knicks for the
National Basketball Association Championship, ``those
tumbleweeds.'' Since the series began, harsh words and wagers have
been flying between the Empire State and the Lone Star state like
bullets in pistol duels. Gov. Bush is betting Gov. Pataki, and
mayors from New York and San Antonio are also laying it on the
line. (Davenport, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKGAME-PROBE _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ A small company set up to
sell black-achievement board games _ and losing about $1 million a
year _ has assumed a curious place in a probe of a sports agent's
alleged gifts to University of Florida players of cash and cars.
BAOA Inc.'s stockholders include Rev. Jesse Jackson, who said
Thursday that as far as he knew, sports agent and BAOA director
William ``Tank'' Black never used the company as a slush fund to
buy gifts for clients. (Dolch/Elmore, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TX-NATGUARD-BOSNIA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Army National Guard
soldiers, including several units based in Austin, have begun
training for deployment early next year to the NATO peacekeeping
mission in Bosnia. (Kelley, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GUN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Guns rival boots, barbecue and pickup
trucks as emblems of the Lone Star State. But as Republican George
W. Bush attempts to move from the Governor's Mansion to the White
House, Democrats are poised to make gun laws that are popular in
Texas a liability for Bush in a national campaign. (Greenberger,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
