<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PROFILE-SHORT-CO     06-18 2884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-SHORT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    The First Son: A profile of George W. Bush
 &HT;    (For Sunday, June 20. Package includes BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE1,
BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE2, BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE3, BUSH-TIMELINE-COX
and photos. A shorter version of the profile is moving as
BUSH-PROFILE-SHORT-COX. This version is also available for sale as
a full-page layout at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Inculcated, that was the word George Bush used.
He said he had the drive to serve inculcated into him by his
father, the future senator from Connecticut, Prescott Bush, who
believed in noblesse oblige, believed it was the solemn obligation
of the elite to serve for the greater societal good. The future
senator inculcated that belief into his second son, the future
president, George Herbert Walker Bush. That son went off to West
Texas, and he raised a family and did some inculcating of his own.
In those days, when the Kennedys reigned as American royalty, the
senior senator's son was on occasion heard to say, ``Just wait till
I turn these Bush boys out.''
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of those Bush boys _ George Dubya, as he is known in
Texas _ is poised to continue the family tradition. After months of
conspicuously not running for president, he finally made it clear
in Iowa last Saturday that he is seeking the office.
</P>
<P>
   The first election of the 21st century then, we currently
assume, may be The Clash of the Scions, Al Gore vs. George W. Bush.
One, Gore, went to Vietnam and didn't fight; the other, Bush, flew
fighter jets and didn't go to Vietnam. One toked a little pot; the
other declines to give a full accounting of his youthful
indiscretions and emphatically considers the matter closed. The
public perceives one as exuding the charisma and warmth of a cheap
Formica countertop; the other is regarded, even by his frustrated
political enemies, as impossible to personally dislike. One has
spent decades being groomed for this moment; the other has
strenuously spent at least the last year not running for president,
listening to the whole world tell him it's his to lose.
</P>
<P>
   From New Haven to Midland
</P>
<P>
   George Walker Bush was born in New Haven, Conn., on July 6,
1946.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bushes moved to Midland, Texas, in 1950, it was still a
small town. Barbara Bush gave birth to John Ellis Bush, the future
governor of Florida whom the family would call Jebbie, in February
1953. (Two other Bush boys, Marvin and Neil, as well as a daughter,
Doro, would follow.) But a family tragedy loomed, too: Pauline
Robinson Bush, George W.'s younger sister, would die of leukemia in
October before her 4th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The elder George Bush was in Houston by the time he ran for the
U.S. Senate against Ralph Yarborough in 1964. Yarborough wouldn't
debate, so Bush and his pal Martin Allday came up with the famous
empty-chair debates, with a tape recording on a chair sitting in
for Yarborough. They got a lot of mileage out of that, but LBJ was
in the White House by then and his coattails stretched from El Paso
to Nacogdoches.
</P>
<P>
   Young George W., when home on break from Andover, sat in on
strategy meetings. And on election night, in the Houston ballroom
his dad had rented for the victory reception that never happened,
young George W. wept.
</P>
<P>
   George W. went to prep school in Massachusetts. He enrolled in
Phillips Academy, which sits atop a long, gradual hill stretching
through Andover. Think of one of those perennially autumnal places,
hundreds of acres of trees and brick and scowling faculty who are
addressed as ``sir.''
</P>
<P>
   Morning chapel was mandatory, as was jacket and tie. The class
work was unrelenting. Fear, intimidation and humiliation were
trusted teaching tools.
</P>
<P>
   Also, no girls. The educational wisdom of the day maintained
that a boy could not have a top-notch education bludgeoned _
inculcated _ into him while in the agitating presence of the fair
sex.
</P>
<P>
   Young George was a social creature, one who went out of his way
to make everybody comfortable. It was here that Bush honed an
essential political skill: getting along with everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Bush roommate John Kidde: ``George and I played sports _ I
played a lot of sports _ and there are some kids at Andover who are
not very outgoing or socially dialed-in, nerds or whatever you want
to call them. I remember two or three of us would be getting lunch
and there'd be Joe Blow, one of the straight-A students who never
talked and nobody socialized with him, and we'd sit down and start
talking and George would make a joke or a comment and always bring
this guy into the conversation, make him a part of the group. He
was real good at that. He always made people feel very comfortable
around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his kind nature, Bush was known as ``Lip'' for his
lightning wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was quick with a quip,'' said Jack Morrison, a close
friend from Andover and Yale. ``He always had a twinkle in his eye
and a ready retort in his mouth. He often got the last word in.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior year was when boys found whether they were going to their
first-choice college. Like the old man, George W. Bush was going to
Yale.
</P>
<P>
   The summer of '68
</P>
<P>
   At Yale, where he would earn a degree in history, they all
seemed to love George W. Everybody except John Lincoln, who lived
across the hall from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was a member of Deke, the fraternity known to be the
drinking fraternity,'' Lincoln said. Nor did Lincoln, a computer
graphic artist, find the younger Bush's intellect to be formidable.
When word of Bush's White House ambition got out, ``I said to
myself, `You know, he's not all that smart.' Which is maybe what
the job takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush and the boys let the good times roll, Morrison says: ``The
things I remember are the times we would go on road trips and just
be weak with laughter,'' said Morrison, a partner in a private
investment firm in Minneapolis. ``We'd pile into a car and head off
to some girls' school up north. Never really got in any serious
trouble at all, but came close a couple of times. There were a
couple of times when you could say we probably consumed more than
we should have, but nothing terribly serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, out in the world, everything was out of the ordinary.
Vietnam, or how to avoid it, was the topic of every other
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   If political ambition beat in George W. Bush's breast at Yale,
it was well-concealed. George's passions, despite his father's
political proclivities, were sports and beer. And fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the Reserves
</P>
<P>
   The document is on Air Force letterhead, dated 7 October 1968.
``The Secretary of the Air Force has directed me to inform you
that, by direction of the President, you are tendered an indefinite
term appointment as a Reserve officer of the Air Force.''
</P>
<P>
   He trained until June 1970, then assumed reserve status in the
Texas Air National Guard, flying F-102 fighters out of Ellington
Air Force Base. George W. Bush was 23, a first lieutenant and a
hotshot.
</P>
<P>
   Young men were getting creative in handling the Vietnam problem.
Hockey saved Morrison. He made the 1968 Olympic team, and the
powers that be decided he'd be better off doing battle on the ice
rather than in the rice paddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the things that makes me a little uncomfortable,''
said Morrison, who served in a reserve unit. ``I sometimes feel I
should have gone to Vietnam. Because I happened to be a good hockey
player, I was able to avoid that. At the time I was delighted _ I'd
just married and had a young child, so I didn't especially want to
go get shot at. And I think George may feel the same way a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably as close as we'll get to how Bush feels about
Vietnam. Bush has said he did not join the Guard to avoid service
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush requested a discharge from the Texas Air National
Guard on 5 Sept. 73. It was approved a day later, and he was off to
Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   To the oil patch born
</P>
<P>
   Despite his newly minted MBA, the corporate path was not the way
for George W. Bush. He was young, he was cocky, and he'd had a
pretty good independent streak inculcated into him. He went back to
Midland. And when he saw opportunity, he impulsively went after it:
He surprised a number of friends when he ran for Congress in '78.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, then-Democrat Kent Hance, had big fun with Bush's
pedigree and Ivy League book learnin' _ and thereafter Bush threw
himself into the oil business. His father's company had been called
Zapata, so Bush continued the tradition by starting Arbusto,
Spanish for ``bush'' and pronounced ``Ar-BOOST-o.'' But the
infrequent success of the company soon had locals calling the
company Ar-BUST-o, and Bush changed the name to the more pedestrian
but less easily ridiculed Bush Exploration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Bush Exploration folded into Spectrum 7 Energy Corp.,
of Cincinnati, Ohio, and Midland. The move also established a
baseball connection that would in little more than a decade lead to
a big payday for George W. Bush: Spectrum included William DeWitt
Jr., the son of the owner who had built the Cincinnati Reds into
the Big Red Machine.
</P>
<P>
   Although beginning to move in tonier circles, Bush was never
what you'd call a GQ type _ if it matched, it was a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very frugal,'' said Charles Younger, a doctor from
Midland who returned about the same time as Don Evans, now Bush's
campaign finance director. ``He never spent any money. He was
perfectly content in a pair of Levi's and a T-shirt and an old pair
of Chinese house slippers he wore everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He had one dark suit, which he wore to out-of-town meetings up
East with Spectrum geologist Paul Rea. One morning he was supposed
to meet Rea at the airport before dawn. Bush is late, flies out the
door, leaps into his old Buick and takes off and drives into D
Street, which happens to be full of water. The water's so high he
can't even open the driver's door. So Bush rolls down the window
and strips to his boxers, climbs out the window, wades through the
street and starts running back to his house, past the residence of
an early-rising bank president, who chances to begin his day by
observing young George dashing along in his underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's impulsive, impatient,'' Younger said. ``He's a man of
action. He's not gonna sit there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, friends and associates from the Midland days
suggest that the elder Bush, by then the vice president of the
United States, wasn't always delighted with the way the younger
Bush conducted himself. Which is to say nothing of what his mother
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were times they'd rather he maybe bit his tongue
or zipped his mouth,'' Younger said. ``He'd just stay right out
there on the edge. He'd never hop over, but he'd lean over.
Mischievous.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also, let us not forget, Midland's most eligible
bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rarely dated,'' said Joe O'Neill, a friend since preschool.
``He was an early-riser, party-pooper kind of date.''
</P>
<P>
   Younger: ``I doubt if he ever took a girl out more than three or
four times other than Laura. I don't think there was anybody who
caught his attention, to be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Catch his attention she did. The cockiness throttled way back
when he was around Laura, and George W. Bush seemed almost . . .
reserved. They were engaged five weeks after they met, and married
in the First Methodist Church in downtown Midland, Laura's family
church _ right in the middle of W.'s run for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Laura, a calming influence on all those around her, did some
inculcating. George was the same old George, just not cranked all
the way up.
</P>
<P>
   The recrafting
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford English Dictionary, second edition, defines
``inculcate'' thus: ``To endeavor to force (a thing) into or
impress (it) on the mind of another by emphatic admonition, or by
persistent repetition; to urge on the mind, esp. as a principle, an
opinion, or a matter of belief; to teach forcibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine this inculcation of the need to serve, something George
W. inherited just as he inherited the grin and the eyebrows from
preceding generations. Imagine that this trait is like any other
genetic propensity. At some point in one's life, a switch flips,
cells begin dividing and before long a fully inculcated George W.
Bush emerges as The Son Who Will Serve the Father, a Sonny Corleone
type whose volatility sometimes gets the best of his judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the inculcation, he may well have stayed in
Midland, continuing his modestly successful business career. But he
answered the call, and a newer, more mature George W. Bush emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Rough around the edges? Yes and no. Somebody was dressing him
better, but Bush still had plenty of Midland in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was working for him in '87, he was still chewing
tobacco, which is a pretty gross trait,'' said Deborah Dunn, who
worked for two years as Bush's assistant before becoming director
of the White House Visitors Office and, later, helping run George
W.'s upset of Ann Richards. ``I'd bring in his campaign itinerary,
and stacks of material I'd already sorted through. He didn't want
excessive detail. And by noon, three-quarters of the stuff would be
in the trash can. And here he was chewing tobacco and spitting in
the trash can, and when he'd go for his noon jog I'd be picking the
stuff out of the trash can and I'd think, `You couldn't have read
this.' But he had, and picked out the facts and put it somewhere in
his mind and moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember the '88 convention? It seemed like half the delegates
in the hall were Bushes, but it was George W. who gave Texas to the
old man, thereby giving the old man the nomination. A great
dynastic moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Natural
</P>
<P>
   He loved baseball _ always said he wanted to play like Willie
Mays when he was a younger man. After he and Laura and the girls
moved to Dallas, darned if he didn't jump in on a deal to buy the
Texas Rangers. He put up $606,000 _ chump change compared with the
other partners _ but he'd get 20 times that on the back end in a
few years. They make him general manager, and there he is running
the team. This is the best job in the whole world for George W.
Bush, who gets along with everybody, knows the office people and
the groundskeeper and the hot-dog vendor, signs autographs and
chats up fans and players. A $200,000 salary (what the president
pulls down) and part ownership in the team _ to watch baseball!
</P>
<P>
   Former Spectrum 7 partner Rea: ``George felt like to get into
politics you needed some personal money, and that was his goal _ to
make enough money where his family would be comfortable and he
wouldn't be beholden to special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   There was quiet talk of running George W. Bush against Richards
in '90 _ Richards went after Dad with that ``poor George'' riff at
the '88 convention, about how ``Poppy'' Bush was ``born with a
silver foot in his mouth.'' Wouldn't it be nice to step up and boot
her out of the governor's office? But George W. didn't run _ told
Rea his mother didn't want him to, for one thing.
</P>
<P>
   When the first son did take on Richards, in '94, she let him
have it. Dubya took the jabs and kept smiling. Richards would say
Bush was a failed businessman; Bush would mourn the governor's
compulsive use of ``personal attacks.'' Richards noted Bush had
never before held elected office; Bush wore his inexperience as a
badge of honor. Morrison says Bush's conduct in the campaign
against Richards showed maturity and clarity of purpose: ``She just
savaged him, and he just killed her with kindness.''
</P>
<P>
   So when he was young and irresponsible and cocky, he was young
and irresponsible and cocky. Now he's mature and responsible and,
well, his friend and former business partner K. Michael Conaway
uses the word ``mercurial,'' meaning volatile. Hot-headed.
</P>
<P>
   He does not suffer fools. He has little time for dissent, and
none whatsoever for disloyalty. He was the loyalty enforcer for his
dad and has continued, as governor, to demand tributes from his
allies, who are expected to cough up money and salute smartly.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's the characterization of Tom Pauken, a onetime
state Republican chairman whose run for attorney general was
derailed by Bush loyalists _ and one of the few Texas Republicans
publicly critical of the popular governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know what moves the governor,'' Pauken said.
</P>
<P>
   So why's he running?
</P>
<P>
   Pauken: ``I guess to follow Bill Clinton after Clinton defeated
his father would prove something.''
</P>
<P>
   The assumption of George W. Bush
</P>
<P>
   A second President Bush seems to be a foregone conclusion. The
belief that the 2000 election has an inevitable conclusion _ let's
just go ahead and call it manifest destiny _ has been thoroughly
inculcated into the electorate and the media.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can catch him, the media seem to be saying, and he hasn't
even officially declared.
</P>
<P>
   All he needs to do is say so. All we need to know is who he is.
With his campaign swing through Iowa and New Hampshire this month,
George W. Bush took his first tentative steps, and the process of
getting to know him is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
