<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE     06-18 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    A look at George W. Bush
 &HT;    (For Sunday, June 20. Package includes BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE1,
BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE2, BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE3, BUSH-TIMELINE-COX
and photos. A shorter version of the profile is moving as
BUSH-PROFILE-SHORT-COX. This version is also available for sale as
a full-page layout at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   ... with kindness.
</P>
<P>
   The mercurial George W.
</P>
<P>
   So when he was young and irresponsible and cocky, he was young
and irresponsible and cocky. Now he's mature and responsible and,
well, his friend and former business partner K. Michael Conaway
uses the word ``mercurial,'' meaning volatile. Hot-headed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his best efforts, it leaks out sometimes publicly.
Reporters often don't finish asking their questions before he
starts answering them, but if a reporter steps on one of his
answers, Bush is likely to lower his head and politely seethe,
``May I finish, please?'' He's like this privately, too; his allies
say it's because he's so well-prepared and moves so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time when a bunch of Canadian reporters were
whining about the planned execution of one of their own, Joseph
Stanley Faulder. When Bush was asked what he would say to the
charge that Texas' enthusiastic application of the needle gave the
state a sort of Wild West air, the governor let fly, ``If you're
Canadian and you come to our state, don't murder anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   He's tamped down that habit of launching strategic zingers, but
the noncampaign will be a long one. At some point, the Lip will
prevail.
</P>
<P>
   He does not suffer fools. He has little time for dissent, and
none whatsoever for disloyalty. He was the loyalty enforcer for his
dad and has continued, as governor, to demand tributes from his
allies, who are expected to cough up money and salute smartly.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's the characterization of Tom Pauken, a onetime
state Republican chairman whose run for attorney general was
derailed by Bush loyalists _ and one of few Texas Republicans
publicly critical of the popular governor.
</P>
<P>
   True, Pauken is a conservative Christian whose ideological tent
wasn't big enough for a Republican like George W. Bush _ the kind
who can win elections. But the conflict seemed to him at its root
personal: Pauken didn't support George Bush in his '88 run for
president, and George W. ``expressed his disappointment with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years later Bush was governor and in a position to once
again express his disappointment with Pauken, which he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're supposed to salute,'' he said. ``If you don't salute
you're an opponent. And Karl Rove, the political genius of the Bush
operation, is very single-minded as far as making anybody pay a
price who's not 100 percent on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Pauken's Machiavellian interpretation of the Rove-Bush dynamic
is a popular one: Rove is the mechanic, this reading goes; Bush is
simply pointed in the right direction and instructed to flash that
big, famous mug _ George W. Bush as anti-wonk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know what moves the governor,'' Pauken said.
</P>
<P>
   So why's he running?
</P>
<P>
   Pauken: ``I guess to follow Bill Clinton after Clinton defeated
his father would prove something.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling Presidential
</P>
<P>
   Before the legislative session ended Memorial Day, Bush went to
great effort to appear focused on the state's business. Before the
session began, he was a cautious man, doing the political math and
keeping the Lip on a tight leash. He even refused to state a
position on whether he would dance with Laura at the inaugural
balls. (He did.) Public appearances were tightly scripted and
usually ceremonial. He had hardly a word to say about any national
issue, and anyway he was too busy to be as available to the press
as he'd been before. Meanwhile, Republican big shots from across
the country were double-parked on the streets around the governor's
mansion, delivering gifts of gold, frankincense and myrrh.
</P>
<P>
   The only flashes of spontaneity were at bill signings, where
Bush would take a few questions. He's got most of the capitol press
well-trained by now. He greets favored ones with exaggerated
deference and chummy nicknames; once, alluding to his habit of
rushing through everything, even signing his name, he joked to a TV
camerawoman, ``I understand you've requested a slow signing.''
Everybody had a nice chuckle at that one.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional arena for these episodes was the governor's
press conference room, a functional but unsexy space with bright
lights and a riser in back for the TV cameras. But on May 25, the
morning the Cox report was released, Bush's meeting with the press
was moved from there _ the previously stated location _ to the
governor's reception room next door. That room is as grand and
dignified as the press conference room is utilitarian. George W.
Bush acknowledged that the Lege was still steaming along and that
he had some time before his victory-lap-slash-summer-tour, but he
had something to say and he was going to say it in a stately
setting in front of the gathered TV cameras and it was this:
</P>
<P>
   He was firmly opposed to China stealing American nuclear
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The Assumption of George W. Bush
</P>
<P>
   ``Inculcate'' comes from the Latin inculcatus, meaning to tread
down or trample underfoot. It means to impress upon the mind via
frequent repetition _ the old-fashioned, rote way of learning. The
belief that the 2000 election has an inevitable conclusion _ let's
just go ahead and call it manifest destiny _ has been thoroughly
inculcated into the electorate and the media. A second President
Bush is considered a foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can catch him, the media seem to be saying, and he hasn't
even officially declared.
</P>
<P>
   All he needs to do is say so. All we need to know is who he is.
With his campaign swing through Iowa and New Hampshire beginning
last Saturday, George W. Bush took his first tentative steps, and
the process of getting to know him is under way.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
