</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    A look at George W. Bush
 &HT;    (For Sunday, June 20. Package includes BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE1,
BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE2, BUSH-PROFILE-COX-TAKE3, BUSH-TIMELINE-COX
and photos. A shorter version of the profile is moving as
BUSH-PROFILE-SHORT-COX. This version is also available for sale as
a full-page layout at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   ... And fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the Reserves
</P>
<P>
   The document is on Air Force letterhead, dated 7 October 1968.
``The Secretary of the Air Force has directed me to inform you
that, by direction of the President, you are tendered an indefinite
term appointment as a Reserve officer of the Air Force.''
</P>
<P>
   He trained until June 1970, then assumed reserve status in the
Texas Air National Guard, flying F-102 fighters out of Ellington
Air Force Base. George W. Bush was 23, a first lieutenant and
thoroughly a hotshot. He was also the son of U.S. Rep. George Bush,
who was again aiming to snatch a Senate seat away from Ralph
Yarborough. (Democrat Lloyd Bentsen would knock Yarborough out in
the primary, then defeat Bush.)
</P>
<P>
   George W. was a commendable pilot, according to his service
record, and he liked it, according to a Texas Air National Guard
press release that began: ``George Walker Bush is one member of the
younger generation who doesn't get his kicks from pot or hashish or
speed. Oh, he gets high, all right, but not from narcotics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighters are it,'' Bush was quoted as saying. ``I've always
wanted to be a fighter pilot and I wouldn't want to fly anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Young men were getting very creative in handling the Vietnam
problem. Hockey saved Jack Morrison, Bush's friend from Andover and
Yale. He made the 1968 Olympic team, and the powers that be decided
he'd be better off doing battle on the ice rather than in the rice
paddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the things that makes me a little uncomfortable,''
said Morrison, who served in a reserve unit. ``I sometimes feel I
should have gone to Vietnam. Because I happened to be a good hockey
player, I was able to avoid that. At the time I was delighted _ I'd
just married and had a young child, so I didn't especially want to
go get shot at. And I think George may feel the same way a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   That's as close as we'll probably get to how Bush feels about
Vietnam. Bush has said he did not join the Guard to avoid service
in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush requested a discharge from the Texas Air National
Guard on 5 Sept. 73. It was approved a day later, and he was off to
Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   To the Oil Patch Born: Boom and Arbusto
</P>
<P>
   The corporate path was not the way for George W. Bush. He was
young, he was cocky, and he'd had a pretty good independent streak
inculcated into him. He went back to Midland. And when he saw
opportunity, he impulsively went after it: He surprised a number of
friends when he ran for Congress in '78.
</P>
<P>
   His opponent, then-Democrat Kent Hance, had great fun with
Bush's pedigree and Ivy League book learnin' _ and thereafter Bush
threw himself into the oil business. He'd gone to see his dad's
friend, Martin Allday, who told him his high-priced Harvard MBA had
some holes in it _ he needed to learn the ways of the land man,
chasing titles and mineral leases and chatting up the clerks in
county courthouses. His father's company had been called Zapata, so
Bush continued the tradition by starting Arbusto, Spanish for
``bush'' and pronounced ``Ar-BOOST-o.'' As in common in the oil
business, Bush was gambling with other people's money besides his
own: His Wall Street-connected uncle had lined up a stable of
wealthy investors willing to take a chance on the novice
entrepreneur. But the infrequent success of the company soon had
local wits calling the concern Ar-BUST-o, and Bush changed the name
to the more pedestrian but less easily ridiculed Bush Exploration.
</P>
<P>
   He still had that stunning capacity for remembering names and
faces. And he remembered more than the names and faces of people
who could help him. He knew the cleaning lady at the office and the
booth attendant at the parking garage and the Odessa roughnecks on
the rigs. He knew everybody, got along with everybody and wasn't
running for anything.
</P>
<P>
   The mergers continued, like little Russian nesting dolls getting
gobbled by the next one. In 1984, Bush Exploration folded into
Spectrum 7 Energy Corp., of Cincinnati, Ohio, and Midland. The move
also established a baseball connection that would in little more
than a decade lead to a big payday for George W. Bush: Spectrum
included William DeWitt Jr., the son of the owner who had built the
Cincinnati Reds into the Big Red Machine.
</P>
<P>
   Although beginning to move in tonier circles, Bush was never
what you'd call a GQ type _ if it matched, it was a miracle. Some
of the boys in Midland had a golf tournament every year, and the
gag prize for the worst-dressed contestant was prime selections
from the George W. Bush wardrobe, polyester pants and a selection
of shirts. Bob Blake in Lubbock dragged Bush into Malouf's Fine
Apparel for Men and Women, the finest clothier there, and bought
him his running-for-Congress suit. An uncle in St. Louis would send
him his discarded shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very frugal,'' said Charles Younger, an M.D. from
Midland who returned about the same time as Bush and Don Evans, now
Bush's campaign finance director. ``He never spent any money. He
was perfectly content in a pair of Levi's and a T-shirt and an old
pair of Chinese house slippers he wore everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He had one dark suit, which he wore to out-of-town meetings up
East with Spectrum geologist Paul Rea. One morning he's supposed to
meet Rea at the airport before dawn and they're going to catch a
flight somewhere. Bush is late, flying out the door, leaps into his
old Buick and takes off and drives into D Street, which happens to
be full of water, which is pretty much what happens on D Street in
Midland when it rains, because in Midland, when it rains, it
floods, but the sun isn't up and George is in quite a rush, and
here he is with a flooded old Buick. Water's so high he can't even
open the driver's door, and anyway that'd flood the interior. So
Bush rolls down the window and strips to his skivs _ boxers, for
those keeping score _ climbs out the window, wades through the
street and starts running back to his house, past the residence of
an early-rising bank president, who chances to begin his day by
observing young George dashing along in his underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's impulsive, impatient,'' Younger said. ``He's a man of
action. He's not gonna sit there.''
</P>
<P>
   And he ran hard. Evans and Bush would meet at Younger's office
for noon runs _ not terribly long, maybe three or four miles, but
grueling. When Bush set the pace, the three of them did six-minute
miles. Maybe 6 1/2 minutes if George took pity. ``Lord, he was
brutal,'' Younger said. ``We kept up with him for a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Carousing? In West Texas? Sure. Miller Lite was the default
adult beverage. He and some friends would head over to the Hector
County Coliseum in Odessa to catch Willie or whoever was passing
through. Rea, his companion on innumerable business trips, never
saw him drunk. Younger saw him pretty close.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would always stay within boundaries, but he'd get on the
edge,'' Younger said.
</P>
<P>
   It messes up the conventional arc of the George W. Bush story _
from unredeemable cad to born-again moral leader _ but during these
purported lost years he was also reading the Bible daily and
attending a businessmen's Bible study group. And when colleague K.
Michael Conaway's wife was dying of leukemia _ the same disease
that had killed Bush's sister three decades earlier _ George W.
would come and take the Conaways' two young sons to baseball games.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, friends and associates from the Midland days
suggest that the elder Bush, by then the vice president of the
United States, wasn't always delighted with the way the first son
conducted himself. Which is to say nothing of what his mother
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were times they'd rather he maybe bit his tongue
or zipped his mouth,'' Younger said. ``He's just stay right out
there on the edge. He'd never hop over, but he'd lean over.
Mischievous.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also, let us not forget, Midland's most eligible
bachelor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rarely dated,'' said Joe O'Neill, a friend since preschool.
``He was an early-riser, party-pooper kind of date.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Younger: ``I doubt if he ever took a girl out more than
three or four times other than Laura. I don't think there was
anybody who caught his attention, to be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Rea and his wife had the cream of Midland's bachelorettes come
to the house to meet Bush: ``There were a lot of ladies here who
wanted to date George,'' he said, ``but I don't think he had a real
girlfriend until he met Laura.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, boy, did he have a girlfriend. The cockiness throttled
way back when he was around Laura, and George W. Bush seemed almost
. . . reserved. They were engaged five weeks after they met, and
married in the First Methodist Church in downtown Midland, Laura's
family church _ right in the middle of W.'s run for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Laura, a calming influence on all those around her, did some
inculcating. George was the same old George, just not cranked all
the way up.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, with the mid-'80s bust looming, Rea and Bush
made a deal to merge Spectrum 7 into Harken Energy Corp. Rea struck
out on his own; Bush, who had a 13.6 percent interest in Spectrum,
didn't get a position with Harken, but he got a chunk of stock and
a seat on the board. Of Spectrum's 15 employees, Harken hired only
one, a land man. George W. Bush went out and found jobs for the
other 12.
</P>
<P>
   The Recrafting
</P>
<P>
   The Oxford English Dictionary, second edition, defines
``inculcate'' thus: ``To endeavor to force (a thing) into or
impress (it) on the mind of another by emphatic admonition, or by
persistent repetition; to urge on the mind, esp. as a principle, an
opinion, or a matter of belief; to teach forcibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine this inculcation of the need to serve, this (by
definition) learned behavior, has developed, over successive
generations of Bushes, a genetic component, something George W.
inherited just as he inherited the grin and the eyebrows from
preceding generations. Imagine that this trait is like any other
genetic propensity. At some point in one's life, say on a blurry
morning after a man's 40th birthday party, a switch flips, cells
begin dividing and before long a fully inculcated George W. Bush
emerges as The Son Who Will Serve the Father, a Sonny Corleone type
whose volatility sometimes gets the best of his judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the inculcation, he may well have stayed in
Midland, continuing his modestly successful business career. But he
answered the call, and a newer, more mature George W. Bush emerged.
</P>
<P>
   He'd quit drinking. Just. Quit. Maybe it wouldn't be an issue if
he hadn't stopped (damned if you drink, damned if you don't),
because Americans find an irresistible mystery in people who drink,
then stop. We think, What else ya got in there?
</P>
<P>
   He helped his dad get elected _ sometimes he was the last person
George Bush consulted before he made a move. George W. went to
Washington to protect his dad and terrorize his enemies. Think a
nice Ivy League boy doesn't have the stuff to get up close like
this and _ bada-bing! _ pull the trigger on John Sununu? Dubya did.
</P>
<P>
   Rough around the edges? Yes and no. Somebody was dressing him
better, but Bush still had plenty of Midland in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was working for him in '87, he was still chewing
tobacco, which is a pretty gross trait,'' said Deborah Dunn, who
worked for two years as Bush's assistant before becoming director
of the White House Visitors Office and, later, helping run George
W.'s upset of Ann Richards. ``I'd bring in his campaign itinerary,
and stacks of material I'd already sorted through. He didn't want
excessive detail. And by noon, three-quarters of the stuff would be
in the trash can. And here he was chewing tobacco and spitting in
the trash can, and when he'd go for his noon jog I'd be picking the
stuff out of the trash can and I'd think, `You couldn't have read
this.' But he had, and picked out the facts and put it somewhere in
his mind and moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   Blustery? Nothing like that doomed bulldog, Lee Atwater, but
sure. Baby-sitting Atwater, in fact, was W.'s job for a time:
``Skeptical in nature, blunt to a fault, Junior was contemptuous of
haughty D.C. insiders,'' John Brady wrote in ``Bad Boy,'' his
Atwater bio. Yes, George W. had a way of making sure no ego soared
too high on that campaign. He ruffled some feathers. Could be a
hothead. Came off cocky and brash. But remember the '88 convention?
Seemed like half the delegates in the hall were Bushes, but it was
George W. who gave Texas to the old man, thereby giving the old man
the nomination. A great dynastic moment, that.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Younger: ``I think he felt responsibility. That was part
of his maturing and I think he sensed he was the oldest son, and
when his father became president, I think his role changed. I think
he assumed responsibilities within the family and without. He
decided he was going to be a devoted son, not that he wasn't
before, and he was going to step up to the plate and be on board
with his dad and mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe O'Neill: ``He got a real taste of the power and what you can
do. It raised his horizons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Natural
</P>
<P>
   He loved baseball _ always said he wanted to play like Willie
Mays when he was a younger man. And after he and Laura and the
girls moved to Dallas, darned if he didn't get in the middle of a
deal to buy the Texas Rangers. He put up $606,000 _ chump change
compared with the other partners, but he'd get 20 times that on the
back end in a few years. They make him general manager, and there
he is running the team, wearing those custom-made Rangers cowboy
boots in his seats right behind home plate. This is the best job in
the whole world for George W. Bush, who gets along with everybody,
knows the office people and the groundskeeper and the hot-dog
vendor, signs autographs and chats up fans and players. A $200,000
salary (what the president pulls down) and part ownership in the
team _ to watch baseball!
</P>
<P>
   All anybody talks about now is The Deal, one of those Byzantine
processes by which this country builds its monuments to sport. Such
deals always get a handful of people filthy rich and another
handful feeling thoroughly shafted. But they built the new
Arlington ballpark, called The Ballpark, which made the value of
the team shoot through the roof, which made George W. Bush more
money than he ever thought he'd see.
</P>
<P>
   Former Spectrum 7 partner Rea: ``George felt like to get into
politics you needed some personal money, and that was his goal _ to
make enough money where his family would be comfortable and he
wouldn't be beholden to special interests.''
</P>
<P>
   There was quiet talk of running George W. Bush against Richards
in '90 _ Richards went after Dad with that ``poor George'' riff at
the '88 convention, about how Poppy Bush was ``born with a silver
foot in his mouth.'' Oh, people loved that one, didn't they?
Wouldn't it be nice to step up and boot her out of the governor's
office? But George W. didn't run _ told Rea his mother didn't want
him to, for one thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Candidate
</P>
<P>
   When the first son did take on Richards, she let him have it.
Dubya took the jabs and kept smiling. Richards would say Bush was a
failed businessman; Bush would mourn the governor's compulsive use
of ``personal attacks.'' Richards noted Bush had never before held
elected office; Bush wore his inexperience as a badge of honor _
not having to say out loud voters might prefer him to a product of
the Travis County Democratic machine. A Richards spokesman noted
that $141 million for The Ballpark came from a sales tax boost and
city bond guarantees. Bush's flack shot back she was just playing a
``political shell game.'' Jack Morrison says his conduct in the
campaign against Richards showed maturity and clarity of purpose:
``She just savaged him, and he just killed her with kindness.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early going, nobody thought Richards was vulnerable _ she
was a star, maybe could be the first woman president, had big
contributions from Don Henley and Steven Spielberg and Willie.
Who'd Bush have in his corner_ Claytie Williams? But Bush saw
weakness, convinced Texans _ without really coming out and saying
it _ that their governor was maybe not all that nice. Even in the
early going, when he was being painted as the spoiled little
dilettante, he exuded this cockiness, like at a meet-the-staff
event where he first met future speech writer Skardon Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm George Bush,'' George Bush says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Skardon Baker,'' Skardon Baker says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gonna win, ya know,'' George Bush says.
</P>
<P>
   He made those young aides and volunteers believe. It was so much
fun _ going flat-out all day long, hopping from town to town on the
plane they dubbed Accountability One, writing thank-you cards to
the hosts of the previous stop as soon as it was wheels-up (a
practice learned from George H.W.), cramming for the next event
even as they hit the ground, doing everything literally on the fly.
He had a three-day rule on getting out thank-you notes, and was
adamant about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign had juice. ``We had more fun days than not,''
said Israel Hernandez Jr., a campaign aide who also worked for Bush
during his first term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   The weird thing was, you could tell Bush wanted to win _ he's a
competitive guy. But there was a part of him that knew the world
wouldn't end if he lost, and that gave him a certain . . .
fearlessness. Skardon Baker's father recently became a Catholic
priest, and he sees a certain parallel between his father now and
Bush then. Bush, he says, felt a guiding hand on his shoulder,
which lent the campaign a calm core amid the chaos.
</P>
<P>
   He ran every day, wherever they were. If they were in Corpus,
Shoreline Drive. Austin, Town Lake or the UT track. And he called
home from the road every day _ more than ``Hi, how are you, OK,
bye,'' but actual want-to-know-what's-going-on conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was living in Dallas, of course, as were the Bushes,
and his place got burgled and the next day he had to deal with cops
and whatnot. Candidate Bush found Hernandez and told him: ``You
know, you shouldn't have to worry about things like that. You'd
better come live with us.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, Hernandez recalls, it was like the Waltons at
bedtime:
</P>
<P>
   ``Good night, George.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good night, Laura.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good night, Barb.'' ``Good night, Jenna.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good night, Izzy.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards, meanwhile, having already learned that it was more fun
campaigning for governor than being governor, discovered
campaigning to keep the job was a lot less fun than campaigning to
win it.
</P>
<P>
   The next campaign was little more than a dry run for the Big One
_ W2K. Democrat Garry Mauro ran on a platform of putting ``Texas
Families First.'' Bush didn't need to ask, if family was so
important to Garry, a divorced father, why he couldn't hold his own
family together. Didn't have to say anything like that out loud.
Just watched Mauro sweat through a brutal summer of knocking on
doors as Gov. Bush would fly to events, acting all gubernatorial.
Nothing to it. Kill 'em with kindness.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-06-16-99 1038EDT &QL;
</P>
