<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPORTER-MURDERED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SEES PROGRESS IN CASE INVOLVING SLAIN JOURNALIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States believes two Huichol Indians jailed in Mexico
are responsible for the brutal death of an American journalist who
was slain while on a solo backpacking trip in a mountainous region
of western Mexico late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects, Juan Chivarra de la Cruz and Miguel Hernandez
de la Cruz, had confessed to Mexican officials that they killed
Philip True, 50, the Mexico City correspondent for the San Antonio
Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   The two men later changed their story, twice, and said they
confessed because Mexican soldiers had tortured them.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Davidow, the U.S. ambassador to Mexico, said in San
Antonio on Thursday that the trial of the suspects is moving ahead.
``From what I've seen, the case against them is very strong,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jalisco state officials and federal administrators in Mexico
have allowed the FBI to review two autopsies of True's body that
produced contradictory results. The FBI also was allowed to inspect
physical evidence and compare witness statements, said Jon
Jennings, acting assistant attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI is confident the investigation shows the two
individuals in custody are the persons responsible for the death of
Mr. True,'' Jennings said in a letter to Rep. Charles A. Gonzalez,
D-Texas. ``Moreover, while Mexican prosecutors work to conclude the
investigation, the suspects remain in custody without bail.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez asked Attorney General Janet Reno earlier this year to
press the Mexican government for timely prosecution of the suspects
charged in the death of True. The original autopsy concluded death
by strangulation, while a second examination suggested True died
from a severe blow to the head.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're asking for is a timely resolution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, in his letter dated June 11, told Gonzalez the Mexican
Embassy in Washington said the Jalisco prosecutor ``is working
diligently on this case in order to bring about its timely
resolution in the Mexican courts.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, meanwhile, has declined to comment publicly on the
investigation into the death of True, whose body was found Dec. 16,
1998, in a shallow grave in the Sierra Madre.
</P>
<P>
   True left Nov. 29 on a 100-mile trek into the Sierra Madre to
document the life in Huichol villages. He was reported missing by
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, members of the Inter-American Press
Association met with Jalisco Gov. Alberto Cardenas Jimenez and
state Attorney General Ledesma Martinez. Jorge Fascetto, an
Argentina newspaper editor and president of the IAPA, said Cardenas
was responsive to the association's appeal for justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the opportunity to tell him a satisfactory conviction
of the killers of journalist Philip True would represent a
significant step forward for justice in the state of Jalisco, for
Mexico as a country and for journalists everywhere,'' Fascetto
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rivard, editor of the Express-News and an IAPA board
member, said unanswered questions surrounding True's death warrant
continued investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we agree there is ample evidence linking the two jailed
suspects with murder, we believe a more complete investigation will
lead to a more satisfactory prosecution and eventual conviction
that people in Mexico and the United States can accept with greater
certainty,'' Rivard said.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Rivard and the IAPA have asked the authorities to
establish a motive in the death. A missing diary discovered earlier
this year suggests True may have had a confrontation with one of
the suspects before his death. The diary details an exchange
between True and a Huichol Indian named Juan, who accused the
journalist of trespassing. The diary, True's camera and a passport
were found with other belongings federal and state officials had
maintained were missing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
