<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR PERFORMANCE OF CD-ROM DRIVE MAY JUST BE CASE OF KIDS' STICKY
FINGERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: We have a single computer in our house that I share with my
wife and two small children. I have noticed that, when the children
are using the computer, their CD-ROM software doesn't work as well
as it used to. Usually it involves the CD drive stalling out and a
blue screen comes up saying the computer can't read from the CD-ROM
drive. I've installed new drivers, checked the connections, but
nothing seems to work. What could be wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A: What's wrong is probably your children's sticky fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The clue here is the fact that it's happening only with your
children's software, not with your own. If you had driver or
connection problems, all your CD-ROM-based programs would be
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Take a close look at the disks your children use. I suspect
they're dirty and need to be cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   Try cleaning a disk as you would a pair of eyeglasses _ with a
soft tissue, perhaps blowing on it first. If this doesn't work, you
might want to pick up a CD-ROM cleaner at your favorite computer
store.
</P>
<P>
   It's also possible the disks in question are severely scratched.
In that case, you'll need to replace them. Some software publishers
will replace scratched CDs for free if you send them the damaged
ones first. Contact the publisher's technical support line for
details.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There are three computers in our house now, and I am
considering setting up a network so we can play games and share the
modem. I am confused about what to get, though. I see both
10-megabit and 100-megabit home network kits that use Ethernet, and
I see some wireless and phone line kits that only can send with 1
megabit. What are the benefits of the faster kits, given my needs?
</P>
<P>
   A: It depends on whether you value convenience and simplicity
over speed.
</P>
<P>
   Unless your computers are all in the same room, the phone-line
and wireless kits will be much easier to set up and install. For
printing, dial-up modem sharing and most multiplayer games, these
1-megabit systems are just fine.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you will be moving large files back and forth
between computers, or want to run multimedia applications over your
home network, you'll find these non-Ethernet systems to be woefully
inadequate. Moving a 25-megabyte file over a phone-line network can
seem to take forever, while it takes just seconds with 10- or
100-megabit Ethernet. And if you are trying to view video over the
network, you should definitely consider 100-megabit Ethernet.
</P>
<P>
   One other consideration: If you are planning to get cable modem
or high-speed ADSL service, you may want to consider Ethernet. The
average transfer rate for cable-modem service is in the six- to
eight-megabit range, while ADSL can go as high as six megabits
(though residential ADSL service in Houston averages between 384K
and 1.4 megabit). That's faster than the 1-megabit throughput of
the wireless and phone-line networks, making those systems a
bottleneck when you are sharing one of these fast connections.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with Ethernet is that you must string cable between
the computers, and a lot of people aren't comfortable with this
process, which may involve cutting holes in walls and running
wiring through them. But for some folks, the speed is worth the
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I connect to a Web site, I sometimes see a picture of a
lock at the bottom of my browser. What does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A: It means your browser has made a secure connection to the
site, and is sending and receiving information that's encrypted, or
scrambled. This guarantees a private exchange, and usually is used
for electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
