<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICE 2000 SINGS BIG, EXPENSIVE TUNE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there are remaining doubts about whether Microsoft ``gets''
the Internet, they are dashed by the latest version of the software
giant's cash cow, Office 2000. It's the first application suite
that treats the Net as a given.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000 presumes its users are connected to a network and
presumes they are also connected to the Internet. That's great if
you are _ this is going to be a popular product with big companies
and users who are on the cutting edge of such practices as document
collaboration. But if you don't fit into those categories, Office
2000 is either a dubious upgrade, or a way for users to begin to
explore this advanced way of working.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I reviewed the competition from Corel, WordPerfect
Office 2000 Professional (See
www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/99/06/11/compute.html). While
it's not as Internet-oriented as the Microsoft suite, it costs
quite a bit less and is otherwise as feature-rich as Office 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For this review, I looked at the Premium edition of Office 2000,
which includes Word, a word processor; Excel, a spreadsheet;
PowerPoint, for presentations; Access, a database; Outlook, a
contact manager; FrontPage, a Web site manager; PhotoDraw, an image
editor; and a set of small-business tools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`BLOATWARE' SLIMS DOWN SOME &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Microsoft claims it has responded to user complaints
about ``bloatware'' by letting you install only the feature you
think you'll need, this is still a lumbering giant of a package.
The typical installation will drop about 300 megabytes onto your
hard drive. The Premium edition comes on four CDs.
</P>
<P>
   This remains the best-integrated suite _ everything works well
together, and the menus and button bars all follow the same design.
Documents designed by any of these applications can be imported
smoothly into other Office components.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000's Web integration begins with the most fundamental
aspect _ Hypertext Mark-up Language, the programming language used
for Web pages. In other suites, HTML is treated as a secondary file
format. With the Office components, though, it's a primary format.
</P>
<P>
   This means that if you design a nifty-looking Word document and
save it as HTML, the HTML version will look as good as if you saved
it in Word's own .DOC format. In the past, saving a Word document
as an HTML file was a hit-or-miss proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2000 also lets you save an HTML document directly to a
Web server, whether it's on your corporate network or out there on
the Internet. When you install the suite, it adds an item in the
Windows Explorer called Web Folders. You can save directly to these
folders, just as though they are sitting on your hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a catch. In order for this to work, the server must
be running special software that works with Office. That's too bad
_ Microsoft could have made this a much simpler, more universal and
less proprietary solution if it had used FTP, or File Transfer
Protocol, the standard way to post documents to most Internet
servers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CUSTOMIZING THE FEATURES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As with the Corel suite, you can install only those features of
Office 2000 that you need. Then, if you later try to use a feature
that you didn't originally include, the ``Install on Demand''
module either grabs it from a central server on your corporate
network, or prompts you for the CD.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of installation _ the install routine gives you
literally hundreds of choices. If you choose a custom setup, you
can choose to install a feature; install it on first use; or never
allow it to be installed; or to run it from the CD. It's a dizzying
array that can be confusing.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the applications, there very few outward changes in
the programs' interface. (Access, which has had a welcome facelift
to make it more user-friendly, is the biggest exception.) The
button bars and top-level menus will be comfortingly familiar to
longtime Office users. One major difference, though, is in the way
Office hides less-frequently used features, and then brings them
forward if you use them regularly.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you click on Excel's Tools menu, you'll see only
about six selections, including one that says Options. If you click
on Options _ or even if you just sit there for a few seconds _ then
the menu automatically expands to show you more. Wait long enough,
and the Office Assistant (Microsoft's animated help feature)
appears to provide help. If you choose one of the hidden options,
and then use it several times, it will appear each time you select
the Tools.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, there's good news for the many Office users who
consider the irritating Office Assistant characters to be the
business-software equivalent of Jar Jar Binks. You can now access
the Help features without having to look at the stupid things.
</P>
<P>
   One of Office 2000's nicest features is its ability to fix
itself. If you accidentally delete a key file, or if one becomes
corrupted, the Office applications can figure out what's wrong and
will install the missing or broken file automatically.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing for the Premium edition of Microsoft's suite is steep.
The least you can get away with is $449, and that's if you are
upgrading from a previous version or a competitor's product. Even
the lowest-end configuration of Office 2000, dubbed Standard, will
set you back at least $249.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
