<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0952 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHERRY-PICKING-2TAKES     06-18 1962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERRY-PICKING-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHERRIES READY FOR PICKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
( HAS ART)  
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
 c.  1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you're dreaming of fresh sweet cherries, the
brief season to take advantage of them has finally arrived. The
start of the season was delayed by two to three weeks this year
because of cold weather in California and the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh sweet cherries will be making their way in ever-increasing
numbers into supermarkets and local stores in the next few weeks.
And for those who want to roam the breathtaking array of trees
laden with bright red sweet and tart cherries and pick their own,
U-pick cherry orchards around Southern California will be open
through July 11 or until all the cherries are gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The advantage of picking your own is that you get to do your
own quality-control testing,'' said Ken Striplin, president of the
Leona Valley Cherry Growers Association, who anticipates the
availability of plenty of excellent-quality sweet-flavored cherries
even though the crop size has been reduced by 10 percent because of
an April freeze.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest commercial cherry production comes from San Joaquin
County. That crop is in markets now, says Jim Culbertson, executive
manager of the California Cherry Advisory Board in Lodi, whose
group represents 600 growers who produce about 35 percent of the
nation's commercially grown fresh cherry crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in peak production now. We started harvesting May 1 _
two weeks later than normal _ and our season will end about July 8
this year,'' he noted. Usually, the California season is finished
before the Northwest growers start shipping cherries to Southern
California markets. However, because of Mother Nature, the two will
overlap slightly this year.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Northwest cherry crop _ from growers in Washington,
Oregon, Utah and Idaho who produce about 65 to 70 percent of the
fresh sweet cherries grown in the United States _ should start
reaching markets June 22, said B.J. Thurlby, national promotion
director, Northwest Cherry Growers, Yakima, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the season's late start, consumers can count on the
availability of plenty of cherries. California growers anticipate a
large crop that may be close to or exceed the 1994 crop, which was
the largest in recent history, added Culbertson.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with the expansion and harvesting of more late-maturing
varieties of cherries at higher elevations, consumers can expect to
find cherries in supermarkets through the second or third week of
August this year, noted Thurlby. Look for the peak of the Northwest
cherry season _ with best product and prices (around $1.49 to $1.89
a pound) _ the second week in July, he advised.
</P>
<P>
   When shopping for cherries, choose plump, sweet cherries with
bright color for the variety. Bing cherries range in color from red
to mahogany or purple-black. Lambert cherries are bright red while
Rainier cherries are yellow-tinged with red. Be aware that once
picked, cherries do not ripen. Keep cherries cold and use within a
few days. Rinse before serving.
</P>
<P>
   To remove cherry pits for recipes, half each cherry and remove
stem and pit or use a cherry pitter available at cookware shops.
</P>
<P>
   Don't limit cherries to out of hand eating. The versatile fruit
makes a good addition to chilled soups, sauces, salads, and baked
and frozen desserts.
</P>
<P>
   Cherries also freeze well. The natural sugar in cherries makes
freezing easy as no processed sweeteners or preservatives are
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   To freeze whole: Rinse cherries (stem intact) quickly in cold
water, drain thoroughly and dry on paper towels. Place cherries in
a zipper-top freezer bag and seal, pressing out as much air as
possible, or use freezer-proof containers. For fastest freezing,
place bags directly on freezer shelves. Leave some space around
each bag until contents are frozen. Once frozen, stack the bags. Be
sure to label and date the cherries. Use within a year.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to use, remove the amount of cherries needed, reseal
the plastic bag and return to the freezer immediately. Eat cherries
right out of the freezer or partially frozen for best flavor and
texture. Keep in mind cherries turn limp and soft if thoroughly
thawed.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the recipes that follow, some additional ways to use
fresh cherries include:
</P>
<P>
   Toss 1 cup pitted and coarsely chopped fresh sweet cherries into
the batter the next time you bake brownies either from scratch or a
mix.
</P>
<P>
   Add cherries to yogurt for a snack.
</P>
<P>
   Use cherries for a pastry filling or bake into cakes, cookies,
quick breads or muffins.
</P>
<P>
   Add cherries to a favorite fruit salad or fruit compote.
</P>
<P>
   Mix pitted cherries with fresh torn-up spinach, cooked crab and
cooked shrimp, and toss with a french, ranch or curried yogurt
dressing for a delicious salad.
</P>
<P>
   Top pitted cherries with yogurt mixed with a little store-bought
lemon or lime curd.
</P>
<P>
   Serve poultry, waffles, pancakes or ice cream topped with cherry
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Stir chopped pitted fresh cherries into pancake or waffle
batter.
</P>
<P>
   Serve fresh pitted cherries topped with creme fraiche or whipped
cream mixed with unsweetened cocoa and powdered sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Stir fresh coarsely chopped pitted cherries into chocolate or
vanilla pudding or tapioca made from scratch or an instant mix.
</P>
<P>
   Top chocolate ice cream with fresh pitted cherries and a jigger
of whiskey or brandy _ or a favorite liqueur.
</P>
<P>
   For brunch, combine a mixture of assorted fresh in-season fruits
including pitted fresh cherries and stir in a little orange juice
concentrate. At serving time, spoon into stemmed wine glasses and
top off with a little lemon-lime carbonated beverage to add an
interesting bubbly effect.
</P>
<P>
   For a special party or dessert, whip up chocolate dipped
cherries. Melt semisweet chocolate chips and a little solid
vegetable shortening in a double boiler over simmering water until
smooth. Remove from heat. Dip fresh rinsed and well-dried cherries,
stems intact (hold by stem), into chocolate then dip bottoms into
chopped almonds. Place on wax apaper-lined tray until set.
</P>
<P>
   Partner fresh cherries with an espresso dip prepared with
instant espresso powder mixed with a little sugar and dissolved in
hot water, then whipped together with whipped cream cheese and a
little vanilla.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRESH CHERRY SALSA
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pitted fresh sweet cherries
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped green bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon EACH Worcestershire sauce and grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Dash bottled hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   Chop cherries in a food processor or manually. Combine cherries
with remaining ingredients; mix well. Refrigerate at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with chicken, pork or fish. Best served freshly prepared.
Flavors dilute with storage. Makes about 3/4 cup. Recipe may be
doubled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QUICK CHERRY CRUMB CAKE
</P>
<P>
   2 cups buttermilk baking mix (such as Bisquick)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup dairy sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons melted butter OR margarine
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups pitted and halved fresh sweet cherries
</P>
<P>
   Streusel Topping
</P>
<P>
   Mix baking mix, sugar and lemon peel. Combine sour cream, melted
butter and egg; mix well. Add sour cream mixture to baking mixture
and stir only until moistened. Fold in 1/2 cup cherries.
</P>
<P>
   Turn into an oiled and floured 8-inch square baking pan.
Sprinkle remaining 1 cup cherries and Streusel Topping over batter.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 35 to 40 minutes or until a
wooden pick inserted near center comes out clean. Makes 9 servings.
</P>
<P>
   STREUSEL TOPPING: Combine 1/2 cup flour, 3 tablespoons packed
brown sugar, 1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon and 1/4 teaspoon salt.
Mix in 3 tablespoons softened butter OR margarine with a fork. Add
1/4 cup chopped walnuts and mix well. Makes about 1 cup. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHERRY PARTY COMPOTE
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh OR frozen blueberries
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh, frozen OR canned pineapple chunks, drained
</P>
<P>
   4 cups stemmed and pitted fresh sweet cherries
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh apricot halves
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chilled white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange liqueur
</P>
<P>
   1 cup club soda
</P>
<P>
   Mint sprigs
</P>
<P>
   In a large glass bowl or compote, layer blueberries, pineapple
chunks, 1/2 of cherries, apricots and remaining cherries. Combine
wine and liqueur; pour over fruits. Chill thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, pour club soda over and garnish with mint
sprigs. Makes 12 to 15 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRESH CHERRY COFFEECAKE
</P>
<P>
   1 cup butter OR margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dairy sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pitted, chopped fresh sweet cherries
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Streusel Topping
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter, 1 1/4 cups sugar, vanilla and lemon peel. Beat in
eggs, one at a time. Add sour cream; mix thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour, baking powder, baking soda and salt. Gradually
add flour mixture to creamed mixture; beat until smooth. Combine
cherries, pecans, remaining sugar and cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   Spread 1/2 of batter in a greased and floured 13x9x2-inch baking
pan; spoon cherry-mixture over batter. Spread remaining batter over
top. Sprinkle with Streusel Topping.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 40 to 45 minutes, or until a
wooden pick inserted near center comes out clean. Makes 8 to 10
servings.
</P>
<P>
   STREUSEL TOPPING: Combine 1 cup flour, 1/2 cup softened butter
OR margarine, 1/4 cup sugar and 1 teaspoon ground cinnamon; mix
thoroughly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SWINE POACHED CHERRIES WITH CREME FRAICHE
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pitted fresh sweet cherries
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 to 5 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   Creme Fraiche
</P>
<P>
   Place cherries in a saucepan with wine, sugar and cloves. Bring
to a boil; reduce heat and simmer 10 minutes. Remove cloves; cool.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon cherries and wine mixture into serving dishes; top with
Creme Fraiche. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CREME FRAICHE: Combine 1 cup whipping OR heavy cream and 1
teaspoon cultured buttermilk OR dairy sour cream; gently heat to 90
degrees F. Let stand, covered, at room temperature (60 to 70
degrees F) about 12 to 15 hours or until thickened. Stir gently;
refrigerate until ready to use. Creme Fraiche can be refrigerated
up to 2 weeks. Makes 1 cup. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRESH CHERRIES JUBILEE
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup EACH cold water and orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh sweet cherries, pitted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brandy (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 quart vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar and cornstarch. Blend in water and orange juice.
Cook, stirring, until thickened and smooth. Add cherries and orange
peel; return to a boil and simmer 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Gently heat brandy, pour over sauce and flame, if desired. Serve
over ice cream. Makes about 8 servings. Recipe may be halved. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FRESH CHERRY PIE
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   5 cups pitted, fresh sweet cherries
</P>
<P>
   Pastry for 2-crust (9-inch) pie
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter OR margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sifted powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle cornstarch over cherries; toss to coat. Turn into
pastry-lined 9-inch pie pan. Dot with butter.
</P>
<P>
   Roll remaining pastry into a 10-inch round. Cut into 3/4-inch
wide strips. Arrange lattice-fashion over filling; seal and flute
edges.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 425-degree oven 35 to 45 minutes or until
filling bubbles. Combine powdered sugar, lemon juice and peel; pour
over warm pie. Makes 1 (9-inch) pie. &UR;  &QL; 
(SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
