r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHERRY-SITES-LADN     06-18 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHERRY-SITES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLACES TO PICK YOUR OWN CHERRIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For a fun outing during the next few weeks, head
to nearby orchards to pick your own cherries.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a list of cherry orchards in the Leona Valley (an
hour's drive from the San Fernando Valley) where you can pick
cherries starting this weekend through the second week of July
(providing the cherries haven't all been picked). Times and days
the orchards are open vary, so call ahead. Most orchards provide
all the equipment needed for picking the fruit, including buckets,
bags and containers.
</P>
<P>
   Prices will vary but will average about $1.50 per pound if you
pick your own (a few orchards also sell already picked cherries).
Also, the minimum amount picked _ and that you're charged for _
varies from orchard to orchard, and in most cases is a pound or
two. Taste-test the cherries right off the trees to find which ones
you like the best. Some orchards offer several cherry varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Leona Valley is in the desert near the mountains and can be very
warm, noted Nessa Ranch manager Ken Striplin, so dress
appropriately. Also it can get very chilly in the late afternoon
and evening, so bring a sweater or light jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Pick plenty of cherries. They'll last about three weeks in the
fridge and are easy to freeze whole with stems attached for a great
snack long after the season is over.
</P>
<P>
   The Leona Valley is 12 miles due west from Palmdale. From the
San Fernando Valley, take the Antelope Valley Freeway (14) north
and exit at Palmdale Boulevard. Go left 12 miles on Palmdale
Boulevard to 90th Street and look for the cherry orchard signs.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like a brochure pinpointing the specific locations of
the orchards, send a self-addressed stamped envelope to Leona
Valley Cherry Growers Association, P.O. Box 817, Leona Valley,
Calif. 93551-7110.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR;  &LR; Amber's Sweet Cherries, (661) 270-9545.
</P>
<P>
   _ Berger's Cherry Ranch, (661) 270-1407.
</P>
<P>
   _ Big John's Orchard, (661) 270-1735.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blackie's Bings, (661) 270-0163.
</P>
<P>
   _ Blossom Hill Ranch, (661) 270-1479.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cherry Hill Ranch, (661) 270-1343.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cherry Pit, (661) 270-0747.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cherry Tyme Sour Pie Cherry Ranch (sour cherries), (661)
270-0649.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chuck's Cherries, (661) 270-0733.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cottonwood Farms, (661) 270-1716.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hobart's Cherries, (661) 270-1685.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leona Valley Pie Cherry Ranch (sour cherries), (661) 270-0666.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lilac Terrace Cherry, (661) 270-0561.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nessa Ranch, (661) 270-1973.
</P>
<P>
   _ Northside Cherries, (661) 270-1290
</P>
<P>
   _ Owl's Roost, (661) 270-1865.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pitchfork Ranch, (661) 270-0680.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rex's Cherries, (661) 270-1465.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sky Meadow Farms (sweet and sour cherries), (661) 270-2456.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wade's Cherry Mart (661) 270-1073.
</P>
<P>
   _ Water's Cherry Ranch, (661) 270-9437.
</P>
<P>
   You can also pick cherries in Valyermo at the Valyermo Ranch,
29831 Valyermo Road, (805) 944-2294. To reach the ranch, take the
Antelope Valley Freeway (14) north to the Highway 138 (Pearblossom
cutoff) exit. Turn right and drive until you reach Longview Road,
then turn right, and at Avenue W make a left. Avenue W turns into
Valyermo Road. Follow the signs to the ranch. Cherries are $1 per
pound (whether you pick them yourself or buy already-picked Bings).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
