<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0977 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-CURSING-$ADV20     06-18 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-CURSING-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WAVY BORDERLINE BETWEEN FREE SPEECH AND FOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., June 20)  
(jt) 
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Timothy Boomer fell out of his canoe into the Rifle River
in Michigan last summer, he did what many men would do _ he swore a
blue streak. Unlike many men, however, he was nailed for it. A
family was within earshot, and Boomer, 25, a computer programmer,
was charged with violating a 102-year-old state law against cursing
in front of women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, after a two-day trial, a jury found him
``guilty of being a potty mouth,'' to quote U.S. News &AMP; World
Report.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union, which represented the
defendant, has said the statute ``smacks of speech police.'' But
the conviction raises the question: Does public decency outweigh a
man's uncivil rights? It is an emotionally charged issue,
particularly at a time when lawmakers in Washington are calling for
new limits to teen-agers' access to movie and television violence,
including violent language, in the wake of the shootings in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The subject, like Boomer's off-color vocabulary, is hard to
avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The world, and particularly our rough-edged corner of it, seems
to be suffering from a mass case of Tourette's syndrome. Foul
language, once the verbal equivalent of hot sauce, is less a
condiment today than a staple in our daily lives. Walk into a CD
megastore to buy, say, an old Peggy Lee reissue, and over the
in-store stereo system you'll very often hear new songs with the
kind of explicit lyrics that require a parental warning label. At a
PG-rated movie, it is not uncommon to hear teen-age ushers using
R-rated language in full voice.
</P>
<P>
   When the soundtrack to the average Jerry Springer show is
bleeped so often that it sounds like a trans-Atlantic call made on
a cheap cell phone, what is left to say on television that hasn't
already been said? There was a time, not that many years ago, when
watching (although not hearing) Cher using a choice word to berate
David Letterman was hilarious. Madonna, chatting with the same
talk-show host, has been known to push the envelope even further.
But even her infamously bleeped antics seem relatively benign
today.
</P>
<P>
   By its sheer ubiquity, such shocking language has lost any
provocative edge it may have had. When, for instance, Chris Rock
used a crude anecdote in his presentation of an American Fashion
Award to Calvin Klein in New York on June 2, it just seemed
inappropriate. Likewise, when Sharon Stone chose an off-color
expression to warn against the dangers of AIDS at the Divas Simply
Singing benefit in Los Angeles on May 8, it just seemed crude.
Neither instance was unexpected. That's the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, when the comedian and legendary ``vulgarian''
Belle Barth talked dirty, it caught audiences off guard. She was a
little old lady with the mouth of a Yiddish-speaking truck driver _
not standard issue in those days _ and she told her audiences, ``If
I embarrass you, tell your friends.'' Her album of that title bore
the words: ``Censored. Not for Air Play. For Adults Only.'' Today,
a half-hour of ``Sex in the City'' on HBO is twice as risque.
Likewise, when Lenny Bruce, Red Foxx or, later, George Carlin
``worked blue,'' as they called it back then, they were breaking
social taboos. Today, there are few barriers of that sort left.
When you can say anything, foul language becomes simply foul,
unless it's used to hilarious effect, which it sometimes is.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, obscenity just seems like yesterday's news.
Although a feature-length version of the animated television series
``South Park'' is set to open this month, there are signs that we
are moving into a post-``South Park'' era. The hit sequel ``Austin
Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' has a naughty word in its title,
but ``shag'' is just that, naughty. The appeal of the film is the
childlike glee of its title character and his nemesis Dr. Evil.
Even in its grossest moments, ``The Spy Who Shagged Me'' possesses
such exuberance that it renders the scatological humor of a
character called Fat Bastard inoffensive. It's not raw, it's just
silly _ so very PG-13, baby.
</P>
<P>
   At Cannes recently, the filmmaker David Lynch stunned the crowd
with his latest picture, ``The Straight Story,'' a fact-based
account of a man who rode his lawn mower from Iowa to Wisconsin to
visit his estranged brother. The shock was that it was G-rated.
Lynch, whose earlier films ``Blue Velvet'' and ``Wild at Heart''
were brutal in both violence and language, has noted in interviews
that a tide of gentleness is overtaking filmmakers of his ilk. Both
the Spanish provocateur Pedro Almodovar and that master of
blue-collar patois David Mamet have chosen to clean up their
vocabularies, at least temporarily. Almodovar's latest film is
``All About My Mother,'' a comedy, and Mamet's ``The Winslow Boy,''
is out now and rated G.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent article in The New York Times, Lynch was quoted as
saying that violence and obscene language on screen ``have been
pushed to an absurd extreme, to the point where you don't feel it
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really explain it, but I feel a change,'' he added.
``I feel something different in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   If only Boomer had predicted such a shift last summer, he might
not be in such hot water today.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
