<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FATHERS-ESSAY-$ADV20-     06-18 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHERS-ESSAY-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GIFT FOR THE FATHER OF INVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 20) 
(jt) 
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the innocent eye, my father seems a mild-mannered radiologist
and suburban grandfather. By day, in his silver-rim glasses,
wearing a lab coat with a calculator in the breast pocket, he looks
like the kind of guy who would kick back with Scientific American.
</P>
<P>
   But Dad is really a cross between Bob Vila, the home improvement
guru, and Dr. Victor Frankenstein. Throughout my childhood he spent
late nights building who-knows-what in a basement workshop that
smelled of sawdust and was filled with menacing-looking machinery
from the 1940s. Twenty years ago, he created a system, operated by
timers, that alternately watered and fertilized the lawn, long
before such devices came on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a success, just as often his mad-scientist
creations have been riddled with glitches. To run the heating and
air-conditioning in his present house, he wired the systems to his
phone lines. Now, he can turn on the cool air away from home by
dialing a number from his cell phone. But the phones in the house
are so staticky that it is nearly impossible to hear voices above
the crackle.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to get out of the rut of Father's Day gifts I buy every
year from Brooks Brothers or Barnes &AMP; Noble, I set out to find
something this year that appealed to his love of tinkering. The
perfect gift, I suspected, awaited in one of the gizmo-stocked
stores of 57th Street: Hammacher Schlemmer, the Sharper Image,
Brookstone.
</P>
<P>
   I am baffled by technospeak, the language of all the men in my
family, and so I enlisted my two brothers to go with me. Michael, a
neuroradiologist, and Paul, a lawyer, are both married with
children and have inherited the paternal fiddling gene.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop was Hammacher Schlemmer, famous for kitchen
knives and novelty tools and, nowadays, high-tech eccentricities. I
knew my father would have no use for a backyard driving range.
Ditto the nail clippers in a leather case, which would lie idle in
the medicine cabinet, since Dad's idea of a manicure is a hand
degreaser called Goop and a roll of paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Just as my brothers and I were about to leave, a high-pressure
washing tool for $219.95 caught my eye. It was powered by an
electric pump and had a hose attached to a long nozzle, which
looked like a machine gun. I could see my father standing hand on
hip, happily spray-cleaning grime off the patio furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many gallons per minute?'' Michael inquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``One point six gallons per minute,'' said Paul, looking the
machine over.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nothing,'' Michael sniffed. ``You need 3.2 GPM or
you're not talking clean. You've got to be able to blast the paint
off your car to get it clean. Plus, it's too expensive. Dad likes
cheap Chinese tools from the Price Club.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheap and turbocharged, that's the kind of stuff that appeals to
Dad, all right. In fact, if it means saving money, no
home-improvement scheme is too ambitious for him. During a
hurricane a few years ago, a tree trunk weighing more than a ton
fell on top of his house. Rather than hire a tree surgeon to remove
it, he rented a hydraulic log splitter. Dressed in a hard hat, he
ordered my brothers to hoist the tree with pulleys and ropes and
then to cut it up with a chainsaw. He stockpiled a lot of firewood
that year.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Hammacher Schlemmer, we headed to the Sharper Image,
where right away Paul spied the Turbo-Groomer, an electric
nose-hair trimmer. ``This, Dad could use,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, for his ears, too,'' Michael said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although he would probably tell you about the biological
virtues of nose hairs as a filter,'' Paul added.
</P>
<P>
   Michael said, ``He'd wind up using it on stray threads on the
car seats.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true. Dad can't resist inventing new uses for tools and
other gear, like the time he adapted the cruise control from his
car to fit his Suzuki motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   Making our way around the store, my brothers and I stopped
before a white-noise machine meant to drown out background sounds
while sleeping. It brought back memories. Dad once installed
speakers in a pillow to study for his nuclear-medicine boards,
playing an endless recording of notes while he slept. He passed the
exam on the first go.
</P>
<P>
   His faith in sleep-teaching was of long standing. It was
instilled the year before I was born, after he read an article
maintaining that the best learning took place during slumber. For
my parents' honeymoon in 1960, Dad recited a textbook aloud into a
tape recorder, and though he had no trouble sleeping with the
cassette player under his pillow, my mother was kept awake night
after night listening to medical mumbo jumbo.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the white-noise machine was a self-cleaning kitty litter
box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not as good as Dad's,'' Michael said. ``Paul, remember when
you had a cat and lived in a studio apartment, and Dad built an
enclosed litter box? He figured out a system where the cat got in
the box and tripped a pressure-weighted switch that triggered an
exhaust fan inside, and the smell was sucked out through a
ventilator duct in the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   As Paul and I nodded at the memory, Michael wondered aloud about
the psychology behind our father's impulse to invent and redesign.
``It's an admission of a lack of masculinity if you hire someone
else to do a job for you,'' he said. ``The more you can create,
build and fix, the more manly you are. This is the essence of being
a Hayt.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder I felt left out growing up.
</P>
<P>
   A few doors down from the Sharper Image, at Brookstone, Michael
was immediately drawn to a set of retractable barbecue tools. Dad
would love the idea of detaching a spatula from its handle for
cleaning, he said. But Paul was sure the wood components, which
were not dishwasher-safe, would prove frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Considering this, Michael agreed. ``Dad likes to be able to put
everything in the dishwasher _ soap dishes, toothbrushes, combs,''
he said. Turning to Paul, he asked: ``Did he ever put automotive
parts in there? I know he's big on using kerosene and gasoline for
cleaning grease.''
</P>
<P>
   As my brothers mulled this over, I drifted to the back of the
store, where I found a simple white box with buttons and numbers in
a digital display. It looked like an alarm clock, but it was
actually an indoor-outdoor thermometer with an electronic memory.
It cost $30. Waving over my brothers, I asked hesitantly: ``What
about this? Couldn't Dad figure out something to use this for?''
</P>
<P>
   Michael studied the device. ``Dad would like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul pointed out that Dad already has remote control over the
air-conditioning in the house (that jury-rigged phone system) and
that he likes to have it cool when he walks in the door. ``This
thing would provide him with information,'' he said. ``It would
allow him to know the temperature of the house without being in it.
He would know if his pipes will burst in the winter, and if his
system is working in the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul's advice was, ``Buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the store with my package, I felt a gift-buying
satisfaction I had rarely known before. My Father's Day purchase
would help me connect with the man so often hidden behind a gaggle
of wires, a cloud of metal shavings or the hood of a car. When I
call him up, our voices rising over the static, now I'll have an
instant conversation opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, Dad,'' I'll say, ``what were the highs and lows today?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1601EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
