<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0981 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PIRATES-REVIEW-SFC     06-18 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PIRATES-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PIRATES' OF THE CYBERBUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for times.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So begins the establishment of a new American myth, maybe even a
whole film genre. Anyway, Westerns are so yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, now kids _ if they still bother to play outside at all _
can divide themselves into the Apple gang and the Microsoft gang.
</P>
<P>
   And fight to the last dollar.
</P>
<P>
   It's iconography for our corporate age. Hell, it's practically
cowboys and integers.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking about this because of the TNT movie ``Pirates of
Silicon Valley,'' which will be shown three times Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Starring Noah Wyle as Steve Jobs and Anthony Michael Hall as
Bill Gates, it's the story of college kids who played with machines
in boxes, then worked, cajoled, borrowed and stole their way to
enormous wealth.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how they'll log off into the sunset.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is written and directed by Martyn Burke (``Pentagon
Wars''). The source material is the book ``Fire in the Valley,'' by
Paul Freiberger and Michael Swaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' isn't as funny or barbed as its
creators seem to think it is. But it's still one of TNT's more
ambitious efforts, and it's never less than entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   It's surprisingly tough on its star marauders, too, especially
Jobs, the visionary who founded Apple Computer with Steve Wozniak
(Joey Slotnick).
</P>
<P>
   Wyle is easily the film's strongest presence as a charismatic
figure with an almost mystical belief in what he and computers can
accomplish. ``This ain't just business,'' Jobs declares. ``This is
practically spiritual. This is about overthrowing dead culture.''
</P>
<P>
   He first tears through countercultural rituals, including a
fling with Hare Krishna and an affinity for LSD, and then turns
into a megalomaniacal brute when Apple catches fire in the late
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   By now he's screaming at employees, bullying job applicants and
even alienating Wozniak. He's also seen denying that he's the
father of his girlfriend's (Gema Zamprogna) daughter, though as
Wozniak reminds him, a paternity test has pretty much nailed him.
</P>
<P>
   I can't vouch for the accuracy of all this. It is distressing,
though, to see the movie pairing Jobs and Wozniak as buddies at UC
Berkeley in 1971, and then read a TNT chronology prepared for
reviewers saying the two met at Hewlett-Packard in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   On to Gates. Hall seems more intimidated by the thought of
playing the world's wealthiest man. His performance is stilted and
lacks the fluidity of Wyle's, though it never crashes all the way
to robotic impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft founder is depicted as a struggling wannabe who
lives on pizza and bluff, who speaks the language of money as well
as the language of computer operating systems, and who swipes the
keys to  &LR;   &LR; Windows from Jobs' Macintosh prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   There's an undeniable thrill in seeing Gates, as a Harvard nerd,
trying to focus his attention on a Boston strip show. Or racing
bulldozers in Albuquerque, the first home of Microsoft. Or
schlepping around a roller-skating rink, trying unsuccessfully to
snag a date.
</P>
<P>
   Burke seems to want the movie to be the sort of frolic that
``Barbarians at the Gate'' was a few years ago on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' can't touch that octave, but he's
delivered a diverting adventure about gunmen riding the high
plateau of sophisticated technology.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if only TNT would tackle ``The Brigands of Broadcasting,''
in which the daring Ted Turner wages corporate warfare with the
wily Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   It could be the second in a series of exciting movies about
fearless desperados ambushing each other in the bushy landscape of
merging technologies, skyrocketing stock options and lax government
vigilance.
</P>
<P>
   Podner, it's enough to make any real American's hair stand on
end.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
