<HEADER>
A0986 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-QUAKE-0619-COX     06-18 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-QUAKE-0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QUAKE WOUNDS SOUL OF COLONIAL MEXICAN CITY
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUEBLA, Mexico _ The Spanish painted tiles, Moorish arabesques
and stone sculptures that grace the ancient buildings in this
colonial city are its pride and soul.
</P>
<P>
   And right now people in Puebla are in mourning, fearing that a
6.7 earthquake that struck Mexico Tuesday may have dealt their
heritage a mortal blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our history has been wiped out,'' said Juan Carlos Castillo,
who stopped with his 5-year-old son outside a 16th-century church
whose bell tower was shredded by the quake, which also killed at
least 23 people in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Architects hope Castillo's prediction is premature and that
careful recontracting -- and millions of dollars -- will save the
majority of Puebla's architectural jewels. This city about 70 miles
southeast of the capital Mexico City is, in fact, so blessed by
buildings of historical and architectural value that it is an
official United Nations cultural landmark.
</P>
<P>
   The death of these 16th- and 17th-century structures with unique
Mexican baroque designs would be like the United States losing New
Orleans' French Quarter or Virginia's Williamsburg. Puebla has a
total of at least 2,600 structures considered colonial treasures or
artistic gems from the 19th and early 20th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   In Puebla's colonial center, initial estimates are that the
quake damaged 33 historic churches, 32 public buildings and six
Autonomous University of Puebla structures. Nineteen buildings,
including the Company of Jesus Church -- built by Jesuits in 1690
-- are considered severely damaged. As many as 300 churches may
have been damaged throughout the entire state of Puebla, whose
capital city was founded in 1531.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe at this point that there are any historic
buildings that will have to be completely abandoned,'' said Sergio
Arturo Vergara of Mexico's National Historical and Anthropological
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday Vergara toured the inside of the badly cracked
Company of Jesus Church and a building that is now the central
structure of the Autonomous University of Puebla.
</P>
<P>
   Vergara urged residents not to panic, and said that if Mexico
can earmark government funds and raise money from private sources
and the United Nations many of Puebla's buildings can be at least
partially preserved. Carefully chosen architects with experience in
repairing earthquake damage will have to be enlisted to take apart
damaged sections of buildings and then reconstruct them using some
of the same stones and bricks they were built with centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the teams of experts surveying the damage all agree that
cash-strapped Mexico will need a monumental effort to raise the
funds necessary for such a massive restoration project.
</P>
<P>
   As Vergara and other architects walked the scarred halls of the
400-year-old university building Thursday, the structure moaned and
shuddered occasionally, reminding those inside that it was still
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican soldiers and university employees scurried about,
packing files and carting off debris. The structure is standing,
but large cracks run the entire length of some of its halls, which
are as long as half a city block.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of cupolas that form the ceilings of each hall are cut in
half by huge cracks that expose ancient brick masonry beneath
delicate facades.
</P>
<P>
   Vergara said Puebla's San Agustin Church, whose original
structure dates back to the late 1500's, may fare better than many
Puebla residents initially thought.
</P>
<P>
   Rubble from a collapsed bell tower is primarily material that
was added as late as the 19th century, he said. Much of the the
original tower survived.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds gathered around the San Agustin Church, taking pictures
and wondering what will become of the glistening gold altar and
colonial paintings inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would feel even worse if it it had been a bomb or
something other than a natural disaster that harmed it,'' said
Francisco Reyes, who grew up in Puebla. ``But you can't help but
feel bad. It's like losing a part of oneself.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations recognized Puebla as one of the world's
cultural landmarks ``not just because of the importance it has for
people here, but for humanity. These buildings were outstanding
examples of architecture in their time,'' said Enrique Loyala
Grageda, a Puebla civil engineer and a member of the U.N.
Education, Scientific and Cultural Organization's International
Council of Monuments and Sites in Puebla.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts believe Puebla's colonial buildings might have
fared better if they had received more intensive maintenance over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The historic center needs constant attention to avoid
deterioration,'' Loyala Grageda said. ``And it should start getting
that from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
