<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-G8-0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YELTSIN TO ATTEND SUMMIT AS RUSSIA'S WOES PERSIST
 &HT;    With G8-KOSOVO-0619; CLINTON-G8;-0619.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ If the Group of Eight industrialized nations were a
country club, Russia would be like the annoying member who cannot
afford to pay the dues, but dominates the debate during the club
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Turbulent relations between Russia and the world's seven richest
nations threaten to overshadow the three-day summit of the G-8,
which opened Friday in Cologne, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The future of war-tattered Kosovo, and Russia's newly defined
role in the international peacekeeping effort there, promises to
dominate the agenda this weekend. Russia's ongoing economic
problems and its efforts to secure a Western bailout are also
central to the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Russian officials ended a weeklong impasse at meetings
in Helsinki, Finland, on Friday reaching and agreement on how
Russian troops will fit into the NATO-led peacekeeping force now in
the Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   The accord was reached just two days before President Clinton
and Russian President Boris Yeltsin were scheduled to meet at an
economic summit in Cologne, Germany. Yeltsin had said earlier
Friday that he expected the issue to be resolved during a meeting
between himself and Clinton scheduled for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement on the peacekeeping plan is important for the
summit, which is focusing on ways to return more than 1 million
ethnic Albanian refugees to their homes and how to pay for
rebuilding of the war-ravaged province.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's rapid move of troops into Kosovo ahead of NATO forces
last weekend raised questions of Yeltsin's grip on power and
Russia's intentions towards the West. Russian forces took control
of the airport near Pristina and used the armored vehicles to bar
the entrance of British and French troops.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin himself will be the center of attention Sunday when he
arrives for the ceremonies closing the summit and to hold talks
with Clinton and German Chancellor Gerhardt Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian president, 68 and in chronically poor health since
heart bypass surgery in 1996, has not held face-to-face talks with
Clinton in 10 months, though the two have been in frequent
telephone contact since the Kosovo war begin in late March. Yeltsin
reportedly has limited periods when he is lucid and has spent much
of the past year out of sight, convalescing from a variety of
illnesses and fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's newly appointed prime minister, Sergei Stepashin, is
attending the working sessions of the summit on Friday and
Saturday. Stepashin, 47, is a former interior minister who was
promoted in May to prime minister in Yeltsin's third government
overhaul in 14 months. He does not have a strong background in
foreign policy, unlike his predecessor Yevgeny Primakov who had
also served as Yeltsin's foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he will seek to convince the other G-8 members
that Russia is addressing its economic problems and deserves
further international aid and loans.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin had not planned to attend the summit, according to
reports in the Russian media. But he changed his mind after
Russia's bold troop movement into Kosovo, a ploy designed to give
Russia a greater role in determining the future of the Balkans
province.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin becomes more active every time there is the 'smell' of
victory in the air, no matter whether it is big or small,'' wrote
the Nezavisimaya Gazeta newspaper on Friday. The real purpose for
his visit to the summit after his long illness is ``to appear as
the real and not the phantom leader of the country,'' the editorial
said.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago, the G-7 became the G-8, as Russia was added to the
exclusive club of the world's wealthiest industrialized nations in
an effort to boost its participation and prestige following the
collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia's economy collapsed last August, prompting Western
nations to halt further aid and loans backed by the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) because of concerns about the way Russian
officials had squandered previous assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. air campaign against Iraq in December and the NATO war
against Yugoslavia this spring drove a further wedge between Russia
and the West as Yeltsin's health worsened and Russia's political
stability seemed less certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that Yeltsin remains the key powerbroker
in Russia. The question is whether he can wield the power and to
what end,'' said a Western diplomat in Moscow, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's economic situation is a separate agenda item for
meetings in Cologne on Saturday. At the least, Russian officials
hope to win an endorsement from the other members for further IMF
assistance, even though Russia's Communist-dominated parliament on
Thursday rejected a tax package thought to be a prerequisite to
further aid.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's handlers apparently hope to limit his public exposure
during his quick visit to Cologne on Sunday. No press conference
has been planned and Yeltsin will fly back to Moscow Sunday
evening. It will be Yeltsin's first trip outside Russia since he
attended the funeral of King Hussein of Jordan in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``World leaders are going to discuss the main political issue
(Kosovo) without Yeltsin, and he won't be there to take part in the
main economic problem -- of how to overcome the disparity between
the richest and poorest regions of the world on the eve of the 21st
century,'' the Kommersant Daily, a Russian business newspapers,
said Friday in a critical editorial.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
