<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-G8-0619-COX     06-18 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-G8-0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SUCCESS OF KOSOVO HAS CLINTON TAKING BOWS ON WORLD STAGE
 &HT;    850&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With G8-KOSOVO-0619; RUSSIA-G8-0619.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ Buoyed by his leadership of NATO's qualified
success in Kosovo, the strongest American economy in a generation
and the fading echoes of his impeachment travails, President
Clinton is projecting an air of fresh authority at the annual
summit of seven of the world's most powerful heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   Walking tall among his counterparts in this 2,000-year-old city
of towering spires and soaring ambitions, Clinton appeared
comfortably in control of the agenda Friday, as the G-7 leaders
opened a weekend of talks on issues ranging from Balkans
reconstruction to debt relief for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   He drew accolades from his fellow heads of state for his role in
leading his NATO partners in the coalition air war against
Yugoslavia's bloody repression in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to thank President Clinton for his leadership and
for his courage and his support,'' British Prime Minister Tony
Blair told Clinton, who looked on beaming in a dark grey suit and a
brilliant yellow tie. ``Without your leadership, and without the
American people's support, we simply couldn't have brought this to
a successful conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   He's even established himself as the senior mentor to two
fast-rising stars in the American political firmament -- his vice
president, Al Gore, the leading Democratic contender for the 2000
presidential race; and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, exploring
the prospect of running for the U.S. Senate. Both are leaning
heavily on the legacy of a man analysts expected them to distance
themselves from just a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a far cry from where Clinton stood at last summer's
Group of Seven summit in Blair's native land, where Clinton was
dogged by an ugly scandal that threatened his presidency and
shadowed his official travels around the world.
</P>
<P>
   It was only six months ago, after all, on the eve of his Dec.
19th impeachment by the House, that Clinton was pelted with so many
scandal-related questions at a Jerusalem press conference that his
host, then Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, was forced to plead
with reporters for a query on the state of Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's response to that atmosphere was to avoid the media as
much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   That was then; this is now.
</P>
<P>
   As he moved with assurance from one press event to the other
Friday in this hub of commerce and culture on the banks of the
Rhine River, Clinton appeared to revel in his renewed relationship
with a press corps more focused on substance than scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly overriding his handlers, Clinton insisted on taking
multiple questions during the sort of routine photo ops that,
during months of impeachment maneuvering, had once showcased
Clinton's frosty relationship with a press corps fixed on the
details of the Monica Lewinsky scandal and frustrated with White
House stonewalling on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   He even stunned a handful of reporters and photographers by
inviting them to join him Thursday night for a dinner of
sauerbraten, apple sauce and dumplings at a Cologne restaurant,
where he chatted into the night -- off the record -- about movies,
novels, food and current events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's eager to talk about the issues and to meet
with the press,'' said presidential assistant Sidney Blumenthal.
``He reflects that privately as well as publicly.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fading emphasis on impeachment -- Clinton was
acquitted in the Senate on Feb. 12 -- the president is riding the
crest of one of the greatest peace time economic expansions in the
nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment, inflation and interest rates at or near
generational lows and job creation, home ownership and family
wealth at or near all-time highs, the American economy is the envy
of the industrialized world. On Friday, Clinton found himself asked
by a Japanese reporter whether he saw Japan's recent growth surge
-- after nearly a decade of weakness -- as an endorsement of Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi's economic policies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's response -- ``It's very good news'' -- meant less than
the question. When Clinton first took office it was more common for
Japanese officials to lecture their American counterparts on
economic policy than to seek their approval of Tokyo's ways.
</P>
<P>
   By far the biggest factor in Clinton's enhanced stature on the
global stage, though, has been the perception that his leadership
was both unique and essential to holding together the 19-nation
NATO alliance during its 78-day air war against Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   As the leaders of the G-7 countries -- the United States,
Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy and Japan -- gathered here
Friday, Clinton announced the latest encouraging statistics behind
NATO's Kosovo operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should all just take a moment to reflect,'' on that
operation, Clinton said, noting that 35,000 Serb forces -- out of a
total of 40,000 -- had vacated the province of Kosovo, as 19,000
NATO peacekeeping troops had poured in, during the week since NATO
air strikes forced a Serb surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three things that we've fought for,'' Clinton said, citing
refugee returns, the NATO peacekeeping force and the exit of Serb
forces from Kosovo, ``are being achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Victory in Kosovo doesn't appear to have notably boosted
Clinton's popularity at home. Only 55 percent of Americans approve
of the way he's doing his job -- with 35 percent disapproving --
according to a poll of 1,153 American adults taken by the Pew
Research Center for the People and the Press between June 9-13.
</P>
<P>
   That's the lowest Clinton's job approval rating has been since
last September, weeks after he went on national television to say
he had intentionally deceived the nation over the nature of his
relationship with Lewinsky, the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   One possible explanation is that the triumph in Kosovo has been
tempered by the humanitarian tragedy in a province where an
estimated 10,000 ethnic Albanians were slaughtered by Serb troops,
police and paramilitary gangs, who forced more than a million
others to flee their homes over the course of the NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't possible to reverse those horrors, even if Clinton
claims to have led NATO in punishing the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   As a way to burnish his image as the twice-elected, and still
very much standing, leader of the last remaining superpower on
Earth, opening the G-7 summit with the news out of Kosovo could
scarcely have been better scripted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There couldn't be any better testament to the new spirt there
is in the world,'' said Blair, ``than the fact that we were
prepared to stand up for the values of civilization and justice as
we approach the 21st Century.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
