<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-QUAKE-0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QUAKE WOUNDS SOUL OF COLONIAL MEXICAN CITY
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PUEBLA, Mexico _ The Spanish painted tiles, Moorish arabesques
and stone sculptures that grace the ancient buildings in this
colonial city are its pride and soul.
</P>
<P>
   And right now people in Puebla are in mourning, fearing that a
6.7 earthquake that struck Mexico Tuesday may have dealt their
heritage a mortal blow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our history has been wiped out,'' said Juan Carlos Castillo,
who stopped with his 5-year-old son outside a 16th-century church
whose bell tower was shredded by the quake, which also killed at
least 23 people in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Architects hope Castillo's prediction is premature and that
careful recontracting -- and millions of dollars -- will save the
majority of Puebla's architectural jewels. This city about 70 miles
southeast of the capital Mexico City is, in fact, so blessed by
buildings of historical and architectural value that it is an
official United Nations cultural landmark.
</P>
<P>
   The death of these 16th- and 17th-century structures with unique
Mexican baroque designs would be like the United States losing New
Orleans' French Quarter or Virginia's Williamsburg. Puebla has a
total of at least 2,600 structures considered colonial treasures or
artistic gems from the 19th and early 20th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   In Puebla's colonial center, initial estimates are that the
quake damaged 33 historic churches, 32 public buildings and six
Autonomous University of Puebla structures. Nineteen buildings,
including the Company of Jesus Church -- built by Jesuits in 1690
-- are considered severely damaged. As many as 300 churches may
have been damaged throughout the entire state of Puebla, whose
capital city was founded in 1531.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe at this point that there are any historic
buildings that will have to be completely abandoned,'' said Sergio
Arturo Vergara of Mexico's National Historical and Anthropological
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday Vergara toured the inside of the badly cracked
