</P>
<P>
   Vergara urged residents not to panic, and said that if Mexico
can earmark government funds and raise money from private sources
and the United Nations many of Puebla's buildings can be at least
partially preserved. Carefully chosen architects with experience in
repairing earthquake damage will have to be enlisted to take apart
damaged sections of buildings and then reconstruct them using some
of the same stones and bricks they were built with centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the teams of experts surveying the damage all agree that
cash-strapped Mexico will need a monumental effort to raise the
funds necessary for such a massive restoration project.
</P>
<P>
   As Vergara and other architects walked the scarred halls of the
400-year-old university building Thursday, the structure moaned and
shuddered occasionally, reminding those inside that it was still
