</P>
<P>
   Mexican soldiers and university employees scurried about,
packing files and carting off debris. The structure is standing,
but large cracks run the entire length of some of its halls, which
are as long as half a city block.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of cupolas that form the ceilings of each hall are cut in
half by huge cracks that expose ancient brick masonry beneath
delicate facades.
</P>
<P>
   Vergara said Puebla's San Agustin Church, whose original
structure dates back to the late 1500's, may fare better than many
Puebla residents initially thought.
</P>
<P>
   Rubble from a collapsed bell tower is primarily material that
was added as late as the 19th century, he said. Much of the the
original tower survived.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds gathered around the San Agustin Church, taking pictures
and wondering what will become of the glistening gold altar and
colonial paintings inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would feel even worse if it it had been a bomb or
something other than a natural disaster that harmed it,'' said
Francisco Reyes, who grew up in Puebla. ``But you can't help but
feel bad. It's like losing a part of oneself.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations recognized Puebla as one of the world's
cultural landmarks ``not just because of the importance it has for
people here, but for humanity. These buildings were outstanding
examples of architecture in their time,'' said Enrique Loyala
Grageda, a Puebla civil engineer and a member of the U.N.
Education, Scientific and Cultural Organization's International
Council of Monuments and Sites in Puebla.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts believe Puebla's colonial buildings might have
fared better if they had received more intensive maintenance over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The historic center needs constant attention to avoid
deterioration,'' Loyala Grageda said. ``And it should start getting
that from now on.''
</P>
<P>
