<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NITEOUT-CATSKILLS-COM     06-18 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-CATSKILLS-COMICS-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-LINERS FOR A NEW GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 20) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``You know what they should call us?'' asked Freddy
Roman. ``Funny comedians. Not Borscht Belt comedians.''
</P>
<P>
   Noisy agreement erupted from around the dinner. Mal Z. Lawrence,
Stewie Stone, Adrienne Tolsch and Dick Capri had finished a
performance a couple of weeks ago at the 92d Street Y, a panel
entitled ``Borscht Belt Confidential.'' All of them said they were
happy to be invited to participate in an evening devoted to
Catksills comedy. They just weren't crazy about the title. ``It's
demeaning!'' boomed Capri, in a voice that did not sound easily
demeaned.
</P>
<P>
   There was no cabbage-based cuisine on the menu at Joanna's, a
little Italian place a few blocks from the Y where this vociferous
group had gathered, but several courses of shtick were served.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like a table near the food,'' said Stone on the way in,
echoing Henny Youngman's standard line on entering the Friars Club
dining room: ``Gimme a table near a waiter.''
</P>
<P>
   Until after midnight, these veterans of the sable circuit told
stories, interrupted and one-upped each other in a scene straight
out of ``Broadway Danny Rose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Too goyish!'' Ms. Tolsch said, when the waiter offered
monkfish. Capri wondered, ``What's a classic Caesar?''The elegant
Lawrence explained: ``After you eat it, they stab you six times.''
</P>
<P>
   The jokes were older than Jeffrey Ross, the kid at the table and
host of the Y event. But he didn't seem to mind. Ross, 33, is also
a stand-up comic and writer. His resume has all the right names on
it (Jay Leno, Conan O'Brien) and the usual clubs (the Comedy
Cellar, Luna Lounge), except for one: the Friars Club, an
institution that used to be considered a retirement home for
has-beens.
</P>
<P>
   When Ross first started playing poker and eating tuna fish
sandwiches at the Friars with men old enough to be his grandfather,
``it was the uncoolest thing I could do,'' he recalled. But his
downtown credibility and industry connections helped make cool
again a style of comedy his peers had written off as beyond corny.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane Garofalo is a Friar now. Last October, Comedy Central's
broadcast of the Friars' Drew Carey roast scored some of the
highest ratings in the cable channel. Buddy Hackett, who got a
standing ovation at the 92d Street Y for telling an ancient
Catskills joke from his seat in the audience, is in the cast of a
biting sitcom called ``Action'' on the Fox network's fall line-up.
</P>
<P>
   With an apprentice's inquisitive awe, Ross asked, ``How did you
guys do late-night shows, then go to work at 9 the next day?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten thirty!'' corrected Stone, 59, who started his comedy
career in the Catskills as a social director at the Concord hotel
(sold last year to Sheraton franchisers), leading groups of
vacationers through their morning rounds of Simon Says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naps were very important,'' added Roman, who is the dean, or
president, of the Friars Club. He started out, at 14, as a busboy
at a small hotel owned by his uncle. At 16, he made emcee,
``because my uncle was cheap,'' he sid. The big act in the
mountains that year (1955): Stubby Kaye, who sang and danced with
Frank Sinatra in ``Guys and Dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Capri felt compelled to interject: ``I opened for Sinatra.
Twice. Never met him.'' The Chairman, he explained, did not like to
waste time with opening acts _ or at all. Once, in Rome, he said,
Sinatra found himself stuck in traffic en route to a show at the
Coliseum: ``He says to the driver, `Couldn't they move it closer to
the hotel?' True story.''
</P>
<P>
   Many anecdotes from the old days involved long-forgotten
bunaglow colonies and tummlers _ Yiddish for the house jesters
hired to keep guests perpetually amused. The name of Myron Cohen, a
Catskills giant, was invoked with reverence. ``A wonderful human
being,'' Roman called him. ``A delicious, wonderful man.''
</P>
<P>
   These stories were often introduced with the prologue ``I must
tell you, in all seriousness . . .'' and concluded, with a hand to
the heart, ``True story.''
</P>
<P>
   Who didn't play the Catskills? The random roster of
show-business names dropped around the table include Sid Caesar,
Danny Kaye, Jerry Lewis, Dick Shawn and Arsenio Hall, who ``died a
horrible death,'' Roman said. He consoled the young Hall in a
coffeeshop afterward: ``I told him, `Up here, if you don't die
first, you ain't gonna live.''' Years later, Roman remembered, Hall
repayed the favor telling a guest not to put down the Catskills and
fondly recalling the name of Freddy Roman.
</P>
<P>
   A little respect is all they're asking, forroutines honed over
half-a-century, in some very tough rooms. ``Audiences never paid in
the Catskills,'' Capri said. ``You had to bang 'em, or they'd get
up and walk! You had to let 'em know where the punchline is.
Subtlety? Humor? Forget humor!''
</P>
<P>
   There was a certain amount of gallows humor, though, on the
subject of lagging careers and intermittent bookings, most of which
are now in Atlantic City or Florida. Stone described his last tour
as ``20 condos in 20 days.'' Many joked that the 92d Street Y was
the best gig they could get. But the mostly gray-haired audience
was their willing captive. Capri killed with the line, ``If a
Jewish man is alone in a forest, and he's talking, is he still
wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   Italian by descent, Capri is Jewish by association. How could he
not be? Catskills comedy is almost by definition Jewish. Lawrence,
who had a cameo in the recent film ``A Walk on the Moon,'' recalled
a stint on the road with Buck Owens and the Buckaroos. ``I said,
`Buck, how come you picked me?' Buck says, `I told 'em I wanted a
fast-talkin' Jew comic and I got you.'''
</P>
<P>
   They are an easy mark, these Runyonesque characters with their
pocket squares, broad delivery and mobster machismo. The Borscht
Belt has been replaced by the Sansabelt. In almost every way, this
group represents everything the younger generation of
``alternative'' stand-up comics set out to rebel against.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Ross said, ``if I can make Dick and Freddy and Buddy
Hackett laugh in conversation, that is a feather in my cap.''
</P>
<P>
   As the dinner broke up, the young Friar put on a baggy white
cardigan that Hackett had given him earlier that evening, was
kissed on the cheek by Roman, and headed back downtown.
</P>
<P>
   True story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
