<P>
   FATHERS-ESSAY (Undated) _ Seeking to get out of the rut of
Father's Day gifts I buy every year from Brooks Brothers or Barnes
&AMP; Noble, I set out to find my father something this year that
appealed to his love of tinkering. By Elizabeth Hayt.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR-SEASONS (New York) _ Designed by Philip Johnson, who is
still given a daily corner booth, the Four Seasons restaurant
opened on July 21, 1959, with a $4.5 million price tag _ in 1959
dollars _ that shocked even jaded New Yorkers. Forty years later,
the Four Seasons thrives. Its singular role in the life of New York
will be marked this Thursday at a 40th birthday party, whose hosts
are Graydon Carter, the editor of Vanity Fair, and Edgar Bronfman
Jr., the president of the Seagram Co., which has been the majority
owner of the restaurant since 1996. By Alex Kuczhynski. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-CATSKILL-COMICS (New York) _ ``You know what they should
call us?'' asked Freddy Roman. (italics)``Funny(end italics)
comedians. Not (italics)Borscht Belt(end italics) comedians.''
Noisy agreement erupted from around the dinner. Mal Z. Lawrence,
Stewie Stone, Adrienne Tolsch and Dick Capri had finished a
performance a couple of weeks ago at the 92d Street Y, a panel
entitled ``Borscht Belt Confidential.'' All of them said they were
happy to be invited to participate in an evening devoted to
Catksills comedy. By Rick Marin. Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-CURSING (Undated) _ The world, and particularly our
rough-edged corner of it, seems to be suffering from a mass case of
Tourette's syndrome. Foul language, once the verbal equivalent of
hot sauce, is less a condiment today than a staple in our daily
lives. Walk into a CD megastore to buy, say, an old Peggy Lee
reissue, and over the in-store stereo system you'll very often hear
new songs with the kind of explicit lyrics that require a parental
warning label. At a PG-rated movie, it is not uncommon to hear
teen-age ushers using R-rated language in full voice. By Frank
DeCaro. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ To garden is to ache. Not only does
gardening entail considerable sweat of brow, but groans and grunts
are also intrinsic to the domain. By Tovah Martin.
