<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A father's lessons, values and humor live on in his grandson
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Ana Pecina Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGVIEW, Texas _ Some of the most powerful people I know are
some of the quietest.
</P>
<P>
   You have met them. They walk in a room almost unnoticed, yet
their presence immediately commands attention.
</P>
<P>
   People lean forward to catch their every word because these
quiet individuals rarely raise their voices but they always have
something worthwhile to say.
</P>
<P>
   My dad is one of those people. He is the stereotypical man of
few words but he is one of the greatest communicators I know. His
teaching is almost
</P>
<P>
   always by example, rarely by lecture.
</P>
<P>
   He can tell a joke as well as anyone but never sets out to do
so. His ``stories'' fit the context of whatever conversation he
happens to be partaking in. He is not a boaster or a braggart but
when he clears his throat, the room falls silent. We all want to
know what he is going to say. Reflections on this Father's Day,
however, led me straight to my son.
</P>
<P>
   At 13, he has provided me with a view of some of his
grandfather's characteristics. It happens in small, seemingly
inconsequential ways. Recently, I was working in the kitchen and
listening to some of that loud rock music from my teen years and my
son walked through the room. Barely above a whisper, he commented,
``All those songs sound the same.''
</P>
<P>
   As I laughed at the reversal of roles, I was struck by sense of
deja vu. I remembered sitting in my parents' living room with my
younger sisters some
</P>
<P>
   30 years ago listening to that very same band. My dad's quiet
remark back then: ``sounds like somebody working on a car.''
</P>
<P>
   My father is fast approaching his 85th birthday as a fairly
healthy man. Still, time is becoming more precious.
</P>
<P>
   As I go about not only asking questions about his past and
gleaning as muchknowledge as I can from him, I also have undertaken
the task of telling him about the many things I have learned from
him.
</P>
<P>
   And as I watch my son grow up, I know that even after my father
is gone, I'll still have his lessons, his humor, his values _ and
the company of a
</P>
<P>
   young man who is very much like him.
</P>
<P>
   Ana Pecina Walker is managing editor of the Longview
News-Journal. E-mail: awalker(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
