<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$Adv20-     06-18 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$Adv20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING IN SHAPE TO TAKE ON THE GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By TOVAH MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was a nascent gardener in the late 1960s, there was a
popular book called ``How to Have a Green Thumb Without an Aching
Back,'' a revolutionary work expounding mulching and other
low-maintenance techniques. It was later reissued under another
title; I think I know why. The original title was an obvious
contradiction in terms.
</P>
<P>
   To garden is to ache. Not only does gardening entail
considerable sweat of brow, but groans and grunts are also
intrinsic to the domain. The pain ensues in the panic of
early-spring planting mania and, if you're worth your salt, it
continues unabated through summer. Aches go with the turf, but
injuries are another matter entirely. All serious gardeners live in
mortal fear of incurring a muscle spasm, wrist trauma or other
debilitating horror that will take them out of commission for the
rest of the growing season.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, I thought the only preventive actions I could
take were bending my knees when picking up manure bags and saying
nightly prayers. Then I met Barbara Pearlman, a 57-year-old former
dancer who has been a fitness expert and personal trainer for 20
years, an avid weekend gardener and author of the new book
``Gardener's Fitness: Weeding Out the Aches and Pains'' (Taylor
Publishing, $12.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``If all you did throughout winter was leaf through seed
catalogs, you are bound to realize aches and pains in spring,''
Mrs. Pearlman said in an interview. At a juncture when your body is
in rock-bottom condition, it is bound to hurt when you suddenly
decide to move mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gardening is an active contact sport,'' she said. And sure
enough, Dr. Gary Ostrow, an osteopathic physician in New York City
specializing in pain management, whose patients include many
gardeners, says he knows when the growing season kicks off. ``They
come in with the whole host of problems, and it's definitely
seasonal,'' Dr. Ostrow said.
</P>
<P>
   In the best of all worlds, gardeners would prepare for the
season by including abdominal strengthening and weight-lifting
exercises into their New Year's resolutions. Prespring training
would be aimed at the back, knees, hands and wrists _ the points of
most common complaint. But who has the foresight or the impetus for
gardener-strengthening calisthenics when the ground is still
frozen?
</P>
<P>
   Spring hurts, but serious injuries may be more apt to occur in
summer. Teresa Cornish, a personal trainer and an intern at the
Rusk Institute of Rehabilitative Medicine in Manhattan, uses the
analogy of ballet dancers' being more prone to serious accidents at
the height of their careers. ``A deconditioned muscle,'' Ms.
Cornish said, ``isn't sufficiently strong to generate enough force
to create a severe injury.''
</P>
<P>
   In spring, the big problem is usually fatigue, and the pain that
accompanies it. Summer is a whole different story. You've built
muscle mass, you've gained strength, so you're more apt to push the
limit. ``You overestimate your strength,'' Ms. Cornish said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Pearlman says that midsummer is when most gardening
accidents happen and that the best precautionary measures are
wearing properly cushioned footwear and being sure to do stretching
warm-ups beforehand. ``You're not warming up for the Olympics,
you're just stretching your hamstrings, knees and other vulnerable
points,'' she said. Knee rolls (lying on your back, knees bent,
moving them side to side) and cat stretches (arching the back
upward while on all fours) are recommended. ``You don't want to do
sit-ups right before you garden,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   During gardening, it's a good idea to alternate activities as
often as possible. ``Switch the workload often, develop
ambidexterity,'' Ms. Pearlman suggested. ``Switch the rake or hoe
from hand to hand. And alternate heavy grunt work with lighter
tasks. You'll still get it all done.'' There are ways of easing
some risks. If you have to push a wheelbarrow uphill, brace
yourself by pulling in your stomach muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you exert, exhale,'' Mrs. Pearlman said. To fend off
accidents when lifting or toting heavy loads, try to move smoothly
rather than making jerking motions.
</P>
<P>
   Although gardeners can be prone to carpal tunnel problems
because of the repetitive nature of some tasks, the back is a
gardener's primary sore point, Mrs. Pearlman said. For this reason,
try to avoid performing chores bending over.
</P>
<P>
   Squat instead. And when you do, ``your heels should be flat on
the ground,'' not raised, Mrs. Pearlman said. ``It isn't easy, but
it's recommended.'' Position yourself as close to your work as
possible so as not to overtax your back in stretching. And when
you've finished, a warm shower or bath is therapeutic.
</P>
<P>
   If you find yourself with severely fatigued muscles nonetheless,
Ms. Pearlman recommends applying a warm heating pad for 15 minutes
on and 15 minutes off to activate the blood flow.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of a spasm, apply ice to keep the swelling down.
Unless a doctor prescribes bed rest after a problem, Mrs. Pearlman
suggests continuing to garden cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   ``But don't be cavalier,'' she said. ``There's no reason why
working the beds should render you bedridden.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
