<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1032 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-ADVISERS20-COX     06-18 1329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ADVISERS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INSIDE AL GORE'S POLICY FACTORY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories for release
Sunday, June 20.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the policies at the heart of his just-launched
presidential candidacy, Vice President Al Gore relies on the help
of a small, tightly knit cadre of advisers who, like Gore himself,
relish the competition of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``A range of views, in many circumstances, is what's wanted, and
(Gore) certainly doesn't discourage competition,'' said William
Galston, a University of Maryland professor who has been a part of
Gore's brain trust since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike President Clinton, whose policy sessions often
resemble a late-night bull session in a college dorm, the Gore
policy team follows a disciplined course, guided by what Galston
calls the ``prism'' through which the vice president evaluates all
issues: ``the well-being of the American family.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the brain trust are ``policy wonks'' around the age
of 50 who share a wry sense of humor. Many are campaigned-hardened,
some even veterans of Democratic Party politics of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   When the Gore brain trust assembles _ typically about once a
week, if travel schedules allow _ it is not unusual for its members
to stage debates for the vice president. And Gore often adopts the
strongest argument as his stand, according to Galston.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, for example, the Gore advisers debated whether the
federal government should form partnerships with religious
organizations involved in social work. Galston argued that
religious organizations are better suited than government to heal
families torn apart by social ills, while Harvard law professor
Christopher Edley asserted that such an arrangement was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Galston prevailed. And within weeks, Gore came out in favor of
the partnerships in an Atlanta speech, promoting the notion that
``the power of love'' and ``the politics of community'' can restore
families and rebuild neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Gore uses these debates to examine all sides of an issue, even
though he often knows in advance what his position will be.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to shaping policy, ``we do not and will not have
an elaborate process as everyone else in the race, for one simple
reason _ the vice president has been in office seven years and he
knows 10 times as much as anyone else,'' said Elaine Kamarck, a
Harvard University political science professor who serves as the
unofficial chair of Gore's group of advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to be briefed on issues,'' she added, a veiled
reference to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican
presidential front-runner. Bush has spent much of this spring
studying national and foreign issues in preparation for his first
White House run.
</P>
<P>
   Kamarck, 48, the executive director of Visions of Governance for
the 21st Century, a research program at Harvard University's John
F. Kennedy School of Government, is the most experienced
``political practitioner'' in Gore's brain trust, having worked on
five presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   She is media-savvy, but sharp-tongued. It was Kamarck who helped
stir up media interest in Gore's Atlanta speech by telling
reporters: ``The Democratic Party is going to take God back this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to joining the Harvard faculty, Kamarck was Gore's senior
policy adviser, a position that gave her responsibility for the
National Performance Review, the official title of the Gore-led
effort to ``reinvent government.''
</P>
<P>
   But before that, she was a senior fellow at the Progressive
Policy Institute, the think tank of the Democratic Leadership
Council (DLC), the centrist organization founded after the
disastrous defeat of Walter Mondale by Ronald Reagan in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Kamarck and Galston published many of the policy papers that
eventually became the ``New Democratic'' philosophy on which Bill
Clinton ran successfully for president in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Gore's positions are not forged in a political vacuum,
but his brain trust is not restricted to DLC types. A relative
newcomer to the group, for example, is Housing and Urban
Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo, the personable son of former
Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York, who advises the vice president on
community development.
</P>
<P>
   Edley is another example. He is largely responsible for the vice
president's ``livability'' agenda and ``lifelong learning''
proposals. But it is on the issue of race that the influence of
Edley, an African American, is mostly felt.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Great Society'' liberal who was one of Mondale's policy
advisers in the 1984 presidential campaign, Edley is a staunch
defender of affirmative action. He helped fashion the Clinton
administration's defense of the anti-discrimination program: ``Mend
it, don't end it.''
</P>
<P>
   He also has helped Gore connect with black voters. He arranged
the vice president's 1998 Martin Luther King Day speech at
Atlanta's Ebenezer Baptist Church, in which Gore, with a preacher's
cadence, railed against opponents of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has also reached beyond the DLC for economic advice. He
often consults former Federal Reserve vice chairman Alan Blinder,
now an economics professor at Princeton University, and Laura
Tyson, dean of business at the University of California at Berkeley
and a former chairman of the White House Council of Economic
Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suggest the following ...'' is a typical professorial
preface to Tyson's remarks. She is more relaxed and jovial than
most of Gore's advisers. When she worked at the White House, her
staff called her Laura.
</P>
<P>
   Blinder, an avid tennis player and sports fan, is a
self-described ``inflation dove'' who tends to emphasize job
creation over any fear of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that Gore would turn to former Clintonites
for economic advice, since it is in the area of economic policy
that the vice president would be least likely to initiate major
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the policies President Clinton and I have proposed ...
America now has the strongest economy in the history of the United
States,'' Gore said in formally declaring his presidential campaign
Wednesday (June 16). ``We remember what it was like seven years
ago. And I never, never want to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, even on economic policy, ``it is in Gore's
interest to go beyond the Clinton circle if he is to effectively
make the case that he is his own man and not just a Clinton
clone,'' warned West.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign policy side of the Gore team _ virtually unknown
outside of Washington _ is led by Leon Fuerth, a former Foreign
Service officer who for the past 20 years has advised Gore on a
wide range of international and military issues.
</P>
<P>
   The quirky and always rumpled Fuerth is ``one of the most
powerful but rarely seen people who play major roles behind the
scene in Washington,'' diplomat Richard Holbrooke wrote in his
memoir, ``To End a War.''
</P>
<P>
   He is a member of the so-called ``principals committee'' in the
Clinton foreign policy apparatus and often sits at the table with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Defense Secretary William
Cohen and White House national security adviser Sandy Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Fuerth hardly ever grants interviews, unusual for someone in
Washington who is at the center of policy making. But it is rare
that Gore does not mention Fuerth when discussing foreign policy
with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two of them underwent a mind meld at some point,'' said
Chris Lehane, the vice president's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Fuerth is an improbable example of the wry humor found in Gore's
brain trust. Once, during a flight to California with the vice
president, Fuerth went to the lavatory to change from a sport shirt
and khakis into a business suit. ``This,'' he said, ``is where I go
into the phone booth and come out as _ STAFF MAN!''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
