<HEADER>
A1037 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PIRATES-BOS &LR;      06-18 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PIRATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PIRATES' HAS GEEKY FUN WITH JOBS AND GATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
PIRATES OF SILICON VALLEY 
Starring: Noah Wylie, Anthony Michael Hall, Joey Slotnick, John
DiMaggio, Josh Hopkins 
Written and directed by: Martyn Burke 
On: TNT 
Time: Premieres Sunday at 8 p.m. 
Rated: TV14 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Pirates of Silicon Valley'' is an amusement-park ride of a
movie, a breezy trip through the ups and downs of the rivalry
between Apple's Steve Jobs and Microsoft's Bill Gates. It's
stylized, surfacy fun, sketching out classic moments in Silicon
legend and Geek culture without really expecting you to grok the
meaning of terms like BASIC, MS-DOS, and Xerox PARC. With a giddy
script and a pair of EZ-to-watch performances, particularly from
Noah Wylie as the obsessive Jobs, the movie is very user-friendly:
Personal Computer History for Dummies.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say that ``Pirates of Silicon Valley,''
premiering Sunday night at 8 on TNT, approaches accuracy, or even
fairness. Writer-director Martyn Burke doesn't bother with
three-dimensional portraits of his pirates or their business
tricks, opting for the broad, the provocative, and, as the industry
explodes wide open, the exhilarating. The unauthorized portrayals
of both Jobs and Gates are negative, for the most part, with the
two men graduating from their quirky college visionary days to
become business tyrants and unappealing individuals. And robbers of
sorts, as they have the insight and ambition to piece together
their revolution from the products of other companies.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is mostly interested in Jobs, whose
hippie-to-big-bully story is juicier than Gates's misfit-to-Big
Brother story, and offers better soundtrack opportunities (is that
really ``In-A-Gadda-Da-Vida''?). We see Jobs as a young, bearded
hippie at Berkeley, taking acid and dancing with the Hare Krishnas.
We hear him railing against IBM and spouting grand notions about
the industry: ``This ain't just business. This is practically
spiritual. This is about overthrowing dead culture, dead gods.''
And finally we see him as a demented leader and soul-sucking
employer, throwing tantrums in the office and demoralizing his
workers. One of the movie's only sympathetic bits shows him as a
troubled adoptee hiring a detective to find his real mother. Later,
when he coldly rejects his own daughter, Lisa (after whom he goes
on to name a computer), we're probably meant to understand his
discomfort with parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, meanwhile, is forever sitting bug-eyed at his computer,
in aviator glasses. While Jobs prods investors with a religious
fury, Gates takes the diplomatic approach to moneymaking: ``Your
machine is brilliant, but it needs our language.'' In some ways,
Gates's stiff, bland demeanor and his talent at poker make him seem
like more of a monster than Jobs, whose flagrant flaws are
recognizably human. But Gates is really a supporting character in
``Pirates,'' there mostly to provide a cool contrast to Jobs. As
Gates, Anthony Michael Hall sets up a collection of convincing
physical attributes, then adds a bit of vague mystique to the mix.
His Gates never seems to have much of an inner life, but then that
may be Hall's precise intention. When an enraged Jobs yells at him,
``You took our stuff, you fooled with it, and you called it your
own,'' he replies, ``Yeah, so?''
</P>
<P>
   Wylie, on the other hand, is a thunderstorm as Jobs. On ``ER,''
he brings a subtle range to his recovering-preppie doctor, John
Carter, but in ``Pirates'' he lets his freak flag fly, with his
Jobs walking that fine line between the headiness of the 1960s
counterculture and old-fashioned fascism. Sure, the period costumes
and makeup help, but Wylie delivers. So does Joey Slotnick as Apple
cofounder Steve Wozniak, the easy-tempered, technology-minded half
of the Apple team who left Apple in 1985 to teach computer classes.
His Woz is the movie's conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pirates'' is alternately narrated by Woz and Gates's
right-hand man, Steve Ballmer, an unnecessary technique that
ultimately peters out. But the real problem with ``Pirates'' comes
at the very end, when the movie trails off without a sufficient
sense of climax. Instead of using the end to clarify and put a
point on the drama of envy and competition and self-delusion and
power that we've just watched, writer-director Burke lets the
action dissipate. The movie disappears in a momentary glitch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
