<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOUR-SEASONS-ART-$ADV     06-18 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUR-SEASONS-ART-$ADV20-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LUNCH COUNTER FOR THE CITY'S POWERFUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., June 20) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a day in early June, a day of unusual social synergy,
when normally opposing planets orbited each other for a brief
moment, aligned and then spun back away into their separate
universes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Grill Room of the Four Seasons restaurant, Brooke Astor
and Barbara Walters occupied the center booth. As delicate looking
as a pair of painted dolls, the two, grande dames of New York
society and media, did not sip their espressos; they merely touched
the silver-rimmed cups occasionally with the most tentative,
symbolic hand gestures.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the room, the designer Yves Saint Laurent sat
while a blonde _ his frequent companion, Betty Catroux _ spoke loud
French and, holding up her arm as if for a bicep curl, fanned the
air beneath her outstretched limb.
</P>
<P>
   And at the far end of the room, the rock star Bono was arriving
to sit down with Timothy P. Shriver, the director of the Special
Olympics and the brother of Maria Shriver. His hair sprouting
erratically upward, Bono wore wraparound sunglasses and took a seat
next to a third table mate, a young woman who seemed to be wearing
a children's toy in her hair. Bono craned his neck up to survey the
room and mouthed one word, ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one bothered to look. Because in the Four Seasons _ where
everyone is well known, wealthy, powerful, politically connected,
supernaturally beautiful or just lucky to be there _ Bono was not,
in this room, a world-famous rock star. He was just there.
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons _ with its coolly elegant interior that is a
designated city landmark _ is New York's ultimate grown-up version
of the high school cafeteria, except every table is the cool table.
On almost any weekday at lunch in the Grill Room _ the smaller of
two rooms with 20-foot ceilings and walnut paneling _ there are so
many familiar figures from finance, politics, media and fashion
that this city of seven million can seem like Mayberry R.F.D., made
up of 100 or so souls, and the Four Seasons its Snappy Lunch
counter at the corner of Main and Elm Streets.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Philip Johnson, who is still given a daily corner
booth, the restaurant opened on July 21, 1959, with a $4.5 million
price tag _ in 1959 dollars _ that shocked even jaded New Yorkers.
Some of the potential names for the restaurant considered by the
then-owners, Restaurant Associates, included Cleopatra's,
Season-o-Rama, Season-Go-Round and Restaurant of the Seven Wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, the Four Seasons thrives. Its singular role
in the life of New York will be marked June 24 at a 40th birthday
party, whose hosts are Graydon Carter, the editor of Vanity Fair,
and Edgar Bronfman Jr., the president of the Seagram Co., which has
been the majority owner of the restaurant since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons may be the only place in the world where a
plain baked potato _ without butter, without sour cream _ costs $9,
a bottle of Bordeaux can easily run $800 and a woman who eschews
dessert will find herself face to face with a three-foot-high pile
of cotton candy, a not-so-subliminal exhortation from the waiter to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   Lest you complain about the price of the baked potato, Julian
Niccolini, the maitre d'hotel, will respond by sending a bushel of
raw Idaho potatoes to your office, and raising the price on the
menu.
</P>
<P>
   Peter G. Petersen, the chairman of the investment banking firm
Blackstone Group, and recipient of such a bushel, sums up the Four
Seasons like this: ``The booths are far enough apart that you can
have a private discussion. The real New York, New Yorkers go there,
like Lew Rudin, Barbara Walters, Diane Sawyer. And it's a social
experience. You'll always see six or eight people who are fun to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Other New York restaurants have their particular crowds. Broadly
speaking, Michael's attracts the publishing world, 44 at the
Royalton Hotel the fashion industry, ``21'' Club the investment
bankers and Wall Street, Elaine's the cigar-chomping columnists and
actors.
</P>
<P>
   But none have the architectural grandeur of the Four Seasons or
the ability to mix movers and shakers from across the board. If New
York business and society were the mafia, the Four Seasons, wedged
into a corner of the Seagram Building on Park Avenue and 52d
Street, would be the meeting place of its five families' high
commission.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it maintains an unexpected level of democracy.
Alan Richman, the food critic for GQ magazine, said that the Four
Seasons ``is one of the last high-level democratic institutions.
You'll see Si Newhouse sitting next to a tourist from Cleveland.
It's one of the things I love about the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Political reputations are not burnished to a high gleam at
``21'' Club, whereas Richard C. Holbrooke, the investment banker
who is the president's nominee to be chief envoy to the United
Nations, is a weekly regular at the Four Seasons. And so is Alfonse
D'Amato, who may no longer have a political reputation to buff, but
he dined there last Monday with Charles A. Gargano, New York
state's commissioner of economic development, and Steven T. Florio,
the president of Conde Nast Magazines. The assumption that
deal-making is always the matter at hand is clearly in effect:
``There's nothing going on here!'' Florio said upon spying a
reporter and waving his hands in front of him, as if to deflect a
wild-eyed member of the paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Fortune 500 Mortimer's,'' said Michael Batterberry, a
cultural historian and co-author of ``On the Town in New York: the
Landmark History of Eating, Drinking and Entertainments from the
American Revolution to the Food Revolution'' (Routledge, 1998).
``Symbolically, its landmark status is apt in that sense. People
who eat there are painfully famous, and excited to see each other,
and famous people seem to need that kind of exclusive shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   Batterberry added that much of the restaurant's feeling of
finesse and pranksterish joie de vivre emanate from Niccolini, a
native of Tuscany, who is also the co-manager and a minority owner
of the Four Seasons. (His rather more forbidding Austrian
counterpart, Alex von Bidder, is the restaurant's general manager
and also a minority owner.) ``Julian understands the discreet
hand-flashing and signals, the subtle salutations across a sea of
celebrities,'' Batterberry said. ``By now, I think it is
indestructible.''
</P>
<P>
   Niccolini, indeed, plays the role of conductor. Every morning
before 11 a.m., he begins constructing that day's seating chart, as
elaborate a diagram as a set of stage directions for a Puccini
opera. His theory is simple: ``If I see a story in the newspaper
pitting two people against each other,'' he said last week over a
glass of 1996 Clos St. Denis, ``then I try and put them near each
other. If I see that an ex-boyfriend and an ex-girlfriend are
coming in, Woops! They go next to each other.'' He paused, sipped
his wine, and said: ``Take into consideration that I am a devil.
But I am a good devil.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Niccolini takes pride that he is as much an agent provocateur as
he is a restaurateur. Two weeks ago, Niccolini seated the
Washington Post columnist Lally Weymouth directly across the room
from Andrew Stein, the former Manhattan borough president. Stein
was lunching with Shirley MacLaine, a longtime friend. Niccolini
said he watched, bemused, as Stein beckoned Ms. Weymouth to come
over and visit their table several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Weymouth thought I was playing Cupid,'' Niccolini said.
And he did not deny it.
</P>
<P>
   If decorum seems to accompany every meal at the Four Seasons, it
is not always the central ingredient. Last summer, for example,
there was ``the naked ladies' incident,'' as the staff calls it.
``A certain New York gentleman of means,'' Niccolini said, asked
him to make sure that his girlfriend and three companions had a
nice lunch in the restaurant's adjoining Pool Room, which features
a softly splashing fountain constructed of white Carrara marble.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much did they drink?'' Niccolini asked himself, stroking
his chin and lifting one eyebrow. ``They drank eight bottles. No,
it was 11 bottles of wine. I walked up to see how they were doing _
it was four women, and 11 bottles of wine is a lot, you know? One
woman said to me, `Julian, can I go for a swim?' No one was left in
the Pool Room, so I said, `Fine. Do whatever you want.' And she
took off the napkin on her lap, and she was totally naked!''
</P>
<P>
   The four women slipped into the pool, he said. He did not stop
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop them?'' he asked, his eyes wide. ``But I'm Italian!''
</P>
<P>
   The women splashed around in the 400-square-foot pool until the
staff gathered, Niccolini said, and then he offered them
tablecloths as towels. The bill for lunch _ 11 bottles of excellent
wine and a few salads _ was $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   In another oft-told incident, Anna Wintour, the editor in chief
of Vogue, was seated in a booth a couple of years ago when an
animal rights protester managed to wind her way past Niccolini and
toss a frozen raccoon on the table, in protest of Vogue's fondness
for fur. Richard D. Beckman, the publisher of Vogue (and a man who
chose the Pool Room as the site for his wedding last fall), said
that Niccolini picked up the raccoon with a tablecloth and asked
the woman, ``Would you like me to put this in the freezer for
you?'' ( Niccolini said that he did not remember exactly what he
said, but he was sure it was not that witty.)
</P>
<P>
   It was Lee Eisenberg, writing in Esquire magazine in the late
1970s, who is thought to have coined the term ``power lunch'' in a
reference to the noon meal at the Four Seasons. And there, last
Wednesday, was the Israeli Ambassador to the United Nations, Dore
Gold, with Ms. Weymouth. (``She's having a good hair day today,''
Niccolini mused.) There was Barry Diller, Art Buchwald, Mortimer
Zuckerman and Joe Armstrong, the publisher of Capital Publishing,
who last month wandered over to Brooke Astor's table, kissed her on
the cheek and said, ``Brooke, did you get that flashlight I sent
you last week?'' (Mrs. Astor, he explained, was traveling to
England, and she had complained to him about the habit in English
country houses of turning off the electricity at night.)
</P>
<P>
   On another date earlier this month, Vernon Jordan worked the
room, receiving at least three visitors to his booth, and stopping
by at least three more tables. Senator Charles Schumer dined in
late May with Bronfman, atop the Grill Room balcony, Bronfman's
usual aerie. Lisa Caputo, Hillary Rodham Clinton's former press
secretary, at center stage down below, wiggled her finger in their
direction and, the husky tones of intrigue coloring her voice,
said, ``I wonder what's going on up there?''
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons works in part thanks to the daily choreography
of Niccolini, and to the famous clientele, further guaranteed by
the presence of the dashing Bronfman _ with his dining companions
from the worlds of politics, business and Hollywood. The
restaurant's landlord is the current owner of the Seagram Building,
the Teachers Insurance and Annuity Association-College Retirement
Equities Fund. ``The rent is substantial, but it allows us to stay
in business,'' von Bidder said. The restaurant generates about $16
million a year in revenue, according to Restaurants and
Institutions Newsletter, the sixth highest-grossing restaurant in
the city. It ranks behind Tavern on the Green, Windows on the
World, Smith &AMP; Wollensky, Sparks and ``21'' Club. But whereas those
others earn their grosses primarily through high turnover of the
tables, the slower-paced Four Seasons charges sky-high prices _ an
average of $100 a person with wine. The Zagat Survey ranked it No.
1 in popularity in 1989, 1990 and 1991; it is now No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   In these giddy times, the prices have not kept customers away.
John Mariani, the author of ``The Four Seasons: A History of
America's Premiere Restaurant'' (Crown, 1994), said that 20 years
ago, the restaurant tended to frighten customers with its frosty
treatment. ``The first time I went there, I tell you, I was coming
up that stairway, and I did not find it a happy place to be,'' he
said. ``It was back in the '70s, and my college friends and I
brought my mother there for drinks, because it was all we could
afford. And we walked out on the bill because no one would bother
to bring it to us.'' Mariani said he has owed them $17 ever since.
``There was something fierce about it then. But they have loosened
up. In terms of the parties they have and the kinds of things
they'll let you do there, well, with enough money, you can get them
to do anything for you.''
</P>
<P>
   For the restaurant's 40th birthday cocktail party this week,
over 800 guests _ Ron Perelman, Wendy Wasserstein, Charlie Rose,
Tommy Mottola, Barry Diller, Ed Koch, Jonathan Tisch, Bryant
Gumbel, Larry Gagosian, David Dinkins _ are expected to throng the
Pool and Grill Rooms.
</P>
<P>
   And Richman, the GQ critic, is nervous. ``People are calling me
to see if I can bring them,'' he said. ``This is the first
out-of-control event I have heard of at the Four Seasons. So this
party gives me the chills. I definitely wanted to be there when it
was a mere 40th anniversary cocktail party. Now, do I want to be
there just because it's important to be there?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
