<HEADER>
A1049 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     06-18 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER'S DAY IS ALL ABOUT ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucky is the boy with a dad like mine. I'd wish for every lad to
have, and every dad to be, such a father. His was clearly the
greatest influence in my life, and the memories of things he said
and did are fresh with me daily, although he died 37 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, my father didn't have a dad to remember. His died
when my dad was an infant. His mother was a polio victim, confined
to a wheelchair. My father, consequently, had to leave school in
the fifth grade to chop cotton and later work at a brick kiln.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now with ghetto youth, the quickest route to money for
a strong Texas farm boy lay in professional athletics. Jack Johnson
was heavyweight champion. Dad, at 20, became a professional boxer,
performing in Detroit, Philadelphia, New York.
</P>
<P>
   When he'd saved up enough cash, he returned to Weatherford and
bought a cleaning establishment and a tailor shop. He also was
commander, in his 20s, of the local National Guard unit when
President Woodrow Wilson federalized the Texas National Guard. It
patrolled the Mexican border to deter incursions by Pancho Villa's
revolutionary army.
</P>
<P>
   There, in the Big Bend town of Valentine, Dad and Mother were
married. She, a teacher and drama coach, was enormously helpful to
him. Dad was an avid reader with a voracious thirst for history,
and the two shared a lifelong love of poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Dad's unfulfilled ambition for higher formal education made him
determined to avail his children of its benefits. Before I was 8,
he was taking me to college football games where he'd extol the
special virtues of various centers of learning.
</P>
<P>
   He gave me my first serious nonfiction book when I was 7. It was
a biography of Jack Dempsey. I practically memorized it. Soon I had
a life story of Andrew Jackson. Then one of Knute Rockne.
</P>
<P>
   Dad and Mother never subscribed to the theory that their
children should be seen but not heard. They actively encouraged
self-expression in each of us. To recite a newly memorized poem at
the dinner table _ be it philosophical, sentimental or humorous _
earned our parents' outspoken approbation.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh grade, I was convinced that geography was boring
until Dad began telling me of things he'd seen in some of the
countries that my class was studying. He convinced me that travel
was fun, and infinitely more fun for somebody who'd studied the
geography of the area and knew what to look for.
</P>
<P>
   He taught me tricks of memory _ like associating names with
other objects _ that made it easier to recall the capitals of other
lands. Constantinople, for example, was a breeze. Just remember:
Can't stand on an apple!
</P>
<P>
   I was 11 the year we lived in Duncan, Okla. Dad was manager of
the local chamber of commerce. We didn't have a car, or really need
one. We walked.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dad's conviction that a boy should have a job. Each
Saturday morning I'd earn a quarter delivering circulars. For a
dime I'd attend a Saturday afternoon movie, and a nickel bought a
hamburger. That left a dime to spend however I wished.
</P>
<P>
   I'd carefully examine the colorful Sunday papers at the town's
best newsstand and then take one home _ from Denver, or Chicago, or
New York. I always looked for one with the most funnies and the
best sport section, so Dad and I could discuss upcoming events.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday mornings, the family went to the Presbyterian church.
But Sunday evenings belonged to Dad and me. We'd visit, by turn,
Duncan's other churches. All had Sunday evening services in those
days. Walking home, we'd discuss the minister's sermon _ its
content, mainly, but also the preacher's oratorical style.
</P>
<P>
   At 12, I was accompanying Dad occasionally on ``Good Will
tours'' to surrounding rural communities. In those days before
television, entertainment was scarce. The chamber of commerce, in
behalf of the town's merchants, would bring home talent to the
hustings. I'd play the harmonica. Later in the program, a sparring
partner and I would put on a boxing exhibition. I didn't know I was
learning things, but I was _ things like confidence and
self-reliance.
</P>
<P>
   Dad was an egalitarian. He met everyone on a level plane.
``Never look down on anybody because of his circumstances,'' he'd
say, ``and never let anyone look down on you for any reason
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   He despised pretensions of class.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such thing as an upper class or lower class in
America,'' he believed. ``Not in this country. Maybe in India or
even England, but not here. In America, the only ceiling above you
is the one you make for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifted with a winning personality and a sense of humor, my
father made most of his own breaks in life. Because he did, the
breaks came easier for me.
</P>
<P>
   Early in my political career, I once complained about three men
who'd opposed my election to the Texas Legislature. ``They've
appointed themselves my enemies,'' I stormed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, now, that's a rare opportunity,'' Dad replied. ``You
don't have to accept them as enemies unless you want it that way.
Why not make friends of them? Show them you're a better man than
they supposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Right again! All three ultimately became friends.
</P>
<P>
   Through good times and bad, triumphs and defeats, joys and
sorrows, Dad was always in my corner. His spirit still is.
</P>
<P>
   Guys like him are what Father's Day is all about.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101, or at j.wright(at)tcu.edu. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
