<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-PROFILE-HAFT-$ADV     06-18 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-HAFT-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENOUEMENT OF A FAMILY FEUD?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va.)   (af)  
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leave it to the Internet to jump-start the formerly famous.
After making headlines five years ago as a key slugger in the Haft
family's legal brawl, the eldest son, Robert M., has re-emerged
selling vitamins in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, Vitamins.com, based in Falls Church, Va., seems
simple enough: Haft plans to use the Internet to sell vitamins that
are now available in his 10 Vitamin Superstores. But it has a
subplot. Not only does Haft, 46, want to bolster his company's
sales, projected this year to hit $28 million, but he also believes
that the site will reaffirm his stature as a wonder boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel like I have something to prove,'' he said. ``I
have to prove to a broader arena that what my father and I created,
I can create on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   One can understand his trepidation. The Hafts have built some
easily recognized businesses, including the Dart Drug and Crown
Books chains. But they equal the Ewings of TV's ``Dallas'' in
spewing venom publicly at each other. And Haft's new venture could
renew the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Looming behind everything Haft does is his father, Herbert H.
Haft, still recognizable for his lacquered pompadour. The senior
Haft bought a drugstore in 1955 and turned it into a big regional
chain. When the Hafts sold Dart Drug to several of its executives
in 1984, it had more than 70 stores.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Herbert Haft and his wife, Gloria, welcomed their
children into the family business, the Dart Group. Linda, 48, took
a job in finance. Ronald, 39, ran the real estate operation. After
getting an MBA from Harvard, Robert joined in 1977 and soon founded
Crown Books.
</P>
<P>
   The family hit its financial peak in 1993 _ its net worth
estimated at more than $500 million. But then everything fell
apart. That June, The Wall Street Journal said Robert Haft was the
sure heir to his father's job; Herbert Haft was enraged, and Robert
soon received a fax at home from his father's lawyer, telling him
never to come to the office again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herbert saw that Wall Street Journal story as his business
obituary,'' said James G. Leonard, a former director at Crown Books
and Trak Auto, a parts chain that was part of the Haft empire.
``Robert was obviously very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Angry might be more the word. Robert Haft sued his father,
contending wrongful termination, and in 1994 won a $38 million
judgment, including the value of investments, in a federal court.
Although Robert has said he would like to mend the rift, he still
dwells on their differences.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he drew a diagram of Dart's sales. On the far
left of the time line, he jotted ``1955,'' the year of his father's
first store. In the middle of the line, he wrote ``1977,'' the year
he joined the company. To the right, he wrote ``1993.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' Robert Haft said, ``here are their sales until 1977.''
He drew a flat line. ``Well, maybe they did a little better than
that.'' He drew a line with a slight incline over his first one.
``Now, here is where I join the company.'' Haft extended the line
sharply northward, toward the company's peak sales. Then he drew a
sharp plunge from 1993, after his dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   The rift didn't end with Robert's lawsuit. His parents divorced,
with Herbert and Ronald soon parting ways over control of the
company. Robert has remained close to his mother and sister, but he
and his brother speak only occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Haft started over in a group of investors that took
control of Phar-Mor, a chain of discount drugstores, in 1995,
eventually raising $1 billion to pull the company out of
bankruptcy. When he tried to merge it with Shopko Stores in 1996,
some investors balked and bought him out.
</P>
<P>
   Haft, once a dedicated jogger, then decided to turn his health
interests into a business. In 1997, he invested $5 million to start
the 10 vitamin stores in the Washington area. He is so involved
with the Web site that he even picked colors for brochures. He
plans to take Vitamins.com public, but did not say when.
</P>
<P>
   Vitamins.com, which went on line in April, fits into his life
style. He usually walks four miles and pops nine vitamins a day. He
also speed-reads (he finished A. Scott Berg's 628-page biography of
Charles Lindbergh in one night) and attends a Bible class monthly.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason that I really like Vitamins.com is that it allows
me to combine commerce with social good,'' Haft said. ``When I was
running Crown Books, I thought it was good that I was selling books
at a discount price. I have always been interested in how I can
help people.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears, too, that Haft has learned from his father's
mistakes. Haft attributes the family quarrel in part to his
father's controlling of the family fortune. Haft and his wife,
Mary, a producer for public TV, have set up trust funds for their
three children, giving them the freedom to enjoy the money when
they turn 21.
</P>
<P>
   Haft also regrets that he and his father, who gave up control of
Dart Group in 1998, aren't closer. But they may have a chance to
battle again. Herbert Haft has announced his own Web site,
Heathquick.com, to sell vitamins and nonprescription drugs. It is
set to go on line in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our companies sell different things,'' the elder Haft said.
``But as far as there is an overlap, you can buy a small part of
what we sell at his site. We wish him well.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussing his father's new company, Haft became sentimental. He
acknowledged that his father was competition but added that other
companies were bigger threats. Could it be that the Haft family
ruckus has finally ended?
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, I get calls all the time from people who say,
`My father did this or my brother did that to me,''' Haft said. ``I
always tell them the same thing: `Go back and try to work it out.'
I tell people that there's no paper too thin that's there's not
another side to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
