<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV20-COX     06-18 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT TRIAL DRAWING TO A CLOSE
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories for
release Sunday, June 20.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a thunderstorm struck during the afternoon rush
hour one day last week, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson, who presides over the Microsoft antitrust trial, stood in
front of the federal courthouse trying to hail a cab.
</P>
<P>
   Three reporters who have been covering the trial since last
October offered to share their cab with Jackson. To their surprise,
the judge, who is known for keeping his distance from the press,
readily hopped into the front seat.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation during the brief ride dealt mainly with
lighthearted courtroom gossip. But Jackson also chided the
journalists for reading too much into his comments from the bench,
some of which have been interpreted as being anti-Microsoft. In
effect, the judge urged the reporters to curb their guesswork, they
said. With the final defense witness in the landmark case due to
testify this week, both sides have begun to prepare their written
closing arguments. Barring an unexpected settlement, Jackson hopes
to issue his verdict by Labor Day, when the law clerk who has been
tracking the case is due to depart.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will wind matters up Monday by calling its only
economic expert witness, Richard Schmalensee, dean of the business
school at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Schmalensee
had testified in January that Microsoft lacked monopoly power and
that its actions were a legitimate response to intense competitive
pressures.
</P>
<P>
   When the current rebuttal phase of the trial opened June 1,
Schmalensee's earlier testimony drew scorn from Franklin Fisher,
his MIT colleague and former teacher. Fisher, the government's
chief economic witness, accused Schmalensee of ``a lack of
systematic thinking.'' When it comes to antitrust policy, Fisher
said, his one-time student advances arguments that are ``silly''
and even ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of tough talk reflects the high stakes in the trial, a
proceeding in which both Microsoft and the Justice Department have,
from time to time, seemingly scored points that made an impression
on the judge.
</P>
<P>
   In the bringing its landmark case against Microsoft, the
government has sought to prove that the software giant withheld
crucial data about its dominant Windows operating system from its
rivals in a bid to prevent them from building successful competing
platforms. Rather than competing on the merits, the government
holds, Microsoft chose to repeatedly abuse its monopoly position to
retain its huge market power and to gain advantage in the emerging
Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   Some figures in the Microsoft camp fear those arguments have
struck home with Jackson. They've urged Microsoft chairman Bill
Gates to cut a deal that would protect the company from facing
corporate lawsuits based on any judicial finding that Microsoft is
a predatory monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   But Gates instead has bet on his ability to persuade key
lawmakers that traditional antitrust principles developed for
smokestack industries have little relevance in today's fast-paced
high-tech world.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, the multibillionaire spent six hours last week on
Capitol Hill. A lunch with 15 high-ranking House Republicans,
including Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois, was balanced by
another meal with Senate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Several people who were present said Gates had told them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Our customers aren't complaining about our Internet products.
Our competitors egged the trust-busters to bring this case. Most
consumers and software developers see big benefits to them from
Microsoft's commitment to integrated products increasingly attuned
to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ The software industry is one of the great engines of economic
growth and job creation. We will soon surpass the motor vehicle
industry as the top manufacturing group in the nation. Competition
remains incredibly fierce, through rapid innovation.
</P>
<P>
   _ In bringing this case, the government undermined the basic
principle that has made this nation such an economic and consumer
success story. It is seeking to curb our freedom to innovate and to
improve our products, a principle we cannot compromise away.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there's no real mystery attached to Gates' agenda. Nor
is the government shy in dismissing his arguments. As the trial
moves to an end, atop an dozens of boxes of once highly
confidential corporate files, about the only secret left is how the
judge will rule.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
