<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1074 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-VINEYARD-PRICES     06-18 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-VINEYARD-PRICES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINEYARD PRICES SKYROCKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By TED APPEL   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. _ Despite forecasts that grape prices will soon
begin to weaken in California with new plantings starting to reach
maturity, vineyard values along the North Coast area of California
have soared to record highs as vintners continue to plant and bid
up the price of existing acreage.
</P>
<P>
   Even as experts hint that land values may be nearing a peak,
they reported that vineyard prices in the past year jumped 15
percent to 20 percent in Sonoma and Napa Counties. Meanwhile,
demand for vineyard land in the area of best-known appellations
shows no immediate signs of tapering off, several real estate
appraisers reported this week at the annual Vineyard Economics
Seminar.
</P>
<P>
   Some prices are staggering: Buyers are paying as much as
$100,000 an acre for established vineyards in the Napa Valley, said
Karl Bucher, an appraiser with Pacific Coast Appraisal Services in
St. Helena.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of qualified buyers out there who are ready to
buy,'' Bucher said. ``A lot of them have cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Napa vineyards continue to command a premium over Sonoma
vineyards. Undeveloped vineyard land in Napa sells for $37,000 to
$50,000 an acre, while an existing vineyard on phylloxera-resistant
rootstock sells for $41,000 to $100,000, Bucher said. Prices vary,
based on location, the availability of water and the ability to
build an estate home.
</P>
<P>
   In Sonoma County, undeveloped vineyard land sells for $20,000 to
$38,000 an acre, while an established vineyard planted with
resistant rootstock commands $35,000 to $57,000 an acre, said Mark
Gregg, an appraiser with Pacific Coast Appraisal Services in Santa
Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as high as it has ever been,'' Gregg said. ``You have a
lot more buyers than you have properties listed for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   The market is driven by several factors, Gregg said. Wineries
are gaining confidence that demand for top-quality wines will
continue to climb. At the same time, there is a growing sense
within the wine industry that there is a limited amount of
developable land in desirable appellations. Finally, wealthy
individuals who have benefited from a strong economy want to live
among the vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect to see vineyard prices soften over the next two
years,'' Bucher said. ``Longer term, we are going to see some
softening.''
</P>
<P>
   Although per-capita consumption of table wine is growing in the
United States, global consumption is sinking while vineyard acreage
and wine production is growing, said Barry Bedwell, president of
Allied Grape Growers, a Fresno trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the challenge that confronts us,'' Bedwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Bedwell forecast that vineyard acreage in the North Coast will
grow 35 percent from 1997 to 2001 for the four major wine
varietals: chardonnay, cabernet sauvignon, merlot and zinfandel. To
absorb those grapes, vintners must increase their sales by 7
percent annually, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seems to be a very much doable rate of growth,'' Bedwell
said. However, growers and vintners could be forced to cut prices
if they cannot boost demand for wines.
</P>
<P>
   New vineyards in the Central Valley _ where cotton farmers are
continuing to convert their fields to grapevines _ threaten to
produce a surplus of cheap wine, Bedwell said.
</P>
<P>
   North Coast growers and vintners will be protected somewhat from
volatility in prices because they specialize in producing
top-quality varietals, Bedwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk wine market has slowed in recent months, an early
barometer of demand for wine, said Steven Fredricks, vice president
of Turrentine Wine Brokerage, a San Anselmo wine broker.
</P>
<P>
   Fredricks said the industry is moving into an economic cycle
where there is a ``slight excess'' of wine. He said vintners'
marketing costs are rising, growers are receiving lower prices in
some parts of California and consumers are seeing a better
selection of wine and some lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
