<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN19-CO     06-18 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: The spirit of the 20th century
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While in our nation's capital, I made it a point to
visit the Smithsonian Aeronautics and Space Museum to pay my
respects to the inventor of the artificial heart.
</P>
<P>
   That's where you can view his airplane hanging from the ceiling,
the Spirit of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we forget, Charles A. Lindbergh, at some point after he got
through soloing the Atlantic Ocean from New York to Paris, got
around to inventing the artificial heart.
</P>
<P>
   When he demonstrated it for a couple of hundred scientists in
Europe, the astounded medical gathering predicted that history
eventually would record his flight only as an asterisk, while
remembering Lindbergh chiefly for his genius as an inventor.
</P>
<P>
   Always hard to say ahead of time what history will say.
</P>
<P>
   At the Smithsonian you also can view Dr. Robert H. Goddard's
1926 rocket, which eventually would lead to space travel. It was
Lindbergh who helped secure early funding for Dr. Goddard's private
experiments in New Mexico that went all but unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh could see what our own government couldn't. Goddard's
work would not be fully appreciated by Washington until after World
War II, when interrogators quizzed captured Nazi rocket scientists
on the workings of their V-1 and V-2 missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans couldn't have been more puzzled. Why not simply ask
your own Dr. Goddard, the scientists replied. That's where we got
our ideas, from studying his work.
</P>
<P>
   As for Nazis, it's hard to argue that Lindbergh was not of a
similar persuasion in a kindly sort of fashion, though he never
realized it.
</P>
<P>
   His speeches urging America to stay out of World War II were
seen as appeasement, pro-Nazi and anti-Semitic, and they often were
full of all of that. Poor Lindbergh believed he was doing what was
right for America, and was never so wrong.
</P>
<P>
   He redeemed himself after Pearl Harbor, flying some 50 combat
missions in the Pacific and even shooting down a Zero in a
dogfight, though he was officially assigned to the war zone only as
a civilian adviser.
</P>
<P>
   In the years after the war, he would fight a different kind of
world war, helping to launch the environmental movement around the
globe. Sad to say that while he was out trying to save the whales,
his wife, Anne Morrow Lindbergh, stayed home having an affair with
her psychiatrist.
</P>
<P>
   For a guy caught up in the importance of eugenics _ a pop form
of genetics that fueled a racist culture in the first half of this
century _ he ignored the fact that his wife's family had a history
of emotional illness that spanned three generations.
</P>
<P>
   But it was, of course, the kidnapping and murder of the
Lindbergh baby that shaped, if not warped, the marriage for all
their lives. His wife could not forget that Lindbergh never once
cried, even when the body was finally discovered. Such was his
stoicism.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the stuff of heroes, triumph and tragedy. And what a
triumph!
</P>
<P>
   When Columbus sailed for the New World, he was accompanied by
three ships and their crews.
</P>
<P>
   When astronaut John Glenn circled the earth, he was supported by
the finest computer technology of the day and remained in almost
constant contact with NASA ground control.
</P>
<P>
   Remember those few moments when radio contact was blacked out
during re-entry. Remember how America held its breath.
</P>
<P>
   For Lindbergh, one man in a single-engine airplane guided by
compass technology, that few moments equaled 33 hours and 30
minutes. From takeoff in New York until touchdown in Paris, he was
on his own in an undertaking fueled foremost by his personal
courage.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine his life. He knew the first man to fly an airplane. He
knew the first man to walk on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   You can read all about it in a wonderful book, ``Lindbergh,'' by
A. Scott Berg, who this year was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for
biography.
</P>
<P>
   (P.S. Lest we forget, Lindbergh did that, too, with his own
book, ``Spirit of St. Louis.'')
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
