<HEADLINE>
LUXEMBOURG AMBASSADOR TO HOST WELCOME DINNER FOR HORMEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Luxembourg's ambassador to the United States,
Arlette Conzemius, will host a dinner at her country's embassy here
to welcome gay rights advocate James C. Hormel to his new post as
U.S. envoy to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased to be able to make this gesture,''
Conzemius said in an interview Friday. ``It's a welcoming and also
a farewell because he's going to Luxembourg.''
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, who will be sworn in at a State Department ceremony June
29, will become America's first openly gay ambassador. He received
a recess appointment from President Clinton on June 4 after more
than 18 months of Senate battles over his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Conzemius said Luxembourg's 340,000 people are not concerned
with Hormel's sexual orientation and want to proceed as if the
Senate fights ``had not interfered'' with his appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll work with him as ambassador; there's no other issue from
this side,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Four conservative senators had put a so-called ``hold'' on
Hormel's nomination, thus blocking a vote on him, because they said
they feared he would pursue a gay agenda in the Luxembourg post.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, a San Francisco philanthropist and heir to a meatpacking
fortune, said he would not do that. But Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott _ who has linked homosexuality to alcoholism, sex
addiction and kleptomania _ refused to lift the hold. Hormel was
said to have had the support of at least 60 of the Senate's 100
members.
</P>
<P>
   Infuriated by Clinton's action, Sen. James M. Inhofe, R-Okla.,
one of those who had put a hold on Hormel's nomination, threatened
last week to block Senate confirmation of the president's other
civilian nominees. But on Wednesday he backed off after Clinton
agreed to notify senators before they go on recess if he plans to
make another recess appointment while they are out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Conzemius said the resistance to Hormel's nomination ``was a bit
unexpected. We consider those matters private ... We hope to be a
tolerant society.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that a new nondiscrimination law went into effect May
1 in the 15 member nations of the European Union, including
Luxembourg. The law contains a provision that says the union's
council ``may take appropriate action to combat discrimination
based on sex, racial or ethnic origin, religion or belief,
disability, age or sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Conzemius said guests at the dinner will include Hormel's family
and friends as well as members of Congress from California who
supported his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Hormel's partner, Timothy Wu, was invited, Conzemius
said she could not divulge the guest list. But she added that
accepting Wu ``is not a problem for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to make this very smooth and very normal,'' said
Conzemius, a career diplomat who arrived at the Washington embassy
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Conzemius also declined to reveal the date of the dinner but
said it would be before Hormel is sworn in. The menu, she said,
would provide a ``summerlike meal with a French flair,'' including
a cold soup, salad with fish and a main course of meat.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel and Conzemius met at the embassy last week and discussed,
among other items, an American art exhibit headed to Luxembourg.
She said she found him ``motivated, interested in doing positive
work and very charming.''
</P>
<P>
   Hormel, 66, is divorced and has five children and 13
grandchildren. He has said that Wu, who trains people to be
fundraisers for nonprofit organizations, will remain in San
Francisco and will not live with him in Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Conzemius said she is looking forward to having the
ambassadorial post filled. It has been vacant since Hormel's
predecessor, Clay Constantinou of West Orange, N.J., left in
January. Constantinou is a lawyer, a former state finance chairman
of the Democratic Party and a former trustee of the Democratic
National Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
