<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEB REWRITES THE RULES ON CUSTOMER SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every so often, corporations rededicate themselves to the idea
of ``customer service.'' This usually occurs immediately after a
sharp downturn in earnings. The boss needs something to say and
someone to blame. Promising better customer service beats
confessing that senior management is clueless.
</P>
<P>
   Most senior managers think of customer service as playing client
golf on a weekday afternoon. The idea that companies have to be
responsive to the people who buy their products _ that they
actually have to interact with them _ is so foreign to their sense
of order and hierarchy that the mere thought of it gives them the
willies.
</P>
<P>
   In an idealized corporate world, customers simply buy the
product and go away. Anything beyond that involves time and money
that could be more profitably expended elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   One of the true horrors of the Internet is that it makes
customer service an essential component of successful business. In
the good old days _ five years ago _ customer service was
invisible; an unflappable voice on the other end of an 800 number,
a letter in the mail explaining some foul-up.
</P>
<P>
   Today, customer service is the front line of e-commerce. It
involves not just transactional success, but a company's brand
image as well. How well it works determines how a company is
perceived. If it doesn't work, the effects are immediate and
profound.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the on-line auction house eBay learned this lesson
the hard way. EBay's computers crashed, rendering its site
inoperative for 22 hours. Over the course of the next few days, the
company lost $4 billion in market capitalization and watched in
horror as some of its best customers double-clicked to Amazon.com's
and Yahoo's auction services.
</P>
<P>
   Big disasters like eBay's computer crash happen irregularly. But
little disasters take place every day and have real consequences.
Consider the following personal experiences.
</P>
<P>
   I recently became eligible for the Boston Globe Employee
Association's 401(k) plan. I was happy about this, since it allowed
me the opportunity to shelter 8 percent of my income. I was also
happy about this because Putnam Investments manages the BGEA 401(k)
plan. I know that Putnam is a first-rate investment firm. I filled
out the forms, making a point of giving Putnam my e-mail address as
well as my postal address. Two weeks later, I received a letter
from Putnam that said: ``Your personal identification number is
1234.'' Nothing else. Not: ``Thanks very much for your business, we
really appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not: ``What else can we do for you?'' Just: ``Here's your
number.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of this transaction, I now think less of Putnam
Investments. I am the definition of a good customer (whom Putnam is
theoretically devoted to) because I am willing to give them, every
week, 8 percent of my income. One would think Putnam would be all
over me, with e-mails and updates and newsletters and
recommendations and research reports, in an effort to get more of
my business. But Putnam doesn't think of me as their client; they
think the BGEA, an affiliate of the Newspaper Guild, is their
client. That's not what I expect from a company to whom I give 8
percent of my income.
</P>
<P>
   I expect that because that is what the Internet does; it makes
me think I'm important. And that is what the Internet does for the
50 million Americans who use it; it makes them think that companies
that offer services work for them.
</P>
<P>
   If I could, I would leave Putnam tomorrow and walk across the
street to Wellington or Fidelity. I probably can't, because the
BGEA doesn't offer its members a choice. But eventually it will,
because it must (unions that don't offer its members a choice
probably won't survive in the new economy). And when it does, I'm
out of Putnam. I don't want any part of a company that doesn't
``get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Weirdly enough, companies that you would never expect to ``get
it,'' do. General Motors recently launched a car-buying service on
the Internet. I have a car lease that soon expires, so I have been
going to the Web to check out my options. Last weekend, I inquired
about two GM products. Within two days, I had seven e-mails from
five different GM dealerships, all of them ``on the case.'' One guy
in Long Island said he would drive the car to me for a test drive.
</P>
<P>
   A brand I thought was great _ Putnam _ I now think is brain
dead. A brand I thought was brain dead _ GM _ I now think is great.
That's a big change in three weeks' time. Multiply my own
experience 50 million times and you get some sense of the
importance of Internet-based customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that don't ``get'' this change will find their best
customers double-clicking away. Customer service is no longer about
lip service. It's now the leading edge of brand management.
Corporations that understand this will be the major brands of the
new economy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
