<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLINGTON-TRIBUTE1STT     06-18 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLINGTON-TRIBUTE1STTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Century drawing to a close on a note of high praise for
prolific, unrivaled jazz master Ellington
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 20.
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the next-to-last year of the 20th century belongs to any
American artist, it belongs to Duke Ellington.
</P>
<P>
   And he's having a timely centennial celebration to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Which, thanks to our national passion for pre-millennial
retrospection, means that the all-embracing composer may finally be
getting full due for his unparalleled achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one major example: Though he led his first band at age 18
and didn't stop until his death at age 75 in 1974, Ellington only
this year won a Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   The posthumous award was better late than never, even if it
smacked of arbitrary atonement. What Edward Kennedy Ellington did
was simply too massive, too singular and too influential to be
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the firstest with the mostest,'' says Phil Schaap, a
Grammy Award-winning record producer, music historian and jazz
radio host for New York's WKCR-FM, who is producing a series of
historic Ellington reissues for the Sony Legacy label. ``He wrote
tunes, tunes with lyrics, blues, extended forms, opera, ballet,
Broadway shows, movie soundtracks, concertos, piano concertos,
individual concertos for band members. There is an element here
that is otherwise not captured in jazz, a prolific nature that
isn't rivaled. You'd have to turn to somebody like Bach.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta audiences can get a taste of that unrivaled nature
today, when the African-American Philharmonic Jazz Orchestra gives
a free concert at the Auburn Avenue Research Library, and Saturday,
when the Duke Ellington Jazz Orchestra visits Chastain Park
Amphitheatre, playing a benefit concert for the National Black Arts
Festival. The latter group, a 15-piece ensemble conducted by Duke's
grandson Paul Mercer Ellington, is what's known as a ``ghost
band.'' Like orchestras once led by Count Basie, Sun Ra and Charles
Mingus, it will strive to sustain the spirit of its namesake, even
though its swing can never mean precisely the same thing as it did
in 1919 or 1927 or 1942 or 1956 or 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you compare anybody to Duke Ellington?'' asks Rocky
White, who joined the band as its drummer not long before
Ellington's death. ``Paul's learning the business, learning his
way. It wouldn't be fair to compare him to his dad (Mercer
Ellington). The one constant is Duke Ellington's music.''
</P>
<P>
   The band's tour is but one of many musical tributes in this
summer of Ellingtonia:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra, featuring trumpeter Wynton
Marsalis, is on a world tour playing Duke's tunes _
</P>
<P>
   one facet of its parent organization's yearlong Ellington
salute, which includes everything from
</P>
<P>
   a national high school band
</P>
<P>
   competition to PBS specials and Manhattan street parades.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On Monday, trumpeter Terence Blanchard performs the master's
soundtrack to ``Anatomy of a Murder'' at a public screening of the
1959 film in New York's Bryant Park.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Saxophonist David Murray is touring with a program devoted to
the ``obscure works'' of Ellington and his longtime collaborator,
Billy Strayhorn.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The 24-CD set ``The Duke Ellington Centennial Edition: The
Complete RCA Victor Recordings, 1927-1973'' arrived in late April,
at once the biggest reissue package ever distributed by a jazz
label and the ultimate totem for obsessive fans willing to spend
$400.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  With more than 200 titles in print already, Ellington also has
a box set _ ``The Duke'' _ coming out in August on Sony Legacy (a
mere three CDs) and batches of individual re-releases that boast
improved mastering and previously unheard material.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of a real, ongoing thing,'' says Valerie
Capers, a New York-based pianist and educator who straddles
classical and jazz worlds on her new album, ``Wagner Takes the `A'
Train.'' ``He will really take his place in history in a monumental
way.''
</P>
<P>
   How monumental, exactly, is mind-boggling. Historian Schaap
masterminded a 24-hour-a-day radio broadcast of Ellington that
began April 20, a week before Ellington's 100th birthday, and
concluded 13 days later. Surely the vaults were exhausted?
</P>
<P>
   ``We played roughly 10 percent of what we had,'' Schaap says.
</P>
<P>
   Ellington produced so much because he never stopped producing.
Over a span of more than 50 years, he was able to maintain and
compose for a band of usually first-rate musicians who were always
in his employ. His orchestra, as is often said, was his instrument,
and he composed with the individual sounds of specific players in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the history of jazz since World War II, I only know of five
or six ensembles that were able to stay on the road and tour 200
nights a year,'' says Rob Gibson, executive producer and director
of Jazz at Lincoln Center. ``John Coltrane didn't do that. Miles
Davis didn't do that. Duke Ellington had years when he was on the
road 300 nights a year. That's an astonishing achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   What made it work was Ellington's incarnation of something
otherwise mythic: He was the total artist, as populist as he was
avant-garde, as entertaining as he was subversive. His stature as a
creative genius is secured by universal appeal. People who agree on
little else can easily agree on Ellington, even when they take
different lessons from his example. New York pianist Matthew Shipp,
recently featured in Downbeat magazine as part of a new generation
of players shaping the future of jazz, cites Duke as an inspiration
even on his most abstract pieces. While others might look to the
virtuoso tradition of Art Tatum, Shipp considers Ellington the
father of modern jazz piano, the square root from which sprang
Thelonious Monk and then Mal Waldron, Cecil Taylor, McCoy Tyner,
Randy Weston and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel him, when he's playing the piano, constantly
smelling and tasting overtones, the harmonies and colors,'' Shipp
says. ``He's totally like a child in the joy that he got in seeing
just how far he could extend certain harmonies, the relativities of
note choices. He was operating on so many levels, but sometimes a
short introduction to a tune, in and of itself, is a whole musical
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of Ellington's gift, in a world where either/or
choices are the norm, is that it always offered a both/and
proposition. Listeners can take pleasure in the microcosmic
details. As Shipp observes, ``He has a way of wringing his wrist
that gets a bell-like quality out of chords that's very unique.''
Or they can sing along, swept up in melodies sturdy and lyrical
enough to last into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something that separates Ellington from other
composers in jazz,'' Gibson says. ``He has `It Don't Mean a Thing
(If It Ain't Got That Swing),' `Do Nothing 'Til You Hear From Me,'
`In a Sentimental Mood,' `Prelude to a Kiss,' `Perdido,' `Beginning
to See the Light,' `Sophisticated Lady.' . . . Even if people can't
necessarily hum the melody to it, they kind of know the song. He
was a force in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
