<HEADLINE>
ANIMANIACS TAKE PLAYERS THROUGH MOVIE SET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland, Fla., Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In early 1998, I reviewed a kids' software game: Animaniacs'
Game Pack. It was a collection of five games featuring the
Animaniacs _ three cartoon characters from Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   It was software with a sense of humor, and even though geared
toward the 8-and-up mind, an adult with an aversion to Barney the
Dinosaur could delight in a slapstick put-down titled ``Baloney's
Balloon Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   The Animaniacs are back. SouthPeak Interactive's Animaniacs: A
Gigantic Adventure (Windows; about $20) is a side-scrolling
adventure that takes players through the fictional movie set
``Gigantic.'' (Think luxury liner and you'll have the idea.)
</P>
<P>
   Players help Yakko, Wakko and Dot evade Thaddeus J. Plotz and
his henchmen, who are trying to destroy old films and movie posters
on the Warner Bros. Studio's back lot.
</P>
<P>
   There are 11 different levels that can be played on three levels
of difficulty. Players can play on an Internet mode (two to four
players can compete against one another on MSN Gaming Zone) or two
players can take turns at the computer trying to score the most
points.
</P>
<P>
   Players start out on the Bridge level of the Gigantic. It's
basically a learning level where players find out how the game
works and what they're expected to do.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Baloney, from the previous Animaniacs' CD, appears
in this game too. He's one of the characters the Animaniacs must
defeat. His attack mode: He'll hug you to death.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1728EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1108 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLINGTON-TRIBUTE2NDT     06-18 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLINGTON-TRIBUTE2NDTAKE-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA: force in this century.''
</P>
<P>
   RECOMMENDED RECORDINGS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to start: Taste has a lot to do with this question.
Because Ellington's career passed through so many stages, new
listeners may want to consider the kind of Ellington they'd most
enjoy. Though, obviously, he's remembered for his orchestra, all of
Duke's music begins at the piano. ``Money Jungle'' (1962, Blue
Note), a meeting with modern titans Charles Mingus and Max Roach,
makes a gentle argument for delicacy, the chime and glimmer of
Ellington's piano underpinning melodies that are heartbreakingly
lyrical. A more standard recommendation is ``The Blanton-Webster
Band'' (1942/1986, RCA), a three-CD set that documents what many
consider to be Ellington's finest band (with bassist Jimmy Blanton
and tenor saxophonist Ben Webster) and the influence of composing
partner Billy Strayhorn. The collection illustrates the magic
Ellington could work even within the three-minute song form.
Included are ``Jack the Bear,'' ``Never No Lament,'' ``Harlem Air
Shaft,'' ``In a Mellotone,'' ``Warm Valley,'' ``I Got It Bad (And
That Ain't Good),'' ``Main Stem'' and ``Perdido.'' RCA will reissue
the set later this year with improved sound.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What's next: Snatch up the revised/reissued ``Ellington at
Newport 1956 (Complete)'' (Columbia/
</P>
<P>
   Legacy), which captures the explosive concert that signaled
Ellington's late-'50s ``comeback'' and nearly sparked a riot. The
two-CD set boasts 100 minutes of new material. It presents, for the
first time in stereo, the actual concert as it happened, with the
studio material that originally substituted for the real deal. The
audio is thrilling: The audience, gone berserk after Paul
Gonsalves' legendary 27 choruses on ``Dimuendo and Crescendo in
Blue,'' refuses to let the band leave the stage. So Duke wisely
decides to keep playing, even as promoter George Wein shouts at
him, ``No! No! No!'' Producer Phil Schaap's liner notes tell the
whole story behind one of the most notorious concerts in jazz
history.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boxed bonanza: Completists will dip into the stocking fund for
``The Duke Ellington Centennial Edition: The Complete RCA Victor
Recordings 1927-1973'' (RCA). List price is $407.52 for this
limited edition set, which spans Duke's career, from the band he
led at the Cotton Club during the Harlem Renaissance to his
latter-day masterpiece ``The Far East Suite.'' The surplus of bonus
tracks can be a boon to the obsessive, though an annoyance to
listeners who prefer to simply hear an album. The package, which
includes a 128-page book and a red clothbound box, is gorgeous. It
is widely discounted. Last week, the Internet retailer CD Now
(www.cdnow.com) was selling it for $285.58 (plus shipping). A
simpler three-CD survey, ``The Duke,'' is due Aug. 10 from
Columbia/Legacy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   IN CONCERT
</P>
<P>
   African-American
</P>
<P>
   Philharmonic Jazz Orchestra
</P>
<P>
   4 p.m. today. Saluting Duke Ellington's 100th birthday. John T.
Peek, conductor. Free. Auburn Avenue Research Library, 101 Auburn
Ave. N.E. 404-730-4001.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Ellington Orchestra
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Saturday. $15-$25. Chastain Park Amphitheatre, 4469
Stella Drive N.W. 404-817-8700.
</P>
