<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1109 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPERA-PREMIERE20-COX     06-18 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-PREMIERE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From `Rough Beast' to polished `Frederick'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 20.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frederick the Great is an unlikely hero for an opera _ but no
more so than the creators of an opera about the 18th-century
Prussian military genius that receives its premiere this week at
Clayton College &AMP; State University in Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Corse, a professor of English and director of theater at
Clayton State, wrote the music for this three-act work. It's not
the first opera by the 59-year-old composer, but it is the longest
and most complex of his ventures into music-theater.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Fairchild, 29, who wrote the libretto, is a former student
of Corse's who graduated from Oglethorpe University and just
completed his master of fine arts in playwriting at the University
of Georgia. An Army brat whose father had three tours of duty in
Germany, Fairchild has a strong interest in German history, which
has provided the raw material for nearly all his plays.
</P>
<P>
   They range from ``What Rough Beast Slouches,'' about Kaiser
Wilhelm II, to ``Three Weeks,'' about the Berlin Olympics of 1936,
to ``Second-Hand Hagiology,'' his thesis play at UGA, about a group
home for dead saints (displaced from bombed churches in Wiesbaden)
and a gaggle of American Army wives who want to turn the home into
a thrift shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear the next thing I write will be about America,''
Fairchild says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frederick Hohenzollern,'' Corse and Fairchild's opera, has its
roots in ``Rough Beast,'' which was produced at Clayton State and
at the 14th Street Playhouse in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its title (from a poem by William Butler Yeats), ``Rough
Beast'' is a drama about Wilhelm's friendship or love affair with
his diplomatic adviser, Count Philipp Eulenburg, who was hounded
from court after a journalist attacked their relationship. In the
play, Eulenburg reminds the monarch that their closeness is not the
first of its kind in the German royal family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives a speech that tells the story of this opera,'' Corse
said. ``And I told Brad: `This is what I've been looking for.'''
</P>
<P>
   That was almost four years ago. Corse wrote some preliminary
music, including an overture, that has since been dumped. Last
spring, both felt spurred to finish the opera, which they completed
in about three months.
</P>
<P>
   Corse, who has undergraduate and master's degrees in music from
North Texas State University, where he studied with Samuel Adler,
has written shorter operas. As might be expected, all have literary
sources: a one-act called ``The Open Window,'' from a story by H.H.
Munro (a.k.a. Saki); another called ``Ligeia,'' from a story by
Edgar Allan Poe. He's written ``quasi-cabaret music'' for
Fairchild's ``Three Weeks,'' and they've also collaborated on a
children's musical based on Rudyard Kipling's ``Just So Stories,''
which has been given at Spivey Hall for school-age audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I've never done anything of this scale,'' Corse says of
``Frederick.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a grant from Info Basics of Atlanta and student
activity fees, the premiere is sung by a largely professional cast.
The conductor is William Whitefield of New York, the stage director
David Z. Saltz of the University of Georgia faculty. The scenic
projections and the expressive poster design are by Suloni
Robertson, an artist from Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The singers include baritone H. Brent Weaver, faculty composer
at Clayton State, as Frederick's repressive father, Frederick
William I, and soprano Cheryl Boyd-Waddell, a voice teacher at
Clayton State, as his mother, Sophia.
</P>
<P>
   Soprano Wendy Baker, who sings the role of Frederick's sister,
and tenor Lee Compton, who sings Frederick as an old man, are both
members of the Atlanta Opera chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Tenor Victor Floyd, who sings the young Frederick, is an
affiliate artist at Emory University and music director at North
Decatur Presbyterian Church; and baritone Jay Beadle, who sings the
roleto C.P.E. Bach's father, Johann Sebastian Bach, with a request
for a set of variations. The result was Bach's late masterpiece,
``The Musical Offering.'' The final duet of ``Frederick
Hohenzollern'' is based on that tune.
</P>
<P>
   _Judith Green
</P>
<P>
   ``Frederick Hohenzollern.'' Libretto by Brad Fairchild; music by
Larry Corse.
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Thursday-Saturday.$10. Thursday performance benefits
Project M.A.G.I.C. and Project Open Hand/Atlanta; VIP tickets ($50)
include reception. Spivey Hall,
</P>
<P>
   Clayton College &AMP; State University, 5900 N. Lee St., Morrow.
770-961-3683;
</P>
<P>
   404-872-8089 (benefit).
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
