<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1111 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-CAREER-CHANGE-$AD     06-18 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CAREER-CHANGE-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EX-TRADER ROLLS THE DICE HAPPILY, IN LAS VEGAS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Nev.)   (af)  
 By LAURA PEDERSEN-PIETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Woody Allen tells it, his father was replaced at work by a
machine that could do everything better and faster than he did. So
then Woody's mother said she wanted to buy one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. Peter J. LaBadia has also felt the anguish of being
replaced by a machine, though his wife, Beverly, has no intention
of replacing him. In the 1980s, LaBadia was pulling down $250,000 a
year as a floor broker at the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Then computers were installed so that orders could be executed
electronically, and his commissions dropped below the cost of
leasing a seat. ``It started costing me money to go to work,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, at 50, he left Wall Street and, with another former
broker, bought a printing business in central New Jersey. But after
three decades of swapping stocks and options in fractions while
frantically throwing hand signals to clerks in the balcony, LaBadia
found that printing overlapped with neither his experience nor his
interests. He missed the action and camaraderie of the stock
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   He has found all that again _ and more _ in Las Vegas. After
moving to Nevada a year ago, he enrolled in a seven-week course at
PCI Dealer School, where he learned to deal blackjack and craps,
oversee a gambling table and pay off on bets. On his first day out
of school, he was hired full-time to run a craps table at the El
Cortez Casino in downtown Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Having lived for many years within driving distance of Atlantic
City, LaBadia was not exactly unfamiliar with gambling. He and his
wife had often made day trips to Harrah's there, usually to play
blackjack. Though by no means a big bettor, he tended to win a bit
more than he lost.
</P>
<P>
   His new starting salary is just $24,000, but it takes only a few
months for someone with good skills to move up. Dealers at top
casinos like Harrah's, the Mirage and Caesar's can make $60,000 a
year and qualify for health and retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
   LaBadia hasn't read a shelf-full of career advice manuals. But
his intuition has led him to the pith of their recommendations:
Assess your skills and your passions _ then see them in a new
light. And he has clearly found a way to harness his Wall Street
acumen in a different venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the exchange,'' he said, ``I did a lot of math very quickly
in my head and kept track of a big deck of orders and listened to
four different conversations at the same time.'' At the craps
table, he must keep track of bets, chips, points and dice and keep
things flowing smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   In his new setting, the gregarious LaBadia (known to ask his
bank teller for ``10s, 20s and an 8-by-10 glossy of yourself'')
still feels right at home.
</P>
<P>
   The road from high finance to the world of high rollers is not
one-way. As fast as computers eliminate jobs in the financial
markets, they create other types of jobs. Consider all those hired
to operate the on-line trading systems and investor Web sites _ not
to mention on-line gambling sites.
</P>
<P>
   And while downsized back-office clerks and floor brokers don't
necessarily end up in Las Vegas or Atlantic City, there are enough
parallels between the Street and the Strip to encourage crossover.
</P>
<P>
   Several options traders at the American Stock Exchange boast of
having been asked to stop playing blackjack at casinos for what is
called ``counting cards'' _ keeping track of what has been dealt.
And the Amex is home to a number of poker aficionados, champion
bridge and backgammon players and a current international chess
grandmaster, Ronald W. Henley.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to use numbers and judge people, of course, proves
valuable in many games. Warren E. Buffett and Bill Gates, for
example, like to play bridge.
</P>
<P>
   As Michael Rosenberg, a 1994 world bridge champion and a current
Amex options trader, explained: ``It's all about looking for value.
You get value when you know how to determine if the probability is
in your favor and then how to act on it.'' You have to have a
system for playing cards, he said, adding, ``it also helps to be
able to read people's faces _ the poker players are best at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Rosenberg doesn't exactly view trading options on Wall
Street as a job. ``It's fun,'' he said. ``Of course, you
occasionally get a run of bad luck. But the same sort of thing
happens in bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   While casinos are proud of the financial credentials of dealers
like LaBadia, brokerage firms don't want investing linked in the
public mind with gambling. A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons declined to allow
one of its stockbrokers, who used to deal high-stakes poker at
Harrah's (a player needed $10,000 just to sit down at her table),
to be quoted for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Las Vegas, LaBadia said working the casinos actually has
several advantages, among them the absence of personal financial
risks. ``I sleep better not worrying about market crashes,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
