<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRICARE-$ADV20-COX     06-18 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRICARE-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILITARY FAMILIES FRET OVER MEDICAL COVERAGE FOR 'CUSTODIAL
CARE'
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 20.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH and SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Jackie Lichnock is a chief petty officer's wife who
has waged a long, pitched battle with tje Pentagon over its
reluctance to pay for the medical care doctors have prescribed for
her dangerously ill son.
</P>
<P>
   When Christopher was born, his skull had prematurely hardened,
leaving too little room for his brain to develop. Doctors removed
the top of his skull, but significant brain damage already had
occurred, and he came home from the hospital with only part of a
skull and a life expectajcy of a weec.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher has defied his grim prognosis, and his mother has
successfully fought off attempts to deny him the medical coverage
to which she is convinced he is entitled.
</P>
<P>
   But Lichnock and others like her fear the Pentagon is on the
verge of picking up a powerful ally in its efforts to contest their
claims: Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Without debate, the House and Senate passed companion measures
</P>
<P>
   that, according to military family advncates, support the Defense
Department's contention that patients with no hope of recovery can
be relegatad to uncovered ``custodial care.'' Even if the patient's
condition requires skilled medical care, Pentagon health benefits
can be denied.
</P>
<P>
   If the provisions ultimately become law, many active-duty
families and military retirees will be in danger of being forced to
turn to Ledicaid or other coverage for the care.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a disgrace,'' said retired Army Col. Charles
Partridge, legislative counsel for the National Association for
Uniformed Services.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the two tiny provisions folded into the massive
$288 billion defense budget appear simply to extend skilled
services such as home nursing to a select group of 25 persons.
</P>
<P>
   But Partridge and other military family advocates fear that by
declaring this group an ``exception'' to Pentagon policy, the
legislation will solidify that policy for all other military
families.
</P>
<P>
   In a response to written questions, the Pentagon stated that the
secretary of defense can waive limitations on ``custodial care''
benefits. However, officials did not respond to the charges by
Partridge and others.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is the unusual definition of the term ``custodial
care'' used by Tricare, the Defense Department's health care
program. The term usually means provision of only such basics as
dressing, bathing and feeding, but the Pentagon, through Tricare,
expands the definition to include skilled medical care if that care
can't be expected to improve the patient's long-term condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``A custodial care determination is not precluded by the fact
that a patient is under the care of a supervising or an attending
physician and that services are being ordered and prescribed to
support and generally maintain the patient's condition,'' according
to the Tricare manual on the Defense Department's Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   For Christopher Lichnock, that means the constant suctioning of
fluid from the tracheotomy tube in his throat isn't covered
because, even though only trained nurses can do the procedure, it
does not improve his chances of recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department has lost two federal court cases in which
Tricare beneficiaries argued that this is a unique and harsh
definition of custodial care that never has received congressional
approval.
</P>
<P>
   In voting to supply continued coverage for 25 Tricare
beneficiaries who have participated for several years in a
``demonstration program,'' Congress would inadvertently provide
that approval, said Charles M. Loeser, a lawyer in one of the two
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a 'stealth' law,'' said Loeser, of South Bend, Ind.
``On its face, it appears to allow benefits to be extended. In
reality, its purpose is to defend against future lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Hickey of the National Military Family Association said
the bill is a ``subterfuge'' that is part of a Pentagon effort to
dump these families into the Medicaid system.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it would actually do is not spelled out in any way, shape
or form,'' said Hickey, who is the associate director for
government relations with the group. ``And the language used
actually disguises what it does.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many active duty families and retirees would be
affected if the provision became part of the final defense
authorization bill.
</P>
<P>
   However, Carrie Sapp, an Oklahoma woman whose special-needs
child has been designated a ``custodial care'' case, said she
personally knew of more than 12.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp and Lichnock, who lives in Jacksonville, Fla., came to
Washington this month to tell members of Congress and their staffs
about problems they were having with Tricare. The two women said
they also asked in a meeting with Tricare officials how many
military families are affected by the custodial care policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us they had no idea,'' Sapp said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Tricare case managers use the threat of being declared
a custodial case ``as a tool to make you do what they want you to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the doctor orders 24 hours of nursing care a day, the case
manager will say something like, 'Well, we can approve 16 hours a
day, but if it goes over that we're going to have to look at
custodial care.' Then you take what you can get and the doctor
takes whatever he can get for you,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Though both the House and Senate have passed budget bills
containing the custodial care provisions, the two budgets differ
slightly and must be merged into a single piece of legislation that
requires another vote before being sent to President Clinton for
his signature.
</P>
<P>
   Hickey's group is working with a coalition of military
organizations to pressure Congress to reword the Tricare language
when a conference committee melds the two budgets when it meets
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to do this, fine,'' Hickey said. ``But by God, I
want it in black and white so everybody knows exactly what they've
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Lichnock will wait to see how this turns out. Within days
of returning from her trip to Washington to lobby Congress on
Tricare, she was notified that her son had been declared
``custodial'' and would soon go from 16 hours of nursing care six
days a week, plus another eight hours on Sunday, to one hour of
skilled nursing each day and a single doctor's visit each month.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly at the same time, Lichnock's pleas were heard by Rep.
Tillie Fowler, a Republican from Jacksonville, who set up a meeting
with her Florida staff to discuss the case. After going over
Christopher's nursing notes, kept by caregivers detailing the type
of medical attention he requires, Tricare officials in that meeting
agreed to provide 24-hour nursing care through November, when his
case will be re-evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the doctor ordered originally,'' Lichnock said.
``But, yes, we expect a battle again (in November). I don't trust
them for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
