<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-STUDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL SEEKS TO OUTLAW INTERNET GAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Warning that adolescents are more likely than
adults to become addicted to gambling, a federal commission
recommended Friday that wagering over the Internet be outlawed and
that states raise the minimum age for placing bets to 21.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gambling Impact Study Commission estimates that
about 85 percent of people ages 12 to 18 have gambled at least once
in their lives and that about 15 percent of those are either heavy
gamblers or are addicted to gambling. Among adults, as many as 7
percent of gamblers are believed to have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``These statistics forewarn of even more serious
gambling-related problems in the future,'' said James C. Dobson, a
member of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, whose recommendations were unanimously supported
by all nine members, sees the Internet as a particular threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gambling on the Internet is especially enticing to youth,
(addicted) gamblers and criminals,'' the report said. ``There are
currently no mechanisms in place to prevent youth _ who make up the
largest percentage of Internet users _ from using their parents'
credit card numbers to register and set up accounts for use at
Internet gambling sites.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission also recommended that states and schools form
prevention programs for adolescents and remind them that sports
betting is illegal. The commission found that betting on sports
``may act as a gateway to other forms of gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   The 300-page report discusses the positive and negative aspects
of legalized gambling and it includes a list of more than 70
recommendations. It will be sent to Congress, the White House,
Native American tribal governments and state governors.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the commission's research was conducted by the National
Research Council, part of the National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, whose members included representatives of the
casino industry, was appointed by a bipartisan group of lawmakers
in 1996. Dobson is president of the conservative group Focus on the
Family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply disturbed by the impact of gambling on individuals,
on families and on communities,'' said Kay James, chairwoman of the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling is a $50 billion annual industry that is permitted in
some form in 47 states. It includes commercial and Indian
reservation casinos, slot machines, state lotteries and horse- and
dog-track betting. In 1973 only eight states had lotteries and one
state, Nevada, had casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Current laws do not address gambling over the Internet, the
newest forum for placing bets that transcends state and national
boundaries. Federal law makes placing a bet or sending gambling
information over telephone lines illegal, but the 1961 law predates
the Internet. Most computer users connect to the Internet through
phone lines but it is also possible to use cable television lines
and satellites, technically skirting the law.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not delve into how U.S. regulators would control
Internet gambling sites located overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The gambling commission estimates that 6.9 million people
gambled over the Internet in 1997 and 14.5 million people did so in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular form of wagering on the Internet is sports
betting, but casino-type games are becoming more popular as
Internet connections become faster.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation is pending in the Senate that would ban placing
wagers over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., said he would also propose legislation
that would prohibit Internet gambling and include the other
recommendations made by the commission. He is the author of the
legislation that created the gambling commission.
</P>
<P>
   But pro-gambling lawmakers have vowed to fight any effort to
impose new federal restrictions on state-approved gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gambling is already well-regulated by the states,'' said Rep.
Shelley Berkley, D-Nev., whose district includes Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The report's recommendations are not binding unless they are
enacted into law. Among other things, the gambling commission
recommends that state governments consider a moratorium on future
expansion of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Commission members admitted that they don't expect many of their
recommendations to actually become law but said the report would
serve to educate policy-makers and the public about the downside of
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the state legislator who has to decide whether to expand
or restrict gambling activity, hopefully the statistics we
collected ... will be helpful,'' James said. ``This report and the
debate is has already created will increase the amount of
information available.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and by
e-mail at jennifer(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
