<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNETEENTH-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOGNITION OF `JUNETEENTH' IS SPREADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CINNAMON BAIR   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On June 19, 1865, Union Gen. Gordon Granger and his troops
arrived in Galveston, Texas, with news that the Civil War was over
and all slaves were free.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time blacks in Texas had heard of the
Emancipation Proclamation, signed more than two years before by
President Abraham Lincoln. Consequently, they became the last
slaves to be freed in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Upon word of their freedom, jubilant celebrations erupted among
blacks throughout the state. The date came to be known as
``Juneteenth,'' an independence day for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   What began as a localized celebration 134 years ago has become a
national phenomenon today. Festivities are planned in nearly every
state. Three _ Texas, Oklahoma and Iowa _ recognize the day as a
holiday. And more celebrations are sprouting up around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly spreading and growing rapidly,'' said Cliff
Robinson, creator of Juneteenth.com, an online database of
Juneteenth activities around the country. ``There's a lot of cities
starting celebrations.''
</P>
<P>
   Juneteenth is recognized as the oldest holiday celebrating black
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of four black holidays gaining prominence nationwide,
including Kwanzaa, which takes place Dec. 26 through Jan. 1; Martin
Luther King Jr. Day, which occurs on the third Monday in January;
and Overcome, which occurs about the time of the Jewish holiday of
Passover each spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a symbol of hope and a symbol of freedom,'' said Michael
Woodward, a graduate student of history who works at the Black
Archives Museum in Tallahassee, Fla. ``It's a day of
reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, all slaves were freed by Lincoln when he signed the
Emancipation Proclamation during the Civil War. That document was
supposed to take effect Jan. 1, 1863.
</P>
<P>
   But the Civil War raged on until May 26, 1865, and the last
vestiges of slavery were not removed until the slaves in Texas
received word of their freedom on June 19, 1865. So that became the
date to celebrate slavery's final eradication in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It could be thought of as the end of the independence movement
in the United States, said Morning Sunday Hettleman of the National
Juneteenth Museum. The United States fought for and received its
freedom from Britain starting on July 4, 1776. Slaves received
theirs on June 19, 1865.
</P>
<P>
   And Juneteenth is for more than just blacks, Hettleman said.
Freedom from slavery was won thanks to Americans of all creeds and
colors, not just blacks. And it meant that no person, regardless of
race, creed or religion, would be forced to work for another person
for free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juneteenth is not just about the black experience,'' said
Hettleman, whose online museum can be found at
www.x-change.com/juneteenth/. ``It's about the American experience.
It's about `e pluribus unum,' '' she said, referring to the Latin
phrase meaning ``out of the many, one.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebration, which originally spread as blacks migrated from
Texas to other parts of the country, has experienced a resurgence
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is on an upswing now,'' Robinson said. ``A lot of
people are learning about it for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the recent increased interest in the holiday is
attributed to advances in civil rights that have caused blacks to
reflect on their own history.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have time to reflect now, we recognize the importance of
this historical event,'' Hettleman said. ``I think as we move into
the 21st century is when we're going to recognize how important our
past is.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
