<HEADER>
A1122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOLEN-BOOKS-NYT &LR;      06-18 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAL THIS BOOK! SOME DO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo., Ore. Mass.)   By JOYCE JENSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If I were asked what book is better than a cheap book, I
should answer that there is one book better than a cheap book, and
that is a book honestly come by.'' James Russell Lowell, poet and
editor (first editor of The Atlantic Monthly), testifying before
the United States Senate Committee on Patents on Jan. 29, 1886.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for many bookstore owners, that is not a sentiment
shared by all of the people who visit their stores.
</P>
<P>
   If the preferences of the book-buying public show up in the form
of a best-seller list, then what of the picks of the book-stealing
public? Arts &AMP; Ideas decided to sample the taste of homegrown book
thieves in an extremely unscientific survey.
</P>
<P>
   Many bookstore owners were reluctant even to acknowledge theft.
(The super bookstore chains like Barnes &AMP; Noble and Borders
declined to make any comment at all.) But among the shops that did
respond, their thieves had remarkably similar tastes. Whether the
West Coast or the East, the Beat poets Jack Kerouac, Charles
Bukowski, Allen Ginsberg and William Burroughs kept popping up as
favorites among shoplifters. (In Britain, The Economist surveyed
booksellers and similarly found that the Beat poet Jack Kerouac had
the No. 1 slot.) Tight behind the Beats, comes the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   At Ventura Bookstore in Ventura, Ca., Kerouac's ``On the Road''
and Ginsberg's ``Howl!'' are at the top of the most-wanted lists as
well as that old favorite, Abbie Hoffman's ``Steal This Book,''
said Ed Elrod, the owner. Tarot cards and how-to books,
particularly sex manuals, are also popular. Even Bibles get taken,
which Elrod says he thinks are used for marriage ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Berman, manager of the historic City Lights bookstore in
North Beach in San Francisco, said that Kerouac, Burroughs and
Ginsberg are the most popular writers to take. It may be a younger
generation of thieves interested in Douglas Coupland's Generation X
books as well.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Millemann, a general manager of the Tattered Cover in
Denver, one of the largest stores in the country at 40,000 square
feet, said the Beat poets rank high in the stolen category, along
with textbooks and art and photography books.
</P>
<P>
   Kerouac is also a favorite at both Shakespeare and Co.'s stores
on the Upper East Side and in lower Broadway in Manhattan. Linda
Marotta, senior buyer at the downtown store, says that Burroughs
and Bukowski are also popular steals. Nick Marino, general manager
of the uptown store, said that Dover Classics books, which sell for
$1 or $2, are also popular. He says he believes that art and travel
books that can be sold on the street are stolen by professionals.
</P>
<P>
   At Powell's Book Store, in Portland, Ore., one of the largest
chain stores, the general manager, Miriam Sontz, said people who
take books fall into two categories: those who steal on impulse and
those who take books to sell for money. She said that people take
books they would be ashamed to buy: books on cocaine cultivation,
sex dysfunction or ``racy'' books for teen-agers. Bibles are also a
favorite, she added, saying she does not know why.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Watkins, vice president and general manager of Vroman's
Bookstore, which has been in Pasadena, Calif., for 105 years, said
that drug dealers and the homeless steal salable books. She said
she believed that these thieves were given lists by used-book
stores specifying which titles were in demand. Art books, first
editions and hard-cover mysteries are hard to keep on the shelves,
she added.
</P>
<P>
   The Strand Book Store in Manhattan seems to attract a more
intellectual crowd. Although electronic detectors installed five
years ago significantly cut down on theft, the owner, Fred Bass,
said that before the heightened security, Greek and Latin classics,
books on higher mathemathics, philosophy, Judaica as well as other
scholarly and religious books were targets. These days, he said,
art books are taken by professional thieves.
</P>
<P>
   At Green Apple Books and Music in San Francisco, the general
manager, Pete Mulvihill, reports that current favorites for
shoplifters include Bibles and books on philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Across the bay, in Berkeley, Patrick Marks, buyer for Cody's
Books, said that before the security system was updated, works by
Toni Morrison and Bukowski would be stolen. Now the more persistent
thieves are more interested in monster books, language audio tapes,
Tarot cards and coins that come in game books.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuscaloosa, Ala., the Book Cellar's manager, Edna Thomas,
said that stealing was not a major problem, although occasionally
rock-and-roll and computer-game magazines were taken.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, theft does not seem to be much of a problem in
Martha's Vineyard, the small affluent resort. Dana Anderson, an
owner of Bickerton &AMP; Ripley in Edgartown, Mass., said that books on
summer reading lists were stolen occasionally as were small gift
books but that nothing major had been shoplifted. Alex Comfort's
``Joy of Sex'' used to be a favorite of thieves, she said, so the
store stopped stocking it.
</P>
<P>
   In Wareham, Mass., on the road to Cape Cod, Steve Bunshaft,
owner of Ken-Mark Books, said there was no problem with stealing.
His real worry? Competition from large chain bookstores in four
nearby malls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
