<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1124 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RAPE-O619-COX     06-18 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RAPE-O619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SERB MURDERS INVESTIGATED, BUT PROBES OF ALLEGED 'RAPE CAMPS'
STALLED
 &HT;    With Photo.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-KLA-0619; G8-KOSOVO-0619.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEC, Kosovo _ Standing looted and lonely on the edge of this
eerily empty city is the Hotel Karagac, which may contain evidence
of one of the most horrid chapters of Serb atrocities during the
ethnic cleansing campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, a villa-type structure around a large courtyard, was
named by the U.S. State Department in May in its report, ``Erasing
History,'' as one of two sites where Serbs were taking ethnic
Albanian women for repeated rapes. But, inspections of the hotel
have not occurred and reporters there Friday were warned it could
be rigged with booby-traps.
</P>
<P>
   Rapes were part of the terror campaign intensified by the Serb
rulers of Kosovo during the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia. The Serbs
have been trying to kill or expel the majority ethnic Albanians
from the southern province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant
republic.
</P>
<P>
   But, while dozens of massacre sites have been found since
Yugoslav forces began withdrawing from the province and NATO troops
entered, evidence of mass rapes has been harder to come by.
</P>
<P>
   British troops found evidence that rapes were committed in the
basement of a Serb police station Thursday, with boxes of condoms,
hard-core pornography and beds with restraints were among the items
in an apparent torture and interrogation center.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army, which has
helped uncover mass graves, said that the evidence of rapes has
come slower because victims fear coming forward and because the KLA
is still securing the region from Serb troops. Also, while bodies
are hard evidence of murder, evidence of rape can be less
definitive.
</P>
<P>
   But, while NATO forces and the KLA have gone to the effort to
close off mass graves, they have not taken action at sites rumored
to have been used for rapes.
</P>
<P>
   Shkendije(CQ) Hoda, deputy KLA commander of information for
Kosovo's Djakovica region, south of Pec, said the KLA have not been
able to track down any direct evidence of a rape center in that
city, though one was reported to be there by the U.S. State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the women have come forward to report it,'' Hoda said.
Among the ethnic Albanians, a largely Muslim group, an extreme
stigma is placed on rape victims.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hoped international aid agencies would help counsel
women who were raped and that the crimes would only be revealed if
``the women of the world will help to convince them that their
stresses will be relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   A superficial review of the Hotel Karagac showed crude graffiti
of women and writing in Serbo-Croatian proclaiming, ``We are the
power forever.'' A woman's skirt was found in the ransacked bar
area.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel is on the edge of Pec in a wooded neighborhood with
few neighbors. The town is still believed to be inhabited by Serb
paramilitary forces and ethnic Albanians have been slow to return
from their refugee hideouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been there because we are doing other jobs that we
think are more important,'' said Pec KLA commander Etem Ceku.
``Yesterday we had more fighting. . . that is more important.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
