<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, June 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, record chill affected portions of the Great
Lakes and Ohio Valley as a large high pressure system from eastern
Canada settled over the region. Similarly, Saturday will dawn quite
cool and clear in the interior Northeast. Abundant sunshine will
propel temperatures rapidly upward, however, with afternoon
readings reaching the middle 70s from Ohio to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Humid air will fuel numerous thundershowers in Florida on
Saturday. The showers will produce locally heavy rain, especially
in southern sections where a slow-moving front augments the ascent
of the sultry air. Intervals of clouds and sunshine will cover the
remainder of the Southeast. Isolated afternoon thunderstorms will
erupt, though it will remain dry in most areas.
</P>
<P>
   Breezes from the south will direct moist air into the eastern
Plains and Mississippi Valley, setting the stage for showers and
thunderstorms. The steadiest precipitation will fall from eastern
Oklahoma to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, the showers and storms will be less numerous but
more potent. Winds changing direction with increasing altitude will
cause a few of the storms to rotate. These rotating thunderstorms,
called supercells, are capable of spawning tornadoes. Eastern
Montana and the western Dakotas are at especially high risk for
severe weather. Clouds and onshore breezes will bring cool air to
the Northwest coast. Interior California and southwest Arizona will
stay torrid while residual moisture in the lower portions of the
atmosphere fuels isolated thunderstorms in southeast Arizona and
southern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Modern Chill
</P>
<P>
   Record low temperatures for June 18 were set at many locations
across the Middle West early Friday as expansive high pressure
crested over the region. In Chicago, the official thermometer
dropped to 46 degrees, eclipsing by one degree a record that had
stood since 1876. Careful records have been kept at most major
cities for about 100 years. But, Friday's chill is made more
impressive when it is considered that in order to set record
minimums, modern air masses must be colder than their 19th century
counterparts records because of the local heating effects caused by
urban growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
