<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN AN INVESTIGATOR BECOMES A TARGET 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If an employee believes he has been discriminated
against at work, he typically lodges a complaint with the human
resource department or affirmative action office.
</P>
<P>
   But what does the employee do when the top officer in charge of
investigating complaints is accused of the very same wrongdoing and
remains in office?
</P>
<P>
   Who does he turn to? More importantly, what can the institution
do to maintain its integrity in handling future discrimination
complaints?
</P>
<P>
   The issue popped up recently in a high-profile case involving
sex discrimination allegations at the University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Equal Employment Opportunity Commission staff members recently
determined that Dennis Duffy, the general counsel of the University
of Houston, created a hostile and abusive working environment for
women and retaliated against an employee who complained.
</P>
<P>
   The case is pending, awaiting settlement discussions. The EEOC
will seek concessions, such as back wages, damages and
reinstatement, and will turn the case over to the Justice
Department if it can't reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   No lawsuit against the university or Duffy has been filed.
</P>
<P>
   Though the situation at the university is unusual, it's even
more unusual, say lawyers who specialize in job discrimination
cases, when the top officer continues handling his or her
anti-discrimination duties as Duffy has.
</P>
<P>
   Duffy didn't return telephone calls for comment. However,
Chancellor Arthur K. Smith said that Duffy is doing an outstanding
job and that he and the board of regents are fully behind Duffy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SHIFT OF RESPONSIBILITIES ADVISED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Notestine, a lawyer who represents employers, said anytime
someone is investigated over allegations of serious wrongdoing,
it's a good idea to shift job responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   That way, employees can feel comfortable coming forward to
complain, Notestine said. Most employers would want to try to keep
a clear path open for making complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Reassigning the responsibilities shows the employees the system
works for them, and it also helps the company's legal position,
because it shows the regulators that the employer is doing
something about the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Bennett-Alexander, professor of employment law at the Terry
College of Business at the University of Georgia in Athens and an
expert on discrimination, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give some integrity to the process,'' she says.
If a company doesn't, she added, ``People won't think it's on the
up and up.''
</P>
<P>
   An employee won't complain if he doesn't feel confident about
the process, she said. And if that happens, employees won't want to
stay and the problems fester.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
COMPANY RISKS LOSING A DEFENSE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Also, by not farming out the duties of the person who handles
sex discrimination complaints, a company can risk losing an
important defense, Notestine said.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled companies can protect
themselves if they have a meaningful system to handle complaints.
But if an employee can prove he was too intimidated to come
forward, a company could lose and wind up liable.
</P>
<P>
   But is it fair to force someone to give up a duty temporarily if
he hasn't been found guilty by a court? Doesn't that affect the
person's reputation? And what recourse does the employee have if,
later, he or she is cleared?
</P>
<P>
   That a lawyer like Notestine who represents companies in
employment cases would urge a client under suspicion to step down
should not be surprising.
</P>
<P>
   The company lawyer is hired to look out for the company's best
interests, even if it means taking actions that might hurt a
potentially innocent employee's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers who represent individuals in such cases also suggest
company officers under suspicion should step aside or voluntarily
give up their sex discrimination investigatory work.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Rosenberg, an employment lawyer who represents
individuals, said he'd advise a client under suspicion to
relinquish his equal employment opportunity oversight while the
case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad to have a cloud hanging over you, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid placing control in the hands of one person or office,
some companies provide many ways to file complaints.
</P>
<P>
   At Baker &AMP; Botts, 34 partners and administrators are designated
as people who can take complaints, said Richard Brann, an
employment lawyer and one of the designees.
</P>
<P>
   That way, people can probably find someone they're comfortable
talking to, said Brann. It takes courage to step forward, he said,
and you have to make it easy, not difficult.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
