<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     06-18 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN DEMOCRATS WALK FINE LINE ON CULTURAL AND GUN VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., N.C., S.C., La., Fla.)   (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers)  
 (bl)  
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was not an easy week to be a Southern Democrat
in the House.
</P>
<P>
   With a high-profile debate on a juvenile crime bill that touched
on gun control, prayer in school, violence in the media and
societal values, Southern Democrats were torn between the desires
of party leaders in Washington and the more conservative leanings
of many voters back home.
</P>
<P>
   The results were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a rash of school shootings, a handful of Southern
Democrats, including Rep. Mike McIntyre, D-N.C., supported new
government restrictions on the entertainment industry, backing a
Republican proposal that still failed because of concerns that such
curbs would violate the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   There were exceptions. For example, Rep. Bud Cramer, D-Ala.,
rejected that GOP effort to make it illegal to sell books, movies,
video games or other materials that are explicitly sexual or
violent to minors. Reps. Mel Watt, D-N.C., Eva Clayton, D-N.C., and
Chris John, D-La., also opposed that measure.
</P>
<P>
   But then Cramer, John, and McIntyre joined 42 other Democrats in
backing the idea that states allow the posting of the Ten
Commandments in public buildings. The measure was passed by the
House on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre, John, and Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C., also supported an
amendment by Rep. Jim DeMint, R-S.C., that makes it harder for
plaintiffs to challenge any religious practices in schools.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Southern Democrats kept a low profile
throughout the debate, declining to take the lead in the fight to
enact stricter gun controls.
</P>
<P>
   Although they voted for some of the measures, they left the
heavy lifting to Democrats from large cities where gun control is
more popular.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Republicans displayed more uniformity and enthusiasm.
They embraced the so-called values amendments and rejected the
stronger gun-control initiatives that had been opposed by the
National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   THE (UN)LOCKED BOX
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are having a mighty hard time displaying consistency
when it comes to protecting Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   They keep pushing legislation that would set up a so-called
lockbox, keeping the Social Security Trust Fund off limits from
lawmakers who want to spend the money elsewhere. But at the same
time, they've voting for bills that violate their own spending
caps.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point. Just hours after Republicans in the Senate tried
for a third time to break a Democratic filibuster against the
Social Security lockbox, many of the same Republicans supported a
separate spending bill that would kick open the lock box to pay for
``emergency'' needs.
</P>
<P>
   On a procedural vote, they supported a bill that would set up a
loan program for the steel industry. Estimated cost: $270 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have it both ways,'' complained Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas. ``You either want to spend money or you don't want to
spend money.''
</P>
<P>
   STRANGE BEDFELLOWS
</P>
<P>
   As a lifelong Democrat, Sen. Bob Graham of Florida might not be
the first choice to headline a policy seminar at a conservative
think tank.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was, center stage at the Heritage Foundation in
Washington, to talk about his proposal to allow private investors
and developers to use tax-exempt private activity bonds to build
schools. Those schools would then be leased to the public school
system.
</P>
<P>
   The Heritage Foundation, a champion of public-private
partnerships and good, old capitalism, sponsored the seminar to
build momentum for the bill, which has already passed the Senate
Finance Committee. Graham supports the measure as a way of
jump-starting school construction, which is lagging behind soaring
student enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is rightfully a state and local matter,'' Graham
said, defending his bill as ``part of what should be a smorgasbord
of innovative school construction incentives.''
</P>
<P>
   GONE FISHIN'
</P>
<P>
   Federal fisheries managers continue to struggle for an
acceptable balance between replenishing the stocks of red snapper
in the Gulf of Mexico and limiting the economic damage to the
thriving recreational fishing industry that depends on the gulf's
signature fish.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest move, the National Marine Fisheries Service upped
the size limit of the allowable catch from 15 to 18 inches per fish
while retaining the bag limit at four per day. The agency estimates
the move will reduce snapper catch and allow the fishing season to
remain open until the end of August rather than closing at the
start of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our analyses suggests the increased size limit will provide
benefits to recreational fisherman and the for-hire fishing
business in the region without affecting the rebuilding schedule
for this overfished stock,'' said William Hogarth, head of the
agency's Southeast region.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin write from the Washington Bureau
of the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
