<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1165 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHITECTURE-LAND-2TA     06-18 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-LAND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE PRITZKER TO THE BLITZKER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Britain, Washington, D.C., Minn.)   By HERBERT MUSCHAMP    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On June 7 Sir Norman Foster received the Pritzker Architecture
Prize. The presentation ceremony was held in Berlin, where, by
chance, Sir Norman's inspired remodeling of the Reichstag was
completed in April. The Reichstag was topped off just in time to
welcome the federal government of a reunited Germany back to its
prewar capital, and to welcome the Pritzker's guests to
architecture's toniest annual bash.
</P>
<P>
   I like the idea of the Pritzker Prize, which had its 20th
anniversary this year. The prize is often described as
architecture's Nobel. If Alfred Nobel, who made his fortune selling
gunpowder, could establish a highly esteemed peace prize, then why
shouldn't we applaud the late Jay Pritzker, who made his fortune
littering the world with Hyatt Hotels, for creating an architecture
prize? At a time of esthetic relativism, the Pritzker is one of the
best instruments we have for distinguishing architecture from
commercial simulations of it.
</P>
<P>
   But the triumphalist aura surrounding the Pritzker Prize is
unsettling in a way that the Swedish Academy's pomp is not. The
designation of the winners as laureates. The spectacular locations
_ Versailles, Prague Castle, the White House _ where the
presentation ceremonies have been held. The celebrity culture,
which the award contributes to, and which degrades architecture.
All this can leave an architecture critic with a feeling of
distaste. But it also leaves me with an uneasy sense of
identification. For, like the Pritzker program, architectural
criticism tends to overlook one simple fact about architecture:
Buildings occupy land. Land is not just so many square feet of
public or private property. As often as not, and regardless of
ownership, land is contested space.
</P>
<P>
   We see this demonstrated graphically when buildings are blown up
or torn down. But even under less dramatic circumstances, property
is a combat zone for opposed interests. What will it be used for?
By whom? Will these community gardens give way to housing? Is the
owner next door allowed to cast shadows on my lawn? And views! Who
gets to control the views?
</P>
<P>
   The smooth skin of architecture glosses over such conflicts. (In
Berlin it's difficult to find where the wall stood just 10 years
ago.) If I think a design is outstanding, the odds are that I'll
gloss over those tensions too. Architecture is a history of style
written by the victors.
</P>
<P>
   Saskia Sassen, a sociologist and urban planning professor at
Columbia University's School of Architecture, argues that such
local disputes are part of a global phenomenon. She has described
ours as a culture of eviction. Land values, free enterprise, the
reliance on housing starts as a leading economic indicator; these
market forces exert a constant pressure to move on. Ms. Sassen
points out that globalization means much more than the
transnational integration of corporate wealth. It also describes
the illegal immigration of the displaced into ``first world''
cities.
</P>
<P>
   If this seems dismayingly Marxist or just plain paranoid, then I
urge you to read ``The Long-Winded Lady,'' a collection of Maeve
Brennan's ``Talk of the Town'' pieces for The New Yorker (reprinted
last year in paperback by Mariner Books). Brennan spent most of her
adult life in small Manhattan hotels. She rented rooms in midtown
in the 1950s and '60s when Rockefeller Center was being extended
westward in the style of the steel-and-glass colossuses that now
line the Avenue of the Americas in the 50s blocks.
</P>
<P>
   The architects who designed the Rockefeller buildings, like
Wallace K. Harrison, were not only responding to economic changes
but were also being idealistic. They believed they were upholding
the principles of good design as taught by the Museum of Modern
Art. Their buildings allowed more natural light into offices and
opened up new spaces to sit or stroll in the congested city. These
were supposed to be good things.
</P>
<P>
   But to Brennan, the long-winded lady, the new buildings were
just office space. ``The new Office Space giants have nothing to do
with our daily lives, or with ordinary things, and they are taking
away our streets,'' she wrote. Yet Brennan seemed conscious that
upheaval, what Henry James called New York's ``perpetual
repudiation of the past,'' was part of the city's excitement. At
least it inspired some of her greatest essays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the inside walls of the building that's coming down
below my office today,'' she wrote in another article. ``Yellow,
green, brown, ugly pale shades of those three colors, the walls
made a poor show. They looked sad, as though they had never
expected anything better than to be thrown away.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of her life Brennan legendarily took up residence
in the ladies' room at The New Yorker's offices. A heavy drinker,
she may well have been sociopathically peripatetic. But her prose
is lucid and sharp, and her stories read like the diary of an
evictee. Eccentric she may have been, but a reader today can easily
identify with her precariousness, her nomadism, her effort to make
a home in an exciting city where even then affordable housing was
hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Since then the housing situation has gotten worse. As an article
in this paper reported, while the building boom is creating new
housing, it is also increasing rents. We are nomads in our own
city. The struggle for space may not involve mass migrations across
national boundaries, but it induces a constant background of
anxiety over imminent displacement. Construction sites are preceded
by destruction sites. If we feel pride in the revival of the city's
economy, we may also legitimately fear that the next boom is going
to pitch us into the streets. Or, as Brennan observed, it might
take the streets themselves away.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is time to create a Blitzker Prize to honor the
world's most creative demolitions. The old Alexander's department
store in New York City. The farms of Lancaster County,
Pennsylvania? Downtown Baghdad?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Lebbeus Woods is one of a number of architects who were students
in the 1960s and sought to drop out of the eviction economy by
confining their work to unbuilt, paper projects. Their designs have
a science fiction look, but they respond to political fact. In the
last decade, many of Woods' projects have dealt with the
destructive rampages in the former Yugoslavia, where he has often
traveled. Metallic forms resembling gigantic shrapnel plunge into
the hearts of cities, their buildings, streets and public squares
</P>
<P>
   We could be looking at images of destruction, but we could also
see these designs as an effort to develop a constructive vocabulary
for building for the eviction society. They are protests against
the smooth facades with which our builders mask the violence, both
military and economic, that we inflict on cities.
</P>
<P>
   I go back and forth about this work. Why does Woods limit
himself to metaphor? One of architecture's glories is to extend
metaphor to material reality. Yet Woods has the right to be a voice
of conscience. Perhaps it's fair to regard him as contemporary
architecture's most salient political cartoonist.
</P>
<P>
   The first Pritzker Prize ceremony was held in 1979 at Dumbarton
Oaks in Washington, a small pavilion designed by Philip Johnson,
the Pritzker's first honoree. Two weeks ago a slide of the
pavilion's garden was projected at the presentation of the first
annual Catherine R. Brown Awards for Landscape Architecture in New
Urbanism. The awards are named for one of America's most gifted
urbanists, who died last year at 47. The garden was one of Brown's
favorite places.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was trained as a landscape architect and urban planner,
but no professional title adequately describes what she did. With
her husband, William R. Morrish, she directed the Design Center for
American Urban Landscape, a study and research group at the
University of Minnesota. The group's focus is the contemporary
American suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Brown understood that specialized disciplines and fields of
information have done as much to fragment the landscape as market
pressures or hostile neighbors. Architects, developers,
environmentalists, politicians, planners, highway engineers,
retailers _ all spin within separate spheres. Her specialty lay in
bringing them into coherent relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Though involved with the New Urbanism crowd, Brown understood
that the problems of suburban sprawl could not be solved simply by
persuading rich people to build big houses in period styles on
small parcels of land. Working mostly with small second- and
third-ring suburban communities in the Midwest, she practiced
planning as a form of adult education. If you build houses on this
slope or cut down those trees, how would that affect the ground
water? Could you set this superstore perpendicular to the highway
instead of parallel to it? Is there a need for public transit? What
kind?
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994 book ``Planning to Stay,'' which she wrote with
Morrish, Brown emphasized that planning is as much a matter of
seeing as of designing. What are the major features in a stable
neighborhood: streets, gardens, libraries, markets? How do they fit
together? She showed that creativity in architecture is not limited
to visual form. It also finds expression in public policy.
</P>
<P>
   She always came back to the land, but never in a naive or
sentimental way. A devotee of the landscape historian J.B. Jackson,
Brown embraced his conception of landscape as a concrete,
three-dimensional shared reality. But shared reality can be
explosive. Brown would never have won a Blitzker. She was a poet in
the sense understood by the Greeks: a maker of the tissue that
holds a society together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
