<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE CAN WE PUT THE GARBAGE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To paraphrase the performer who once called himself Prince, I
was dozing when I started writing this, so please forgive me if it
turns surreal.
</P>
<P>
   More precisely, I had a nightmare, and at the point where the
foul fiends from the black landfill closed in on me, I awakened and
had a vision.
</P>
<P>
   There I was, trapped in Lady Liberty's torch, gazing down at the
horrid spectacle of a New York harbor turned rusty red, and
smelling _ even at that height _ the stench of mountains of rotting
garbage along the shore and piled in the streets as far inland as I
could see.
</P>
<P>
   I had fled there in desperation, trying to escape from dozens of
hideous monsters who looked for all the world like the thing from
the junk movie ``The Toxic Avenger.'' But there was no escape. They
were closing in on me there in the Statue of Liberty when I bolted
awake, yelling, ``Chad!''
</P>
<P>
   It was the name of the country, not that of a person, that I
called out. I said it the way someone says, ``Eureka! I've found
it!'' Chad and some other places like that, I had concluded, might
be this country's escape from the waste disposal nightmare that
threatens to engulf us.
</P>
<P>
   I had fallen asleep after reading the recent article in Parade
magazine that poses the alarming question, ``What Will We Do With
All Our Garbage?''
</P>
<P>
   That story asserts that:
</P>
<P>
   _The amount of solid waste generated by America annually has
doubled and then some since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   _California, Texas, New York and Florida (in that order) produce
the most garbage.
</P>
<P>
   _Total production of garbage in this country divides out to
about 4.4 pounds per person per day.
</P>
<P>
   _Cities are running out of landfill space. And the landfills may
pose problems for public health.
</P>
<P>
   The story points out that the conventional wisdom that materials
deposited in landfills rot away over time and become harmless isn't
necessarily so. Some things remain just as they were when buried,
and others are mummified and preserved permanently, the article
asserts.
</P>
<P>
   That is believed to happen because of the Tupperware effect
created by the plastic lining of modern landfills. And even with
the liners, landfills are prone to leak hazardous liquids that can
pollute ground water.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the problems with landfills, the greater problem is
that there are not going to be enough of them to meet the nation's
garbage disposal needs if Americans keep generating as much of the
stuff as they now are and the population keeps growing.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the answer? Parade speaks of recycling, avoiding
excess packaging, reusing more things and throwing away less. Those
things will help. But I think the answer is Chad.
</P>
<P>
   I hope no citizens of that country are offended by this, but I
think there is a financial bonanza to be reaped by countries like
Chad through leasing solid-waste burial rights in their desert
regions to giant waste disposal companies like Waste Management
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   I focus upon Houston-based Waste Management because it is the
biggest such company, with about 22 percent of the nation's garbage
disposal business, and because it already is an international firm.
Moreover, I know something about the company _ most of it positive
_ because it collects and disposes of solid refuse in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management definitely will need more landfill capacity
somewhere, if it overcomes the legal obstacles to its getting the
contract to dispose of New York's garbage after that city closes
its mammoth Fresh Kills landfill on Staten Island in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If I were in charge at Waste Management, I would have
international lobbyists cultivating relationships with countries
like Chad, Sudan and Morocco that have large expanses of arid,
unproductive, uninhabitable desert.
</P>
<P>
   I'd have them make the case that sand with no oil under it is a
liability that could be turned into a huge asset _ a source of
revenue for the government and employment for hundreds of its
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   I'd have those lobbyists emphasize that the refuse would pose no
health risks because it would buried far away from urban centers,
that the intense desert heat would cause it to degrade, and there
would be no leaching because of the sparse rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   Then they could throw out the possibility that the rotting
garbage might make some portions of the desert bloom again
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Far-fetched, you say? Hardly. I doubt that this vision is in any
way original. Planners at Waste Management and its competitors
probably already are working on it, or something like it.
</P>
<P>
   No, the desertification of garbage is not a pipe dream. The
notion is far more realistic than the belief that America can ever
recapture enough landfill capacity for its future needs just
through conserving, recycling and reusing.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
