<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEYING THE SHIFTING PHONE-DEAL LANDSCAPE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo.)   (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors are excused if their wires are crossed by developments
in the $1 trillion telecommunications business.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, even the professionals are a bit bewildered by the
battle two fast-growing upstarts _ Global Crossing and Qwest
Communications International _ are waging for US West, a stodgy
Baby Bell, and the Frontier Corp., a long-distance company that in
1996 bought part of Qwest's network.
</P>
<P>
   The market has already rendered verdicts of sorts. Global
Crossing's stock has fallen more than 20 percent since it struck an
agreement with US West. And Qwest's shares have retreated about 25
percent since last Sunday, when it began a hostile bid. The decline
probably isn't sitting well with Qwest shareholders, a group that
includes BellSouth, which in April paid $3.5 billion for a 10
percent slice of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Brian B. Hayward, manager of the Invesco Worldwide
Communications fund, owns shares of both Qwest and Global Crossing.
From his office in Denver, he took some time last week to sort
through the events. Here are some excerpts. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)There have been a lot of combinations in this
industry the last few years. Is the struggle for US West comparable
with any telecommunications deal that preceded it?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Worldcom going after MCI is somewhat comparable, but MCI was
not a regional Bell company. But there really hasn't been a
situation before this where a new upstart carrier went after a
local carrier. It's going to be interesting. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Which company would benefit most from owning US West
and Frontier?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Of the two, it makes more sense for Qwest. But I have a lot
of questions.
</P>
<P>
   Why, for starters, go after US West, the slowest-growing
regional Bell in the country? Around here, it is called US Worst.
If you had told me three months ago there would be a bidding war
for US West, I would not have believed it.
</P>
<P>
   I think both companies are going after it because they feel they
need these local assets, and that US West is about the only
regional Bell left that either can afford to go after, with the
exception of BellSouth, which has a stake in Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   And I am not clear why Qwest feels the need to get Frontier's
assets back. If they do, they will be paying billions for assets
they sold for about $400 million. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)But US West does offer access to the so-called last
mile into homes, doesn't it?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. At base, that is what they are after. It is the most complex
and difficult part of the network to complete. It is also
effectively impossible to duplicate because it is prohibitively
expensive. But that is where the holy grail is: serving customers.
The more you can offer the consumer _ local and long distance,
Internet access, data transmission, you name it _ the better. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)So how do you think this will play out?(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In the conference call after it announced its hostile offer,
Qwest made it plain it was making two stand-alone offers, one for
US West, the other for Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   If I were guessing, I could see Global Crossing getting Frontier
and US West going with Qwest. And remember, we don't know where
BellSouth is in all of this. I would have to think that at the
least Qwest put in a phone call to them before they launched their
bid.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, BellSouth and US West together with Qwest would make a
much more formidable combination.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the premium Qwest offered over Global Crossing was taken
out last Monday, the day after the deal was announced. I am sure
Qwest management expected some decline in the stock price when they
announced it, but I doubt they thought the stock would fall as much
as it has. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)How does this fight fit into the evolution of the
telecommunications business?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know how many major worldwide telecommunications
companies there will be at the end of this, maybe five or six.
</P>
<P>
   But they will be able to serve their customers end-to-end with
their own plant. Long-distance carriers will not only have their
own domestic backbone, but also an international one.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest has that in mind. They have a nationwide network here and
are doing joint ventures internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing is moving in the same direction: They are
building trans-Atlantic and trans-Pacific cables and have
competitive local exchange plans for Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But we have years to go with the consolidation in this industry.
Some of the regulatory issues with AT&AMP;T alone are going to take
years to resolve. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Who are the survivors?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. MCI Worldcom is a survivor. They are further along in
assembling these kinds of assets around the world than anyone. AT&AMP;T
is another, although the joint venture approach they have
internationally makes things difficult. And British
Telecommunications would want to be a world player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
