<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-FOSSILS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR CHINESE FARMERS FIND ILLICIT PROFITS IN HARVESTING FOSSILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DINGJIAERGOU, China _ In Ding Yaohong's tiny sitting room, mud
walls are etched with deep cracks and two tattered chairs vie for
space with roosting chickens, signs of this remote region's
desperate poverty. But the new centerpiece of the room, displacing
a small, rotting table, is the spine of an ancient spade-toothed
elephant _ recently unearthed evidence that Ding's hard homeland
may have some wealth to offer after all.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the farmers here struggled to coax wheat and corn to
grow on these arid, rocky hills, but the land gave little in
return. ``Plant a handful of seed and you get a handful of crops,''
a local saying goes.
</P>
<P>
   But recently this barren, brown wasteland has yielded a
lucrative new crop that stands to repay the generations of
suffering: a cache of nearly intact 15 million-year-old fossils,
which the villagers plan to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been digging for fossils for more than 10 years, but
this is the first time we've hit upon anything like this,'' Ding
said.
</P>
<P>
   His home is now littered with valuable specimens excavated in
the last two months, including prehistoric crocodiles, rhinos and
pigs. ``When the experts come to buy, I hope it will be a very good
harvest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As China has moved toward a market economy, peasants all over
rural China have had to devise ways to buy goods and services that
were once provided for free by the state, like education and
medicine. Where land is good they farm. Near cities, they turn to
migrant labor.
</P>
<P>
   But the village of Dingjiaergou, whose residents belong to
China's Hui Muslim minority (and are mostly surnamed Ding), is 15
miles from the nearest paved road. It is six hours by car from
Yinchuan, the sleepy provincial capital of the Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region, one of the poorest in China, with a per capita
income of less than $100 a year. The village got electricity
several years ago, but houses still lack running water, phones or
heat, even though winter temperatures drop well below zero.
</P>
<P>
   So peasants here have turned to large-scale fossil excavation to
make ends meet _ a unique if dangerous (and illegal) sideline.
</P>
<P>
   When not tending their crops, the men of Dingjiaergou can often
be found tunneling like groundhogs 10 feet under the region's
hills, in the hopes of finding ancient bones.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago Ding and 17 other villagers hit gold. They
burrowed their way into the underground cache. Now, the three-room
mud-brick house he shares with his wife and three children
resembles a museum storeroom, with the spine in the sitting room,
piles of skulls in the bedroom, and the huge-tusked skull of a
spade-toothed elephant blocking access to the family kang, a
traditional brick bed built over an oven to provide winter warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have long known that this arid land in Tongxin County
was once a richly forested terrain, filled with lakes and rivers,
said Ye Jie, deputy director of the Institute of Vertebrate
Paleontology at the Chinese Academy of Sciences in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and '70s some farmers picked up spare cash by
digging up and selling ``dragon bones'' _ fossil shards used to
make traditional medicines for treating stomach troubles and scars.
In the next two decades, Chinese scientists occasionally made
research expeditions to this remote region, cataloguing its past.
</P>
<P>
   But farmers here say they only recently realized that there was
big money in excavations, and began carving out their peculiar
niche in China's emerging market economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, we didn't know how valuable this stuff
was,'' said Ding Yuzhu, a grizzled 50-year-old in a Mao jacket and
white skullcap.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in the last few years, Chinese scientists as well
as foreign experts had come to view _ and buy _ their wares. ``Now
we have discovered we could do this to make a living,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ding Yaohong, a burly man of 38, said that even before the major
discovery this spring, most of his income in recent years had come
from fossils. He makes about $35 a year from growing wheat and corn
_ and $125 a month selling the smaller fossils and bone shards he
unearthed in the past.
</P>
<P>
   With this year's jackpot, his second income stands to increase
many times. He and his partners say they will price the elephant
skull alone at $4,000 to $6,000. Ding says they plan to sell the
fossils to the Natural History Museum in Beijing, but experts
predict that many will end up on a lucrative black market.
</P>
<P>
   Neither farmers nor local officials seem terribly perturbed that
their digging is technically illegal. ``In fact we don't have much
choice,'' the older Ding said, ``since our land is so poor we would
starve otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials have done little to intervene, noting that the
region's government does not have the money for proper excavation
anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many scientists are concerned that these amateur fossil
hunters may be destroying valuable scientific evidence with their
rudimentary picks and shovels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most scientists are opposed to this unscientific digging, even
though it has been a convenient way to get specimens,'' said Ye of
the Academy of Sciences. ``The peasants' goal is to sell fossils _
not to gather related scientific information _ so things are lost.
And because of their limited knowledge they often damage valuable
things which they think of as unimportant.''
</P>
<P>
   To get to the fossils, groups of villagers first dig a hole down
several yards into the earth, and then often tunnel laterally
hundreds of yards.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, the 18-man team from Dingjiaergou tunneled 500
yards before they found fossils, which Ding said could be
distinguished from the surrounding rocks by their color and also
their unique taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found so many things there,'' he said, ``but it was hard
since the tunnel was only 1.5 yards high _ you couldn't stand up
and only one person could go in at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Each fossil had to be dragged out of the narrow tunnel using
ropes. And scientists complain that the villagers inevitably chop
up large specimens to get them up through their maze, destroying
evidence in the process.
</P>
<P>
   It is a dangerous after-hours job that has killed two men from
Dingjiaergou in the last 10 years. Since there are no trees in this
desertlike region, tunnels are not reinforced by root networks and
are thus prone to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our first big find after years of looking,'' the elder
Ding said, ``and two people have died doing it. That's why the
bones are so expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The villagers say that over the last few years, visiting experts
have taught them how to handle the fossils more carefully and
brought scientific charts that help them identify bones from
ancient mammals.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the fossils remain inscrutable to the peasants.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that?'' a visitor asked, pointing to a pear-shaped
15-inch skull on the dirt floor, with dull yellow teeth protruding
at odd angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh that, that's some kind of monster,'' the elder Ding said
with assurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
