<P>
   G8-KOSOVO _ COLOGNE, Germany _ At the opening of the Group of
Eight summit meeting here on Friday, National Security Advisor
Samuel E. Berger said the White House still is uncertain, a week
after the fact, why Russian troops deployed to Kosovo and what it
says about the state of Russian President Boris Yeltsin's control
there. The Clinton administration feels the troop decision was made
amid a fog of uncertainty inside Moscow and, as a result, the
United States is no longer sure quite what it's dealing with. Will
fold in the day's other developments out of Helsinki and Cologne,
including details on a massive (approaching $50 billion) debt
relief program. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-G8 _ COLOGNE, Germany _ Bouyed by his leadership of a
NATO win in Kosovo, the strongest American economy in a generation
and the fading echoes of his House impeachment six months ago
Saturday, President Clinton is projecting an air of fresh authority
at the annual summit of seven of the world's most powerful heads of
state. Walking tall among his counterparts, Clinton appeared
comfortably in control of the agenda Friday, as the G-7 leaders
opened a weekend of talks on issues ranging from Balkans
reconstruction to debt
</P>
<P>
   relief for developing countries. And he drew one accolade after
another from his fellow heads of state for his role in leading his
NATO partners in the coalition air war against Yugoslavia's bloody
repression in Kosovo. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-G8 _ MOSCOW _ If the Group of Eight industrialized
nations were a country club, Russia would be like the annoying
member who cannot afford to pay the dues, but dominates the debate
during the club meeting. Turbulent relations between Russia and the
world's seven richest nations threaten to overshadow the three-day
summit of the G-8, which opened Friday in Cologne, Germany. Russian
President Boris Yeltsin is not scheduled to arrive at the summit
until Sunday. (Holmes, Cox News Service) 30.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-QUAKE _ PUEBLA, Mexico _ Many of the buildings damaged
here in Tuesday's earthquake are colonial architectural jewels that
date back hundreds of years. The temblar raises questions about the
future of structures in Puebla and other cities. Loosened by the
earthquake, chunks of brick and plaster were thrown from the
baroque cupolas' graceful arches, landing on a cracked floor at the
state university of Puebla. Stunned by the death of 17 people in
the region _ a toll that was expected to rise _ residents of this
city of 1.2 million also mourned the damage to buildings whose
baroque, renaissance and Arabic-influenced architecture have been a
source of pride and a draw for tourists from around the world.
(Ferriss, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA _ VERDAN, Yugoslavia _ German soldiers detained 25
ethnic Albanian rebels today after finding one elderly man dead and
more than 15 others hurt in a police station that had been under
control of the Kosovo Liberation Army since early this week. Most
of the victims seemed to be ethnic Albanians or Gypsies between the
ages of 50 and 60, said Lt. Col. Dietmar Jeserich, a spokesman for
the German army serving in the Kosovo peace force in the region.
The Kosovo Liberation Army moved Friday to repair its ties with
U.S. peacekeepers by promising to release five kidnapped hostages
who it described as Serb war criminals. A KLA brigade commander
said in an interview that he had told the top U.S. commander of the
82nd Airborne Division that from now on he was going to leave it up
to NATO investigate war crimes. Even with this development, NATO
faces problems trying to keep peace between the KLA and the Serbs.
In one region with 43 villages and 56,000 people, Americans are
making do with only 200 peacekeepers. (Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RAPE _ PEC, Yugoslavia _ At the Hotel Karagac here,
mentioned prominently in the U.S. State Department's report on Serb
atrocities in Kosovo as the site of a ``rape camp,'' there are
small signs of the horrors that are believed to have taken place.
But NATO peacekeepers have yet to investigate the hotel because
it's ``low on their priority list'' the Kosovo Liberation Army and
Serb troops are still fighting on the roads around it. Developing.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
