<P>
   LIQUOR _ It's been decades since Alabama state Legislators could
be identified as wet or dry, based on their stance on alcohol.
Nearly two-thirds of Alabama's counties already permit alcohol
sales and the largest metro areas allow sales on Sunday. In
Birmingham and Mobile, you can even go to the local grocery store
and buy a six-pack on Sunday _ something you can't do in Atlanta.
As Gov. Don Siegelman mulls over a bill that would liberalize
Sunday sales in wet counties, the fact is that liquor has dried up
as a political issue. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REVEREND-VIDEO _ ATLANTA _The Rev. Danny Bruce Moody, 52, pastor
of the Mount Carmel Baptist Church in Douglasville, Ga, was
arrested this month for videotaping under women's dresses while
riding on the escalators at Hartsfield International Airport. Moody
has served as the church pastor for 24 years, and the congregation
is supporting him. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HERITAGEHIGH _ ATLANTA _ Almost a month after six students were
shot at one of the district's high schools, the county school board
has approved three new psychologists positions to handle the
increasing number of kids who need help. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASTE _ They couldn't stop the poop from getting in the water,
so now federal regulators are considering weakening the rules on
Florida utilities' widespread practice of pumping treated sewage
deep underground - waste that the feds acknowledge is seeping into
potential drinking water supplies. The U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency says the rules may be unreasonably strict, since
Florida's geology makes it impossible to guarantee that the waste
won't escape upward from the depths of the Floridan Aquifier. The
EPA insists it would make sure none of the waste is dangerous by
the time it reaches drinking water. But the idea horrifies
environmentalists. ``EPA's proposed solution is to legalize the
contamination rather than prevent it,'' says Suzi Ruhl of the Legal
Environmental Assistance Foundation, which has been fighting for
years to rein in the underground injections. Waste has shown up in
shallower monitor wells of Seacoast Utilities in northern Palm
Beach County and other areas around Flroida. (King, Palm Beach
Post).
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM-RIDERS _ ATLANTA _ In 1964, civil rights freedom rider
James Earl Chaney and two others were killed in Meridian, Miss.,
while advocating for black suffrage in the South. This week, the
freedom riders are riding again, in the form of the Unity
Coalition, to introduce a new generation to Chaney's struggle for
civil rights. We'll accompany them as they pass through Atlanta and
find out what their goals are and how they are working to achieve
them. (Rodriguez, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY-GEORGIA _ Georgia political react to national gambling
study report due out Friday. Report may call for some form of
federal oversight of lotteries, some state officials fear. They
don't want that. (Mantius, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BULLOCK-OBIT _ AUSTIN _ Two unavoidable cliches: Former Lt. Gov.
Bob Bullock really was larger than life. And his death really does
mark the end of an era. Bullock died Friday morning at home,
surrounded by family. A first-generation Texan, Bullock fiercely
embraced the state's colorful history and did more than his part to
preserve and contribute to it. His temper could melt a brass
doorknob, but he was considerate of his friends. He could be
courtly and combative, gentlemanly and lewd, magnanimous and
unforgiving, humble and intimidating, persuasive and threatening _
all within seconds. He also pushed through monumental programs _
changing everything from the way Texas collects taxes to how it
funds its schools _ and never shied from a little political
bloodletting for what he believed to be in the best interest of
Texans. (Beach, Austin American-Statesman). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BULLOCK-HIGHLIGHTS _ Time line of Bullock's life. (McCarthy,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BULLOCK-ACHIEVE _ Bullock's accomplishments. (Reynolds, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BULLOCK-REACT _ Reaction quotes, with mugs. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
