<P>
   FAULDER-SCENE _ HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Described by prison
officials as being peaceful and calm, Joseph Stanley Faulder, 61,
became the first Canadian executed in the United States in 47 years
on Thursday. ``He said he was at peace with his maker and ready to
go, and one way or another, he would be set free tonight,'' Texas
Department of Criminal Justice Public Information Officer Larry
Todd said. Faulder was sentenced to die by lethal injection for the
beating and stabbing death of 75-year-old Inez Phillips during a
1975 robbery of her home in Gladewater. (Longview News-Journal).
</P>
<P>
   BKN-FINALS-WAGERS _ U.S. Sen. Phil Gramm fired the first salvo
from his Washington office.''Eat our dust, city boy,'' he said to
his New York counterpart, Sen. Charles Schumer. ``And hey, what the
heck is a Knick anyhow?'' Schumer, fired back as quickly as a Texas
outlaw: ``Ask Larry Bird what a Knick is, senator. I'm sure they
have a clear idea.'' He then went on to call the San Antonio Spurs,
who are currently tangling with the New York Knicks for the
National Basketball Association Championship, ``those
tumbleweeds.'' Since the series began, harsh words and wagers have
been flying between the Empire State and the Lone Star state like
bullets in pistol duels. Gov. Bush is betting Gov. Pataki, and
mayors from New York and San Antonio are also laying it on the
line. (Davenport, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports categories.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKGAME-PROBE _ TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ A small company set up to
sell black-achievement board games _ and losing about $1 million a
year _ has assumed a curious place in a probe of a sports agent's
alleged gifts to University of Florida players of cash and cars.
BAOA Inc.'s stockholders include Rev. Jesse Jackson, who said
Thursday that as far as he knew, sports agent and BAOA director
William ``Tank'' Black never used the company as a slush fund to
buy gifts for clients. (Dolch/Elmore, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TX-NATGUARD-BOSNIA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Army National Guard
soldiers, including several units based in Austin, have begun
training for deployment early next year to the NATO peacekeeping
mission in Bosnia. (Kelley, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GUN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Guns rival boots, barbecue and pickup
trucks as emblems of the Lone Star State. But as Republican George
W. Bush attempts to move from the Governor's Mansion to the White
House, Democrats are poised to make gun laws that are popular in
Texas a liability for Bush in a national campaign. (Greenberger,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
