<SLUG> BC-MA-JOBLESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYMENT IN BAY STATE AT HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The number of people employed in Massachusetts reached
yet another high _ 3.218 million _ despite a slowdown in job
growth, the state said Friday in its monthly employment report.
</P>
<P>
   While the report seemed to give out mixed signals, the
underlying message was positive: Massachusetts' economy is going
strong.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate edged up to 3.1 percent, from 2.9 percent
in April. But, the state's rate of joblessness still rests well
below the national jobless rate of 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And while only 900 jobs were added in May _ down sharply from
7,600 jobs, the revised count for April _ the state over the past
four months has generated more than 24,000 new jobs, according to
the state's monthly survey of payrolls of nonfarm businesses
operating in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're almost pushed to the brink,'' said Elliot Winer,cq!
economist for the Massachusetts Division of Employment and
Training. ``You can't get many more people into the labor force
than you have.''
</P>
<P>
   The jobs report caps a week in which a series of developments
indicated that the US economy may be entering new terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported inflation, after spiking in April
by 0.7 percent, was nonexistent last month. Nevertheless, Alan
Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve Board, hinted in
public speeches during the week that he would seek to raise
interest rates, possibly at the next meeting of the Federal Open
Market Committee meeting June 29-30. Pressure on wages in an
ever-expanding economy are a key Fed concern, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   While Greenspan argued a Fed interest-rate hike would
``pre-empt'' future inflation, there are risks to a Fed strategy of
trying to cool down a sizzling economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you put on the brakes you can never tell if you're
going to skid,'' said Nicholas Perna, chief economist for Fleet
Financial Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   An 0.2 percentage point rise in Massachusetts' unemployment
rate, to 3.1 percent in May, was blamed largely on the fact that
optimistic job hunters continue to stream into Massachusetts' labor
force, including retirees, out-of-staters, and students.
</P>
<P>
   The labor force had a ``sizable'' 5,500 gain in May _ on top of
a 8,100 gain in April _ according to the state's survey of
households. The household survey is used to calculate the
unemployment rate.
</P>
<P>
   Services in Massachusetts, especially business services, had the
biggest job gains last month. Services added 2,400 jobs, according
the payroll survey.
</P>
<P>
   Other industries, including finance and wholesale trade, grew.
The exceptions were construction, which lost 800 jobs in May, and
manufacturing, which lost 600 jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
