</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOWS TO FIRE BACK IN AFTERMATH OF HOUSE VOTE ON GUN
CONTROL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ Firing a warning shot across the Atlantic
Ocean, President Clinton on Friday vowed to ratchet up his fight
for gun control in the aftermath of the House defeat of its gun
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week instead of listening to the American people and
strengthening our gun laws, the House of Representatives listened
to the gun lobby and did nothing at all,'' said the president, who
is meeting with the leaders of industrialized nations. ``The House
leadership gutted this bill in the dark of night to keep
common-sense gun legislation from seeing the light of day.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement was issued after the House killed a bill that
contained a weak gun-control measure opposed by many Democrats and
the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Since he left for Europe on Tuesday, Clinton has been paying
close attention to the gun-control issue and telephoned wavering
Democrats to lobby them to support restrictions that include
background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   When the House, shortly before midnight, approved a watered down
version of the gun-show provision the president denounced the vote
and attributed it to the clout of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   The president also acknowledged the resistance to gun-control
measures in the United States as he met with leaders of nations
with generally tougher gun restrictions and lower crime rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is a great country, but it is the only
country in the world that's still living as if you don't have to
take reasonable precautions to keep guns out of the hands of
children and criminals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said the House defeat had only spurred him to work
harder for tougher gun legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting warmed up,'' he said after meeting with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair ``I'm energized for the fight,
and I hope Carol McCarthy is and Sarah Brady and all of our
allies.'' Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., who lost her husband to
gun violence, was the sponsor of the failed anti-gun measure
favored by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The House narrowly approved a less restrictive measure favored
by the NRA and sponsored by another Democratic House member, Rep.
John Dingell of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   But liberal House Democrats, angry at the defeat of the gun
measure, later joined with conservative Republicans to defeat the
entire gun-control bill.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the president would
begin waging his counteroffensive Saturday by devoting his radio
address to the gun-control issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president will use his weekly radio address to
reiterate the fact that this fight over sensible gun control has
just begun and we're going to continue until the American public
gets what they deserve,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was less critical of another measure approved by the
House, which would let public schools post copies of the Ten
Commandments. While the president said he believed the provisions
faced constitutional hurdles, he added that he understood the need
to teach students about character building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that the schools ought to build the character of
children I think is a good idea,'' he said after a meeting with
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. ``But it ought to be done in a
way that respects the wide diversity of our student body and that
doesn't lead to a long drawn-out legal challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The House actions were prompted by the April killings at
Columbine High School in Colorado, which many liberals attributed
to the easy access to guns and conservatives blamed on too much
violence in the media and the lack of ethics among young people.
</P>
<P>
   The White House immediately seized on the gun-control issue in
the aftermath of the shootings and polls showed the public
overwhelmingly supporting modest restrictions on firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The gun-control debate appeared to be going the administration's
way last month when the Senate reversed itself and approved tougher
gun restrictions favored by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton blamed his reversal of fortune in the House on the NRA,
which he maintained convinced GOP leaders to postpone the vote so
they could whip up gun owners' opposition to the measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA can always produce several hundred phone calls for
every one an ordinary citizen can make,'' he said. ``They did win,
and it's a great tribute to their money and their power; but it's
not a tribute to the children or the future of America ... So one
more time the Congress of the United States, with the majority in
the lead, says, we don't care what's necessary to protect our
children, we can't possibly bear to make anyone in the NRA mad.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that House Republican leaders waited until ``the dark of
the night'' to take the vote on the gun-show measure to avoid the
publicity of defeating a popular measure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was less harsh in his assessment of Dingell, saying he
has an ``honest disagreement'' with the liberal Democrat who is
also a member of the NRA. And Lockhart said ``the opposition was
really led by a small group of the Republican leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
