<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-CUP-SABRES-BOS &LR;      06-18 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CUP-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTSEASON CHALLENGE DOESN'T GET ANY TOUGHER FOR SABRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ They faced a huge obstacle when they were matched up
against No. 2 seed Ottawa in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They faced another when they had a long layoff and were pitted
against the surging Bruins. Another hurdle came in the form of
having to shut down the highest-scoring team in the NHL, the
Toronto Maple Leafs.
</P>
<P>
   Through those challenges, the tenacity and teamwork of the
Buffalo Sabres shone through while they overcame all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Now they face their biggest challenge of the postseason. After
being shut out by the Dallas Stars in Game 5 Thursday night, the
Sabres trail the best-of-seven Stanley Cup finals, 3-2, and face
elimination at home Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The series has been so close, with a paper-thin margin
separating the teams in each of the five games. There have been
momentum shifts that have come from moment to moment, period to
period, and game to game. But with Dallas needing only one more
victory in the next two games, there was a quiet confidence
emanating from the Dallas dressing room Thursday night and a quiet
desperation coming from the Sabres'.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought both teams emotionally really gave it everything
they had,'' said Sabres coach Lindy Ruff. ``It was a lot of emotion
out there on both sides and it was tight as tight could be. Not a
lot of ice for either team.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the game proved to be Darryl Sydor's
power-play goal at 2:23 of the middle period, which held up as the
winner, and Pat Verbeek closed it out at 15:21 of the third at even
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really done much, I guess, offensively,'' said
Sydor, who had no points in the series' first four games. ``But
that is one thing I have learned over my years, not to really get
down or try to force things. It was a battle out there and every
shift is so intense. This is the time of year that everyone wants
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   It was goalie Ed Belfour's third shutout of the playoffs and
seventh of his career. So much has been written about the play of
Dominik Hasek, but on Thursday night, Belfour was calm, cool, and
collected and is one victory away from his first Stanley Cup. Hasek
has a better save percentage (.937 to Belfour's .925 but Belfour's
goals-against average is 1.76 to Hasek's 1.85.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie has been playing unbelieveable for us,'' said Sydor.
``He has been in a shadow of a lot of goaltenders and I think he
has really, really taken that as motivation to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Hasek hasn't played badly. He didn't have a chance on
either of the Stars' goals. Hasek said he expects his team to come
back with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say; we tried the whole game,'' he said. ``We had a
couple of chances. I think both teams had not too many chances.
They scored the first goal on the power play and it was probably
the difference in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   History favors the Stars, who were the NHL's best regular-season
team. In the 15 times the finals have been tied at 2-2, the club
winning Game 5 has gone on to win the Cup 12 times. The last team
to lose a fifth game and win the Cup was the 1971 Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   The area in which the Sabres were so strong during the first
three rounds, the power play, has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars held the Sabres without a power play in all three of
their chances in Game 5, stretching their consecutive number of
kills to 17. The last time the Stars allowed Buffalo to score a
power-play goal was in the third period of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   While the Sabres try to find a way to turn that around, the
Stars said they fully expect that Game 6 will be their finest hour.
If that's the case, it could well mark the end of Buffalo's
impressive run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect nothing less than our best game,'' said Stars
forward Jamie Langenbrunner. We will be excited to play. I am sure
that we will play our best game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is the more seasoned team, predicted to be a Cup
contender even before the Stars finished with the best
regular-season record. Call them experienced but don't call them
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we lose, automatically, our age becomes a factor,'' said
veteran forward Mike Keane. ``Right now, we're feeling very fresh.
Any time we lose, we're an old club. Big deal. I don't care how old
this club is. We're one win away from a Cup and I don't think
anyone feels old now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
