<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REPLAY OF TRAGEDY AS FARCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 20, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIMOLEAGUE, Ireland _ When the 17th century British burned the
Catholic monastery that had guarded the tidal riverfront here since
the 12th century, the intent was to destroy a symbol as much as an
edifice of stone and wood.
</P>
<P>
   The stones still stand, impervious to fire as well as ire, and
the bygones are bygones. On Ireland's balmy south coast, at least,
if not in the rockier and more hostile turf of the still-Balkanized
North, tribes of different antecedents prosper and proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   But word of the systematic destruction of symbols still reaches
the peaceful tourist towns, whether it be a church arson or a
pub-bombing in Ulster, the demented bloodletting in the Balkans, or
the destruction of more benign symbols by British newspapers for
something so banal as profit.
</P>
<P>
   In the same week I circumlocuted the fishing spots of Ireland's
southwest, the British newspapers were agog with three scandals,
each of which falls into the category of destroying contemporary
symbols for profit.
</P>
<P>
   Every press baron has his foibles, but Rupert Murdoch, the
Australian whose business skills and journalisitic mendacity have
made him the world's premier media buccaneer encouraged one of his
saffron-tinted editors (that's a boss of yellow journalists) at his
tabloid Sun to run an 11-year-old snapshot of a royal fiancee shorn
of half her bathing-suit top.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in the run-up to the royal wedding, the insult could not
have been timed better to infuriate supporters of the beleaguered
royal family, which has been carpet-bombed by Murdoch's
hydra-headed News Corp. outlets ever since he realized there was
money to be made in denigrating high society.
</P>
<P>
   By paying a large sum, speculated to be in the vicinity of
$160,000, Murdoch's Sun bought a snapshot taken over a decade ago,
when Sophie Rhys-Jones was skylarking on a trip in Spain, and the
fellow in the back seat snapped her bra, and the lady in front
snapped the picture. From such old and innocent horseplay the Sun
ran a photo of a now-mature woman who's engaged to Prince Edward,
her breast bared in four million copies of Murdoch's rag.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's campaign to bury Britain's royal family in
newspaper-selling smut is a long-running soap opera. To say people
were disgusted at the Sun's gaucherie is to understate the
reaction. ``Reprehensible,'' sniffed the quasi-official Press
Complaints Commission.
</P>
<P>
   It was another Murdoch tabloid, the News of the World, that
entrapped a prominent British athletic hero, and goaded him into
bragging about exploits selling drugs and chasing loose women in
Amsterdam. The rather simple-minded and single-minded captain of
Britain's world-class rugby team, Lawrence Dallaglio, was
apparently so intent on impressing his duplicitous inquisitors that
he bragged of all sorts of racy indiscretions. He was tape-recorded
over four hours in a hotel room with reporters, one of them an
attractive female, pretending to offer him a lucrative endorsement
contract.
</P>
<P>
   When the ``story'' was published, on the eve of a widely
publicized world rugby tour by the national team, the captain was
forced to resign in disgrace, with the Lords of Rugby tut-tutting
about how they could not afford to have a one-time drug hustler
captaining the national squad. Another tabloid victim bites the
dust ``the supposed admissions . . . amounted to an elaborate
set-up by the writers of the News of the World . . . to which I
fell victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch reappears again in the third episode of manufactured
disgrace. His Sunday Times paid a large sum to a gossip columnist
for a rival paper to print her lengthy recounting of her 27-year
affair as mistress of former Irish government leader Charlie
Haughey.
</P>
<P>
   By spilling the sordid beans in his Times, Murdoch's
hench-editors held the randy Haughey up to ridicule, and themselves
up to scorn. For a sum speculated to be around $90,000, the
ex-mistress, Terry Keane, spread venom, as vulgar as it was
vengeful, with such obvious spite that the most-unlikely result
eventuated:
</P>
<P>
   A wave of sympathy enveloped not only the harried and hapless
Haughey, who's up to his ears in financial as well as sexual
scandal, but also his long-suffering wife and his adult children,
all of whom behaved with far more grace and taste than Keane, her
journalistic Johns at the Times, or the Grand Titillator Himself,
Rupert the Tasteless.
</P>
<P>
   He's also on the verge of becoming Rupert the Wifeless. His
second wife, Anna, is in court divorcing him. Rupert has a new lady
friend, a 31-year-old employee of his octopus-like organization.
``How would you like to see your lover nude on Page 3, Mr.
Murdoch?'' demanded a headline in the rival Daily Telegraph, whose
owner, Canadian Conrad Black, likes the royal family as much as he
dislikes Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch not only revels but prospers in poking his thumb in the
eye of symbolic figures, tempting targets whose feet he is
determined to show are naught but common clay. The consumers whose
newspapers and TV diets are increasingly dictated by Murdoch's
gargantuan News Corp. have less and less chance to avoid his
thumb-in-the-eyeball journalism, which coarsens taste and elevates
lowbrow sentiment in print as well as on broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   This tropism toward tabloidism has crossed the pond, with a big
boost from the Murdoch wanna-bes who increasingly dominate American
journalism. It is now being documented that the Monica-mania of
America's media has cost us news outfits circulation and audience
share, not to mention respect. The journalism that was our best and
brightest is turning base and brassy.
</P>
<P>
   Brawny Bob Woodward was the Washington Post's big-game hunter
who bagged Tricky Dick in Watergate. He's back now on the Clinton
beat, but Bob's quarry is now the yeasty gossip-pit of Bill &AMP; Hill,
Monica and Linda, Whitewater and wet dreams. The replay of tragedy
as farce is a plot older than the Timoleague abbey. Murdoch remains
journalism's pace-setter. No matter how low you think we can go,
Rupert can always go you one lower.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
