<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1218 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLBROOKE-U.N.-NYT     06-18 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLBROOKE-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELMS APPEARS READY TO ALLOW APPOINTMENT OF HOLBROOKE TO U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
 (rm) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Richard C. Holbrooke appeared near victory in his
year-long struggle for confirmation as chief American diplomat to
the United Nations when the chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, Jesse Helms, suggested Friday that Senate
approval of the nomination was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, who until Friday had left open the possibility that he
might kill the nomination through procedural tactics, said in a
speech on the Senate floor that Holbrooke ``probably will be
confirmed in a week or so as the new U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms was seen as the last major hurdle in Holbrooke's struggle
for the U.N. post, which has been vacant since Bill Richardson left
the job last September to become energy secretary. On Thursday,
other members of the committee signaled their support for his
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional officials said that Helms, the fiercely
conservative North Carolina Republican, appeared to have been
satisfied by Holbrooke's acknowledgment in Senate testimony on
Thursday that his carelessness led to ``misperceptions'' about his
ethics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse wanted contrition from Holbrooke and he got it,'' said a
congressional aide.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, a veteran diplomat turned investment banker, paid
$5,000 to the Justice Department in February to settle civil
charges that he had violated federal lobbying laws in his contacts
with American diplomats in South Korea after he resigned from the
State Department in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Helms had said on June 4, when he announced that his committee
was ready to hold confirmation hearings, that he could not recall
another Cabinet-level nomination before the panel ``with so much
ethical baggage.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration and congressional officials said Helms was also
pleased by Holbrooke's vow at the confirmation hearing on Thursday
that he would make reform of the United Nations his ``highest
sustained priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms is the Senate's leading critic of the United Nations and
has demanded a streamlining of the organization's bureaucracy. In
his Senate speech Friday, the senator noted approvingly that
Holbrooke ``strongly favors the reform of the United Nations.''
</P>
<P>
   The senator's comments Friday suggested that he would allow the
Foreign Relations Committee to vote on the nomination as early as
next week, clearing the way for final Senate confirmation a few
days later and for Holbrooke to take up his duties in New York this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke faces two more hearings before the committee next
week, one on Tuesday focusing on U.N. reform and the last one on
Thursday about his role in policymaking in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has been without a so-called permanent
representative, the title given to the senior American diplomat
assigned to the United Nations, during most of a tumultuous year in
American foreign policy, including the Kosovo crisis and the
showdown with Iraq that led to several days of American-led air
strikes on Baghdad last December.
</P>
<P>
   There has been an acting permanent representative at the United
Nations, A. Peter Burleigh, a respected career diplomat, but
Clinton administration officials say American foreign policy has
been hindered by the lack of a figure of Holbrooke's stature and
celebrity in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, the former ambassador to Germany, was the architect
of the 1995 peace agreement that ended the war in Bosnia, and he is
close to both President Clinton and Vice President Gore. Within the
administration, senior officials often speak of Holbrooke as a
likely secretary of state if Gore is elected president.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If Helms decides to vote for Holbrooke's confirmation, the
nomination may well be approved unanimously by the Foreign
Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   At the opening confirmation hearing on Thursday, senators other
than Helms, Democrats and Republicans alike, praised Holbrooke
enthusiastically, and his broad bipartisan support was made clear
by the fact that he was introduced at the hearing by the Republican
chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, John W. Warner of
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot think of another individual whom I have known in a
public service career in national security matters, foreign affairs
matters, for over 30 years who is better qualified or has had more
experience to take on this position,'' Warner said of Holbrooke.
``I think he's eminently qualified.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
