<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1224 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-GRANT-SAVARESE-BO     06-18 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-GRANT-SAVARESE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORE CHIN, LOTS OF MONEY IN STORE FOR SAVARESE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lou Savarese is being paid a million dollars to fight
Michael Grant Saturday night at Madison Square Garden. He is not
being paid to beat him.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese understands that because he is a professional and has
been around the fight game a long time but he doesn't accept it. To
win is not supposed to be his role when this passion play unfolds
on HBO sometime around midnight, but it is his goal despite other's
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   He has been brought here to lose to Grant, who is considered the
hottest prospect in the heavyweight division in large part because
he is 6 feet 7 inches, 257 pounds and looks as if he could play
power forward for the Spurs if he decided to. But Lou Savarese will
tell you he's looking pretty good these days himself, down to 240
pounds after spending months working with Evander Holyfield's
physical trainer, Tim Hallmark, and is himself ready to win again.
</P>
<P>
   He is fit and he is ready to fire, he believes. Whether that
makes a difference to Grant or not only time will tell but for the
moment at least Savarese believes a mistake was made in casting
either by Grant's manager or his promoter or HBO, which has Grant
signed to a long-term television deal.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever made the mistake, if indeed there has been one, is of no
concern to him. His only concern is hitting in the chin an opponent
who, according to CompuBox statistics gets, hit 48 percent of the
time he's in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   This has not yet meant a thing to Grant, who is 29-0 with 21
knockouts but it means something to Savarese, who is 39-2 himself
with 32 of those wins coming by putting his opponent to sleep. It
means something because he has been put to sleep himself in the
ring once so he understands what Michael Grant does not. He
understands you don't want to get hit 48 percent of the time you're
in the ring with heavyweights because if you do, eventually you
will go to sleep for a few seconds yourself and nothing will be the
same for you after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I match up good with the guy,'' Savarese said of Grant while
also acknowledging Grant's punching power and apparently stiff
chin. ``I do best against guys who are big and strong and don't
move much. Grant is right in front of you. He doesn't move his feet
too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Only, Grant might say, when he has to get out of the way of a
falling opponent, which is what he and trainer Don Turner assume
will be the position Savarese eventually takes at 33rd and
Broadway, because Savarese has already had the tar beaten out of
him by George Foreman two years ago and since has been KO'd by
journeyman David Izon (whom Grant knocked out in five rounds) and
been in dire straits against Lance Whitaker in March before
reluctantly getting off the floor to win a 10-round decision.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese understands this is their thinking. He understands much
of the boxing public views things the same way. But what he also
understands is none of that will matter unless he agrees with them,
which for the moment at least he does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant is a very good fighter,'' Savarese said. ``He's
well-schooled and he's very relaxed in there. I gotta do what I can
do to make him not so relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   What Savarese intends to do is punch Grant in the face as often
as possible in the hopes that eventually this will not be to
Grant's liking. More to the point, he hopes a series of such
punches will send Grant to a place he knows nothing about _
boxing's dark room, where the sound of Chinese chimes go off in
your head and the next thing you hear is a referee saying, ``. . .
six . . . seven.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lou Savarese can do that, he's been told, he might be the
next opponent to challenge WBC champion Lennox Lewis, who will be
at ringside to study both fighters as possible challengers if a
rematch with Evander Holyfield can't be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Grant knows this as well but neither fighter is talking about it
much. Grant isn't talking because he's still young and caught up in
the moment and not concerned about what might follow it. Savarese
isn't talking about it because he's older and has heard such talk
before and knows it means nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the heavyweight champion of short lists,'' Savarese said,
alluding to past times when his name has been mentioned as a
possible challenger for the heavyweight title only to never see
those fights materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something's always coming next fight. I don't let that affect
me anymore. A day is a year in this business. You never know how
it's going to be tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Lou Savarese hopes Michael Grant will learn that for the first
time when he wakes up to a new day and a sore chin.
</P>
</TEXT>
