<HEADLINE>
RICHARD SMITH QUITTING CEO POST AT HARCOURT GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Richard Smith is retiring for the second time as chief
executive of Harcourt General Inc. The 74-year-old Smith will stay
on as chairman of the textbook publishing and retail firm, while
handing off the CEO duties to his son and son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Smith and Brian Knez will serve as co-CEOs beginning
November 1. Both men have been carefully groomed for their new
roles. Smith and Knez presently share the office of chief operating
officer of Harcourt General. They're also co-CEOs of the company's
Neiman Marcus retailing unit and the Harcourt publishing operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our way of passing the torch, so to speak,'' Richard
Smith said. ``The guys are ready. Robert Smith and Brian Knez are
absolutely ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Smith served as CEO from 1961 to 1991, resuming the job
in 1997 after the resignation of his successor Robert Tarr Jr. He
said his departure would not signal any dramatic changes in
strategy. ``There'll be no change really in the way the company
will be run in the immediate future,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt will follow through on a plan announced in May to spin
off its 54 percent stake in Neiman Marcus to form a new,
independent company, which would remain under its existing
management. Richard Smith said that creating two separate
publishing and retail businesses would lead to a fairer -- and
higher -- market valuation for Harcourt General's assets.
</P>
<P>
   News of the personnel changes was greeted calmly on Wall Street,
where Harcourt General stock rose 5/16 to 50 15/16 on the New York
Stock Exchange. ``The market's been anticipating this for awhile,''
said Peter Appert, media analyst at Deutsche Banc Alex Brown in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Smith's family holds 28 percent of Harcourt General's
stock. Smith said he will continue to play an active role as
chairman, partly because so much of his family's fortune is bound
up in the firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
