<SLUG> BC-US-RUSSIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND RUSSIA STRIKE DEAL ON RUSSIAN TROOPS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ The United States and Russia agreed late
Friday to award Russian troops a prominent role in peacekeeping
operations in Kosovo one week after Russian troopers defied NATO
and seized the largest airfield in the bloodied Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached by U.S. and Russian negotiators in
Helsinki, Finland, cleared the way for a summit meeting Sunday
between President Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin here
in Cologne.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is attending the annual summit of the world's seven
most powerful industrialized democracies here, said he was ``very
pleased'' with the outcome of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a good day _ we are achieving our objectives,''
Clinton said. ``We know that we have 35,000 Serb forces out, 19,000
KFOR forces in. Now we have the agreement with the Russians and the
Kosovars are going home,'' Clinton said. ``I feel very good and
very grateful for their (Russia's) support.''
</P>
<P>
   KFOR is the acronym for the peace-keeping force led by the
United States and other members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official said 3,600 Russian troops will be
deployed in Kosovo ``within the KFOR command structure'' and within
the chain of military command of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
   A total of 2,850 Russian troops will patrol geographic areas
within three sectors supervised by the United States, France and
Germany. The remaining 750 Russian troops will administer and
provide security for the airfield in the Kosovo capital of
Pristina, located in the British sector. Russian forces must permit
all nations' forces to use the facility.
</P>
<P>
   That same airfield has been under Russian control since last
Friday when Russian troops rushed from peacekeeping duties in
Bosnia _ another province of the former Yugoslavia _ and into
Kosovo to seize the airfield.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, right after the Yugoslav government had agreed to
withdraw from Kosovo and NATO had ended its bombing campaign, NATO
and Russian officials were still debating what role Russia should
play in Kosovo. The hangup was NATO's insistence that Russian
troops operate under NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's surprise move of troops to the Pristina airport led to
the Helsinki agreement reached Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Russians' presence is needed to help allay the
concerns of Serbian civilians and protect Serbian religious and
cultural sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's quite important that every effort be made to
secure both the physical sites and the personal security of the
Serb minority as well as the Kosovar Albanian majority,'' Clinton
said. ``We think it will give confidence to (Serbs) that the
Russians are in more than one sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia and Serbia, which share religious and ethnic ties, have
been long-standing allies.
</P>
<P>
   The senior White House official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, insisted the Russian troops will be joining a NATO-led
operation working from a NATO operational plan that will carry out
peacekeeping operations ``with a common command and common rules of
engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian force, consisting of five battalions, will join the
50,000-strong international security force in Kosovo known as KFOR
but will be commanded by Russian officers. Russian officers also
will serve as liaisons at KFOR headquarters in Pristina; NATO
regional headquarters in Naples, Italy; and NATO military
headquarters in Mons, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along we want Russians to participate and we
think it will be a stronger and better force,'' the senior White
House official said, adding that there will be ``no Russian sector
and no partition'' of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was reached in negotiations in Helsinki that
included Defense Secretary William Cohen and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright bargaining with the Russian defense minister,
Marshall Igor Sergeyev, and Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev said the 3,600 Russian troops will ``remain under the
complete military and political control of the Russian side.''
</P>
<P>
   The senior White House official in Cologne said if a nation's
forces declined to carry out an order within KFOR ``for any
reason,'' the KFOR commander was authorized to dispatch other
nations' troops to complete the task.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The compromise was designed to enable Yeltsin to claim that
Russian peacekeeping troops will serve as independent partners with
allied forces in Kosovo. The compromise also sought to provide the
U.S.-dominated 19-nation NATO alliance the unified chain of command
that it insisted was needed to guarantee the effectiveness and
neutrality of a peacekeeping force that is needed to encourage the
return of an estimated 1.6 million ethnic Albanian Muslim refugees
uprooted by Serbian ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   The deal eased U.S.-Russian tensions that had been growing
during the U.S.-led 78-day bombing of Yugoslavia and the expansion
of NATO to include Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic _ three
former nations of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the Helsinki agreement was reached, National
Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger expressed concern about
the Russians' ambiguous explanations for the surprise seizure of
the Pristina airfield.
</P>
<P>
   Berger conceded that the White House still does not know the
truth behind the Kremlin's mysterious decision to take control of
the airfield.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's foreign minister had assured Albright at one point last
Friday that the movement was a mistake and would be reversed. His
assurances raised the specter that Russia's nuclear-equipped armed
forces might have acted independently beyond the constraints of
civilian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin leaders later said that Yeltsin had given the order to
military leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of different possibilities about who
ordered what when, and who knew what when, what did he know and
when did he know it,'' Berger said. He declined to speculate about
why ``Russian soldiers wound up at the airport when they were not
supposed to be there and why we were told that they would not
deploy and they deployed nonetheless,'' adding: ``There are, as I
say, a number of possible scenarios and I think we have to be wise
enough to contemplate all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via E-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
