<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BROTHERSQUINN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BROTHERS QUINN EXPLORE THEIR IRISH ROOTS IN `FATHER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Aidan Quinn ambles up to the table to join Paul Quinn for a
late breakfast at a Dallas hotel restaurant, there's no doubt that
the two are brothers. Both have the same steely eyes, the same
Midwestern baritones, the same cadences to their sentences. They
both sport goatees that offset sharp features, inspiring a joking
comment about how they vaguely resemble bikers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a biker in `Leaving Las Vegas,' '' Paul Quinn pipes
up, amused. ``I beat up Nicolas Cage.''
</P>
<P>
   Aidan Quinn then mentions that he still has the bike he rode in
1984's ``Reckless,'' his first film. ``I love that bike, man,''
Quinn says.
</P>
<P>
   The only bikes you'll find in the Quinns' latest movie, ``This
Is My Father,'' are the unmotorized kind. ``Father'' stars James
Caan as a depressed Chicago schoolteacher who travels to Ireland to
learn about the father he never knew. The movie switches between
the present and 1939, telling of a star-crossed romance between a
poor tenant farmer named Kieran O'Day and the younger,
free-spirited Fiona Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   For the Quinns, ``Father'' gives new meaning to ``family film.''
Paul Quinn wrote the movie, inspired by a story the Quinns' mother
told them about events in her Irish village. He also directed, with
Aidan Quinn in the role of Kieran O'Day. Another brother, Declan
Quinn, did the film's sterling cinematography. Even sister Marian
has a small role in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinns believe that their labor of love is a family film in
another way, too _ it's a family film that is suitable for
teen-agers. They're stunned that the gentle movie, with its tiny
doses of sex and violence, received an R rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sensitizing film,'' Paul Quinn says. ``It makes people
go through a catharsis and have to face some of their own pain
about being left alone and abandoned, and their father issues. A
lot of men I know, boy, this film hits 'em hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Aidan is the more famous Quinn, Paul is the more
loquacious. As a writer, he tries to pack a lot into ``Father's''
screenplay, including material about the Catholic Church's
influence in midcentury Ireland, class structure and the immigrant
experience.
</P>
<P>
   The Quinns want to make it clear that the father in the movie
isn't their father. Kieran O'Day, the title character, is somewhat
slow-witted; the Quinns' father is an erudite, retired English
professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very interested in knowledge,'' Paul says. ``He got me
interested in literature. But not right away. I resisted him for
ages. Once I sort of relented, I really just became obsessed with
reading fiction. He's got a massive library. He's an Irish scholar.
... I was drawing pictures of James Joyce when I was 8 years old.
It's kind of a strange thing to be doing, in retrospect.''
</P>
<P>
   You could hardly call the Quinns a ``show-biz'' family along the
lines of the Baldwin brothers, but the Quinns' close upbringing
helped give them a sort of unspoken shorthand on the set of
``Father.'' It helped that they share a curiosity about their Irish
roots.
</P>
<P>
   Paul wants to do a movie that's more specifically about his
parents' experiences _ about their move from Ireland to the States
in the '50s, when they became active in Kennedy-era Democratic
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I showed (''This Is My Father'') to them, it was one of
the great thrills I ever got,'' Paul Quinn says. ``It was sort of a
rough cut, two Thanksgivings ago. My mom's face was wet. My dad
walked in the kitchen _ he would nod affirmatively as he walked
into the kitchen to have a cry. It was great to see that and effect
that. And part of it, I think, is that they were really proud of us
pulling it together, and proud that the Ireland they knew was on
the screen and it wasn't some characterization they would have been
offended by.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
