<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1232 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS &LR;      06-18 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS MAY NOT BE ABLE TO PASS GUN-CONTROL LEGISLATION  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House rejected a major gun-control bill Friday,
raising the possibility that lawmakers may not be able to produce
legislation this year in the wake of the Colorado school tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing a blow to Clinton administration efforts to force
background checks on firearms purchases at gun shows, flea markets
and pawn shops, lawmakers voted 280-147 against passage of a
Republican-sponsored bill that gun-control advocates feared would
not go far enough in limiting access to weapons by criminals and
children. The bill dealt with gun shows but would have weakened
existing laws governing background checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people will not stand for this'' President
Clinton said in a statement. ``Our nation is waiting for Washington
to pass a real law that keeps guns away from children and out of
the hands of criminals. I call on the Congress to stop playing
politics and start living up to its responsibility to help save
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., accused the Democrats
of turning their backs on ``a sensible'' gun-control measure when
they had the chance to pass the first significant bill dealing with
firearms legislation since Congress banned the sale of assault
weapons in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let there be no mistake,'' Hastert countered, ``the vast
majority of the Democrat caucus walked away when they had the
chance to walk forward for the good of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   All but 10 Democrats did end up voting against the bill, but so
did 82 Republicans, who rejected Hastert's pleas that they rally
behind some form of gun control to show their concern about what
happened two months ago in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All 17 Texas Democrats voted against the bill, as did
Republicans Kevin Brady of The Woodlands, Joe Barton of Dallas,
Larry Combest of Lubbock, Sam Johnson of Plano, Ron Paul of
Surfside and Mac Thornberry of Clarendon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the House bill found particularly objectionable a
provision approved late Thursday night by a vote of 218-211 that
would have extended the current instant background check to guns
sold by unlicensed dealers at firearms shows, but set a deadline of
only 24 hours for completing checks before the purchaser got the
gun anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All 13 of the Texas Republicans voted for that provision, the
state's Democrats split over it, with nine of them also voting in
favor of it. They were Reps. Gene Green of Houston, Max Sandlin, of
Marshall, Ciro Rodriguez of San Antonio, Jim Turner of Crockett,
Solomon Ortiz of Corpus Christi, Nick Lampson of Beaumont, Ralph
Hall of Rockwall, Silvestre Reyes of El Paso and Charles Stenholm
of Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Democratic leaders had been pushing for at
least a three-business-day period for checks at guns shows, which
is the requirement now under the Brady law for purchases made
through licensed dealers.
</P>
<P>
   They called the 24-hour provision, which was sponsored by Rep.
John Dingell, D-Mich., ``a ruse'' that would really undermine the
Brady law on background checks while appearing to crackdown on
unlicensed dealers.
</P>
<P>
   They also charged that the Dingell amendment and the underlying
House gun-control bill, which would have still allowed nine or
fewer unlicensed sellers to hold a gun show without having to
conduct any background checks, was ghostwritten by lobbyists with
the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   The claim was not disputed by NRA representatives who
acknowledged that many of their ``suggestions and proposals'' were
accepted by Dingell and House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., who authored the larger bill that would have exempted
background checks at gatherings of fewer than 10 gun sellers.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection of the Hyde bill ended an emotional three-day
debate among Republicans and Democrats on the House floor trying to
come to grips with the shooting and bombing incident last April at
Columbine High School in Colorado that killed 15 people and wounded
21 others.
</P>
<P>
   The vote leaves the fate of gun-control legislation uncertain
for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has approved a much stronger gun-control measure as
part of a larger juvenile crime bill. The House has also passed a
separate $1.5 billion juvenile justice measure designed to crack
down on minors who commit violent crimes. But without a significant
gun-control element as part of it, the two chambers may not be able
to settle on a final piece of legislation that President Clinton
will be willing to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Other provisions in the House juvenile crime bill may also make
it difficult to reach a compromise. For example, the House bill
contains a provision that would allow the states to display the Ten
Commandments in classrooms and government buildings, a move that
its Republican sponsor said is aimed at helping to restore ``a
sense of morality'' to the nation's young people.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton praised the idea behind the religious amendment,
he said he would encourage legislators to explore ``another
option'' that would not prompt a court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many in the Senate _ Democrats and Republicans alike _
find the provision objectionable. There also are disagreements over
how severe the penalties should be for minors who commit violent
acts and whether prosecutors instead of judges should decide
whether to try minors as adults in extreme cases _ as the House
bill requires _ where the juvenile punishment system doesn't seem
to fit the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Democratic leaders said they were still hopeful
that a juvenile justice bill could be produced in conference that
includes ``meaningful'' gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said the main focus
for Democratic conferees would be ``getting closer'' to the
Senate-passed provisions on gun control, which would ban large
capacity ammunition clips, require safety locks to be sold with
handguns, and extend the three-business-day background checks to
all unlicensed dealers at gun shows and other venues where weapons
are sold.
</P>
<P>
   But that could be a problem, since the House also rejected
242-182 Friday a similar bill containing the Senate language.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who led the fight to
prevent the Senate provisions from passing in the House, said
Republicans would still try to get some kind of gun-control bill
through conference. But he acknowledged that it would likely be
``difficult'' given the great differences that exist among
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif., agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, there were things in this (House) bill that were
not philosophically palatable for Democrats and Republicans
alike,'' he said. ``There were votes against this on both sides of
the aisle, for reasons having to do with personal philosophy, not
party politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the votes on the Dingell measure and the larger Hyde
bill were seen as victories for the NRA, which spent some $1.5
million trying to defeat the gun-control bills in both the House
and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also acknowledged defeat for the time being, telling
reporters that the NRA had succeeded _ with the help of
conservative Republicans _ in turning the debate over gun control
into a debate over cultural problems that contribute to violence.
</P>
<P>
   But neither the president nor gun-control lawmakers were ready
to give up on efforts to enact legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, told reporters. ``This issue
is not going away ... and those of us who care about the safety of
our children are not going away.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech before Friday's final vote on the gun-control bill,
Jackson Lee warned the NRA, ``We're going to turn the lights out on
you. We can beat the gun lobby.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1859EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0619-COX     06-18 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GERMAN NATO TROOPS FIND KLA BEATING ALBANIAN PRISONERS
 &HT;    575&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-RAPE-0619; G8-KOSOVO-0619.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Kosovo _ German NATO troops found a dead man and 15
other people badly beaten in a former Serbian Interior Ministry
police station and detained 25 members of the Kosovo Liberation
Army in the latest step by NATO peacekeepers Friday to reign in the
rebel army.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA guerillas, who were disarmed by the German troops, had
apparently imprisoned and severely beaten the elderly people,
mostly Gypsies, accusing them of looting the homes of ethnic
Albanians and cooperating with Serbian military or police forces.
</P>
<P>
   According to German NATO officers, troops found the dead elderly
man chained to a chair in what may have been a KLA torture chamber
for alleged collaborators with the Serbs during their attempts to
terrorize Albanians into fleeing the wars-torn province.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses saw the Germans take weapons away from scores of KLA
soldiers and eventually carry the stiff body of the elderly man
into a military truck. German troops piled up a small collection of
about four rifles, 30 clips for automatic weapons, a bag of shotgun
shells and 10 hand grenades outside the police station -- actually
just a smattering of armaments in a region where nearly every man
owns weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything went without problems,'' German Sgt. Maj. Johann
Fritsch said. ``The situation was tense, but the handing over of
weapons was not.''
</P>
<P>
   But the discovery, which came four days after the separatist
rebels returned triumphantly to Prizren, a city in southern Kosovo,
following the withdrawal of Yugoslav force and Serb police and
paramilitary gangs serves as a reminder of the KLA's reputation for
brutality -- something frequently overlooked in recent months as
the group became a convenient ally of NATO in its 78-day air war
against Serb-led Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have long considered the rebel group to be
undisciplined and violent, and at one point claimed it was a
terrorist organization -- a claim echoed by the Yugoslav government
in defense of its brutal actions against Kosovo's ethnic Albanian
majority. That ended around the time the group became a significant
political and military threat to Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic,
president of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   While the gruesome discovery shows the difficulties NATO may
face in transforming the KLA from a war-hardened guerrilla group to
a modern, democratic political organization that respects human
rights, German commanders did reach an agreement Friday with the
KLA that its soldiers could not walk openly with weapons anywhere
in the southwestern sector of Kosovo overseen by German troops.
</P>
<P>
   KLA fighters are commonly seen on the streets of Prizren,
Kosovo's second largest city, with rifles and hand grenades. They
were supposed to stop carrying weapons at midnight (local time)
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   German troops had insisted previously that they had no legal
authority to disarm KLA soldiers unless they interfered with Kosovo
Force, or KFOR, peacekeeping troops. KLA leaders have insisted that
their weapons were needed to protect ethnic Albanians while some
Serbs remained in the region and threatened to commit acts of
terror.
</P>
<P>
   However, the relative quiet in Prizren the last couple of days
seemed to clear the way for the agreement. U.S. troops began
disarming the KLA in their sector of Kosovo on Thursday while in
Pec, a northern city where Serbs are still active, Italian troops
have yet to disarm the KLA -- which taken control in scattered
areas of the province as Serb troops have withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   As further evidence of KLA cooperation Friday, the rebels agreed
to turn over to the American NATO troops five Serb kidnap victims
whom KLA activists had seized inside Kosovo this week for allegedly
burning Albanian villages and killing Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to keep them,'' said KLA brigade commander Agron
Hoxha in an interview at his hilltop headquarters here in
southeastern Kosovo. ``We are interested in giving NATO these war
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoxha said the five Serbs would be released Saturday morning in
reasonably good health, even though he acknowledged they ``have
been beaten up a little bit'' by the KLA irregular forces he said
had captured the five men for interrogation.
</P>
<P>
   At least 27 Serbs, many from prominent families, were kidnapped
within two days in the American occupation zone of Kosovo by armed
gunmen claiming to represent the KLA during an orgy of retribution
before American peacekeepers had taken firm control.
</P>
<P>
   If the promised release occurs, it will mean that about 25 of
about 27 Serb kidnap victims have been released. At least two
others are still thought to be missing.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
