<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1242 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-ART-2TA     06-18 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH NO ONE ELSE IN CHARGE, KOSOVO REBELS TAKE OVER CIVIL
AUTHORITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ The Kosovo Liberation Army is setting up
interim governments in a number of cities, moving rapidly to fill
the civic vacuum. In at least one case of exerting their
self-appointed authority, the rebels arrested and beat several
prisoners, apparently so severely that one of them died Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-guerrillas are moving into city halls and makeshift
municipal buildings, with their own black-uniformed police at the
doors, trying to get electricity, water and other basic services
working. Their major problem, several of the newly minted civil
officials said, is that there is virtually no food and tens of
thousands more refugees are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, under the terms of the agreement signed with
the Serbs, is supposed to set up a civil authority, but has not
done so. The KLA is acting without any legal mandate, but NATO
commanders appear to have allowed the KLA to deal with several
local matters.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for the KLA to be demilitarized by NATO
forces, but that has been enforced more strictly in some sectors
than in others. As the KLA flexes its muscles among a population
that still includes many frightened or hostile Serbs, its swift
assumption of power has brought it into conflict with NATO in some
cases, most notably in the German and American sectors.
</P>
<P>
   The tenuous and volatile nature of NATO's balancing act _
allowing the KLA to operate where it is convenient and trying to
rein them in where it is not _ was illustrated here Friday
afternoon when German troops swooped down on a former Serb special
police headquarters taken over by the KLA, briefly held 25 of the
guerrillas' military police and seized a pile of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the police station, the German troops found 15 prisoners
held by the KLA, including an elderly man who was found dead,
handcuffed to a chair and badly beaten, according to a German
military spokesman, Lt. Col. Dietmar Jeserich. The prisoners were a
mixture of Serbs, Albanians and Gypsies, and it was not clear why
they had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   One man had red welts across his back as if he had been lashed,
an old man had a bandage on his head and cuts on his face where he
had been beaten and another man said he had been stabbed in the
leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even your worst enemy could do such a thing,'' said
Jankovic Janko, an elderly Serb who was beaten on the head. He said
he was seized outside his house on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The German troops confiscated weapons from stunned KLA soldiers
in passing cars and announced that no more weapons would be allowed
on the streets here after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Rolf Bescht, the German commander, said the NATO troops
were taking over the police station ``to make it perfectly clear we
are the only force, the only authority in town, not the KLA.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, relations between the NATO peacekeepers and the KLA
have for the most part been cordial, with the guerrillas regarding
the peacekeepers as allies who forced out the Serbs, and NATO
commanders _ whose own troops and tanks are only now spreading out
any distance from their bases _ tolerating the KLA guardposts along
the roads. The major tension has been in the American-controlled
sector where marines and paratroopers have aggressively disarmed
KLA patrols.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The good feeling is symbolized by posters bearing the rebel's
double-headed Albanian eagle and their Albanian initials UCK along
with those of NATO, posted all over the city of Djakovica. But all
that could change rapidly if there are clashes over disarming.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the KLA is the only coherent Albanian force on the
ground at the moment, the only group with an organizational
structure and, now, a mass base of support developed during the
Serb campaign of terror. But the KLA has been united solely by its
resistance to the Serbs. Any other ideology is murky, and the group
is believed to contain a number of factions.
</P>
<P>
   When Slobodan Milosevic ignited passionate Serb nationalism in
Kosovo a decade ago as his means to political power, he fired all
Albanians from management positions, the police force and any other
post of authority. Albanians responded with their own ``parallel
society,'' running, for example schools and widely attended
elections in their homes. But, despite the approval of Western
leaders _ mainly because they didn't cause trouble _ their
nonviolence brought few gains, and its advocate Ibrahim Rugova, is
widely discredited.
</P>
<P>
   The new mayor here, Masar Shala, was the KLA's information
director across the Albanian border in Kukes last week. Up the road
in Djakovica, the district prefect, Mazllom Kumnova, is another KLA
member, a former political prisoner and longtime opposition
activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing is to form a government administration,''
Kumnova said. ``With the end of the war, the KLA will form also the
civil government. We will every day have more and more problems.
This government will be until we have elections.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   He said he had arrived two days ago, chosen by the military
command, from a KLA headquarters in the village of Mazreka. It was
difficult to work, he said, because people kept coming in to ask
about the more than 1,000 missing men believed to have been taken
from the city by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we don't have laws, we don't have written norms,''
he said, but we have enthusiasm for building a new state.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has said that it intends to establish a civil
administration, but details of how it plans to do so are vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I notice that the U.N. is going to do this organization of the
administration but they are late,'' Kumnova said. ``We couldn't
leave a vacuum without a government. Our purpose is that the
Albanians should be ready when the administration of the UN comes
to offer our project for a civil government. We are in the process
of assessing our needs.''
</P>
<P>
   United Nations and German officers worked closely with the KLA
in bringing the refugees across the border. KLA troops, first in
uniform and then, after some discussion, in civilian clothes,
helped register the refugees and screen out aspiring Albanian
looters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KLA has been extremely constructive at the border,'' said
a high ranking U.N. official. ``They have made themselves a very
significant force inside the country.''
</P>
<P>
   But for some NATO officials the immediate problem was not civil
authority, but the guns being carried on the streets by the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   At a NATO briefing Friday morning, a German troop commander
announced that an agreement had been reached with the regional KLA
chief, known as Commander Drini, that no guns would be carried in
town after midnight and that military apparel would soon be shed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``With the agreement with the KLA, we now have the green light
to disarm anyone who goes around armed in the city. After two
further days, we will also have a ban on appearing in KLA uniform
in the city,'' Bescht said.
</P>
<P>
   Bescht also said the German troops had taken over the police
station to reinforce NATO authority. Germans had given the KLA
until noon to leave the station. But shortly after that, a German
patrol led by Maj. Dietrich Jensch saw that the guerrillas were
still there. The police station was soon surrounded by German
troops. The prisoners held by the KLA were released and several
treated by German medics.
</P>
<P>
   The 25 KLA military police who had been inside the police
station were gathered in one corner, under the guns of the German
troops, looking discomfitted at this turn of events. Their weapons,
mostly Kalashnikov assault rifles and extra clips of ammunition,
were piled up near the steps. Eventually, after much discussion,
the KLA troops were marched off by one of their commanders to their
own base.
</P>
<P>
   Commander Drini, who rushed to the scene to negotiate with the
German officers, said the prisoners were ``criminals.'' Several
people in the crowd of onlookers said there were two people who
were believed to be Albanians who had been informers for the Serbs.
A youth, Gzim Raduni, 16, said he recognized a Gypsy whom he had
told the KLA had stolen plates and silverware from his home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
