NYT-06-18-99 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1247 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-NYT &LR;      06-18 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO DISTRAUGHT AS KOSOVO SERBS, WARY OF KLA, FLEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IAN FISHER    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORAHOVAC, Yugoslavia _ A few days ago, the Serbs here made a
brave and unusual decision: They would stay in this Kosovo hillside
town, nearly 4,000 of them, and try to live again beside Albanians,
even as their fellow Serbs fled the province in the tens of
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   That all broke down Friday, and with it one small pocket of hope
for re-creating a multi-ethnic Kosovo. Friday afternoon, heavily
armed young German soldiers were reduced to escorting scared
Serbian women to their homes so they could pick up a few things and
leave town, probably forever. One woman walked down the street
grasping a soldier's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's war,'' said Andelka Jovicic, a 42-year-old Serb, as she
dropped some old photos and a white shoe into her suitcase in the
apartment where she has lived for 20 years. ``I'm afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   For the previous few days, NATO officials had been advertising
Orahovac as a bright spot in the Kosovo devastation _ and they have
worked hard to persuade the Serbs to stay. Friday, officers took
that message house to house in the Serbian quarter, which is
crowded with the cars of Serbs who had lived around the town and
are now waiting to leave Kosovo for other parts of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sergio Vieira de Mello, the United Nations envoy to Kosovo,
was here Friday talking to the mayor, who is a Serb. Asked if he
was having any success in reassuring him, Vieira de Mello said, ``I
don't seem to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs' reasons for leaving town are particularly disturbing
to NATO, because they seem closely linked to the peacekeeping
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs here allege that guerrillas of the Kosovo Liberation Army
kidnapped seven men Wednesday and Thursday as they went house to
house confiscating weapons. And as the guerrilla force only came
out of hiding since the arrival of the peacekeepers Sunday, the
Serbs here say they believe that the peacekeepers are cooperating
with the former rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we live here?'' asked Ljubisa Vitosevic, 25, who said
his 61-year-old father, Marko, was kidnapped two days ago. ``You
can see after only two days what's happening here. Nobody can
guarantee us anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogoljub Kujunojic, 57, a food inspector, said: ``We would all
stay here. But we've lost the trust. I don't know what to expect
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the Serbs have eyed the peacekeepers, under NATO
command, with distrust for a reason that is hard to overcome: It
was NATO, after all, that bombed the Serbs for more than two
months, with some degree of cooperation with KLA forces on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   But since the peacekeepers arrived, that distrust has only
deepened as the KLA has tried to step in to become the new civil
and administrative force in Kosovo. NATO insists that it is the
only real power in Kosovo and that it is completely even-handed
with Serbs and Albanians alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to try to tell the Serbs that they are safe
here,'' said Captain Peter Egger, who commands the unit of 120
German peacekeepers here. ``We have checkpoints in and out of town.
We control the KLA. Nobody has to be anxious.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality, though, is that the KLA has felt free to demand
weapons from local people _ even as they themselves are supposed to
disarm under the terms of the peace agreement _ and they have taken
over the police station here as their new headquarters. But they
strongly deny having kidnapped anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs lie to you,'' said Skender Hoxha, the local KLA
commander. ``It's Serb propaganda.''
</P>
<P>
   What is happening in Orahovac seems only to give credence to the
view that too much happened in Kosovo over the last year _ too many
Albanians dead and displaced _ for Serbs and Albanians to live
together any time soon. Mayor Andelk Kovosinac, 49, said he hoped
that would not have been the case here, where some 7 percent of the
population is Serb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that more Albanians were killed than Serbs'' in the
conflict, Kovosinac said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``We're always lived together. We all want to stay
here.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that in the streets, in casual chats between neighbors,
Serbs decided several days ago that they would try to make it work:
At a meeting several days ago, he said, the peacekeepers, local
Albanians and the KLA, all assured him that the Serbs should stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone said it was going to be OK,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But then the kidnappings were reported, mostly of older men, and
Serbs from around town moved up the hill in fear into the Serb
quarter. Top Serb officials in Belgrade have tried to convince the
Serbs here to leave.
</P>
<P>
   And as word spread among Albanians that the Serbs were going to
leave,_ any early optimism among the Serbs has disintegrated. A
Serb civilian with a machine gun, threatening to kill KLA soldiers,
had to be prevented by friends from going down into the main
square.
</P>
<P>
   In the square, Albanian men kept watch in the town center to
halt the convoy of Serbs: One reason is that Albanians claim that
many of the cars and trucks that the Serbs have were stolen from
them. Albanian refugees also want about 40 men arrested who they
say committed atrocities over the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we also want to live with them,'' said Qant Sharku, 33, a
driver and construction worker. ``But only the Serbs that aren't
dirty.'' But when asked how many of them participated in the war,
he answered, ``Almost all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali Kabashi, 62, called his nephews, Sakip, 13, and Sahit, 14,
out of a crowd here. He said the boys had survived an attack from a
grenade, which he said was thrown into a basement full of 30 people
in a nearby town by a local Serb policeman. Five people died,
including the boys' mother, grandmother and two sisters, one of
whom was only six months old.
</P>
<P>
   Kabashi first said that he thought some Serbs should stay, that
it was possible for Orahovac to return to something resembling what
it was like before. But then he changed his mind: In truth, he said
he could never again live next to a Serb family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't,'' he said. ``They killed a six-month-old baby. They
all should go. How can they stay?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
