<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV TROOPS WITHDRAWING SLIGHTLY AHEAD OF SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODUJEVO, Yugoslavia _ Yugoslav troops pulled out of northern
towns of Kosovo Friday, moving slightly ahead of schedule and
showing a readiness now to leave ahead of Sunday's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav troops still manned posts along the roads, looking out
from the second-floor balconies of roadside houses, or sitting on
chairs by the entrances of buildings. Around them in the villages
along the road several houses were still burning, the smoke thick
and white under a light rain. They seemed to be Albanian houses,
evidently set on fire just a few hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The British 4th Armored Brigade moved into the town of Podujevo,
making a big show of force and stationing three gigantic guns on
the main street and half a dozen troop carriers beside the Serbian
police station. They were in place by 6 a.m. to watch columns of
Yugoslav tanks, troop trucks and armored cars leave.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time French troops moved in to Mitrovica to the
west, coordinating their entrance with the departing Yugoslav
forces. The northern part of Kosovo is the last area to see troops
go.
</P>
<P>
   Some 10,500 Serbian police and army are left in Kosovo now, and
have to leave by midnight Sunday. NATO spokesmen said the departure
is moving ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian refugees, meanwhile, are pouring into the province from
the south. Some 50,000 have now crossed over from Albania and
Macedonia into Kosovo in NATO's wake, a spokesman from the U.N.
high commissioner for refugees said Friday. More than 18,000 alone
crossed over on Wednesday, 13,000 of them from Kukes in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   A Yugoslav officer guarding the army base in Podujevo alongside
two British soldiers said the last troops would be gone from the
town by Saturday morning, well ahead of schedule, since Podujevo is
one of the last major towns in the north.
</P>
<P>
   The officer watched the ethnic Albanian residents of Podujevo
strolling on the streets for the first time in two months now that
NATO is in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strange to see all these people, especially the young
ones,'' he said. ``We only saw old men and women coming out for
bread before.''
</P>
<P>
   As elsewhere, the local residents lined the streets and tossed
flowers to the arriving NATO troops. Many said they had fled the
town in March and lived in the hills for a month. They filtered
back down to their homes a month ago, since the conditions had been
so desperate and food so scarce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just stayed indoors all the time,'' said Imer Aliu, a
gray-haired man standing admiring the British AS-90 vehicle-mounted
guns. ``For the first time we will sleep soundly tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
