<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-2TAKES-N     06-18 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-BARAK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: ISRAELIS HEAR TROUBLE IN BARAK'S SILENCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israelis abhor silence, and their prime
minister-elect, Ehud Barak, has been silent as a stone since his
overwhelming victory a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, Barak has conducted extensive negotiations with
political parties to form a coalition government. But he has made
few public declarations, given few interviews and refused to show
his hand through the news leaks that have long been tradition here.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an unusually protracted limbo between governments,
and anxious Israeli commentators first read trouble into the
vacuum. They decided that Barak, 57, a highly decorated former
general, was a political rookie who was undergoing an excruciating
hazing. They criticized his slowness to form a government, pressing
him, as did political associates, to be less obstinate, to soften
his demands, to hurry up and fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of this week, after the resignation of Aryeh Deri
as the leader of the ultra-Orthodox Shas party, public opinion had
turned around. Barak, many realized, was pursuing a strategy: With
complete deliberateness, he was choosing to set his course and then
wait for others to come around. He is not a man who blinks first.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our country of fleeting images,'' Chemi Shalev, a
columnist, wrote Friday in the newspaper Maariv, ``Barak changed
overnight from being a loser to a winner, from being an
inexperienced political apprentice to a real `wizard.' The truth
lies, as usual, somewhere in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Deri, who was convicted of corruption this
spring, represented a breakthrough in the coalition negotiations.
Immediately afterward, Barak gave his first extensive interview
since his victory, published Friday in the newspaper Haaretz.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Barak said he would move quickly to
construct a $200 million, 29-mile elevated highway between
Palestinian territories in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, in the Haaretz interview and in recent private
conversations, Barak has made it clear that he considers himself to
be charting a new course, learning from the mistakes of his
predecessors. Better to build a government slowly than to make
alliances or promises he would live to regret, he has said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said it is better to make peace with the Palestinians
and the Syrians a priority _ if priorities must be chosen _ than to
turn first to solving internal divisions. The internal divisions,
however grave, will not literally blow up in Israel's face, he has
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Palestinians officials say his silence toward them has
been unnerving, Barak has said he is sending messages to Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader. He has congratulated Arafat for
recent arrests of terror suspects, urged him to be patient and
proclaimed that they will not sit opposite each other but beside
each other at negotiating tables.
</P>
<P>
   On May 18, the day after he was elected by a wide margin, Barak
and his Labor Party faced a critical choice. He was determined to
form a broad coalition so that his parliamentary backing would
match the sweeping electoral mandate he believed he had received.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Party, remade into a coalition party called One
Israel, had received only 26 seats in the fractious 120-member
Parliament. So he felt he needed to turn to one of the other two
medium-sized parties: Shas, with 17 seats, or Labor's traditional
opponent, the defeated Likud Party of Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, with 19 seats.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, he was also choosing between internal peace and
external peace, both of which he had promised to pursue. With Shas,
which is moderate on external talks, he would be able to move
forward with the Palestinians and the Syrians. With Likud, he would
be able to move forward on his domestic program, including a
difficult agenda for the religious parties: drafting yeshiva boys
and writing a constitution that would institutionalize Israel as a
secular, democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations with the acting head of Likud, Ariel Sharon, the
departing foreign minister, broke down when Sharon demanded too
much personal power and right-wing ideological control of the peace
effort.
</P>
<P>
   But Shas, which burgeoned during the elections into a major
political force, presented other problems, primarily Deri.
</P>
<P>
   Deri, who remains out of jail while he appeals his conviction,
had been pronounced an unacceptable partner by Barak and his
centrist and leftist allies. His resignation was considered a
precondition for his party's inclusion in the government, but
seemed difficult to imagine because he is a charismatic leader with
loyal backing.
</P>
<P>
   When he did step down, volunteering to leave town during the
talks so he would not be seen as manipulating behind the scenes,
political analysts here revised their thinking on Barak. They
decided that he plays a good waiting game. They pointed to the way
he also waited out Yitzhak Mordechai, the Center Party leader,
until he stepped down the day before Election Day, assuring Barak's
big victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The model that beat Deri was that same model, that same
determination, those same nerves of steel that Barak used while
waiting for Yitzhak Mordechai to withdraw,'' Sima Kadmon wrote this
week in the newspaper Yedioth Ahronoth. ``Barak believes that if
one is adamant about an issue of principle, if one does not falter
or begin to sweat, the other one will blink first.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak needs to negotiate terms with Shas, and renegotiate with
the other parties whose standing is altered by the inclusion of
Shas. If Barak succeeds in coming to terms with the parties still
at the table, he would end up with a 77-seat bloc, a clear
majority.
</P>
<P>
   It would include Shas, Meretz (the large, traditional left
party), the new Center Party, the Russian immigrant party of Natan
Sharansky, the settlers' party, the ultra-Orthodox United Torah
Judaism party and a small party of trade unionists.
</P>
<P>
   Left in the opposition would be 10 Arab party members and 6
members of the aggressively secularist Shinui party _ which refuses
to sit in a government with Shas, but would probably support Barak
on peace deals and otherwise help keep him in power.
</P>
<P>
   But issues remain to be resolved so Barak does not end up with a
platform so broad that it ties his hands. Israeli law gives him
until July 8 to form a government.
</P>
<P>
   The religious parties are still looking for Barak to compromise
on his campaign pledge to draft the yeshiva boys, who are now
exempt from mandatory army service. The settlers want to secure a
commitment that he will not strip the settlements of their special
financial status. Sharansky's party is intent on holding on to two
ministries.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, having given up Deri, will seek to retain the Interior
Ministry, which Barak promised to take away from them.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Election Day, when Barak's supporters begged him
to close the door on Shas, chanting ``Just not Shas!'' at his
victory rally, a kind of rehabilitation of the party's image has
been under way.
</P>
<P>
   Barak himself has said that the party should be as much a
Sephardic-pride movement as a religious party, and that its
constituency _ Jews who come from the Middle East and North Africa
_ should not be tarred with the same brush as its corrupt leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``In contrast to my friends on the left, who view Shas as a lost
cause, I say that the court passed its verdict on one person,''
Barak told Haaretz. ``I suggest we not cast aspersions on a whole
movement.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In addition to exacting the removal of Deri, which was made
possible by the determination of Shas' spiritual leader, Rabbi
Ovadia Yosef, to join the new government, Barak is also certain to
demand newly transparent accounting practices. ``There will be an
end to the fictitious nonprofit associations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Having determined that waiting worked, it is possible that Barak
will try to sweat out the parties on all their remaining concerns
and stick to his guns.
</P>
<P>
   But he has made it clear that he is willing to defer decisions
on the draft and on the constitution so that he can put the
external peace effort first. He is determined, he has said, to keep
his eye on the bridge he wants to build, and not to be distracted
by the imperfections in individual stones.
</P>
<P>
   Barak seems intent on turning down the volume of the heated
discourse in this country, on introducing greater ``sobriety.''
</P>
<P>
   Very sure of himself, he seems determined to defy conventional
wisdom about what can and cannot be accomplished in Israel. He
wants to rise above the fray. Whether, as a political novice, he
has the ability to do so remains to be seen in what are likely to
be tumultuous months ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
