<SLUG> BC-DADDAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF WISHES WERE FATHER'S DAY GIFTS, THIS FATHER WOULD BE KING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BUZZ MCCLAIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My fourth Father's Day was rapidly approaching, and I found
myself conflicted.
</P>
<P>
   What, pray tell, did I want?
</P>
<P>
   My wife's favorite Mother's Day gift is an afternoon at the
Galleria _ without the kids. She thinks Mother's Day is
Independence Day, with a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   My own mother was the same way. Whenever we asked her what she
wanted on Her Day, she never failed to reply: ``A day of peace and
quiet.'' At the time, I couldn't understand why she would ask for
this _ the very thing we were entirely at a loss to accomplish (no
way was my father going to stay home alone with four wild
children). So every year we gave her stinky cheap perfume and a new
set of drinking glasses _ and every year she'd unwrap them and
smile and tell us it was exactly what she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   With two precocious children, ages 4 and 20 months, I was
beginning to understand the appeal of peace and quiet _ whatever
that might be _ but I just wasn't sure.
</P>
<P>
   With my wife pressing for some answers, I gave the day some
thought.
</P>
<P>
   First I thought of what I'd like. That seemed like the easy
part:
</P>
<P>
   Rangers tickets. For the family. So the Rangers are in Boston on
Father's Day, but they're at home Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday
in a crucial home stand against division rivals the Oakland
Athletics, and they're not back in Arlington again until July 2.
And to sweeten the deal, June 22 is Decker Dog Night, which means
the weenies will only be a buck. Failing to get to the game, one of
those Rangers red polo shirts would be acceptable (I wear XL).
</P>
<P>
   A DVD player. I know, I know _ they're expensive, but it IS
Father's Day. If the household budget can afford a splurge, there
are some very nice DVD players out there for about $400, although
Samsung makes one that goes for about $250 (however, you get what
you pay for in the way of digital component compatibility, sound
quality, etc.). And this isn't entirely selfish _ if we're not at
the Rangers game, the family can have movie time. Don't forget the
popcorn, please.
</P>
<P>
   A Weber gas grill. One big enough to land an aircraft on _ and
feed a family. One of the cliches we dads can't live down is that
we only cook when there's a roaring fire involved, so you may as
well oblige us and get us something that's safe. However, if a gas
grill threatens to bust the budget, one of those classic Weber
charcoal kettle types will be fine. And if that's too expensive,
how about a New York strip steak for dinner? Just think meat.
</P>
<P>
   Golf sandals. OK, this one is entirely selfish, but I could
never bring myself to fork over $70 at the pro shop for a pair of
these monsters. Golf sandals are just what they sound like, a pair
of fortified sandals with short, round studs just like golf shoes.
They are ideal for days when the temps climb into the high 90s _
before breakfast _ but you don't dare cancel your tee time. (I wear
11 1/2.)
</P>
<P>
   A rusty lid for the ``honey-do'' jar. Should all of the above be
too expensive or logistically difficult (and never let it be said I
wanted anyone to go out of their way to get a gift for me, no way),
this would be a superb Father's Day gift. The ``honey-do'' jar is
chock-full right about now, what with the deck needing a coat of
sealant, the attic needing cleaning before the yard sale, and the
boat needing a coat of shellac (What, we don't have a boat? Well
put that on the gift list, too). It would be very nice if for just
one Sunday that jar could stay sealed.
</P>
<P>
   A pneumatic paint sprayer. Should the ``honey-do'' jar be pried
open, it would be wonderful to have one of these motorized
contraptions in the garage to make life a little easier. Please?
</P>
<P>
   But as I made my list and checked it twice, pleased with the
choices that I knew Dads Everywhere would like, too, I began to
realize that Father's Day bliss, for me, meant more than just
getting.
</P>
<P>
   It meant not getting, too.
</P>
<P>
   So, here's what I don't want:
</P>
<P>
   I do not want a ``Teflon necktie'' from J.C. Penney. The Teflon
necktie, which is supposed to repel food stains, is insulting _
it's a glorified bib, for crying out loud. At least save it for my
``golden years.''
</P>
<P>
   I also don't want a videotape of a John Wayne film. Some
big-name video retailers think giving Dad a macho movie is the
perfect way to say, ``Love ya, dad, and thanks for being a man.'' I
think it's silly.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I don't want a day without my kids. Because without
them, I decided at last, I wouldn't even have this special day.
Peace and quiet are overrated. And I miss my kids enough as it is.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
