<SLUG> BC-NJ-BANKS-INVEST-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT FOR THE FAINT-HEARTED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This is a sidebar to NJ-BANK)  
 (af)  
 By RICHARD KORMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does buying shares in a new community bank in your town make
investing sense?
</P>
<P>
   The main attraction is the chance to acquire, at close to book
value and with no fees, a security that subsequently may sell for a
modest multiple of book value.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six new banks that opened their doors in 1997 in New
Jersey, one, Community Bank of New Jersey in Freehold, has run
ahead of the pack. The bank has pumped up its assets, to $94
million last month from $13 million two years ago, and deposits are
growing by $5 million a month. It now trades at 1.7 times book
value.
</P>
<P>
   (The average publicly traded bank that opened in 1997 now trades
at 1.3 times book value; older small- and mid-cap banks trade at
1.9 times book value, according to Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co., a broker and
underwriter based in Livingston, N.J.)
</P>
<P>
   Community Bank of New Jersey is the clear leader in its class
because it is already generating profits, said Cassandra Toroian,
an analyst for Ryan, Beck who follows the stock but has no rating
on it. ``It's usually a couple of years before they break even,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But like all small-bank stocks, it should be viewed as a thinly
traded, and therefore illiquid, microcap. Many start-up banks have
no ready market for their shares. Some, like Village Bank, arrange
for a broker to be a market maker.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hughes, a money manager in Hunter, N.Y., who invests in
bank stocks, thinks that start-ups are a waste of time when bigger,
better-capitalized bank stocks are available at a better value. ``I
could name 50 I'd rather be in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors buy small-bank stocks hoping for a premium in the
event of a takeover. But while there are several recent examples of
big banks' buying small ones and paying an average of three times
book value for them, Ms. Torian said it was not a good idea to
count on a buyout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
