<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Happy Ending &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Was it a blow to crush the spirit of a budding entrepreneur?
Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   To earn enough to buy a pack of Pokemon trading cards, Aaron
Faughn, 9, with two friends, set up a stand in front of his
Hamilton, Ohio, home a week ago and sold lemonade and Kool-Aid for
a quarter a cup until two older kids robbed him of $6.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out to have been the best thing that could have
happened to young Aaron. Local news coverage brought sympathetic
customers flocking, along with invitations to sell his drinks at
neighborhood businesses. Gross receipts rocketed into the hundreds
of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Kraft Foods unit of Philip Morris dispatched a
promotional aide dressed as a pitcher of Kool-Aid to present Aaron
with balloons and gifts, including a Nintendo game. (According to
The Cincinnati Enquirer, the sight of the guy in the pitcher suit
at first sent Aaron ducking behind the stand in fear.)
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, Butler County Sheriff's deputies tracked down and
arrested two teen-agers in connection with the theft. The deputies
got certificates from the Kool-Aid man, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
