<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WORLD-BRITAIN-ART-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BRITAIN, MINING THE ARTS FOR MANAGEMENT METAPHOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20)  
 (af)  
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ At first blush, the idea might seem stretched, even
silly. For $1,800, British executives can spend a weekend at the
Globe Theater being tutored in management skills through the prism
of Shakespeare's plays _ notably ``Henry V'' and ``Julius Caesar.''
</P>
<P>
   But then consider the plot of ``Henry V'': an ambitious leader
(Henry) covets a rival's assets (France) and makes an offer. The
offer is refused. But by marshaling his allies (earls), weeding out
the waverers and deploying true grit and new technology (the
longbow), Henry prevails.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare was dramatizing the Battle of Agincourt of 1415, but
to modern eyes his play is the story of a perfectly executed, very
hostile takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise, a cooperative venture between the Cranfield
University School of Management and the Globe, is one of many
kindred projects in Britain introducing the performing arts into
the repertoire of management education.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is more familiar in the United States than it is
here. But Britain, with a rich cultural heritage on which to draw _
and many arts companies seeking new revenue sources _ is rushing to
embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   In April, for instance, the New York-based conductor Roger
Nierenberg came here to work with the London Philharmonic Orchestra
in presenting a program called the Music Paradigm. Executives from
companies including the Bank of Scotland, BP-Amoco, Nestle and
South African Airways sat among the musicians to glean an
understanding of how orchestral harmony might be translated to
their business organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Nierenberg is to return to England from New York next week to
record a further session for broadcast on BBC television in July;
executives from companies including Allied Domecq, British Airways,
Natwest and Barclays will sit in on Brahms' First Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   His aim is to let executives experience how the orchestra works
_ or doesn't. For instance, he said, he might ask the oboist to
tune down the wind and brass section by a quarter tone. When the
section plays together, it's fine. ``But when the entire orchestra
plays together, the orchestra as a whole is dysfunctional,'' he
said, a parallel to a corporation whose units are not in sync.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Nierenberg might conduct the orchestra in a manner
intended to evoke the tensions that often arise in a merger. ``Two
cultures haven't aligned around the goals, so I'll provoke
difference and then solve the differences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nierenberg, the exercise allows executives to
perceive both the challenges they face and the potential solutions.
``It leaves a new way for them to talk about themselves,'' he said.
``It gives them a metaphor, a vocabulary.'' The cost: $20,000 to
$40,000 a session for a group of executives.
</P>
<P>
   In Stratford-on-Avon, meanwhile, the Royal Shakespeare
Company &UR;  &LR; has initiated a program called Directing Creativity _
usually a one-day event in which managers are coached by a
director, using theatrical techniques, in skills from voice
projection to problem-solving.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, said Kate Hunter, a spokeswoman for the company, is to
use the experience of creating a theatrical ensemble as a model for
teamwork in business.
</P>
<P>
   After a visit this month to the London Business School, the
company is scheduled to go to New Haven, where it will run a course
for managers from Dunkin' Donuts. (The doughnut chain's owner,
Allied Domecq, has an $8.8 million sponsorship deal with the Royal
Shakespeare.)
</P>
<P>
   In part, the rise of arts-based management courses reflects
educators' recognition that their techniques needed to be updated,
said Professor Martin Christopher, head of executive development
programs at Cranfield, which is north of London, in Bedford.
``After all these years, we have discovered that there are a
variety of ways in which we can improve skills, knowledge and
capabilities other than chalk-and-talk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, executives are looking for innovative ways to
enhance managers' performance. ``In the old days, people would come
on a course because it was a good thing to do,'' Christopher said.
``In these more hard-pressed times, the question is, `How can I do
my job better?'''
</P>
<P>
   Fiona Clark, 30, a development and training officer at the
Design Council, which is financed by the British government, said
she had found some answers to that question last September, at a
weekend ``Henry V'' session at the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   The play is regarded as a classic analysis of a young person
stepping into power and exercising it in the face of overwhelming
odds. At the siege of Harfleur, in Act III, for example, the young
King Harry exhorts his followers to again storm the ramparts of the
French port:
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   (italics)I see you stand like greyhounds in the slips,
</P>
<P>
   Straining upon the start. The game's afoot!
</P>
<P>
   Follow your spirit; and, upon this charge
</P>
<P>
   Cry `God for Harry, England and Saint George!'(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   ``What was interesting was that he talked about higher
purpose,'' Ms. Clark said, noting that the King doesn't simply
exhort his soldiers to beat up the French. ``He talks about England
and God,'' she continued. ``That's how he rallied his troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is driven home by Richard Olivier, who runs the
Globe's management seminars. (And yes, if the name seems familiar,
he is the son of the late Lord Olivier, who played Henry V on stage
and screen.) ``The use of language to make the future real _ that,
to me, is one of the key skills of leadership,'' Olivier said.
``It's not enough to put an action plan down on paper or in an
e-mail. You actually have to talk to people, enthuse them with your
passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Clark took the lesson home with her. ``The challenge is to
make it personal to the individual,'' she said. ``What you want is
to inspire people to think what the basic goal means to them.''
</P>
<P>
   But the play is not only about being persuasive. Well before the
battle, the king has three noblemen executed in short order for
treason. There's a corporate lesson in that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you truly believe in what you are doing,'' Ms. Clark said,
``then once you have made that decision, you can't waiver.''
</P>
<P>
   Sending people on training courses is, of course, slightly
different from sending traitors to their deaths. But the parallel
lies in the exercise of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the links I made early on is that Shakespeare, more
than any other playwright, deals with people in a position of
power,'' Olivier said. ``There are always kings, dukes, princes who
are put in some kind of dilemma about how to deal with authority,
whether it is being threatened by someone or where power has to be
negotiated.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Shakespeare's plays end as well as ``Henry V'' ends for
King Harry. But there are business applications in the body-strewn
denouements of tragedies like ``Macbeth'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can learn about what not to do,'' Olivier said darkly.
``When people become too focused on one particular goal or outcome,
then tragedy is not far behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
