<HEADER>
A1300 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-EXECS-PAY-ART-     06-18 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EXECS-PAY-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO PROFITS IF THE BOSS IS OVERFED? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of worst performing companies with low paid CEOs
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20)  
 (Eds: Please note subslug for INVEST-EXECS-PENSION)  
 (af)  
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Graef Crystal has spent years opining about the excesses in
executive pay. He has taken on corporate chieftains like Sanford I.
Weill of Citigroup, Charles B. Wang of Computer Associates and
Linda Wachner of Warnaco for their fat compensation packages.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two decades as a compensation consultant with
Towers Perrin, he now edits an Internet newsletter,
Crystalreport.com, which regularly pillories chief executives that
he contends are grossly overpaid.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal, who has studied the relationship between pay and
performance, does not believe that executive pay, in and of itself,
has much influence on a company's success.
</P>
<P>
   Pay ``doesn't really motivate the CEO,'' he said, adding, ``They
are already working as hard as they can; they are already working
as smart as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he did wonder if investors could improve their returns by
avoiding companies that overpaid their chief executives. By last
summer, he had selected 60 companies whose pay packages he thought
included overly high salaries, undeserved bonuses or inordinately
large stock option grants.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped two companies from his list after they ousted their
chief executives; he then tracked the stock performance of the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal found that those 58 companies, on average, significantly
underperformed both the overall market and other companies in their
respective industries. They lost, on average, 1.5 percent for the
12 months through May 28, compared with a 12.2 percent gain for the
average of companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, regardless
of market capitalization. Roughly two-thirds of the stocks dropped
in price.
</P>
<P>
   A year, of course, is not enough time to form a definite
conclusion about the relationship between high pay and poor
performance, but Crystal thinks he may be onto something. While
paying a chief executive too much may not have a direct impact on a
company's performance, he thinks that it could signal a lack of
concern for investors on the part of corporations and their chief
executives.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Crystal said, those executives may lack the
discipline to cut costs, including other executives' salaries.
</P>
<P>
   In determining whether a chief executive was being overpaid,
Crystal looked at the size and stock market performance of the
company. He also took into account factors like profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Books Family Entertainment, for example, was chosen
because of its 1997 employment agreement with Richard E. Snyder,
its chairman and chief executive. Although the publisher's stock
had lagged behind the overall market and the company was losing
money, the new agreement about doubled Snyder's base salary, to
$950,000; awarded him a special bonus of $500,000, and offered him
the possibility of earning an additional $6.1 million if the stock
reached a certain target, Crystal said. (The stock lost 95.8
percent of its value over the 12 months ended May 28.)
</P>
<P>
   At Sequent Computer Systems, Crystal noticed the chief
executive's history of high pay and some details of his dealings
with the company. Sequent's stock had done poorly over the last
decade, and Karl C. Powell Jr., the company's chief executive, had
participated in three different repricings of stock options. He
also received $600,000 a year for leasing his corporate jet to the
company, and his daughter received a salary of $65,000 to drive a
race car in competitions that the company said helped promote
Sequent's products. (Its stock fell 21.2 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   A Sequent spokesman said Powell's daughter technically was not
paid by the company but by the racing team, which in turn is paid
by Sequent.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies made Crystal's group for different reasons. At
Conseco, Stephen Hilbert received a cash bonus of $15 million in
1997 _ in addition to stock options and restricted stock. At
Cendant, Henry Silverman owned no actual shares in his company,
although he was awarded numerous options to buy shares.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the companies defended their pay practices, saying the
chief executive is responsible for key strategic decisions that
have a long-term impact.
</P>
<P>
   There were exceptions to the overall record of losing stock
prices. Consider Amgen Inc. Although Crystal selected Amgen because
it effectively gave its chief executive, Gordon M. Binder, a raise
by awarding him roughly three times the number of stock options he
was given the year before, even after it cut his bonus, the stock
more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal cautions against relying too heavily on executive pay
when deciding to buy or sell a stock. But he does believe that
investors should take pay into account. At the very least, he said,
large investors could use this information to lobby for change, as
they do about other matters of concern to shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
