<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1303 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-G8-KOSOVO-0619-COX     06-18 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-KOSOVO-0619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S., RUSSIA AGREE ON RUSSIAN TROOP ROLE IN KOSOVO PEACEKEEPING
FORCE
 &HT;    425&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With G8-DEBT-0619; CLINTON-G8-0619; RUSSIA-G8; KOSOVO-KLA-0619.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ The United States and Russia reached an
agreement Friday to allow 3,600 Russian troops to participate in
the NATO peacekeeping operation in Kosovo, nailing down the final
elusive plank in the security framework meant to stabilize the
war-ravaged province.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton hailed the accord, saying he was ``very
pleased,'' with a deal meant to end a week-long standoff that has
sown confusion inside Kosovo and undermined trust between
Washington and Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a good day. We are achieving our objectives
now,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will work,'' he said of the agreement. ``I expect
it will be honored.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is here for the three-day summit of the leaders of the
so-called Group of Seven industrial powers. Russian President Boris
Yeltsin is scheduled to joint the G-7 leaders here on Sunday for
what's called the G-8 leaders' summit.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's agreement places Russian troops under NATO command and
required Moscow to drop its insistence that Russian troops be
assigned their own territory to control inside Kosovo, a demand
that had been the key sticking point throughout weeks of talks
among Russian and NATO officials.
</P>
<P>
   The accord was hammered out during three days of negotiations
among Defense Secretary William Cohen, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and their Russian counterparts -- Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov -- in Helsinki, Finland.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Albright were scheduled to present the agreement on
Saturday to the North Atlantic Council -- NATO's political arm --
at NATO headquarters near Brussels, Belgium. The NAC was expected
to quickly approve the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement brought to an end a torturous closing chapter in
the effort to find a formula for peacekeeping in Kosovo that would
permit a face-saving way for Russian troops to serve in an
operation commanded by Moscow's Cold War nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   NATO was formed 50 years ago as the strategic counterweight to
the military threat of the former Soviet Union. Russia remains
deeply suspicious of NATO's motives, largely resentful of its post
Cold War operations and was deeply opposed to the alliance's 78-day
bombing campaign against Yugoslavia targeting Serb repression in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In a final act of defiance, some 200 Russian troops sped into
Kosovo in the early morning hours last Saturday from peacekeeping
duties in Bosnia -- another province of the former Yugoslavia --
beating NATO peacekeepers into the troubled province, and taking up
posts at the airport near the provincial capital of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, right after the Yugoslav government had agreed to
withdraw from Kosovo and NATO had ended its bombing campaign, NATO
and Russian officials were still debating what role Russia should
play in Kosovo. The hang-up was NATO's insistence that Russian
troops operate under NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's National Security Adviser, Samuel E. ``Sandy'' Berger,
conceded Friday that the administration had yet to penetrate the
fog of uncertainty surrounding Russia's troop deployment last week.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear, for example, whether Yeltsin ordered the
deployment -- after assuring the White House that it would not go
forward -- or whether it was ordered by the Russian Defense
Ministry, or whether it was simply a potentially dangerous bit of
freelancing by unit commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a number of possibilities about who ordered what
when and who knew what when,'' Berger said. ``We have to operate as
if any of them might be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton played up the fact that the Russian presence will help
allay the concerns of Serb civilians and protect Serb religious and
cultural sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's quite important that every effort be made to
secure both the physical sites and the personal security of the
Serb minority as well as the Kosovar Albanian majority,'' Clinton
said. ``We think it will give confidence to (Serbs) that the
Russians are in more than one sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia and Serbia, which share religious and ethnic ties, are
long-standing allies.
</P>
<P>
   Under Friday's accord, about 2,850 Russian troops will not
operate their own sector -- as Moscow had sought -- but will
instead be dispersed across three separate sectors, one controlled
by U.S. forces, a second by Germans and the third by French.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops will report to their own officers, who in turn
will take orders from the commanders in control of each sector.
Those commanders, in turn, report to the ranking NATO commander in
charge of the overall operation, British Maj. Gen. Sir Michael
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at a press conference in Helsinki whether Russian troops
would command their own sector, Sergeyev conceded that Russia had
instead settled on the ``alternative solution'' insisted upon by
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found solutions to the issue,'' Sergeyev said, ``and
we are satisfied with the results of our work.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 750 Russian troops will be assigned some security
functions and other tasks -- such as vehicle maintenance, control
of parking slots, shuttle bus operation and public affairs -- at
the Pristina airport.
</P>
<P>
   The airport will remain under Jackson's control, however, with
NATO forces responsible for all flight operations, ground controls
and tower functions. The airport will be accessible to all
participants in the Kosovo peacekeeping operation, called KFOR,
under the terms of Friday's accord.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian troops, consisting of five battalions, will augment
the main KFOR force of some 50,000 NATO troops -- including 7,000
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
