<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETURNING REFUGEES ALERTED TO MINE DANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ Heading back into a homeland laced with
deadly land mines, some 10,000 Albanian Kosovar refugees flooded
across the border here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As the column of returning families in beat-up taxis, tractors,
and on foot wound its way toward the final checkpoint at the
border, UNICEF workers handed out leaflets and hung posters showing
how to identify and avoid land mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are flooding back in to Kosovo to go to their homes. We
cannot stop them, so all we can do is do our best to educate them
on the dangers of the land mines,'' said Astrid Zangenderen Stort,
a spokeswoman for the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials say that Kosovo is the most heavily mined real
estate in the world right now, although the full extent of the
danger will not be known until anti-land mine teams begin the
arduous task of locating and then removing the buried explosive
devices.
</P>
<P>
   The task could take years, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   In Kacanik, a town just inside the border, UN officials report
that 160 land mines were found and cleared in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``If 160 land mines are found in one small town, then that is a
very alarming indication of what we're going to be dealing with,''
said Zangenderen Stort.
</P>
<P>
   To date, UN officials say, seven land mines have exploded,
causing three deaths and approximately six severe injuries. As
impatient refugees ignore the UN officials' warnings and return to
their homes, many fear it is only a matter of time until more are
injured or killed.
</P>
<P>
   The land mines are scattered in fields and in wooded areas on
the outskirts of towns. There are also many reports of
booby-trapped homes with explosive devices triggered to doors and
with trip wires.
</P>
<P>
   The UN commissioner's offices in Prizren, for example, were
found booby trapped.
</P>
<P>
   UNICEF is heading up the awareness campaign and urging refugees
to wait until the land mines can at least be marked before
returning home.
</P>
<P>
   The pamphlets and posters are brightly colored cartoon
depictions of land mines and are intended to grab the attention of
children, who are often the victims of land mines because the
devices can bear a cruel resemblance to toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some shaped like jacks and some that look like a
dart. They are intriguing to children,'' said Julia Spry-Leverton,
a UNICEF official heading up the education campaign.
</P>
<P>
   She said UNICEF is also using mimes and acrobats in schools and
day care centers in the refugee camps to try to educate children
about how to identify and avoid land mines.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of experts from as far away as Laos and as close by as
Sarejevo are descending on Kosovo. They are working first with
Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas and local residents to try to
pinpoint the locations of the Serb-planted mines.
</P>
<P>
   They are also waiting for Serb forces to hand over maps of the
mine fields, which could potentially save many lives.
</P>
<P>
   The removal process is gruelling and dangerous and will take
``up to several years,'' said Spry-Leverton. Nevertheless, Kosovar
families were undeterred Friday, as thousands leaned into a driving
rain and made their way toward home in the gathering darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Humdi Nuha, 20, and 14 members of his extended family were in a
three-car convoy waiting to cross the border. He said that their
homes in the town of Ferizay were burned to the ground, but that
they wanted to go back anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to rebuild,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it is dangerous. I worry about the children. How can
you keep children from running in a field, or walking in the woods?
Everywhere there are land mines,'' he added as four younger
siblings fidgeted and giggled into the backseat of the taxi. ``But
still we have to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed Velia, 38, was returning with his two brothers and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a risk to return, but we have to be in our homes,'' he
said. ``It is risk we feel we have to take.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
