<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-OUTLOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETE SHARES TAKE A HIT ON NEGATIVE EARNINGS OUTLOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Gillette Co. shares tumbled Friday as Wall Street
reacted to an announcement by the world's largest maker of razors
and blades that profits again won't meet analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In a frenzy of trading, Gillette shares plummeted to a low of 41
1/4 before recovering somewhat to close down 11 percent at 42. It
was the single largest decline among companies in the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index Friday, and the biggest one-day drop in Gillette
shares since it issued its last profit warning in April. Friday
30.5 million Gillette shares traded hands, more than nine times its
average three-month daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder if the wheels are starting to come off the
cart here,'' said Robert Izmirlian, a Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst who
Friday downgraded his recommendation to ``avoid,'' S&AMP;P's
second-lowest rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any confidence in what they're doing anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   In its third earnings warning in the last four quarters,
Gillette said late Thursday slower-than-expected recoveries in key
international markets would mean a 20 percent decline in
second-quarter earnings from the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings per share are expected to fall to between 26 cents and
27 cents per share, the company said. Analysts had expected 29
cents, according to research firm First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   While Gillette's largest area of business _ razors and blades,
led by the popular Mach3 _ remained strong, the company said it was
surprised by weakness in Braun appliances, Papermate pens, and
toiletries.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was centered in markets outside the United States,
particularly Brazil, Germany, Japan, and Russia, where economic and
political turmoil has lingered much longer than Gillette
anticipated, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recovery is still coming,'' said Eric Kraus, a Gillette
spokesman. ``It's just that the pace is not what we had thought it
was going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The company continues to forecast improved earnings in the
second half of the year, with percentage increases in the ``high
single digits'' in the third quarter and ``the mid-teens'' in the
fourth quarter. Both are less than analysts had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Friday several analysts cut their ratings on the stock. Alice
Beebe Longley at Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities Corp.
downgraded the stock to ``market perform'' from ``buy.'' Analyst
Sally Dessloch at J.P. Morgan Securities cut Gillette to
``long-term buy'' from ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette shares have fallen about a third since they hit a
52-week high of 64 3/8 on March 23, slashing $24.8 billion from
their total value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
