<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZENGA'S RESCUE PLAN MAY BE WORKING FOR REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Conservative tactics and optimism are usually considered
mutually exclusive terms. But they are the basis of player-coach
Walter Zenga's formula for rescuing the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there are signs that Zenga's ideas are functioning. The
Revolution are more effective defensively than a year ago, and they
are at least acting like a hopeful team.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have earned 5 points from the last four games
and, significantly, they have regained some confidence. Though they
lost the shootout to Columbus Wednesday, they never trailed in the
game. And in the last four games, they have trailed for a total of
only 37 minutes. This is a significant statistic since it indicates
that the Revolution are not constantly trying to recover from a
deficit, a situation which can take a large toll psychologically.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga presented a no-frills starting lineup against the Crew,
and the Revolution's aggressiveness paid off in a fourth-minute
Giovanni Savarese goal, set up by a Ted Chronopoulos steal and
cross. There will probably be some changes in the lineup when the
Revolution visit Tampa Bay Saturday for their third game in seven
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the other players and teams fear the Revolution,''
Savarese said. ``We have beaten the best teams, D.C. United and
Chicago. And we had a good half and could have beaten Columbus,
which is a team that has had a very good start to the season and
had every advantage, playing at home in a new stadium with everyone
supporting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good group this year. I think we are on the right
track. Now it only depends on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 8 points separate the second-place Crew from the last-place
Miami Fusion and New York/New Jersey MetroStars. And, as the season
nears the halfway mark, the Revolution are poised to either take
command as a playoff contender or sink to their customary position
of scrounging to avoid the cellar.
</P>
<P>
   With 12 points in 13 games, the Revolution are slightly ahead of
last year's pace. But it was about this time last year that the
Revolution were slumping to a nine-game losing streak as former
coach Thomas Rongen, plus starters Mike Burns and Joe-Max Moore,
participated in the France '98 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are used to this kind of schedule,'' Savarese said. ``We've
had to do this before, and we have enough players to bring in in
case somebody gets tired. We don't know what the lineup will be,
but whatever decision the coaches make, we will support their
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, we will close in on Columbus, get ahead of Tampa
Bay, and put some distance between us and the lower teams.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Savarese, who has 46 goals in his MLS career, will likely miss
only two Revolution games if he joins Venezuela for the Copa
American tournament starting June 29 in Paraguay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
