<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-STONE-NYT &LR;      06-18 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-STONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWRENCE STONE, 79, HISTORIAN OF CHANGING SOCIAL ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Professor Lawrence Stone, a social historian whose broad view of
the past helped transform historical studies, died June 16 at his
home in Princeton, N.J. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was Parkinson's disease, said his wife, Jeanne.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, who taught at Princeton University for 27 years, wrote on
a wide range of topics, including the social and economic position
of the English aristocracy, the nature of the English Revolution of
1640-1660, the history of education, medieval sculpture and family
life, including marital relations and the rise of divorce over the
last five centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his work he examined profound changes in the social
order over a long time span, in contrast to a more conventional
approach restricted to the activities of the political elite. As
such, his work on England converged with a similar postwar
intellectual approach in France associated with Marc Bloch and
Lucien Febvre. It applies social science techniques to history,
using the tools of demography, economics, political science and
anthropology.
</P>
<P>
   The more usual view of history was expressed by Thomas Carlyle,
the 19th-century Scottish essayist who wrote that history ``is at
bottom the history of Great Men.'' If the traditional Carlyle
approach could be called history from the top down, the new history
was from the bottom up.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, who often found himself embroiled in polemics and
relished that fact, liked to call himself an exponent of
prosopography, or group biography. More could be learned, he
insisted, from the study of the history of the family, or of the
institution of divorce, than from even the most insightful
biography of Henry VIII or Anne Boleyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``History, as Professor Stone presented it to rapt audiences of
students and colleagues, cannot be confined to the tiny elite who
dominate events,'' said historian Robert Darnton, a Princeton
colleague. ``It involves entire populations.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone was not without critics. In 1985, Norman F. Cantor, a
history professor at New York University, wrote in the
neoconservative journal The New Criterion that Marxists, led by
Stone, were taking over the teaching of history. That charge, which
stemmed from Stone's early association with the English Christian
socialist historian R.H. Tawney, was vehemently denied in letters
to the editor by members of the Princeton history department and by
conservative scholars like Gertrude Himmelfarb and Jack Hexter.
Stone would only describe the charge as ``ridiculous.'' Cantor
repeated his accusation in Commentary and asserted that Princeton's
history department was in the clutches of ``the leftists.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Stone's scholarly books are ``The Crisis of the
Aristocracy, 1558-1641'' (1965), ``The Causes of the English
Revolution, 1529-1642'' (1972), ``The Family, Sex and Marriage in
England, 1500-1800'' (1977), and ``Broken Lives: Marital Separation
and Divorce in England, 1660-1857'' (1993).
</P>
<P>
   Born in Epsom, Surrey, in England, on Dec. 4, 1919, Lawrence
Stone studied at the Charterhouse School, the Sorbonne and Christ
Church, Oxford. His university studies were interrupted by war
service as a lieutenant in the Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   He received his B.A. and M.A. degrees from Oxford in 1946 and
remained there until 1962, first as a lecturer at University and
Corpus Christi colleges and then as a fellow of Wadham College.
</P>
<P>
   After two years at the Institute for Advanced Study in
Princeton, he joined the Princeton University faculty in 1963. He
served as chairman of the history department from 1967 to 1970 and
in 1968 became the founding director of the Davis Center for
Historical Studies, which was established to promote innovative
methods of historical research. He retired in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Stone is survived by two children,
Elizabeth Cecilia Stone Zimansky of Stony Brook, N.Y., and Robert
Lawrence Fawtier Stone of Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
