<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-RUSSIA (Cologne, Germany) _ The United States and Russia
agree to award Russian troops a prominent role in peacekeeping
operations in Kosovo one week after Russian troops defied NATO and
seized the largest airfield in the bloodied Yugoslav province. The
agreement clears the way for a meeting Sunday between President
Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin. By STEWART M. POWELL.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SUMMIT-KOSOVO (Cologne, Germany) _ The summit of the seven
leading economic powers, plus Russia, begins with Kosovo and its
reconstruction dominating the proceedings. The leaders also reach
agreement at their first session on a plan to provide up to $100
billion in debt relief to the world's poorest countries and endorse
changes to the global financial system aimed at lowering the threat
of future Asian-style currency crises. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUNS (Cologne, Germany) _ President Clinton fires a
warning shot across the Atlantic, diverting attention from an
international economic summit to say that he will ratchet up the
fight for gun control in the aftermath of the House defeat of a gun
measure. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Washington) _ In a 280-147 vote, the House kills a
gun-control bill, raising the possibility that lawmakers may not be
able to produce legislation in the wake of the Colorado school
shooting. By GREG McDONALD. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-STUDY (Washington) _ Adolescents are more likely than
adults to become addicted to gambling, says a new federally study.
The National Gambling Impact Study Commission estimates that about
85 percent of youngsters 12 to 18 have gambled at least once in
their lives. The commission recommends raising the minimum gambling
age to 21 and banning Internet gambling. By JENNIFER CORBETT
DOOREN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-AMBASSADOR (Washington) _ Luxembourg's ambassador to the
United States, Arlette Conzemius, will host a dinner at her
country's embassy here to welcome gay rights advocate James C.
Hormel to his new post as U.S. envoy to Luxembourg. Hormel, who
will be sworn on June 29, will become America's first openly gay
ambassador. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SEAWEED-TEXAS (Galveston, Texas) _ The crowds of beachgoers
flocking to the Texas coast are encountering another feature along
with sand, surf and sun. Seaweed. For reasons that even the experts
haven't determined, an unusually large influx of the brown, stringy
algae has inundated many of the state's coastal areas in recent
weeks. By KEVIN MORAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BULLOCK-OBIT (Austin, Texas) _ Former Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, who
became a dominant figure in modern Texas politics during four
decades of public service, dies at his home in Austin at the age of
69. By CLAY ROBISON and R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HEARST-COSMOPOLITAN (New York) _ Hearst Magazines, publisher of
37 international editions of Cosmopolitan, the world's best-selling
title for young women, announces that the company will introduce a
new teen title under the Cosmopolitan name. The magazine, titled
CosmoGIRL!, and its related Web site (www.cosmogirl.com), are
designed for girls 12 to 17 and will debut on June 29. By The
Hearst Newspapers. (Already filed.)
</P>
