<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIQUOR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alabama may OK more Sunday sales of alcohol
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Alabama state legislators once were clearly
distinguished as wet or dry, depending on their views on alcohol.
Trying to forbid the sales of beer, wine and spirits any day _ not
just Sunday _ formed a heady, Baptist voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been a long time ago, though,'' said Joe Bob Mizzell,
director of church ethics for the Alabama State Baptist Convention.
``That's about 30 years ago that we could speak out against alcohol
and it did make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, nearly two-thirds of Alabama's 67 counties permit alcohol
sales. In Birmingham and Mobile, you can even go to the local
grocery store and buy a six-pack on Sunday  &Cx1f;  &Cx1f;  &Cx1f;  &Cx1f;  &Cx1f;  &Cx1f; _ something you
can't do in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Don Siegelman is reviewing a bill that would allow Sunday
sales in wet counties without a local vote. He has till midnight to
sign, veto or walk away, which would also kill the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his decision, it appears that alcohol in Alabama has
dried up as a watermark political issue, especially among Christian
activists.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Ireland, an interdenominational Christian lobbyist who spoke
with the governor Friday, said the Sunday alcohol bill is a
critical test for his constituency. Religious activists already are
battling Siegelman over a proposed state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that we would be totally annihilated'' if Siegelman
approved Sunday sales, Ireland said. ``But it is reflective ... on
our ability to get something done.'' Broader Sunday alcohol sales
have been pushed by Marc Reynolds, the legislative liaison for the
Retirement Systems of Alabama, a $23 billion agency that
distributes pensions for state teachers and judges, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement agency owns the Robert Trent Jones golf trail, a
collection of courses throughout Alabama. Reynolds said resorts in
South Carolina and Arizona use Alabama's limited Sunday alcohol in
their marketing.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Reynolds has lobbied the Legislature for a permit to
allow golf courses to sell alcohol on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A small, vocal group always stymies us,'' he said. ``They're
the same group that's anti-gambling, anti-abortion, anti-alcohol.
Anything they perceive as a sin, they jump on the state government
to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Siegelman has been less receptive to those pleas than his
predecessor, Republican Fob James, who made a name for himself as a
crusader for social conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure any organized religion has any influence with
Siegelman,'' said Mizzell. In northeast Alabama, where Sand
Mountain stands as the dominant feature, DeKalb County stands rock
solid against any liquor sales. ``It's the Bible Belt,'' said Wade
Gorham, manager of Gary's TV &AMP; Appliance in Fort Payne, where he
sells Simmons mattresses alongside RCA televisions. ``A majority of
people have strong beliefs and moral values. ... People want it dry
for their kids, for their family, to keep it a nice place.'' Rural
outposts may regard Sunday alcohol sales as another step lost to
immorality, said Wayne Flynt, an Auburn University history
professor, but it's hardly the shock it would have been in the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like people don't leave DeKalb County and go to
Nashville, where they have Sunday liquor sales, or go to Atlanta,
where they have Sunday liquor sales,'' Flynt said. ``Forty years
ago, it was rare to see anyone from Sand Mountain go to Atlanta.
But it's not that kind of assault on their culture today.''
</P>
<P>
   Tradition has kept DeKalb dry. The force of time will change
that, said Jim McGee, appointed Fort Payne city clerk in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of these days,'' McGee said, ``it will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
