<P>
   SOCCER
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WOMENSCUP _ The third Women's World Cup comes to America
starting today and with it some lofty expectations of elevating the
game worldwide. More than 450,000 tickets have been sold, including
an expected sellout at Giants Stadium for today's opener between
the U.S. and Denmark. More than $6 million in corporate
sponsorships has rolled in, and ABC/ESPN/ESPN2 will televise every
match. (Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   w/SOC-MIAHAMM _ BERNARDS TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ Ask Mia Hamm about
soccer, her friends on the U.S. national team and the Women's World
Cup, and you'll discover a straightforward young woman who says all
the right things and presents herself in stark contrast to the
crude profile of the American sports superstar these days. Ask her
about herself, and the phenomenon that has sprung up around her as
the glamour girl for her sport, and her face quickly flushes red
with embarrassment.(Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
WITH POSTER.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-MIA-HAMM _ Mia Hamm is often identified with North Carolina,
the school where both she and her I-can-do-anything-better-than-you
commercial co-star, Michael Jordan, won national championships. Yet
it was in Texas that Hamm, international soccer's all-time leading
scorer, first learned that sport and many others, including tackle
football. ``All our children have Texas roots,'' said Stephanie
Hamm, Mia's mother. Stephanie and Bill Hamm, a retired Air Force
colonel, settled in Austin three years ago and lived in Wichita
Falls and San Antonio when Mia was growing up. (Maher, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SOC-MICHELLE-AKERS _ Although Mia Hamm has become a glamorous
icon for women's soccer in general, and the U.S. team in
particular, 33-year-old Michelle Akers is considered its heart and
soul. The star of the first World Cup in 1991, Akers is nearing the
end of a lengthy career in which she has scored 102 goals, gone
through a turbulent marriage and divorce, suffered from chronic
fatigue syndrome and learned to play a new position. The Grand Old
Lady of women's soccer is still a vital part of a team trying to
get back the World Cup that eluded it in 1995. (Parker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-CUP-CAPSULES _ A rail providing a group-by-group capsule
look at the Women's World Cup, with short takes on each of the four
qualifying groups, the favorites, players to watch, schedule, etc.
(Parker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 60.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS-KNICKS _ SAN ANTONIO _ Coverage, Game 2 of the NBA
Finals between the Spurs and Knicks. Spurs lead series 1-0. (Bunn,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 14.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SPURS _ SAN ANTONIO _ Game 2: Coverage of the San Antonio
Spurs playing host to the New York Knicks. (Rosner, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   w/BKN-FINALS-WAGERS _ U.S. Sen. Phil Gramm fired the first salvo
from his Washington office.''Eat our dust, city boy,'' he said to
his New York counterpart, Sen. Charles Schumer. ``And hey, what the
heck is a Knick anyhow?'' Schumer, fired back as quickly as a Texas
outlaw: ``Ask Larry Bird what a Knick is, senator. I'm sure they
have a clear idea.'' (Davenport, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (s) Sports.
