<SLUG> BC-HERITAGEHIGH19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    County home to Heritage High OKs adding 3 school psychologists
 &HT;    By Leon Stafford
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Rockdale County schools plan to hire three more
psychologists, doubling the current staff, as part of its response
to the Heritage High School shootings.
</P>
<P>
   That would give Rockdale one psychologist for every 1,650
students. The national average is one for every 1,800 students, and
Georgia schools average one for every 2,200.
</P>
<P>
   Actually hiring the psychologists may not be easy. Alex Thomas,
president of the National Association of School Psychologists, said
they are in such high demand that the nation's colleges can't
graduate them fast enough for the market. About 1,900 school
psychologists graduate yearly.
</P>
<P>
   And the need for more school psychologists didn't start with the
recent spate of high school shootings, he said. It has been growing
for years because of the increased number of American children who
come to school unable to cope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shootings highlighted the increased mental health problems
in youth,'' said Thomas, chairman of the educational psychology
department at Miami University of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come to school with so much more baggage,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Rockdale's board approved the hiring Thursday night at the
recommendation of a committee studying ways to make the district's
schools safer. Anthony ``T.J.'' Solomon, a 15-year-old sophomore at
Heritage, is accused of shooting six of his classmates May 20 as
they waited for school to begin in the commons area.
</P>
<P>
   Rockdale's three psychologists have evaluated about 250 students
a year. Because of the workload, they were unable to do additional
counseling, said counselor John Poidevant.
</P>
<P>
   The district may have to dip into its reserves to hire the last
psychologist because only two extra positions were funded in the
$77 million budget for the 1999-2000 school year, approved
Thursday. But board member Jim Borland said the position is too
important to let it slip through the financial cracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers were elated to find out that we were doing this,''
said Borland, who also heads the School Safety Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Allbritten, executive director of the Georgia Association
of Educators, commended Rockdale for ``being proactive.'' But he
said another solution would be to make sure that counselors _ who
traditionally deal with students whose problems are not severe _
are not burdened with paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you don't want to have is counselors being attendance
officers and psychologists being counselors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
