<HEADER>
A1332 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTERY-GEORGIA19-COX     06-18 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTERY-GEORGIA19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia leaders: Gambling study rigged
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia leaders were highly critical of a federal
gambling study released Friday that recommends limiting advertising
by lotteries and setting a nationwide minimum age of 21 for all
legal betting.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Frank Wolf (R-Va.), author of legislation creating the
study commission, said he plans to introduce a bill to impose a 1
percent tax on legal gambling proceeds to treat addicted gamblers
and their families. He said he may include other recommendations
from the report in his legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Lottery contributes $200,000 a year _ or about .01
percent of its anticipated annual revenues _ to a state agency to
be used for gambling addiction programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine (the commission's report) will cause Georgia
to change its course,'' Lt. Gov. Mark Taylor said Friday. He said
he hoped federal lawmakers would not interfere with the states'
regulatory authority over gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by the National Gambling Impact Study Commission,
estimates that America has 5.4 million pathological gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   It urged prohibiting or phasing out video gambling and
keno-style games, such as the Georgia Lottery's Quick Cash game.
The report was particularly harsh on video poker machines in South
Carolina, which it called ``the crack cocaine'' of gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Video gambling and casinos aren't allowed in Georgia. But the
state expects to collect about $2 billion this fiscal year from its
6-year-old lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery is required by law to pay about 35 percent of its
proceeds to the state for education programs, including HOPE
college scholarships for students with 'B' averages,
pre-kindergarten classes for 4-year-olds and school technology and
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who had not had time to read the report, said he
understood the nine-member commission was dominated by casino
interests and religious conservatives who oppose gambling. He said
he had expected the report to be critical of lotteries, which were
not represented on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Lottery President Rebecca Paul also claimed the report
was biased. ``There's virtually no balance in terms of the lottery
side of the report,'' she said. ``Everything it recommended is
stuff we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertising guidelines, we have. A citizens' advisory board,
we do. Background checks on employees, vendors, retailers, we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul said a recent Gallup poll showed 75 percent of Americans
favor state lotteries. ``If Congress looks at how people feel, the
report will have little if any impact on how lotteries actually
operate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another national group, the Public Sector Gaming Study
Commission, will provide a more balanced view of the impact state
lotteries have on their states, Paul said. She and Gov. Roy Barnes
are among the 11 members of the group, which expects to release its
report in January.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Paul helped obtain $250,000 in state funding for a
national study by the University of Georgia's Vinson Institute on
the economic benefits of the nation's 38 state lotteries. Hank
Huckaby, the institute's director, was the state budget director
for Gov. Zell Miller, who made the lottery the cornerstone of his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
