A1334 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-GUN-CONTROL-BOS     06-18 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-GUN-CONTROL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL VOTE DOOMS LATEST GUN CONTROL EFFORT IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A passionate, three-day House debate over guns and
juvenile crime came to a jarring end Friday when the most ardent
advocates of gun control voted against a bill they said had been
watered down too much by amendments backed by the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The 280-147 defeat of the bill, coming nearly two months after
the high school shootings in Littleton, Colo., and an intensive
lobbying campaign by pro- and anti-gun lobbies, cast doubt on
whether Congress will agree on any measures to strengthen gun laws
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic turn of events led to rounds of political
finger-pointing in Capitol Hill hallways and press conferences.
Republican leaders said Democrats, who initially pushed hard for
new gun-control measures, were playing politics and defeated the
bill to make guns an issue in their 2000 campaign to win back the
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provided two-thirds of our (members) for the bill,'' said
Republican Whip Thomas DeLay of Texas. The Democrats who voted
against it, he said, ``chose politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrat leaders claimed that Republicans voted for so many
loopholes to the legislation that its impact would be to weaken,
not strengthen, existing laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leave it to the Republicans to tarnish the memories of those
children (in Littleton) by creating a bill with scores of
loopholes,'' said Representative John Conyers, a Michigan Democrat
and ranking member of the Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was defeated by a vote of 280-147, with 197 of 207
Democrats opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in Cologne, Germany, responded angrily to the
earlier passage of the amendments that weakened the bill, saying
the vote was ``a great victory for the NRA, but it was a great
defeat for the safety of our children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people will not stand for this,'' the president
said in a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it was the House's most senior Democrat _ John Dingell
of Michigan, a former board member of the NRA _ who introduced what
many of his fellow Democrats considered the ``killer'' amendment
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell proposed limiting the period for law-enforcement
background checks on buyers at gun shows to 24 hours, down from the
three days proposed in both the original House bill and the
legislation passed by the Senate last month. With the support of 45
Democrats, the Dingell amendment passed, and a substitute measure,
allowing for a three-day check, failed.
</P>
<P>
   The substitute was offered by Representative Carolyn McCarthy, a
New York Democrat whose husband was killed and son severely injured
by a gunman on a Long Island train. The defeat of the McCarthy
proposal, which occurred at 1:20 a.m. Friday, led many Democrats to
say they would oppose the overriding bill.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Democrats who voted against the gun-control bill
Friday was Dingell himself, who cited ``amorphous reasons'' for his
objections to the legislation. Dingell declined to elaborate as he
headed into a House elevator as reporters pressed him for an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   All lawmakers from Massachusetts, Vermont, Maine, Connecticut,
and Rhode Island opposed the final bill. New Hampshire's two
representatives, both Republicans, voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   The action by the House stands in contrast to the Senate, which
last month passed a three-day waiting period after Vice President
Al Gore cast a tie-breaking vote, reversing an earlier Senate vote
for a shorter background check.
</P>
<P>
   The House's defeat of the gun-control bill does not affect
companion juvenile justice legislation passed late Thursday by the
House. That bill expands the power of prosecutors to try young
offenders as adults and mandates some ``cultural'' remedies for the
outbreak of juvenile violence, including a provision that allows
states to let schools post the Ten Commandments in classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   But the defeat of the House gun-control bill is likely to be
problematic when a House-Senate conference committee tackles the
differences in the chambers' juvenile justice bills. The Senate
version contains a variety of gun-control measures, including child
safety locks and the three-day waiting period for gun show
purchases, while the House version does not.
</P>
<P>
   Some House members said Friday that it was possible for the
conference committee to take the unusual step of fashioning a final
bill incorporating all of the Senate's gun control measures. But
many agreed with Representative Constance A. Morella, a Maryland
Republican, who said that scenario was ``possible, but not
likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats promised to wage a public effort and prompt a public
outcry to put pressure on the conference committee to include the
gun measures. They noted that the Senate last month initially
rejected a three-day waiting period for gun show purchases but then
reversed itself after many constituents flooded the Capitol with
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Following Friday's vote, there was much speculation about
whether Republicans had strategized to kill the gun-control bill
and blame the defeat on Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, Democrat of Massachusetts, said he
and many other Democrats opposed the bill because it was ``silly,
fradulent, and allowed the Republicans to say they did something
when they didn't.'' He called the Republicans ``the gang that can't
shoot straight, even the help of the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said it made no sense for Democrats, who are in
the minority, to insist on passage of their own version of the
bill. Representative Bob Barr, the Georgia Republican, rejected
suggestions that the defeat would hurt the GOP in next year's
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If each member correctly read their constituency, none of them
should be hurt by it,'' said Barr, who voted for the gun-control
bill even though he said he disliked parts of it.
</P>
<P>
   When the gun-control bill died, so did amendments that would
have required child safety locks on guns and overturned a local
ordinance that forbids most residents in the District of Columbia
from possessing handguns in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Representative Virgil H. Goode Jr., Democrat of
Virginia, proposed an amendment that would have gone farther,
allowing District residents to carry a concealed weapon. Goode
argued that the city's gun ban was unconstitutional, prompting an
angry response from the city's non-voting delegate, Eleanor Holmes
Norton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gentleman has some nerve. Most of the guns that are
killing people in the District of Columbia come from the state of
the gentleman from Virginia,'' Norton said. ``They come from his
state. Get off my back. Get out of my business.'' The Goode
amendment was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Before the final vote, Representative Tom G. Tancredo, a
Colorado Republican whose district includes Columbine High School,
pleaded for bipartisan support of the one-day waiting period for
gun show purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I would be standing before this body and
asking them to vote for a bill that contains any type of gun
control,'' Tancredo said. But he said the shootings in Littleton
had changed that. ``Nobody will be the same after April 20, 1999,''
said Tancredo, who voted against the Democratic proposal for a
three-day background check.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
