<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1336 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-DEBATE-BOS &LR;      06-18 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONAL DEBATE FILLED WITH ANGER, FRUSTRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House chamber was, for once, silent. Even as
the clock ticked well past midnight, Congress paused its grinding
debate over gun control early Friday morning to watch a woman cry
at the podium.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Carolyn McCarthy had told her story before: of
the gunman who killed her husband and severely wounded her son
during a shooting spree on the Long Island Railroad. But in the
midst of a vitriolic debate _ as Congress grappled with core
beliefs ranging from individual freedom to prayer _ McCarthy's
two-minute speech became a symbol of how personal the entire debate
was, and why, for the first time since the impeachment of President
Clinton, everyone was so upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Irish, and I am not supposed to cry in front of anyone,''
McCarthy, a Democrat from Long Island, N.Y., said quietly, wiping
both eyes. ``But I made a promise a long time ago. I made a promise
to my son and to my husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was anything that I could do to prevent one family
from going through what I have gone through and every other victim
that I know have gone through, then I have done my job. Let me go
home. Let me go home.''
</P>
<P>
   When McCarthy was finished, the House erupted in applause. The
debate then moved on, and her proposal for tougher restictions on
sales at gun shows was voted down. The debate continued into Friday
afternoon, when a vote killed the overall measure at hand _ a gun
bill viewed as too weak by strict gun-control advocates such as
McCarthy, and too invasive by ardent gun-rights advocates.
Throughout, there were moments of grief, anger, frustration. And,
at times, disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months after the shooting at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., in which 15 people died, it appeared to many that
the gun-control issue was as politicized as ever.
</P>
<P>
   To Democrats, the powerful National Rifle Association still
seemed to be calling the shots, lobbying congressmen hard to weaken
even existing gun restrictions. To Republicans, it was the
Democrats who were playing politics _ trying to kill the bill in
order to paint the Republicans as soft on crime just in time for
next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess what, guys? We get to do this late into the night a few
more times,'' Representative F. James Sensenbrenner, Republican
from Wisconsin, sarcastically announced after casting his vote in
favor of the bill but glimpsing at the electronic scoreboard long
enough to see it was going to fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you're knocking your head against a wall,'' said
Representative Sheila Jackson Lee, a Texas Democrat, after voting
against it and leaving the chamber in obvious exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was tired. The debate on the floor had dragged on each
night until after midnight, keeping some members at work as late as
4 a.m. Friday morning. And it was only the latest in a string of
exhausting struggles over legislation in the 106th Congress, where
even routine appropriations bills have taken weeks to negotiate,
and where large pockets of both parties are pessimistic they will
get anything done.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois was noticeably absent,
refusing to call on members to vote a particular way and calling it
it was a vote of conscience. But other familiar faces resurfaced _
especially members of the House Judiciary Committee, the panel that
voted to impeach Clinton and produced the team of House managers
that led Clinton's prosecution in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't I prove to you folks over in the Senate that it takes a
lot to scare me?'' said Representative James Rogan, a Republican
from California.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the divisions were not drawn strictly along
partisan lines. Instead, it was longstanding passions on both sides
of the gun-control debate _ the sort of lifelong opinions that led
Democrat John Dingell of Michigan to lead the charge against the
Clinton administration. It was Dingell who offered an amendment
that opponents said would have weakened existing restrictions by
reducing the time allowed for background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   His amendment in turn fueled the rage of gun-control advocates,
even sparking a moment of rowdiness in the chamber Thursday night
as Democrats burst into a chant, reportedly at the urging of Rhode
Island Democratic Representative Patrick Kennedy. As the votes were
being counted, they shouted in unison: ``Six more seats! Six more
seats!'' _ an apparent reference to the six seats that now separate
Democrats from being the majority party.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was McCarthy's speech that clearly touched members the
most.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke for a little over two minutes, giving a speech
Minority Leader Richard Gephardt later described as the ``most
incredible speech I've ever seen on the House floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You could hear a pin drop. Every member was listening to every
word she said,'' said Gephardt, a Democrat from Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   And yet she had prepared none of it. She walked to the podium
with tears in her eyes and notecards in her hand. Then she tossed
the notes aside on order to speak, a spokeswoman said, ``from the
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying to stop criminals from being able to get guns.
That is all I am trying to do. This is not a game to me. This is
not a game to the American people,'' McCarthy said. ``If we do not
do it, shame on us, because I have to tell my colleagues, the
American people will not forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve hours later, it was still unclear what would happen.
House Majority Leader Dick Armey shrugged when asked whether the
bill would pass just minutes before the vote. Members streamed into
the chamber to cast their vote, then stood staring at the
scoreboard, some with their jaws partly open as the bill
overwhelmingly failed. No one, it seemed, expected both parties to
be split _ a sign, some said, that members had voted how they
really felt.
</P>
<P>
   Outside in the speaker's lobby, Representative Barney Frank had
a different take. He assessed the recent history of bitter battles
in the House. This, he said, wasn't quite like impeachment, though
it was becoming a familiar act.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the difference between `King Lear' and `A Night at the
Opera,' '' said Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat. ``We've gone from
high drama to very low burlesque.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
