<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1338 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-REPORT-BOS &LR;      06-18 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-REPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL PANEL URGES CURBS ON LEGALIZED GAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Citing the financial and emotional toll that
gambling takes on millions of Americans, a federal commission
Friday urged state and local government to curb the explosive
growth of legalized gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the nine-member National Gambling Impact Study
Commission contained 76 recommendations that urge lawmakers to
examine the good as well as the detrimental effects of gambling on
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   While enactment of the recommendations is doubtful, the report
presents a vivid picture of the growth in gambling and number of
problem gamblers. Commission members hope that at the very least,
the report will stir awareness and debate on the issue, while
gambling opponents will use the findings to buttress their push for
legal restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The report ``will act like the surgeon general's 1964 report on
smoking and health,'' said Tom Grey, executive director of the
National Coalition Against Legalized Gambling, ``a wake up call for
America on the dangers of gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission chairwoman Kay James, a gambling opponent, said at a
press conference that although legalized gambling had created
thousands of jobs, she was ``deeply disturbed by the impact of
gambling on individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Another commissioner, James Dobson, criticized gambling for
luring poor people into betting. ``It offers wealth without work,
success without sweat, and prosperity without perseverance,'' said
Dobson, who is also president of Focus on the Family, an
organization that says
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the National Opinion Research Center reported
that 2.5 million Americans are ``pathological'' gamblers; another 3
million are ``problem'' gamblers; and 15 million are ``at risk'' of
developing a gambling problem.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's report, submitted to the White House, Congress,
state and tribal leaders Friday, struck harder on ``convenience
gambling'' such as state lotteries and slot machines than on
casinos, by recommending a nationwide minimum age of 21 to place
bets. In states like Massachussetts, New Hampshire and Connecticut,
the minimum age is 18.
</P>
<P>
   Recommendations also include reducing state lottery
advertisements, banning bets on collegiate sports, prohibiting
gambling industries from contributing to political campaigns, and
removing automated teller machines from casino floors.
</P>
<P>
   The report also recommended that casinos post visible signs that
warn gamblers of the downsides of gambling and that a portion of
profits go to treatment programs for compulsive gamblers. In a
controversial move, the report also recommended a moratorium on
further expansion of legalized gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Morgaga, spokeswoman from the National Indian Gaming
Association, said the group agrees with ``80 percent'' of the
report's recommendations, but added that any pause in gaming
activities could be ``detrimental to the Indian community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Economically, the Indian community is still playing catch-up
and gambling has been good for economic development,'' Moraga said.
</P>
<P>
   Legalized gambling has enjoyed a surge in popularity in the last
two decades. Thirty-seven states and the District of Columbia
succesfully run state lotteries and casinos operate in 10 states.
Native American tribes have also opened casinos in at least 22
states.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that revenues from legal wagering grew 1,600
percent from 1976 to 1997, with Americans spending more than $47
billion of their leisure activity money on gamgling.
</P>
<P>
   That popularity could make it difficult for the commission to
convince the public of the need for restrictions. A recent Gallup
poll showed nearly two-thirds of American adults approve of legal
gambling. Seventy-five percent said they approve of state
lotteries, and 67 percent acknowledged that opening a casino can
help a community's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Fahrenkopf, president of the American Gaming Association,
criticized the report's recommendation that barred the gambling
industry from contributing to political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of people work for this industry,'' Fahrenkopf said.
``To say they cannot contribute to campaigns is disenfranchising
all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine-member commission, appointed in 1996 by President
Clinton, former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, and Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, held 250 hours of hearings throughout the
country and conducted studies to compile the report. The panel
included both gambling foes and industry supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Wolf, a Virginia Republican and a gambling opponent
who sponsored the legislation creating the commission, said he
plans to introduce bills to enact some of the recommendations. Wolf
also said he may go further than the report and propose a federal
tax on gambling revenues and elimination of a tax deduction for
gambling losses.
</P>
</TEXT>
