<HEADER>
A1344 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TARZAN-OTHERANIMATION     06-18 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TARZAN-OTHERANIMATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(EDS: DISNEY-TARZAN) 
COMING CARTOON ATTRACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It hasn't been much of a year for animation thus far: Warner
Bros.' ``King and I'' earned a much-deserved early dethronement,
and Disney's ``Doug's 1st Movie'' will, we hope, also be Doug's
``last'' movie. But ``Tarzan'' aside, there are plenty of animated
projects coming to theaters this year:
</P>
<P>
   ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' Paramount is banking big
on Trey Parker and Matt Stone's construction paper-cutout hit from
the Comedy Central cable network. Though considered ``animation''
only in the crudest sense (and we mean ``crude'' in a number of
ways), ``South Park'' follows the adventures of a band of
foul-mouthed grade-schoolers. Opens June 30.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iron Giant'' Warner hopes to the wash out the bad taste
that ``The King and I'' left in the mouths of cartoon aficionados
with this impressive-looking feature. Set in the '50s, the story
follows a young boy who befriends a giant machine that crashes to
Earth. Voices include Jennifer Aniston, Harry Connick Jr., John
Mahoney and Cloris Leachman. Opens Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Princess Mononoke'' Miramax tries to cash in on America's
fascination with Japanese animation with this groundbreaking anime
title from writer/director Hayao Miyazaki. It's the story of an
epic battle between nature and encroaching civilization. Voices
include Gillian Anderson, Billy Crudup, Claire Danes, Minnie Driver
and Billy Bob Thornton. Opens in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Toy Story 2'' Pixar wasn't content with following its smash
hit ``Toy Story'' with a slapped-together sequel for
direct-to-video, so here's a second one. This time, Woody gets
snatched up by a wicked toy collector; Buzz Lightyear and the other
playthings must rescue him. Voices include Tom Hanks, Tim Allen,
Joan Cusack, Kelsey Grammer and Wayne Knight. Opens in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantasia 2000'' Disney updates its 1940 classic in time for a
millennial sneak preview in December at Carnegie Hall. Three
original segments return, along with new sequences that include
Camille Saint-Saens' ``Carnival of the Animals,'' Ottorino
Respighi's ``Pines of Rome'' and Donald Duck's spin on the story of
Noah's Ark set to Sir Edward Elgar's ``Pomp and Circumstance.''
Beginning Jan. 1, 2000, the film plays IMAX theaters around the
country. The Fort Worth Museum of Science and History's Omni
Theater is still in the discussion phase.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   _Todd Camp
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
