<HEADER>
A1346 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-TARZAN-TEX     06-18 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-TARZAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY MAGIC GIVES `TARZAN' TALE VISUAL THRILL OF A ROLLER-COASTER
RIDE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by TARZAN-OTHER ANIMATION) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ ``He could spring 20 feet across space at the dizzying
heights of the forest top and grasp with unerring precision and
without apparent jar a limb waving wildly in the path of an
approaching tornado ... he could drop 20 feet at a stretch from
limb to limb in a rapid descent to the ground or he could gain the
utmost pinnacle of the loftiest tropical giant with the ease and
swiftness of a squirrel.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Edgar Rice Burroughs in ``Tarzan of the Apes''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Burroughs wrote those words in 1912. But after 47 film
adaptations _ making the ``Tarzan'' films second in number only to
``Dracula'' _ Hollywood has yet to accurately capture the ape-man.
Enter Disney, which opened its big summer animated feature
``Tarzan'' on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that you could understand that it's really the
marriage of `Tarzan of the Apes' and Disney,'' co-director Kevin
Lima said during a recent promotional sweep through Texas. ``It's
not just Edgar Rice Burroughs' novel. I can't even guess how a
purist will respond. I assume that there will be some who are very
angry, and some who are overjoyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering what Burroughs fans have had so far, you'd think
they'd be delighted. Johnny Weissmuller and the other loinclothed
lads who've swung through the trees may have done their best, but
come on. Gelled hair and a gleaming smile are hardly byproducts of
an adolescence spent with apes.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's vine king (given voice by actor Tony Goldwyn) is a more
simian, agile sort, with flapping dreadlocks, bulging, muscular
forearms and distinctive gorillalike mannerisms. He looks like a
monkey, man, and also (we hate to admit) a little like Miles
O'Keeffe in the 1981 Bo Derek picture ``Tarzan, the Ape Man.'' But
there's no doubt that the character lends itself to the freedom of
animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can really mess around with his anatomy,'' Lima says. ``We
can give him a furrowed brow, strong jaw muscles. We can mess
around with his forearms, make them larger, just to make him
emulate, somewhat, gorilla anatomy. It would be really hard for an
actor to just work out those parts of his body.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-director Chris Buck was interested in the story for another
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I related more to the journey of the apes, someone living with
apes,'' Buck says. ``Jane Goodall and Dian Fossey and their
journeys _ I'd watched all those National Geographic specials.''
</P>
<P>
   Buck says he wanted to relate to the story emotionally rather
than just to play up the adventure, so he and Lima strayed from the
studio's traditional cartoon musical path, recruiting Phil Collins
to record five new songs that act more as background pieces
throughout the film than as musical numbers. But despite the
presence of comic voices like Rosie O'Donnell as Tarzan's ape
buddy, Terk; Minnie Driver as Jane; Nigel Hawthorne as Professor
Porter; and Wayne Knight as Tantor the elephant, don't be surprised
if this ``Tarzan'' is darker and more intense than the average
offerings from the House of Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty early on, we knew that we wanted to portray the savage
world of the story, because we wanted Tarzan to overcome something,
to show he could survive in this world that wants to kill him, so
to speak,'' Lima says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   IN THE JUNGLE, THE MIGHTY JUNGLE
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that everything should be made to look as natural as
possible. ... I see no reason why the animation should not be
excellent. The cartoon must be good. It must approximate Disney
excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Edgar Rice Burroughs, writing to his son in 1936 after being
approached about doing an animated version of ``Tarzan''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Talk about pressure. Buck and Lima say they were grateful not to
have known of Burroughs' letter until after the production was
completed. But they also believe that their picture lives up to its
creator's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't going for a realistic look, we were going for a
naturalistic look,'' says Buck, who along with Lima and a small
team of animators visited Africa to capture the film's distinct
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, animation is on an open plain,'' Buck says. ``You
create a flat surface or a stage for the characters to work on
because it's really difficult to have them interact with their
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided early on that we were going to try and do this.
Let's put the animals and Tarzan knee-deep in the world,'' Lima
says. ``It led in a way to Deep Canvas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep Canvas'' is the name given to the technique the studio
pioneered to allow Tarzan to interact more fully with his jungle
world. The technique sets ``Tarzan'' apart from the studio's other
African-based animated films _ ``The Lion King,'' which was set on
the open plains of the Serengeti, and ``The Jungle Book,'' which
``takes place very much in that theatrical stage world,'' Lima
says.
</P>
<P>
   For each scene, they would build a computer set, ``in a sense,
our jungle gym for that moment,'' Lima says. They would do a
computerized camera move through the set following a stand-in for
the character. Once the speed of the scene was determined, the
animator goes to work in 2-D while the background painter actually
paints three-dimensionally in the computer.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is stunning. Some of Tarzan's breakneck treks through
the trees rival even the best amusement park stomach-churners. Glen
Keane, Tarzan's supervising animator, patterned the character's
movement through the trees after his skateboarding son, while
Tarzan's rescue of Jane from a horde of angry baboons was designed
to feel like a roller-coaster ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go up in the trees, and before they start going down
there's that little pause,'' Buck says. ``Then ... down they go
with the big chase sequence.''
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. You
can call him at (817) 390-7691, or e-mail:
tcamp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
