<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAGAN-PROTEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP PLANS FATHER'S DAY PROTEST OF DAUGHTER KIDNAPPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As many as 200 demonstrators are expected outside Stephen
Fagan's mansion in Palm Beach Sunday _ Father's Day _ to protest
what they consider lenient treatment by the Massachusetts judicial
system.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Mulky, who organized the demonstration, said parents of
children who have been abducted by spouses and strangers will fill
the oceanside street to tell their stories and assail Fagan's
sentence for kidnapping his two small daughters from Massachusetts
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan agreed to plead guilty to the felony last month in
exchange for five years' probation, 2,000 hours of community
service, and a $100,000 donation to the New England Home for Little
Wanderers.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan has said he fled with the girls to Florida to rescue them
from an alcoholic, neglectful mother. The daughters _ 5 and 2 at
the time of the kidnapping _ were told by Fagan that their mother
had died in a car crash. The girls did not know the truth until
Fagan, who had changed his name and concocted a prestigious fake
resume, was arrested in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts sentence ``was the biggest slap in the face we
could have ever had. It just makes it so much harder,'' said Mulky,
who suspects her ex-husband in her son's disappearance 25 years
ago. ``A lot of men have responded to this protest and said,
`That's terrific.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, after a proposal from his attorney, was ordered by
Middlesex (Mass.) Superior Court Judge Peter M. Lauriat to perform
community service at the Veterans Affairs Medical Center in nearby
Riviera Beach, Fla. But after an outraged letter from former
Florida Governor Claude Kirk, a World War II and Korean War
veteran, Florida probation officials agreed to seek an alternate
location for Fagan to perform the 2,000 hours of unpaid work.
</P>
<P>
   ``A veteran is entitled to the best possible service our country
can give him. We don't need vagrants or convicted felons doing
something with them or within the organization,'' Kirk told the
Globe Friday. ``This is a federal facility. A crook like Fagan,
who's an admitted convicted felon, could not even apply and get a
job there as a volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're messing around with drugs, with records that are
important, with things that crooks can play with. And he's a known
liar, crook, and all the other bad things we can say about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan could not be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, a high-ranking Florida corrections official wrote to
Kirk, a West Palm Beach resident, to inform him that a new work
site would be proposed for Fagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This matter has been reviewed with appropriate regional and
local authorities in West Palm Beach, and a suggested change is
being prepared for submission to the Massachusetts court,'' Robert
M. Porter, chief of the Florida bureau of interstate compacts,
wrote Kirk. ``Staff in the office of the Massachusetts commissioner
of probation is also aware of our concerns about this particular
condition and will approach the court.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a spokeswoman for the Massachusetts probation system
said Friday that no correspondence has been received from Florida
on this subject. But if a change of venue for community service is
requested, spokeswoman Coria Holland said, the proposal will be
forwarded to Lauriat for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan continues to work at the VA medical center near West Palm
Beach, said his Boston attorney, Richard Egbert. ``It strikes me as
pure silliness that anyone would deny to the Veterans
Administration the help of a good, solid volunteer,'' Egbert said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney lashed out at Kirk, 73, a Republican who served as
Florida governor from 1967-1971. ``Those are the comments of a
self-righteous blowhard who obviously has no understanding of our
system of criminal justice,'' Egbert said. ``This is a
court-ordered community service for a person who can add many
talents as a volunteer and has been happily accepted by the VA.''
</P>
<P>
   The VA medical center in Riviera Beach confirmed that no changes
had been made regarding Fagan, who did volunteer work at the
hospital even before his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex District Attorney Martha Coakley, whose office
prosecuted Fagan, defended the sentencing agreement. ``This is a
substantial commitment of time and hard work, and it seemed an
appropriate place for him,'' Coakley said. ``This is work that's
needed and productive, we believe. We don't put people to breaking
rocks anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk, however, suggested that Fagan be ordered to work at places
that receive less volunteer help than a VA hospital, such as
homeless shelters, soup kitchens, or wards for babies with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could be there changing diapers or whatever they do. A
father who took two girls away knows how to change diapers,'' Kirk
said. ``This guy is not guilty in his own mind. What he ought to
say in order to get himself straightened out is: `I did it; I
shouldn't have done it; I should have taken other steps.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But he ain't done it, and he's not going to do it. He's the
ultimate con man. If I had my way, he probably wouldn't even live
in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulky, the protest organizer who has founded an advocacy group
for abducted children, said she expects the demonstration will last
two hours. The mansion, which Fagan and his fourth wife bought in
1996, has recently been put up for sale for $3.5 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
