<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLOCK-OBIT19-COX     06-18 1605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLOCK-OBIT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bullock's death brings close to a `great, grand' life
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach and Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Former Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock really was larger
than life. And his death Friday really does mark the end of an era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Bullock,'' said Gov. George W. Bush, ``was the largest
Texan of our time, as great and grand as the state he loved.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, 69, died at his Austin home Friday at 7:05 a.m. after
battling congestive heart failure, lung cancer and a string of
other challenges that might have taken out a smaller Texan years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   A first-generation Texan, Bullock fiercely embraced the state's
colorful history and did more than his part to preserve and
contribute to it. He prodded a major restoration at the State
Cemetery, where he picked his plot several years ago. Bullock also
led the effort to create a state museum, now under construction,
that will bear his name.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, the name, spoken emphatically, was enough to strike
fear in the hearts of staffers, allies and opponents. Bullock, the
man, rode a basic formula to decades of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He simply worked harder than anyone else,'' said longtime
Austin political consultant George Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's temper could melt a brass doorknob, but he was
considerate of his friends. He could be courtly and combative,
gentlemanly and lewd, magnanimous and unforgiving, humble and
intimidating, persuasive and threatening _ all within seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was Vesuvian,'' said Texas Railroad Commissioner Tony
Garza, likening Bullock to a volcano. ``Bullock could summon one's
best angels with his worst temper.''
</P>
<P>
   He also pushed through monumental programs _ changing everything
from the way Texas collects taxes to how it pays for its schools _
and never shied from a little political bloodletting for what he
believed to be in the best interest of Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was Bullock-proof.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unpredictable,'' Bush said of Bullock's personality,
``in a charming way. He was a high-energy man. He was
well-prepared. He could be volcanic in his language.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet beneath the rough-hewn exterior there was a very
loving, decent man,'' Bush concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's mark on state government will be felt for years to
come, according to Bush, who said ``almost everything about modern
Texas bears his imprint.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, as a result of his willingness in 1995 to cross party
and generational lines to befriend a rookie Republican governor,
Bullock's impact may be felt on the nation for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when Bush took office, the far-more-experienced
Bullock, who had backed Democrat Ann Richards in her unsuccessful
1994 re-election bid against Bush, could have made the new
governor's life miserable. He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to put partisanship aside,'' Bush said. ``He wanted
to focus on what's best for Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had a successful legislative session, putting him on the
course that has led him to front-runner status for the GOP
presidential nomination. Bush and Bullock became close friends.
</P>
<P>
   In his final years, after a lifetime of Democratic loyalty,
Bullock found a Republican to back for president. He endorsed Bush
(over Democrat and longtime Bullock friend Garry Mauro) for
re-election last year and, long before others talked publicly about
it, said he wanted to see Bush in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wept together, and I think that is part of what our tears
were about,'' Bush said of his final meeting with Bullock on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   During a Wednesday visit, Bush said Bullock wanted to know every
detail of the governor's recent first presidential campaign swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to hear what I saw,'' Bush said. ``He wanted to know
why I didn't smile on the Newsweek cover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to go win,'' said Bush, a man who learned that it
could be counterproductive not to do what Bullock wanted you to do.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock was born in Hillsboro in 1929. His father died when
Bullock was a teen-ager. The family moved in with Will Bond, his
elder sister's husband, and it was Bond who first prodded Bullock
to explore politics. He came to the Legislature in 1957 after, he
said, knocking on every door in Hill County twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife in those days wore size six shoes; she did the same
thing,'' Bullock said late last year. ``Amelia Bullock here in town
_ fine lady, she doesn't have much to do with me, but she's a fine
lady _ she did the same thing. Her foot grew to a 7 1/2. I think
that's what she holds against me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock finished Baylor law school in 1958, and under a system
in place at the time, got both his law degree from Baylor and his
undergraduate degree that year from Texas Tech University. He quit
the Legislature before his term ended because he couldn't survive
on a legislator's salary. He practiced law in the Rio Grande Valley
and in Tyler, then returned to government for a brief time as
assistant attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   With the 1968 election of Gov. Preston Smith, whose campaign
Bullock helped run, Bullock established a foothold. Smith rewarded
Bullock with a job as appointments secretary, a job at which the
future lieutenant governor joked he was woefully inept, appointing
dead people and convicted felons to important positions.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he did well enough to get promoted to secretary of
state. But his fortunes were still tied to Smith's, and as the
governor was on his way out of office, Bullock found himself in a
crossfire _ Smith tried to get his ally a slot on the state
insurance board, but senators hostile to Smith sank the
appointment. Had the victim been anyone but Bullock, the event
would have been long forgotten. But Bullock never forgot anything,
especially the names of every senator who voted to bust him.
</P>
<P>
   Although defeated for the moment, Bullock soon moved to run for
comptroller of public accounts _ then an obscure pocket of the vast
state bureaucracy that seemed to have last seen substantial change
in the Victorian Era. Bullock had a card file of 40,000 Smith
supporters from which to build his own political base, and he had a
driver, a 24-year-old aide named Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   After winning election in 1974, Bullock knocked down the walls
of his new office building so that his staff could share ideas and
communicate more effectively. Not long after that, ``Bullock's
Raiders'' were knocking down the doors of businesses that were
delinquent in their sales tax payments. The raids, sometimes
conducted with armed men, helped the state's bottom line. And they
were priceless PR for Bullock, whom the press painted more as
latter-day G-man than tax collector. He also sent auditors out of
state to increase Texas' tax collections, and he appointed women
and minorities to important positions within the office.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1992, after a stint as press secretary to Gov. Bill
Clements _ himself a demanding boss _ Reggie Bashur took a similar
post with Bullock. He quit after one day.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be fired by Bullock at least once was seen as an insult.
And those who did their jobs to Bullock's satisfaction had a
lifelong ally and booster.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the Bob Bullock university of public service here in
Austin with hundreds of graduates all throughout state
government,'' Bush said. ``And he was their mentor and their
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   If Comptroller Bullock was gaining a reputation as an autocrat,
he was also growing restless, dismantling and rebuilding parts of
his own organization just to keep busy, and criticizing other state
departments for leaving their lights on. (Bullock, meanwhile, took
heat for staying in $180 a night hotel rooms.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, when he won the lieutenant governor's job _ regarded as
the most powerful elected position in Texas politics _ statehouse
types wondered if Bullock's management style would sit well with
the 31 senators over which he would preside.
</P>
<P>
   He hauled every one of them to the woodshed at one time or
another. The combination of velvet glove and iron fist became known
as The Bullock Treatment or, more famously, the ``drive-by ass
chewing.'' For a senator to get chewed out by Bullock became a rite
of passage, just as getting fired from the comptroller's office had
been. But when it was over, it was truly over _ no hard feelings.
The howling and cussing and threatening was invariably a means,
albeit it crude, to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a management style,'' said Ralph Wayne, a friend for 35
years. ``It was a facade he put up about being mean and rough. He
could take the bark off a cinnamon tree, and at such times it was
best to take your whipping and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his bluster, Bullock knew he needed Republican support
to be an effective leader. And it was Republicans _ chewed behinds
or not _ who uttered some of the most unqualified praise of Bullock
as he prepared to retire in January after eight years in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a public servant in the highest sense of the word,''
said Sen. David Sibley (R-Waco).
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Teel Bivins (R-Amarillo) went further, naming Bullock one
of the ``three giants of Texas politics in the 20th Century,''
along with icons Lyndon Johnson and U.S. House Speaker Sam Rayburn.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock is survived by his wife, Jan; a son, Robert D. ``Bobby''
Bullock Jr., of Austin; a daughter and her husband, Lindy and Phil
Ward, of Austin; a grandson, Grant Bullock Robinson, of Austin; a
stepdaughter and her husband, Kimberly and Jeff Ader of Houston; a
brother and his wife, Tom and Jane Bullock of Brenham; and several
nieces and nephews.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
