<HEADER>
A1354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT &LR;      06-18 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7 RUSSIANS KILLED AND 14 WOUNDED AS FIGHTING BREAKS OUT ALONG
CHECHEN BORDER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia closed all but 10 of its 60 checkpoints along
the Chechnya border Friday after nighttime firefights with Chechen
rebels killed seven Russian policemen and interior ministry troops
and wounded 14 others. The interior ministry said a helicopter
counterattack wiped out a 15-truck convoy carrying perhaps 200
rebels, but it was impossible to verify the report.
</P>
<P>
   The firefights, the worst in several months, occurred along the
borders separating Chechnya from the Dagestan republic on the east
and Stavropol region on the north. The three, all members of the
Russian Federation, have been riven by clan warfare, criminal gangs
and religious strife, much of it centered in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials in Dagestan, the latest fights began
about 9 p.m. &QL; 
Thursday when Chechen rebels fired shots and mortars at Russian
outposts and barracks near the border between the two regions.
Three interior ministry guards died in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Mi-24 helicopter gunships joined the attack on the rebels and
the fighting spread along the border before it ended about 4 a.m.
Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Residents of a Chechen village near the border said 17 homes
were hit by Russian helicopter rockets and mortar fire, but the
Russian Interior Ministry claimed the fighting never spread across
the Dagestani border.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Chechen rebels attacked a Russian patrol vehicle
Thursday night along the northern border with Stavropol, killing
four Russian policeman. A fifth was still missing on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Chechnya has enjoyed broad autonomy since Russia quit a costly
civil war and withdrew its troops four years ago. But rebels there
still seek independence from Russia and Chechen militants and gangs
have frequently raided neighboring territories.
</P>
<P>
   Violence and crime is so widespread in Chechnya that most
foreigners regard the region as too dangerous to visit, and even
President Boris N. Yeltsin's personal envoy to the region was
kidnapped last year. Russian officials say Chechen gangs still hold
at least 500 Russians hostage, usually for ransom. Since the war
ended, Russia has tried, with mixed results, to keep Chechnya's
chaos from spreading. Some of the 60 border outposts have been
converted into small fortresses, holding as many as five dozen
policemen, armored vehicles and weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has begun a $900,000 project aimed at sealing much of the
border between Chechnya and Stavropol with two ditches, a rampart a
fence and 15 turrets for lookouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
