</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-GILLETTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL SALES PUT A DAMPER ON GILLETTE PROFITS FOR 2ND
QUARTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Germany, Japan, Russia)  By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Gillette Co. has hit a wall even as its core business is
growing.
</P>
<P>
   Reeling from several quarters of disappointing financial
results, it announced this week that more bad news is ahead. By all
appearances, its main business line of blades and razors is doing
well, adding to its leading worldwide market share. But the company
is being dragged down by the weak international performance of some
products, including Braun electric shavers, shaving cream and
stationery.
</P>
<P>
   While its poor foreign results might bode poorly for some other
marketers of consumer products, financial analysts said Gillette's
problems seemed to be more isolated and pointed out that many of
its peers had seen profits in overseas markets improve recently.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gillette's management warned investors that
second-quarter profits would fall by 20 percent, to about 26 cents
a share, from a year earlier. Wall Street analysts had been
expecting 29 cents, after some previous downward revisions,
according to the First Call Corp., which tracks corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third such warning in four quarters. The latest
shortfall, 10 percent shy of Wall Street forecasts, stunned
investors and even seemed to take management off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that surprised me more than anything else about this
announcement is that they were surprised,'' Sally Schaadt, an
analyst with Fourteen Research, said. ``I consider them pretty
savvy guys, and they were pretty insistent in April that the rest
of the year would be pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors hoping for a return to the type of earnings growth
that made the stock the bluest of blue chips were slammed.
Gillette's stock tumbled 10.8 percent to $42.187 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette's woes come at a time when it should be frisky. The
company controls 72 percent of the $7 billion worldwide razor and
blade business, which has grown 11 percent in the last 12 months.
Gillette's share has increased 3 percentage points, driven by the
strength of its new three-blade Mach 3 shaving system, which has
captured 13 percent of the total global market since its
introduction in April 1998. The company's Duracell battery unit is
also growing, and its Oral-B dental products remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's Braun products, which include electric razors
that have been big sellers in Japan, have suffered along with the
Japanese economy. The company's toiletries and stationery sales
have sagged in Germany and Russia where consumer spending is weak.
The strong dollar also has reduced the value of revenues abroad,
making foreign sales less profitable.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many multinational companies have been hurt by the
collapse of global markets over the last year. Some, like Procter &AMP;
Gamble, continue to struggle, but many of Gillette's peers,
including the Colgate-Palmolive Co. and Avon Products, are growing
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Gillette faced challenges that would linger well
into the year. For one, Braun's premium pricing makes its products
a tough sell in hard economic times. ``Braun is not an everyday
purchase, so you can certainly defer it,'' William Steele, a
managing director of Banc of America Securities, said.
</P>
<P>
   In the toiletries business, which includes Right Guard deodorant
and Gillette shaving cream, consumers in countries with sluggish
economies have probably been trading down to less expensive brands.
At the same time, the company's stationery business, which includes
Waterman pens, suffered from poor holiday sales as consumers abroad
tightened their budgets; they have not yet opened their purses.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the outside, investors are looking at the Braun,
toiletries and stationery businesses and scratching their heads
wondering how they can be so exasperatingly unprofitable and how
they can be so volatile,'' Constance Meneaty, an analyst with Bear,
Stearns, said.
</P>
<P>
   Some stock analysts are beginning to wonder if Gillette should
simply dump its poorly performing units. ``These are lower-margin,
less-profitable businesses that are not providing any cushion for
the company,'' said Mark Godfrey, an analyst at Invesco funds,
which owns 930,000 Gillette shares. He said he remained bullish on
the company because of the strength of its core franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette this week has sought to reassure investors that its
fundamental business remains strong and that its performance abroad
should begin to improve in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the recovery isn't happening as quickly as we had
projected, I still believe that Gillette's business growth will
accelerate through the last half of 1999, with sales approaching
double-digit growth and earnings improving,'' Michael C. Hawley,
the company's chairman and chief executive, said. He said profits
should return to traditional growth rates of 15 percent to 20
percent, but analysts are left to wonder if once again the company
may be too optimistic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
