<HEADER>
A1358 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-VETOES19-COX     06-18 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VETOES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush works to sign or veto bills
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Facing a Sunday deadline, Gov. George W. Bush
was expected to work through the weekend to finish reviewing,
signing and vetoing the more than 1,600 bills that lawmakers sent
to him this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush held a public ceremony Friday to sign two bills he has
sought, one to restructure the state's electricity industry and the
other to put tighter clamps on air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The electricity bill, Senate Bill 7, will restructure the entire
industry and, by 2002, deregulate the system by which most Texans
get power at their homes and businesses. Under the current system,
Texans buy their power from particular companies based on where
they live.
</P>
<P>
   Under Senate Bill 7, electricity companies will have to compete
to sell power to Texans regardless of where they live. The bill
also contains measures to reduce air pollution from power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 766 encourages owners of industrial plants that were
built before modern air pollution laws to bring those plants up to
snuff with current pollution standards. It contains hefty fines for
the largest polluters that don't go along with the voluntary plan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who pushed for the voluntary program without the fines,
said he's happy with the final product and believes it will
``result in cleaner air in communities across the state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that the legislation contains additional
incentives for companies to clean up sooner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday afternoon, Bush had signed more than 400 of the
bills lawmakers approved during this year's session. It ended May
31.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Bush has until Sunday to sign or veto the bills. Those
that don't get action from the governor become law without his
signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made up my mind,'' Bush said Friday. ``You can ask
me about bill number so-and-so and so-and-so, and I will give you
the same answer on each of them: I will not finish the process
until probably Sunday and I will put out the veto messages at that
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the bills that Bush already has signed are $506 million in
tax breaks for Texas corporations and consumers and $3.8 billion in
new education spending. Those bills include business breaks for
research and development spending, sales tax exemptions for all
over the counter medicines, about $1.3 billion in property tax
breaks and $1.7 billion for teacher salary increases.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday afternoon, Bush has vetoed only two bills.
</P>
<P>
   House Bill 64, sponsored by Rep. Sherri Greenberg (D-Austin),
would have provided grants to encourage business loans for small
businesses and those owned by minorities in poorer areas of Texas.
Bush said lawmakers didn't set aside money for the program.
</P>
<P>
   House Bill 2107, the other bill Bush vetoed, would have raised
sales taxes on fireworks in order to provide more money to
volunteer fire departments. Bush said the proposed tax hike would
push the rate above the constitutional limit of 8.25 percent and
would duplicate a separate fire prevention program that the
Commission on Fire Protection already runs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said while there's a crush of
bills awaiting the governor's signature, his staff has been working
on them all year and knows what needs to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every bill is reviewed by general counsel, the budget office,
policy office, legislative office and executive office. There are
some people that have have several feet-high stacks of bills
covering desks and tables,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   She added, however, that many of the bills easily clear the
review process and take less time than those that face questions or
concerns. Edwards also said Bush staffers have been tracking
legislation all year and aren't completely overwhelmed by the
onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking at legislation as soon as legislation is
filed,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   But while the policy and legal decision-making isn't overly
taxing, Edwards said there is the physical aspect of signing bills.
</P>
<P>
   By law, there's one official copy of each bill lawmakers passed.
That's the bill that Bush must sign and must be tracked carefully
as it moves through the process. That bill is filed with the
Secretary of State's office after its signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of people . . . simply involved in the
technical and physical aspects of the process who are working very
long hours,'' Edwards said. ``They know what to expect and are used
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
