<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-18 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: EX-OFFICIAL TIED TO AIDS SCANDAL
</P>
<P>
   Former Health Minister Claude Evin was put under investigation
for suspected manslaughter, the latest politician to be linked to a
scandal involving deaths due to AIDS-infected blood. Former Prime
Minister Laurent Fabius and one of his ministers were acquitted
this year of responsibility in allowing the use of unscreened blood
for hemophiliacs in the 1980s. A third official was convicted but
not jailed, a decision that angered many relatives of the 3,600
infected people, of whom close to 1,000 have died.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: SHOOTING INQUIRY URGED
</P>
<P>
   David Trimble, the Protestant first minister of the Northern
Ireland Assembly, called on the British government to investigate
the shooting of a former IRA official to determine if the attack
was made by the IRA. A finding involving the group would give
Protestant leaders grounds for excluding its political wing, Sinn
Fein, from the Assembly, causing a serious disruption of the peace
effort. Martin McGartland, who informed on the IRA, was shot and
wounded at his home in England.
</P>
<P>
   SWITZERLAND: BLOW TO HOLOCAUST FUND
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers dealt a blow to the government's plan to set up a fund
to help the needy, including Holocaust victims, by rejecting a
constitutional article clearing the way for the sale of excess gold
reserves to finance the fund. The fund, which government officials
said they would continue to pursue, was set up after disclosures of
Switzerland's role as banker for Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: SANCTION PLAN REJECTED
</P>
<P>
   A senior official rejected a U.S.-backed proposal that would
partially lift sanctions on Iraq if it answered questions about its
weapons programs and cooperated with a new group of U.N. arms
inspectors. Only an immediate lifting of sanctions would satisfy
Iraq, the official, Abdulghani Abdulghafur, told visiting Russian
legislators in Baghdad, the official Iraqi News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH AMERICA
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: TALKS ON ELECTORAL REFORMS
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties and the governing party, known as the PRI,
opened talks over proposed electoral reforms that would permit
coalitions and allow Mexican exiles to vote in presidential
elections. The changes are favored by the opposition and opposed by
the PRI. ``Our party will not approve election law reforms that
mean suicide for the PRI,'' said Jose Antonio Gonzalez Fernandez,
the PRI's leader.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ATTORNEY GENERAL'S SISTER HELD
</P>
<P>
   The sister of Attorney General Jorge Madrazo Cuellar was
arrested on a warrant accusing her of fraudulent use of an official
document. The arrest was cited by the office of the attorney
general, which was not involved in the investigation, as proof that
even the country's well-connected are no longer above the law. If
convicted, Lourdes Madrazo Cuellar faces up to three years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   KOREAS: NORTHERN NO-SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   Officials from North Korea failed to show up at a ceremony in
Panmunjom to hand over remains believed to be those of GIs killed
in the Korean War. The failure to appear is likely to have been a
response to a naval battle this week in which South Korean patrol
boats sank a North Korean torpedo boat in the Yellow Sea. The
firefight also threatens talks between the two Koreas set for
Monday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   EAST TIMOR: RIVALS REACH ACCORD
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of rival factions in the disputed territory signed an
agreement to cease intimidation and violence in advance of a
referendum on independence set for early August. Although a similar
accord was signed in April, armed men who favor autonomy under
Indonesia have continued to terrorize residents.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: MAHATHIR'S DUAL ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad hit two of his favorite targets
with one shot when he accused his jailed rival, Anwar Ibrahim, of
being a puppet of ``ethnic Europeans'' who want to recolonize Asia.
``The list of despicable acts by Europeans on us is long and I am
unable to name them all,'' he said in a speech at a meeting of his
ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   SWISS GROUP EXPELLED
</P>
<P>
   Christian Solidarity International, a Zurich-based human rights
group that says it has rescued more than 9,000 children and young
women from slavery in Sudan since 1995, was effectively expelled
from the U.N. at the urging of the Sudanese. The 19-nation
committee in charge of accrediting private nongovernmental groups
voted 12-1 to cancel the accreditation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
