A1368 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      06-18 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US AGREES TO GIVE RUSSIA PEACEKEEPING ROLE IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ Removing a major obstacle to the
international peacekeeping force in Kosovo, the United States and
Russia agreed to give Russian peacekeepers a major role, but not
sole control over any single sector of the province.
</P>
<P>
   The pact ends a weeklong diplomatic standoff that began when 200
Russian troops surprised NATO by taking up positions at the airport
near the Kosovo capital of Pristina after Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic began withdrawing his forces from Kosovo as part
of a NATO peackeeping plan.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement followed a day in which NATO faced several
challenges from within the province, including:
</P>
<P>
   _The detention by NATO peacekeepers of 25 members of the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army after NATO's rescue of 15 battered Gypsies
and ethnic Albanians from what may have been a KLA torture chamber
for alleged collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   _The continued influx of ethnic Albanian refugees, despite the
threat of land mines. At least 50,000 refugees have already
returned to Kosovo, the UN refugee agency says.
</P>
<P>
   _The outflow of ethnic Serbs from the province, despite new
appeals to stay by the leader of the Serbian Orthodox Church. Up to
50,000 Serb civilians have already left and the rest are
increasingly fearful as Serb troops pulled out of central Kosovo
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the US-Russian peacekeeping plan, Russian troops will
serve within sections of Kosovo controlled by peacekeeping forces
from the United States, France and Germany. Their commanders will
report to officials from those three countries.
</P>
<P>
   NATO will maintain air-traffic control of the airport near
Pristina, which is in the British section, but the Russians will
have other responsiblities at the airport, such as space allocation
and public works, US officials here said. Russians will constitute
no more than 3,600 of the 50,000 troops that will control the
province under the NATO-led effort.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who is here for an economic summit with heads
of leading industrial nations, applauded the agreement, saying it
provides ``a significant range of responsibilites for the Russians,
which I think are entirely appropriate and will enhance the
mission's effectiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I am fully supportive of this agreement and very
pleased by it. This has been a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan was hashed out during three days of talks in Helsinki,
Finland between Defense Secretary William Cohen and Russian Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright
and Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov became involved in the
sessions Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations had encountered many twists and turns, and
although US officials had remained optimistic that an accord could
be reached, Clinton suggested at one point Friday that the issue
might not be settled before Sunday, when he is scheduled to meet
here with Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement recognizes the stakes that Russia and NATO
share in Europe's future,'' Cohen said. ``It also shows that the
United States and Russia can work together on important security
issues. As major powers, we share a responsibility to work together
for peace and stability, and we have shown that we can measure up
to and meet that responsibility,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev called the agreement ``an alternative solution'' that
will allow Russia to participate in Kosovo peacekeeping and
``ensure that cooperation with our neighbors is effective in the
interest in implementing the common task.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Albright were to head for Brussels Saturday to brief
NATO allies on the details of the plan, which is expected to be
approved by its North Atlantic Council.
</P>
<P>
   A major stumbling block had been NATO's demand _ resisted by
Russia _ that all countries participating in peacekeeping in Kosovo
operate under a single NATO-led command. Russia also desired its
own geographic ``zone of responsibility'' within a section of
Kosovo. US officials opposed that, fearing it would amount to a
partitioning of Kosovo, because of the Russians' close ties to the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said in the beginning that we wanted the Russians to
participate'' in the peacekeeping effort, said a senior US
official. ``We think it will be stronger and better for it; but
this could only take place under an arrangement which provided for
the NATO-led operation with unity of command and did not in any way
undermine the effectiveness of the force.''
</P>
<P>
   The official added, ``We believe these requirements are met:
There is no Russian sector, there's no partition here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said it was important that the Russians play an active
role in peacekeeping effort because of their links to the Serbs. He
has repeatedly said that NATO bore no grudges against the Serbian
people, and had not taken sides in their conflict with ethnic
Albanians in the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will help us to send the message, to model the message, to
both groups that we really do want all law-abiding people to be
able to live in peace in Kosovo, and we intend to honor our
commitments to that end,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Russian's unpredictability, Clinton suggested that
he trusted they would follow through on the agreement. ``All I can
tell you is, every time I've had an understanding with Boris
Yeltsin he's kept it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, US officials said it was Yeltsin who suggested the two
defense secretaries get together in Helsinki for the talks after
the early Russian troop move into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Those negotiations had dominated the first day of the three-day
economic summit here, including a working dinner Friday night,
along with discussions on rebuilding Kosovo and its neighbors in
southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   US National Security Adviser Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger said the
leaders have agreed to hold a ``donor's conference'' possibly in
the next several weeks that would address Kosovo's short-term
needs. They have also begun discussing, at least conceptually, a
plan for rebuilding Kosovo and its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he believes Europe should carry the bulk of the
cost of rebuilding southeastern Europe, but that the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank ``should do a lot of it'' and the
``United States should contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair said he agreed entirely with
Clinton on the shouldering of the cost. ``We acknowledge our
responsibility in relation to reconstruction. There's a different
set of balances in relation to the cost of the troops that are
going in now, and you've got to look at everything in the round,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We can debate about the cost, and balance it out in
terms of the overall military campaign _ how we deliver the proper
administration in Kosovo, how we then reconstruct the Balkans. But
the key thing about this is our determination to make sure that
reconstruction actually happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
