<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    G-7 AGREES TO $90 BILLION DEBT RELIEF PACKAGE FOR POORER NATIONS
 &HT;    400&AMP;ADD.
 &HT;    With G8-KOSOVO-0619.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ Tossing a lifeline to poor countries awash in
a sea of debt, leaders from seven of the world's wealthiest nations
called Friday for a program aimed at wiping out up to $90 billion
worth of unpaid loans.
</P>
<P>
   The money would be available only to those countries that pledge
to use the savings from reduced debt payments to improve the health
and education of their poorest inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be writing off literally billions of dollars worth of
debt,'' said British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who joined
President Clinton and five other world leaders here for the annual
summit of the heads of state of the so-called Group of Seven, or
G-7, industrial powers. ``I believe this summit will mark,
probably, the single biggest step forward in debt relief and help
for the poorest countries that we've seen in the international
community for many years.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the G-7 set up a pool, now worth $13 billion,
of money that would be available for debt reduction to poor
indebted countries meeting certain criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Under the existing program, 26 countries -- most of whose people
scrape by on the local equivalent of a dollar a day or less -- are
eligible for the relief.
</P>
<P>
   The G-7 leaders agreed Friday to expand that program to take in
a total of 33 needy countries that together owe wealthy nations a
staggering $127 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The G-7 plan also calls for member states to add up to $37
billion to the existing pool, making as much as $50 billion in
direct debt relief available to qualifying countries.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the G-7 leaders called on member states -- the
United States, Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy and Japan --
to collectively forgive up to $20 billion in debts owed through
concessionary foreign assistance loans.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the G-7 urged other industrial powers not belonging to
the prestigious club to chip in with another $20 billion worth of
debt relief.
</P>
<P>
   Indebtedness is a leading impediment to development among dozens
of the world's poorest countries, many of which are forced to pay
up to 30 cents on every dollar of government revenue simply to make
payments on debts owed to wealthy nations.
</P>
<P>
   Those commitments leave impoverished nations too strapped to
adequately address legitimate development needs ranging from
education to the prevention of AIDS, a chronic malady that
threatens tens of millions of people across the continent of Africa
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
