<P>
   GORE-SEATTLE (Seattle) _ Vice President Al Gore looked every bit
the frontrunner as he wrapped up his presidential announcement tour
with a stop in Seattle on Friday. He touted record economic growth,
identified himself with Washington's export and technology-driven
economy, and accepted endorsements from the state's top-ranking
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   PIPELINE (BELLINGHAM, Wash.) _ Had a valve just a tenth of a
mile from the spill worked properly, the damage might have been
much less severe, say federal investigators looking into last
week's deadly pipeline explosion in Bellingham. The malfunctioning
valve allowed as much as 3,100 more barrels of gasoline to escape.
Total spill was 3,600 to 6,600. Olympic Pipe Line will be ordered
to reduce pressure to 80 percent of normal from Skagit County to
Renton, about 10 miles southwest of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Sunde. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   RUNWAY-SEATTLE (Seattle) _ The third runway at Seattle-Tacoma
International Airport will cost $186 million more than initially
projected and take two years longer to complete, planners say. The
overruns bring the total cost of the runway to $773 million _ 31
percent more than previously thought. The expected completion date
is bumped to 2006 from 2004. It is at least the second time airport
officials have boosted their estimates for the project's cost.
</P>
<P>
   By Jack Hopkins. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-AIRBUS (Paris) _ The competition between Boeing and
Airbus reached new heights Friday, with Boeing agreeing to buy 17 _
some used and some as yet undelivered _ Airbus A340-300s from
Singapore Air which in turn agreed to convert 10 of its options on
777s to firm orders. Analysts say it raises the question of whether
Boeing is creating a new opportunity for a new extended range
version of the 777, which had been delayed for lack of a launch
customer.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   JOBS-SEATTLE (Seattle) _ They arrive in Seattle from places in
the world as diverse as The Netherlands, Barbados and India and
they are seeking the high-paying high-technology jobs that
Seattle-area companies can't fill. International trade delegations
have paraded into Seattle in recent weeks reassuring computer
software developers with a common message. They have skilled,
trained people ready and eager to take on work, often at low cost,
that Seattle-area companies need to complete before their customers
switch to competitors, they say.
</P>
<P>
   By Arthur C. Gorlick. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   DADS-ANIMALS (Seattle) _ Motherhood is well-understood, even in
the animal kingdom. Lactate, nurture, teach. But fatherhood's
another matter. Some dads slap their young, some kill them, some
take over for Mom. We visit local zoos to get the low-down.
</P>
