<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0368 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1393 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-RECREATE19-COX     06-18 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-RECREATE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Restored Delta plane flies original route to celebrate 70 years
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. _ Big corporations often celebrate birthdays by
recalling their humble origins.
</P>
<P>
   At Delta Air Lines this week, a group of pilots and mechanics
went a step further, faithfully re-creating those origins for what
amounted to a barnstorming history tour across the South.
</P>
<P>
   They marked the 70th anniversary of Delta's first day of airline
service by flying a single-engine, five-passenger Travel Air along
the carrier's original route.
</P>
<P>
   Just after 8 a.m. on June 17, 1929, a Travel Air belonging to
what was then called Delta Air Service lifted off a dirt runway at
Dallas' Love Field on a hopscotch flight to Jackson, Miss., via
Shreveport and Monroe, La.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot Johnny Howe was alone at the controls. Delta's first three
passengers, their names lost to time, sat on wicker chairs behind
him in the Travel Air's boxy, cramped fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday morning, 70 years later almost to the minute, a
restored Delta Travel Air taxied past huge modern jets to the end
of a vast cement runway at Love Field.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots Ted Abbott, retired from Delta, and Robin Maiden, who
usually flies 757s for a living, drew a verbal double-take from a
controller when they radioed for takeoff permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of aircraft are you again?'' the perplexed
controller asked before granting clearance.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Abbott applied full throttle, and the craft
eagerly bounded down the runway and into the air in less than 400
feet, a fraction of the space needed by a modern jet.
</P>
<P>
   Delta mechanics who helped restore the plane rode along on the
daylong sentimental journey, as did an Atlanta Journal-Constitution
reporter and a Delta public relations officer dispatched to handle
the small crowds that turned out at each stop.
</P>
<P>
   Other pilots and mechanics traveled in a vintage DC-3 that flew
along as a support plane. On Friday, the Travel Air flew back to
Atlanta, where it's kept and maintained as part of Delta's Air
Transport Heritage Museum project.
</P>
<P>
   The trip offered both a vivid glimpse into Delta's beginnings
and testimony to the astonishing progress made in commercial
aviation during this century.
</P>
<P>
   The first Dallas-Jackson flight took about five hours, and cost
$90 round-trip _ nearly $800 in today's dollars. Then as now,
passengers were buying time. The 1929 service shaved 12 hours off
the time required by ground transport, which a Delta marketing
pamphlet declared ``too slow to meet the needs of a new epoch in
human affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the 400-mile flight takes about an hour nonstop on a
Delta jet and costs between $170 and $310. Passengers are
transported in fast, quiet aluminum cocoons with scarcely any
awareness of the miracle of flight or their precarious position in
space. No such blissful ignorance was allowed in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Powered by a nine-cylinder radial engine, the Travel Air was a
sturdy and well-built plane, heralded in its day as ``the last word
in airplane construction'' and the ``limousine of the skies.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, on Thursday's flight the little plane bobbed on
each fresh air current as Abbott and Maiden steered it eastward
beyond the Dallas sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers sat behind them in narrow seats _ mercifully padded
during Delta's restoration _ with an open view of the rudimentary
cockpit and the exposed cylinder heads beyond the front windshield.
</P>
<P>
   The Travel Air's wide, tall side windows afforded panoramic
views as the plane cruised at about 90 mph over the countryside
3,000 or so feet below.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's restored plane has earphones so that occupants can speak
to each other; without them, the din from the engine and the
airflow made shouting or hand gestures the only practical form of
communication. Early passengers stuffed cotton in their ears.
</P>
<P>
   After an initial indulgence in air traffic control guidance _
which didn't exist in 1929 _ Abbott and Maiden resorted to
old-fashioned navigation techniques as the plane churned just
beneath a low cloud layer toward Shreveport.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, we're looking for a big lake,'' said Maiden, consulting a
chart and peering out the windscreen at the ground 2,500 feet
below. Addison should be up here on the left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times in the early days when the pilots did get
lost,'' Abbott noted cheerfully. ``They'd just land at a strip or
in a field and ask where they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Delta's early route maps advertised numerous ``emergency
landing strips'' along with the intended destinations, as if to
reassure customers there really was a plan B if the weather soured
or the engine conked out.
</P>
<P>
   No such excitement occurred on Thursday's flight, although
Abbott and Maiden once resorted to circling a small town water
tower _ ``Ringgold,'' (La.) it announced _ to get their bearings.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Maiden decided it was time to clean a few oil
droplets off the front windshield _ a normal by-product of radial
engine operation, he assured. He grabbed a rag, rolled down his
window and reached around to wipe away the oil.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours into Thursday's trip, Shreveport's airport came into
view and Abbott brought the Travel Air down to a butter-smooth
landing using a fraction of the runway. On final approach, the
Travel Air passed a taxiing Delta MD-88, whose captain opened his
window to wave.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, a few dozen Delta employees, local aviation buffs
and airport officials gaped at the antique plane as it taxied to
the ramp and the engine wheezed to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this anything like Lindbergh's plane?'' 78-year-old
Shreveport resident Will McNutt asked the pilots. He recalled his
own first ride on a similar-looking plane in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot gave me a little card saying I'd been on an
airplane,'' he said. ``It was a big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gassed up and topped off with a couple of quarts of oil by Delta
mechanics Bill Tinsley and Jeff Hoole, the plane left Shreveport
about 12:30 p.m., the skies now clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice day for an inaugural flight,'' remarked Abbott,
now navigating while Maiden handled the controls. ``The Gods are
smiling on Delta Air Service today.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour and numerous lakes and small towns later, the plane
crossed the Ouchita River near Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home office is dead ahead,'' said Abbott as Maiden zeroed in
on the Monroe airport. Delta was a Monroe-based crop dusting
service before becoming an airline, and it didn't move its
headquarters to Atlanta until 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Maiden brought the plane down to within a few feet of the runway
and then back up and around the airfield for the assembled crowd.
After he landed, a convoy of emergency trucks tailed the Travel Air
to the terminal and gave it another waterspray salute.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Monroe greeters was Henry Biedenharn III, who sits on
Delta's board of directors. His family helped bankroll Delta in the
early days and has had a seat on the board ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it just shows that as large and complex a company
Delta has become, it's not too big to return to its roots and
beginnings,'' Biedenharn said.
</P>
<P>
   Just after 2 p.m. the plane churned skyward once more for the
final leg to Jackson. Jake Boyd, another retired Delta pilot, now
took a turn at the controls with Maiden as co-pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the Mississippi River came into view as a broad,
brown-green band on the hazy horizon. Its enormity was far more
impressive at 2,000 feet _ the Travel Air's altitude as it passed
near Vicksburg _ than from 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Travel Air touched down in Jackson about 3:15 p.m.,
passengers and pilots alike by now sweaty and tired from the
daylong noise, heat and vibration.
</P>
<P>
   Maiden managed a moment of reflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun and we had a good time,'' he said. ``But I had a
few quiet moments up there, thinking, `Here are the same fields
(Howe) saw, here's the same river he saw, the same railroads.' It
does makes you appreciate what came before.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
