<HEADER>
A1395 &Cx1f; tth-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DADS-ANIMALS-SPI &LR;      06-18 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DADS-ANIMALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S HEAR IT FOR THE MR. MOMS OF THE ANIMAL KINGDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Your Homo sapiens dad's a real stand-up guy.
</P>
<P>
   But would he roll you up in a dung ball for protection?
</P>
<P>
   Would he undergo wrenching contractions to give birth to you and
a couple hundred siblings?
</P>
<P>
   Would he sacrifice food for a significant chunk of his limited
life span to carry you through incubation _ then stifle a gnawing
urge to eat you?
</P>
<P>
   Raise those fins and claws and pointy little talons and give it
up for the Mr. Moms of the animal kingdom, those hard-working,
overlooked Superdads who do twice the work and get half the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hear about the mothers, not the fathers,'' says
Holly Reed, associate veterinarian at Point Defiance Zoo and
Aquarium in Tacoma. ``The male has a major role in a number of
obscure species.''
</P>
<P>
   This oversight is understandable. Earth moms are easy. Most coo
and cuddle, lick and suckle, nest and nurture.
</P>
<P>
   Their mates present a more complicated picture. There are
deadbeat dads who breed-and-run. And worse.
</P>
<P>
   Sea lion dads have a nasty tendency to roll over and squish
young pups. Roaringly hungry Daddie Dearest bears have been known
to make quick meals of small cubs. And alligators, although gentle
lovers and faithful mates, will _ given half a chance _ dine on the
tasty eggs containing their young.
</P>
<P>
   But animal dads can be endearingly tender.
</P>
<P>
   One beguiling papa is the pint-size Golden Lion tamarin, a
miniature Chewbacca with a coat the color of honey. Several weeks
after mom gives birth, the little fellow takes over, carrying his
gold children nestled in the silky fur of his back.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they're big kids, the tamarins rely on dad. ``When
they get scared, they will still jump back on him,'' says zookeeper
Diane Yoshimi of Seattle's Woodland Park Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Another conscientious caretaker is the pygmy marmoset. He's one
of the tiniest primates, at approximately 4 inches and 2 ounces.
But he is a towering father figure. While mom feeds the babes, dad
carries them, watches over them, plays with them, keeps them safe,
and eventually teaches them some of the nurturing skills learned
from his own father.
</P>
<P>
   Many big, oafy bovines are true Good-Time Charlies, running off
to bachelor herds after a one-night stand. A stalwart exception is
the musk ox. These long-haired, prehistoric-looking beasts stick
around mom and babes, acting as protectors, listening to the
pitter-patter of little hooves.
</P>
<P>
   When danger's near, they alert the herd, round up the children,
then ``circle the wagons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The adult males get in big circles, shoulder-to-shoulder,
their derrieres together, facing outward,'' says Reed. ``All the
youngsters are in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene might have heartened Sigmund Freud, who once
commented: ``I cannot think of any need in childhood as strong as
the need for a father's protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Deserved or not, the Animal Dad of the Year award invariably
goes to the seahorse. His coy, colorful sweetheart injects his
pouch with up to 600 eggs, then scoots, leaving him holding the
bag. The eggs incubate in the nutritive-lined pouch until dad's
belly stretches and swells like a tiny water balloon.
</P>
<P>
   When B-Day arrives, his body begins contracting and contorting,
each spasm expelling tiny, perfectly shaped seahorses.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story with special appeal to female Homo sapiens who have
wished hellish labor pains on indifferent husbands. But it's a
story short on bonding. The seahorse's job is done as his brood
drifts away in a strong current.
</P>
<P>
   A more deserving underwater family man is the eel-like lungfish.
This Mr. Nice Guy broods fertilized eggs in his mouth and, once
they hatch, gingerly introduces his offspring to the big world.
``He guards them, keeps them in the area and, at the least sign of
danger, he opens his mouth and draws them back in,'' says exotics
biologist Bill Robertson at the Seattle Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   Male mouth brooders are role-switchers from way back.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the tiny Andean Darwin frog, a dad with a communal love
family take on child-rearing. Dandy Andy fertilizes mom's eggs, she
hip-hops off into the sunset, and he and his pals hang out, posing
for Budweiser commercials and watching over the eggs until they're
about to hatch.
</P>
<P>
   When tadpoles look imminent, the Darwinian dad dudes each grab a
clump of eggs, and slide them down their throats into their vocal
pouches. Some days later, out hop their little darlings.
</P>
<P>
   Even bug dads can do right by their women. One pungent example
is the dung beetle, who helps his mate roll up a nice sphere of
ZooDoo for her eggs. The eggs inside the ball develop into larvae,
and the larvae eat up the inside of the poop scoop, emerging feisty
and funky.
</P>
<P>
   Martyrdom's a maternal specialty, but there's one father at
Woodland Park Zoo who could major in it. His name is Abedus herbeti
_ the water bug _ and his woman's a two-timing manipulator. She
glues eggs to his back then bolts, looking for another sexy sucker
doing push-ups on a log.
</P>
<P>
   Dad is stuck carrying the eggs, looking like a miniature
porcupine, unable to eat until the last little bugger breaks its
case and swims free.
</P>
<P>
   Survival of the babes depends on suppression of the appetite.
Explains Erin Sullivan, Woodland Park Zoo bugkeeper: ``If he still
had the eating instinct during this time, he would probably feed on
the young.''
</P>
<P>
   Birddom has its share of stellar dads, too. Particularly
accommodating is the emperor penguin, a tuxedoed, 4-foot gent with
the patience of Job. Shortly after his mate lays a single egg, she
heads out into the icy unknown in search of food. She may be gone
two months or more, leaving him to incubate the egg between feet
and belly in 70-degree-below-zero Antarctic weather.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't eat until mom returns, eager to regurgitate the
months-old, half-digested fish she has collected for her loved ones
to feast on. And it isn't even Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The handsome, big-headed, red-knobbed hornbill is a regular
zippety-zoo-dad. He dotes on his woman. She seals her self away in
a nest cavity for months to incubate and hatch her three eggs. She
is totally dependent upon dad to provide meals through a tiny
opening in the cavity.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the three chicks will survive in the nest. Two will
starve. Woodland Park Zoo birdkeeper Erick Kowalczyk, who has a
videocam trained inside a hornbill nest, describes watching a
father feeding a fresh-dead nestling to its two siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a Norman Rockwell moment.
</P>
<P>
   But it's nature's way _ Father Nature's way.
</P>
<P>
   Sources for this story include ``How They Do It,'' by zoologist
Robert Wallace, ``The LaRousse Encyclopedia of Animal Life,'' and
Microsoft Encarta `98.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMBLING-REPORT-NYT &LR;      06-18 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBLING-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEANING OF GAMBLING REPORT DEPENDS ON WHO'S INTERPRETING IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev., Va., N.J.)  (mk) 
 By BRETT PULLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The enduring battle over legalized gambling in the
United States received a new blueprint Friday, as the National
Gambling Impact Study Commission released the results of a
two-year, $5 million study of the social and economic impact that
the gambling boom has had on the nation.
</P>
<P>
   As the report was handed over to President Clinton, members of
Congress, governors and Indian tribal leaders, gambling advocates
and foes alike wasted little time seizing upon the document and
selectively highlighting the aspects that seem to best suit their
positions. Rep. Jim Gibbons, R-Nev., issued a statement proclaiming
that ``as this commission properly reports, gaming enjoys a
positive image as part of the mainstream culture of American
society.'' At the same time, Tom Grey, executive director of the
National Coalition Against Legalized Gambling, called the report
``a wake-up call for America on the dangers of gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   With the work of the nine-member commission now complete, the
scene of the gambling debate will shift venues as state legislators
and Congress must now decide which, if any, of the report's 76
recommended changes for the casinos, state lotteries, pari-mutuel
games and video betting machines that now cover the country will
ever become a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the great debate begins and we'll have to see where it all
falls out,'' said Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., who sponsored the
legislation that established the commission. Wolf, a staunch
opponent of gambling, said he planned to introduce legislation to
fulfill many of the commission's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the recommendations in the report, which states that
gambling activities ``have become familiar backdrops to daily
life,'' is a call for states to impose a moratorium on gambling
expansion to allow time to assess the impact of any proposed
developments; a requirement that all gambling be limited to people
21 and over since some states allow 18-year-olds to purchase
lottery tickets and patronize casinos; bans on the Internet
gambling business that has mushroomed over the past few years; a
ban on all wagering on college and amateur sports, which currently
takes place only in Las Vegas; a ban on all political contributions
to state and local campaigns, and a curtailing of lottery
advertising as well as a decrease in the number of outlets selling
lottery products.
</P>
<P>
   But no issue seemed to receive more attention from the
commission than problem gambling. Over two thirds of the
recommendations in the report are aimed at research and treatment
for problem gamblers, who the commission found account for 15
percent of the industry's gross revenues. Among those
recommendations is a call for state and tribal governments to use a
``gambling privilege tax'' to create a dedicated fund to address
problem and pathological gambling. Most states with casinos already
collect such a tax but would still need to adopt legislation that
would dedicate some of the money to problem gambling. Another
recommendation calls for providing medical insurance coverage for
problem and pathological gamblers, who the commission said now
amount to 15.4 million adult and adolescent gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 15.4 million number sticks in my mind,'' said Leo
McCarthy, a member of the commission and a former lieutenant
governor of California. ``That's a fairly heavy price to pay unless
we go after that downside.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such alarming statistics, the very first sentence in the
first chapter of the report states that ``Today, the vast majority
of Americans either gamble recreationally and experience no
measurable side effects related to their gambling, or they choose
not to gamble at all.'' The report goes on to note that because of
legalized gambling, ``sleepy backwaters have become metropolises
almost overnight; skyscrapers rise on the beaches at once-fading
tourist areas; legions of employees testify to the hope and
opportunities that the casinos have brought them and their
families; some Indian nations have leapt from prolonged neglect and
deprivation to sudden abundance.''
</P>
<P>
   Such laudatory phrases were quickly treated like declarations of
emancipation by executives and leaders in the casino industry, who
had feared that the commission would result in a full-scale
indictment of their businesses. ``The verdict is in and the accused
has been exonerated,'' said Frank Fahrenkopf Jr., the president of
the American Gaming Association, the gambling industry's lobbying
arm. In a statement he handed out following Friday's press
conference, he added, ``The commission puts to rest claims of
organized crime involvement, of increased crime related to casinos,
of exaggerated numbers of pathological gamblers, of economic
benefits being outweighed by absurdly high social costs and a host
of other outrageous charges we've had to deal with for years.''
</P>
<P>
   But as was evident by the individual statements that each of the
commissioners made during the press conference, how the report is
interpreted all depends on who is doing the interpreting. James
Dobson, the commission's most strident gambling opponent and the
founder and president of Focus on the Family, a conservative
nonprofit organization, said that after two years of studying the
issue, ``I am even more convinced now that gambling is a
destroyer.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Terrence Lanni, the chairman and chief executive at MGM Grand
casinos and a commission member, lauded his fellow commissioners
for refusing to recommend that the federal government regulate or
tax casinos, as had been feared when the commission first convened.
``The states are best left to determine the regulation and taxation
of this industry,'' he said. He and other commissioners noted that
although they were deeply and emotionally divided on the issue of
gambling from the outset, they were able to compromise and complete
the report. The commission, Lani quipped, ``started with the notion
that we needed metal detectors coming into our meetings.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And for the first time since the commission began its work, Kay
James, the chairwoman, publicly stated her personal position on
gambling. ``Kay James, if it comes as a big surprise, is
anti-gaming,'' she said, referring to herself in the third person.
Ms. James, who recently resigned as dean of the school of
government at Regent University in Virginia, had routinely voted in
favor of anti-gaming measures. But her refusal to impose some tough
measures like federal taxes and regulations on the big casino
companies had led to some recent speculation in the press that she
had been controlled by the powerful gambling industries _ a charge
she denied in no uncertain terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a black, conservative Republican, pro-life, evangelical
Christian,'' Ms. James said. ``Do you think I can be influenced?''
</P>
<P>
   With all of the anxiety and speculation over the commission's
report now behind them, the legislators who can pass the laws that
will affect the gambling industry are girding for a battle. ``Our
goal now is to insure the report's recommendations on under-age and
problem gambling are adopted by policy-makers at the national,
state and local levels,'' said Keith Whyte, executive director of
The National Council on Problem Gambling, a nonprofit organization.
``It's only half time in the game,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Rep. Wolf of Virginia promising to get legislation passed
in Congress and appeal to the nation's governors to do the same at
the state level, two of New Jersey's representatives in Congress,
who also happen to be two of Atlantic City's biggest champions,
were promising to fight some of the initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with reporters following Friday's press
conference, Rep. Frank LoBiondo, a Republican, and Sen. Robert
Torricelli, a Democrat, said they would oppose dedicating a portion
of the gaming taxes that the state already collects to finance
research and treatment for problem gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be like having a tax on beer because there's a
problem with alcoholism,'' Torricelli said. ``In our society we
deal with funding for these problems on a voluntary basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
