<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPRISE? MEXICO STARTS NEW BILLION-DOLLAR BANK BAILOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ As a reminder that the banking system is still a
worrisome weak link in Mexico's robust economy, a newly created
federal bank insurance agency has initiated two huge bailouts
reminiscent of bank rescues of just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, the Bank Savings Protection Institute, decided
hursday to take over Grupo Financiero Serfin SA, Mexico's
third-largest bank. Vicente Corta Fernandez, director of the
agency, said it expected to have to put up at least $1.3 billion to
save the bank, which declared that in practice it was bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Corta said in a radio interview Friday morning that
the agency expected to begin the cleanup of another bank, Bancrecer
SA, in coming weeks. He said the government might have to spend as
much as $9 billion to make the bank sound in preparation for
selling it.
</P>
<P>
   The banking system is the spoiler in the parade of upbeat
economic news from Mexico. In the first quarter, industrial output
expanded at a 4.3 percent annual rate, and purchases by consumers,
which had long lagged behind other signs of growth, rose 1.8
percent. Mexico's government was so confident of a strong
performance this year that it pledged Thursday to reach 5 percent
growth in 2000 and, more significant, to reduce inflation to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue of Serfin had been expected, but the size of both
bailouts was a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   At an emergency meeting July 8, the Serfin shareholders will be
asked to provide more capital, said Serfin chairman Adolfo Lagos.
But they are expected to decline and swallow the loss of their
investment in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Armendariz, the vice president of the National Banking
and Stock Commission, the top federal regulatory agency, estimated
that Serfin needed a total of $2.1 billion, including capital to be
provided by investors, to return to health.
</P>
<P>
   The bank insurance agency, which went into operation last month,
will inject enough capital to make Serfin viable for sale, Corta
said, and will begin to take bids later in July. All bank deposits
are guaranteed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   All of Mexico's banks sold bad debt to a predecessor bailout
agency in 1995 and 1996, after a devaluation of the peso. But
Serfin's troubles date from before that crisis, starting with the
large concentration of home and commercial mortgages in its
portfolio. When interest rates soared to nearly 100 percent in
1995, thousands of these loans went bad. Analysts said Serfin
unloaded about $6 billion in bad debt on the government in the
first bailout, more than any other bank.
</P>
<P>
   It tried repeatedly to climb out of the hole but was hit last
year by the turmoil in Russia and Brazil and more recently by the
demise of its loans with Altos Hornos de Mexico SA, the country's
largest steelmaker, which recently sought bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Corta said the 20 percent stake in Serfin held by HSBC Holdings
PLC, of London, would be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican banks have seen a wave of foreign takeovers since 1996
as local shareholders failed to find sufficient capital to keep
their banks. Citigroup Inc. and two Spanish banks, Santander and
BBV, are among the leading foreign acquirers.
</P>
<P>
   The reform of the $65 billion bank bailout program became the
stormiest political debate in Mexico in 1998, occupying the
Congress virtually full time for the entire year. Many Mexicans
believed there would be no more bailouts after the new insurance
agency was formed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
