<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTON-PLEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTON SAID TO PLAN GUILTY PLEA ON IMPROPER-PAYMENTS CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Litton Industries has agreed to plea guilty to
charges stemming from illegal payments it made to secure nearly
$200 million worth of defense business in Greece and Taiwan,
officials close to the case said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The company will plead guilty to three counts, including one of
conspiracy to defraud the government, and pay an $18.5 million
fine, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the negotiated plea agreement, the government will
drop the more serious charges that Litton violated the Foreign
Corrupt Practices Act, which prohibits bribes to foreign officials.
If the company had been found guilty of violating that law, it
would have been barred from doing business with the federal
government, a serious blow for the shipbuilding and
defense-electronics giant.
</P>
<P>
   Litton said Friday that it was negotiating with the U.S.
attorney's office in Los Angeles, which is handling the case, but
declined to say anything else publicly. The plea agreement is
likely to be announced next week, a government official said.
</P>
<P>
   Within the government, there was some dissatisfaction that the
foreign bribery charges had been dropped. The law was passed in the
mid-1970s following disclosures that Lockheed had paid millions of
dollars to public officials to win defense contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign companies have long argued that U.S. companies routinely
use ``commissions'' to ``consultants'' to circumvent the law, and
American and foreign critics say that enforcement of the law has
been lax.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a mom and pop grocery store, $18 million would be the end
of the world,'' one official said. ``But for Litton, it's
nothing.'' Litton had earnings in 1998 of $181 million on sales of
$4.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the fine about equaled the company's improper
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Litton Applied Technology paid four Greek agents $12 million in
commissions in a successful effort to win a $150 million contract
to supply radar systems for Greece's F-16 fighter jets, according
to an official. Litton won the contract, in 1993, over stiff
competition from Marconi Defence Systems Ltd., a unit of General
Electric PLC of Britain, according to reports at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Litton first described the payments in the company's books as
``other direct costs,'' and later as ``outside computer services,''
according to an official who has been working on the case.
</P>
<P>
   In Taiwan, Litton Systems Ltd., Canada, paid $4.3 million in
commissions to Richard Hei, a former Taiwan air force officer who
set up a consulting firm when he left the military, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Litton exploited those contacts and illegally paid him
commissions,'' an official involved in the case said. The
commissions were 10 percent of the value of the contract, which is
a routine payment practice in foreign sales.
</P>
<P>
   After being prosecuted by the U.S. government on charges of
income tax evasion, Hei begun cooperating with the government in
its case against Litton, according to government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Hei's largest receipt was $3.2 million, for a $32 million
contract Litton won to upgrade Taiwan's anti-submarine aircraft,
the officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
