A1407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-CARBONDIOXIDE19-     06-18 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-CARBONDIOXIDE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carbon dioxide's usage usually not a concern
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Carbon dioxide, a harmless gas we breathe every day,
is used in a number of ways _ from making the ``fizz'' in soft
drinks to extinguishing fires to cleaning electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The gas is at the heart of the investigation into what caused
illnesses among Europeans who drank Coca-Cola Co. products over the
past week. The company cited defective carbon dioxide in bottles
from a plant in Antwerp, Belgium, for illnesses in that country.
</P>
<P>
   Colorless and odorless, the gas is usually sold as dry ice or in
liquid canisters. Generally, ``there's no concern about its use in
food products,'' said Dr. LarenTolbert, chair of Georgia Tech's
School of Chemistry and Biochemistry.
</P>
<P>
   In the soft drink industry, bottlers use pure carbon dioxide as
a compressed gas in high-pressure tanks. The gas is absorbed into
the flavored soft drink in a ``carbonator'' machine just before the
bottle or can is sealed, according to the National Soft Drink
Association Web site.
</P>
<P>
   When a product has a problem, it's typically not because the
carbon dioxide is defective, said Tolbert, but because canisters or
machinery have become contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   If dissolved in water, carbon dioxide gives the liquid the extra
kick, making natural sources of carbonated water prized for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1900s, companies were producing drinks comprised of
flavored water and carbon dioxide. The gas was created from sodium
salts _ thus the drinks were dubbed ``sodas'' or ``soda pops.''
</P>
<P>
   But carbon dioxide is useful for a number of other purposes. It
is used in some fire extinguishers because it is heavier than air
and does not burn. When sprayed over a fire, it blankets the blaze
and prevents any more oxygen from reaching and feeding the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have found that carbon dioxide in its
``supercritical'' form _ a stage when the gas is under extreme
pressure _ is useful as a cleaning solvent. Both the dry-cleaning
and electronics industries are looking into the gas as a
replacement for more dangerous chemicals, Tolbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Carbon dioxide is also necessary to regulate the Earth's
temperature. When sunlight reaches the Earth, some of the rays are
transferred into heat. Carbon dioxide absorbs some of that heat and
keeps it near the Earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, however, worry that too much heat is being
retained by carbon dioxide _ produced in part by burning fossil
fuels _ creating a greenhouse effect.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
