<HEADER>
A1412 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV20-B     06-18 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV20-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO OWNS THE BRIDGE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 20, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Microsoft case is rumbling toward a climax, if not a
conclusion. The trial is in its rebuttal phase. Bill Gates
testified before the Joint Economic Committee of Congress last
week, paying obeisance to what he called, hopefully, ``the light
hand of government.''
</P>
<P>
   Most persons think it is the break-em-up Section 2 of the
Sherman Antitrust Act that the government has in mind. But there is
another precedent, a good deal older than the 1890 statute, that is
as essential in its way to the deep architecture of the Republic as
such landmark decisions as Marbury v. Madison or McCullough v.
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   That is the matter of the Charles River Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   And while it hasn't come up in the formal proceedings, an
argument based on the 170-year-old case by a University of
California law school professor has been making the rounds,
attracting attention among those following the case.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Who Owns the Charles River Bridge? Intellectual Property
and Competition in the Software Industry,'' Ropert P. Merges argues
that if it can be shown that property rights are limiting
innovation, a strong case can be made for limiting them _ in favor
of open competition.
</P>
<P>
   For while the economy has mutated greatly, he says, the
parallels with the past are clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be deprived of a single focal point such as the Charles
River Bridge case,'' he says, ``although US v. Microsoft is
certainly a candidate.'' But the underlying conflict is the same,
he says _ between private property and open competition. Either all
at once or piecemeal, it will have to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1785 that the Massachusetts legislature granted a
charter to a group of businessmen who promised to build a bridge
from Charlestown to Boston to relieve traffic of the necessity of
the slow and unreliable ferry. The legislature guaranteed the
bridgebuilders tolls for 40 years _ if they succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the bridge was complete, connecting Charlestown
with Boston's North End -- a technological marvel at the time. The
money started flowing in. Curiously enough, the legislature
promptly extended the monopoly for another 30 years, or 70 years in
all. The original investors floated a public offering. The shares
soared 600 percent. (Historian Stanley Kutler has colorfully
described the saga.)
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1828 that the legislature again voted to charter a
north-south bridge _ to stand right next to the existing facility,
its Charlestown entry barely 90 yards away. Warren Bridge Corp.
would charge the same tolls as the Charles River Bridge, but only
for six years. After that the bridge would become free.
</P>
<P>
   Charles River Bridge investors _ they included Harvard College
and many other leading citizens _ immediately hired Daniel Webster
and Lemuel Shaw to sue the proprietors of the Warren Bridge. The
lawyers, among the most distinguished in the Commonwealth, argued
that creating a new bridge would destroy Charles River's ability to
collect its tolls.
</P>
<P>
   Such a ``taking'' would chill the climate for future investors
for years to come, they said. Economic progress might slow to a
crawl.
</P>
<P>
   The case rose to the US Supreme Court, where it was hampered by
dissension and delayed by the death of Chief Justice John Marshall.
Then in 1835 Marshall was succeeded by Roger Taney. The new chief
justice wore trousers instead of the traditional knee breaches, the
historian Arthur Schlesinger Jr. has noted in his classic ``The Age
of Jackson.'' ``He showed in other ways he was prepared to ignore
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1837, the Court finally found for the state against the
plaintiffs. The Warren Bridge would remain open. (It is long gone,
though a successor to the Charles River Bridge connects Boston and
Charlestown today.) ``While the rights of property are sacredly
guarded, we must not forget that the community also have rights,
and that the happiness and well being of every citizen depends on
their faithful preservation,'' Chief Justice Taney wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives, of course, were despondent. They were at odds
with the great public movement that came to be known as Jacksonian
democracy. With the Charles River Bridge decision, the Supreme
Court was seen to have gone over to the populist foe. Taney might
as well have pulverized Plymouyth Rock into gravel; the decision
``undermined the foundations of morality, confidence and truth,''
wrote one prominent jurist in New York.
</P>
<P>
   How exactly does the case reverberate today? In his paper,
Merges notes that today's property rights are much more variegated
and complicated than those of early industrial America, just like
the more complex assets they cover. Often they are held by more
than one firm.
</P>
<P>
   In one key way, however, the ``cornerstone pieces'' of
technological networks resemble the bridge. Their ownership and
control may be used to bar entry of new technologies. They may
stand in the way of competition.
</P>
<P>
   The key has to do with the principle of ``interoperability,'' he
says, as it usually applies in standards-intensive industries,
whose oversight has come to be a central problem of antitrust
policy. Microsoft has been accused of using its dominant position
in a variety of imaginative ways to absorb competitors _ or make it
difficult for them to connect up with its vast network.
</P>
<P>
   Merges surveys developments in intellectual property law,
searching for principles that may be helpful in understanding the
Microsoft debate. In copyright law, he identifies abuses he
describes as ``disproportionate leverage'' and ``user hold up'' _
tiny lock-out codes used to prevent the use of ``unauthorized''
computer game cartridges, for example; or the tendency of
standard-owners to seek to deprive those who have learned to use
their wares of the right to use their skills in other settings
(suppose you could use the standard QWERTY keyboard or a certain
structure of menu commands only on a Microsoft program?).
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Merges tentatively proposes a doctrine he labels
``technological genericide'' to deal with problems like the
ubiquity of the Microsoft Windows operating system. Stated as
bluntly as possible, such a principle borrowed from trademark law
could be interpreted to say: If you are successful enough _ if you
invent a technology that becomes a standard _ we will take your
propery right away.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to product descriptors like ``cola'' and
``yo-yo'' and ``cellophane,'' after all; why not with a popular
computer operating system? But if the law of property needs
updating, the law of takings will require some re-thinking too,
says Merges. Maybe the solution to the Microsoft problem will turn
out to have to do with publishing or ``opening up'' the propriety
source codes of its Windows operating systems, as a way of putting
them in the public domain. But there would have to be some
compensation _ unless, of course, an antitrust violation is proven.
</P>
<P>
   Merges, 40, is one of the liveliest legal minds around. For a
time he practiced law for the firm of Fenwick &AMP; West in Palo Alto,
Calif. For the last dozen years he has taught, since 1995 at Boalt
Hall, the law school of the University of California at Berkeley;
before that he was at Boston University. His paper was presented at
at a recent conference on competition and innovation in the
computer industry sponsored by Microsoft and other firms. Since
then the paper has been circulating rapidly in
(itals)samizdat.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
