<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOMA-MALEVICH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MODERN GETS TO KEEP MALEVICH WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An unusual legal settlement reached Friday will allow
the Museum of Modern Art to retain 15 works by the Russian
avant-garde artist Kazimir Malevich that it has held in safe
keeping since 1935, in exchange for a cash payment to Malevich's 31
descendants.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the payment, believed to be $5 million, the
descendants _ grandchildren, nieces and nephews in Russia and
Eastern Europe _ will receive one painting, ``Suprematist
Composition,'' which dates from 1923-1925 and which experts say is
worth about $10 million. The Modern will keep six paintings and
nine works on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the parties said they believed the agreement
to be the first settlement between a major international museum and
citizens of the former Soviet Union. (A lawyer for the Malevich
heirs said they were also discussing ownership of works held by the
Busch-Reisinger Museum at Harvard University, and more than 30
paintings at the Stedelijk Museum in Amsterdam.) The agreement with
the Modern concludes a saga that spans some of the greatest
upheavals of the 20th century, including the formation of the
Soviet Union and the rise of Nazism.
</P>
<P>
   How these paintings and drawings ultimately found their way from
1920s Leningrad to 1930s Berlin to New York's Museum of Modern Art
is a complex tale of politics, history and the daring of Alfred
Barr, the Modern's founding director. It was not until 1993, after
the breakup of the Soviet Union, that the heirs came forward with
their claims. Even though it took years to settle the two sides
said negotiations were amicable. Officials at the Modern expressed
relief that the dispute over ownership has been settled. ``It is
rare we can find an equitable solution to a complex problem,'' said
Glenn Lowry, director of the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, after holding the works for nearly three decades and no
heirs came forward to claim them, the museum made the borrowed
works part of its permanent collection. Many of the paintings have
been on view since 1935 and almost constantly since 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never clear what Malevich's intentions were or who
actually owned the art. This is a case where we were all acting in
the best interest of the artist in trying to work out an
arrangement that benefits everybody, while ensuring the public
access to Malevich's greatest works.''
</P>
<P>
   Malevich, a major 20th-century painter who was the the founder
of Suprematism, Modernism's first completely abstract painting
style, was known for his austere, simplistic forms like the iconic
painting ``White Square on White'' from 1918. He was as much a
theoretician as a painter. His works often held an underlying
political message.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1935, Barr was traveling through Europe in
search of works to include in what would become the seminal 1936
exhibition ``Cubism and Abstract Art.'' While in Germany, Barr met
with Alexander Dorner, the director of the Provinzialmuseum (which
was later renamed the Landesmuseum) in Hannover. Dorner took Barr
to the basement of his museum and revealed a cache of paintings,
drawings and charts by the already renowned pioneer of the Abstract
movement which was shaking the foundations of the art world. Dorner
had stashed the works for safe keeping, since the Nazis had banned
such art as ``degenerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr, believing that Dorner was an agent for Malevich, bought
two paintings and two drawings for the Modern's permanent
collection. Fearing that the Nazi government might stop the export
of Malevich's works, Barr later told how he smuggled the paintings
across the German-Dutch border by rolling them up and wrapping them
in his umbrella. He put the drawings in his suitcase and described
them to authorities as ``study materials.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Provinzialmuseum, Barr borrowed 17 other works for the
exhibition he was organizing. Dorner shipped them to New York using
an assumed name, officials at the Modern said. Soon after, Dorner
returned the remaining Malevich works to Hugo Haring, an architect
and friend of whom the artist entrusted with many works during
World War II. Around 1937, Dorner resigned from the
Provinzialmuseum and emigrated to the United States. Reluctant to
return Malevich's works to Nazi Germany, which had officially
denounced modern art and sold or destroyed the work of many
artists, Barr decided it would be safer to keep them at the Modern.
</P>
<P>
   But by the mid-1920s, after Stalin's rise to power, Soviet
authorities viewed Malevich's art with increasing suspicion and he
was attacked in the Soviet press because his art was thought to be
too antiproletarian and counter-revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   After years of trying to leave Russia, Malevich was granted his
first and only exit visa in 1927 to show his works in Berlin. He
took with him about 100 works for an exhibition at the Berliner
Ausstellung where an entire room was devoted to his paintings,
drawings, architectural models and theoretical writings. When the
artist was suddenly recalled to the Soviet Union in early June,
before his visa had expired, he left his art behind.
</P>
<P>
   Russian artist Naum Gabo, who knew Malevich in the 1920s, told
art historians that he believed the paintings Malevich brought to
Germany would have ``no future in the U.S.S.R. since abstract
painting was officially discouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Until his death in Leningrad in 1935, Malevich tried to return
to the West without success. But he made no efforts to bring his
art back to the Soviet Union, where it continued to be attacked by
critics because of the unorthodox nature of his work. In 1930, a
retrospective of his work closed in Kiev shortly after it opened.
Around that time he was arrested in Leningrad, detained for two
months and questioned about his work. In 1933, the ailing artist's
requests to go abroad for medical treatment were denied by Soviet
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Works that were in the custody of Haring and Dorner are still
the focus of ownership claims by the artist's relatives. Lawrence
Kaye, their lawyer, said that besides the painting and drawing that
Dorner had given to the Busch-Reisinger at Harvard, the heirs are
seeking works held by the Stedelijk Museum which had had been lent
in exchange for an annual fee payable to Haring, who had left
Berlin in 1943 and later lent and then sold the works to the
Stedlijk Museum.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves the question of what Malevich's many heirs plan to
do with their painting returned by the Modern. Will it eventually
find its way to auction? ``They haven't made a decision,'' said
Kaye. ``Right now they're just happy to have it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
