<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1422 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DADS-ANIMALS-SPI &LR;      06-18 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DADS-ANIMALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET'S HEAR IT FOR THE MR. MOMS OF THE ANIMAL KINGDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By M.L. LYKE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Your Homo sapiens dad's a real stand-up guy.
</P>
<P>
   But would he roll you up in a dung ball for protection?
</P>
<P>
   Would he undergo wrenching contractions to give birth to you and
a couple hundred siblings?
</P>
<P>
   Would he sacrifice food for a significant chunk of his limited
life span to carry you through incubation _ then stifle a gnawing
urge to eat you?
</P>
<P>
   Raise those fins and claws and pointy little talons and give it
up for the Mr. Moms of the animal kingdom, those hard-working,
overlooked Superdads who do twice the work and get half the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hear about the mothers, not the fathers,'' says
Holly Reed, associate veterinarian at Point Defiance Zoo and
Aquarium in Tacoma. ``The male has a major role in a number of
obscure species.''
</P>
<P>
   This oversight is understandable. Earth moms are easy. Most coo
and cuddle, lick and suckle, nest and nurture.
</P>
<P>
   Their mates present a more complicated picture. There are
deadbeat dads who breed-and-run. And worse.
</P>
<P>
   Sea lion dads have a nasty tendency to roll over and squish
young pups. Roaringly hungry Daddie Dearest bears have been known
to make quick meals of small cubs. And alligators, although gentle
lovers and faithful mates, will _ given half a chance _ dine on the
tasty eggs containing their young.
</P>
<P>
   But animal dads can be endearingly tender.
</P>
<P>
   One beguiling papa is the pint-size Golden Lion tamarin, a
miniature Chewbacca with a coat the color of honey. Several weeks
after mom gives birth, the little fellow takes over, carrying his
gold children nestled in the silky fur of his back.
</P>
<P>
   Even when they're big kids, the tamarins rely on dad. ``When
they get scared, they will still jump back on him,'' says zookeeper
Diane Yoshimi of Seattle's Woodland Park Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Another conscientious caretaker is the pygmy marmoset. He's one
of the tiniest primates, at approximately 4 inches and 2 ounces.
But he is a towering father figure. While mom feeds the babes, dad
carries them, watches over them, plays with them, keeps them safe,
and eventually teaches them some of the nurturing skills learned
from his own father.
</P>
<P>
   Many big, oafy bovines are true Good-Time Charlies, running off
to bachelor herds after a one-night stand. A stalwart exception is
the musk ox. These long-haired, prehistoric-looking beasts stick
around mom and babes, acting as protectors, listening to the
pitter-patter of little hooves.
</P>
<P>
   When danger's near, they alert the herd, round up the children,
then ``circle the wagons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The adult males get in big circles, shoulder-to-shoulder,
their derrieres together, facing outward,'' says Reed. ``All the
youngsters are in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene might have heartened Sigmund Freud, who once
commented: ``I cannot think of any need in childhood as strong as
the need for a father's protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Deserved or not, the Animal Dad of the Year award invariably
goes to the seahorse. His coy, colorful sweetheart injects his
pouch with up to 600 eggs, then scoots, leaving him holding the
bag. The eggs incubate in the nutritive-lined pouch until dad's
belly stretches and swells like a tiny water balloon.
</P>
<P>
   When B-Day arrives, his body begins contracting and contorting,
each spasm expelling tiny, perfectly shaped seahorses.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story with special appeal to female Homo sapiens who have
wished hellish labor pains on indifferent husbands. But it's a
story short on bonding. The seahorse's job is done as his brood
drifts away in a strong current.
</P>
<P>
   A more deserving underwater family man is the eel-like lungfish.
This Mr. Nice Guy broods fertilized eggs in his mouth and, once
they hatch, gingerly introduces his offspring to the big world.
``He guards them, keeps them in the area and, at the least sign of
danger, he opens his mouth and draws them back in,'' says exotics
biologist Bill Robertson at the Seattle Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   Male mouth brooders are role-switchers from way back.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the tiny Andean Darwin frog, a dad with a communal love
family take on child-rearing. Dandy Andy fertilizes mom's eggs, she
hip-hops off into the sunset, and he and his pals hang out, posing
for Budweiser commercials and watching over the eggs until they're
about to hatch.
</P>
<P>
   When tadpoles look imminent, the Darwinian dad dudes each grab a
clump of eggs, and slide them down their throats into their vocal
pouches. Some days later, out hop their little darlings.
</P>
<P>
   Even bug dads can do right by their women. One pungent example
is the dung beetle, who helps his mate roll up a nice sphere of
ZooDoo for her eggs. The eggs inside the ball develop into larvae,
and the larvae eat up the inside of the poop scoop, emerging feisty
and funky.
</P>
<P>
   Martyrdom's a maternal specialty, but there's one father at
Woodland Park Zoo who could major in it. His name is Abedus herbeti
_ the water bug _ and his woman's a two-timing manipulator. She
glues eggs to his back then bolts, looking for another sexy sucker
doing push-ups on a log.
</P>
<P>
   Dad is stuck carrying the eggs, looking like a miniature
porcupine, unable to eat until the last little bugger breaks its
case and swims free.
</P>
<P>
   Survival of the babes depends on suppression of the appetite.
Explains Erin Sullivan, Woodland Park Zoo bugkeeper: ``If he still
had the eating instinct during this time, he would probably feed on
the young.''
</P>
<P>
   Birddom has its share of stellar dads, too. Particularly
accommodating is the emperor penguin, a tuxedoed, 4-foot gent with
the patience of Job. Shortly after his mate lays a single egg, she
heads out into the icy unknown in search of food. She may be gone
two months or more, leaving him to incubate the egg between feet
and belly in 70-degree-below-zero Antarctic weather.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't eat until mom returns, eager to regurgitate the
months-old, half-digested fish she has collected for her loved ones
to feast on. And it isn't even Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The handsome, big-headed, red-knobbed hornbill is a regular
zippety-zoo-dad. He dotes on his woman. She seals her self away in
a nest cavity for months to incubate and hatch her three eggs. She
is totally dependent upon dad to provide meals through a tiny
opening in the cavity.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the three chicks will survive in the nest. Two will
starve. Woodland Park Zoo birdkeeper Erick Kowalczyk, who has a
videocam trained inside a hornbill nest, describes watching a
father feeding a fresh-dead nestling to its two siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a Norman Rockwell moment.
</P>
<P>
   But it's nature's way _ Father Nature's way.
</P>
<P>
   Sources for this story include ``How They Do It,'' by zoologist
Robert Wallace, ``The LaRousse Encyclopedia of Animal Life,'' and
Microsoft Encarta `98.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
