<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EIGHTH-GRADE-GRADS-NY     06-18 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EIGHTH-GRADE-GRADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THESE 8TH GRADERS, SIGNIFICANCE OF GRADUATION IS GENUINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (bl)  
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Decked out in blue caps and gowns, the eighth
graders took the stage in a sweltering gym packed with family
members and local dignitaries. The guest speaker, Alice Turkel, a
school committee member, compared them to the residents of the
mythical Lake Wobegone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every graduate at Graham and Parks is above average,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Solo, the principal of Graham and Parks, a progressive
public elementary and middle school in Cambridge, sent his students
off into the world with advice from Bob Dylan: ``Now each of us has
his own special gift; you know that was meant to be true, and if
you don't underestimate me, I won't underestimate you.'' Then Solo
hugged each of them as they walked across the stage to claim their
diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   For the 47 eighth graders, most of whom had entered Graham and
Parks in kindergarten, Thursday's graduation had loomed every bit
as large as the other, more widely publicized commencement that was
held last week across town, at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so permanent, final and definite,'' said Rachel
Philbrick, 14. ``Nothing will ever be the same. I'll never be in
this school again.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the melodrama of youth, Henrietta Oakley, 14, added,
``It's the end _ the end of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In many communities, graduations are so common at all grade
levels, starting with preschool, that they begin to lose their
significance as turning points in life. But at Graham and Parks,
leaving eighth grade is so momentous, and the school makes such a
fuss over graduation, that it becomes a time when 13- and
14-year-olds normally preoccupied with such things as, say, the
symbolism of sneaker laces and face glitter, are instead pondering
the meaning of transitions.
</P>
<P>
   It was the end of elementary school, the end of moving together
as a class through the day, the end of recess, the end of life in
the four-story red brick building where, with only 376 students, it
is possible to know just about everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, like so many other endings, graduation also marks the
beginning of other things, starting with high school. ``It's the
first step to the real world,'' said Stephane Gracia, 13.
</P>
<P>
   Isabel Yalouris, 14, said she was ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in second grade, I felt I could be in elementary
school for the rest of my life,'' she said. ``But now, whoa! I've
got to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Three nights before his graduation, Judd Bornheimer, 14, stayed
up an hour past his bedtime, reviewing his life at Graham and
Parks. ``I was just sitting in bed, in the dark, thinking about
what I've gone through,'' he said. ``My first day in kindergarten,
I cried, `Mom and Dad, don't leave me!' I was very shy, very
family-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   These days no one would call Judd shy. With his teachers
commending his kindness to others, he shared the Graham and Parks
community service award today with a classmate, Daniel Mehr. Judd
has his own call-in show on a Cambridge cable television station.
He is a lineman on the Warriors, a Pop Warner football team. He has
overcome some major obstacles, including the breakup of his
parents' marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm becoming my own person,'' Judd said.
</P>
<P>
   This has naturally created conflicts with his mother, Carole
Bellew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been disagreeing on a lot of things,'' Judd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tie my sneakers on the fourth lace,'' he said. ``She
wants me to tie them on the sixth lace. She doesn't understand what
I'm going through.''
</P>
<P>
   Ketna Julmeus, 13, who is the president of the eighth grade
class and who arrived from Haiti five years ago, feels the same way
about her father. ``He doesn't understand American culture,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   While many of Ketna's friends are exploring their newly found
interest in the opposite sex, Ketna says her father has decreed
that she may not have a boyfriend before she is 20. That does not
stop her from daydreaming. ``What would it be like if I had a
boyfriend?'' she said. ``Would it affect my schoolwork?''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two percent of the students at Graham and Parks _ the
school is named for Rosa Parks and Saundra Graham, an
African-American Cambridge community organizer _ are white and 58
percent are African-American, Asian or Hispanic. They are the sons
and daughters of bookkeepers and cabdrivers as well as doctors and
college professors. They boast about the diversity of their class.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Graham and Parks, like childhood itself, is no utopia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ridiculed from kindergarten to third grade,'' Daniel
Mehr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was big,'' said Daniel who, at 6 feet 2 inches tall, towers
over his classmates. ``And I was always somewhat chubby. In the
beginning, I went to the teacher. But then I said, `What the heck,
they're going to keep doing it, I might as well get used to it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel has since found a circle of friends who share his
interest in math and science, sailing and laser tag. But he will be
leaving the group in September. His family is moving to the suburbs
so that Daniel can go to the nationally acclaimed Lexington High
School.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his classmates are going on to Cambridge Rindge and
Latin, the public high school here, with 2,500 students. ``We're
going to a huge high school where we're going to know nobody,''
Henrietta Oakley said.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Wisner, 14, said he wished he could join the handful of his
classmates who will be going to private schools. ``Rindge is too
big,'' he said. ``You could get lost. A private school is more of a
community.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ben said he worried that there could be gang members at the
high school. While gangs have not made inroads at Graham and Parks,
he said he had been fending off their approaches in the
neighborhood. Ben, who plays basketball, soccer and golf, said he
had no interest in joining a gang.
</P>
<P>
   Emma Alexander, 14, has other worries. ``The older kids are big,
and tall,'' said Emma, a star soccer player who is 5 feet 2 inches
tall.
</P>
<P>
   It is not only high school that Emma and her classmates are
worried about getting lost in. ``We're told we can be anything and
do anything,'' Isabel Yalouris said. But she already knows that
reality may be somewhat different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be an actress,'' Isabel said. ``But you can go to
Hollywood and be a nothing. You can fall through the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan McCray was listening to Isabel, Emma and Ben talk moments
before graduation. Ms. McCray had taught the eighth graders
humanities. She had been in the school, watching them emerge, since
they were in fourth grade. ``It's the end of childhood,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kids,'' Isabel said. ``We're older kids, but we're still
kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
