<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is He Getting Ready To Return to Belgrade? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As NATO troops rolled into Kosovo last week and Serbian troops
rolled out, Milan Panic, who took time out from running ICN
Pharmaceuticals to serve briefly as Yugoslavia's prime minister in
1992, shuttled around European capitals and the United Nations. His
goal was to get rid of Slobodan Milosovic and rebuild Yugoslovia
under a democratic leader, perhaps by the name of Milan Panic.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at the United Nations last week, Panic said
weighty things like, ``We have a very serious legal, political and
practical problem.'' He could have been referring to ICN as well as
the country. ICN, based in Costa Mesa, Calif., watched the Yugoslav
government confiscate its Belgrade plant in February.
</P>
<P>
   Panic evidently thinks that what's good for ICN is good for
Yugoslavia, leadership included. ``Officially, Milan would say he's
not interested in running the country,'' said Eugene Melnitchenko,
a health care analyst with Sutro &AMP; Co. in Los Angeles. But, he
added, ``If given the opportunity, he would do so.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Adelson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UBS Is for Art Lovers  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, many wealthy collectors thronged Art Basel, the
reknowned 20th-century art fair, which runs through Monday. Among
them were Charles Schwab; Arthur Fleischer, the New York takeover
lawyer; Mick Flick, a Daimler-Benz executive; Achille Maramotti,
the owner of Max Mara, the clothing company, and Jochen Holy, a
former owner of Hugo Boss.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough competing for attention with all the art. But UBS,
with three art advisory offices in Europe, sees the fair as a
chance to expand that business, which includes trading,
transporting and storing art for those who have at least $675,000
in assets with the bank.
</P>
<P>
   So under Karl Schweizer, the head of art banking at UBS, the
company built a lounge in the form of an Italian villa (with faux
marble walls, gilt borders and a fountain), where its private
banking clients could sip Moet and nibble on aged Parmesan and
Parma ham. Groups of 50 were treated to dinner and music in UBS's
own red-velvet restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Americans were especially welcome, since UBS plans to open an
art banking office in New York this year, competing with Citibank.
</P>
<P>
   Does the wooing work? ``Ask me after the fair, and I'll tell
you,'' Schweizer said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Judith H. Dobrzynski &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There Goes the Island? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The battle among the millionaires who live on Fisher Island _
home to various retired chief executives, the financier Bennett S.
LeBow, Oprah Winfrey and Mel Brooks _ continues over condomium
development on this exclusive redoubt a short ferry ride from Miami
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   On June 10, John Melk, the Chicago investor who paid more than
$50 million last year for development rights, marshaled the votes
to suspend Isadore and Maxine Pines, his most ardent opponents,
from membership in the Fisher Island Club. Their offense: wearing
``Save Fisher Island'' T-shirts. The Pineses say that Melk's plan
to build 315 million-dollar-plus condominiums will cause
overcrowding, delays for golfers and long waits for the ferry.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents of the island's condominium associations struck
back by electing Pines, ex-chairman of Hebrew National, to the
board of the Fisher Island Community Association.
</P>
<P>
   That infuriated Melk, who says he is building only about half
the number of condominiums allowed. While Melk has started
construction, Pines has continued to put up ``Save Fisher Island''
billboards, pass out leaflets and hire people to picket the
island's sales office.
</P>
<P>
   Charles V. Bagli &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some On-the-Job Research &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Uwe E. Reinhardt, a leading health policy pundit, professor of
political economy at Princeton University and headliner on the
lecture circuit, is the latest academic luminary to be recruited as
a board member by an industry on his radar screen. He recently
joined the board at Triad Hospitals Inc., a group spun off last
month by Columbia-HCA Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhardt, 60, hardly your corporate conformist, is quite the
zingermeister, having described managed-care moguls, for example,
as ``bounty hunters'' who live by squeezing money from doctors and
hospitals. After spurning several other offers, he signed up with
Triad, a 33-hospital group based in Dallas, much more for
experience and insight than for money, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhardt said he wanted to see how for-profit hospitals look at
ground level, rather than from the policy wonk perspective that he
compares to ``flying at 37,000 feet.'' He will get $18,000 a year
plus $1,500 a meeting _ no great sum, he said, after accounting for
board homework, travel to meetings and possibly missing lecture
gigs. Putting Princeton first, he skipped the first Triad board
meeting last month to supervise final exams.
</P>
<P>
   Milt Freudenheim &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
