<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1427 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMIT-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      06-18 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMIT-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT REACHED ON DEPLOYMENT OF RUSSIAN TROOPS IN KOSOVO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional ending) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ The United States and Russia finally reached
an agreement Friday on deployment of Kremlin troops as part of the
international force occupying Kosovo, almost completely on lines
long demanded by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   After three days of negotiations in Helsinki, Finland, Russia
abandoned its key plea for a separate zone for its troops. A
Russian force of 2,850 soldiers will be spread among three other
sectors of the war-torn province already assigned to troops from
the United States, Germany and France. The Russians will be part of
a total force of about 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The chief concession to the Russians was that a contingent of an
additional 750 of its soldiers will be deployed at the airport in
Pristina, the provincial capital, where they will serve primarily
as maintenance and security personnel. Russia also will have a
representative at each NATO command center involved in the
peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which is expected to be approved Saturday by
NATO's political arm, is the final step in implementing the peace
plan that ended the alliance's 78-day air attack on the forces of
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Fallout from the Balkan conflict was the focus of the opening
day of the annual economic summit here as leaders from the most
powerful democracies debated aid for southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The key U.S. objective in the Helsinki talks was not to give
Russian forces control over a section of the largely Muslim
province which it might use to lever advantage for the Serb
minority, who are fellow-Slavs and primarily Christian Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no partition here,'' said a senior White House
official traveling with President Clinton in Europe. The
administration went out of its way not to gloat over its success in
the talks even while pointing out that the key NATO aim of unified
command under alliance control was maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel quite good about this,'' Clinton said near midnight
outside the imposing Cologne cathedral. ``I think it will work.''
Clinton was told of the agreement as he attended a summit-opening
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was announced in the Finnish capital by Defense
Secretary William Cohen and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and their Russian counterparts, Marshall Igor Sergeyev and Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev refused to directly deal with questions from reporters
about why Russia had abandoned the demand of President Boris
Yeltsin for a zone of its own to police. Sergeyev said only that an
``alternative solution'' had been found.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he trusted the Russian leader to abide by the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is, every time I've had an understanding
with Boris Yeltsin he's kept it,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin is to attend the final day of the summit Sunday and then
hold a private meeting with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said that one or two Russian battalions
will be stationed with a U.S. force at Kosovska Kamenica, one or
two Russian battalions with Germans at Malisevo and one Russian
battalion with French forces at Lausa.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. official said the White House hoped the presence of
Russian forces would convince Serbs left in Kosovo not to flee the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the Russian troops would be able to join the
peacekeeping force quickly, ``a matter of a day or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the Russian troops at Pristina airport, the U.S.
official said, NATO forces will oversee air traffic in and out of
the field. The surprise arrival of about 200 Russian soldiers at
the facility last weekend sparked a standoff, which led Clinton and
Yeltsin to send their military chiefs to Helsinki to negotiate the
overall Russian role in the NATO-led occupation force.
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO will lay out orders for all troops in KFOR (for
``Kosovo force``), they will be relayed to Russian forces by a
Russian commander _ a more direct NATO-to-Russia command
arrangement than is used in the Russian peacekeeping force in
Bosnia-Herzegovina, where the alliance also is in charge.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Friday, Cohen said he was prepared to leave the
talks without a final agreement. But late in the afternoon the U.S.
defense chief postponed a trip to NATO headquarters in Brussels,
Belgium, to remain in the Finnish capital and press the agreement
to completion.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Sergeyev at one point in the day said a final deal
might have to be put off until the meeting Sunday between Clinton
and Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Clinton and other leaders, gathered by the
Rhine for their annual session, awaited a breakthrough in the
Helsinki talks.
</P>
<P>
   Decrying the ``wholesale slaughter'' in Kosovo being revealed as
Serb troops withdraw and NATO forces move in, Clinton expressed
concern about any missteps in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not make any decisions which will in any way, shape or
form undermine the ability of the Kosovars or the willingness of
the Kosovars to come home,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair said that only now was the
``full horror'' coming to light and further justifying NATO's
78-day bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the daunting task of rebuilding Kosovo that lies ahead,
Clinton expressed confidence that a multi-ethnic society could be
established in the heavily Muslim province of what remains of the
former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing,'' Clinton said, ``is to get the truth out
and make all the people safe.''
</P>
<P>
   As he arrived in Cologne for the summit session, Russian Prime
Minister Sergei Stepashin warned that his nation, which has
longstanding ties with Serbia, wanted an even-handed approach to
peacekeeping in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must be no double-standard approach toward the
settlement of the situation when some (ethnic Albanian) refugees
are coming back home while others have to flee their places,''
Stepashin said of the large number of ethnic Serbs who are leaving
Kosovo. ``If there is a peace, it should be a peace for all.'' The
White House would not comment on renewed reports that Clinton has
signed an order directing the CIA to attempt to destabilize
Milosevic's government. But Berger did little to discourage
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been supporting the opposition of President Milosevic
quite openly for some time _ independent media, opposition
parties,'' Berger said. ``And I would expect that would only
intensify.''
</P>
<P>
   The summit leaders have reached basic agreement on the design,
but not the cost, of a post-war reconstruction package for Kosovo
and southeastern Europe. The key points are:
</P>
<P>
   _ A short-term aid package for Kosovo, to provide food and
housing for returning refugees and immediate repairs to roads and
other components of the infrastructure battered by Serb forces and
the NATO bombardment. A determination of the exact amount needed
was left until the growing scope of damage can be assessed. Berger
called for a conference of donor nations ``as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A longer-term rebuilding program, including reconstruction of
a civil society, including the creation of a police force and
holding of local elections.
</P>
<P>
   _ An even more expansive, and possibly more expensive, program
to aid the poorer Balkan nations, especially those that cooperated
with NATO during the air strikes by accepting refugees and basing
of NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frontline states'' such as Albania and Macedonia ``in many
ways carried the heaviest burdens of this war,'' in which their
economies and fragile democracies were strained, said Clinton's
national security adviser, Samuel Berger. ``We now have a very
serious obligation to try to help them build a broader future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other developments at the annual meeting, leaders:
</P>
<P>
   _ Approved a proposal that could dramatically reduce the
government debt strangling hope of economic growth in many of the
poorest nations. Funding would require the International Monetary
Fund to sell gold reserves, a move that could not go forward
without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   _ Backed a series of steps to require better government
financial reporting and regulation, in a bid to stave off future
fiscal crises such as the economic slide in eastern Asia three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
