<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS WAGE A WAR OF WORDS OVER THE ROLE OF DISSENT IN ROMAN
CATHOLIC THEOLOGY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Canada)   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, Cardinal Bernard Law of Boston denounced the
Catholic Theological Society of America, the nation's leading
professional society of Roman Catholic theologians, as ``a
wasteland'' for its criticism of official church teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Avery Dulles, an elder statesman of Catholic theology
and an outspoken supporter of the papacy and its policies, later
seconded the judgment, wondering in print whether church
authorities could even ``recognize the CTSA as Catholic.''
</P>
<P>
   Dulles' opinion, issued after he had read the proceedings of the
society's 1997 convention, was sharply challenged by officers of
the CTSA and other theologians. But no one disputed his conclusion
that the gap between the theological community and Catholic
authorities revealed ``severe fault lines in contemporary American
Catholicism.''
</P>
<P>
   Not just American Catholicism, one might add. Cardinal Joseph
Ratzinger, the Vatican's custodian of doctrinal orthodoxy, has
declared war on the church's theologians for some years now. Of
course, tension is inevitable between the religious authorities
responsible for preserving their faith's tenets and theologians
trained to probe life's knottiest questions, and there will always
be some theologians whose speculations cannot be reconciled with
the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But what does it mean for a church when high officials perceive
those trained to explicate the faith as, in fact, prime threats to
it? It is rather like an airline that accuses its pilots of
deliberately trying to crash the planes.
</P>
<P>
   One sign that this dysfunctional state of affairs is not
immutable was the presence of Dulles himself at the podium of the
latest convention of the Catholic Theological Society of America,
held last weekend in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   He was there to engage in an extended public dialogue on ``The
Nature and Authority of Doctrine'' with the Rev. Richard A.
McCormick, a theologian of equal stature, who has repeatedly
contended that the Vatican has short-circuited theological
discussion in an effort to shore up an unpersuasive teaching on
contraception and related sexual issues.
</P>
<P>
   Their exchange was part of the meeting's general theme:
development of doctrine. For centuries, theories of doctrinal
development have been offered to explain how the church could come
to promulgate beliefs not explicitly stated in Scripture or taught
in apostolic times while still remaining faithful to what was
revealed in Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   But the subtext of the two theologians' exchange was the
legitimacy of dissent from official teaching as part of the process
of doctrinal development. The two men, both Jesuit priests, shared
considerable common ground, including knowledge of the traditional
set of categories used to analyze church pronouncements.
</P>
<P>
   Dulles, for instance, did not deny that dissent was sometimes
justified, but it should be ``rare, reluctant and respectful,'' he
said. His stance was clearly developed against the backdrop of
contemporary culture _ a post-Christian, secular culture, he called
it, that puts ``extreme pressure on the church'' and that will
wield an ``enormous influence'' over theologians unless it is
resisted.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick agreed that official teaching should enjoy the
presumption of truth and that dissenting views should not be
presented as though on an equal footing with the authorized ones.
</P>
<P>
   But dissent is nonetheless essential, he said, if the church is
to correct its errors and develop its doctrines, especially ``when
the church is irresponsible and authoritarian.'' McCormick's stance
was also developed against a particular backdrop _ what he
described as a Vatican pattern of composing official documents
behind closed doors and raising particular schools of thought into
the universal norm for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Are the unity of the church and the credibility of its teachings
imperiled by public theological dissent, as Dulles warned? Or are
they even more imperiled by a refusal to alter an untenable
teaching, as McCormick suggested?
</P>
<P>
   After a dozen or more other theologians added their own comments
and questions, Margaret O'Gara, a theologian from University of St.
Michael's College in Toronto, summed up much of the discussion:
Both speakers regarded authority as a gift, she said, but two areas
of difference kept coming up:
</P>
<P>
   One was how much significance ought to be given to the actual
faith and convictions of the whole church, and not just its
governing ranks. The other was how large a place should be given to
past errors or reversals, to changes over the centuries or even
official apologies for past evils, when theologians embark on
analyzing the development of doctrine and the role of dissent.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting did not dodge examples of past teachings that have
been reversed or disavowed, however difficult they make it to
portray doctrinal development as a relatively seamless process.
</P>
<P>
   The use of coercion to suppress heresy, the official defense of
slavery, widespread teachings about Jews and Judaism, the doctrine
of ``no salvation outside the church,'' the medieval prohibition of
lending money at interest, all these and more were the hard cases
that came up in the course of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers proposed new theories that might accommodate
even these dramatic changes without abandoning the church's claim
to be a trustworthy teacher of constant doctrine. Most of the
theories seemed to win a moderate interest, none of them a clear
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   A consensus appeared stronger, however, when it came to
suggestions about the kind of virtues Catholic theologians needed
in addressing these issues: truthfulness, civility, courage,
prudence, humility before the tradition, willingness to correct
one's colleagues and a deep-down trust in the church's future.
</P>
<P>
   As the meeting wound down, Dulles himself seemed satisfied that
these virtues had been well represented.
</P>
</TEXT>
