<HEADER>
A1438 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WOMENSCUP19-COX     06-18 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMENSCUP19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'It seems like we've arrived'
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Women's soccer is a mere blip on the
radar screen of the world's biggest sport, which still struggles to
gain a mainstream footing in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the voracious American appetite for big sporting events,
plus the emergence of women's team sports after the 1996 Olympics,
has dovetailed into optimism that the third Women's World Cup can
help scale both barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Today's opening matches will be played to full houses. But
realizing FIFA President Sepp Blatter's declaration that ``the
future of football is feminine'' figures to be a considerable
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is happening in the right place and at the
right time,'' Denmark coach Jorgen Hvidemose said. ``We just really
believed in the tournament,'' said Marla Messing, a leading
executive of the men's World Cup '94 committee who is president and
chief executive officer of the Women's World Cup. ``In 1994, people
thought we were crazy, that we couldn't fill the stadiums or
interest the American public. But this country gets up for big
events.''
</P>
<P>
   And the American proclivity for loving winners doesn't hurt,
either. At a Wednesday news conference at a New York City hotel,
almost all the snippets in a promotional video were of the U.S.
team. Apparently, little footage exists of the others, including
defending champion Norway, one of the favorites with the U.S. and
China. ``The demands have been a burden for this team to a point,
but you can't do much about it,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said.
``That's just where the sport is. We're trying to be a seed for the
other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   The present scenario is a far cry from the ``seven or so''
people U.S. midfielder Michelle Akers recalls greeting the U.S.
women at John F. Kennedy Airport in the fall of 1991 when they
brought back the first World Cup trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were excited about where the game was at that point,'' said
Akers, who had 10 goals in that tournament in China. ``Even now, it
seems like we've arrived, but there still remains so much to be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the success of this World Cup depends on the results of
the U.S. team. Months before the draw, the U.S. schedule was
already filled in, placing the Americans in six of the seven venues
_ if they reach the finals _ to maximize ticket sales and media
interest across the country.
</P>
<P>
   If they trip, no Plan B has been revealed for what would be a
severe drop in attendance and ratings. But an upset of America
might do wonders in the rest of the world, where soccer is
considered a macho sport.
</P>
<P>
   The respected ``Encyclopedia of Football,'' a hefty 648 pages
thick, contains just one page on the entire subject of women's
soccer, and that's limited to the two previous World Cup and the
1996 Olympic competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, Germany and Italy are the exceptions among the
powerhouse nations in men's soccer in developing women's teams.
Because of liberal social attitudes toward women in Scandinavia,
Norway, Sweden and Denmark have been established for at least two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Even in England, which lauds itself as the ``home of football,''
a full-time women's coach was appointed for the first time only
last year, right after the national team finished last in its World
Cup qualifying group.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, playing in its first World Cup, began its women's team
last year, and nearly half of its players were raised in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Defender Susy Mora, who grew up in Los Angeles and plays at
Southern Cal, said perceptions about women playing soccer are
unspoken in her parents' homeland, but she knows that the cultural
belief is that they don't fit in. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't hear them say that, but you can feel it,'' Mora said.
``It's starting to change, but we have to do well here and work
hard to keep this going.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
