<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1441 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLOCK-OBIT-REACTION     06-18 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLOCK-OBIT-REACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS POLITICAL GIANT LEFT LASTING MARK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Legendary, great and grand. Gritty and
iron-fisted.
</P>
<P>
   Visionary and courageous. Rowdy and raucous.
</P>
<P>
   Vesuvian.
</P>
<P>
   Stubbornly independent, sometimes loved and other times loathed.
</P>
<P>
   Giant among Texas leaders and passionate lover of all things
Texan.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and state leaders all across Texas struggled Friday
to describe the essence of former Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, who died at
home Friday at the age of 69 just five months after retiring from
four decades of public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no words big enough to capture Bob Bullock,'' said
Gov. George W. Bush. ``Bob Bullock was the largest Texan of our
time, as great and grand as the state he loved. Almost everything
about modern Texas bears his imprint ... from the water we drink to
the schools and universities that educate our children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to put in words how I feel,'' Bush added. ``I'm sad
and I feel like I really lost a great friend.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the two ``wept together'' when they visited the night
before his death, tears that were shed, in part, over Bullock's
publicly expressed desire to see Bush elected president. ``He told
me to go win,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Houston Mayor Bob Lanier, who had been friends with
Bullock for more than a quarter of a century, described him this
way:
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything else, he was just a man. He was kind of the
total man. The person that loved Texas, the guy who lived a rowdy
and raucous life and then straightened up, the guy who'd get
knocked down and then back up and come to the fray. A smart guy. A
guy who got things done. But then all but none of those. It's just
kind of the aggregate image of Bob Bullock as a bigger-than-life
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, who succeeded Bullock at the
helm of the Texas Senate in January, said Bullock ``loved Texas
with every fiber of his iron fist and kind heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bob Bullock I knew was a kind-hearted, compassionate and
gentle man,'' Perry added. ``Texas is, and always will be, a better
and stronger place because of him. ... He truly broke the mold and
there will never be another Texas leader like him.''
</P>
<P>
   He was as infamous for his mercurial temper _ which often left
employees and other elected officials quaking _ as he was for his
heavy-handed, back-door deal-making in the Senate, a double-edged
sword that left some folks grumbling they'd been left out of the
process while also getting legislation passed.
</P>
<P>
   So forceful of a leader was Bullock, that his death had some
pondering whether the familiar ``God Bless Texas'' refrain that
punctuated the end of his speeches wasn't more of an order than a
personal prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that when he said that he was not just suggesting that
God (should) bless Texas but that God already had,'' chuckled
fellow Democrat and former Attorney General Jim Mattox.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's death undoubtedly will lead to embellishments of his
prowess and power, Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, countered Republican Sen. David Sibley of Waco, whose
grin and recollection of having been at the receiving end of
Bullock's temper a time or two suggested there would be no need to
embellish any tales.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never pretended to be anything he wasn't,'' Lanier said.
``If he had a wart he'd show it to you and then brag his was bigger
than yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bullock became well known in his later years for
publicly acknowledging his personal foibles, from his struggle with
alcoholism to his multiple marriages.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979 he issued a press release about his pending hemorrhoid
surgery, stating that he would not display surgical scars, which he
was certain ``nosey'' members of the Capitol press corps would want
to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was smart, he was rowdy and you know he could be raucous,''
Lanier said. ``But he loved this state and the state loved him
back.''
</P>
<P>
   He was as effective a politician as Texas has even known, others
chimed in, and deft at maneuvering people into compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Bullock was one of the great characters in Texas
history,'' said Robert B. Sloan Jr., president of Baylor
University, where Bullock received his law degree in 1958. ``In
fact, he was a master at striking deals, finding common ground and
making coalitions with very different kinds of people. He was
powerful in the best sense of the word. He knew power and was not
afraid to wield it, yet he used it for the benefit of all Texans.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor Chancellor Herbert H. Reynolds, whose friendship with
Bullock dates back to their days in the Air Force, said Bullock
also made a lasting contribution to Baylor, the state ``and even
our nation as one of the most unique and strongest leaders of our
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Garza, chairman of the Railroad Commission, said Bullock
ranks with the greatest leaders in Texas history and called him
``the gold standard for public service.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sam) Houston, (Stephen F.) Austin, (President) Johnson and
(Sam) Rayburn better make room at the table for Bullock,'' Garza
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was Vesuvian and seemingly contradictory, but always
passionate about his love for Texas,'' Garza added.
</P>
<P>
   One of those seeming contradictions occurred in 1993. A
supporter of women's rights, Bullock angered some women when he
suggested that Sen. Judith Zaffirini, D-El Paso, could be more
effective in passing legislation if she ``cut her skirt off about
six inches and put on some high heels.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaffirrini said she wasn't bothered by his comment because she
took it for the teasing he intended it and that his actions _
appointing her to important committees _ spoke more.
</P>
<P>
   And he once told her, during some intense negotiations on a
higher education bill, that she was ``so mean (she) made his second
wife look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Zaffirini said she would much rather have been the object of
Bullock's teasing than his wrath, something with which she, too,
was familiar. Her strategy for dealing with those scoldings stemmed
from a survival tactic she had learned from admonishments of the
principal, Mother Andrew, at Ursala Academy, where she attended
high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd look him in the eye and just keep saying to myself, `Yes,
Mother Andrew. No, Mother Andrew. Whatever you say, Mother
Andrew,''' Zaffirini said.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's death brought kind words from one of his most ardent
enemies during his early days in state government, former Lt. Gov.
Ben Barnes, who blocked Bullock's appointment to the then-Board of
Insurance and sparked intensely personal feuding between the two
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``For over 40 years, Bob gave himself, his energy and his soul
to the leadership of this state,'' Barnes said. ``I, as all Texans,
am grateful to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Charming, highly energetic, and sometimes volcanic in his
language, Bush said Bullock's success was based in large part on
his unpredictable personality.
</P>
<P>
   And he was vintage Bullock till the end. Describing the Democrat
as ``lucid and funny'' and aware of those around him when Bush
visited the Bullock home Thursday evening, Bush said: ``He was
Bullock. He was battling to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mattox and several other leaders said they have no doubt
that wherever Bullock is now he probably already is taking charge
and barking orders.
</P>
<P>
   Should weather turn foul during memorial services Sunday and a
crash of thunder punctuate graveside ceremonies, it most likely is
a sign, Mattox said, ``Bullock's probably already got his gavel
working there.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Billie Carr, a longtime Bullock friend and Democratic Party
stalwart in Houston: ``Wherever he is, he's probably saying, `This
place is in a helluva mess and it needs to be organized.' I suspect
wherever he is, it will have to be redone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
