<SLUG> BC-BKC-ODOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URI BACKS AWAY FROM ODOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lamar Odom's basketball career has taken several dramatic twists
and turns since he enrolled at the University of Rhode Island two
years ago. Now it appears URI has brought its role in the sophomore
sensation's ever-changing story to a close.
</P>
<P>
   In a Friday, URI officials said they will not seek restoration
of Odom's eligibility, voided when the forward from Queens, N.Y.,
made himself eligible for the NBA draft a month ago and
subsequently signed with an agent.
</P>
<P>
   URI's move Friday reverses the school's announcement on Thursday
that it would petition the NCAA to have Odom's eligibility
restored. And that followed an announcement on Wednesday by URI
coach Jerry DeGregorio that Odom was staying in the draft pool but
had merely sought new representation.
</P>
<P>
   Under NCAA rules, underclassmen players who sign with agents
forfeit their eligibility. But Odom, after participating in a
workout with the Vancouver Grizzlies, began expressing interest in
returning to school and subsequently severed ties with agent Jeff
Klein on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's statement, URI officials said they agreed to help
Odom petition the NCAA prepare his petition and make the request
for eligibility ``if it is determined that the facts and
circumstances were sufficient to warrant taking such action.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The university conducted this review within this week and it
has determined that the facts did not justify going forward with
the request,'' the statement went on to say. ``As a result, the
university will not file a request for restoration of his
eligibility.''
</P>
<P>
   URI athletic director Ron Petro said in the statement, ``Due to
the high profile of this student athlete, we made every effort to
review this matter carefully. Lamar was a major reason for our
success last season and we wish him well as he moves to the NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom was also quoted in the statement, saying, ``I have great
memories of my time at URI. I want to thank all the URI fans for
their support. In many ways, this has been the best year of my
life. Coach (Jerry) DeGregorio, the rest of the coaching staff, Ron
Petro and everyone at URI has made me feel at home. It has been
time that I'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the events surrounding Odom will affect his draft status
remains to be seen. He has been projected as a top-10 pick and
missed a scheduled workout with the Chicago Bulls, who have the
first overall pick in the draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
