<SLUG> BC-G7-DEBT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEALTHIEST NATIONS AGREE TO BILLIONS IN DEBT RELIEF FOR POOREST
NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany _ Leaders from the Group of Seven wealthiest
nations agreed Friday to cut the debt burden of the world's poorest
countries in what they described as a decisive push to alleviate
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac of France said the relief for mainly
African countries could total about $65 billion. But Gene Sperling,
the national economic adviser to President Clinton, said the amount
could approach $90 billion if other creditors join the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Some loans would be canceled outright, and mechanisms would be
put in place to evaluate other debt relief, tied to economic
reforms in the indebted countries in future years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If other countries were to share in this effort, then a full
70 percent of the $127 billion owed by qualifying states could be
relieved,'' Sperling said. He estimated that 33 countries could
benefit, including Ethiopia, Niger, Nicaragua, Tanzania, Uganda,
Ghana, Rwanda and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   Some charitable organizations have argued for more debt
forgiveness, but the lenders oppose setting a precedent of wiping
out all of a lender's debt.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the United States, Britain, France, Germany,
Italy, Canada and Japan said the resources made available by the
debt relief should be used for health and educational programs,
particularly AIDS programs in Africa. Congress would be asked to
approve some elements of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came on the first day of a three-day summit here
devoted largely to Kosovo and the troubled relations with Moscow
resulting from the Kosovo War. The Russian prime minister, Sergei
Stepashin, joined the seven leaders after their debt discussions,
and President Boris Yeltsin is expected Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, the U.S. national security adviser, said the debt
relief plan would have ``an enormous impact on poorer countries,
perhaps more than any other single action taken by the developed
countries at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   But the reality seemed rather more uncertain. Similar promises
in the past have proved agonizingly slow in application. Many of
the affected states are unable to meet their debts in any event, so
they will not abruptly find themselves with more money. And without
stable governance, the impact of debt relief on society may be
slight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are demonstrating we are active and concerned, but unless
we really invest in establishing civil society in these countries,
we may be pouring water into sand,'' Norbert Walter, the chief
economist at Deutsche Bank, said. ``Opening agricultural markets in
Europe and the United States might have provided more real help to
these states.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the decision clearly reflected a sense of urgency born of
the realization that a program of debt relief for the poorest
countries set in motion in 1996 had proved too limited, stringent
and slow-moving for the more than 400 million people potentially
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Under the extended plan announced Friday, the Group of Seven
countries will cancel between $15 billion and $20 billion of
official development assistance debt _ money lent on easy terms.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac said that members of the Group of 7 would bear the cost
of debt relief equitably among themselves; the International
Monetary Fund and World Bank, whose main shareholders are the
wealthy nations, made most of the lending, for development.
</P>
<P>
   Further relief will be provided by international financial
institutions like the IMF and by forgiving trade debts backed by
government guarantees. Businesses that have made loans to
qualifying states will also be asked to make similar concessions.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the criteria for qualifying for relief will be eased
and the procedure accelerated, allowing a current list of 26
countries that had secured debt cuts under the 1996 plan to be
expanded to 33 states. The newly qualified nations include Benin,
Ghana, Honduras, Laos and Senegal.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sperling took the example of Mozambique, which is about to
qualify for relief under the plan, to illustrate its effectiveness,
suggesting that the 30 percent of the country's resources that is
currently used for debt service would be cut to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would free up $30 million of debt service per year,
allowing the health budget to be increased by 50 percent,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Oxfam, one of several charitable organizations that has been
lobbying for more sweeping debt relief, said in a statement that
even with the new measures, Mozambique would be paying twice as
much a year in debt as for primary education.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   What seems clear is that unless they are accompanied by
determined programs for the relief of poverty, the establishment of
the rule of law and sharply improved standards of government, the
measures are unlikely to have a significant impact in Africa, the
continent principally targeted.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would be financed to a small degree by the possible
sale of close to 10 perkent of the gold reserves of the IMF Earlier
discussions of such a move by finance ministers worried some
traders who believe the price of gold could be further depressed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The leaders said the IMF should finance the program partly
through ``use of interest on the proceeds of a limited and
cautiously phased sale of up to 10 million ounces of the IMF's gold
reserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Those sales have to be approved by Congress and the IMF itself.
At current prices, they would yield about $2.8 billion, providing a
portion of the whole program.
</P>
<P>
   Turning from the world's poorest regions to the general state of
the world economy, the leaders approved a six-point plan aimed at
stabilizing world financial markets in the wake of the contagious
crises that spread through Asia, Russia and Latin America in 1997
and last year.
</P>
<P>
   The measures fell short of many of the more radical proposals
made since the dangers of a fast-moving globalized economy became
evident. These had included regulating hedge funds, introducing
forms of capital control and vastly increasing the powers of the
IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the leaders decided to create a so-called Financial
Stability Forum bringing together international regulators and
authorities from the Group of Seven; provide new IMF credit lines
to protect developing countries with sound policies; increase the
standards demanded of governments and financial institutions;
impose capital charges on banks that better reflect the risk of
lending, and prepare programs for rapid IMF and World Bank support
of the most needy in any future crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has proved crazy of late,'' President Chirac said,
alluding to Kosovo and the financial crises in the same breath.
``We are taking measures to create a world that is more stable,
more generous and more courageous.''
</P>
<P>
   His words reflected a sort of millennium fever that seemed to
infect the leaders as they proclaimed the arrival of a braver, new
world. The relief at the end of the fighting in Kosovo and, late in
the day, at an accord on a Russian troop deployment with the NATO
forces in the province was palpable.
</P>
<P>
   But President Clinton was obliged to deal with a mundane and
contentious reality in a meeting with Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi. Although the president proclaimed himself ``thrilled'' with
Japan's surprisingly strong first-quarter economic performance, he
warned of sharp tensions over United States imports of Japanese
steel.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has threatened to impose quotas on the Japanese steel
industry, and Obuchi expressed concern at what he called the
``growing protectionist sentiment'' in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton told Obuchi that steel imports, which have recently
declined somewhat, would have to drop further and said that he
might not be able to prevent a congressional imposition of quotas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point that was made to the prime minister was that they
need to get their imports down to pre-crisis levels because this is
a bill that he may not be able to sustain a veto on,'' said Joe
Lockhart, the presidential spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   After the Asian financial crisis curtailed Japanese steel
exports to its neighbors, Japan's exports to the United States
soared to four million tonnes last year from 2.8 million tonnes in
1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
