A1450 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-CAPSULES19-CO     06-18 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-CAPSULES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women's World Cup capsules
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROUP A
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK, NIGERIA, N. KOREA, UNITED STATES
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have a relatively easy group. Their toughest match
should be today's opener against Denmark, a respectable club but
not in the same league with Scandinavian rival Norway. Mia Hamm,
Tiffeny Milbrett and Cindy Parlow are unparalleled up front, but
the U.S. team has been suspect to teams with equal skill and speed,
especially on the counterattack. Nigeria has great individual skill
and flair at some positions, especially from forward ``Marvelous''
Mercy Akide. Nigeria beat China in a closed-door match earlier this
week, but it does not have enough experience. North Korea is in the
World Cup for the first time and has given China a good challenge
occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: United States, Denmark advance.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP B
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL, GERMANY, ITALY, MEXICO
</P>
<P>
   Easily the Group of Death, with Brazil and Germany possible
quarterfinal and semifinal opponents for the U.S. team. The
Brazilians never have finished better than ninth in the World Cup,
but their vast improvement started with a fourth-place finish at
the 1996 Olympics. Brazil's women are fast and skillful and should
advance easily despite a knee injury to star striker Roseli. Katia,
Sissi and Pretinha are a real treat to watch on the attack. Germany
has skill and fortitude and is led by Doris Fitschen and Steffi
Jones and midfielder Bettina Wiegmann. Italy is a team in
transition, although it still has some fine players. Mexico, with
its assortment of U.S.-raised players, many with college
experience, makes its World Cup debut.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Brazil, Germany advance.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP C
</P>
<P>
   CANADA, JAPAN, NORWAY, RUSSIA
</P>
<P>
   Even softer than the U.S. group, this collection of teams should
be little more than tune-up fare for Norway, the defending World
Cup champion. Veteran striker Linda Medalen of Norway has been
moved into a defensive role, which is even more important because
of an injury to sweeper Gro Espeseth. The Norwegian midfielders,
led by Hege Riise, routinely dominate matches and a young infusion
of scoring talent has been added since Sweden '95. Canadian striker
Charmaine Hooper could be one of the best players in the
tournament, although the rest of her team is relatively average.
Japan is industrious and Russia is making strides, but neither has
enough to move beyond the pool stage.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Norway, Canada advance.
</P>
<P>
   GROUP D
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA, CHINA, GHANA, SWEDEN
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese should be able to run all over this group, with only
Sweden and top-flight goalkeeper Ulrika Karlsson making a nominal
challenge. With two wins against the U.S. team this year, China has
been in sensational form, and has all the tools to win the
championship. Only Hamm may be a better all-around offensive player
than Sun Wen, while veteran Liu Ailing patrols a versatile,
aggressive midfield. At 31, Gao Hong is reaching her peak in front
of the nets. Australia is trying to build a solid program as it
bids to host the 2003 World Cup. Ghana, which got in mainly because
Africa was allotted another spot when the tournament was expanded
to 16 teams, is soaking up the atmosphere for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: China, Sweden advance.
</P>
<P>
   QUARTERFINAL PREDICTIONS
</P>
<P>
   United States over Germany; Brazil over Denmark; Norway over
Sweden; China over Canada.
</P>
<P>
   SEMIFINAL PREDICTIONS
</P>
<P>
   United States over Brazil; China over Norway.
</P>
<P>
   FINAL PREDICTION
</P>
<P>
   China over United States
</P>
<P>
   PLAYERS TO WATCH
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvelous'' Mercy Akide, Nigeria
</P>
<P>
   Antonella Carta, Italy
</P>
<P>
   Doris Fitschen, Germany
</P>
<P>
   Gao Hong, China
</P>
<P>
   Monica Gerardo, Mexico
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm, U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Charmaine Hooper, Canada
</P>
<P>
   Ulrika Karlsson, Sweden
</P>
<P>
   Katia, Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Lilly, U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Liu Ailing, China
</P>
<P>
   Linda Medalen, Norway
</P>
<P>
   Tiffeny Milbrett, U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Birgit Prinz, Germany
</P>
<P>
   Hege Riise, Norway
</P>
<P>
   Sissi, Brazil
</P>
<P>
   Sun Wen, China
</P>
