NYT-06-18-99 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1453 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-CONTROL-TEX     06-18 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CONTROL-TEX </SLUG>
 
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hours after approving an amendment to loosen
restrictions on gun-show sales, the House reversed course Friday
and rejected the entire gun-control bill in an outburst of bitter
partisan sniping.
</P>
<P>
   The 280-147 vote scuttled legislation that would have required
background checks on all gun buyers at flea markets and gun shows.
In an unusual alliance, advocates on both sides of the gun control
debate teamed to keep the measure from being included in a juvenile
crime package.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control activists said the Republican-backed proposal did
not go far enough; gun rights advocates said it would place an
unnecessary burden on law-abiding gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Barton, R-Ennis, and Rep. Martin Frost, D-Dallas,
joined forces in opposing the gun control bill. House Majority
Leader Dick Armey of Irving and Rep. Kay Granger, R-Fort Worth,
voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control supporters said the outcome is a tribute to the
power of the National Rifle Association, a lobbying organization
that donated $1.6 million to congressional candidates in the last
election. About 83 percent of the money went to Republicans,
according to the Center for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan
group that tracks campaign spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope in my lifetime the marriage between the NRA and my
party ends in divorce,'' said Rep. Chris Shays, R-Conn., a party
maverick. ``It's a bad marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   The gun show restrictions could be revived in negotiations
between the House and Senate over the final version of the juvenile
justice bill. Because the Senate passed a youth crime bill that
includes comprehensive background checks for gun show buyers, the
House's version of juvenile-justice legislation will be sent to the
House-Senate conference committee to hammer out differences between
the measures.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, even though the House rejected its rendition of
gun control, the issue could be resurrected in the conference
committee. A compromise could conceivably be worked out, but strong
gun control legislation is unlikely because the House bill has no
such provision.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats blamed one another for not reaching a
compromise on an issue that moved to the top of the congressional
agenda after the April 20 massacre at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House leadership gutted this bill in the dead of night to
keep common-sense gun legislation from seeing the light of day,''
President Clinton said. ``The American people will not stand for
this. Our nation is waiting for Washington to pass real laws that
keep guns away from children and out of the hands of criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., accused Democrats of derailing
the bill in an attempt to gain political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let there be no mistake. The vast majority of the Democrat
caucus walked away when they had the chance to walk forward for the
good of the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was a bitter disappointment for rank-and-file
lawmakers who had hoped that the House could put aside politics in
dealing with the recent wave of school violence.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the vote, Granger burst through the swinging doors
from the House chamber sputtering with anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very frustrated, and I'll bet the American people are
frustrated,'' she said. ``It's who gets the vote or who doesn't get
the vote, not are we really dealing with the problem. I'm angry
about it, because it's not right. It deserves more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The House vote capped three days of emotional debate over how to
deal with school violence and juvenile crime. In passing the
Juvenile Offenders Act late Thursday night, lawmakers endorsed a
wide range of possible solutions, including tougher penalties for
juvenile offenders, $1.5 billion in federal grants and a proposal
that would let teachers post the Ten Commandments in their
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the sensitivity of the issue, House leaders put the
gun control proposals in a separate bill that would have been added
to the rest of the juvenile justice package if the gun bill had
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Working late into the night Thursday, lawmakers approved an
amendment backed by the NRA that would have put a 24-hour limit on
background checks at gun shows. The sale would be approved
automatically if the check had not been completed within the time
limit.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates favored a 72-hour limit because most gun
shows occur on weekends, when court records are generally
unavailable. When the bill came to a final vote Friday,
background-check opponents joined gun-control advocates in
defeating it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill tried to be all things to all people and ended up
being nothing to anybody, especially our children,'' said Rep. Nick
Lampson, D-Beaumont, who opposes gun control. ``The final version
of the bill was so jelled up by numerous amendments that it would
have tied the hands of responsible gun owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 10 of the 207 Democrats endorsed the gun show proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world needs to know that the Democratic House minority is
not serious about protecting our nation's children. They turned
their backs on this nation's children,'' said Rep. Deborah Pryce,
R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats countered that 82 Republicans joined 197 Democrats in
opposing the gun control measure. Republican Whip Tom DeLay of
Sugar Land, an ardent gun control foe and arguably the most
powerful House leader, did not try to line up support for the bill
on his side of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
