<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1454 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOBS-SEATTLE-SPI &LR;      06-18 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBS-SEATTLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERSEAS GOVERNMENTS SAY THEY CAN HELP FILL SEATTLE'S HIGH-TECH
JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ARTHUR C. GORLICK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They arrive in Seattle from places in the world as
diverse as The Netherlands, Barbados and India and they are seeking
the high-paying high-technology jobs that Seattle-area companies
can't fill.
</P>
<P>
   International trade delegations have paraded into Seattle in
recent weeks reassuring computer software developers with a common
message.
</P>
<P>
   They have skilled, trained people ready and eager to take on
work, often at low cost, that Seattle-area companies need to
complete before their customers switch to competitors, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Trade delegation leaders tell large Seattle audiences that their
government will help pave the way if only companies here set up
shop there and give jobs to their workers.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gary Locke, in a speech to the Technology Alliance of
Washington this month, outlined much of Seattle's attraction to
these technology-savvy nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some 7,000 job openings right now in our state of
Washington in the high technology and information fields,'' Locke
told the organization whose membership includes companies forming
the economic power of the state _ Boeing, Microsoft, Immunex, Icos
and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet our colleges and universities are only turning out
some 1,300 students a year with the appropriate degrees to fill
these jobs. So Washington state employers are hiring people from
out of state and out of country and (qualified Washington) students
can't get into these courses to get the degrees they need to fill
these jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, said Deputy Mayor Pauline Krikke of Amsterdam, who
listed her city's high-tech attributes before a Seattle audience
that included representatives of several Seattle-area software
producers.
</P>
<P>
   For example: Amsterdam is considered the ``Cyber City of
Europe,'' Krikke said. Its Science Park houses 45 international
information technology companies, and a high proportion of the
Internet traffic between the United States and Europe is channeled
through Amsterdam. The government offers substantial tax breaks for
U.S. companies setting up operations there.
</P>
<P>
   Davrick Liles and Brent Willen, two of three partners who own
Bellevue's Ardent Consulting, a computer software development
company, were in the audience of almost 200 at a symposium this
week sponsored by the government of Barbados in a plush, paneled
hall at Seattle's Rainier Club.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of skilled people in the Seattle area to take on software
jobs has driven up the cost of hiring workers _ and the price
offered to clients, Liles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us as software developers, the rate for people can be as
much as $150 an hour,'' Liles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for ways to lower our costs and this would
allow us to pay a lot lower and develop software in Barbados for
our clients that would be 25 percent to 30 percent lower.''
</P>
<P>
   The company will get its skilled workers and talent wherever it
can find it, Willen said.
</P>
<P>
   Reginald Farley, minister of industry and international business
for Barbados, and his staff passed out pamphlets from one company
in Barbados offering to solve the problems of the Bellevue software
developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are your labor costs too high? Are you looking to reduce
costs?'' the pamphlet entices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business process outsourcing can increase profitability and
productivity in your organization by strategic partnerships that
focus on core competencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The translation from cyberspeak is, ``Form a partnership with us
and send us the work you need to get done and we'll increase your
profits.''
</P>
<P>
   While Farley reminded those attending the symposium that
Barbados offers white sand beaches and comfortable living to those
moving there, it is not necessary to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the information technology industry make distance
and international boundaries almost meaningless, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   That point was made, too, by Sergey Volkov of Seattle's
Russian-America Society, who attended a luncheon of the European
Chambers of Commerce in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia has many computer scientists and mathematicians who are
out of work because of the financial problems there,'' said Volkov,
a former Soviet Foreign Ministry official now living in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would be more than happy to do computer software work
that can be sent to them via the Internet. It could get done
without the cost of travel by some of the most capable people in
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Some local companies have already gone beyond simply setting up
sales offices abroad. Microsoft has production operations in
Ireland and India. A Bellevue company, Aditi, acts much like a
broker handling technical support for Seattle-area software
companies at its facilities in India.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, India's National Association of Software and Service
Companies and the Consulate General of India will hold business
seminars here next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``India, your software partner,'' is the headline on the
delegation's invitations and advance publicity.
</P>
<P>
   It touts India as having the second-largest number of
English-speaking scientific professionals in the world, behind only
the United states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is a country that offers cost-effectiveness, great
quality, high reliability, rapid delivery and, above all,
state-of-the-art technologies in software development and Web-based
services,'' their literature says.
</P>
<P>
   While Washington's universities turn out 1,300 people a year to
fill computer company employee needs, India's institutions of
higher education overwhelm that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are over 1,832 educational institutions and polytechnics
training more than 67,785 computer software professionals on an
annual basis,'' India's literature says.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of trained people is so great here that even the
University of Washington has problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't afford them,'' said Bob Roseth, the university's
director of news and information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to hire the computer science program's students. The
shortage affects recruitment for staff positions at the university.
You have trouble keeping people in high-tech jobs because of what's
going on in the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   What's going on is that Washington's high-tech companies are
paying nearly $20,000 a year more than those in California to
attract employees, according to the American Electronics
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The trained employee shortage affects not only Microsoft, Locke
lamented, but banks, insurance, financial institutions and major
manufacturing in the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
