<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1458 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLOCK-MCNEELY19-COX     06-18 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLOCK-MCNEELY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For us, it was a tumultuous relationship, to say the least
 &HT;    By Dave Mcneely
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In 1974, when I was a reporter for The Dallas
Morning News, Bob Bullock and I and some of our mutual friends
killed a couple coolers of beer at Willie Nelson's Fourth of July
Picnic at Dripping Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock had just won the Democratic primary for comptroller,
after scaring the aging incumbent into retiring rather than seeking
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, I covered one of Bullock's first raids on a Dallas
restaurant that hadn't paid its sales taxes. He loved the
publicity. In later years, I had an occasional whiskey and
intriguing political talk with him at the comptroller's office,
while LBJ's bust looked on.
</P>
<P>
   He controlled a lot of people and events. State tax collector
for 16 years. Honcho of the Texas Senate for another eight. Many
folks kissed his ring.
</P>
<P>
   I called him ``Bob'' _ not ``Mr. Bullock,'' as his comptroller
employees did, and seldom ``governor'' after he became lieutenant
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists shouldn't be awed of politicians. Another cog in the
apparatus of democracy, we report on them, ask tough questions. We
remind them they work for the people, put their pants on one leg at
a time like everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Bob was periodically in fights with other officials, always at
least on the edge of trouble, if not directly in it. And drunk a
lot.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, his friend Ann Richards and others helped persuade him
to go to Betty Ford's ``drunk school.'' He quit the sauce, but not
his classic alcoholic behavior _ slap and soothe, punish and
praise.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote a lot about the good things he did _ like bringing the
comptroller's office into the 20th century, instituting an
affirmative-action policy before there was even a name for it,
pushing the state to change its outmoded tax system.
</P>
<P>
   But I never admired the more-than-occasional abuses of power and
of people. I think he felt he was doing good; it didn't matter how
he got it done.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, he ended speeches with ``God Bless Texas'' _ and
he meant it. But even while I wrote of Bob's accomplishments, the
hypersensitive, perfectionist control freak didn't like attention
to his dark side.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1988, he was oiling up his political machine to run
for lieutenant governor in 1990. I warned Texans there were two Bob
Bullocks:
</P>
<P>
   ``The good Bob Bullock is a caring, decent, loyal human being,
with a strong sense of democracy. He thinks government should serve
the people and search for new and innovative ways to deliver the
most services to taxpayers for the least amount of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be up at all hours of the night, dictating memos and
otherwise trying to figure out ways to make things run better. He
will be a stern taskmaster to make sure that government efficiently
helps those who can't help themselves and doesn't hurt those who
can.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad Bob Bullock is mean, arrogant, sometimes petty,
impetuous, mercurial, bullying. He sometimes carries loyalty to the
point of keeping people around who shouldn't be, while making life
so miserable for people who should be that they figure they'd
rather work somewhere else.'' In 1994, he had a heart attack a few
weeks before the election. Had surgery. I wrote a column about how
the lieutenant governor's job, and ballot slot, would be filled if
Bullock didn't survive the operation.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, 35 minutes into an interview about his extensive
network of former employees scattered throughout Texas government,
Bullock suddenly boiled over.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 column, he said, was ``the most callous disregard . . .
the most irresponsible act, that I have ever known.'' Said I'd
scared his wife.
</P>
<P>
   After several minutes more of what others told me was the
classic Bullock butt-chewing, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``You ain't up here to write a story. You're up here to gut my
ass. And that's the way I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that was clear.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this same man, when my late wife and fellow journalist
Carole Kneeland's breast cancer got worse, told me his plane was
available, any time, to fly her to M.D. Anderson Cancer Treatment
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in 1994, another column ended by asking what he'd like
carved on his tombstone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That `He did the best he could, and he loved his state' _
because I do,'' Bullock said. ``I love this state, and I love its
people _ almost an obsession with me. But I don't see anything
wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Me, neither _ you crusty old hard-ass. Godspeed, Governor
Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
