<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL, MICKELSON LOOK LIKE CONTENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ Competition? What competition?
</P>
<P>
   David Duval is in at 67-70-137. Phil Mickelson is in at
67-70-137. They share the U.S. Open second-round lead with Mr.
Knickers, Payne Stewart. They also shared a lot of time together,
having been playing partners for the first two days.
</P>
<P>
   But they weren't, you know, in ITALICS competition. END ITALICS.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Mickelson, ``it's the second round. I feel, and I
think David feels, that we all know even par tends to win the U.S.
Open. The idea is to get a few shots in hand before the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' echoed Duval. ``Not at all. I felt if I could just keep
hanging out where I was, things would sort themselves out. This was
not a day to worry about one-on-one competition with anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, guys, have it your way. Say the reasonable and intelligent
thing. Confirm the intellectually obvious. Sure, we know that a
little BEGIN ITALICS mano a mano END ITALICS thing on Friday won't
be remembered much by Sunday at around 7 o'clock (or perhaps even
Monday if we have a not exactly unprecedented playoff). But for the
people who watched these two under-30 contenders for the title of
Best Player Never To Have Won A Major (BPNTHWAM) wage concurrent
battles against Pinehurst Number 2 these past two days, it was
impossible not to frame their little confrontation in terms of
one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   Can't help it, guys. That's just the way we are.
</P>
<P>
   Duval went out in a one-under 34 and came back in a one-over 36.
``I feel very positive,'' he said, considering that the course was
a lot more difficult (Friday), and I didn't play as well, but
somehow managed to shoot even par.'' His adventurous front nine
included four birdies, a bogey and a double bogey. That took place
on the 222-yard par 3 sixth hole, when his second shot flew out of
a bunker on the right side clear past the green.
</P>
<P>
   But he demonstrated a little bit of the reason why he has
already won $2,861,350 on the tour this year when he responded to
that double bogey with back-to-back birdies. On the 398-yard
seventh he nailed a 9-iron three feet from the pin. He likewise
birdied the 485-yard par 4 eighth by following up a nice 7-iron
with a 14-foor putt.
</P>
<P>
   Informed that he leads the tour in the ``bounce-back'' category,
he scratched his head. ``I don't know what the `bounce-back' stat
is,'' he shrugged. ``I think the reason I can do that, is that I
really don't care. I just keep going. If I have a bad six, I say,
`I've got to play seven now.' It's just one of the 18 scores you're
going to have for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson had a classically circuitous route to his 36-34-70. He
was Mr. Up and Down, continually salvaging pars with superb
artistry on the side of, below and in back of the treacherous
Number 2 greens. He also was called upon for three spectacular
recoveries after slightly errant tee shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really pleased with the opportunity that this golf course
presents,'' pointed out the 29-year old King of Southpaws. ``If I
or another player misses a shot, we have an opportunity to hit a
great recovery and get up-and-down.''
</P>
<P>
   He was thinking more of his up-and-down work around the greeen,
which speaks to just how amazing these guys really are. Not to take
anything away from his short game, but anyone watching him play
might have been more taken with his dramatic rcoveries from
roadsides, or in front of TV trucks, or in close quarters with a
hundred people within a foot of his backswing. To him, that's like,
``What's the big deal?''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson is not quite Duval in the golfing public's eye. He's
more than $2,200,000 behind him on this year's money list, for one
thing (not that you need plan running a benefit for any of the
marquess guys). But he is a star. He has won more career
tournaments (13-11), and he's been in the public consciousness
longer. Five years ago casual sports fans knew Phil Mickelson. Only
the hard core golfing afficionados knew David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   If he appears to be playing in a blissful state in this Open,
there are two reasons. The first is his confidence, especially in
his short game. In preparation for Pinehurst, he spent time with
noted guru Jackie Burke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not worked on my short game for the past few years, and
it has deteriorated,'' he admitted. ``I've worked hard the past few
months, and I feel it's as good as it's been in years. I don't feel
I have to hit every shot perfect. I feel like there is enough
margin of error where my short game can make up for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The second reason is that wife Amy is back home awaiting the
birth of a baby. The due date is June 30, but, hey, you never know.
Mickelson says the decision has been made: If caddy Jim Mackey gets
a call on the beeper saying it's time for you-know-what, Mickelson
says he's outta here, even if he's putting for the championship on
number 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I worry about,'' he said. ``The decision
has been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval's got no sub-plot to match that. With him it's just a
matter of making those pars and allowing everyone else to
self-destruct. As for being the BPNTHWAM, the leading money winner
said that doesn't bother him. ``You only get four chances a year to
win one,'' he said, ``and you'd better hope you're playing well
when they come along.''
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't be an issue. The guy is only 27.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, there wasn't any competition. They may have each pulled
out drivers for their second shots on the monstrous 610-yard tenth,
but let's not read anything into that.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
