<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1463 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLOCK-OBIT-HNS &LR;      06-18 1950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLOCK-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGENDARY FORMER LT. GOV. BULLOCK, 69, DIES IN TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Former Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, who became a
dominant figure in modern Texas politics during four decades of
public service, died Friday at the age of 69.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock had a long history of health problems. Since leaving
office in January, he had been undergoing chemotherapy for lung
cancer, and recently developed pneumonia and congestive heart
failure. The cause of death was not immediately known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is the last giant of a past era,'' said Gov. George
W. Bush, who will deliver the eulogy at Bullock's funeral services
on Sunday. ``I think people will talk about him for a long, long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's body will not lie in state at the Capitol at the
request of the family. Services will be at 2 p.m. at Austin's
Central Christian Church; former Texas House Speaker Byron Tunnell
also will deliver a eulogy. Graveside services, to which the public
is invited, will follow immediately at the Texas State Cemetery.
Pallbearers will be a detachment of Texas Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A colorful, crusty figure, Bullock's take-no-prisoners style
led him to be revered by many and feared by others. Though he never
made a race for Texas governor, the Hillsboro native served as
legislator, secretary of state and state comptroller before winning
election in 1990 as lieutenant governor, a position he held until
January.
</P>
<P>
   As lieutenant governor, the presiding officer of the Senate,
Bullock was a major political player this decade along with Govs.
Ann Richards and George W. Bush. A 1950s-style conservative
Democrat, Bullock helped shape state government to enter the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   He typically closed his speeches with the personal benediction,
``God bless Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   As his star in politics rose, his personal life was a roller
coaster, with five marriages, two to the same woman. He married his
current wife, Jan Felts Teague, in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   A tumultuous period of Bullock's life that would have finished
many political careers ended in 1981 when Bullock, then state
comptroller, entered treatment and became a recovering alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he shocked the Texas political community by announcing
he would not seek re-election as lieutenant governor the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   In January, when he left office, a bipartisan state Senate
passed a resolution honoring Bullock as ``a legendary figure ... a
uniquely talented individual of imposing political presence ... a
man of remarkable insight and vision.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution didn't spare the superlatives. Few people would
deny that the plaudits were well-deserved tributes to the single
biggest presence in state government of most living Texans'
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   But the resolution didn't come close to capturing a public
career often &UR;  &LR; abrasive, sometimes pure political genius and
certainly never dull.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock made innumerable marks, not only on state policy but
also on the backsides of as many aides, lawmakers and lobbyists as
he deemed necessary to get those policies forged.
</P>
<P>
   He first earned statewide prominence during a 16-year reign as
state comptroller, in which he brought that office into the
computer age and became a key player in the state's budget-setting
process.
</P>
<P>
   His subsequent eight years as lieutenant governor, in which he
helped draft or negotiate virtually every major piece of
legislation to emerge from the Capitol, earned him a revered _ and
feared _ status achieved by few political figures.
</P>
<P>
   Austin political consultant George Christian, a Democrat who
worked with Bullock on civil justice changes, said Bullock's
eagerness to lead in offering solutions to controversial problems
set him apart from most state officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most public officials today are so cautious and so reticent to
get out in front on controversial issues,'' Christian said. ``He
was totally unafraid to move right into battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line for Bullock, according to former longtime aide
Glen Castlebury, was making government work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really believed government could work, and for everything
under his jurisdiction, it did,'' Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people compared Bullock's stature to that of President
Lyndon B. Johnson, for whom Christian worked as White House press
secretary. In some ways, Christian said, Bullock reminded him of
Johnson because both had ``so much drive behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were significant differences. For one thing, Christian
said, even the hard-boiled LBJ was no match for Bullock in the art
of what Bullock-watchers came to call ``drive-by ass chewings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Whitmire, D-Houston, a key Senate committee chairman
under Bullock, recalled that the tongue-lashings could get ``pretty
personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury said the dressings-down were ``commensurate with the
capability of the person being chewed out. He didn't chew out
janitors.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Castlebury added, ``The rewards were equally
commensurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury, now public information director for the Texas
Department of Criminal Justice, is one of many former Bullock
staffers still in state government or the Austin lobby. Their
training and work experience under the taskmaster made them
invaluable to their new employers.
</P>
<P>
   In a Houston Chronicle interview shortly before he left office,
Bullock said his alumni were the proudest accomplishment of his
political career: ``We attracted the brightest that there were in
state government,'' he said. ``I'm real proud of that. A person is
only as good as the staff he employs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullock associates said he was a demanding workaholic.
</P>
<P>
   More than once, Whitmire recalled, he was awakened by a phone
call from Bullock in the middle of the night or interrupted while
mowing his lawn on a Saturday to learn Bullock's latest idea.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock also was unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks after moving into the lieutenant governor's office
during a budget crunch in 1991, he shocked the statehouse and the
business community by advocating a personal income tax _ a major
political taboo in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know deep down in my heart, deep down in my heart, that it's
the right thing to do for Texas,'' Bullock said.
</P>
<P>
   But he lost that initiative _ one of the few losses of his
career _ after Gov. Richards, other state leaders and most lobby
groups remained adamantly opposed to it.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Bullock pulled another surprise by engineering
a constitutional amendment that most observers believe all but
guaranteed that Texas would never have a personal income tax in his
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, overwhelmingly adopted by lawmakers and Texas
voters, bans a personal income tax unless the voters approve one.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock denied making an about-face on the tax issue and said
simply that the taxpayers are in partnership with the Legislature
and should decide about an income tax together.
</P>
<P>
   Liking nothing better than unanimous votes in the Senate on
major issues, Bullock pressed senators and lobbyists to negotiate
compromises in private. There were so many unanimous or
near-unanimous Senate votes in 1993 that some House members joked
that senators who wanted to express dissent voted ``aye'' with
their eyes closed.
</P>
<P>
   And the process, although effective, drew complaints from
consumer advocates who felt they were locked out of negotiations on
such key decisions as tort reform and utility regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock's early political career was nothing extraordinary, with
a few years spent in the Texas House, a few years practicing law
and a stint as an assistant attorney general, where he headed up
the first anti-trust and consumer protection division. In that
office he won several historic cases, including a multimillion
dollar recovery in a price-fixing lawsuit against five
pharmaceutical companies. He served as a counsel to Gov. Preston
Smith from 1969-71 and was then appointed secretary of state by
Smith. As secretary of state, Bullock pushed to give 18-year-olds
voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also appointed Bullock to the then-State Board of
Insurance. But Ben Barnes, a political enemy and lieutenant
governor at the time, arranged to have the Senate bust his
confirmation, an act that Bullock never forgot.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock earned a reputation as Smith's ``hatchet man,'' who took
delight in attacking the governor's political opponents. When
Barnes challenged Smith in the 1972 governor's race in the
Democratic primary, Bullock _ or so it has been told _ would
gleefully call the Barnes campaign almost daily to announce how he
was going to mess with his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Barnes lost the race to an outsider, Uvalde rancher
Dolph Briscoe, and Bullock took another leave from state government
until he was elected comptroller in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   As comptroller, Bullock modernized the state's tax collection
procedures and conducted well-publicized raids of businesses owned
by delinquent taxpayers, spawning the term ``Bullock's Raiders'' in
government lexicon. But he was often controversial.
</P>
<P>
   A state grand jury, which investigated Bullock for political
misuse of office, issued a critical report, but cleared him of
criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock openly feuded with some reporters and even sent two
newsmen gift boxes of cow chips (the real thing) for writing things
he particularly didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   Although he usually arrived at the office by 7 a.m., a former
assistant recalled, Bullock would frequently leave by midafternoon
and go to happy hour. Beer or Old Charter and 7-Up were his drinks
of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alcohol was in control. The slave had become the master,''
Bullock told a 1981 Capitol news conference, after returning home
from alcoholism treatment in California.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock repeatedly tried to quit smoking, following a series of
serious health problems. He lost part of a lung years ago,
underwent heart bypass surgery in 1994 and last fall had surgery to
implant a pacemaker. He was suffering from pneumonia in January as
he presided over the Senate on the opening day of the session.
</P>
<P>
   If Bullock didn't completely mellow, he at least adjusted to the
state's changing political winds.
</P>
<P>
   During his first session as lieutenant governor in 1991, he
bumped two Republicans from committee chairs and appointed an
all-Democratic leadership lineup in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But he became bipartisan as Republicans increased their Senate
membership. He named GOP senators to key committee posts and
developed a good working relationship with Republican Gov. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bullock endorsed Bush for re-election over Democrat
Garry Mauro, his own protege, and even said Bush would make a great
president.
</P>
<P>
   After he turned over his job to Republican Rick Perry this year,
Bullock joined Public Strategies Inc., a public affairs and
management consulting firm headed by close friend Jack Martin.
</P>
<P>
   As he prepared to leave office, Bullock briefly reflected on his
political career for reporters:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the most fascinating life that I could imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of flowers, the family prefers memorial donations be
made to the Bob Bullock Endowed Scholarship Fund, Baylor
University, P.O. Box 97026, Waco, Tx., 76798.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock is survived by his wife, Jan; son, Robert D. ``Bobby''
Bullock Jr. of Austin; daughter, Lindy Ward of Austin and her
husband, Phil; grandson, Grant Bullock Robinson of Austin; and
stepdaughter, Kimberly Ader of Houston and her husband, Jeff.
Bullock also is survived by his brother, Tom, of Brenham and his
wife, Jane. Bullock was preceded in death by two sisters, Sara Read
and Louisa Bond. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
