<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIO AT TOP OF OPEN AFTER TWO DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ The almanac for North Carolina lists the
indisputable fact that the sun will rise here Saturday morning at
6:08 a.m. That fact is as relevant to what will happen today and
tomorrow in the 99th United States Open as the golf almanacs of the
future listing Payne Stewart, David Duval and Phil Mickelson as the
co-leaders after Friday's second round.
</P>
<P>
   That's because 156 of the best golfers of the world have been
baffled, befuddled and mesmerized by Pinehurst No. 2, so much so
that only three golfers managed to better par -- and that by only a
stroke -- and only four more equaled par on a day that one lifelong
Southener described ``as the best day I've ever seen here in late
June.'' Clear, crisp, cool and dry, no humidity. Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the golfers could only fidget and fret as they neared
closer and closer to the greens and the starched, crisp collars
that surround these greens. Some lost their cool, such as Spain's
Jose Maria Olazabal, the Masters' champion, fashioning his personal
Grand Slam by pounding the wall of the locker room Thursday in
frustration after shooting an opening round 75 but breaking a bone
in his hand, causing him to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was upset with myself to finish like I did,'' said Olazabal,
who is expected to be out three to four weeks and may also miss the
British Open. ``I did something I shouldn't have done; I wasn't
happy with the way I hit the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor were many others who teed it up at Pinehurst No 2. Others,
such as Greg Norman, Mark O'Meara, Fred Couples, Curtis Strange,
Jack Nicklaus and Lee Westwood saw their scores sky to the upper
ozone, all missing the cut. Two-time Open champion Ernie Els also
missed the cut and Lee Janzen, the defending champion, only made
the cut by chipping in from the fringe on the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the weather was perfect, the golf was far from it.
``It was like I was in the video store picking out all the bad
movies instead of the good ones,'' said Norman, who on Wednesday
had praised this ``as the best Open ever'' but whose 78-141 left
him four strokes from further competition. ``It was a horror show
out there; it was not enjoyable out there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, 21 golfers had shot birdie rounds. But the mere
three who could manage it Friday -- Stewart, Jeff Maggert and John
Huston -- showed the mesmerizing effect of Donald Rosss' Pinehurst
No. 2 on the field. Usually at the Open, red (birdie) scores do not
begin dropping from the leaderboards until midway through the
Saturday round when pressure builds; at Pinehurst, it began a day
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need a little more turf around the greens,'' complained
Curtis Strange, who missed the cut on the last year of his 10-year
exemption for winning the Open at Brookline in 1988 and Oak Hill in
Rochester in 1989. ``They said they wanted more chipping from
around the greens here for this Open, but what they did was have a
lot more putting from off the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus agreed (``I chipped the ball once in 36 holes
here'') but both Nicklaus and Strange, as well as Norman and many
other golfers who struggled here said Pinehurst, which is holding
its first Open, should be included in the usual rotation of Open
courses. ``The Open definitely should come back here,'' said
Norman.
</P>
<P>
   As for Olazabal's grand slam, Norman said he could understand
the Spaniard's frustration. ``But I would have kicked the wall,''
said the Australian. ``I wouldn't have punched it.'' And John Daly,
whose score ballooned Friday to 77 (145), commiserated, saying,
``We all do it. But he's got the Green Jacket and I'm playing like
crap.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, just as the 6:08 time for sunrise here must be
noted in almanacs, Stewart (69-137), Duval (70-137) and Mickelson
(70-137) are tied for the lead. Tiger Woods (71-139), Hal Sutton,
Vijay Singh and Billy Mayfair are all tied at 139, two strokes
behind the three leaders, with Maggert and Huston a stroke behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   The true Open won't begin until Sunday afternoon when the
converging pressures of winning the Open and dealing with Donald
Ross' golf architectural idiosyncracies will clash here at
Pinehurst. No prediction of any kind can be made by anyone since
this is the first Open in eons where it is the chipping areas
around the greens, and not ankle-high rough, that is trapping the
world's best golfers.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-Open prediction, for instance, that it would be the
Europeans whose finely-tuned short-game was most suited for Ross'
Pinehurst No. 2, proved to be a myth. Of the 10 leaders on the
board, all except Singh of Fiji, are Americans and the top European
scorer is Sweden's Jesper Parnevik, who is tied for 14th place.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, meanwhile, is in contention for a major for only the
second time since crushing the 1997 Masters field. ``I mean, I've
played two rounds in competition now here and I feel I've hit only
one or two putts for birdies where you can actually take a run
at,'' said Woods, hinting at the mysteries of No. 2. ``You don't
see that very often. You can say that about Augusta all the time;
... these greens are very severe.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, meanwhile, is a fixture at the Open. He won at
Hazeltine eight years ago and four times in the 1990s Stewart has
been the leader or co-leader after two rounds. Indeed, Stewart has
played 55 rounds at the Open and has been in the top 10 at the end
of an amazing 22 of those rounds; in 10 of those rounds he has been
the leader.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he has won only once. ``I think one of the reasons I do
well at US Opens is that I get a mindset that par is a good
score,'' said Stewart. ``You're never losing to anybody (with a
par).''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important is that Stewart had spent extra time
working on his short game preparing for the Open at Pinehurst.
``But I don't know where there's a place that you can create the
chipping that you have to do around here,'' said Stewart. ``But
what I was doing was working on my feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, meanwhile, still has not received the beeper from
wife Amy, due with child in 10 days, ``but when I hear it, I'm
making a bee-line to the airport and I'm out of here,'' Mickelson
said again. The lefty, another renowned chip-meister, said his
confidence in his short game gives him an extra cushion of
confidence here; ``I don't feel I have to hit every shot perfect
because I feel there's a margin of error where my short game can
make up for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
