<SLUG> BC-GUNS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gun bill shot down by House
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a dramatic twist to the fractious debate over
firearms, the House of Representatives rejected a modest gun
control bill Friday, raising the possibility that Congress may not
be able to pass such legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   As Republicans and Democrats traded blame, President Clinton
vowed to renew his campaign for tougher gun laws and fulfill his
pledge ``to the families of the children who died in Littleton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting warmed up,'' said Clinton. ``I'm energized
for the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats joined more than 80 Republicans to defeat the
package of gun control measures supported by the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would have required criminal background checks at gun
shows, but reduced by two-thirds the waiting period allowed under
current law for the checks to be completed. An amendment would have
overridden laws in the District of Columbia barring residents from
owning handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Other amendments adopted before the bill's defeat would have
imposed new controls, such as mandating the sale of trigger locks
with guns, banning high-capacity ammunition clips and prohibiting
violent juveniles from later possessing guns as adults.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, rallied by House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt,
said they could not support the bill because it weakened existing
Brady laws, reducing to 24 hours the waiting period at gun shows
and allowing dealers to ship guns across state lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans and the NRA put this together to defeat
common-sense legislation,'' said Gephardt. ``This whole process has
been an abomination.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans accused Gephardt and the Democrats of rejecting
``sensible'' gun control and putting ``partisanship over
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let there be no mistake,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert
(R-Ill.). ``The vast majority of the Democrat caucus walked away
when they had the chance to walk forward for the good of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither side talked much about defections within their own
ranks. Forty-five Democrats voted for the weakened gun show
language before switching to vote against the final bill.
Eighty-two Republicans, both conservatives and moderates, voted
against the final bill, which failed 147-280.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
