<HEADLINE>
HANGOVER FROM A MERRY MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of IPO of Internet stocks is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 20)  
 (af)  
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Internet stocks hit new highs two months ago, a giddy fever
swept through the corridors of on-line companies nationwide. Young
entrepreneurs and their venture backers holed up in cramped
offices, hatching plans to go public.
</P>
<P>
   The market for Internet stocks was searing and, they believed
then, there was no better time to sell new shares to the
dot.com-hungry investors who craved them.
</P>
<P>
   And so May was the busiest month in the short history of public
ownership of Internet companies. But despite one-day gains that
doubled some offering prices, many of these issues subsequently
sank, a result of the recent disenchantment with Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 25 Internet concerns that went public in May, 14 are now
trading below their offering prices. The worst performer is
Comps.com Inc., the Internet real estate site brought public by th
underwriter Volpe Brown Whelan &AMP; Co. Comps.com closed on Friday at
$7.375, 51 percent below the price at hich it went public on May 5.
</P>
<P>
   The star, so far, is Redback Ndetworks Inc., which is up an
eye-popping 345 percent since Morgan Stahnley Dean Witter took it
public on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   But kudos for the time being, may belong to Goldman Sachs Group.
It brought five companies public in May, more than any other
investment bank. And investors who were lucky enough to get shares
early were generally rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   Of those five companies, four are trading above their offering
prices, with Portal Software the best of the bunch _ up 243
percent. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
