<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL FACES FORMIDABLE TASK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the NFL preseason hype begins in the next few weeks, look
for Pete Carroll to win the honors as most likely coach to get
fired. Despite all the optimism after the Patriots' minicamp
workouts concluded, Carroll is a dead man walking. A couple of days
after the draft, a top Patriots executive asked me: What do you
think? I told him I thought Carroll just got fired; that nothing
happened in the draft that would help Carroll win this year.
</P>
<P>
   It says here that Carroll has the toughest job of any coach
heading into training camp next month. His team finished fourth in
the AFC East last year, and you can bet the preseason polls will
rank the Patriots fourth or worst. If the Colts hadn't traded
Marshall Faulk and his 2,300 yards of offense, I'd pick them for
fifth myself.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of last year, the Patriots have lost their top
running back, Robert Edwards, to a knee injury and have no one of
his caliber to replace him. The Patriots lost center Dave
Wohlabaugh, arguably their best offensive lineman, to free agency
and are supposed to replace him with top draft choice Damian Woody.
Woody will not be as good this year as Wohlabaugh.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are also trying to force one or two second-year
players, Ed Ellis and Damon Denson, into the lineup at guard to
replace either Todd Rucci or Max Lane, who have been regulars the
last two years. Without playing a game since last year, how did
Ellis and Denson become better than Rucci and Lane? So, with no
big-time running back, and the possiblity of two or three rookie
offensive linemen, the Patriots are going to be worse off than last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, linebacker Todd Collins left for the Rams via free
agency. He was the team's best pass coverage man, and released
defensive end Ferric Collons, who was its best run stopper. The
Patriots also lost a terrific punter and backup quarterback, Tom
Tupa, to free agency and the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Jets have signed four other free agents whom they
are going to plug into the starting lineup. Miami coach Jimmy
Johnson says the Dolphins are much better than last year's playoff
team. Buffalo, with Doug Flutie having a full year running the
offense under his belt, is the AFC's real sleeper, in this humble
writer's opinion. The Bills could win it all. Indianapolis is going
to be better after signing a ton of free agents to help its
defense, the Colts' weak spot last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now take a Patriots team that doesn't look as good as last
year's, four immediate competitors who look better and mix in the
new stadium situation, and Pete Carroll has a load to try to carry.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to sell luxury boxes, premium seats, and tickets for a
new stadium in Foxborough, it is imperative for the Patriots to get
off to a fast start. Flutie proved it in Buffalo last year. The
Bills couldn't get the big-money seats sold, until Flutie came off
the bench to electrify the city with his play, and produce an
atmosphere of excitement that led to all of the seats being sold
before the December deadline, ensuring the Bills would remain in
Buffalo for the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is going to need every break he can get to survive. At
the end of last year, the Patriots ``reviewed'' his efforts as head
coach before saying he would be back for another year. Carroll is
on the third year of a five-year contract. There are 10 players,
five starters, who are heading to free agency at the end of the
season. That is about normal for an NFL team, but as Drew Bledsoe
said: ``This might be the last year a lot of us play together.'' It
is critical that the Patriots sign Lawyer Milloy and Ty Law, two of
the best players in the league, to long-term contracts. However,
there is only one ``franchise'' designation left, in case both want
to remain Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   So this is the most critical time since Bill Parcells arrived in
Foxborough in 1993 for the Patriots to start to turn the franchise
around. Carroll must try to keep it afloat under some very tough
circumstances. It's not going to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adam Harrington stopped by the Massachusetts-Amherst basketball
offices a couple of weeks back to say he didn't want to go to
school close to home. Harrington, the state's top prospect two
years ago, started at guard in his freshman year at North Carolina
State but decided to move on. The guessing is that he will end up
at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bradley, a Kentucky transfer, has announced for
Villanova, but Rick Pitino reportedly was working hard to keep him
at home in Worcester at Holy Cross, with old friend Ralph Willard.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy began his college
and pro coaching career under Pitino. Pitino gave him his first
assistant's job at Providence and later brought him to New York and
the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Zero on Nit-Wit Radio likes to say that Pitino can't be
successful coaching the Celtics because he is a control freak,
calling all the offensive and defensive sets. Van Gundy does the
same thing with the Knicks, making all the calls when the ball
moves over halfcourt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston College athletic director Gene DeFilippo thinks the
proposal not to allow freshmen to play varsity sports is going
nowhere. ``I don't think it has a chance. It would be too costly
for the colleges to do something like that, although they (NCAA)
are looking hard to find some kind of reasonable solution to kids
just coming to college for a year or two and then jumping into pro
ball. But not letting them play as freshmen is not the way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul McMahon would love to see the NCAA rule freshmen
ineligible. ``I think it would really help us,'' said McMahon, who
is trying to put together the Collegiate Professional League. ``We
still hope to open our league in November of 2000,'' says McMahon,
who wants to take high school basketball players and pay them to
play in his league rather than go to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the big-time high school players do not get an
education in college,'' said McMahon. ``You can see that by looking
at the graduation rates. If a player comes to our league, he would
get $17,000 the first year to play, all the way up to $25,000 in
his senior year, if he was still in the league. We would love to
see our players get drafted by the NBA. But until they do, we would
put them in a local college, to fit their level of education, in
whatever city they would play in.''
</P>
<P>
   McMahon envisions an eight-team league, set in big markets in
the Northeast and Midwest. ``We have three major sponsors committed
already,'' said McMahon, ``and we have sent letters to all NBA
owners offering an equity position in our league to join forces
with us.'' Simply put, in McMahon's plan, a top high school player
would go to high school, then play in his league, and then go on
the NBA, finishing his education when his playing days are all
over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball is going to have a press conference in
Boston the week before the All-Star game to announce the plan to
bust ticket scalpers and sellers of counterfeit merchandise.
``Because of the size of Fenway Park (smallest in the major
leagues) and a lot of people going to Boston to try to see the
park, this is going to be the most sought after All-Star ticket of
them all,'' says Kevin Hallinan, Major League Baseball's director
of security. ``We have already been in touch with the Boston Police
and all the major law enforcement agencies on this. They will be at
the press conference to emphasize how tough we are going to be
looking for scalpers and people selling counterfeit merchandise. We
can guarantee that there are people around this country who have
alrady made up All-Star Game T-shirts, hats, and other merchandise,
and have it loaded in tractor-trailer trucks ready to sell in
Boston. Then when the T-shirt falls apart after the first washing,
we are the first ones to get the complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a rags-to-riches story. Joe O'Donnell, the head of Boston
Concessions, was recently elected to Harvard's board of overseers,
one of only 30 such positions. O'Donnell, the son of an Everett
cop, came to Harvard hat in hand and holes in pants in 1963 and was
captain of its baseball team and started on the football team for
two years. Now he'll serve for six years on the board, which meets
five times a year and, among other functions, approves Harvard's
presidential appointment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consider this. In this era of baseball, major league teams
usually have their top prospects at the Double-AA level. The cycle
works this way. Each year the teams sign a bunch of young players
out of high school and college after the draft. They send them to
four Class A, or entry-level, teams. With the Red Sox, that means
Fort Myers in the Gulf Coast League or Lowell in the New York-Penn
League. Most of the time, the young players on Lowell are the
drafted high school kids or youngsters out of the Caribbean
leagues. They play a ``short season,'' running from June to early
September. The other Red Sox Single-A teams are in Augusta, Ga.,
and Sarasota, Fla. These are where the college players are assigned
and play a longer season than the young signees. When the year is
over, the four teams are evaluated, and the best players are sent
to the Red Sox' Double-A team in Trenton, N.J. The Trenton Thunder
had the best record of any team in professional baseball starting
the week, 42-18. So this seems to indicate the Sox' talent at that
level, is as good, if not better, than any team in the majors. It
appears that, in the next three years, the Red Sox should be able
to bring up several players who are better than they now have to
start at some positions . . . Some NBA insiders are saying the
Celtics really are shopping Ron Mercer and Ken Anderson, but that
if any team wants Mercer, it has to take Anderson, too, because the
Celtics want to get rid of Anderson's money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ed Anderson, one of the Providence Bruins' owners, said he and
his partners won't see any financial benefits from his team's
record-breaking season until next year. ``We didn't make a lot of
money,'' says Anderson, whose team won a record 71 games and the
American Hockey League championship. ``Our attendance went up about
1,200 more per game than the year before, but we spent more on
player payroll getting players in here that could turn this team
around. This town fell in love with our team, so we hope to see the
(financial) benefits next year when our fans start buying season
tickets.'' The old AHL record of wins in a season was 64, combining
regular-season and playoff wins. Providence passed that by seven
wins was an incredible 43-7 at home with a 15-game Civic Center
winning streak to end the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
