<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT REACHED ON DEPLOYMENT OF RUSSIAN TROOPS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland _ Russia and the United States, ending three
days of grueling negotiations, Friday signed a military agreement
that integrates Russia into the Kosovo peacekeeping force, dividing
the bulk of 3,500 Russian troops among three of five sectors led by
NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement broke a tense stalemate over Russia's role in
Kosovo, and opened the way for restoration of Russia's links to the
Western alliance, which Moscow froze last March when NATO launched
airstrikes against Yugoslavia, its historical ally in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our agreement recognizes the stakes that Russia and NATO share
in Europe's future,'' said Secretary of Defense William Cohen at
signing ceremonies held late Friday at Finland's presidential
palace. ``It also shows that the U.S. and Russia can work together
on important security issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks here began at a low point in U.S.-Russian relations,
which have been scarred by the conflict in Yugoslavia and again
last week by Moscow's sudden decision to preempt NATO by
dispatching 200 Russian paratroopers to the Kosovo capital of
Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing to a distribution of Russian troops in sectors of
Kosovo controlled by France, Germany and the United States, Russian
negotiators stepped back from an initial demand for a separate
Russian sector in the Serbian province. That demand had been
reinforced by President Boris Yeltsin, who said in Moscow on
Thursday that he had instructed his top envoy to the talks, Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev, to stand fast on Russia's insistence for a
sector of its own.
</P>
<P>
   But at the signing ceremonies, Sergeyev and Russian foreign
minister Igor Ivanov said the compromise arrangement, thrashed out
during 33 hours of negotiation and laid out in exhaustive detail in
the final document, had met Yeltsin's requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found an alternative solution which will assure such kind
of deployment that will enable Russian troops to actively
participate in the peacekeeping operation,'' Sergeyev said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the agreement carried out Yeltsin's instructions,
Ivanov gave a curt reply. ``If it did not correspond to the
president's instructions, Sergeyev would not have signed,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the talks American negotiators, acting on
behalf of their NATO allies, said they would not yield on certain
principles _ or ``red lines'' _ which included the preservation of
a unified command structure for the NATO-led force in Kosovo, and a
refusal to grant Russia a sector of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, for its part, had said it would not put its troops under
NATO command, or follow arrangements now in place for the shared
command of 1,300 Russian soldiers deployed as part of an
international peacekeeping force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   According to a senior Defense Department official, the command
arrangement included in the agreement would give Russian commanders
a greater say in the Kosovo peacekeeping operations, at all levels.
``There is an important distinction from the Bosnia arrangement,''
he said. ``Under this arrangement, the Russian role is more
intensive, more integrated and the participation is greater.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the agreement calls for a 10-member Russian
military delegation to NATO's military headquarters, three Russian
officers posted at NATO's southern command headquarters in Naples,
Italy, and Russian commanders assigned to the NATO-led peacekeeping
forces in the three sectors where their troops will serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russian troops will be under the tactical command of KFOR,''
said Cohen Friday night, referring to the Kosovo peacekeeping
force. ``But in operational terms, political and military, they
will be answerable to the national command authority of Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the senior Defense Department official, the
agreement also gives Russian forces the right to refuse to
participate in certain operations as long as they recognize that
other forces may move in and carry out the disputed tasks. He said
the Russians were reassured that similar conditions have been
imposed on other national forces participating in the Kosovo
peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   In NATO's view, a separate Russian sector would have resulted in
a de facto partition of Kosovo, with the Serbian population
withdrawing to the area under Russian protection, and Kosovo
Albanians dominant in the five NATO sectors, controlled by Italy,
Britain, France, Germany and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials are also concerned that the Russians, left in
control of a large patch of territory, would pull away from the
unified command structure that is considered essential to an
effective peacekeeping operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
