<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HILLS-ART-960&AMP;     06-18 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HILLS-ART-960&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME KOSOVAR ALBANIANS, 3 MONTHS IN THE WILD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRYKA E NEKOVCIT, Yugoslavia _ For more than a mile, they line
the hillsides of this narrow gorge in the heart of Kosovo:
makeshift shelters put together from tree branches and plastic
sheeting that gave shelter to more than 5,000 Albanians fleeing
Yugoslav attacks during the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   Faik Thachi came here in late March with his wife and five
children thinking that his stay would last just a few weeks. It
would be uncomfortable and cold, but they would be safely out of
range of Yugoslav artillery.
</P>
<P>
   They ended up staying three months. As the conflict wore on,
life became a grinding waiting game in this crowded gorge clogged
with mud, smoke and squalor. Food occasionally ran out. The
children became ill with dehydration and diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   Thachi passed his days dreading long-range rocket attacks and
listening to the radio for the faintest sign of change. At one
point, a rocket landed 700 yards from him and his daughter. At
night, he and hundreds of other men searched desperately for food
in abandoned villages nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult moment was when I knew I didn't have any
more food for my children,'' said Thachi, a bespectacled,
soft-spoken man who is 41. ``There wasn't anything left.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is certain how many Kosovo Albanians managed to hide
themselves in the woods. But Thachi and his family were among the
thousands who managed to stay out of harm's way in this gorge.
Their plight was the focus of intense concern among aid groups that
unsuccessfully proposed missions to air-drop food into the forests
to help them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them, according to initial reports, appear to have
survived, though there are many cases of malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Lul Raka, a 30-year-old doctor from the town of
Kacanik, practiced medicine in the woods of southern Kosovo for
three months and grew to enjoy life in the wild. Others, like Asem
Hasan, a 50-year-old bus driver from the village of Dumsic in
northern Kosovo, lost their cat-and-mouse game and were driven from
the hills by Yugoslav soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   For Thachi, his time in hiding proved far more arduous than
expected. But he said he was always completely convinced that NATO
would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ``When most wars begin, people aren't sure what will happen, who
will win,'' he said. ``But I knew from the first moment that the
Serbs could never win.''
</P>
<P>
   But early on, they did, sending Thachi and his family to the
hills six days after NATO airstrikes began.
</P>
<P>
   When Yugoslav soldiers rolled into his small hometown, Komarane
in central Kosovo, Thachi quickly loaded his wife, Sheherije, and
their children, ages 12, 10, 8, 7 and 17 months, onto a trailer,
hitched it to his farm tractor, threw in pre-packed bags, and
headed for the woods.
</P>
<P>
   He had done this before, living in the same narrow gorge, with
its fast-running stream and verdant hillsides, for a month in May
of last year after a Yugoslav offensive also drove him from home.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife packed plastic sheeting for a shelter, a small
wood stove, warm clothing and several mattresses, as well as flour
and other food.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day he carved out a spot of level ground from the
hillside and fashioned a shelter by nailing together tree branches,
bending them to form a smooth, curved roof, and lining them with
plastic. More plastic was placed on the ground to keep their
mattresses dry. Finally, dirt was piled along the sides of the
shelter to seal it. With the wood-burning stove, the shelter was
smoky but warm.
</P>
<P>
   Makeshift outhouses positioned over the stream running through
the center of the gorge made the water dangerous to drink. To
prevent the children, particularly their youngest, from getting
sick, Thachi and his wife drew water from a nearby spring. But even
that failed to keep the children from quickly contracting diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   To Thachi's dismay, the conflict did not end quickly. A
political moderate who worked with Serbs and had a Serb girlfriend
when he was younger, he was stunned by the intensity of the Serbian
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   After a few weeks in the woods, their initial supply of food
quickly dwindled as the family shivered in the late winter
temperatures. In the first of what would be a half dozen trips, his
foraging for food in abandoned Albanian homes and farms turned up
sacks of wheat or corn flower, which could be made into bread, as
well as dry beans or vegetables and potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Venturing as far as five miles from the gorge, he and other men
scavenged during nights when there was little or no moon. Unarmed,
they feared tripping a mine or encountering a Yugoslav patrol. ``We
had to get back before dawn,'' he said. ``Whoever was left would be
shot by soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the first month, his fears of starvation eased
with each successful foraging mission. As temperatures warmed, the
gorge evolved into a small makeshift city. Bread was baked on the
small wood stoves, cows brought into the hills by Albanians were
slaughtered, and women tried to keep a semblance of normality by
ceaselessly washing their children's clothes and brushing dirt from
their plastic shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Thachi's family gradually grew accustomed to living outdoors.
They ate bread and beans each day. They ate meat and drank cow's
milk once a week. His infant son was fed powdered milk, and the
diarrhea, which could have killed him if he had become too
dehydrated, eased.
</P>
<P>
   As the conflict moved through its second month, the only thing
separating Thachi from the Serbs was a stack of boulders manned by
Kosovo Liberation Army rebels with 100 rounds of ammunition. Other
nearby valleys in the area, the southern tip of the Drenica region,
the heartland of the rebels, were also packed with Albanians. He
feared that they might make a tempting target.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Thachi, who observed the Yugoslavs from the hills by
binoculars, said that on several occasions NATO air attacks
thwarted potential Yugoslav attacks. ``When a lot of tanks would go
down close to the hill, NATO would bomb them,'' he said. Kosovo
Liberation Army soldiers also managed to mine the roads below,
slowing Yugoslav operations.
</P>
<P>
   But as the third month began, two incidents alarmed Thachi. He
returned from two foraging trips empty-handed and realized that he
and other men were being gradually forced to venture farther and
farther away from the hills to get food.
</P>
<P>
   And in late May, 16 screeching Katyusha rockets fired miles away
by the Yugoslavs fell into nearby hills. One rocket struck a tent
in the gorge 700 yards from where he and his daughter were
gathering wood, and it killed four children and a mother. ``I was
very frightened my children would be hurt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Thachi said that even at this point he did not consider
fleeing to Macedonia or Albania. He said he believed that it would
be safer to remain in the woods than pass through Serb lines.
Leaving, he also said, would only further President Slobodan
Milosevic's goal of emptying Kosovo of Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But he also bluntly said he was willing to risk the lives of his
wife and children for Kosovo. ``I was willing to risk my life and
the lives of my family because I knew freedom was close,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom came early this week with the arrival of British troops
in the area. Over the next several days, he and the other 5,000
people in the gorge packed up their tractors and drove home.
</P>
<P>
   But when he finally returned to Komorane on Wednesday, he found
his home gutted by fire.
</P>
<P>
   Thachi said the experience had changed him in many ways. A heavy
drinker and big spender before his time in the woods, he now
pledges to be a better provider for his family. He is clearly proud
of weathering the ordeal and of the toughness he showed. And in a
change that does not bode well for any semblance of a multi-ethnic
Kosovo, Thachi, once a moderate, now views Serbs through a
different prism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respected the Serbs very, very much before,'' he said.
``Now, I don't even want to look at them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
