<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1488 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-1STLD-W     06-18 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN CONTROL BILL, SEEN AS BOTH TOO WEAK AND TOO TOUGH, DEFEATED IN
HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: 3rdtake is new) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By FRANK BRUNI and JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House on Friday concluded a bitter,
wide-ranging debate over the seeds of violence among American
children by rejecting, 280 to 147, a package of new restrictions on
firearms that was significantly weaker than legislation approved by
the Senate last month.
</P>
<P>
   An odd coalition of liberal Democrats, moderate Republicans and
conservative opponents of gun control in both parties banded
together to defeat the House measures, which struck many lawmakers
as too little and many others as too much. In the end, 82
Republicans joined with 197 Democrats and one independent in
opposition to the legislation, while only 10 Democrats sided with
137 Republicans in favor of it.
</P>
<P>
   That outcome seriously clouded the prospects for the passage of
modest new gun-control measures in Congress this year and brought
to a close _ at least for now _ the long, intense weeks of
political wrangling and legislative soul-searching touched off by
the massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., on April
20.
</P>
<P>
   A House juvenile crime bill that was passed on Thursday, before
the companion legislation on gun control was considered, will
proceed to a conference committee to be reconciled with a Senate
juvenile crime bill that comprised an array of modest new
restrictions on firearms.
</P>
<P>
   But that could be many weeks away, and the absence of gun
control in the House version makes it unclear how much, if any, of
the Senate measures will survive. House Democrats vowed to push
their cause in other ways and perhaps use parliamentary maneuvers
to bring back to the House floor stronger gun-control provisions
than the ones they opposed today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll use every method we can,'' said Rep. Dick Gephardt of
Missouri, the Democratic minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   The House has traditionally proven more resistant to gun control
than the Senate, but Friday's defeat also reflected the
relentlessly building war between Republicans and Democrats as they
head into the 2000 elections, when control of the House as well as
the White House is up for grabs. The political calculations of each
party helped to doom any kind of consensus, and the finger pointing
began almost instantly after the final vote.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said that they had succeeded in blocking and exposing
a Republican deception of progress that, in fact, relaxed a number
of aspects of current gun-control law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House leadership gutted this bill in the dark of night,''
President Clinton said Friday, referring to a vote at midnight
Thursday for the most lenient of several proposals to regulate the
sale of firearms at gun shows. It was the passage of this measure,
supported by House Republican leaders and the National Rifle
Association, that stirred such solid Democratic opposition to the
final gun-control bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation is waiting for Washington to pass a real law that
keeps guns away from children and out of the hands of children,''
Clinton said. ``I call on Congress to stop playing politics and
start living up to its responsibility to save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, an Illinois Republican,
accused Democrats of the same games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let there be no mistake,'' said Hastert, who did not join
other Republican leaders at a news conference following the vote,
in a written statement. ``The vast majority of the Democratic
caucus walked away when they had the chance to walk forward for the
good of the country.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' opposition to the bill stemmed from the stinging
defeat, around 1 a.m. Friday, of a measure sponsored by Rep.
Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., to require mandatory background checks on
all buyers at gun shows. Mrs. McCarthy's measure, which largely
mirrored the Senate legislation, defined gun shows broadly and gave
vendors up to three business days to conduct those checks.
</P>
<P>
   But the House defeated it only an hour after narrowly approving
a rival gun-show measure that was sponsored by Rep. John D.
Dingell, a Michigan Democrat, that relaxed current law in some
ways. Dingell formerly served on the board of the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   His measure, like Mrs. McCarthy's, obliged the 40 percent of
vendors at gun shows who are hobbyists or collectors to conduct the
kinds of background checks that only the 60 percent of sellers who
are licensed dealers must now perform. But it gave both these
groups only 24 hours before the sale would be allowed to go
through. Licensed dealers currently have three business days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   All the Republican leaders in the House voted with Dingell, and
in the minutes between his victory and Mrs. McCarthy's defeat,
which was all but certain at that point, she choked back tears as
she addressed her colleagues from the well of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCarthy, whose husband was killed and her son critically
injured by a gunman on the Long Island Rail Road in 1993, said, ``I
made a promise to my son and to my husband.'' The nature of that
vow was implicit as she added, ``If there was anything that I could
do to prevent one family from going through what I have gone
through and every other victim that I know have gone through, then
I have done my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCarthy drew a standing ovation, even from many of the
Republicans and conservative Democrats who then voted against her
proposal, which was defeated, 253 to 193. Dingell's measure had
passed by a vote of 218 to 211.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1491 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-MAIN19-COX     06-18 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-MAIN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ivester takes charge in Belgium
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Time may be money, but to Coca-Cola these days it
represents priceless image.
</P>
<P>
   The longer the European health scare involving Coca-Cola's soft
drinks drags on, the more damaging it can become for arguably the
best-known brand in the world.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason company Chairman M. Douglas Ivester is in
Europe this weekend to take personal command of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   And several industry observers predict Ivester will be able to
help end the company's crisis, possibly early next week. On Monday,
he is expected to meet with the Belgian government, according to
government and company officials.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian and French authorities have questioned Coca-Cola's
explanations of what caused scores of illnesses to consumers who
drank its products. Both countries, along with several other
European nations, have pulled Coke products or curtailed shipments
in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola blamed the sicknesses on two causes: defective carbon
dioxide injected into drinks at a plant in Antwerp, Belgium, and an
offensive odor on the outside bottom of cans produced at a plant in
Dunkirk, France. The company said the odor originated from a
fungicide sprayed on wooden pallets carrying cans that were sent to
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   But both governments said more testing and data are needed to
demonstrate that the company's explanations are accurate before the
partial ban on its products can be lifted. ``I think that's a PR
disaster,'' said Marc Cohen, a beverage analyst for Goldman Sachs.
``The Belgian Health Ministry is not accepting what their analysis
is yielding. ... It must be enormously frustrating for the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   But frustration is the least of the company's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``In part of their business, they're out of business,'' Cohen
said. ``The longer this goes on, the more damage it does to their
reputation and their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said it's a challenge for the company to get government
officials to move quicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what's in their control,'' he said. But with
Ivester in Belgium now, events are likely to speed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a positive thing that Doug is visibly involved. People
always take confidence in a CEO that's standing up and facing the
issue,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, however, the crisis will go into a second week.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts believe Coca-Cola needs to resolve the
issues by the end of next week or the road back to regaining public
confidence could get considerably rougher.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts, however, believe the largest beverage company in
the world has the ability to steadily rebound _ even if it takes a
longer time to get its products back on the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   They said that's partially because Coca-Cola will have a number
of aggressive marketing and advertising initiatives when the
governments give the green light.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brand is very strong and has an enduring nature,'' said
John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage Digest. ``Long term,
I don't anticipate problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, Cohen agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $64,000 question is the lasting impact with the customer
and the consumer,'' he said. ``I suspect there won't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff correspondent Bert Roughton in Brussels contributed to
this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
