<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1492 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-1STLD-W     06-18 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: 218 to 211.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The House went on Friday to consider, and approve, a host of
other gun-control measures, many of them identical to the Senate's.
They included a requirement that licensed dealers provide
child-safety devices with all the handguns they sold, new
restrictions on the possession of semi-automatic rifles by children
under 18, and a ban on the import of high-capacity ammunition
clips.
</P>
<P>
   But the House also approved a proposal to create an exemption
under the District of Columbia's ban on firearms possession that
would allow people without criminal histories to keep a gun at
home.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, most Democrats said that because the weakness of
Dingell's gun-show provision eclipsed the strengths in some of the
other measures they decided to vote against the bill that stitched
them all together.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many conservative of both parties who had
voted with Dingell so disliked the additional restrictions on
firearms that passed that they abandoned the bill for the opposite
reason.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle were Republican leaders who felt a need to show
that they could pass a bill and even many conservative Republicans
who wanted to pass legislation and ensure that they would not have
to return to the subject of guns anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   They also wanted to show that Hastert could marshal his unruly
caucus, with its narrow majority, toward the enactment of
legislation. Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the Republican majority whip,
lobbied conservatives in his party to accept the new firearms
restrictions and even voted for them himself, though he had made
clear all week long how odious he found them.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, who also voted for the bill, sat down with moderate
Republicans just an hour before the vote, urging them to support
the legislation, according to Rep. Amo Houghton, a Republican from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that it was important that we got something done and
not let it go down and have wasted all this time posturing,'' said
Houghton, who voted for the bill. ``I'm sure he was very concerned
that here was another handful of sand in the gears, when we needed
some lubrication.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the NRA recommended the legislation's approval in a
last-minute letter to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   James Jay Baker, the chief lobbyist for the organization, said
Friday that the NRA had cared most about defeating Mrs. McCarthy's
gun-show amendment and promoting Dingell's. Having accomplished
that, he said, the rifle association was willing to live with the
other restrictions that had been woven into the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, on balance, it was better to get this issue over
and done with,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic leaders decided to oppose the bill, and the party
hung together more solidly in the final vote on the bill than they
had on the rival gun-show measures.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., conceded that some Democrats who had
broken party ranks on other votes simply decided that ``they wanted
to screw up the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also kept many Republican advocates of gun control,
like Rep. Christopher Shays of Connecticut, on their side. Shays,
in a floor speech just before his vote to kill the bill, explained
his decision in terms of the flaws in Dingell's measure and the gun
lobby's sway over that proposal and the Republican majority voting
for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope, in my lifetime, the marriage between the NRA and my
party ends in divorce,'' Shays said. ``It's a bad marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after the vote, DeLay said he was actually
pleased with the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guns have little or nothing to do with juvenile
violence,'' DeLay said, adding that he ``had a great time this
week'' getting to debate other causes, like children's estrangement
from religion and the violent wares peddled by the entertainment
industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
