<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-RUSSIA-NY     06-18 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO-MOSCOW TIES BEGAN WORSENING BEFORE BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Exclusive)  
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ A few hundred Russian soldiers in Kosovo,
commanded by a general who outranks the British lieutenant general
who will be in charge of the 50,000 NATO troops there, have had the
alliance trying to figure out since last weekend how Russians can
be included without being under NATO command, which they reject, or
weakening the mission.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, allied officials said Friday, NATO's military
relationship with Russia started going seriously wrong months ago,
when Moscow tried to assign a senior military intelligence officer
to the alliance's command headquarters in Mons, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, the officer, Maj. Gen. Roman Yepifanov, was to have
coordinated with NATO orders to the 1,300 Russian troops in Bosnia.
But more likely, the allies thought, he was sent to spy.
</P>
<P>
   The allied military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark of the United
States, objected to the appointment, diplomats here said, and tried
informally to persuade senior Russian military officials to send
somebody else. Alliance ambassadors backed Clark and formally
rejected Yepifanov's assignment in February, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the cold shoulder in Brussels, Yepifanov, considered by
his intelligence counterparts in NATO to have no evident
qualifications to command troops in the field in Bosnia, went there
anyway and is apparently still in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for NATO in Sarajevo, Col. Lee Hockman, said
Yepifanov was a special representative of the chief of staff of the
Russian airborne forces, the bulk of the Russian peacekeepers in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had absolutely no previous operational command experience
that would have qualified him to direct peacekeeping operations in
Bosnia,'' an allied diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Yepifanov's rejection, Russia froze all military
relations with the alliance to protest the NATO bombing of
Yugoslavia that started on March 24. Consequently, the Russian
forces in Bosnia technically have no one to report to at Clark's
headquarters, which may explain why some of them simply pulled out
of Bosnia last week and headed for Kosovo, infuriating Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The man whom Yepifanov was nominated to replace, Maj. Gen.
Anatoly Krivolapov, was abruptly pulled back to Moscow at the turn
of the year, with no explanation to his NATO counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Krivolapov was effective, and Clark had a professional
association with him,'' one allied officer said. ``They met once
every week or two and discussed serious military matters. And we
saw him as a very successful appointment. All of a sudden he got
orders to leave, and ever since the post has been vacant.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not the only vacant post. The officer who was Russia's
military representative to the alliance until the NATO bombing
started, Lt. Gen. Viktor Zavarzin, turned up a week ago at the
airport near Pristina, Kosovo, in command of the Russian troops who
arrived in the dead of night determined to seize a role in the
security force.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Clark, with all the infrared sensors and spy satellites
his air forces had used to such great effect in the 78 days of the
bombing, was aware that the Russian soldiers moved into Pristina
early last Saturday until they arrived there, to a huge welcome
from the city's Serbs, allied officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Zavarzin, freshly promoted to four-star colonel general rank,
not only outran the British commander of the allied peacekeeping
force, Lt. Gen. Sir Michael Jackson, he even outranked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't seen him in Brussels since the bombing started,''
said a Russian journalist who covers NATO, hugely amused at the
whole show.
</P>
<P>
   Zavarzin had been sent to Brussels under the 1997 treaty that
established a formal relationship between the alliance and Russia
despite Moscow's vehement objections to Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic's joining NATO. The three former Warsaw Pact allies
of the Soviet Union became NATO members just before the Yugoslavia
bombardment started.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO and Russia do not consider each other as adversaries,''
the treaty, signed by President Boris Yeltsin in Paris, says. It
provides for a Russian mission to NATO and an ambassador, with a
senior military representative _ still Zavarzin _ as part of the
mission for what the treaty describes as ``military cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   With taut grins on their faces, allied diplomats have been
maintaining for a week that they were happy to see that Russia was
so eager for military cooperation with the alliance in Kosovo that
it had dispatched Zavarzin to Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   But American officials have been so infuriated that Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine of France told journalists in Paris this
week that he thought that the Americans should not exaggerate the
importance of the affair. The Russian military, humiliated and
broke since the end of the Cold War, was simply trying to show that
it was not a complete cipher. Give 'em a break, Vedrine said in
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Secretary of Defense
William Cohen were in Helsinki, Finland, for a second straight day
Friday trying to untangle the mess. Their talks produced agreement
on command arrangements for an estimated 3,600 Russian troops in
Kosovo to report technically to a Russian officer at Clark's
headquarters in Mons, allied diplomats said. A Russian military
representative would also be assigned to NATO's Southern Europe
Command in Naples.
</P>
<P>
   The setup in Kosovo would be similar to the one under which the
1,300 Russian troops in Bosnia serve with, but not technically for,
the NATO force there. The Russian commander in Bosnia, Col. Nikolai
Ignatov, coordinates day-to-day operations with the American
officer who heads the multinational NATO division headquartered in
Tuzla, Maj. Gen. Kevin Byrnes. But formally Ignatov had been taking
orders from Krivolapov as a special deputy to Clark.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, allied diplomats said, the Russians will have a
high-ranking officer who will be a special deputy to Jackson in his
role as commander of the British contingent. That will allow the
Russians to maintain that they are technically not subordinating
their troops to NATO orders. At least, allied diplomats said, it
will mean that Moscow, after a two-month freeze, is finally willing
to resume relations, good or bad, with the alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 2128EDT &QL; 
