<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1501 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIGS-MIGS_SFCHRON &LR;      06-18 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIGS-MIGS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 War Birds Without Talons  &HT;     By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
To Randy Howell and Jerry Gallud, the MiG-17s that they will be
flying this weekend at the Moffett Air Show are the airborne
equivalents of 1950s muscle cars. Eye-catching, fire-spitting
aerobatic hot rods that climb like rockets and descend at speeds
that could rip a hole in the sound barrier (if the FAA would let
them).
<P>
   Two years ago, the United Airlines pilots who have been
waterskiing buddies for 20 years and have been flying stunt planes
for most of that time, heard that an aviator friend had run across
four snub-nosed MiG-17 fighters that had been decommissioned by the
Polish air force and were for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want four MiG-17s,'' Howell says with a sigh. ``I
really only wanted one, but it was pretty much a package deal.''
</P>
<P>
   After thousands of hours of labor and an undisclosed investment,
the two pilots finally have the fighter jets on in &LR;   &LR; the air show
circuit. To help fund their passion, the fliers recently signed a
deal with Stolichnaya, a Russian vodka company. ``Stoli'' will
cover MiG costs in exchange for exclusive promotional rights.
</P>
<P>
   Repainted a flaming red last month to match the scarlet on
Stolichnaya labels, the jets were rechristened the ``Stoli MiGs''
early this month and made their debut at the Paso Robles Air Show
in San Louis Obispo County.
</P>
<P>
   For Howell and Gallud, the course they have traveled the past
two years could not have been summarized in a single flight plan.
It has involved lots of side trips and course corrections.
</P>
<P>
   It started when they first heard the MiGs were on the auction
block. They were among the thousands of Mikoyan-Gurevich (``MiG'')
war birds built by the Soviet Union after following &LR;   &LR; World War II
and dispatched to Soviet flying forces and allies in Eastern
Europe, North Korea, North Vietnam, Cuba and China.
</P>
<P>
   For two generations of American and NATO fliers, MiGs were the
nemesis, the shadowy, nimble fighters to be feared and outfoxed.
But, with the collapse of the Soviet Union, a small number of the
planes began showing up on the collectors' market. Howell bought a
MiG trainer jet, an L-29, six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  According to the Federal Aviation Administration, there are
20 MiGs in private hands in the United States. They are listed on
the FAA's civil aircraft registry.
</P>
<P>
   For a price they will not disclose, Howell and Gallud grabbed
all four Cold War relics, not really having any idea what it would
cost to get them flying again or how they would pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   They were disassembled and shipped in 40-foot containers to the
Port of Oakland, where federal agents for the Department &LR;   &LR; Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms disabled the planes' 23mm and 37mm
guns. From Oakland, the aeronautic oddities were transported to the
pilots' hangar at Byron Airport, nestled in a break in the Contra
Costa County hills. beyond Livermore. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Word spread quickly, from aviator to aviator, that four MiGs
were being refurbished in Byron. Steve Magnuson, a former jet
mechanic for United Airlines, came for a look and wound up spending
hundreds of hours helping rebuild the late '50s planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was remarkable to see a piece of history sitting in the
hangar. Real MiGs,'' says Magnuson who has since become Howell and
Gallud's crew chief, responsible for maintaining the jets and
prepping them for air shows. ``They were in such rough shape I
didn't think they'd ever fly again.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting MiGs certified to fly in U.S. airspace is not easy. It
took 4,000 four thousand  &LR; hours of labor to get the first two MiGs
in flying shape. In addition to big things like rebuilding the jet
engines, there were myriad small tasks like relabeling the Cyrillic
control panels in the single-seater jets.
</P>
<P>
   As the planes got close to being ready to fly, Howell and Gallud
began training on an older-generation MiG-15 two-seater they found
in Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural flights, though long anticipated, were not exactly
joyrides. After taking the jets up, the men went through a lengthy
checklist of maneuvers, each learning his plane's exact
characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an awesome feeling,'' says Howell. ``To finally be in
the air.''
</P>
<P>
   On successive flights, Howell and Gallud practiced the aerobatic
maneuvers that now are part of the team's performance repertoire:
loops, vertical rolls, crossover passes and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   All technical systems were go, but there was a major financial
glitch at Red Star Airshows, the company they formed. MiGs, unlike
muscle cars, can't be topped off for $20.
</P>
<P>
   The pugnacious-looking jets, with 7,900 pounds of thrust, guzzle
1,000 gallons of jet fuel an hour compared with 12 to 15 gallons
for the small stunt planes the pilots had flown at other air shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would definitely go broke if we were trying to keep them
flying with the money we make at air shows,'' says Gallud, who,
like Howell, learned to fly by taking private flight lessons, not
by joining the Navy or Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   The motto of the flying community might as well be ``Will fly
for fuel,'' since many performers make appearances in exchange for
nothing more than a hotel room and jet fuel.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that they needed a corporate sponsor to cover
hangar and crew team costs. They hired a New York promotions firm
and, this spring, Stolichnaya agreed to sponsor the flying team
under a one-year contract with an option to renew.
</P>
<P>
   For Stolichnaya, the fit seemed as natural as an olive in a
martini glass.
</P>
<P>
   The No.5 vodka in the United States, Stolichnaya is being
marketed to 21-to-34-year-old drinkers who gravitate toward premium
spirits like ``Stoli'' and Absolut, the No.2 brand, that sell for
twice as much as market-leading Smirnoff.
</P>
<P>
   United Distillers and Vintners, the British-owned company that
markets Stolichnaya in this country, is trying to develop a hip
image for Stolichnaya, using contemporary Russian art in its
advertisements that say the vodka is ``as authentic as the soul of
Russia herself.''
</P>
<P>
   When he heard the MiG pilots were looking for a corporate
sponsor, United Distillers executive Peter Heyworth was enormously
intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MiG is an icon of Russia and Stolichnaya is an authentic
Russian product with a lot of heritage,'' says Heyworth. ``It's not
often in marketing that you get such a close fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they were not feeling very picky about patrons, the
pilots nevertheless were relieved when Stoli came forward.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Heyworth was surprised to discover there are not
many corporate sponsorships of air shows or stunt teams. ``It's one
of the few uncluttered media left,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Moffett Field, the MiGs will do fly overs &LR; 
 &LR; flyovers next Sunday at the San Francisco gay pride parade, for
which Stolichnaya is major sponsor, and will perform a 10-minute
stunt routine at the Marysville Air Show in Yuba County, also next
weekend. Other appearances are listed on their site on the World
Wide Web at  &LR; redstarmigs.com &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   Like championship wresting, air show promoters find it
irresistible to have Yankee fighters like the F-86cq  &LR;  fly with its
alter ego, the MiG-17. Hokey, perhaps, but Howell and Gallud aren't
complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get to go up and pull some G's,'' says Howell. ``We
couldn't be happier.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
