u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WCUP-386&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      06-18 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-386&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN ' S WORLD CUP IS A BIG-STADIUM SELLOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup of soccer, once planned for small stadiums
on the East Coast, will instead open Saturday before what is
expected to be the largest audience ever to attend a female
sporting event in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   All 77,716 seats at Giants Stadium have been sold for a
doubleheader featuring the United States versus Denmark and Brazil
versus Mexico, organizers said Friday. That total surpasses the
76,489 who attended the gold-medal game at the 1996 Summer
Olympics, where the American women prevailed over China in Athens,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   That Olympic crowd, many have argued, was inflated by the
ravenous desire of spectators to attend any available event at the
Summer Games. But the World Cup is a stand-alone tournament, and
Saturday's sellout amounts to an affirmation of the insistent
belief of American players and organizers that women's sports can
attract a mass audience. A second doubleheader Saturday, China
versus Sweden and Japan versus Canada, is expected to fill 20,000
of the 26,000 seats at Spartan Stadium in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' said Julie Foudy, the American co-captain. ``We've
been predicting this all along. The biggest hindrance in promoting
the women's game is that they're afraid it won't draw. I hope this
encourages people to put on other events like this, not just for
soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   However, even Marla Messing, president of the Women's World Cup
organizing committee, admitted Friday that she stepped onto a risky
limb in the fall of 1997, when she announced that the 16-team
tournament would be moved from small stadiums to the same cavernous
football arenas used for the men's World Cup in 1994. Some senior
soccer officials in the United States thought the idea of filling
big stadiums was ludicrous and that organizers were setting
themselves up for a huge embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hanging out there,'' Messing said. ``I said we would
have sellouts or near-sellouts. I felt certain about the
near-sellouts. But actually selling out a big stadium, I don't
think I ever envisioned that.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Joseph (Sepp) Blatter, who has since become
president of FIFA, soccer's world governing body, declared that
``the future is feminine.'' But even Blatter could not have
realized that the possibilities would be so immediate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Organizers have sold more than 460,000 tickets so far to the
Women's World Cup, which eclipses the 300,527 tickets sold for the
1999 women's collegiate basketball tournament, the previous
standard for women's sporting events in the United States. A sale
of half a million tickets has been predicted, and there is a
confident feeling that the attendance of 510,000 at the inaugural
Women's World Cup in China in 1991 will be surpassed, making the
1999 World Cup the largest sporting event ever held for women. The
China figure is considered unreliable anyway, because workers were
given tickets and told to attend matches.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States reaches the final on July 10, as expected,
organizers believe they can sell out the Rose Bowl's 92,542 seats,
a number made more impressive by the fact that only 113,000 tickets
were sold to the entire 1995 Women's World Cup in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   While NBC showed only highlights of the American soccer team
winning the gold medal in 1996, all 32 matches of the 1999 Women's
World Cup will be telecast by ABC, ESPN and ESPN2. A cumulative
worldwide television audience of 1 billion is expected, organizers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a look into the future,'' said Tony DiCicco, coach of
the women's national team. ``We are only scratching the surface
with women's athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the buoyant expectations, however, the success of the
1999 Women's World Cup is pegged largely on the success of the
American women, who managed only a bronze medal in 1995 after
losing to Norway, the eventual champion, in the semifinals. In the
unlikely event of an early American exit, interest would likely
plummet and the event could become a financial and public relations
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the U.S. is in the final, we think we can sell out the Rose
Bowl,'' said Alan I. Rothenberg, the chief organizer of the 1994
men's World Cup and chairman of the 1999 Women's World Cup. ``If
they don't, there will be fewer people because some of us will have
slit our throats.''
</P>
<P>
   An early failure by the Americans could also ruin the cautious
hopes for a women's professional league in the United States,
beginning in 2001. Even a victory by the United States, however,
won't guarantee the viability of a women's league. One of the
professional women's basketball leagues has gone under, and the
surviving Women's National Basketball Association exists with the
support of the strongly entrenched NBA Major League Soccer, the
nascent men's league, is still struggling to maintain itself and
may not be capable of starting a women's division.
</P>
<P>
   The American women feel a professional league is vital to their
continued success. The rest of the world is catching up in terms of
finances and participation; countries such as Germany, Japan and
Brazil have thriving women's soccer leagues. In the United States,
by contrast, there is nothing to sustain female players after
college if they do not make the national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's imperative that a league happen for women's soccer to
continue to compete at this level,'' said defender Joy Fawcett.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams in the Women's World Cup are looking to increase the
visibility of the game in their countries and, in the case of some,
are looking to eradicate negative stereotypes about women playing
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexican women have always been behind soccer, mostly as
spectators, and they have taken a beating _ not physically, but
emotionally _ depending on how their men's favorite team did,''
said Leo Cuellar, coach of the Mexican women's team. ``I think
millions of Latin women are looking for ways to express themselves.
Soccer is a way to say: `I'm tired of being behind. I want to put
on the shorts and shoes and shirt and go out and kick the ball.'''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating Saturday's sellout, the American women have
practiced recently with simulated crowd noise, getting accustomed
to signaling each other when it becomes impossible to hear the ball
being kicked or a teammate shouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a huge advantage to play in front of a
crowd that's 99.9 percent American,'' said goalkeeper Briana
Scurry. ``Denmark could come out shellshocked to see the crowd. If
they aren't ready, it could be a long afternoon.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
