<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGE-FUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-TERM CAPITAL PLANS TO CASH OUT ORIGINAL INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital Management, the giant celebrity-studded hedge
fund whose near-collapse last fall sparked concerns about an
impending global market failure, is preparing to redeem investments
made five years ago by its original outside partners, wealthy
individuals and institutions that will wind up getting, on average,
considerably less than they would have earned in a plain-vanilla
stock index mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter distributed on Wednesday, Long-Term Capital, based
in Greenwich, Conn., notified its original 1994 investors that it
would cash out their stake in the $4.7 billion fund ``in the near
future.''
</P>
<P>
   That redemption, combined with cash distributed to those
investors at the end of 1997, will produce a total average annual
return of roughly 18.7 percent. During the same five-year period,
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index gained an average of 26.48
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the fund's return does not include the debatable
value of a ringside seat at one of capitalism's most exciting
eleventh-hour rescues.
</P>
<P>
   And while the payment will close the books on the original
investors' experience, it is not clear how this drama will end for
the fund's rescuers, some of Wall Street's largest institutions,
and for its founding partners, who are already discussing forming a
new money-management venture.
</P>
<P>
   The hedge fund, founded in mid-1994 by a bond-market star, John
Meriwether of Salomon Brothers, seemed to be touched by magic in
its first three years of operation, enhancing Meriwether's already
formidable reputation and generating wealth for his partners, who
included two Nobel Prize-winning economists.
</P>
<P>
   Every dollar invested in the fund in 1994 was worth $2.82 by the
end of 1997, when $1.82 of those gains were distributed to outside
investors.
</P>
<P>
   As 1998 opened, the fund's managers had combined the $4.8
billion left in the fund with oceans of borrowed cash to accumulate
a staggeringly complex portfolio worth about $125 billion. The
portfolio was intended largely to exploit small deviations in the
historic relationships among various interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   But in August, a debt crisis in Russia set off a worldwide
scramble for the safety of U.S. Treasury securities, distorting
interest-rate patterns. The hedge fund's interest-rate bets
suddenly began to plunge in value, ultimately wiping out 91 cents
of every dollar that had been left in the fund at the beginning of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   By late September, regulators were confronted with the
possibility that the sudden liquidation of the hedge fund's huge
portfolio would touch off panic in an already fragile and
frightened global marketplace. Consequently, officials at the New
York Federal Reserve Bank helped 14 banks and brokerage houses form
a consortium to make an emergency $3.6 billion investment in the
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan the rescuers got a 90 percent stake in the fund,
reducing the original outside investors' stake to just under 10
percent, with Meriwether and the other managing partners retaining
only a tiny sliver of equity.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, markets have stabilized, and the fund has steadily
reduced the riskiness of its holdings and improved its investment
results. It announced in March that it had gained roughly 20
percent since the bailout, and that it expected to be able to
return some of its rescuers' capital later this year.
</P>
<P>
   People briefed on the fund's plan said that Wednesday's letter
was an outgrowth of the plan to return capital to the consortium.
</P>
<P>
   But, in addition, the redemption moved Meriwether slightly
closer to the day when he could be free of the consortium's
involvement in the fund he founded. In addition to cashing out the
original investors, the fund will also be making a partial payment
to the consortium that bailed it out in September.
</P>
<P>
   One person familiar with the plan said that somewhere in the
neighborhood of $500 million would be distributed to the
consortium, which includes Bankers Trust Corp., Chase Manhattan
Corp., Goldman Sachs Group, Lehman Brothers Holdings, Merrill Lynch
&AMP; Co., J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co., and
Citigroup, along with six European banks.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone involved with hedge fund will fare as well as the
original investors, who included top Wall Street executives, as
well as a unit of the Bank of Italy. Various Merrill Lynch
executives in that company's deferred compensation plan began tying
their future earnings to the then-impressive hedge fund's results
in April 1998 _ rather like boarding the Titanic just in time for
the iceberg collision. They missed the handsome cash distributions,
and apparently will suffer the full damage of the subsequent
meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Meriwether and the other founding partners of
Long-Term Capital also saw their equity in the fund virtually
evaporate in the course of last fall's rescue.
</P>
<P>
   But the damage done to the bank accounts and professional
reputations of the founding partners does not seem to have
dissolved the glue that binds them to Meriwether.
</P>
<P>
   People who have been told the contents of e-mail that has
circulated at the fund's offices in Greenwich say that at least
five of Meriwether's original colleagues from the Salomon Brothers
bond desk _ Eric Rosenfeld, Lawrence Hilibrand, Richard Leahy,
Victor Hagani and Arjun Krishnamachar _ have agreed to join him in
exploring the possibility of forming some new investment venture
within the next six to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely that this new venture will be approaching potential
sources of investment capital later this year, these people said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who will not be joining Meriwether's faithful band
will be David Mullins Jr., who quit as vice chairman of the Federal
Reserve to become a partner in Long-Term Capital. Two other jewels
in Meriwether's crown, the Nobel laureate economists Myron Scholes
and Robert Merton, have already left the fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
