<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1514 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-POLICE-NYT &LR;      06-18 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHICAGO, BLACK POLICE AND VICTIMS, DEFY PATTERN OF RACISM
CHARGES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Chicago police superintendent, responding to
charges of racism in the department after the fatal shootings of
two unarmed blacks here during traffic stops, said that officers
had violated department policy and announced that video cameras
would be placed in patrol cars.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent, Terry Hillard, spoke on Thursday when he was
summoned to appear before a committee of the City Council after
protests this week near police headquarters denouncing racism and
``police brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cases do not fit a familiar racial pattern: the officers
who fired the shots were black.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings have caused an uproar on the City Council,
especially among black politicians who say a climate of racism can
even taint the judgment of black police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Hillard, who is black and has criticized how the police handled
the cases _ five officers have been notified that they will face
charges of violating police rules _ said the installation of video
cameras was ``not only for the safety of the citizens, but for the
police officers, to dispel some of the rumors that the entire
Chicago Police Department is corrupt, abusive and using excessive
force day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing before a City Council committee, Hillard said
that a preliminary investigation showed that the death of LaTanya
Haggerty, 26, on June 4, happened after four officers ignored an
order to stop pursuing a car that had fled a traffic stop. Ms.
Haggerty was a passenger in the car and was shot after an officer
mistook her cellular phone for a gun, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second incident, a Northwestern University football
player, Robert Russ, 22, was shot on June 5 after the police say he
grabbed an officer's gun, which had been pointed inside his car
after the police knocked the glass out of his car window following
a car chase. Hillard said the officer had acted improperly by using
a lug wrench to knock out a window in Russ' car.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after the hearing, Hillard said he had asked
prosecutors to investigate a third case, the death of a man in a
struggle with police officers. The man, Gregory Ryan, 31, who was
suspected of drug dealing, died on Monday night after he fell to a
sidewalk on the city's West Side. The Cook County Coroner's Office
ruled the death a homicide Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hillard has bristled at suggestions of racism in the cases,
noting that the Police Department has rules against stopping
drivers simply because they are black, a practice sometimes called
``racial profiling.'' But he has acknowledged that the department
has a credibility gap with many of the city's black residents.
</P>
<P>
   The city's police union has defended the officers in the cases,
saying it is unfair to second-guess the actions of officers who
know the dangers of the streets and realize that a delay of a
second can mean being killed.
</P>
<P>
   But Ronald Hampton, the executive director of the National Black
Police Association in Washington, said it was impossible to ignore
the harsher treatment meted out to blacks, even by black police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception that gets drummed into everybody's head is that
everyone in a black community is dangerous,'' said Hampton, a
retired Washington police officer. ``Even people of color start
believing the myths.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said it was naive for cities to believe that racial
diversity alone would bring fair treatment to blacks, especially
those in poorer neighborhoods. ``If you're a black police officer
who wants to be successful, who wants to get ahead,'' he said,
``you're going to take on the thinking of the institution'' and act
especially tough with people in black neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Hampton added, many blacks distrust black
police officers. ``To black people, policing in America goes back
to slavery,'' he said. ``And so people tend to be skeptical of a
young person who joins the police force. They'll say, `He's part of
the system now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks account for about 25 percent of the officers on the
Chicago Police Department. Blacks make up nearly 40 percent of the
city's population.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard M. Daley, who in 1998 appointed Hillard to lead
the Police Department, has said the Russ and Haggerty cases have
``chipped'' the relationship between the police and people in the
neighborhoods. Daley said the families of the people killed by the
officers deserve ``a full explanation,'' and he said they would get
it ``very shortly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
