<HEADER>
A1515 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-THRASHERS19-COX     06-18 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers net a goalie
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Thrashers general manager Don Waddell has
secured one of the goalies most people thought he would take in
next week's expansion draft _ only he didn't wait for the expansion
draft.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of what figures to be a series of complex trades in
the next week, the Thrashers Friday acquired Ottawa goalie Damian
Rhodes for future considerations. Rhodes, who would have been a
free agent, immediately signed a four-year contract believed to be
worth approximately $9 million, although it has not yet been filed
with the NHL Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the guys we've watched a lot,'' Waddell said. ``He
doesn't panic, and as an expansion team you can assume he'll see a
lot of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes is the Thrashers' first player and probably will be their
starting goaltender next season, pending the outcome of the
expansion draft. He shared starting duties on the Senators last
season with Ron Tugnutt and posted a record of 22-13-7 with a 2.44
goals against average and a .905 saves percentage.
</P>
<P>
   But Rhodes said he grew weary of coach Jacques Martin's goalie
rotation, in which each started two games in a surprising
first-round playoff sweep by Buffalo. He allowed six goals on 65
shots (.908) in his two playoff losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't getting the amount of playing time I wanted in
Ottawa, but I didn't want to say anything and rock the boat,''
Rhodes said. ``This year neither one of us could get in a groove.''
</P>
<P>
   On going from a team that finished with the third-best record in
the regular season (44-23-15) to an expansion club, Rhodes said,
``That's the hardest part about it. But I'll get more work in. I
was only seeing about 15 or 20 shots a game in Ottawa.''
</P>
<P>
   By trading for Rhodes rather than drafting him next week, the
Thrashers still can select the maximum five goalies in the
expansion draft next Friday. In return, Atlanta agreed to select an
Ottawa player in the draft from a list provided by the Senators.
The Senators could not afford to re-sign Rhodes, who earned $1.6
million this season, but wanted something in return. They were
concerned that the Thrashers might not want to use an expansion
pick on Rhodes because he was unsigned.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers can draft as many as six free agents, but only one
can be a goalie. If they take a free agent but fail to sign him,
they receive a compensatory pick in next year's amateur draft.
</P>
<P>
   Trading for Rhodes leaves Waddell with more options. Waddell
first contacted then-Ottawa general manager Rick Dudley on June 2
about a possible deal. But talks were put on hold when Dudley left
for Tampa Bay. Waddell resumed conversations with new Senators
general manager Marshall Johnston earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great opportunity for us,'' Waddell said. ``We've
talked all year about building around goaltending and we feel
comfortable that we'll go into our first season with one of the top
goaltenders in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
