</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WOMEN'S SOCCER TRYING TO CRACK A GRANITE WALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great Pele was surrounded by children and besieged by
adults. For a moment he was the acrobatic Cosmos' star at midfield,
surrounded, seemingly trapped. As a player he would simply spin.
Accelerate, explode and score. On this bright afternoon, there was
no escape _ everywhere Pele turned there were love and
reminiscences.
</P>
<P>
   This was Friday afternoon, on the lawn of the U.N. building, on
the eve of the Women's World Cup soccer tournament. U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and FIFA President Joseph (Sepp)
Blatter announced a partnership to promote world peace. After the
announcement, Pele was mobbed, by children not even born when he
had scored his final goal and by parents who have vivid memories of
each electric moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped playing soccer so many years ago, but the kids,
generation after generation, still love me,'' Pele said. ``It's a
privilege granted by the gods.''
</P>
<P>
   Soccer in the United States has made major strides between
Pele's last goal and his appearance Friday, when the United Nations
announced a partnership between the U.N. and FIFA. There is a
significant difference in the atmosphere surrounding soccer. During
the 1970s and '80s, Pele was the battering ram for men's soccer as
the sport tried to take a share of a market dominated by American
football, baseball and basketball. Soccer couldn't crack that
granite wall.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, women's soccer has achieved a level of success the men
never dreamed of. Behold the miracle: Giants Stadium sold out
Saturday as the women's tournament begins. The United States and
Denmark will play in the opening match, a game that is critical not
merely for want of a championship, but for the continued growth of
women's soccer in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The women desperately need a league, and they have earned that
right with their performance. Female basketball players have a
league of their own _ the Women's National Basketball Association _
which largely piggybacks off the NBA. The jury is still out,
however, on whether there is enough interest to sustain that league
_ the American Basketball League, another women's professional
league, folded in December. The level of athleticism in women's
basketball games has hit a striking new gear. But, whether it's
right or wrong, the women's game _ based largely on fundamentals
and finesse _ still suffers by comparison to the men's game, a more
explosive game played largely above the rim.
</P>
<P>
   Women's soccer in the United States can stand on its own. In
fact, the women have done far better in international competition
than the American men. This is in large part because of the battle
for men's bodies among football, baseball and basketball. Those
sports have an extensive conveyor-belt system that cultivates and
delivers athletes to major league sports through an intricate
network. Women are largely excluded from these football and
baseball tributaries. The chauvinism of football and baseball has
backed those sports into a corner. How much longer will women
support what they can't participate in?
</P>
<P>
   Increasing numbers of women are flowing into basketball and
soccer, creating an expanding talent base and a widening spectator
base as well. ``Four years ago I predicted that the future of
football will be women,'' Blatter said. ``I said that in 10 years
we will have as many girls playing the game as boys.''
</P>
<P>
   As Pele signed autographs in the middle of a throng of bodies,
Nene, the star of the women's Brazilian national team, waited on
the periphery of the crowd for her own autograph. Pele was her
hero, too. She was a little girl when he signed his first
professional contract at age 17. There were no female role models;
female participation was discouraged. ``He motivated me, at a young
age, to train,'' Nene said. ``I became one of the few players that
participated in my first World Cup at 17. Once I accomplished that
I kept going and going. Now I am on my third World Cup. ``
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Annan called soccer the only true global sport. In fact
basketball has become a global sport as well, and both sports are
beginning to draw talent from the same sources: suburban areas and
increasingly the inner cities. The subsequent battle for bodies
between women's basketball and women's soccer will be fascinating
to observe, with each sport becoming richer for the battle.
</P>
<P>
   There is mighty symbolism in Giants Stadium this evening,
American football being shoved aside for a day by real football.
``This is the reality,'' Pele said. ``This is not the future _ this
is reality today. In the United States, where people supposedly
don't play soccer but play football, you see Giants Stadium sold
out for a women's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer in the United States, between the kids and the women,
is one more pastime. That's a reality.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
