<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1517 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     06-18 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WINDOW FOR WOODS SEEMS WIDE ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ His tee shot, as he likes to say, had ``flamed
out'' to the right into the tall pines on the Pinehurst No. 2
course's 485-yard par-4 eighth hole, but when Tiger Woods got to
his ball, he knew he had a shot off the pine straw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a little window; I could fit a ball through there pretty
easily,'' he said. ``It was only about 3 feet, but it was plenty
wide from the distance I had to work with. I just tried to hit a
nice, drawing 8-iron. I had 146 yards to the right bowl in the
green. I hit it pin-high to the bowl, two-putted and walked out of
there very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the 610-yard 10th hole, Woods' 2-iron second shot stopped in
a swale short of the green, some 50 feet from the pin. His chip
with a 3-wood rolled up the slope and across the green to within 8
inches. Birdie.
</P>
<P>
   With those two shots helping to preserve his one-over-par 71
Friday, 23-year-old Tiger Woods was at 139 in this United States
Open _ his lowest 36-hole score in his five Open appearances. His
best previous score halfway through an Open was 141, at
Congressional two years ago, when he finished at 289 and tied for
19th. At Olympic last year, he shot 290, tied for 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased just to be under par,'' he said. ``In the
Open, you have to hang in there. You have to keep grinding it out
and making the pars, but the guys will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The guys weren't that far away. David Duval, Phil Mickelson and
Payne Stewart shared the lead, only two strokes ahead of Woods. In
Saturday's third round, Woods will be playing with Mickelson in the
next-to-last twosome, ahead of Stewart and Duval.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Open and PGA Tour rules, Stewart, the first to
finish at 139, was paired with Duval instead of Mickelson, because
Duval was listed first in Group 33 in Friday's starting times,
ahead of Carlos Franco and Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   Theatrically, a Duval-Woods pairing would have provided a rare
mano a mano between No. 1 (Duval) and No. 2 (Woods) in the world
ranking, with the third-round Open lead up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   But depending on their scores Saturday, a Woods-Duval pairing
could develop for Sunday's final round, as each player pursues his
first United States Open title.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the leaders, Woods has been the hottest golfer lately,
arriving here as a co-favorite with Duval after having won his
previous two tournaments _the Deutsche Bank SAP Open in Germany and
the Memorial at Muirfield Village outside Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thought process is still the same as it's been in the Open,
trying to make pars, just that my execution is a lot better,'' he
said. ``I didn't have the shots that I did in my other Opens. Even
last year at Olympic, I did not have the shots I have now.''
</P>
<P>
   On the PGA Tour this year, he has already won nearly $1.9
million, winning the Buick Invitational and the Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lot better than I was in other years,'' he said. ``My
game is better. My swing is better. I'm stronger than I've ever
been. Different things have contributed to my good play, but more
important, I think it's the revamping of my swing that really feels
good. I wasn't happy with '97 because I was so inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Woods earned $1.8 million on the PGA Tour last year, he
won only once, at the Bell South Classic in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was frustrating,'' he said. ``I wasn't that far
away. I was finishing in top 10's, but I wasn't getting the W's
because my swing wasn't as good as it is now.''
</P>
<P>
   On the range before Friday's round, Woods hit balls as Butch
Harmon, his swing guru, watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got back in good position again, then went out there and hit
the same way as I did on the range,'' Woods said. ``To be able to
carry what you worked out on the range out on the golf course, that
definitely builds confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Tiger Woods was asked if he were looking at the leader
boards, he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you,'' he said, ``I don't really care what
they're doing because I can't afford to. I need to play my own game
and get myself into contention and keep executing my shots. It's
not where it's a showdown between two or three players right now.
You can focus on that when you have two or three holes left on
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   As if he had no doubt that he'll be there on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
