   (NYT34) SAN ANTONIO, Texas -- June 18, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-SPURS,
6-18 --Texas Gov. George W. Bush and the filmmaker Spike Lee
exchange greetings before game two of the NBA Finals on Friday at
the Alamodome in San Antonio. The San Antonio Spurs defeated the
New York Knicks 89-77 in the first game of series. (Jerry Lara/San
Antonio Express News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- June 18, 1999 -- COKE-EUROPE, 6-18 -- Since
a number of Belgians fell ill after drinking Coke last week, M.
Douglas Ivester, the chairman and chief executive of the Coca-Cola
Co., has been trying to assure the public and government officials
that his product is safe. But he is being criticized as slow to
respond to a crisis, one that increasingly appears to be born of
panic rather than reports of serious illness. (Don Hogan
Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- June 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 20 --
INVEST-INTERNET-B&AMP;W, 6-18 -- Lawrence York, a portfolio manager,
believes investors are likely to stick with their holdings in
Internet funds. Until investors ``see a real blowup in the economy,
I think they're going to stay hard and fast,'' he says. While
Internet stocks, and the funds that invest in them, have plunged in
the last two months, fund investors have not fled - as so often
happens when a sector is slammed so quickly. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) GRYKA E NEKOVCIT, Yugoslavia -- June 18, 1999 --
KOSOVO-HILLS, 6-18 -- Faik Thachi outside what is left of his home
on Thursday after returning from hiding. No one is certain how many
Kosovo Albanians managed to hide in the woods to avoid Serb forces
and artillery fire. But Thachi and his family were among the
thousands who managed to stay out of harm's way in this region.
(Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- June 18, 1999 -- SOC-WCUP-GROWTH, 6-18 --
Members of the ``Urban Soccer Girl'' program practice at Corporal
Thompson Park on Staten Island on Thursday. The practice, sponsored
by organizers the Women's World Cup, was part of a week-long clinic
to introduce soccer to urban children. Saturday's match between the
United States and Demark at Giant Stadium in New Jersey will
inaugurate competition for the Women's World Cup. (James Estrin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- June 18, 1999 -- STOLEN-BOOKS, 6-18 -- The
books of choice for shoplifters include the Bible as well as works
by Beats like William Burroughs, Jack Kerouac, and Allen Ginsberg.
Many bookstore owners were reluctant even to acknowledge theft, but
it exists, and the favorites remain remarkably consistent
worldwide. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
