<P>
   (NYT22) LONDON -- June 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 20 --
BIZ-WORLD-BRITAIN, 6-18 -- Richard Olivier (Yes, he is the son of
Laurence) runs management seminars at the Globe Theater that
translate Shakespeare into business lessons. For $1,800, British
executives can spend a weekend at the Globe Theater being tutored
in management skills through the prism of Shakespeare's plays -
notably ``Henry V'' and ``Julius Caesar.'' ``The use of language to
make the future real - that, to me, is one of the key skills of
leadership,'' he says. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- June 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 20 --
ABOUT-CARS-SAAB, 6-18 -- The Saab 9-5 has joined a number of
European luxury wagons in the competition for a portion of the
market in the United States. Audi, BMW, Mercedes, Volvo and now
Saab have unveiled ``sport wagons'' aimed at buyers who want a
little more than a trunk but would rather walk than ride in a
four-wheel drive Exterminator, or whatever Detroit is calling its
latest brute ute. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- June 18, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JUNE 20 --
CAR-SMART-PETS, 6-18 -- Saab's pet accessories include a special
leash that can be secured to a cargo track. Saab says its research
has found that 60 percent of its American customers are pet owners
- the highest percentage in the auto industry. And when these Saab
owners take to the road, they say there is a good chance their
Saint Bernard or Siamese will go along for the ride. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) PUEBLA, Mexico -- June 18, 1999 -- MEXICO-QUAKE-2-COX,
06-18 -- The bell tower of the San Agustin Church was shredded
Tuesday during the 6.7 earthquake that struck the area. The church,
whose original structure dates back to the late 1500's, may fare
better than many Puebla residents initially thought. Rubble from a
collapsed bell tower is primarily material that was added as late
as the 19th century, and much of the original tower survived.
(Sergio Dorantes/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) PUEBLA, Mexico -- June 18, 1999 -- MEXICO-QUAKE-1-COX,
06-18 -- Members of the San Geronimo church begin to clear a floor
full of rubble that fell from the walls and ceiling during the 6.7
earthquake that struck Mexico Tuesday. In Puebla's colonial center,
initial estimates are that the quake damaged 33 historic churches,
32 public buildings and six Autonomous University of Puebla
structures. (Sergio Dorantes/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
