</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP619-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sabres don't want view of Cup tonight
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ In the final minutes of a game in Dallas the
other night, a faux Stanley Cup constructed of cardboard and
aluminum foil was tossed from the stands into the Buffalo Sabres'
bench.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought the Sabres, given their dire situation, did not
find the faux Cup amusing, imagine what their reaction will be if
they see the real thing tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Buffalo nor Dallas has ever won a Stanley Cup. But the
Stars, who lead the series 3-2, can celebrate with a victory on the
Sabres' home ice tonight at Marine Midland Arena. It would be a
painful flashback for the Sabres, who in 1975 saw Philadelphia
close out its second Cup in the old Buffalo Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want that to happen in our building,'' said Sabres
coach Lindy Ruff. ``We'll do everything possible to force a Game 7
(in Dallas Tuesday). I truly believe you'll see our best game of
the series. We'll compete to the bitter end. It will be a game that
will sum up our community. We'll outwork them and outhit them and
do everything possible to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Appropriate that Ruff should invoke the community in his
comments. If the Sabres lose, the only Buffalo residents who might
feel some relief are current and former Bills, who lost four Super
Bowls and at least would have some company. Two of those losses
came to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we've been waiting for all year,'' said Stars
center Mike Modano, an original draft pick of the Minnesota North
Stars, who moved to Dallas. ``We knew it would take 16 wins in the
playoffs and we've got 15. The anticipation of waiting for the game
is getting overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Said veteran Guy Carbonneau, who played on two Stanley Cup teams
in Montreal, ``We played this year for the home ice advantage. But
we don't want to have to go to the seventh game to use it.''
</P>
<P>
   If they continue to get the kind of defense and goaltending from
Ed Belfour that they have, a win will come. The Sabres scored three
goals in their Game 1 victory but have only five in the four games
since. Buffalo also must play without defenseman Rhett Warrener,
who suffered a broken ankle in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres, meanwhile, sparked another war or words by calling
the Stars a dirty team. Center Michael Peca said, ``They have the
dirtiest team we've ever faced. I guess part of the thing about
experience is they know how to hide all their two-handed slashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said, ``They're a vicious team with their sticks. Like
(assistant coach) Mike Ramsey said, `On offense they use their soft
sticks and on defense they swing by the bench and pick up their
hatchets.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau's response: ``We expect to win. If they want to call
us cheap-shot players, let them. But we're going to do everything
we can to win games. We don't try to hurt anybody. But we have one
goal in mind: to win the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock accused Ruff of intentionally sending Warrener
(6-foot-1) to go after Dallas' Derian Hatcher (6-3) in the final
seconds. The two wrestled to the ice, and Warrener broke his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ruff, ``Be honest. If we wanted to go after somebody, are
we gonna go after Hatcher? We'll go after Carbonneau or Modano or
(Joe) Nieuwendyk. We're not going to send David after Goliath.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
