<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1527 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-BANK-$ADV20-ART-3T     06-18 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BANK-$ADV20-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BANKS GET BIGGER, A FEW STRUGGLE TO START ON A SMALLER, MORE
PERSONAL SCALE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Calif., Fla., N.C. )  (ART ADV: A graphic and a photo are being sent. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD KORMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCEVILLE, N.J. _ You might call it Russo's revenge.
</P>
<P>
   The Russo in question, Paul J., felt ignored by the $100 billion
bank where his family home-improvement business keeps its accounts.
Despite a hefty checking balance, he was often asked to produce two
forms of identification at the teller window. ``Not one person
knows my name,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last year, Russo was invited to help start a new bank in
this suburb near Princeton, a bank that would be based on friendly
service, not nationwide heft. Two local men _ a young banker and an
insurance executive _ were looking for investors, and Russo bought
in.
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of small-business people across the country
who are taking similar stands. Sweeping bank consolidation has left
many states, particularly New Jersey, California and Florida, with
a landscape of regional bank giants and tiny credit unions, and
little in between.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing opportunity in a long economic boom, organizers like
those who approached Russo have sought or won charters for 19 new
community banks in New Jersey since 1996. Nationally, there were
216 new bank charters granted in 1998, compared with 53 in 1994;
though no one keeps an exact count, bank experts presume that many
of these new institutions are community banks.
</P>
<P>
   The rallying cry for a lot of the new ventures is a Howard
Beale-like ``I'm not going to take this anymore,'' but banking is
no field for amateur enthusiasts with good Rotary Club connections.
Chartering a new bank is costly and time-consuming, requiring the
mobilization of market and technical expertise and the ability to
satisfy demanding regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part nowadays is raising capital. Small bank stocks
are out of favor, some of the last places many people would invest.
As a result, asking local merchants and neighbors to open their
wallets may not yield enough money, forcing organizers to turn to
wealthy, well-connected financial professionals who may be prone to
second-guessing a bank president at every bump in the road.
</P>
<P>
   Village Bank, the start-up that attracted Russo, is being
chartered in the name of customer service. But to reward its
investors and to survive, some analysts say, it will have to plunge
into the currents of deregulated financial services and swim
rapidly to assets of $75 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Even experienced bankers can find the going tough.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth J. Stephon, 40, hatched the idea for Village Bank and
helped convince Russo and others to invest their reputations, as
board members, as well as their money. Now, as the bank rides the
uncertainties of an initial public stock offering, Stephon must
work against a loudly ticking clock.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to know how close Village Bank's offering has
come to its goal so far _ Securities and Exchange Commission rules
prohibit the bank from saying. But after easily attracting $948,000
of seed capital, outfitting two small, well-situated offices and
hiring core staff, Village Bank failed to meet a self-imposed
eight-week deadline, on March 26, to raise the balance of the $5
million minimum capital required to open.
</P>
<P>
   As the bank's founders reach further into their webs of
neighbors, friends and relatives, the offering can seem more like a
charitable fund-raiser than a small-cap share placement.
</P>
<P>
   Rents, salaries and other costs, meanwhile, are eating through
the seed capital at a rate of more than $50,000 a month. According
to the bank's latest filing with the SEC, the initial $948,000 will
be exhausted by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   (Dick Wines, a partner in Capital Consultants of Princeton, who
is following Village Bank, says that if the organizers run out of
cash, they can go to the individual investors for more money or ask
some of the people who have bought shares to designate their
investment as seed money.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, the bank has until Dec. 7 to complete its offering.
Only then, if the necessary $5 million has not been raised, would
Village Bank die aborning, with the subscribers to the stock
offering getting their money back and the original seed-capital
investors eating the losses.
</P>
<P>
   Village Bank plans to offer low-fee checking, at least at the
outset, and ready access to the bank president. Many community
banks that have been chartered in the last few years have thrived
in just that way, by beating the big banks on price and service.
</P>
<P>
   But according to some bankers, the giants are responding more
quickly to competitive pressure. In New Jersey, for example, Summit
Bank, one of the state's largest, recently rolled back its minimum
balance for free checking from $1,000 to $99. Summit said it simply
wanted to provide more competitive products and accelerate deposit
growth. ``We consider ourselves 73 community banks that form
Summit,'' said Robert G. Cox, the bank's president.
</P>
<P>
   Another giant, First Union of Charlotte, N.C., which acquired a
big branch network in New Jersey when it bought First Fidelity in
1996, says it has introduced several programs geared toward small
business _ and a menu of ways for customers to invest small
deposits or balances.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say public disgust with poor service and high fees
alone are not enough to spur the creation of a new community bank.
</P>
<P>
   Steven A. Seelig, a researcher with the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. who has studied bank start-ups, said: ``Our results
show it's not just because Nationsbank or another comes in. You
have to have enough of a customer base to really make money at
it.'' That, and not mergers, is spawning the new banks, he added.
</P>
<P>
   (more)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Many of New Jersey's new banks are being chartered in its most
affluent neighborhoods, like the areas of Mercer County around
Princeton where Village Bank hopes to do business.
</P>
<P>
   Stephon does not see doing well and doing good as mutually
exclusive. ``There are economic motives in everything, except maybe
the Red Cross,'' he said. ``But we're not a group of capitalists
who said, `Where can we best deploy our funds?' We said, `There's
an absolute need for community services.' Economic opportunity is a
marvelous byproduct, not the impetus.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephon and Village Bank's chairman, William C. Hart, 65, have
been friends for years. Hart, currently chief executive of Mercer
Mutual Insurance, once ran Centennial Savings and Loan in
Pennington, N.J., where Stephon was a part-time management trainee.
Stephon later became chief executive of Cloverbank, a small, old
savings and loan association in Pennsauken, 40 miles from
Lawrenceville, where Hart served on the board. Both men cut their
ties to Cloverbank last year.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, 1998 was one of the best years in memory for
savings banks, with profits spiking on a steady diet of fees and a
healthy 1.01 percent return on assets, according to the FDIC. But
Stephon hungered for a more entrepreneurial banking style than
Cloverbank's conservative culture would allow. So for months, he
and Hart chewed over the idea of a new bank.
</P>
<P>
   The first choice they faced was what kind of bank charter to
seek. Mercer County was not underserved _ there are 39 bank
branches within four miles of Village Bank's headquarters. But most
of those are commercial banks or credit unions; locally owned
savings and loans have become an endangered species. A savings and
loan charter held another attraction: Stephon knew the regulatory
personnel at the Office of Thrift Supervision and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   So Village Bank is going the savings and loan route and will
focus its lending on mortgages and other real estate-backed loans.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be fooled by the apparent narrowness of the savings
and loan's mission. Village Bank's entrepreneurial intent is
embodied in its corporate form, a holding company called the
Village Financial Corp. with the bank as its only operating unit.
That structure allows the parent to offer a full range of financial
services, or to sell mutual funds and securities through
affiliates. The directors can sell Village Financial to a
nonbanking business, greatly widening the pool of possible
acquirers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To sign the needed investors and directors, Stephon and Hart got
busy networking in early 1998. They assembled a board, including a
local investment adviser, William V.R. Fogler; two of Fogler's
clients, Paul Russo and Jonathan R. Sachs, a gastroenterologist;
and George M. Taber, president of a regional magazine, Business
News New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   While that core group was forming, Hart got in touch with Fred
D. Price, a partner at a New York firm of banking industry
underwriters and consultants, Sandler, O'Neill &AMP; Partners. Price
lives in Cranbury, a 20-minute drive from Lawrenceville; Sandler,
O'Neill had done some consulting for Hart's firm, Mercer Mutual.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with Hart and Stephon, Price personally put in
$200,000, making him Village Bank's biggest investor.
</P>
<P>
   Price's involvement strikes some bank executives as a danger
signal. ``I wouldn't want to be CEO with him on board,'' said
Anthony S. Abbate, chief executive of Interchange Bank, a
successful community bank in Saddle Brook, N.J. ``People put money
up, but then they get antsy,'' he said, referring to investors like
Price. ``If you don't leverage up the capital, and guys are sitting
there who made investments and are not happy, you will see the CEO
turn over two or three times. It's not at all uncommon.''
</P>
<P>
   Other community bank executives said an investor like Price
might push Village Bank to engage in sophisticated financial
engineering that it may be ill-equipped to handle. Price has been
quoted in trade publications explaining the advantages of using
derivatives to limit banks' interest rate risk. Such instruments,
handled improperly, have been at the heart of some notable
financial disasters across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Price said any worries about his role at Village Bank stemmed
from misunderstandings. First, he said, derivatives have no
relevance for Village Bank because start-ups rarely have enough
assets with interest rate risk to justify hedging with derivatives.
(The Office of Thrift Supervision says that only a handful of
savings banks use derivatives, and they are all large banks.)
</P>
<P>
   Price also said he had invested in Village Bank because he
believes in community banking, not because he wants to be a
backseat driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intention to be on the board, and did not make this
investment to have any controlling or undue influence,'' he said;
rather, he wanted an investment on which ``my kids someday down the
road enjoy the return.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephon said he doesn't know Price well, but is pleased that
``one of the best banking minds in the country'' has a large vested
interest in the success of Village Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel privileged that he is involved,'' Stephon added. &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In the search for suitable premises, Village Bank got lucky.
Another bank was pulling out of a 3,952-square-foot branch on
Quakerbridge Road, convenient to the Quakerbridge Mall. Village
Bank took over the lease at an initial rent of $4,000 a month. A
counter with six teller stations was in place, and Village Bank
bought the furniture and vault from the departing tenant for
$35,000. Space for a second, limited-hours office was rented next
to a retirement housing complex in Pennington, near the homes of
several board members.
</P>
<P>
   The time had come to raise the rest of the $5 million minimum
capital. The board hired Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. to administer the
offering, which started last Feb. 3. The bank priced the shares at
$10 each with a $1,000 minimum, intending to issue 425,000 to 1.2
million shares, depending on demand. As chief executive, Stephon
will be one of the bigger shareholders if he exercises all of the
10,000 stock options granted under his contract.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall, other new community banks in New Jersey raised
capital with relative ease. After 14 organizers kicked in $1.8
million to seed Red Oak Bank in Morristown, new subscribers bought
shares worth $9.6 million within 10 weeks. Red Oak's chief
executive, Dale G. Potter, had piloted to success another community
bank in New Jersey, Growth Bank, in Harding Township; it has since
been absorbed by Hudson United Bank, a midsize bank in Union City.
</P>
<P>
   Hopewell Valley Community Bank, a close neighbor to Village
Bank, failed to meet the preliminary termination date for its
public share offering, Oct. 30, but only by a single day. Its total
equity capital has since risen to $7.8 million from $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Village Bank's offering is moving much more slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of holding a large community meeting _ a common
shareholder recruiting tactic _ Village Bank chose smaller,
roadshow-style meetings and advertised aggressively. It even
splurged on an ad in The Wall Street Journal, on the theory that
sophisticated investors might not see ads in local papers.
</P>
<P>
   The sales drive drew some undesired attention. When the offering
remained incomplete after the self-imposed March 26 deadline
passed, local news accounts raised questions whether Stephon had a
high-enough local profile to make the bank fly. Federal regulations
have prevented Stephon from saying publicly exactly how well the
offering is going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Village Bank is getting a lot of press, and I think that's
good news and bad news,'' said Wines of Capital Consultants of
Princeton. The March deadline was too optimistic, but it ``got
blown out of proportion,'' he said. Even so, the bank's
preoccupation has remained raising capital, in small meetings like
one held on April 14. Such meetings, Stephon said, communicate the
intimacy the bank hopes to embody.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun set, about 15 people gathered in the
living-room-sized employee cafeteria of the Mercer Mutual Life
Insurance building in Pennington. Outside, commuters clogged the
two-lane roads that embroider fallow pastures and strip-mall
parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Hart introduced Stephon, who made his presentation and
introduced each director. They stood like sentries around the
room's perimeter, jacket buttons resolutely fastened. During the
evening, each offered a personal horror story of what big bad banks
do.
</P>
<P>
   Sachs said his bank had done nothing to help his practice with
its annual year-end cash flow crunch. Fogler, the investment
adviser, was more scalding, saying he ``is totally disgusted'' with
the treatment from his bank _ including taking three months to fix
a minor problem with his checking account.
</P>
<P>
   Taber, the publisher, said the idea of getting personal service
from a bank based in Charlotte (a reference to First Union) was a
contradiction in terms.
</P>
<P>
   Village Bank, Stephon pledged, will never lose sight of its
customers. ``You will be able to reach me 24 hours a day, seven
days a week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the attendance was light, spirits were high. Most of the
prospects, it turned out, knew someone connected to Village Bank.
One was the chairman's sister; another had a daughter about to
start work at the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Christie, a New Jersey doctor, said he had known Bill
Hart for more than 30 years. Christie remembered that his uncle had
opened a $100 account for him at the long-departed Trenton Banking
Co. on May 6, 1931, the day he was born, and he said he planned to
subscribe to some Village Bank shares.
</P>
<P>
   Two months after the meeting, though, Christie hadn't sent in
his check. The bank is a great idea, he said, but ``I'm worried
about whether they are going to get the money.'' His accountant, he
added, had discouraged the investment, saying it was imprudent for
a man his age.
</P>
<P>
   The longer the offering remains open, the harder it is to
sustain an appearance of momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Russo wonders at investors' reluctance. ``If people are willing
to put money in an Internet stock with no earnings, then they ought
to be willing to invest in Village Bank,'' he said. ``They'll be
able to sleep at night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
