<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI CLOSES LOOPHOLE ON PURCHASES OF FIREARMS AT GUN SHOWS ON
STATE PROPERTY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki said Friday that he would
require a background check for anyone who buys a firearm at a gun
show held on state property.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's comments came after the House of Representatives
narrowly passed a measure to regulate the sales of weapons at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current federal laws, collectors and hobbyists who
sell firearms at gun shows are not required to conduct criminal
background checks on buyers, but licensed dealers who sell guns at
the shows are required to conduct the checks.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said his order ``closes the loophole that exists under
federal law.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's aides said he plans to submit a bill to the State
Legislature if the efforts to regulate the sale of weapons at gun
shows failed in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   His aides did not elaborate on those plans, and it was unclear
how such a move would be received in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's comments came in response to questions by reporters
over whether he would require background checks during a gun show
scheduled for this weekend at the Empire State Plaza, a state-owned
complex near the Capitol. The governor's aides said there are only
a handful of gun shows held on state property each year.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's show, sponsored by a group called the New York
State Arms Collectors, is expected to draw several thousand people
over two days. Roughly 150 gun dealers have registered to attend
the event, according to state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has been under intense pressure by gun-control groups and
lobbyists to cancel the show. But he has refused to do so, saying
that the state had entered into a contract with the organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Pataki announced that he had used his executive
authority to require collectors and hobbyists selling weapons at
the show to conduct background checks of buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to direct that all state agencies be required, if
they are going to permit these kind of activities, that there are
full and complete background checks,'' he said in response to
questions from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something that I have the power to do on state
property,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the governor's order, all firearm buyers at gun shows on
state property must undergo a criminal background check through a
national registry known as the National Instant Criminal Background
System. The background checks are often instantaneous, meaning
people can buy the weapons immediately if they do not have a
criminal history that would prevent them from making such a
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki's order would require a waiting period of up to three
days if, for whatever reason, a background check on a buyer could
not be completed immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said his order would not apply to police officers and
licensed gun dealers. He said State Police officers would be posted
at the gun show in Albany to insure his order is enforced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
