</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-476&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET MUSIC TAKES A FIRST STEP INTO THE MAINSTREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (kd) 
By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delivering music over the Internet, long depicted by record
labels as the illegal pastime of college students and pirates, won
an important measure of legitimacy this week when ASCAP, the
American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers, announced a
licensing agreement with MP3.com, one of the leading music Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, announced on Wednesday, songwriters whose
work is offered on MP3.com and who agree to pay ASCAP a $10
membership fee will receive royalty payments based on how often
their music is downloaded or purchased as a compact disk.
</P>
<P>
   The license will also allow MP3.com to offer downloads of music
from artists already represented by ASCAP online, though the
details of this arrangement have not been worked out, said Marc
Morgenstern, ASCAP's senior vice president for strategic planning
and new media.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between ASCAP, the world's largest performing
rights organization, and MP3.com, a two-year-old online distributor
of digital music, represents a breakthrough truce between the
industry's old guard and the young turks of the Internet who want
to change the rules of music sales and distribution. Just as the
major record companies have viewed online music with alarm,
MP3.com's founder, Michael Robertson, has long distanced himself
from the traditional business.
</P>
<P>
   MP3, the popular, easy-to-copy computer file format for which
the site is named, has become a symbol of the turmoil that exists
within the music industry as it wrestles with alternative
distribution models.
</P>
<P>
   The MP3.com site is a sort of combination digital jukebox and
digital radio station. It allows unknown musicians from around the
world to circumvent traditional record companies and find an
audience for their work by making it available for listening or
purchase online. Music fans can download songs for no charge or, if
they choose, buy a compact disk.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the exposure, artists split the revenue
generated by sales of their recordings with MP3.com. The site also
makes money by selling advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at MP3.com declined to comment on the licensing deal
on Thursday, citing the ``quiet period'' following the initial
public offering of its stock last month. ASCAP's Morgenstern called
the licensing deal ``a creative approach to something that ASCAP
and MP3.com have in common, which is, how do you find, promote and
develop musical talent?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to show that there is a major site that
recognizes the value of copyright,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   While promoters of the MP3 format have celebrated its outlaw
image, ASCAP has already sold about 1,000 performance rights
licenses to Web sites, most of which offer other formats. The
Digital Millennium Copyright Act, signed into law last year, makes
it illegal to offer copyrighted material online without such a
license.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fees for the online licenses range from $250 for home-grown,
low-traffic Web sites to $200,000 for commercial sites. The amount
MP3.com will pay was not disclosed. Fees for online licenses are
minuscule compared with those paid to ASCAP by television and radio
stations. But as the Web continues to grow, such payments could
come to represent substantial income for ASCAP and the composers it
represents.
</P>
<P>
   The MP3 format is the most popular way of distributing music
online. It is revered by denizens of the Web and reviled by the
music industry because MP3 files have no built-in copyright
protections and performers, songwriters, publishers and recording
companies receive no income when users copy and distribute
MP3-encoded music.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to MP3's growing popularity, the Record Industry
Association of America, which represents all the major labels, last
December formed the Secure Digital Music Initiative, a joint
attempt by record companies, the computer industry and
manufacturers of consumer electronics devices to create a standard
technology for selling and transmitting music over the Internet.
Though the group's leaders promised to release a standard by June
30, over the last few months the major record companies have struck
individual alliances, suggesting that the group is having
difficulty reaching a consensus.
</P>
<P>
   In the last four months, MP3.com has doubled the number of
artists it features, to 12,000. Last week, Cox Enterprises Inc.
announced that it was investing $45 million in MP3.com in return
for an undisclosed equity stake.
</P>
<P>
   The economic pressures of a growing business may compel MP3.com
to distance itself further from its underground roots, industry
analysts say. It is one thing to open up a Web site to all
performers who wish to make their music available, but it is
another matter to handle copyright and distribution issues for all
those artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're fast approaching the point where they may have
to abandon the ideals of a grass-roots music company,'' said Mark
Hardie, a senior analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass.
``Increasingly, MP3.com is looking more like a traditional record
company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
