</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-FIRINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC SCHOOLS CHANCELLOR TO REMOVE LAGGING SUPERINTENDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LYNETTE HOLLOWAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew has decided to remove at
least five superintendents because he has lost confidence in their
ability to lead and to improve student achievement, a top aide said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The aide, Chiara Coletti, Crew's director of public affairs,
said the superintendents would be identified next week, and other
dismissals may follow.
</P>
<P>
   Other aides said the superintendents to be removed included two
of the five boroughwide superintendents who oversee high schools,
along with several of the 32 district superintendents, who
supervise elementary and middle schools. It was not clear Friday
night whether the superintendents had been notified.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the chancellor had said he planned to take action
against superintendents and principals in districts where large
numbers of students performed poorly on state and citywide tests.
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has also called for the removal of
principals in low-performing districts.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Ms. Coletti said the coming dismissals would not be
based solely on test scores and that Crew was not limiting his
actions to the school districts with the worst performance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she said, he is looking at factors like whether there
was an achievement gap between whites and Asian students, on one
hand, and black and Hispanic students, on the other; and how well
superintendents were meeting the needs of low-income students,
immigrants and special-education students. He was also looking at
their ability to supervise teachers and principals, divide their
budgets fairly among all schools in the district, and develop and
carry out new curriculums.
</P>
<P>
   Such a wholesale shake-up has ``never been done in the history
of the school system that we know of,'' Ms. Coletti said. But she
said the chancellor had the power to act under the school
governance law approved in Albany in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The removals will mark Crew's most aggressive use of his
expanded powers under the new law, which was prompted by
allegations of patronage and corruption among local school boards.
It shifted many powers to the chancellor and district
superintendents, and gave the chancellor broad powers over
superintendents, including hiring them from a list put together by
local school boards and dismissing them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Coletti said some of the superintendents being removed from
their positions would be pushed into retirement, some would be
dismissed outright and others would be offered lower-ranking jobs
within the school system. Some superintendents, she said, might
have failed in their current jobs but would be assets to the system
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after both city and state standardized tests have
shown a decline in achievement among city schoolchildren. One out
of five city students scored in the bottom level of a new state
fourth-grade reading test, meaning that they could barely read or
write.
</P>
<P>
   Crew has promised to move aggressively to hold administrators,
teachers and students accountable for results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
