<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOND YIELD FALLS BELOW 6 PERCENT; STOCKS POST SMALL GAINS
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bonds turned in their best weekly performance in more
than eight months on expectations that the Federal Reserve will
raise interest rates by only a quarter percentage point later this
month. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond fell to 5.97 percent
from 6.16 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 13.93 points, to
10,855.56, while the broader Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was
up 2.94 points, to 1,342.84. The NASDAQ composite index rose 19.29
points, to 2,563.44. The market outlook improved with comments on
Thursday by the chairman of the Fed, Alan Greenspan, who suggested
that a modest pre-emptive interest-rate increase would obviate the
need for more drastic action later.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN SALES ARE HURTING GILLETTE
</P>
<P>
   Gillette is being dragged down by the weak international
performance of some products, including Braun electric shavers,
shaving cream and stationery, while its main business line of
blades and razors is doing well. On Thursday, Gillette's management
warned investors that second-quarter profits would fall 20 percent,
to about 26 cents a share. Wall Street analysts had been expecting
29 cents, after some previous downward revisions.
</P>
<P>
   LICENSING DEAL FOR MUSIC WEB SITE
</P>
<P>
   Delivering music over the Internet won an important measure of
legitimacy this week when the American Society of Composers,
Authors and Publishers announced a licensing deal with the music
Web site MP3.com. Under the agreement, songwriters whose work is
offered on MP3.com and who agree to pay ASCAP a $10 membership fee
will receive royalty payments based on how often their music is
downloaded or purchased as a compact disk.
</P>
<P>
   SHARES OF INTEL FALL ON DELAY NEWS
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Intel dropped more than 5 percent, or $3.0625, to
$54.9375, after the company informed personal computer
manufacturers that a faster version of its Pentium III processor
would be delayed by two months. Two analysts lowered their earnings
estimates, but the consensus remained unchanged for the current
quarter, at 54 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   A SPOILER: MEXICO'S BANKING SYSTEM
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, a newly created federal bank insurance agency has
initiated a $1.3 billion bailout of the nation's third-largest
bank, Grupo Financiero Serfin, and is considering a $9 billion
cleanup of Bancrecer.
</P>
<P>
   LAWSUIT DRAWS ATTENTION TO NAFTA
</P>
<P>
   A $970 million lawsuit against the U.S. government by a Canadian
fuel additive manufacturer has focused attention on a clause in the
North American Free Trade Agreement that experts say may have to be
rewritten. It allows companies to sue the governments of the United
States, Canada or Mexico if export opportunities are lost for
reasons unrelated to normal commerce.
</P>
<P>
   COMMERCIAL BANKS ARE PROSPERING
</P>
<P>
   Improved international operations and strong trading revenue
helped commercial banks book record profits in the first quarter of
1999, Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said. Insured commercial
banks earned $18 billion in net income in the first three months of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ADOBE SHARES UP ON EARNINGS NEWS
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Adobe Systems rose 12 percent after the company, a
maker of graphics software used by magazines and newspapers, said
its fiscal second-quarter earnings rose 61 percent, beating
estimates. The company's shares rose $8.6875, to $82.5625.
</P>
<P>
   ALPHARMA BUYS A GENERIC DRUG UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Alpharma said that it had bought the German generic-drug
business of Schwarz Pharma AG for about $150 million in cash,
expanding its operations in Europe. Alpharma said the business,
Isis Pharma Group, includes about 200 employees. No plants were
included.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
