A1565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BULLOCK-HIGHLIGHTS19-     06-18 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLOCK-HIGHLIGHTS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Highlights of Bob Bullock's life
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ In 1947, Bob Bullock was
<TEXT>
a member of his junior college's football team in Hill County. Just
10 years later, he would be elected to the Texas House _ and would
quit before his term ended because he couldn't live on a
legislator's salary.
<P>
   Bob Bullock
</P>
<P>
   1929 - 1999
</P>
<P>
   1929: Born in Hillsboro.
</P>
<P>
   1949: Associate degree from Hill College.
</P>
<P>
   1957: Elected to the Texas House.
</P>
<P>
   1958: Bachelor's degree from Texas Tech University; law degree
from Baylor University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   1960: Leaves Texas House and practices law in Harlingen, then
Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   1963: Joins Texas Automobile Dealers Association as lobbyist.
Two years later, returns to private law practice.
</P>
<P>
   1967: Heads new antitrust and consumer protection division for
then-Attorney General Crawford Martin.
</P>
<P>
   1968: Joins then Lt. Gov. Preston Smith's campaign for governor,
then serves Smith as appointments secretary, legal counsel and
political fund-raising chief.
</P>
<P>
   1971: Appointed secretary of state, pushing changes to allow
students to vote in their college towns.
</P>
<P>
   1972: Supports George McGovern for president. Despite his
conservative credentials in House, he now is considered a liberal
Democrat. Third of a lung removed to excise benign tumor.
</P>
<P>
   1974: Elected state comptroller under slogan: ``You know where
he is.'' As comptroller, made headlines and evening news with raids
on businesses delinquent on state taxes, collecting millions in new
revenue and building a formidable political power base. But when
oil revenue falls in the 1980s, he cuts nearly 500 jobs and 15
offices across the state.
</P>
<P>
   1977: Undergoes treatment for severe depression.
</P>
<P>
   1978: Entertains notion of running for governor against
incumbent Dolph Briscoe.
</P>
<P>
   1979: Has moderate heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   1983: Signs intent to run for governor in 1986, but rescinds it
the next year.
</P>
<P>
   1981: Undergoes alcohol-abuse treatment in California.
</P>
<P>
   1986: Undergoes smoking-cessation treatment in California for
three- and four-pack-a-day cigarette habit. He continues to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   1990: Elected lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   1997: Announces his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   1998: Leaves office in January.
</P>
<P>
   1999: Dies at his Austin home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
