<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VLASTO-WIDOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG WIDOW INDICTED FOR KILLING OLD HUSBAND FOR HIS MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Nev.)   (bl)  
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The marriage of Andrew Vlasto, 85, to a woman 57
years his junior lasted only three months before Vlasto, a member
of a prominent Greek-American family here, died.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, almost six years after the wedding, the widow, Sylvia
Mitchell, was indicted in Manhattan on charges that she had killed
her husband with lethal drug cocktails in a scheme to acquire more
than $500,000 from his bank accounts and his real estate holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mitchell, now 33, was extradited Friday from Las Vegas,
where she had been living, and charged with manslaughter in the
second degree and 11 counts of grand larceny, attempted grand
larceny and perjury.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain under state law a conviction of second-degree
manslaughter, the prosecution must prove that Ms. Mitchell caused
Vlasto's death through reckless actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our theory of the case is that she intended to steal his
property and that she drugged him, not meaning to kill him, but to
keep him in a drug-induced state so she could steal his assets,''
Daniel Castleman, the chief of the Investigation Division in the
Manhattan district attorney's office, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mitchell pleaded not guilty in Manhattan state Supreme Court
on Friday. She was ordered held without bail until a hearing July
28.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of manslaughter, she faces a maximum penalty of 15
years in prison. She faces an additional 15 years if found guilty
of stealing $95,000 from her husband in 1993, attempting to steal
more than $100,000 from a money market account and lying in court
depositions after his death in an attempt to obtain about $400,000
in real estate and bank accounts in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mitchell's lawyer, Barry Fallick, said in an interview that
he might move to have the indictment dismissed on the ground that
her due-process rights were violated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have indicted her six years ago,'' Fallick said.
``The delay makes it more difficult to find witnesses and evidence
that could exonerate her.''
</P>
<P>
   Vlasto was a lawyer and a banker in Greece before immigrating to
the United States in 1947 and working as an editor for Atlantis, a
Greek language newspaper owned by relatives. After Atlantis ceased
publication in 1974, he organized a company that sold church
supplies, and looked after his investments.
</P>
<P>
   A bachelor, Vlasto lived frugally in a one-room apartment in the
Chelsea section of Manhattan. His relatives said he became
reclusive in the early 1990s, and in August 1993, he married Ms.
Mitchell, who was then 28.
</P>
<P>
   At Ms. Mitchell's arraignment Friday, Youmin Kim, a prosecutor,
said Vlasto was so infirm on his wedding day that Ms. Mitchell had
to carry him into the chapel of a Pentecostal minister in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, the prosecutors said, Ms. Mitchell obtained a
joint bank account giving her access to Vlasto's savings. In
September and October 1993, she withdrew $95,000, including the
wire transfer of $70,000 to the Taj Mahal Casino in Atlantic City,
N.J., in her name, according to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1993, Vlasto's relatives learned of the marriage
after his neighbors informed them that he had collapsed and was in
Bellevue Hospital. He died in the hospital on Nov. 10, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Over the objections of Ms. Mitchell, an autopsy was performed by
the City Medical Examiner's office. Vlasto's death was attributed
to pneumonia and sepsis, which is a toxic infection, ``complicated
by an overdose of benzodiazepines, barbiturates and opiates,''
drugs that had not been administered to him by the hospital's
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Vlasto did not leave a will, and Ms. Mitchell's attempt to
obtain his entire estate was blocked by Vlasto's relatives. In a
1994 settlement, she was allowed to keep what remained of the
$95,000 withdrawn from his bank accounts but waived all rights to
the rest of his estate.
</P>
<P>
   James Vlasto, a nephew of Andrew Vlasto, praised the district
attorney's office for pursuing charges against Ms. Mitchell.
``Other law enforcement agencies should follow New York's lead and
give a high priority to aggressively pursuing cases involving the
murders, abuses and exploitation of the elderly,'' Vlasto said.
</P>
</TEXT>
