<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-MIA-HAMM19-COX     06-18 1626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MIA-HAMM19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hamm breaks out of leg casts into soccer world
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Mia Hamm often is identified with the University
of North Carolina, the school where she and her
I-can-do-anything-better-than-you commercial co-star, Michael
Jordan, won national championships. Yet it was in Texas that Hamm,
international soccer's all-time leading scorer, first learned that
sport and many others, including tackle football.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our children have Texas roots,'' said Stephanie Hamm,
Mia's mother. Stephanie and Bill Hamm, a retired Air Force colonel,
settled in Austin three years ago and lived in Wichita Falls and
San Antonio when Mia was growing up.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamms recently returned from a trip to Oregon, where Nike
dedicated a building _ even bigger than Michael's _ to their
daughter. They will travel to some of the U.S. women's World Cup
matches.
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm and the U.S. national team open the World Cup
tournament at 2 p.m. today against Denmark in East Rutherford, N.J.
Mia &AMP; Co. are favored to win the tournament and garner millions of
new fans.
</P>
<P>
   Little girls already shriek Mia's name. A few years ago, People
magazine anointed her one of its 50 Most Beautiful People, and
she's on her way to becoming the most marketable female athlete on
the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Her success story seems so smooth, so well-orchestrated. It is
however, quite an improbable one, tinged with pain and tragedy as
well as serendipity and triumph. It reflects the journey of her
family around Texas and the world and through life.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer first entered the Hamms' life while Bill was at squadron
officer's school in Montgomery, Ala. It was no big deal at the
time. Just another mandatory activity he had at a Friday sports
day, like volleyball. When the military says have fun, you have
fun, sir!
</P>
<P>
   Mia was just a few months old then, and Fridays were anything
but fun for her. That was her day for orthopedic treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was born with some problems with her legs,'' Bill
explained. ``They diagnosed it as a partial club foot. So the first
few months, she was in casts. She grew up and had these little
backwards shoes. They're curved out instead of in. There were
braces in between to keep the proper distance, and there were
little screws in the bottom to keep them at the right angles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She had to sleep with them,'' Stephanie interjects.
``Instruments of torture. Our second daughter was born that way,
and they weren't nearly as aggressive, and her legs turned out
beautifully. And then Mia was born and had the same thing, and the
doctors just flipped out. They said, `She's going to have to be in
casts for the first four months of her life. Then you're going to
have to put her in these braces.'''
</P>
<P>
   More than a quarter of a century has passed, but Stephanie's
voice still cracks and shrinks as she recalls, ``She and I would
get in the bathtub at 4 o'clock in the morning every Friday to melt
those casts. You had to get them all wet and then pull them off.
She was so little, and she cried ... And then we'd drive to the
appointment. They'd rotate the legs a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   And put on more casts. The treatments stopped only by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved so far away that there was nothing we could do,''
Stephanie said. In Florence, Italy, where Bill landed on a
post-graduate scholarship, the Hamms made do with high-top shoes
for Mia.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie recalled, ``We were stuck in an apartment, and the
kids didn't get out much. But we had this huge hall that was at the
entrance of our apartment, and she'd just run up and down and up
and down and up and down like she was practicing getting her feet
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Mia was running. And speaking and gesturing in Italian.
That's all the family spoke at home, trying, as Bill's scholarship
charged, to immerse themselves in Italian culture. Florence is
famous for its art galleries, but Bill found that on Mondays, no
one in the coffee houses and restaurants talked about art or much
of anything else except soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no other sports over there,'' Bill said. ``If you
ever wanted to discuss something on Monday you had to go to the
soccer match on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   He bought season passes, and the family's Sunday began revolving
around soccer. If the team was out of town, they'd visit friends.
If it was at home, they were at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A brother to play with
</P>
<P>
   The Hamms moved to Wichita Falls in 1976, and Texas, like many
other states, was getting a big soccer push. The North American
Soccer League's New York Cosmos had signed Brazilian star Pele to a
three-year contract in 1975 in an attempt to bring the world's game
to the world's most lucrative market.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Mia might not have thrived in or even tried the game except
for a change in the family. The Hamms, a family with four girls,
decided to adopt a boy. They ended up adopting two. And in Garrett,
an 8-year-old Thai American orphan, Mia acquired an instant older
brother.
</P>
<P>
   While the girls in the family liked to read, Garrett loved to
run. He was soon playing Pop Warner football and then switched to
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Bill said, ``I got involved first just going to the practices.
Then I got into helping the coach. Then I got into refereeing. It
was because he was involved that she got involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She stuck to him like glue,'' Stephanie said. ``She realized
that it was OK to be competitive once Garrett came into our lives.
I think Mia had this desire to bust a gusset and go for broke, and
it wasn't until she got to play with Garrett and his friends that
she realized it was OK to just throw yourself into that. He loved
playing any kind of game, and she played any sport around.''
</P>
<P>
   Mia was small and shy, and sports were her way of making herself
known. ``You moved to a new base and made new friends as soon as
you joined a team,'' Mia has said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, when Mia was 8, the family moved to San Antonio. Bill
wound up coaching a kids' team a year later. By the fall of 1982,
it was a ``select'' team for only the best players. Back in Wichita
Falls in 1983, Mia still wasn't specializing. At a small school
that didn't have enough players for football, she suited up as a
cornerback-wide receiver. As a high school sophomore, she played on
the boys soccer team along with several other girls.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1986 she tried out for a regional soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   John Cossaboon, then coaching a North Texas regional team and
now women's soccer coach at San Diego State, recalled, ``We had
state teams in all different age groups, and I heard from different
people that there was this great player in Wichita Falls, so we got
her down for a tryout. She blew you away with her acceleration and
her natural athleticism. A few can accelerate like that, and some
people can sustain their speed for 60 yards, but to have both, I've
not seen it since.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mia was quiet. She let her game do her talking, and she was
always concerned with how the team did. She was ahead of the rest.
We learned more from her than we actually gave to her, and it goes
far beyond soccer,'' Cossaboon said.
</P>
<P>
   Shot out of a cannon
</P>
<P>
   Cossaboon shared his find with Anson Dorrance, who coached the
U.S. national team. Dorrance has said he's usually skeptical of
such tips. He came to Texas to see Mia play, but didn't want to
know who she was. He wanted to see if she could make herself known.
</P>
<P>
   That took all of a couple of seconds. Dorrance has described the
opening kick this way, ``I saw this kid accelerate like she was
shot out of a cannon. Without seeing her touch the ball, I ran
around saying, `Is that Mia Hamm?'''
</P>
<P>
   At 15, Hamm became the youngest-ever member on the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Dorrance was also the coach at North Carolina, and Mia enrolled
there. Jordan won one NCAA championship at that school. Hamm did
much better than that, capturing four. She also played on the U.S.
team that captured the inaugural women's World Cup in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 she married Christiaan Corry, a Marine helicopter pilot
she met while they were both students at North Carolina. In 1996
she starred for soccer's Dream Team, the U.S. squad that won a gold
medal in the Atlanta Olympics before a crowd of 76,489, the largest
ever to see a women's sporting event. After winning the gold, Mia
hugged Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, tragedy followed triumph. Years earlier, Garrett had been
diagnosed with a rare disease, aplastic anemia. Aplastic anemia
results from a failure of the bone marrow to produce adequate
quantities of the essential blood components. It worsened to the
point that he needed a bone marrow transplant, a difficult
procedure made even more risky by his distinct genetic background.
His natural father served as a donor, and the operation at first
appeared to be a success.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie and Bill Hamm moved to Austin in part to be near M.D.
Anderson, the hospital in Houston where Garrett would receive
treatment. But he developed a fungal infection that was too much
for his weakened immune system and died in April 1997 at 28.
</P>
<P>
   Mia missed the first two games for the U.S. squad after his
death. When she rejoined the team for a game against South Korea,
her teammates showed their support by donning black armbands. The
U.S. squad is a team in the true sense of the word, probably
because Mia so unselfishly shares the praise heaped on her.
</P>
<P>
   Although the U.S. players have tried to downplay it, the
pressure on them to win the World Cup will be enormous, and
millions around the world will be watching the every move of Mia,
who not all that long ago was a brown-eyed slip of a girl playing
on the Texas sandlots.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
