<HEADLINE>
TOUGHER, HIGHER, STRONGER: PINEHURST IS THE DAZZLER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ The conditions got tougher, the scores got
higher and the leader board got even stronger. The first 36 holes
of the U.S. Open have been intriguing, but the final two days
should be memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's second round ended with three of the world's top
players tied for first place: David Duval, Phil Mickelson and Payne
Stewart. Meanwhile, former major tournament winners like Tiger
Woods, Vijay Singh and Hal Sutton lurked close behind. All faced
the challenge of beating each other while trying to remain composed
on a difficult course that is expected to become even more
unyielding.
</P>
<P>
   With only seven players in the tournament under par through two
rounds, Stewart, Duval and Mickelson ended the day at
three-under-par 137, while Woods, Sutton, Singh and Billy Mayfair
were all two strokes behind at one under par. How difficult was it
to play 18 holes at Pinehurst Resort and Country Club's fabled No.
2 course on Friday? The best score was 69, accomplished by only
three players, Stewart, Jeff Maggert and John Huston. The bright
sunshine made the turtleback greens harder, faster and more
diabolical, and to make matters worse, unpredictable wind gusts
often made club selection a guessing game.
</P>
<P>
   It is anyone's guess who will win, but a leader board with an
abundance of star power should produce ample fireworks. Saturday's
final twosome will be Duval and Stewart, while the next-to-last
twosome will be Mickelson and Woods. And imagine a Sunday showdown
that could feature Duval, Woods and Mickelson, three under-30 stars
who have never battled during the final holes of a major. Duval
would welcome it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to be part of a battle,'' Duval said after his
even-par 70. ``It's kind of like they talk about different
rivalries. As long as I'm part of the rivalry, I'm all for them.
But I just hope I'm in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   To become part of the Sunday battle, however, all the contenders
will have to hold their own on Saturday. And that will be
difficult. Pinehurst played more like Pinehurst Friday than it did
on Thursday, when rain softened the greens and gave players more
margin for error on their approach shots. On Friday, the margin for
error was minuscule. Any shot that was not placed with pinpoint
accuracy on the green was in danger of rolling off, sometimes 35 or
40 feet from where it landed. Meanwhile, chipping up the slopes at
Pinehurst can be like chipping a golf ball up a slide. If you do
not hit it hard enough, it will come back to you.
</P>
<P>
   At Pinehurst, you cannot breathe easy when the ball lands on the
green. You can only exhale when the ball finally stops rolling, and
sometimes that takes a while. Duval, Mayfair and John Daly, who
stumbled to a second-round 77, each watched the ball roll down a
slope and off the green, leading to a double-bogey. Only the most
resilient players managed to cope. And Mickelson, who shot a 70,
was glad to be among that group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have taken 70 at the start, and I'm very pleased with
70 at the end,'' said Mickelson, who started the day tied for first
place at three under par with Duval, Mayfair and Paul Goydos, who
fell to one over par after Friday's 74. ``The goal is to make pars
as you stand on each tee box. You just don't know when you're going
to make birdies. You want to give yourself a 30-footer, but it's
still not easy to make 30-footers here. Just keep making pars and
let things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who had a 7:50 a.m. tee time, shot a 69 and was in the
clubhouse relaxing before much of the field had reached the back
nine. For Stewart, who won the Open in 1991 and finished second in
1993 and '98, the weekend represents another chance to win the
major that best suits his game. And he left the course Friday
feeling confident about his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm playing better at the U.S. Open than I played
last year,'' Stewart said. ``I feel I've got more control over my
golf game, and over my swing.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how much control you have, Pinehurst can make you
lose it. Even the normally steady Duval had an up-and-down round
that featured five birdies, three bogeys and a double-bogey. After
Duval birdied No. 2 and No. 5 to reach five under par, he made a
rare double-bogey at the par-3 No. 6. After hitting his tee shot
into a bunker, Duval blasted out fairly softly, but not softly
enough to stay on these greens. After landing about six feet from
the pin, the ball kept rolling and rolling as the gallery groaned,
never stopping until it was off the green. Then Duval chipped to
five feet, but he missed the putt.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed, Duval birdied the next two holes to reach five under
again, but he bogeyed two of the next three holes. Afterward, he
was happy to have a share of the lead, and his sanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy what it does to you as a player, how it makes you a
little goofy at times,'' Duval said. ``I think that's the beauty of
this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a tournament that remained far from decided. Mickelson,
who used his terrific short game to get up and down from several
precarious situations, said that his wife, Amy, was still not
expected to deliver their first child until June 30. Mickelson
expected to be around for the entire tournament, and he also hoped
to stay in contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent the past month working on my short game, and I feel
it's as good as it has been in years,'' Mickelson said. Would it be
good enough to win the U.S. Open? The weekend would reveal the
answer. But all of the contenders agreed on one thing. If any
player finished the weekend under par, he would probably leave with
a trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're going to see players backing up,'' Duval said.
``The greens are going to get harder and faster. Even par is going
to be a real nice position come Sunday about 7 o'clock. And if
you're one or two over, you might not be too bad either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
