<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANGER IS NOW MODANO'S MIDDLE NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ A few years ago, when Mark Messier was a Ranger,
he checked Mike Modano of the Dallas Stars so hard that Modano
sustained a concussion. When the medics tried to lift Modano into
an ambulance on a stretcher, they accidentally dropped him. So
Modano knows that a hockey rink can be a dangerous place.
</P>
<P>
   His current injury, a damaged left wrist, prevents him from
shooting pucks as well as he usually does. Modano has no goals in
the Stanley Cup finals, which his team leads by 3 games to 2 over
the Buffalo Sabres, with Game 6 on Saturday night in Marine Midland
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   But Modano's feet are fine. He skated well in a 2-0 victory in
Dallas' Reunion Arena on Thursday night, a mean-spirited affair
that left both teams talking tough Friday. Modano even kicked a
pass with his skate for his second of two assists, which left him
with five for the series, the most points of any player in this
round, and 21 points for the playoffs, tied for the team lead with
Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   And there is nothing wrong with Modano's heart. Earlier in his
career, he was typecast as a skillful artiste who avoided the
dangerous places where good players go to get great. In his 10th
season, Modano now absorbs punishment to make important plays. When
he slips into his old ways, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock talks to him,
as he did by telephone before Game 5. Even opponents have noticed
the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed to be getting in traffic a little more,'' said Mike
Peca, the captain of the Sabres. ``He was working down low a lot
better. Obviously, he's very comfortable with the wrist injury. We
want to make sure we make him a target again, not to go after his
injury by any means, but just make sure we're finishing him like we
were earlier in the series.''
</P>
<P>
   This would be in the spirit of Thursday's conclusion, when Rhett
Warrener of Buffalo tried to attack Derian Hatcher of Dallas. When
the big defensemen grappled and fell, Warrener broke his leg,
ending his season. Sabres coach Lindy Ruff said Friday that his
players would target Modano and other Stars on Saturday. Peca said
the Stars were a dirty team. Hitchcock, who argued with Ruff at the
benches after the buzzer, said that Ruff wanted to start trouble by
sending out Warrener to get Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Modano's injury came during Game 2 on a legal check into the
boards by Jay McKee, a Sabres defenseman who said Friday that each
round gets ``a little more chippier, a little more dirtier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to keep your head up,'' McKee said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano has since played with pregame injections of pain-killing
medication and a soft cast on the forearm. There is nothing wrong
with his vision. Early in Game 5, he saw Peca barrelling toward him
for a high, hard hit that might have endangered a few more body
parts. Modano dodged it and Peca sprawled. Modano said he
understood the intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You circle names at the start of the game, which guys you go
after,'' Modano said. ``I'm sure mine's circled. We have a few of
their guys circled. That's the kind of hockey I've learned to enjoy
the last couple years. They push me to the limits. That's what I
want.''
</P>
<P>
   When Modano returned from the injury, he said the Sabres hacked
his wrist with sticks. He responded with three consecutive
penalties, one of them a serious slash. His ordeal typifies that of
an older, experienced Dallas team that plays an exhausting style of
body contact and checking effort. Brett Hull returned to the Stars'
lineup Thursday after missing almost two games with a groin injury.
Benoit Hogue played despite a badly damaged knee that will require
off-season surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Steadily improving in the six seasons since they moved from
Minnesota, the Stars are one victory away from what Nieuwendyk
calls ``the light at the end of the tunnel.'' As for focus, Modano
said: ``It's easy, but it's hard. That light's still a long way
away, a glimmer in the distance. It's a great position. The deeper
you have to go, the more gratifying and satisfying it is when you
come out on top. Guys are very hungry and very excited about this.
It's a real weird feeling. You have butterflies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
