<SLUG> BC-NY-REGENTS-TEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGENTS EXAM TESTS NERVE, AS WELL AS ENGLISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In their first crack at one of the new and stiffer
high school exams that are meant to raise academic standards in New
York state, about 200,000 11th graders across the state took the
first part of the revised regents English exam Friday and many gave
it mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Although the exam is crucial to graduation, it was not so bad,
said Joseph Bell, a 17-year-old at John Jay High School in the Park
Slope section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this test was easier for everybody, even though we had
heard it was going to be harder, because we were all prepared,'' he
said after taking the three-hour exam in the morning. ``The
teachers really focused on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Angel Figueroa, another 11th grader at John Jay, said he had
prepared for the test with after-school courses and also felt
ready. ``My whole class was ready,'' he said, calling the exam
``straightforward.''
</P>
<P>
   But others admitted to having felt great trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   Kristal Ennist, a 17-year-old student at Poughkeepsie High
School, said she could not put aside thoughts of how critical the
test is for her future.
</P>
<P>
   ``You correct yourself too many times because you don't want to
get it wrong because you really, really want to pass school,'' she
said. The new exam is twice as long as any previous English regents
test, and it is meant to be more comprehensive. The first part,
given Friday, included a section in which teachers read passages
and students answered questions about them. The second three-hour
portion of the test, to be given Wednesday, will involve writing an
essay and interpreting an aspect of literature.
</P>
<P>
   The testing apparently went smoothly. State and city education
officials reported no problems.
</P>
<P>
   All of this year's 11th graders, except special education
students, will have to pass the test with a grade of 55 or better
in order to graduate in 2000. For the class of 2004, the passing
score is to be raised to 65.
</P>
<P>
   The exam is the first in a revised battery of regents tests to
be given to high school students as part of a broad drive to raise
academic standards in the state. Less demanding competency tests
are being phased out so most students will have no option other
than passing the regents exams if they want a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three years, tougher and more comprehensive
regents exams in mathematics, social studies and science will be
introduced, and by the time this year's sixth graders graduate,
they will have been required to pass all of the new regents exams.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the self-assurance of some students, who said after the
exam that they felt fine, the pressures of the test did appear to
take a toll.
</P>
<P>
   In Poughkeepsie, English teacher Laura Ahlert said she thought
the exam was more rigorous than the model test that teachers had
used to drill students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The task they have to do is much more complicated than the
example we had,'' she said. ``It was an arduous task; you could see
it in their faces. We had one student who was physically ill during
it. She actually had to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ahlert said the student returned and completed the exam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
