<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-COLLEGE-LANDLORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., R.I.)  
 NYC COLUMN: COLLEGE CAST IN ODD ROLE _ LANDLORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The hallways of Teachers College at Columbia
University in upper Manhattan form a maze so complicated that a
visitor is tempted to pull out a compass before finally finding the
two classrooms in Grace Dodge Hall that house the nonprofit
program, Brotherhood/Sister Sol.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, Brotherhood/Sister Sol has rented
space from Teachers College in what seemed like a perfect marriage
between a program for disadvantaged students from minority groups
and a school regarded as a national leader in training teachers.
Students at Teachers College volunteered as tutors for kids in the
program. The kids also got to use the school gym to play basketball
or kickball.
</P>
<P>
   But, now, the marriage is souring, not because of any
differences in mission or ideology, but because of the pressures of
the Manhattan real estate squeeze. Citing a space shortage for
classrooms, Teachers College has told the program's founders that
they need to be out by the end of August. It might just be another
story of an unhappy sublet except that the dispute has touched
issues as complicated as the school's labyrinthine hallways.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Brotherhood/Sister Sol began five years ago in
Providence, R.I., when two Brown University seniors, Khary
Lazarre-White, 25, and Jason Warwin, 26, created a support and
guidance program, called The Brotherhood, for 13 troubled boys from
minority groups. Then the two, childhood friends both born to
inter-racial couples in Manhattan, created The Brotherhood Inc. in
New York after their graduation with a $20,000 pledge from a
benefactor impressed by their work.
</P>
<P>
   The program grew from two chapters in 1995, at Central Park East
Secondary School in East Harlem and at East Side Community High
School on Manhattan's Lower East Side, to seven today (including
two girls' chapters), with an annual budget from private grants of
about $544,000. The 140 students attend five schools in Manhattan
and the South Bronx, and the after-school program tries to attract
teen-agers from single-parent homes who might otherwise fall
through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to not only develop leadership but also critical
thinking,'' said Lazarre-White. He added, ``What is a success to
us? If a young person learns to be a good man, a good father,
responsible and caring, we consider it to be a success.''
</P>
<P>
   There are weekly chapter meetings, tutorials and required study
halls. There are summer retreats in the Berkshires, and more
ambitious trips (using grant money and proceeds of T-shirt sales)
to Morocco and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, East Side Community High School held its
commencement, and of the 15 male students who joined The
Brotherhood as sophomores, 14 graduated, with nine advancing to
college and the other six holding down full-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarre-White and Warwin praise Teachers College, and its
Institute of Urban and Minority Education, for providing it with
space at below-market rents since 1996. But the pending eviction
has evolved into a bitter dispute. Dr. Sandra Wilcox, a director of
the Sister Sol program and formerly a Teachers College student and
adjunct professor, said the administration has confused its
priorities. ``I think there is the larger issue of the lack of
commitment by the school to urban education and youth,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the school's diversity committee have protested
the eviction notice, while more than 100 Teachers College students
signed a petition opposing the move.
</P>
<P>
   Public officials, including U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel and state
Sen. David Paterson, both of Harlem, have written to school
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Warwin said the program wants to stay for a year or two to plan
for a smooth exit and find an affordable and safe location. He said
moving now would mean a large rent spike at a time when the program
is $40,000 over its budget.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers College spokesman Barry Rosen said school
administrators gave the program more than a year's notice (a point
disputed by Lazarre-White and Warwin) and offered to help them
relocate. Rosen said rising enrollment and demand for more faculty
and research space has created a need for 10 to 15 extra rooms by
September and more by next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We value what they do tremendously,'' Rosen said. ``This has
nothing really to do with the diversity issue in any way, shape or
form. It has to do with space issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lazarre-White said administrators should look to the words
of the school's president, Arthur Levine, who wrote in 1997 that
the mission of Teachers College was ``educational opportunity to
all, particularly the most disadvantaged populations in our
society, and continually improving the quality of education at all
levels, especially in urban areas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
