<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUDSON-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUDSON FESTIVAL RETURNS TO HUDSON SITE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROTON-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. _ Starting in 1978, a music and
environmental festival called Clearwater's Great Hudson River
Revival was held every Father's Day weekend on Croton Point, a
tree-studded peninsula 20 miles up the Hudson from Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1987, the 60-year-old county dump on the same spit was
found be to leaking streams of contaminated runoff. ``The chemicals
were in puddles on the roadway,'' said Pete Seeger, the folk singer
and one of the founders of Clearwater, the private conservation
group that organizes the revival.
</P>
<P>
   So the event moved to a college campus in the middle of
Westchester County, where the only water in sight was in aquariums
full of fish and crabs in educational displays.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the revival has returned to the river for which it was
named.
</P>
<P>
   The landfill was sealed in 1995 with a watertight cap and seeded
with meadow grass. The river recovered enough for the park's beach
to be opened to swimmers two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   So the board members of Clearwater decided last year that it was
safe to return to Croton Point.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, dozens of volunteers checked in at a booth labeled
``Immaculate Reception,'' then scattered across the Westchester
park, erecting stages, painting signs and marveling at the view.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time,'' said Myrna Ross, a volunteer and
Clearwater board member who worked at the first festival on Croton
Point, a decade after it was first held as an informal fund-raising
picnic in Garrison, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day event, which includes performances by Seeger and
Arlo Guthrie, is expected to draw about 15,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
   A truck topped with large sheets of solar panels _ providing two
kilowatts of electricity for sound and light equipment _ was next
to one stage. Seeger parked his electric-powered pickup truck
nearby, and where it was joined by a Mercedes diesel sedan rigged
to run on used cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
   In an area reserved for advocates of all stripes, John Mylod,
57, a former executive director of Clearwater and now a volunteer,
helped put up a display about sign language for the deaf.
</P>
<P>
   Mylod, a commercial shad netter from Poughkeepsie, said that
slowly, landfill by landfill, waste site by waste site, the Hudson
was getting better but still had a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   The campground for the 800 volunteers began to fill up, and a
woman directed them to various sections: ``Noisy and campfires is
up here, quiet is down below.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Aja, the event's manager, dispatched volunteers to
prepare banners, erect fences and check cables. The festival had
been at two different locations the last two years, he said.
Surveying the point and the river, he smiled and said: ``This is
where we were meant to be. My sincere hope is that this is home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WCUP-GROWTH-ART-N     06-18 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-GROWTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY GIRLS TAKE TO SOCCER, THE SUBURBAN GAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Adrice McMichael, 10, is eager to learn this new game
about kicking a ball into a net. In jeans and a white ``Urban
Soccer Girl'' T-shirt that hangs to her knees like a dress, she
runs determinedly after the rolling sphere, the rainbow of beads in
her braids bopping behind.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard ``trying to kick the ball, trying to get it in the
goal or trying to pass it to the partners,'' Adrice says during a
brief break from the scrimmage at Lawrence C. Thompson Park on
Staten Island, in the shadow of the West Brighton housing project,
where some of the 100 girls scurrying around the field in red, blue
and yellow pinnies live. ``I try to hit it with my head,'' she
adds, ``but it hurts after awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Six of the Staten Island girls, none of whom had ever played
soccer before this week, are scheduled to carry a flag during
Saturday's opening ceremonies of the 1999 Women's World Cup at
Giants Stadium, at once symbolizing a milestone in the struggle for
gender equity in athletics and the challenges yet to come for the
nation's fastest-growing sport.
</P>
<P>
   While soccer, and the national women's team's extraordinary
success, has sent millions of girls onto the playing fields of
America over the last decade, it has thus far been mainly a
suburban craze. Now World Cup corporate sponsors are hoping to use
the enthusiasm of the tournament to turn city girls into devotees
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   In New York and the other six cities playing host to the
tournament, there are ``Urban Soccer Girl'' programs for girls who
live in housing projects, as well as soccer skills clinics like the
one that drew some 5,000 schoolchildren to Bryant Park in Manhattan
on Thursday. At the clinics, girls and boys alike learn to shoot,
pass, trap and head the ball, and are sent home with souvenir
photos of themselves dressed up as World Cup stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of nice to have a suburban activity inside the
city,'' said Stacey Fenley, a teacher at Public School 33 in
Manhattan who brought her first and second graders to Bryant Park.
``I don't hear a lot of our kids playing on soccer teams.
Hopefully, this will give them a spark.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, soccer leagues have sprouted in American
suburbs as fast as subdivisions, with parents signing children up
as early as preschool, and adults playing well into middle age. Of
18 million registered soccer players in the United States, 7.5
million are women and girls, according to the Soccer Industry
Council of America.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer looks to be the great gender equalizer among youth
sports: as membership in one national league, the American Youth
Soccer Organization, has more than doubled to 607,000 over the past
dozen years, the percentage of girls has jumped from 25 percent to
40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's amazing that the women get to play,'' said Dawn
Perry, 10, who was wearing her green Nigeria soccer jersey with No.
13 on the back as she practiced trapping at the Bryant Park
workshop. ``For so long, all we see is men playing positions. We
never see a girl on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn, who lives in East Harlem and is in the fifth grade, used
to play in a league and would like to once again. The clinic
coaches said she was one of the few girls there who had playing
experience, and one called her a natural, even as the ball slipped
through her legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a girl, and I just love soccer,'' Dawn said. ``Maybe now
when I grow up I could be a soccer player in a World Cup. A Women's
World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the success of women's soccer can be attributed to the
implementation over the past decade of Title IX, a federal law
mandating equity in school sports programs, and the rise in
prominence of women's sports generally, including the Women's
National Basketball Association, but experts say soccer also has
particular appeal to young girls. Height is not essential, strength
not as important as skill. It's a social game with low scores, and
thus less focus on the stars. It's cheap, requiring little
equipment commitment, and can be played anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about running around, it's not too violent, it's team
oriented and it's something they can play with their friends,''
said Marla Messing, president of the Women's World Cup organizing
committee. ``I think it's something girls feel they can own; this
is my sport. The other sports are so dominated by men; in the
United States, this is something they can really own.''
</P>
<P>
   While the WNBA had to sell itself to basketball fans used to
watching men play, women have had a prominent role in soccer's rise
in the United States practically from the beginning. Among men, the
United States is a relative novice at the world's most popular
sport; in contrast, soccer became popular among women here earlier
than in most other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The women's national team, unlike its male counterpart, is
really good: the United States won the first Women's World Cup in
1991, took third place in 1995 and won the gold medal during
women's soccer's debut at the 1996 Olympics and is favored in this
year's tournament. Mia Hamm is not America's best female soccer
player, she's America's best soccer player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought the women played better than the guys,'' said
Cait Kilpatrick, 9, who has been kicking since she was 4 years old
and has a poster of Hamm, her favorite player, hanging in her
family's home in Forest Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Cait, wearing shiny blue game shorts and white soccer jersey,
was kicking goal after goal at the shooting station in Bryant Park
in Manhattan on Thursday. She had come with her mother, a soccer
coach, and two older brothers, to volunteer at the clinic. They
will do the same thing at Giants Stadium Saturday morning, and then
watch the games it seems they have been waiting years for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women should just play,'' Cait says. ``It doesn't matter
what the guys do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Bryant Park clinic and the Staten Island camp, young
girls and teen-agers alike clustered around the ball like the
newest soccer players, refusing to stay in position. They lifted
their feet in hopes of planting them on top of the ball only to
watch it roll underneath. They tried to trap the ball with their
chests, but ended up using their arms _ off limits in the no-hands
game _ instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's boring, all you do is kicking,'' complained Joyce Jian,
11, a fifth grader at Public School 20 on the Lower East Side of
Manhattan, after she dribbled through the obstacle course and
tested her power shot at Bryant Park. ``My favorite activity is
volleyball. You can do it with your hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassandra Pena, 10, said she likes football, baseball and
kickball better, but when she got the ball through one of the holes
in the ``accuracy shot'' workshop for the third time, soccer was
starting to look pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys always say, `You can't kick, you're not good,'''
Cassandra explained, even as she showed a whole crowd of children
that she can, indeed, kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only some boys,'' piped in Victor Figueroa, 11.
</P>
<P>
   And the girls agreed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
