<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS-MIXUP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLACK TAX CREDIT' LANDS MAN IN A HEAP OF TROUBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LAURA VOZZELLA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The long and largely luckless campaign to
secure reparations for descendants of American slaves has a few
radicals who vow to win redress ``by any means necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Foster took a more moderate approach. He simply filled
out an IRS form, requested a $43,209 ``black tax'' credit and got a
check from the U.S. Treasury in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time they gave us something for that lost time in
slavery,'' said Foster, 35, a part-time minister from Fort Worth
who said his great-grandparents were slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, there is no ``black tax credit,'' despite persistent
rumors to the contrary. The government goofed in 1996 when it paid
Foster $30,085.89 _ the amount he requested, minus about $13,000
owed for child support and student loans.
</P>
<P>
   Foster still has the money, but now his freedom is at stake. He
faces up to 15 years in prison for helping three friends apply for
the same tax credit _ one of the three got it _ after the Internal
Revenue Service told him there was no such thing.
</P>
<P>
   Foster is scheduled to be tried in Dallas federal court this
month on three counts of filing false claims.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of reparations has circulated since just after the Civil
War, when Congress voted to give freed slaves 40 acres and a mule.
But President Johnson killed the plan with a veto.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has bubbled up on and off ever since. U.S. Rep. John
Conyers, D-Mich., has tried unsuccessfully to introduce legislation
on the matter. A group called the National Coalition of Blacks for
Reparations in America is holding its 10th annual convention this
weekend in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The debate landed in the lap of the IRS after L.G. Sherrod, a
New York journalist and economics consultant, wrote an essay in
``Essence'' in April 1993. Noting that the government has paid
reparations to Native Americans cheated out of lands and
Japanese-Americans interned during World War II, Sherrod urged
readers to use their tax forms to claim the modern-day equivalent
of 40 acres and a mule _ as calculated by The People's Institute
for Economics in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply enter $43,209 in `black taxes' and compute
accordingly,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   There was a flurry of filings that year and occasional waves
after that as Sherrod's suggested act of defiance morphed into
urban legend and the occasional con game. In 1996, Ben Badio, a
Liberian citizen living in Dallas, was sentenced to three years in
prison for charging almost 200 people $750 to $1,000 to fill out
tax forms claiming the ``credit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those myths that continues to resurface
across the country,'' said Phil Beasley, spokesman for the IRS in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor apparently popped up in Fort Worth around tax time in
1996. Foster, who is a minister at Mount Olive Baptist Church in
Arlington and an investigator for a local branch of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said he heard
about the black tax credit while applying for public assistance. He
said he inquired at a now-defunct tax preparation office, which
referred him to a local businesswoman he knew only as ``Miss
Ruby.''
</P>
<P>
   She told him to get IRS form 2439 _ Notice to Shareholder of
Undistributed Long-Term Capital Gains. In a box marked ``Regulated
investment company's name, address and ZIP code,'' he wrote,
``Black Taxes.'' In a box below that he wrote, ``$43,209.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was upfront. He wasn't trying to hide anything,'' said Doug
Greene, an assistant federal public defender representing Foster.
</P>
<P>
   After filing the form with the rest of his tax return in April
1996, Foster received six or seven letters from the IRS, adjusting
the amount of the tax credit because of outstanding student loans
and child-support payments, Greene said. None of those letters
called the credit itself into question, Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scrutinized it,'' Greene said. ``That's the killer.''
</P>
<P>
   Beasley said that he could not discuss the particulars of
Foster's case but that the IRS has inadvertently granted some bogus
tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the desire to provide good customer service and processing
the tax refunds as quickly as possible, sometimes money goes out to
people who don't deserve it,'' he said. ``But we usually catch it
later.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRS caught the mistake before the check actually made it to
Foster. In August 1996, Foster said, he received a telephone call
from a man identifying himself as an IRS agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You will be receiving a tax refund check, and the
amount is wrong,' '' Foster said. ```Tell me where you live and
I'll pick up your check, and we'll send you a new one.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Foster said he didn't know whether to believe the man, so he
headed for the post office, found that the check had just been
delivered to his box, and deposited it in the bank. Foster said he
did not hear from the IRS again for two months.
</P>
<P>
   Then came an October letter stating that there is no black tax
credit and asking for the money back. Two more letters followed,
but those said he owed less than $300, according to documents in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was getting mixed signals,'' Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   Foster didn't send the money back. When the next tax season
rolled around, he agreed to help three co-workers who knew about
his windfall apply for the credit. He filled out their tax forms in
February 1997, not charging for his services. One of the three
received $2,300. The others received nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's tax-credit help _ not the money he owes _ is what got
him indicted. The three men he helped will testify against him.
</P>
<P>
   Greene faults the government for seeking criminal prosecution
instead of seeking to recover the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's willing to pay the money back and has made that offer to
the IRS,'' Greene said. ``The IRS messed up by sending him the
money and must have been too embarrassed to go through their
regular collection method, so they thought they'd prosecute him.''
</P>
<P>
   Terri Moore, the assistant U.S. attorney handling the case,
could not be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
