<HEADLINE>
ABC AND UNION REACH TENTATIVE AGREEMENT ON CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A tentative contract agreement was announced Friday
between ABC and the union representing hundreds of its camera
operators, editors and other technical staff members nationwide,
who have been involved in a protracted labor dispute that included
an 11-week lockout.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, which faces a ratification vote by July 16, awards
ABC far greater latitude in using temporary workers who do not
receive pension or health benefits. The temporary workers would,
however, be covered by the contract terms negotiated by the
National Association of Broadcast Employees and Technicians.
</P>
<P>
   The initial contract offer in February was rejected by most of
the 2,400 off-camera employees it covered. It would have increased
the number of temporary workers, now at 14 percent, to 26 percent
this year and 45 percent by 2002. The new contract raises those
numbers of temporary workers, known as daily hires, even higher,
allowing for 40 percent right away and 50 percent starting in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to use daily hires _ it gives us more
flexibility,'' said Julie Hoover, a spokeswoman for ABC, noting
that the network wanted to use freelance staff for sports events,
news programs and other broadcasts that have changing needs for
camera operators, video editors and other technicians.
</P>
<P>
   She said the new contract mirrored those at other networks, with
NBC able to hire 50 percent of its technical staff on a freelance
basis and CBS able to hire without limits.
</P>
<P>
   The greater number of temporary workers at ABC would not
threaten the job security of existing members, said Tom Donahue, a
spokesman for the union, known as NABET, which is part of the
Communications Workers of America. ``The whole industry is
changing,'' he said. ``At least there is a 50 percent cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Donahue said new provisions that benefit members included
loosening the rules for when technical workers are eligible for
buyouts at ABC, which has gone through repeated waves of
downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract also increases the allowance for working
through lunch and specifies that those involved in the strike can
reclaim some vacation time. In addition, anyone working as a daily
hire for more than 20 days per year would be required to join the
union.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the provisions remain unchanged from the February offer:
the contract still provides for raises of about 13 percent over
four years, alters the health care plan and lowers the amount the
company contributes to workers' pensions.
</P>
<P>
   NABET claimed that even getting a contract after two years of
fighting constituted success. ``There is job security associated
with having a contract,'' Donahue said. ``We see that as the
largest gain.''
</P>
<P>
   An initial contract was rejected by engineering units in five
cities, including about 1,800 members. If those units in New York,
Washington, Chicago, San Francisco and Washington ratify the new
agreement, the other 600 employees in seven units of traffic
coordinators, publicity agents, telephone operators and others who
accepted the February contract would be covered by the new
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders are recommending ratification of the new contract,
which would expire March 31, 2003. Ms. Hoover said employees
covered by the contract with NABET earn on average $80,000 per
year, including overtime but not benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The union, whose members had been working without a contract
since March 1997, staged a one-day strike last November over
changes in the health benefits. The network responded with a
lockout, hiring part-time workers to fill the technical slots and
winning a ruling from the National Labor Relations Board that the
lockout was legal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
