<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pars precious as Duval, 2 others lead
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINEHURST, N.C. _ It should be a typical U.S. Open weekend at
Pinehurst No. 2. The course that was defenseless 48 hours ago has
returned to its more famously fierce self. The score of par is
still to be treasured. The leaderboard possesses enough talent and
name recognition to delight television executives.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hear it for fairways and greens. There's a three-way tie
for the lead at 3-under-par 137 featuring Payne Stewart, who has a
U.S. Open trophy in his home, and young guns David Duval and Phil
Mickelson, who realize their careers will not be complete without a
major championship.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to the equation after 36 holes in the Sandhills.
Two strokes off the lead are Tiger Woods, Hal Sutton, PGA champion
Vijay Singh and Billy Mayfair. That's quite a representation from
the world rankings.
</P>
<P>
   With Pinehurst No. 2 drying out and drawing respect on a mild,
breezy, low-humidity day, only three players broke par, compared to
23 Thursday, when rain had softened the greens. Stewart, the 1991
champion, shot one of three 1-under-par 69s. The others came from
Jeff Maggert and John Huston, who are three shots off the pace at
140. Duval and Mickelson posted 70s and were darn proud of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt starting the day that 70 was going to be an exceptional
score because the winds were stronger and the greens weren't nearly
as soft,'' said Mickelson. ``I would have taken 70 at the start and
I'm very pleased with 70 at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who has never finished better than 18th in a U.S. Open,
stayed close with a 71. Sea Island's Davis Love III is six shots
back at 143 after a 73. Larry Mize of Columbus is seven back,
adding a 75 to his opening 69.
</P>
<P>
   Although Duval and Mickelson played together for a second day,
they downplayed any match-play situation. Both, however, bogeyed
the par-3 16th to eventually remain tied at 3-under. If not for a
double-bogey 5 at the par-3 6th hole, where he blasted over the
green from a bunker and missed a five-footer for par, Duval would
have been all alone at the top. He birdied the 7th and 8th holes
following the error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad I had gotten enough under par before the sixth
hole,'' Duval said. ``I just wasn't quite as sharp today. I just
seemed to hit the ball off the tee to yardage where I was in
between clubs all day.''
</P>
<P>
   The cut came at 7-over-par 147, taking two-time champion Ernie
Els, who missed a 10-footer for birdie at the 18th and finished
8-over; Greg Norman (73-78_151); and 1998 Masters and British Open
champion Mark O'Meara (71-79_150). Defending champion Lee Janzen
chipped in at the 18th to make it on the number, shooting a 73.
</P>
<P>
   If Stewart can stay out of sand divots and keep away from any
circuslike USGA pin placements, maybe he can hang in all the way
this year. He led for three rounds at Olympic in 1998, only to
finish behind Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm playing better than at the U.S. Open last
year,'' Stewart said. ``I feel I've got more control over my golf
game, over my swing. ... I could have crawled away and hid after
what happened last year or I could have built on what happened to
use it to strengthen myself, and that's the avenue I chose to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Goydos, who spent much of the day around the lead, fell
apart on the back nine for a 74 and fell to 1-over 141.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, reaffirming his pledge to leave the tournament if his
wife, Amy, goes into labor, said she had another visit with her
physician Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it's still going to be another week and a
half,'' he said. ``I'm really not overly concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech players Matt Kuchar and Bryce Molder both failed to
make the cut. Kuchar shot a 79 to finish at 155, never threatening
a year after tying for 14th at the Olympic Club. Molder slipped on
the back nine for a 40, shooting 78 for 11-over.
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia Tech player Stewart Cink of Duluth fought off a
severe cramp in his right side for a 74 and made the cut at 146.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hardly swing,'' he said. ``I couldn't hardly hit the
ball straight, that's for sure. Good timing, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
