<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RUSSIA'S MILITARY ROLE IN KOSOVO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, June 19:
</P>
<P>
   Provided no new hitches develop, the weeklong crisis over
Russian participation in the NATO-led peacekeeping operation in
Kosovo now appears satisfactorily resolved. Negotiations between
top U.S. officials and their Russian counterparts have produced an
agreement that defines the zones where Russian troops will operate,
the channels through which they will report to NATO's commander and
their role at Pristina's airport.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden arrival of 200 Russian troops at that airport last
Friday was unnerving. But the talks that followed have been useful
and gave both sides what they needed. NATO blocked creation of a
separate, Russian-controlled sector that could have split Kosovo
into Serbian and ethnic Albanian zones and preserved overall
command of peacekeeping operations. Russia secured the respectful
treatment for its forces it needs to maintain domestic support for
joining in the NATO-led mission.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement provides that the Russian troops will operate
within the U.S., French and German sectors of Kosovo, plus
Pristina's airport in the British sector. With no separate Russian
sector, there will be no obvious geographic basis for partition.
Russian troops will serve under Russian commanders, who will in
turn report to the top NATO officers of their sectors. This
parallel structure allows Moscow to say that Russian troops are not
under direct NATO command, but leaves NATO fully in charge of all
peacekeeping forces. At the Pristina airport, the Russians will
share responsibility but British forces will direct air traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Potential problems include the possibility that Russian
soldiers, many of whom sympathize with the Serbs, might intimidate
returning Kosovar Albanians or tolerate Serbian violence. There is
also a risk that Russian officers might try to bypass NATO command
structures. That is essentially what happened last week when some
Russian troops broke off cooperation with NATO peacekeepers in
Bosnia and rushed to Pristina. Military relations between NATO and
Russia have been troubled in recent months. The agreement will only
work as planned if the Russians carry it out in good faith and
maintain professional discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Russia remains an important European power, and its role in
Kosovo should reflect that status. Regrettably, during most of
NATO's 11-week air campaign against Yugoslavia, Moscow stood
sullenly on the sidelines. But in the last weeks, constructive
Russian diplomacy was crucial to avoiding a bloody ground war and
securing a just peace. The participation of Russian troops, on the
terms now agreed, can strengthen that peace. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990618.0477 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1625 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASTE19-COX     06-18 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waste pumped underground nears likely water supply in Fla.
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A half-mile beneath the earth, amid
boulders and pockets of salty water, Florida utilities have found a
perfect dumping place for their treated sewage.
</P>
<P>
   Injection wells pump as much as 400 million gallons of the stuff
underground each day _ never to be seen again, or so the theory
goes.
</P>
<P>
   But federal regulators are acknowledging what environmentalists
have argued for years: The waste is bubbling up into shallower
underground layers reserved for potential drinking water. The
evidence, seen at one north Palm Beach County site and others
around the state, includes ammonia appearing in test wells.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators could respond by stopping the injections. The U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency is also considering another
strategy: relaxing its rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mind-boggling,'' said Suzi Ruhl of the Legal
Environmental Assistance Foundation in Tallahassee, which has
fought for years to curb the pumping. ``Their solution to a known
violation is to change the law.''
</P>
<P>
   David Guest, an attorney for the Earthjustice Legal Defense
Fund, said changing the rules would be ``idiocy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not be putting contaminated waste underground and
then rolling the dice over whether we'll be drinking it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No evidence
</P>
<P>
   Utility managers dismiss the issue as a technicality, saying no
proof exists that even a drop of waste has reached anyone's tap,
let alone made anyone ill. And that's out of hundreds of billions
of gallons that utilities have pumped during the past two decades
into a porous pocket 3,000 feet below ground.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, they say, any waste seeping upward would have to filter
through thousands of feet of fine sand, clay and limestone _ making
it cleaner than the water that nature placed there.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County Utilities Director Gary Dernlan warned that
alternatives wouldn't be cheap. He said customers' water bills
could rise 35 percent if the county had to cleanse the waste to
drinking-water quality before injecting it.
</P>
<P>
   Underground pumping also has let utilities sharply reduce
dumping into the Atlantic Ocean and other waterways.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhl countered that the seemingly cheap price of underground
injection deters utilities from more responsible strategies, such
as increased recycling or conservation. She said it also masks the
high cost of letting developers attract even more sewage-producing
households.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means you can grow and grow and grow and grow regardless of
the consequences,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A similar controversy may be awaiting the federal government's
$7.8 billion plan to restore the Everglades, which partly relies on
pumping more than a billion gallons of excess water underground
each day from Lake Okeechobee and other waterways.
</P>
<P>
   The Everglades proposal calls for temporarily storing the water
and later reusing it _ not getting rid of it forever. The stored
water wouldn't include treated sewage, and it would be about 1,000
feet to 2,000 feet shallower than the injected waste.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a key legal question is the same: Should the EPA relax
its rules prohibiting any potential contamination of underground
drinking water?
</P>
<P>
   On the treated sewage injections, the EPA has scheduled a
meeting next month in West Palm Beach to listen to ideas.
</P>
<P>
   One option is to let the utilities keep injecting, but only if
engineers prove that the waste would be clean by the time it
reaches drinking water supplies, EPA scientist Howard Beard said.
Another is to order the utilities to stop injecting.
</P>
<P>
   No other state allows utilities to pump their treated waste deep
underground, EPA engineer Nancy Marsh said.
</P>
<P>
   The method is based on the existence of the boulder zone, a
layer of porous rock at the lower depths of the Floridan Aquifer.
Thick mud, limestone and dolomite are supposed to separate the zone
from the aquifer's shallower regions, which serve as the state's
major water source.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was that the two would never meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found it just doesn't work for these wells in Florida,''
Beard said. But so far, he said, no evidence exists that the leaks
create a health threat. Beard said the rules protect much of the
aquifer as a drinking water source, even though a big swath of that
water is so salty that nobody is using it. Ruhl said the rules
protect water for future generations, not just what we're using
today.
</P>
<P>
   Telltale signs
</P>
<P>
   Of nearly 120 utility injection wells statewide, the EPA has
reports of waste residues escaping to the edge of potential
drinking water layers from 20 wells.
</P>
<P>
   Chemicals linked to waste residues are also showing up near a
Palm Beach County Utilities injection well near Boynton Beach,
although they're still hundreds of feet beneath any possible
drinking water supplies, Dernlan said. The telltale signs are
ammonia, which contains nitrogen, and fresh water. Dernlan said no
tests of county wells have shown signs of viruses or pathogens, but
Ruhl argued that nobody is testing thoroughly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Ruhl said the regulators' track record doesn't persuade her to
accept their assurances that the injections can be made safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have confidence in any more projections from
engineering studies,'' she said. ``And I certainly wouldn't let
that be the protection and the safety net for our drinking water
supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
