<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS WILL BE ANSWERED AFTER GRANT FIGHTS SAVARESE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Pa., Texas)   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Grant is being marketed as this generation's
next heavyweight champion, and he certainly looks the part. Grant
is big and strong with a stiff jab, when he is inclined to use it.
He is a young, clean-cut man who sings and plays the piano for his
church choir in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still questions about Grant's capabilities. He
lacks the extensive amateur background that most world-class boxers
have. Grant took up the sport only six years ago after brief stints
playing basketball and football at two junior colleges in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those questions, however, may be answered Saturday night
at the Theater in Madison Square Garden, where Grant (29-0) will
take on Lou Savarese (39-2), a tough native of the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The bout will be broadcast on HBO's ``Boxing After Dark,''
beginning at 11 p.m. with a 10-round heavyweight match between
Jeremy Williams (31-1) and Maurice Harris (14-9-2).
</P>
<P>
   Savarese took George Foreman the distance before losing on a
decision and he displayed awesome power by knocking out Buster
Douglas with a crushing right to the chin.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese said that when he was walking into the Garden on
Wednesday for a news conference, a boxing fan told him he had to
stay away from Grant in the bout. ``I said, `Buddy, you haven't
seen me fight, have you?''' Savarese said.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese and Grant used to work out at the same Houston gym that
Evander Holyfield uses, so both fighters are familiar with each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Savarese is a coming-at-you kind of guy,'' Grant said. ``He
takes a good shot. He's not the kind of person to back up. He makes
you earn his respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese hears all the talk about Grant being the future of the
heavyweight division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm fighting a god with everyone saying he's the
next great heavyweight,'' Savarese said. ``We need to see more of
Mike. He's going to have to come out there and prove it to me and
make me respect him as a fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant said: ``Maybe I will. All of my fights I have to show
everybody something.''
</P>
<P>
   Lennox Lewis, the World Boxing Council heavyweight champion, is
expected to be sitting at ringside Saturday night scouting Grant as
a possible next opponent should Lewis' proposed November rematch
with Holyfield fall through. Grant said he was not holding his
breath waiting for a title shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a season for everything,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   On the undercard, Williams was set to fight Hasim Rahman, but
Rahman pulled out with a backache. That brought an incredulous
response from Kathy Duva of Main Events, the promoter of the bout.
``Rahman said he had a bad back and that's not surprising for
people who are spineless,'' Duva said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
