<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: )  
 PAK FIRES A RECORD 63   FOR A ONE-SHOT LEAD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABSECON, N.J. _ After accelerating to stardom last year as a
rookie on the Ladies Professional Golf Association tour, Se Ri Pak
has succumbed to pressure and fatigue in the early part of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   All the attention from government officials in her native South
Korea and from friends and family, along with the demands from
sponsors and the news media in North America, seemed to be too much
for the 21-year-old golfer who last year won four tournaments,
including two majors.
</P>
<P>
   This season it took Pak 16 rounds before she broke 70. She has
missed the cut three times and has seldom been in contention.
</P>
<P>
   But a few weeks ago her game started to come together. After
tying for fourth place last weekend in the Rochester International
for her best finish of the season, Pak returned to top form this
afternoon with a sizzling eight-under-par 63 in the opening round
of the ShopRite LPGA Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Pak was a shot ahead of Trish Johnson, who shot 64 on the
strength of eight birdies and a bogey. That score tied Johnson's
career-low round in 12 years on the LPGA tour, where she has three
victories, the last one in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The 63 by Pak, accomplished on 10 birdies and two bogeys on the
6,051-yard par-71 Bay Course of the Seaview Marriott Resort, set a
course and tournament record. The previous record of 64 was shared
by four players, including Karrie Webb of Australia last year.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, who changed irons after an opening-round 77 last week in
Rochester, shot a 66 on her first day with the new irons.
</P>
<P>
   With her parents listening during a post-round meeting with the
news media, Pak kept repeating how the presence of her father, Joon
Chul, had helped during the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was busy and didn't come until last week,'' Pak said.
``He checks my game better than anyone and he knows me better than
anyone. I'm also a lot happier now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf is important, but my life is important, too. Whether I
win or not, I'm happy. I won tournaments in 1998, but I'm more
confident now.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak said she had started to trust her swing the last two weeks,
but the main reason for Friday's exceptional round was her putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured the speed and I made every putt,'' Pak said. ``My
putting has been bad, but not today. Shooting eight under makes me
comfortable to defend next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak was alluding to playing in the McDonald's Championship, the
major that set off her string of victories that year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty-three is a phenomenal round,'' said Juli Inkster, who
shot five-under 66 and was alone in third, three shots behind Pak.
``But I'll tell you what: I'll take two more five-unders and walk
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, who has won this tournament twice, in 1986 and 1988,
accomplished her 66 on six birdies and a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   At 67 were Kim Saiki, Shani Waugh, Charlotta Sorenstam, Sherri
Steinhauer, Wendy Ward and Leta Lindley.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy King shot a record 29 on the back nine for a 68 Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Annika Sorenstam, last year's winner, struggled to a one-over 72
under virtually ideal conditions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
