<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-WIFE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fla. governor's wife fined for customs breach
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A $19,000 shopping spree in Paris turned
into an expensive embarrassment for Florida's first lady Columba
Bush when she was detained by U.S. Customs agents Thursday for
failing to declare her purchases and was forced to pay a $4,100
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's luggage was searched when she arrived at Atlanta's
Hartsfield Airport after a five-day trip to France. Gov. Jeb Bush
did not accompany his wife on the trip. The search was part of a
routine, random check of luggage made by U.S. Customs agents who
said they treated the first lady like any other overseas passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised in the Central Mexico town of Leon where she met
her husband when they were both teen-agers, Bush, 46, is a seasoned
overseas traveler. On the campaign trail, she always wore
well-tailored clothes and modest jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   After opening her bags, Customs agents found clothing and
jewelry worth $19,000 that was bought during her trip. She
immediately wrote a personal check for the $4,100 fine. The fine
was three times what she would have paid if she had reported the
merchandise to customs.
</P>
<P>
   After paying the fine, Bush returned to Tallahassee on Thursday
night. When word of her troubles in Atlanta got out Friday, the
governor's office issued a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly regret this unfortunate mistake,'' she said. ``I am
sorry for exercising bad judgment and can assure everyone this will
never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Gov. Bush had just eight words to say about the
episode. ``Both Columba and I deeply regret this mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
