<SLUG> BC-ABC-CONTRACT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORK MAKES TENTATIVE DEAL WITH TECHNICIANS IT LOCKED OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The ABC network announced Friday it has reached a
tentative, four-year deal with negotiators for the 2,400 unionized
technicians it locked out for 11 weeks last fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
   The pact, which must be ratified by employees, ends more than
two years of working without a contract for camera operators,
producers and other behind-the-scenes workers represented by the
National Association of Broadcast Employees and Technicians. About
600 of the affected employees work in the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're recommending ratification even though the tentative
contract falls short of our objectives, because we believe it's the
best agreement that can be achieved at this time,'' said NABET
negotiator John Krieger. Results of the vote are expected to be
released July 16.
</P>
<P>
   The pact provides for a 3.5 percent salary increase, retroactive
to June 26, 3 percent increases for each of the next two years and
a 3.5 percent increase in the final year through March 31, 2003.
The union said the agreement also improves contract provisions
covering vacation, discharges and the hiring of daily workers.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, owned by The Walt Disney Co., locked out NABET members in
November after the union staged a one-day strike to protest the
network's imposition of reduced health benefits. The walkout
disrupted live telecasts by ABC, which barred the employees from
returning to work unless it gave the network 72 hours' notice of
future job actions.
</P>
<P>
   During the lockout, ABC used temporary workers while NABET
members picketed network facilities, and prominent Democrats and
entertainers refused to be interviewed for shows like ``Good
Morning America,'' ``Nightline'' and ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   Five units turned down a network proposal in December, but the
union returned to work in January after agreeing to give advance
warning of future strikes in exchange for obtaining binding
arbitration on dismissals of several members.
</P>
<P>
   Tentative agreements will be submitted to the 1,400 members of
NABET units in Chicago, Los Angeles, New York, San Francisco and
Washington, D.C., that turned down ABC's December proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Upon ratification, the new contracts will become part of the
master agreement between ABC and NABET and cover seven smaller
units, which ratified the package in February.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
