<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT &LR;      06-18 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: WHAT TO DO IF YOUR COMPANY IS OVERVALUED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine yourself in the following position:
</P>
<P>
   You've started a company and begun to build it, with a story
that has captured the imagination of Wall Street. You've sold stock
to the public and seen it rise much further than seemed possible.
You suspect that one of these days investors will wise up and the
share price will plunge.
</P>
<P>
   What should you do?
</P>
<P>
   First, take profits by selling some of your shares at high
prices. Then use the company's overvalued stock to buy assets that
are relatively cheap. You do that by offering stock to acquire
companies that Wall Street does not love but that would raise the
value of your company.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good strategy, but it has one flaw. When Wall Street sees
what you are doing, it may not like it. After all, it doesn't agree
with the basic premise, that your stock is overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   That scenario, it appears to me, is now playing itself out as
two telecommunications wunderkinds bid against each other for the
same telephone companies. The targets have something the bidders
need _ real, live customers.
</P>
<P>
   Bidder No. 1 is Global Crossing. Founded only two years ago by
Gary Winnick, once a colleague of Michael Milken at Drexel Burnham
Lambert, it went public 10 months ago and by early May was trading
for almost seven times the offering price from last summer. It has
installed a new fiber-optic cable under the Atlantic and is
building cables in other parts of the world. It rents capacity on
its system to other phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bidder No. 2 is Qwest Communications, which has almost completed
an 18,500-mile fiber-optic network covering most of the United
States. It also rents out capacity to phone companies, but through
acquisitions it now has four million customers who deal directly
with it. It was started in 1994 by Philip Anschutz, an oil and
railroad magnate, and went public two years ago. At its peak this
spring, it was trading at nearly 10 times its original offering
price.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are trying to buy U.S. West, the Baby Bell based
in Denver, and the Frontier Corporation of Rochester, N.Y., which
operates a local phone company and a long-distance system. Global
Crossing was there first, reaching deals with both companies, while
Qwest has entered with hostile bids.
</P>
<P>
   Both Winnick and Anschutz have arranged to take out big profits
by selling stock in their own companies at prices that prevailed
before they got into this bidding war. Now they are trying to merge
with U.S. West and Frontier to get 30 million customers.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has been dubious about companies like U.S. West,
fearing that much of their capacity is outmoded and that they will
face increasing competition. That led to the shares of Global
Crossing and Qwest falling when they got into this battle. But this
is a case where the bidders know what they are doing. Eventually
there will be more than enough fiber-optic capacity, and prices for
it will fall. So long as they are selling capacity to other phone
companies, Global Crossing and Qwest face the possibility of seeing
their revenues slide when that happens.
</P>
<P>
   But the lesson of telecommunication wars to date has been that
retail customers are slow to move. All the long-distance companies
have customers who pay more than they would have to if they just
asked their current carrier for the best plan available. Both
Global Crossing and Qwest need customers, and they need to get them
before investors realize how great the need really is.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to determine which of the two bids is better, for
that calculation revolves around such issues as which one of the
companies would be better at managing the combined entity and which
of them is offering less-overvalued stock.
</P>
<P>
   But shareholders in U.S. West and Frontier don't have to decide
that. With the stock prices of both companies having risen because
of the bidding war, they should sell now and consider putting the
money into other companies with customers _ the commodity that is
on the way to becoming more valuable than fiber-optic cables.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
