<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CUSTOMS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fla. first lady detained at Atlanta airport
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Florida Gov. Jeb Bush's wife, Columba, was detained at
Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport and ordered to pay
$4,100 in penalties for failing to declare items she had purchased
on an overseas trip, U.S. Customs Service officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was detained and treated just like anybody else,'' said
customs spokesman Bill Anthony in Washington. ``It was for not
declaring legal merchandise. It's not a unique situation with
people coming back from overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida's first lady was not incarcerated, although the
incident, which happened Thursday, is considered a violation of
customs law, he said. Columba Bush spent about 3 1/2 hours at the
Atlanta airport and missed a connecting flight, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office issued a statement Friday evening
acknowledging the incident and saying Columba Bush paid a civil
penalty of $4,100 by personal check. The statement said the penalty
represented three times the duty that would have been assessed on
the merchandise purchased in France, mostly clothing and jewelry,
valued at $19,000.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office quoted Columba Bush as saying, ``I truly
regret this unfortunate mistake. I am sorry for exercising bad
judgment and can assure everyone this will never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush, elected in November, is the son of former President
George Bush and younger brother of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the
current front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush met his wife in her native Mexico when he was an exchange
student from Phillips Academy at Andover, a prestigious New England
prep school. The couple courted by mail and on Bush's return visits
for several years before marrying in the early 1970s. They have
three children between the ages of 15 and 22. According to
published reports, Columba Bush is a stylish dresser who has
frequented expensive boutiques in Bal Harbour, an upscale Miami
suburb. She is a devout Catholic, is active in a Dade County drug
abuse education group and has raised money for the Ballet
Folklorico of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials in Atlanta said officers, during a routine
inspection of her luggage, found more items than she had reported
on her customs form.
</P>
<P>
   Customs allows people to bring $400 worth of merchandise into
the country, but anything over that amount must be reported for the
purpose of assessing duty on the merchandise, Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
