<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DISABLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HELPING THE DISABLED WORK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, June 19:
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a piece of legislation makes such obvious good sense
that it commands support from all points on the political spectrum.
That happened on Wednesday when the Senate voted 99-0 to pass the
Work Incentives Improvement Act to allow disabled Americans to work
without fear of losing health coverage under Medicare and Medicaid.
The legislation would at last end the perverse financial
disincentives in disability law that prevent people from becoming
self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   More than 7.5 million disabled Americans receive federal
benefits through Social Security Disability Insurance and
Supplemental Security Income. Many may want to work, but less than
one-half of 1 percent receiving disability insurance do because
they would lose their cash benefits if they earned more than $500 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, they would lose their health coverage after three years.
The new act _ sponsored by James Jeffords and William Roth, both
Republicans, and the Democrats Edward Kennedy and Daniel Patrick
Moynihan _ would allow the disabled to keep their Medicare benefits
when they return to work, and also create a system under which cash
benefits would gradually diminish as earnings rose.
</P>
<P>
   The House should move on this legislation quickly. If only 1
percent of the disabled receiving federal benefits _ or 75,000
people _ were to work, the government would save an estimated $3.5
billion in disability payments over the lifetime of the
beneficiaries. That kind of return makes this program fiscally
smart as well as compassionate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
