</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BROWNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MS. BROWNER RESPONDS ON CLEAN AIR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, June 19:
</P>
<P>
   Carol Browner, administrator of the Environmental Protection
Agency, has unveiled a rejiggered plan to improve air quality in
the Northeastern United States. This will benefit residents in
places like New York and New Jersey, which have long suffered from
dirty air blowing in from the South and Midwest. It also sends a
strong message that the administration is not yet prepared to let
two conservative federal judges rewrite its clean air strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The judges are Douglas Ginsburg and David Williams, Reagan
appointees who dominated two court rulings last month by separate
three-judge panels of the 2nd U.S. Court of Appeals. The first
ruling, on dubious constitutional grounds, overturned tough air
quality standards imposed in 1997 for air and soot _ the
cornerstone of the administration's clean air policies.
</P>
<P>
   The second suspended Ms. Browner's subsequent order requiring 22
states and the District of Columbia to submit detailed plans for
reducing emissions of nitrogen oxide, the main ingredient in smog,
that is blown eastward by prevailing winds from Midwestern power
plants and industrial boilers. The 22-state order had been based on
the new air quality standards that the court had just invalidated.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Browner had one weapon in reserve. Two years ago, before
the 22-state plan was devised, several Northeastern states filed
individual petitions based on older, less stringent air quality
standards than those rejected by the Second Circuit. The states had
said that no matter what they did within their own borders, they
could not meet the older smog standards because too much pollution
blew in from other states. In effect, what Ms. Browner has now
decided to do is resurrect those petitions and use them to impose
at least some controls on out-of-state polluters.
</P>
<P>
   This backup strategy will apply to only 12 polluting states
named in the petitions, and will therefore provide less relief to
Northeastern residents than the 22-state plan. To obtain broader
relief, Ms. Browner and the Justice Department must eventually
persuade the Supreme Court to overturn the Second Circuit's ruling
tossing out the new smog and soot standards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is a modest first step that has a good chance of
surviving legal challenge, since it is based on old standards that
remain in force. It also reassures anyone interested in cleaner air
that Ginsburg and Williams are not the only people calling the
shots in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-18-99 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
