</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-RIDERS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ride recalls Mississippi slayings
 &HT;    By Erik Rodriguez
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new generation of freedom riders rolled through
Atlanta on Friday night to commemorate three men who were murdered
working to challenge segregation laws in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom Ride 1999, sponsored by the New York-based Chaney
Goodman Unity Coalition, seeks to honor the lives of freedom riders
James Earl Chaney, Andrew Goodman and Michael Schwerner. The three
men were murdered in Mississippi while working to secure voting
rights for blacks in the South in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The charter bus trip, which began in New York City, also aims to
bring people together to voice opinions on congressional issues,
such as nondiscriminatory employment practices and domestic and
workplace violence.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 participants stopped for dinner and services at
Temple Emanu-El of Greater Atlanta on Friday night as their buses
swept through Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Allan Gould, a Toronto writer who said that 35
years ago, he was on the bus behind the one carrying Chaney as
their caravan headed south.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mississippi was in flames,'' recalled Gould, who is in his
50s. ``People were afraid to register to vote. It was horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Greer, a 25-year-old student from Philadelphia, said the
civil rights issues facing young people today differ from those
that cost the three civil rights workers their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't compare, because we're not risking anything,'' said
Greer. ``But everyone here is an activist and we're just trying to
get them to do more when they get home.''
</P>
<P>
   During Friday evening's observances, Antonio Pryce of Hyde
Point, N.C., began to sing an old spiritual that began with the
words: ''I woke up this morning with my mind stayed on freedom.''
One by one, people joined in, until the room was filled with
singing and clapping.
</P>
<P>
   The caravan, which also stopped in Washington, D.C. and
Greensboro, N.C., will leave Atlanta today. It will pass through
historic sites in Selma, Birmingham and Montgomery, Ala., before
ending the ride Monday with a dedication at Chaney's gravesite in
Meridian, Miss. It will mark the 35th anniversary of the murders.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney was 21 years old when he, Schwerner and Goodman were
killed by a mob after being detained by the Neshoba County
Sheriff's Department in Philadelphia, Miss. They were found six
weeks later, buried beneath a nearby dam, ending a nationwide
search.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 ride is important to help people remember the
sacrifices made by the three men, organizers of the event said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are beginning to have an actual sense of what it was
like to be in the actual freedom rides in the 1960s, when those
folks put their lives on the line,'' said Katwy Heru, director of
operations for the Unity Coalition, which is run by Chaney's
younger brother, Ben. ``They also (are getting) an understanding of
the history that they are participating in.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
