<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-18 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1763 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-2NDLD-WR     06-18 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HELSINKI: sector,'' he said. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATO's reluctance to permit Russia a separate role has to do
with doubts about Moscow's reliability as a military partner. ``It
has to do with something that is not so pleasant to talk about,
which is trust,'' said one American at the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of Russian paratroopers at the Pristina airport
last week _ ordered as Russian diplomats were assuring the
Americans that no such order had been given _ damaged Russia's
credibility in the West. But in Moscow the move was seen as a
tactical triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcements for the 200 paratroopers never arrived because
countries neighboring Yugoslavia denied Russia permission to fly
over troop transport planes until there was an agreement with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian soldiers, supplied with food brought on convoys from
Bosnia, have spent the last week in tenuous isolation, depending on
British troops for water.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement Friday allows for up to 750 Russian troops to be
stationed at the airport, with five battalions _ or 2,850 troops _
to be distributed among the French, German and American sectors.
According to a map distributed Friday night, the Russians will be
assigned zones within the sectors. The Russian zone within the
American sector will be located in Kosovo's northeastern corner.
</P>
<P>
   According to a senior State Department official, the Russian
zones were allocated in areas where both Serbs and Albanians live,
in order to dispel any notion of ethnic division. He said Russian
negotiators expressed concern about the reaction of the Albanians
to Russian troops, but were given assurances that NATO plans to
press ahead with the disarming of Albanian militants.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of the command structure was resolved on the first day
and by Thursday the work shifted to expert military groups,
interspersed with meetings between Cohen and Sergeyev, and Albright
and Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement now goes to the North Atlantic Council, where NATO
allies are expected to approve it. Yeltsin, who was also consulted,
is expected to endorse the agreement when he meets Clinton in
Cologne.
</P>
</TEXT>
