<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING STRIKES UNUSUAL DEAL TO BUY AIRBUS PLANES FROM CARRIER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Boeing Co. has raised the level of competition in
its battle with archrival Airbus Industrie.
</P>
<P>
   In a bold move that industry analysts said aims to blunt the
momentum of Airbus with Asia's most profitable airline, the
Seattle-based aerospace giant said Friday it will buy 17 Airbus
widebody planes from Singapore Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual deal includes two planes that likely aren't built
yet; they haven't even been delivered by the European planemaker.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Singapore Airlines will convert options from a
previous order and buy 10 new 777s worth nearly $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal's significance is that it once again gives Boeing
the upper hand over Airbus with a crucial Asian airline _ one of
Boeing's best customers for the 777, according to Paul Nisbet,
aerospace analyst with JSA Research Inc.
</P>
<P>
   And if more Asian carriers opt for the 777 over Airbus' planes,
it could also have implications for a proposed new, longer-range
version of the big wide-body Boeing jet that had been postponed
when Singapore opted for big, new Airbus jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly raises the level of competition,'' Nisbet said.
``It swings the potential market share a little in Boeing's
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not unprecedented for Boeing, as part of an order
transaction, to buy and remarket an Airbus plane acquired from an
airline. But a Boeing spokesman said this is far and away the most
Airbus planes the company has ever bought at one time.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came at the end of the Paris air show, and for
Boeing it capped what has been a good week with a parting shot at
its European rival.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Mark Hooper said Boeing will buy Singapore's existing
fleet of 15 Airbus A340-300 aircraft. In addition, he said, Boeing
will buy two A340-300s that are to be delivered to Singapore
Airlines in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Neither company would disclose what Boeing is paying for the
Airbus planes, but a new A340-300's list price is $140 million to
$145 million, depending on the configuration.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 options being exercised are part of a $12.7 billion order
placed by Singapore Airlines in 1995 for 77 of Boeing's 777s. Of
those, 34 were firm orders. The dollar value of the order,
including options, was Boeing's biggest ever.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the 1995 contract, Singapore Airlines had the option
to sell its fleet of A340-300s to Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The latest 777s are scheduled for delivery between 2001 and
2004.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines said it expected to finance the latest
purchase largely through cash flow but it would resort to borrowing
or leasing if needed. The carrier, Asia's most profitable, has 89
aircraft in its fleet. It expects to have a fleet of 120 aircraft
by the end of the financial year 2004.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the airline may have decided to go with the 777 over
the Airbus planes is a recent proposal by the Federal Aviation
Administration to relax a rule known as ETOPS, (extended range
twin-engined operations). Under present ETOPS rules, a twin-engine
plane such as the 777 is limited on its route to 180 minutes from
an emergency airport. Because the A340-300 is a four-engine plane,
it is under no such restriction.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA recently proposed a 15 percent extension of ETOPS to 207
minutes. That extension would open more routes to the 777.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, of course, is in favor of the extension, as are U.S.
airlines that fly the 777. Airbus has opposed the extension,
arguing a twin-engine plane is not as safe as a four-engine plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Singapore Airlines is obviously expecting ETOPS to be relaxed,
as well it should be,'' said Nisbet.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what the development may ultimately mean for the
10 A340-500 planes ordered by Singapore Airlines last year. Hooper,
the Boeing spokesman, said the agreement by Boeing to buy the
A340-300s has nothing to do with the A340-500s.
</P>
<P>
   The A340-500 order last year was an important Airbus victory
over Boeing, which was counting on Singapore Airlines as a launch
customer for the 777X, a longer range version of the present 777.
</P>
<P>
   The A340-500 is a 313-seat plane that will be able to fly nearly
10,000 miles, further than any other plane now in production.
Singapore Airlines plans to use the plane to fly non-stop from
Singapore to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's 777X would have longer range than current 777 models.
</P>
<P>
   Because Singapore Airlines only ordered 10 of the A340-500s,
industry analysts speculated at the time that the Boeing's 777X
might still be in the running before the airline completes its
long-range fleet.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known when Boeing will launch the 777X. But engine
makers have already submitted bids to Boeing to supply the monster
engines that will be needed to power the huge new plane.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Boeing must now find buyers for 17 Airbus planes.
</P>
<P>
   Nisbet said Boeing should have no problem remarketing the
planes, since it likely got a steep discount from Singapore
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will certainly be airlines out there figuring they can
get these planes on the cheap,'' he said. ``I expect Boeing to
dispose of them fairly rapidly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
