<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GUNS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SIGNS BILL BANNING ANTI-GUN LAWSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 4th and 5th grafs on Gore's response.)  (With CONGRESS-GUNS and related stories.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Gov. George W. Bush on Friday signed into law a bill
making it illegal for any of the state's cities or other local
governments to file suit against gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The move lands Bush, the Republican presidential front-runner,
in the middle of what is emerging as a hot-button debate in the
2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush does not believe the manufacturer of a legal product
should be held responsible for the criminal use of that product,''
said Linda Edwards, the governor's director of communications.
``This legislation seeks to curb frivolous lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's signing of the bill prompted Vice President Al Gore to
take direct aim at his potential presidential opponent, accusing
the Texas governor of being soft on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are too high for any presidential candidate to
stand on the sidelines'' of the gun-control debate, The Associated
Press quoted Gore as saying. The vice president provided the vote
to break a Senate deadlock and require background checks when guns
are sold a gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of gun control were quick to see Bush's action as
proof of a cozy relationship with the National Rifle Association,
which has championed similar bills in state capitals around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a question of priorities,'' said Joe Sudbay, director
of state legislation for Hand Gun Control in Washington. ``The NRA
said, We want this, and the governor showed that that's where his
loyalties lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill was one of more than a thousand awaiting the governor's
signature in the wake of the legislative session that adjourned on
May 31. The gun legislation had not emerged as a particularly
contentious issue in gun-friendly Texas, certainly not to the level
that Washington has become embroiled in the topic.
</P>
<P>
   Texas now becomes one of 14 states that have adopted such
legislation, passed in response to recent suits filed in New
Orleans, Atlanta and other cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
